<HEAD>Here ginne&thorn; Sir Gij. (AUCHINLECK MS. 107v)</HEAD>

<PB REF="00000006.tif" N="2">
<HEAD>Gij of Warwike.</HEAD>
<HEADNOTE><P>[<I>The first leaf is wanting in the Auchinleck MS., and the story is here supplied from the French version, MS. Corpus Coll., Camb., leaf</I> 6, <I>collated with MS. Harleian</I> 3775, <I>leaf</I> 15.]</P></HEADNOTE>
<DIV2 TYPE="section">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Puis cel tens ke deus fu nez</L>
<L>e establi crestienetez,</L>
<L><SUP>1</SUP>multz des<SUP>1</SUP><NOTE PLACE="marg">1_1 multes, <I>Harl</I>.</NOTE> auentures sont auenues,</L>
<L>ke<NOTE PLACE="marg">Qui</NOTE> a tuz hommes ne sont pas<NOTE PLACE="marg">omit.</NOTE> sues.</L>
<L N="5">pur ceo deit l'em mult enquere,</L>
<L>e pener sei de bien fere,</L>
<L>e de <SUP>4</SUP>bons prendre<SUP>4</SUP><NOTE PLACE="marg">4_4 aprendre bons</NOTE> esperimentz,</L>
<L>de faitz, de diz as aunciens</L>
<L>qui deuant nus esteient.</L>
<L N="10">auentures beles lur aueneient,</L>
<L>pur ceo qu'il amoient uerite,</L>
<L>tut dis fei e leaute.</L>
<L>De eus deit l'um bien souenir</L>
<L>e lur bons faitz dire e oir:</L>
<L N="15">qui mult out e ceo retient</L>
<L>souent mult sage deuient;</L>
<L><SUP>5</SUP>ceo est tenu<SUP>5</SUP><NOTE PLACE="marg">5_5 il ceo tent ben.</NOTE> a bele mestrie,</L>
<L>ki fait le sen e lest la folie.</L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L N="20">De un counte uoloms parler</L>
<L>qui mult fait<NOTE PLACE="marg">feseit</NOTE> a preiser,</L>
<L>e de un son senescal</L>
<L>qui pruz ert<NOTE PLACE="marg">esteit</NOTE> e leal;</L>
<L>e de son fiz, un damoisel</L>
<L N="25">qui mult par ert gent e bel;</L>
<L>e com il amat une pucele,
<PB REF="00000008.tif" N="4"></L>
<L>la fylle au counte, ke mult ert bele.</L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L>En engleterre un coens esteit,<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="25"></L>
<L>en Warewik la cite maneit:</L>
<L>riches ert e de grant Foer<NOTE PLACE="marg">pouer</NOTE>,</L>
<L N="40">queintes, sages, bon cheualer;</L>
<L>riches ert de or e de argent,</L>
<L>de Dras, de seie, de vesselement,</L>
<L>de fortz chasteul<NOTE PLACE="marg">chastels</NOTE>, de riche citez;</L>
<L>par tut le rengne ert mult dotez.</L>
<L N="45">n'i<NOTE PLACE="marg">n'</NOTE> aueit homme en tote la terre</L>
<L>qui uers li osaht<NOTE PLACE="marg">osat</NOTE> prendre guerre,</L>
<L>ke par force toht<NOTE PLACE="marg">tost</NOTE> nel preist,</L>
<L>e en la<NOTE PLACE="marg">sa</NOTE> chartre nel meist.</L>
<L>bons cheualers mult ama,</L>
<L N="50">riches douns souent lur dona;</L>
<L>pur ceo fu cremu e dote,</L>
<L>e par tut le rengne preise.</L>
<L>coens esteit de mult grant pris,</L>
<L>sires ert de tuit le pais;</L>
<L N="55">de oxeneford tut le honur</L>
<L>sue estoit a icel iour;</L>
<L>de bukingham de<NOTE PLACE="marg">omit.</NOTE> tut le counte</L>
<L>sire en tel<NOTE PLACE="marg">cel</NOTE> tens esteit clame.</L>
<L>li coens roaud out a nun,<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="51"></L>
<L N="60">mult par esteit noble barun.</L>
<L>vne fylle auoit<NOTE PLACE="marg">out de</NOTE> sa mulier,</L>
<L>sa grant beaute ne puis conter:
<PB REF="00000010.tif" N="6"></L>
<L>pur la plus bele le unt choisie.</L>
<L>ore est reisun ke l'em uus die</L>
<L N="65">vn petitet de sa grant<NOTE PLACE="marg">omit.</NOTE> beaute:</L>
<L>le viz out blank e colore,</L>
<L>lunge, traitet<NOTE PLACE="marg">treitis</NOTE>, e auenaunt;</L>
<L>bele buche, e nes bien seaunt,</L>
<L>les euz uairs e le chief bloi;</L>
<L N="70">de li ueer uus semblast poi:</L>
<L>bien faite de cors, de bele estature,</L>
<L>tant par ad duce la reguardure.</L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L>corteise ert e enseignee,</L>
<L N="80">de tuz artz ert enseignee<NOTE PLACE="marg">endoctuinee</NOTE>:</L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L>ses mestres esteient venuz</L>
<L>de tulette<NOTE PLACE="marg">toulette</NOTE>, tut<NOTE PLACE="marg">touz</NOTE> blaunks chanuz,</L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L>qui la apernoient de astrenomie,</L>
<L>de arsmetic<NOTE PLACE="marg">arsmetrike</NOTE>, de Geumetrie.</L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L>mult par ert fere de corage:</L>
<L>pur ceo ke ele fud tant sage,</L>
<L N="95">ducs e countes la requeroient;<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="71"></L>
<L>de <SUP>7</SUP>multz de<SUP>7</SUP><NOTE PLACE="marg">7_7 mute; <I>read</I> multes</NOTE> terres pur li<NOTE PLACE="marg">luy</NOTE> venoient,</L>
<L>mes nul de eus amer ne uoleit,</L>
<L>pur ceo ke tant bele esteit.
<PB REF="00000012.tif" N="8"></L>
<L>felice fu la bele appellee:</L>
<L N="100">pur sa beaute fu mult amee;</L>
<L>de totes beautez fu ele la flur,</L>
<L>tant bele ne ert a icel iour.</L>
<L>ki totes terres dunc serchast</L>
<L>vne tant bele n'i<NOTE PLACE="marg">ne</NOTE> trouast:</L>
<L N="105">qui tote sa beaute countereit</L>
<L>trop grant demorance i freit.</L>
<L>de la pucele lerrum ester,<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="83"></L>
<L><SUP>2</SUP>e de<SUP>2</SUP><NOTE PLACE="marg">2_2 del</NOTE> senescal uodrum parler,</L>
<L>ke<NOTE PLACE="marg">Qi</NOTE> mult ert corteis e sage:</L>
<L N="110">homme fu de mult grant parage;</L>
<L>riches ert e de mult<NOTE PLACE="marg">omit.</NOTE> grant ualur;</L>
<L>en icel tens ni out meillur,</L>
<L><SUP>5</SUP>ne ke<SUP>5</SUP><NOTE PLACE="marg">5_5 Ni qi</NOTE> fuht tant des armes prise,</L>
<L>kar en mainte terre aueit este</L>
<L N="115">pur sun pris enhaucier;</L>
<L>pur ceo <SUP>6</SUP>fait il<SUP>6</SUP><NOTE PLACE="marg">6_6 feseit</NOTE> mult a loer.</L>
<L>en Walingeford nez estoit,</L>
<L>tuit le pais a li apendoit:</L>
<L>pur ceo fud il nobles e fier;</L>
<L N="120">tant bon n'i<NOTE PLACE="marg">n'</NOTE> aueit de ca<NOTE PLACE="marg">sa (= &ccedil;a)</NOTE> la mier,</L>
<L>ne ki seruist sun seingnur,</L>
<L>tuz iours a si grant honur.</L>
<L>His lord he serued treweliche<MILESTONE N="108a:1" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>In al &thorn;ing manschipeliche.<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="93"></L>
<L N="125">&thorn;er was non erl in Inglond</L>
<L>&thorn;at to &yogh;eines him durst stond,</L>
<L>Bot, &yogh;if he wold be wi&thorn; him at on,</L>
<L>He wald do nimen him anon,</L>
<L>&amp; wi&thorn; streng&thorn;e him nim wolde,</L>
<L N="130">&thorn;ei he to Scotlond suwe him scholde.</L>
<L>His lordis honour he held wor&thorn;schipliche,</L>
<L>&amp; defended it wele &amp; hardiliche;</L>
<L>&thorn;er nas<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. was</NOTE> kni[&yogh;]t in Inglonde</L>
<L>&thorn;at wi&thorn; wret&thorn;e durst him atstonde.
<PB REF="00000014.tif" N="10"></L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L>&thorn;ei a man bar an hundred pounde,</L>
<L>Opon him, of gold y-grounde,</L>
<L>&thorn;e[r] nas man in al &thorn;is londe</L>
<L N="140">&thorn;at durst him do schame no schonde,</L>
<L>&thorn;at bireft him wor&thorn; of a slo,</L>
<L>So gode pais &thorn;er was &thorn;o.</L>
<L>&THORN;ilke steward hadde a sone<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="110"></L>
<L>Trewe &amp; wise atte frome;</L>
<L N="145">Al folk he dede him loue,</L>
<L>For &thorn;at noman schuld him schoue;</L>
<L>&amp; riche &yogh;iftes &yogh;iuen he wold,</L>
<L>For &thorn;at he schuld be fre yhold.</L>
<L>&thorn;erl Rohaud he serued &thorn;o,</L>
<L N="150">As he schuld his kinde lorde do;</L>
<L>&thorn;erl him loued swi&thorn;e dere,</L>
<L>Ouer al o&thorn;er &thorn;at &thorn;er were.</L>
<L>Of his coupe serue he him dede,</L>
<L>He was preysed to him in euerich stede:</L>
<L N="155">&thorn;erl michel him wor&thorn;schipede,</L>
<L>&amp; for his fader loue to him clepede.</L>
<L>Gij of Warwike his name was,<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="123"></L>
<L>In court non better beloued &thorn;er nas,</L>
<L>So he was among gret lordinges,</L>
<L N="160">Litel &amp; michel in al &thorn;inges.</L>
<L>Gentil he was &amp; of michel mi&yogh;t,</L>
<L>Ouer al o&thorn;er feirest bi si&yogh;t<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. bisi&yogh;t</NOTE>:</L>
<L>Al &thorn;ai wonderd strongliche,</L>
<L>For his feirhed was so miche;</L>
<L N="165">So mani godenes in him were,</L>
<L>Al him preysed &thorn;er y-fere,</L>
<L>Of bordis &amp; turnament y-wis,</L>
<L>Kni&yogh;tes to hauen &amp; holden of pris.</L>
<L>Gij a forster fader hadde,<MILESTONE N="108a:2" UNIT="folio"><MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="139"></L>
<L N="170">&thorn;at him lerd &amp; him radde
<PB REF="00000016.tif" N="12"></L>
<L>Of wodes &amp; riuer &amp; o&thorn;er game:</L>
<L>Herhaud of Ardern was his name.</L>
<L>He was hende &amp; wele y-tau&yogh;t,</L>
<L>Gij to lern for&yogh;at he nau&yogh;t;</L>
<L N="175">Michel he cou&thorn;e of hauk &amp; hounde,</L>
<L>Of estriche faucouns of gret mounde.</L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L N="185">It was opon a Pentecost day yteld,<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="143"></L>
<L>&thorn;erl a gret fest held</L>
<L>At Warwike in &thorn;at cite,</L>
<L>&thorn;at &thorn;an was y-won to be.</L>
<L>&thorn;ider cam men of miche mi&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="190">Erls &amp; barouns bo&thorn;e apli&yogh;t,</L>
<L>Leuedis &amp; maidens of gret mounde,</L>
<L>&thorn;at in &thorn;e lond wer y-founde.</L>
<L>Eueriche maiden ches hir loue</L>
<L>Of kni&yogh;tes &thorn;at wer &thorn;ider y-come,</L>
<L N="195">&amp; euerich kni&yogh;t his leman</L>
<L>Of &thorn;at gentil maiden wiman;</L>
<L>When &thorn;ai were fro chirche y-come,</L>
<L>&thorn;er ali&yogh;t mani a noble gome.</L>
<L>&thorn;erl to &thorn;e mete was sett,</L>
<L N="200">Gij stode forn him in &thorn;at flett,</L>
<L>&thorn;at was &thorn;e steward sone,</L>
<L>&thorn;erl to serue it was his wone.</L>
<L>To him he cleped Gij,</L>
<L>&amp; him hete &amp; comandi</L>
<L N="205">&thorn;at he in to chaumber went,</L>
<L>&amp; grete wele &thorn;at maiden gent,
<PB REF="00000018.tif" N="14"></L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;at he schuld &thorn;at ich day</L>
<L>Serue wele &thorn;at feir may.</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="section">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Gij him answerd freliche:<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="159"></L>
<L N="210">'Sir, ichil wel ble&thorn;eliche.'</L>
<L>In a kirtel of silk he gan him schrede,</L>
<L>Into chaumber wel sone he &yogh;ede.</L>
<L>&THORN;e kirtel bicom him swi&thorn;e wel,</L>
<L>To Amenden &thorn;er on was neuer a del;</L>
<L N="215">&THORN;e maidens biheld him feir &amp; wel,</L>
<L>For &thorn;at he was so gentil.</L>
<L>Gij on his knes sone him sett,<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="161"></L>
<L>&amp; on hir fader half he hir grett,</L>
<L>&amp; seyd he was &thorn;ider sent</L>
<L N="220">To serue hir to hir talent.</L>
<L>Felice answerd &thorn;an to Gij<MILESTONE N="108b:1" UNIT="folio"><MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="167"></L>
<L>'Bieus amis, molt gramerci.'</L>
<L>&amp; se&thorn;&thorn;e sche asked him in &thorn;e plas</L>
<L>Whennes he cam, &amp; what he was.</L>
<L N="225">'Mi fader,' he seyd, 'hat Suward,</L>
<L>&thorn;at is &thorn;i fader steward,</L>
<L>&thorn;at wi&thorn; him me ha&thorn; y-held</L>
<L>&amp; for&thorn; y-brou&yogh;t, God him for-&yogh;eld!'</L>
<L>'Artow,' sche seyd, 'Suward sone,</L>
<L N="230">&thorn;at of al godenes ha&thorn; &thorn;e wone?'</L>
<L>Gij stode stille &amp; seyd nou&yogh;t.</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; &thorn;at was the water for&thorn; brou&yogh;t:</L>
<L>&thorn;ai sett hem to mete anon,</L>
<L>Erl, baroun, sweyn &amp; grom.</L>
<L N="235">&para; Gij was bisy &thorn;at ich day</L>
<L>To serue wele &thorn;at feir may.</L>
<L>&thorn;at day Gij dede his mi&yogh;t</L>
<L>To serue &thorn;ritti maidens bri&yogh;t;</L>
<L>Al an-amourd on him &thorn;ai were,</L>
<L N="240">&amp; loued Gij for his feir chere.</L>
<L>&thorn;er of no &yogh;af he ri&yogh;t nou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>Al ano&thorn;er it was his &thorn;ou&yogh;t:
<PB REF="00000020.tif" N="16"></L>
<L>On Felice &thorn;at was so bri&yogh;t,</L>
<L>Gij hir loued wi&thorn; al his mi&yogh;t;</L>
<L N="245">So michel sche was in his &thorn;ou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>&thorn;at neye he was to de&thorn; y-brou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>He gan to wepe &amp; sore siche,</L>
<L>&amp; biment him wel reweliche;</L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L N="251">&amp; grete wonder he hadde y-wis</L>
<L>&thorn;at Felice so feir a creatour is.</L>
<L>Ac he no dar his loue ke&thorn;e,</L>
<L>No sen hir wel vnne&thorn;e,</L>
<L N="255">He is in so gret &thorn;ou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>His conseyl wil he schewe nou&yogh;t.</L>
<L>Into &thorn;e maidens chaumber he is y-go,<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="187"></L>
<L>At Felice he tok his leue &thorn;o,</L>
<L>&amp; in his way he go&thorn; apli&yogh;t.</L>
<L N="260">Vnto his chamber he went ful ri&yogh;t,</L>
<L>&amp; wepe &amp; made grete wo,</L>
<L>For he loued &thorn;at maiden so.</L>
<L>His men axed him on hy,</L>
<L>Whi &thorn;at he was so sori?</L>
<L N="265">He hem answerd sone anon,</L>
<L>&thorn;at swiche iuel is comen him on</L>
<L>&thorn;at he wene&thorn; his liif forgon,<MILESTONE N="108b:2" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Bote no tit him neuer non.</L>
<L>In &thorn;e court biment was Gij;<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="207"></L>
<L N="270">Mani man for him was sori,</L>
<L>For he was won to serue hem wel,</L>
<L>&amp; &yogh;if hem mani a iuwel.</L>
<L>Now is Gij in gret tempest,</L>
<L>Sorwe he make&thorn; wi&thorn; &thorn;e mest</L>
<L N="275">Of Felice &thorn;at feir may;</L>
<L>For hir loue he sorwe&thorn; ay.</L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L>
<PB REF="00000022.tif" N="18">. . . . . </L>
<L>&amp; grete wonder he ha&thorn; y-wis</L>
<L N="280">&THORN;at him so hard bifallen is;</L>
<L>He acursed &thorn;e time &thorn;at [he] hir say,</L>
<L>Felice wi&thorn; hir ey&yogh;en gray,</L>
<L>Hir gray ey&yogh;en, hir nebbis schene:</L>
<L>'For hir mi liif is miche in wene.</L>
<L N="285">To hir ichil tellen al mi &thorn;ou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>Whi &thorn;at icham in sorwe brou&yogh;t.</L>
<L>Tide me gode o&thorn;er qued,</L>
<L>Y nil it hele for no nede,</L>
<L>Ri&yogh;t to hir that y ne go</L>
<L N="290">&amp; schewe hir of mi miche wo.</L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L>&para; Ac now to hir schewen y nille;</L>
<L>Allas, wreche, hou may i duelle?</L>
<L N="295"></L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L>For mi lordes douhter sche is,</L>
<L>&amp; ich his nori, forso&thorn;e y-wis;</L>
<L>&THORN;erfore ich au&yogh;t him trewe&thorn;e bere,</L>
<L N="300">&amp; neuer more him to dere.</L>
<L>&YOGH;if ich hir loued, &amp; it wist he,</L>
<L>&amp; he mi&yogh;t ouer-take me,</L>
<L>He wald anon mine heued of smite,</L>
<L>O&thorn;er heye hong, for that wite,</L>
<L N="305">O&thorn;er hewe me wi&thorn; swerdes kene,</L>
<L>&YOGH;if ich hadde don him &thorn;at tene.</L>
<L>Allas, wreche, what may y do?</L>
<L>Y loue &thorn;ing y no may com to!'</L>
<L>&para; Now is Gij in sorwe ybrou&yogh;t;<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="191"></L>
<L N="310">Of his liif nis him nou&yogh;t.</L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L>He went and trent his bed opon,</L>
<L>So man &thorn;at is wo bigon;
<PB REF="00000024.tif" N="20"></L>
<L N="315">He no may sitt no stonde,</L>
<L>No vnne&thorn;e drawen his onde;</L>
<L>Rest, no take slepeinge,</L>
<L>Mete ete, no drinke dringe;</L>
<L>No may him noman comforti,<MILESTONE N="109a:1" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="320">Bot euer his song is wo &amp; wi.</L>
<L>In so gret &thorn;ou&yogh;t was he &thorn;o,</L>
<L>&amp; so gret sorwe toke him to,</L>
<L>Leuer him wer walk &amp; wende,</L>
<L>&amp; dye in trewe loue bende.</L>
<L N="325">&para; &THORN;us [Gij] lay in grete turment</L>
<L>Til &thorn;at &thorn;e fest was al to-went.</L>
<L>Swiche an iuel is on him fast,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he no may it of him cast;</L>
<L>He no wil noman his care schewe.</L>
<L N="330">His sorwes ben euer aliche newe,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he no may his loue haue,</L>
<L>Grete streng&thorn;e him do&thorn; wi&thorn;-drawe.</L>
<L>&THORN;er-fore he seyd, 'ichil hir schewe,</L>
<L>My peyne is euer aliche newe;</L>
<L N="335">Of al mi sorwe nis hir nou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>Ich wold ich were to de&thorn; y-brou&yogh;t.</L>
<L>Bitide me iuel o&thorn;er gode,</L>
<L>Ichil it held in mi mode;</L>
<L>&amp; &yogh;if sche wil, sche may me spille,</L>
<L N="340">Ac for al &thorn;at leten y nille.'</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="section">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Now is Gij to court y-go,<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="215"></L>
<L>As<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>As</I> illegible in MS.</NOTE> man &thorn;at is ful of wo,</L>
<L>&amp; on his knes he him dede</L>
<L>Bifor Felice in &thorn;at stede,</L>
<L N="345">&amp; to hir he spac wel euen</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; a wel queynt steuen,</L>
<L>&amp; seyd, 'Felice &thorn;e feir, merci!</L>
<L>For godes loue &amp; our leuedi,</L>
<L>&THORN;at y &thorn;e no finde mi dedliche fo,</L>
<L N="350">For godes loue herken me to!
<PB REF="00000026.tif" N="22"></L>
<L>No longer hele y nille,</L>
<L>Al that so&thorn;e tellen y wille.</L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L N="355"></L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L>&THORN;ou art &thorn;e &thorn;ing &thorn;at y most &yogh;erne,</L>
<L>Fro &thorn;e no may mine hert terne;</L>
<L>Opon al o&thorn;er y loue &thorn;e,</L>
<L N="360">Y no may it lete ded to be.</L>
<L>Vnder heuen no &thorn;ing nis,</L>
<L>Noi&thorn;er gode no qued y-wis,</L>
<L>&THORN;at y for &thorn;e don y<NOTE PLACE="marg">so MS.; read <I>it.</I></NOTE> nolde,</L>
<L>To lete &thorn;at liif don y wolde.</L>
<L N="365">&THORN;ou art mi liif, mi ded y-wis,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn;outen &thorn;e haue y no blis;</L>
<L>Y loue &thorn;e and tow nou&yogh;t me,<MILESTONE N="109a:2" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Y dye for &thorn;e loue of &thorn;e.</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;ou haue merci on me,</L>
<L N="370">For sorwe ichil me self sle,</L>
<L>For wistestow &thorn;e heuinisse,</L>
<L>&THORN;e sorwe and &thorn;e sorinisse,</L>
<L>&THORN;at me is on ni&yogh;t and day</L>
<L>(Bi trewe loue siggen ich it may)&mdash;</L>
<L N="375">&amp; tow it mi&yogh;t wi&thorn; ey&yogh;en se,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou wost haue merci on me.'</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="section">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Felice &thorn;e feir answerd &thorn;o,<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="219"></L>
<L>'Artow &thorn;is, Gij, so mot &thorn;ou go,</L>
<L>&THORN;e steward sone Suward,</L>
<L N="380">Ich wene &thorn;ou art a fole musard!</L>
<L>When &thorn;ou of loue me hast bisau&yogh;t,</L>
<L>Al to fole-hardy &thorn;ou art y-tau&yogh;t.</L>
<L>Wele &thorn;ou holdest me for a fole;</L>
<L>&THORN;ou art y-tau&yogh;t to a li&thorn;er scole,</L>
<L N="385">&amp; icham &thorn;i lordes douhter biname;</L>
<L>&THORN;an dostow him wel michel schame,
<PB REF="00000028.tif" N="24"></L>
<L>When &thorn;ou of loue bi-sechist me</L>
<L>&THORN;at y schold &thorn;i leman be.</L>
<L>No fond y neuer man me so missede,</L>
<L N="390">No me so of loue bede,</L>
<L>Noy&thorn;er kni&yogh;t no baroun,</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;ou &thorn;at art a garsoun,</L>
<L>&amp; art mi man, &amp; man schalt be.</L>
<L>Yuel were mi fairhed sett on &thorn;e,</L>
<L N="395">&amp; y swiche a grome toke,</L>
<L>&amp; so mani grete lordinges for-soke.</L>
<L>Erls, doukes of &thorn;e best</L>
<L>In &thorn;is world, &amp; &thorn;e richest,</L>
<L>Me haue desired apli&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="400">&THORN;at neuer of me hadde si&yogh;t.</L>
<L>&THORN;at wer gret deshonour to me!</L>
<L>Al to lo&thorn; mi liif me schuld be.</L>
<L>Al to fole-hardi &thorn;ou were,</L>
<L>When &thorn;ou me of loue bisou&yogh;test here.</L>
<L N="405">Bi mi trew&thorn;e y schal &thorn;e swere,<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="224"></L>
<L>Schal y mi fader &thorn;e tiding bere,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou wor&thorn;est to-hewen, o&thorn;er for-do,</L>
<L>(Bi &thorn;e be warned o&thorn;er mo)</L>
<L>O&thorn;er wi&thorn; wilde hors to-drawe,</L>
<L N="410">For &thorn;i foly, &amp; &thorn;at wer lawe,</L>
<L>&amp; o&thorn;er schul be warned bi &thorn;i dede,<MILESTONE N="109b:1" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&amp; her lordinges &thorn;e more drede.</L>
<L>Go he&thorn;en,' sche seyd, '&amp; vp arise,</L>
<L>&amp; cum nam-more in mi purpris!'</L>
<L N="415">&para; Wel sorwefuliche went Gij<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="235"></L>
<L>In to his chaumber al dreri:</L>
<L>Gij in to his chaumber gan to gon,</L>
<L>&amp; schett him &thorn;er in anon.</L>
<L>&THORN;er in he made sorwe anou&yogh;,</L>
<L N="420">&amp; his clo&thorn;es al to-drou&yogh;.</L>
<L>Vnder heuen nas &thorn;at it ne mi&yogh;t haue rew&thorn;e</L>
<L>Of his sorwenes &amp; of his trew&thorn;e.
<PB REF="00000030.tif" N="26"></L>
<L>Of loue he bi-ment strongliche</L>
<L>For whom &thorn;at he loued so miche:</L>
<L N="425">'Loue,' he seyd, 'slake now mi sore</L>
<L>&THORN;at is dedeliche, as y seyd ore.</L>
<L>Loue of &thorn;is &yogh;ongling</L>
<L>Make&thorn; me iuel fonding.</L>
<L>Loue, bring me of &thorn;is wodenisse,</L>
<L N="430">&amp; bring me in to sum lisse,</L>
<L>For to reste me a&thorn;rowe,</L>
<L>&THORN;at y mi&yogh;t meseluen knowe.</L>
<L>Sore me mene&thorn;, for me smert,</L>
<L>Miche care is in mine hert,</L>
<L N="435">Michel ich am y-cast of mi&yogh;t</L>
<L>Al to fer wi&thorn; vnri&yogh;t.</L>
<L>Loue me do&thorn; to grounde falle,</L>
<L>&THORN;at y ne may stond stef wi&thorn; alle.</L>
<L>Loue do&thorn; min clo&thorn;es done,</L>
<L N="440">&amp; after me clepe&thorn; 'wreche' sone.</L>
<L>Hou schal y liue? hou schal y fare?</L>
<L>Hou long schal y liuen in care?</L>
<L>Leuest &thorn;ing me were to dye,</L>
<L>&amp; ich wist bi wiche weye.</L>
<L N="445">De&thorn;,' he seyd, 'wher artow so long?</L>
<L>&THORN;ou makest me y may nou&yogh;t stond.</L>
<L>&THORN;ou makest me out of &thorn;e way to gon;</L>
<L>Whi ne comestow to feche me anon?</L>
<L>Wor&thorn;i ich were ded to be:</L>
<L N="450">Y loue &thorn;ing &thorn;at loue&thorn; nou&yogh;t me.</L>
<L>Herkene&thorn; now hou sei&thorn; &thorn;e wise:</L>
<L>Y schal &yogh;ou schewe bi &thorn;is asise.</L>
<L>For a fole he schal him held</L>
<L>&THORN;at take&thorn; more &thorn;an he may weld.</L>
<L N="455">To a fenestre &thorn;an Gij is go,<MILESTONE N="109b:2" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Biheld &thorn;e castel, &thorn;e tour also.<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="269"></L>
<L>'Tour,' he seyd, 'feir artow bisett!</L>
<L>In &thorn;e is &thorn;at maiden bischett
<PB REF="00000032.tif" N="28"></L>
<L>&THORN;at liue&thorn; &thorn;er in ioie &amp; blis,</L>
<L N="460">&amp; ichir loue for so&thorn;e y-wis.</L>
<L>Tour, when wer thou ouer-&thorn;rowe,</L>
<L>And wi&thorn; &thorn;e winde al to-blowe!</L>
<L>&THORN;at y mi&yogh;t hir wi&thorn; ey&yogh;en se</L>
<L>&THORN;at y loue more &thorn;an me!'</L>
<L N="465">He ginne&thorn; to wepe &amp; sore siche,</L>
<L>His care him newe&thorn; eueriliche;</L>
<L>Adoun he fel and swoune bigan,<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="278"></L>
<L>(More sorwe made neuer man)</L>
<L>&amp; cursed &thorn;e time &thorn;at he was bore,</L>
<L N="470">For now he ha&thorn; his witt forlore.</L>
<L>'Loue,' he seyd, 'acursed &thorn;ou be!</L>
<L>To michel mi&yogh;t it is in &thorn;e</L>
<L>&THORN;at y ne may me fro &thorn;e were;</L>
<L>Loue, merci, &thorn;atow me no dere!</L>
<L N="475">Leuer me were forto dye</L>
<L>&THORN;an long to liuen here in ey&yogh;e.</L>
<L>Allas, Felice, &thorn;at ich stounde,</L>
<L>&THORN;i loue me ha&thorn; so ybounde!</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;at y serued &thorn;e &thorn;at day,</L>
<L N="480">Acursed be &thorn;at time, seyen y may!</L>
<L>No bid ichaue non o&thorn;er mede,</L>
<L>Bot slake mi sorwe, ichaue nede.</L>
<L>Y loue &thorn;e &amp; tow nou&yogh;t me.</L>
<L>Euen dole may it nou&yogh;t be;</L>
<L N="485">For of mi sorwe no hastow nou&yogh;t.</L>
<L>Allas! to grounde icham ybrou&yogh;t!</L>
<L>&THORN;ou hast &thorn;e gode, &amp; y &thorn;e quede:</L>
<L>Y brenne so spark on glede.</L>
<L>Se&thorn;&thorn;e &thorn;ou me lokedest first to,</L>
<L N="490">&THORN;ou me woundest wi&thorn; a flo.</L>
<L>Schal y dye for &thorn;at si&yogh;t?</L>
<L>Merci, Felice, &thorn;at swete wi&yogh;t!</L>
<L>Mine hert is ful of venim spilt,</L>
<L>Of blis no wor&thorn; it neuer filt.'
<PB REF="00000034.tif" N="30"></L>
<L N="495">Swiche liif ladde Gij sikerliche</L>
<L>Al that seuenni&yogh;t holeliche.</L>
<L>His fader was for him sori,</L>
<L>Sabin his moder biment Gij,</L>
<L>&THORN;erl for him sori was,<MILESTONE N="110a:1" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="500">&THORN;er liked non in that plas:</L>
<L>Litel &amp; michel, al &amp; some,</L>
<L>Biment Gij att[e] frome.</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="section">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;erl dede &thorn;e leches of-sende<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="247"></L>
<L>Of Gyes iuel to wite &thorn;at ende.</L>
<L N="505">&THORN;e leches ben to him y-go:</L>
<L>Gij &thorn;ai finde blaike and blo;</L>
<L>Hij asked him where his iuel stode.</L>
<L>He seyd for hete he brend nere wode:</L>
<L>'So hot ich am, &amp; bren[n]inge,</L>
<L N="510">Mi sorwe is euer cominge,</L>
<L>&THORN;at al mi limes it ha&thorn; to-ti&yogh;t;</L>
<L>Swiche liif y lede day &amp; ni&yogh;t.</L>
<L>After &thorn;e hete me come&thorn; a chele</L>
<L>&THORN;at me greue&thorn; wi&thorn; vn-skele,</L>
<L N="515">&THORN;at y wex cold as ise.</L>
<L>So vn-kinde iuel it is,</L>
<L>&THORN;at al mine limes it wil to-te;</L>
<L>&amp; se&thorn;&thorn;e me come&thorn; swouninges &thorn;re,</L>
<L>For anguis swoune it me do&thorn;</L>
<L N="520">Tviis or &thorn;riis, y say for so&thorn;.</L>
<L>Swiche liif y lede ni&yogh;t &amp; day:</L>
<L>Non o&thorn;er wise y no can &yogh;ou say.'</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;an seyd &thorn;at on, 'a feuer it is.'<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="265"></L>
<L>'&YOGH;a,' quod Gij, 'a li&thorn;er y-wis.'</L>
<L N="525">&THORN;e leches gon, &amp; lete Gij one,</L>
<L>&THORN;at make&thorn; wel michel mone.</L>
<L>'God,' quod Gij, 'what schal y do?</L>
<L>Hou long schal y liuen in wo?</L>
<L>&THORN;at y no mi&yogh;t ded be,</L>
<L N="530">When y no may hir wi&thorn; ey&yogh;en se,<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="285">
<PB REF="00000036.tif" N="32"></L>
<L>&THORN;at ha&thorn; al mine hert &amp; &thorn;ou&yogh;t!</L>
<L>&amp; y no misgilt hir neuer nou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>Bot on &thorn;at ichir loue wel,</L>
<L>&amp; euer more loue schel!</L>
<L N="535">&YOGH;if ich it hir schewe, sche wil telle</L>
<L>Hir fader, &amp; he me wil quelle.</L>
<L>&THORN;ei he it wist, siker apli&yogh;t,</L>
<L>More &thorn;an me sle don he no mi&yogh;t.</L>
<L>&YOGH;if he me slou&yogh;, it were schonde,</L>
<L N="540">Schuld y &thorn;an for de&thorn; wonde;</L>
<L>To hir for so&thorn;e ichil go</L>
<L>&amp; schewe hir of mi michel wo.</L>
<L>Vnder heuen [n]is so strong &thorn;ing<MILESTONE N="110a:2" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>So is loue and wowing.</L>
<L N="545">Now,' he seyd, 'what for &thorn;an?</L>
<L>&THORN;ei ich hir loue, blame me noman;</L>
<L>To warant ichil drawe atte frome</L>
<L>&THORN;at loue do&thorn; me &thorn;ider come,</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;at loue do&thorn; me go to &thorn;e</L>
<L N="550">&THORN;at y no may wi&thorn;-hold me.'</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="section">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>With &thorn;is Gij arisen is,<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="293"></L>
<L>&amp; to &thorn;e gate go&thorn; y-wis.</L>
<L>'God,' quod Gij, 'y do foliliche:</L>
<L>Y sle me seluen sikerliche;</L>
<L N="555">Mine owhen [de&thorn;] y go now secheinde.</L>
<L>God,' he seyd, 'be mine helpinde!'</L>
<L>Adoun he fel a-swounie;</L>
<L>&amp; when he gan to dawei,</L>
<L>'To &thorn;e court,' he seyd, 'ichil go,</L>
<L N="560">Be it for wele or for wo:</L>
<L>To &thorn;e court ichil, what so bitide,</L>
<L>&THORN;ei gret streng&thorn;e me do abide.'</L>
<L>Now is Gij to court y-comen<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="295"></L>
<L>As man &thorn;at is wi&thorn; sorwe y-nome,</L>
<L N="565">&amp; in to an erber he is y-go,</L>
<L>Felice finde&thorn; &thorn;er in &thorn;o;
<PB REF="00000038.tif" N="34"></L>
<L>At hir fet he him leyd,</L>
<L>Al wepeand to hir he seyd,</L>
<L>'Felice, now ich am comen to &thorn;e,<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="304"></L>
<L N="570">&amp; &yogh;if &thorn;ou wilt, &thorn;ou mi&yogh;t m[e] sle,</L>
<L>For now icham wi&thorn;-in thi loke,</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;ine hest ichaue to-broke.</L>
<L>For ich would &thorn;atow seye</L>
<L>&THORN;e sorwe &thorn;at y for &thorn;e dreye:</L>
<L N="575">&THORN;e strong pine &amp; &thorn;e wo</L>
<L>Y dreye for &thorn;e euer-mo.</L>
<L>Mine hert schal bileue wi&thorn; &thorn;e:</L>
<L>Wiltow, niltow, it schal<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>itschal</I>.</NOTE> so be,</L>
<L>&THORN;at<NOTE PLACE="foot">read <I>&thorn;at me?</I></NOTE> mi bodi ferli<NOTE PLACE="foot">read <I>fersi?</I></NOTE> may,</L>
<L N="580">Bot &thorn;at wille it laste&thorn; ay.</L>
<L>&THORN;er while y liue, loue y &thorn;e wille,</L>
<L>&amp; bot &yogh;if y do, ichil me spille;</L>
<L>For me no schal it to-deled be</L>
<L>&THORN;er while &thorn;at liif it laste&thorn; in me;</L>
<L N="585">&THORN;e to loue no mi&yogh;tow me forbede,</L>
<L>In wo &amp; sorwe &thorn;ou dost me fede.</L>
<L>Whan it wor&thorn; &thorn;i fader y-teld<MILESTONE N="110b:1" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&THORN;atow hast mine hert in weld,</L>
<L>&amp; he wite that y loue &thorn;e,</L>
<L N="590">Ichot for so&thorn;e he wil me sle;</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;at schal turn me al to blis</L>
<L>When y schal dye for so&thorn;e y-wis.</L>
<L>Henne forward ne reche y me</L>
<L>Of mi liif, whare it be,</L>
<L N="595">No of mi de&thorn; neuer &thorn;e mo</L>
<L>No reche y neuer where y go.'</L>
<L>He ferd as he wer mat,<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="317"></L>
<L>Adoun he fel aswoune wi&thorn; &thorn;at;</L>
<L>Felice stode &amp; loked him to</L>
<L N="600">&amp; biheld his strong wo;</L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L>
<PB REF="00000040.tif" N="36">. . . . . </L>
<L>To a mayde sche seyd &thorn;o:</L>
<L>'Take him vp in &thorn;ine armes to,</L>
<L N="605">&amp; lay him soft on &thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. <I>on&thorn;e</I></NOTE> grounde';</L>
<L>&amp; sche dede so in &thorn;at stounde.</L>
<L>&THORN;at mayden &yogh;ede to him wepeinde,</L>
<L>&amp; Gij wel sore biminde:</L>
<L>'Bi god<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. <I>Bigod</I></NOTE> of heuen,' sche seyd,</L>
<L N="610">&amp; ich wer as feir a mayd,<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="330"></L>
<L>&amp; as riche kinges douhter were</L>
<L>As ani in &thorn;is warld here,</L>
<L>&amp; he of mi loue vnder-nome were,</L>
<L>As he is of &thorn;ine in strong manere,</L>
<L N="615">&amp; he wald me so o loue &yogh;erne,</L>
<L>Me &thorn;enke y no my&yogh;t it him nou&yogh;t werne.'</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="section">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Felice the feir answerd &thorn;o:</L>
<L>'Damisel,' sche seyd, 'whi seistow so?</L>
<L>&THORN;ou art to blame, al-so y se,</L>
<L N="620">No-&thorn;ing &thorn;er-mid no paistow me.</L>
<L>Oft &thorn;ou hast y-herd in speche</L>
<L>&THORN;at we no schal no man biseche,</L>
<L>Ac men schul biseche wimen</L>
<L>In the feirest maner &thorn;at &thorn;ai can,</L>
<L N="625">&amp; fond to speden &yogh;if &thorn;ai may</L>
<L>Bo&thorn;e bi<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. <I>bini&yogh;tes</I></NOTE> ni&yogh;tes and bi day.'</L>
<L>Of his swouning he vpros &thorn;o;</L>
<L>&THORN;e maiden him tok in armes to.</L>
<L>Felice seyd to Gij, '&thorn;ou dost folie,</L>
<L N="630">&THORN;atow wilt for mi loue dye;</L>
<L>Schal y do mi fader of-sende?</L>
<L>I schal him telle word &amp; ende,</L>
<L>&THORN;at tow dost me litel wor&thorn;schipe,<MILESTONE N="110b:2" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>When &thorn;ou me desirest to schenschipe;</L>
<L N="635">In his court he schal deme &thorn;e,</L>
<L>&amp; al to-lime, to queme me.'</L>
<L>&para; Gij answerd anon &thorn;er-to,</L>
<L>'God &yogh;eue &thorn;at it wer y-do,
<PB REF="00000042.tif" N="38"></L>
<L>&THORN;at of mi de&thorn; &thorn;ou haddest<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. <I>&thorn;ouhaddest</I></NOTE> wite!</L>
<L N="640">Of mi liif is me bot lite;</L>
<L>Redi ich am it to vnder-fong,</L>
<L>Be it wi&thorn; ri&yogh;t, be it wi&thorn; wrong.'</L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L>&para; Felice hadde of him gret rew&thorn;e:<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="341"></L>
<L>'Gij,' quod [sche], '&thorn;ou louest me in trew&thorn;e;</L>
<L>Al to michel &thorn;ou art afoild,</L>
<L N="650">Now &thorn;i blod it is acoild.</L>
<L>Ac o thing y grant &thorn;e;</L>
<L>More no mi&yogh;tow asky me:</L>
<L>&THORN;er nis leuedi, no maiden non,</L>
<L>In &thorn;is cuntre so wide so man may gon,</L>
<L N="655">&amp; tow louedest hir astow dost me</L>
<L>&THORN;at sche no wold grant hir loue to &thorn;e.'</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="section">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Gij seyd to Felice, 'now lete &thorn;is be;</L>
<L>Now me &thorn;enke &thorn;ou scornnest me.</L>
<L>Nis me nou&yogh;t iuel anou&yogh; y-di&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="660">When &thorn;ou wilt of me no-wi&yogh;t?</L>
<L>Now a fole<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. <I>afole</I></NOTE> ich-il be</L>
<L>&amp; mi witt chaunge for &thorn;e!'</L>
<L>'Gij,' seyd Felice, 'now vnder-stond:<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="355"></L>
<L>For now nil y no&thorn;ing wond;</L>
<L N="665">&amp; &thorn;ei y say &thorn;e al mi wille,</L>
<L>No hold it for non vn-skille:</L>
<L>No grome louen y no may</L>
<L>Fort he be kni&yogh;t forso&thorn; to say,</L>
<L>Feir &amp; beld to tellen by,</L>
<L N="670">S[t]rong in armes &amp; hardi;</L>
<L>&amp; when &thorn;ou hast armes vnder-fong,</L>
<L>&amp; ichaue it vnder-stonde,</L>
<L>&THORN;an schaltow haue &thorn;e loue of me,</L>
<L>&YOGH;if &thorn;ow be swiche as y telle &thorn;e.'
</L>
</LG>

</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="section"><PB REF="00000044.tif" N="40">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="675">When Gij herd &thorn;at tiding,<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="384"></L>
<L>For ioie his hert gan to spring;</L>
<L>At hir he tok leue anon,</L>
<L>In-to the castel he gan to gon;</L>
<L>Al so swi&thorn;e as he it mi&yogh;t do,</L>
<L N="680">In-to the court he gan to go:</L>
<L>Of euerich day him &thorn;ought ten<MILESTONE N="111a:1" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Fort he seye his<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>s</I> added over the line.</NOTE> lemen.</L>
<L>&amp; when he feld him hole &amp; fere,<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="375"></L>
<L>He went to court wi&thorn; glad chere;</L>
<L N="685">Michel ioie wi&thorn; him &thorn;ai made,</L>
<L>&amp; alle &thorn;ai wer bli&thorn;e &amp; glade.</L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L>To &thorn;erl &thorn;an went Gij,</L>
<L N="690">&amp; gret &thorn;at kni&yogh;t hardi,</L>
<L>&amp; seyd, 'sir, &thorn;ine armes ich ax;</L>
<L>&YOGH;if ich am &thorn;er to y-wax,</L>
<L>Ich am redi hem to fong,</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;e to serue wi&thorn;-outen wrong.'</L>
<L N="695">&THORN;erl answerd, &amp; seyd &thorn;o,</L>
<L>'Ble&thorn;eliche, Gij, se&thorn;&thorn;e &thorn;ou wilt so.'<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="365"></L>
<L>&para; &THORN;erl dede anon aparaile</L>
<L>Gyes dobing wi&thorn;-outen feyle;</L>
<L>Wel richelich he dubbed Gij,</L>
<L N="700">&amp; wi&thorn; him felawes tventi,</L>
<L>&THORN;at al barouns sones were</L>
<L>(For Gyes loue he dubbed hem &thorn;ere),</L>
<L>&THORN;at wi&thorn; &thorn;erl Rohaud hadde ben long,</L>
<L>In his seruise armes to vnder-fong.</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="section">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="705">It was at &thorn;e holy trinite,</L>
<L>&THORN;erl dubbed sir Gij &thorn;e fre,</L>
<L>&amp; wi&thorn; him tventi god gomis,</L>
<L>Kni&yogh;tes and riche baroun sonis.</L>
<L>Of cloth of Tars &amp; riche cendel</L>
<L N="710">Was he[r] dobbeing euerich a del;
<PB REF="00000046.tif" N="42"></L>
<L>&THORN;e panis al of fow &amp; griis,</L>
<L>&THORN;e mantels weren of michel priis,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; riche armour &amp; gode stedes,</L>
<L>&THORN;e best &thorn;at wer in lond at nedis.</L>
<L N="715">Alder-best was Gij y-di&yogh;t,</L>
<L>&THORN;ei he wer an emperour sone, apli&yogh;t:</L>
<L>So richeliche dobbed was he,</L>
<L>Nas no swiche in &thorn;is cuntre;</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; riche stedes wele erninde,</L>
<L N="720">Palfreys, coursours wele bereinde.</L>
<L>No was &thorn;er noi&thorn;er sweyn no knaue,</L>
<L>&THORN;at ou&yogh;t failed &thorn;at he schuld haue.</L>
<L>&para; Now is sir Gij dobbed to kni&yogh;t;</L>
<L>Feir he was and michel of mi&yogh;t.</L>
<L N="725">To Felice went sir Gij,<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="429"></L>
<L>&amp; gret hir wel curteyslie,</L>
<L>&amp; seyd, 'ichaue don astow seydest me to,<MILESTONE N="111a:2" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>For &thorn;e ichaue suffred miche wo:</L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L>Arme for &thorn;e ichaue vnder-fong,</L>
<L>&THORN;e to se me &thorn;ou&yogh;t long.</L>
<L>&THORN;ou art me bo&thorn;e leue &amp; dere,</L>
<L>Ich am y-comen &thorn;i wille to here.'</L>
<L N="735">&para; 'Gij,' seyd Felice, 'heye &thorn;e nou&yogh;t:</L>
<L>&YOGH;ete hastow no &thorn;ing of armes y-wrou&yogh;t.</L>
<L>No artow &thorn;e better neuer a del</L>
<L>&THORN;an &thorn;ou wer ere, y say &thorn;e wel,</L>
<L>Bot on &thorn;atow [hast] newe dobing,</L>
<L N="740">&amp; art cleped kni&yogh;t wi&thorn;-outen lesing;</L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L>
<PB REF="00000048.tif" N="44">. . . . . </L>
<L>Bot it be &thorn;urch &thorn;i mi&yogh;t,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou no mi&yogh;t chalang loue &thorn;urch ri&yogh;t.'</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="section">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>When Gij herd Felice so speke,<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="445"></L>
<L N="750">He tok his leue and gan out reke;</L>
<L>At hir leue he tok anon,</L>
<L>&amp; to his fader he gan to gon,</L>
<L>&amp; seyd, 'fader, vnder-stond me:</L>
<L>Icham newe dobbed as &yogh;e may se,</L>
<L N="755">Ouer &thorn;e se ichil now fare</L>
<L>To win priis &amp; los &thorn;are.'</L>
<L>His fader him answerd sone,</L>
<L>'Sone, god leue &thorn;e wele to done!<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="475"></L>
<L>&amp; als michel as &thorn;e nede be,</L>
<L N="760">Sone, schaltow haue wi&thorn; &thorn;e.'</L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L>&para; Suward cleped Herhaud to him,</L>
<L>&amp; seyd, 'Herhaud, frende min,</L>
<L N="765">Wi&thorn; Gi mi sone schaltow wende;</L>
<L>In gode stede mot &yogh;e lende.</L>
<L>&THORN;ou schalt kepe mi sone Gij,</L>
<L>For he is mi sone &amp; tow mi norri.</L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L>Loke, Herhaud, &thorn;at tow him kepe;</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;ine felawes &thorn;at ben &yogh;epe,</L>
<L>Bo&thorn;e Torold &amp; sir Vrri,</L>
<L>On &yogh;ou y trust sikerli;</L>
<L N="775">&amp; wi&thorn; Herhaud schul &yogh;e go</L>
<L>To kepe mi sone from care &amp; wo.'</L>
<L>&amp; hii answerd sone anon,</L>
<L>'Hastiliche, sir, wil we wi&thorn; him gon.'</L>
<L>&THORN;ai weren bo&thorn;e strong kni&yogh;tes,</L>
<L N="780">Bold and hardi in ich fi&yogh;tes.<NOTE PLACE="marg">altered to <I>fi&yogh;ttes</I> in MS.</NOTE></L>
<L>Gij tok wi&thorn; him what he wold<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="485"></L>
<L>Bo&thorn;e of siluer &amp; of gold.
<PB REF="00000050.tif" N="46"></L>
<L>To &thorn;e se &thorn;ai ben now y-come,<MILESTONE N="111b:1" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&amp; seyled ouer atte frome.<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="500"></L>
<L N="785">&THORN;ai comen in-to Normondye,</L>
<L>Knight-schippe &thorn;ai sechen on heye;</L>
<L>In Ron Gij take&thorn; his herberwe</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; &thorn;e richest man of &thorn;e borwe;</L>
<L>Mete &amp; drink &thorn;ai hadde anou&yogh;,</L>
<L N="790">Nas &thorn;er non &thorn;at it wi&thorn;-drou&yogh;.</L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L>Sir Gij his ost cleped him to,</L>
<L>&amp; him bi-gan to frein &thorn;o,</L>
<L N="795">&amp; asked him wher &thorn;e turnament schuld be,</L>
<L>So mani scheldes &thorn;an seye he.</L>
<L>His ost seyd, 'sir, wite &yogh;e nou&yogh;t<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="511"></L>
<L>Of &thorn;is turnament &thorn;at is bi&thorn;ou&yogh;t?'</L>
<L>'No,' seyd Gij, 'bi mine wite,</L>
<L N="800">Y no herd &thorn;er-of neuer &yogh;ete.'</L>
<L>His ost him answerd snelle,</L>
<L>'Of &thorn;at turnament y schal &yogh;ou telle:</L>
<L>It schal be for a maiden of pris,</L>
<L>&THORN;emperours douhter sche is;</L>
<L N="805">A turnament he ha&thorn; don grede,</L>
<L>A swi&thorn;e michel &amp; vn-rede.</L>
<L>&THORN;er nis no kni&yogh;t in Speyne,<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="521"></L>
<L>Al to &thorn;e se of Breteyne,</L>
<L>&THORN;at ou&yogh;t y-told wi&thorn; be,</L>
<L N="810">&THORN;er men schal his mi&yogh;t se.</L>
<L>He &thorn;at best do&thorn; &thorn;at day,</L>
<L>&THORN;er he schal winne &thorn;at play.</L>
<L>Of euerich londe &thorn;ider com kni&yogh;tes,</L>
<L>&THORN;at strong ben &amp; bold in fi&yogh;tes;</L>
<L N="815">For who that is gode &amp; snelle,</L>
<L>As ichaue herd o&thorn;er men telle,</L>
<L>Who &thorn;at &thorn;er be of mest mi&yogh;t,</L>
<L>Grete wor&thorn;schipe he winne&thorn;, apli&yogh;t.
<PB REF="00000052.tif" N="48"></L>
<L>For &thorn;e maiden y spac of er,</L>
<L N="820">Is &thorn;emperours douhter Reyner;</L>
<L>He schal bring to &thorn;e turment &thorn;at day</L>
<L>(Wele is him &thorn;at it winne may)</L>
<L>A ger-fauk &thorn;at is milke white<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="537"></L>
<L>(To him nis nowhare his liche),</L>
<L N="825">&amp; a stede of gret bounte</L>
<L>(He no schuld be &yogh;ouen for a cuntre).</L>
<L>&amp; tvai grehoundes &thorn;at white ben</L>
<L>(Swiche no ha&thorn; men nowhare y-sen).</L>
<L>&amp; who so winne&thorn; &thorn;e turnament al<MILESTONE N="111b:2" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="830">Bi ai&thorn;er half, &thorn;e priis have schal,</L>
<L>&THORN;e gerfauk &amp; &thorn;e gode stede</L>
<L>Bo&thorn;e he schal haue to mede,</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;e tvay grehoundes &thorn;at gode be&thorn;</L>
<L>He schal haue &thorn;at &thorn;er best de&thorn;,</L>
<L N="835">&amp; &thorn;e maiden &thorn;at is so fre,</L>
<L>Bot he haue a fairer in his cuntre.'</L>
<L>&para; When sir Gij herd &thorn;at tiding,<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="549"></L>
<L>Glad he was wi&thorn;-outen lesing;</L>
<L>Sir Gij seyd to his fere,</L>
<L N="840">'In gode time come we here:</L>
<L>To morwe, so sone so it is day,</L>
<L>We wil wenden in our way.'</L>
<L>Sir [Gij] his ost a palfrey &yogh;af &thorn;o,</L>
<L>For &thorn;e tiding he teld him to.</L>
<L N="845">Anon amorwe wel erliche</L>
<L>&THORN;ai don hem in her wai sikerliche.</L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L>Of rideing wil &thorn;ai neuer stent</L>
<L N="850">To &thorn;ai com to &thorn;e turnament.</L>
<L>&amp; when &thorn;ai wer &thorn;ider y-come,</L>
<L>&THORN;ai seye &thorn;er mani dou&yogh;ti gome:</L>
<L>Bi feldes &amp; bi riuers ridinde</L>
<L>Mani a kni&yogh;t &thorn;ai seye cominde.
<PB REF="00000054.tif" N="50"></L>
<L N="855">&amp; when &thorn;ai were &thorn;ider y-come,</L>
<L>To &thorn;e turnament &thorn;ai went al &amp; some;</L>
<L>Out of &thorn;e rengge &thorn;ai gun hem di&yogh;t,</L>
<L>&THORN;e barouns &thorn;at were of miche mi&yogh;t.</L>
<L>&THORN;an oxed anon sir Gij</L>
<L N="860">To &thorn;e barouns &thorn;at oned<NOTE PLACE="marg">read <I>houed?</I></NOTE> him bi:</L>
<L>'What is he, &thorn;at ich kni&yogh;t,<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="570"></L>
<L>&THORN;at out of &thorn;e renge ha&thorn; him di&yogh;t,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; &thorn;o armes bri&yogh;t &amp; schene?'</L>
<L>Hii answerd anon: 'y wene,</L>
<L N="865">It is a kni&yogh;t of miche priis,</L>
<L>Douhti he is bi Seyn Deniis;</L>
<L>Out of &thorn;e rengge he ha&thorn; him di&yogh;t,</L>
<L>&YOGH;if he mi&yogh;t finden ani kni&yogh;t</L>
<L>&THORN;at wi&thorn; him wald iusti;</L>
<L N="870">&THORN;er-to he make&thorn; him redi.'</L>
<L>O&yogh;aines sir Gij &thorn;er come Gayer,</L>
<L>To iuste wi&thorn; him he drou&yogh; him ner;</L>
<L>He rode to him as a gode kni&yogh;t,</L>
<L>He semed a man<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. <I>aman</I></NOTE> of miche mi&yogh;t.</L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L>Gaier smot sir Gij bifore<MILESTONE N="112a:1" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;urch &thorn;e scheld<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. <I>&thorn;escheld</I></NOTE> him ha&thorn; i-bore;</L>
<L>&THORN;e launce brak, &thorn;at was wele wrou&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="880">&THORN;e hauberk was gode &amp; failed nou&yogh;t.</L>
<L>Gij afterward Gaier smot,</L>
<L>To grounde he feld him fot hot,</L>
<L>&THORN;e stede toke bi the reyn,</L>
<L>&amp; lepe vp wi&thorn; gret meyn.</L>
<L N="885">Now ginne&thorn; &thorn;e turnamint:<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="582"></L>
<L>Ich smit on o&thorn;er wel gode dint;</L>
<L>&THORN;ai smiten togider for so&thorn;, y pli&yogh;t,</L>
<L>Eueriche to nim o&thorn;er dede his mi&yogh;t.</L>
<L>Wel mani kni&yogh;tes Gij wan &thorn;at day,</L>
<L N="890">Of &thorn;e maistri he wan &thorn;at play;
<PB REF="00000056.tif" N="52"></L>
<L>So mani helmes he to-drof,</L>
<L>&THORN;at mani man wonderd &thorn;er-of:</L>
<L>Sat he neuer so wel no so fast,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he no feld him sone on hast.</L>
<L N="895">&THORN;e douke Otus of Pauie</L>
<L>To Gij he hadde envie;</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; him he wald iusti,</L>
<L>It turned him to vilani.</L>
<L>&THORN;e douke come prikiand on his stede</L>
<L N="900">&THORN;at certeyne was, and gode at nede,</L>
<L>&amp; sir Gij on ano&thorn;er al-so;</L>
<L>Gode kni&yogh;tes &thorn;ai weren bo.</L>
<L>Gij &thorn;urch &thorn;e scholder him smot,<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="603"></L>
<L>&amp; feld him to grounde fot hot.</L>
<L N="905">&para; &THORN;e douke Reyner seye &thorn;at cas</L>
<L>Of Sessione: wel modi he was.</L>
<L>He come als swi&thorn;e as he mi&yogh;t driue,</L>
<L>Gij to smite he heyed bliue,</L>
<L>&amp; seyd to him: 'in iuel stounde</L>
<L N="910">&YOGH;af &thorn;ou &thorn;e douke Otous wounde.</L>
<L>To wro&thorn;er hele iuste &thorn;ou wi&thorn; him.</L>
<L>He is mi germain cosyn:</L>
<L>Icham &thorn;e douke Reyner &thorn;at to &thorn;e speke;</L>
<L>Icham y-comen him to awreke:</L>
<L N="915">Turn &thorn;e and iuste wi&thorn; me.'</L>
<L>'Ble&thorn;eliche,' quod Gij, 'bi my leute.'</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="section">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Gij him turned &amp; gan to smite;<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="617"></L>
<L>He nold spare him bot lite;</L>
<L>He smot &thorn;e douke on &thorn;e scheld,</L>
<L N="920">&THORN;at it fleye in &thorn;e feld,</L>
<L>&amp; bar &thorn;e douke Reyner saunfeil<MILESTONE N="112a:2" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Ouer &amp; oue[r] his hors tayl.</L>
<L>&THORN;e stede bi &thorn;e reyn he ha&thorn; y-nome,</L>
<L>O&yogh;ain to &thorn;e douke he is y-come.</L>
<L N="925">'Here is &thorn;ine hors, y &yogh;iue it te;</L>
<L>When ichaue nede, aquite it me!'
<PB REF="00000058.tif" N="54"></L>
<L>&amp; wele he &yogh;alt him his while,</L>
<L>As gode kni&yogh;t wi&thorn;-outen gile;</L>
<L>I schal &yogh;ou tel feir &amp; wel</L>
<L N="930">Hou he it &yogh;ald him eueridel.</L>
<L>When &thorn;e douk Otus y-seye &thorn;is,<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="627"></L>
<L>To-&yogh;aines Gij he come, y-wis:</L>
<L>'Sir kni&yogh;t,' he seyd, 'y prey &thorn;e,</L>
<L>Tel me &thorn;i name<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. <I>&thorn;iname</I></NOTE> and whenne tow be.'</L>
<L N="935">&para; Sir Gij answerd wel freliche,</L>
<L>'Y schal &thorn;e tel ful ble&thorn;eliche:</L>
<L>Gij of Warwike men clepe&thorn; me;</L>
<L>Ich was y-born in &thorn;at cuntre.'</L>
<L>&THORN;e douk Lowayn cam wi&thorn; &thorn;is,</L>
<L N="940">A gode spere in his hond, y-wis;</L>
<L>To Gij he smot wi&thorn; gret hete,</L>
<L>&amp; Gij o&yogh;ain to him smite:</L>
<L>To-gider so hard gun &thorn;ai driue,</L>
<L>&THORN;at her speres gan al to-riue.</L>
<L N="945">&THORN;ai smiten togider hard &amp; wel</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; her swerdes of grounden stiel</L>
<L>&THORN;urch scheld &amp; hauberk also:</L>
<L>Strong fi&yogh;t was bi-tven hem to.</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; that come Herhaud priking;</L>
<L N="950">&THORN;e douk he met coming,</L>
<L>&amp; of his hors him ha&thorn; y-feld</L>
<L>Ri&yogh;t long stre&yogh;t in &thorn;e feld.</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; &thorn;at come &thorn;e douke Gaudiner,</L>
<L>&amp; mett wi&thorn; sir Torold &thorn;er;</L>
<L N="955">Sir Torold smot him on &thorn;e scheld,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he feld him in the feld;</L>
<L>He semed kni&yogh;t gode &amp; hardi.</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; &thorn;at come prikeing sir Urri;<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="648"></L>
<L>&THORN;an gan &thorn;e fi&yogh;t to ben aferd;</L>
<L N="960">Of swiche ne haue &yogh;e nou&yogh;t y-herd,</L>
<L>No ich it nou&yogh;t telle no mi&yogh;t,</L>
<L>For long dueling, y &yogh;ou pli&yogh;t,
<PB REF="00000060.tif" N="56"></L>
<L>No no clerk vnder sonne,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;e so&thorn;e &yogh;ou telle conne;<MILESTONE N="112b:1" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="965">Bot al &thorn;e folk of &thorn;at cuntre</L>
<L>Seyd &thorn;at Gij &thorn;e best mi&yogh;t be.</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;at o&thorn;er day y-same</L>
<L>Sir Gij wan &thorn;at ich game;</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;er-fore, on euerich a side,</L>
<L N="970">On him was leyd al &thorn;e pride.</L>
<L>So opon &thorn;e &thorn;ridde day</L>
<L>&THORN;e kni&yogh;tes tok her leue and went oway.<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="660"></L>
<L>&para; Wi&thorn; &thorn;is come &thorn;e douk prikeing,</L>
<L>A gode kni&yogh;t and wele doing.</L>
<L N="975">'Lordinges,' he seyd, 'herkene&thorn; to me:</L>
<L>Ichil &yogh;ou telle hou it schal be;</L>
<L>&amp; who so &thorn;er-o&yogh;ain sey ou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>Of bateyl no &thorn;arf him feyl nou&yogh;t.'</L>
<L>&THORN;ai seyden al couinliche,</L>
<L N="980">&THORN;e dome was &yogh;ouen sikerliche;</L>
<L>&THORN;e gerfauk and &thorn;e gode stede,</L>
<L>&THORN;e grehoundes schul haue to mede</L>
<L>Gij of Warwike, &thorn;e noble kni&yogh;t,</L>
<L>For best nov doand in &thorn;is fi&yogh;t.</L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L>&THORN;us &thorn;e kni&yogh;tes ben departed y-wis;</L>
<L>Sir Gij to jn y-comen is,</L>
<L>&amp; dede him vnarmi:</L>
<L>Of turnament he was weri.</L>
<L N="995">&para; Wi&thorn; &thorn;at come a seriant prikeinde,<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="679"></L>
<L>Gentil he was &amp; wele spekeinde;</L>
<L>To sir Gyes in he is y-come,</L>
<L>&amp; him he gret atte frome:
<PB REF="00000062.tif" N="58"></L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L>'Thou art y-chesen chef &amp; pris</L>
<L>Of al &thorn;is cuntre for so&thorn;e y-wis;</L>
<L>For &thorn;ou hast y-won &thorn;is turnament,</L>
<L>Y make &thorn;e here &thorn;is present</L>
<L N="1005">Fram &thorn;e maiden Blancheflour,</L>
<L>&THORN;at is mi lordes douhter &thorn;emperour:</L>
<L>&THORN;e gerfauk &amp; &thorn;e stede also,</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;e tvay grehoundes &thorn;er-to;</L>
<L>&amp; &yogh;ete hir loue wi&thorn; &thorn;an,</L>
<L N="1010">Bot &thorn;ou haue a fairer leman.</L>
<L>Sche &thorn;at is &thorn;e tour wi&thorn;-inne,</L>
<L>To day &thorn;ou mi&yogh;t hir loue winne.'</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="section">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Wel curteysliche answerd sir Gij:<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="691"></L>
<L>'Sir,' he seyd, 'gramerci;</L>
<L N="1015">Ich vnder-fong &thorn;is present,</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;onke hir &thorn;at it hider sent;</L>
<L>Hir druerie ich vnder-fong,<MILESTONE N="112b:2" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Hir kni&yogh;t to [be] wi&thorn;outen wrong.</L>
<L>Leue fere,' he seyd, 'herken to me,</L>
<L N="1020">What &thorn;at y schal telle &thorn;e:</L>
<L>&THORN;is armes ichil the &yogh;iue,</L>
<L>&amp; make riche while &thorn;ou liue;</L>
<L>&amp; al &thorn;ine feren &thorn;at be wi&thorn; &thorn;e</L>
<L>Riche &yogh;iftes schullen hauen of me,</L>
<L N="1025">&amp; do ich-il &yogh;ou grete honour</L>
<L>For &thorn;at maidens loue Blauncheflour.'</L>
<L>'Gramerci, sir Gij,' seyd he;<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="703"></L>
<L>'For armes come y nou&yogh;t<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. <I>ynou&yogh;t.</I></NOTE> to &thorn;e,</L>
<L>Ac to &thorn;e maiden ichil wende,</L>
<L N="1030">&amp; tel hir bo&thorn;e ord &amp; ende,</L>
<L>Blauncheflour, &thorn;at swete thing,</L>
<L>Ichil hir tel gode tiding.'</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="section">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;e seriant go&thorn; &amp; lete Gij &thorn;are,<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="709"></L>
<L>&THORN;at liue&thorn; in ioie and nou&yogh;t in care.
<PB REF="00000064.tif" N="60"></L>
<L N="1035">Tvay swaines Gij clepe&thorn; him to,</L>
<L>Anon he seyd to hem bo:</L>
<L>'This present &yogh;e schullen vnderfong,</L>
<L>&amp; wende &thorn;er-wi&thorn; into Inglond,</L>
<L>&amp; present &thorn;er-wi&thorn; bi mi word</L>
<L N="1040">Rohaut, mi kinde lord.'</L>
<L>&amp; when &thorn;ai herd what he hem hete,<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="718"></L>
<L>In her way &thorn;ai dede hem skete,</L>
<L>&amp; went &thorn;e[r]wi&thorn; in-to Inglond,</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;erl Rohaut &thorn;er &thorn;ai fond.</L>
<L N="1045">&THORN;e gerfauk and &thorn;e gode stede,</L>
<L>&THORN;e tvai grehoundes wi&thorn; hem<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. originally <I>him</I>.</NOTE> &yogh;ede;</L>
<L>&THORN;erl &thorn;ai made &thorn;er-wi&thorn; present,</L>
<L>&THORN;at sir Gij wan in turnament.</L>
<L>&amp; anon &thorn;ai him teld</L>
<L N="1050">Gij was &thorn;e best in &thorn;e feld,</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;at he was best y-teld bi</L>
<L>Of al &thorn;e kni&yogh;tes of Normandi.</L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L>&THORN;erl &thorn;er-of wel glad he was,<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="737"></L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;onked god of &thorn;at gras;</L>
<L>&amp; Felice &thorn;e feir dede al-so,</L>
<L N="1060">When &thorn;e tiding come hir to;</L>
<L>And al his frendes eld and &yogh;ing</L>
<L>Glad were of &thorn;at<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>d</I> expunged after <I>&thorn;at</I>.</NOTE> tiding.</L>
<L>Nov Gij wende&thorn; in-to fer lond,<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="743"></L>
<L>More of auentours for to fond;</L>
<L N="1065">For&thorn; he went in-to Speyne,<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. originally <I>Speyine</I>.</NOTE><MILESTONE N="113a:1" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&amp; after in-to Almeyne.</L>
<L>&THORN;er nas noi&thorn;er turnament no burdis,</L>
<L>&THORN;at Gij &thorn;er-of no wan &thorn;e priis.</L>
<L>He was out al &thorn;at &yogh;er</L>
<L N="1070">In mani londes fer &amp; ner,
<PB REF="00000066.tif" N="62"></L>
<L>And best is teld vnder sunne,</L>
<L>&amp; mest frendes ha&thorn; y-wonne.</L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L N="1075">&THORN;an seyd Herhaud to sir Gij</L>
<L>(His maister he was &amp; kni&yogh;t hardi):</L>
<L>'In-to Inglond we schul nov go,</L>
<L>So wele so we may it do,</L>
<L>For we han ouer al y-be,</L>
<L N="1080">&THORN;e pris y-wonne in euerich cuntre.'</L>
<L>Gij seyd, 'maister, y grant wel;</L>
<L>At &thorn;i wil be it eueridel.'</L>
<L>'Now we han ben her &amp; tar,</L>
<L>&THORN;e pris y-wonne euer ay-war;</L>
<L N="1085">To king A&thorn;elston &thorn;ou schalt aqueynt &thorn;e<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="756"></L>
<L>Of Inglond &thorn;at is so fre,</L>
<L>&amp; wi&thorn; &thorn;e barouns also,</L>
<L>So wele &thorn;ou may it nov do.</L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L>&para; Gij seyd, 'tomorwe, when it is day,</L>
<L>Wende we wil in our way.'</L>
<L>&amp; when &thorn;e day is y-come,</L>
<L>In her way &thorn;ai ben y-nome;</L>
<L N="1095">Ouer se &thorn;ai gan wende</L>
<L>In Inglond &thorn;ai gun lende.<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="765"></L>
<L>Anon &thorn;ai com to king Athelston,</L>
<L>Wel fair he hem vnder-fenge anon;</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; erls &amp; barouns aqueynt him dede</L>
<L N="1100">&THORN;at riche &yogh;iftes him bede.</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="section">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Nov is Gij to Warwike fare;</L>
<L>&THORN;erl Rohaut he fint &thorn;are.</L>
<L>He welcomed him &amp; his fere,</L>
<L>For he was him leue &amp; dere,</L>
<L N="1105">&amp; kist him wel sweteliche,</L>
<L>&amp; of his present &thorn;onked him miche.
<PB REF="00000068.tif" N="64"></L>
<L>To his leman he is y-come,</L>
<L>&amp; euen for&thorn; hir-self sche ha&thorn; him nome.</L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L>Glad was his fader for him,</L>
<L>Sabin his moder &amp; al his kin,</L>
<L>&amp; al &thorn;e folk of &thorn;at cuntre</L>
<L>Bli&thorn;e were &thorn;ai mi&yogh;t him se.</L>
<L N="1115">&para; To Felice &thorn;an sir Gij is go;<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="777"><MILESTONE N="113a:2" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Sweteliche he seyd hir to:</L>
<L>'Leman,' he seyd, 'wele &thorn;ou be,</L>
<L>Mi liif ichaue for loue of &thorn;e;</L>
<L>Ded ich were &yogh;if &thorn;ou nere,</L>
<L N="1120">Mi bodi destrud and leyd on bere.</L>
<L>When &thorn;ou &thorn;i wille hadde seyd to me,</L>
<L>Armes y fenge for loue of [&thorn;e];</L>
<L>&amp; when ich hadde armes take,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou seyd &thorn;ou noldest me for-sake,</L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L>&THORN;ou noldest &thorn;i loue werne to me;</L>
<L>&amp; nov ich am her comen to &thorn;e:</L>
<L>Dere leman, y prey &thorn;e</L>
<L N="1130">&THORN;i wille &thorn;atow tel to me.'</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="section">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Felice answerd swi&thorn;e an heye,<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="793"></L>
<L>'No rape &thorn;e nou&yogh;t so, sir Gij;</L>
<L>&YOGH;ete nartow nou&yogh;t y-preysed so,</L>
<L>&THORN;at me ne may finde o&thorn;er mo;</L>
<L N="1135">Orped &thorn;ou art and of grete mi&yogh;t,</L>
<L>Gode kni&yogh;t &amp; ardi in fi&yogh;t:</L>
<L>&amp; &yogh;if ich &thorn;e hadde mi loue y-&yogh;eue,</L>
<L>To welden it while &thorn;at y liue,</L>
<L>Sleu&thorn;e &thorn;e schuld ouercome:</L>
<L N="1140">Namore wostow of armes loue,</L>
<L>No comen in turnament no in fi&yogh;t.</L>
<L>So amerous &thorn;ou were anon ri&yogh;t.
<PB REF="00000070.tif" N="66"></L>
<L>Y schuld misdo, so &thorn;enke&thorn; me,</L>
<L>&amp; miche agilt o&yogh;aines te,</L>
<L N="1145">&amp; ich &thorn;i manschip schuld schone,</L>
<L>Wit<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>t</I> over an erasure.</NOTE> me euer more to wone.</L>
<L>Gij,' quod Felice, 'forhele y nille,<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="807"></L>
<L>Ac al &thorn;e so&thorn;e ichil &thorn;e telle:</L>
<L>&THORN;ou art me leuest of o&thorn;er alle,</L>
<L N="1150">For &thorn;i 'leman' ichil the calle;</L>
<L>Ac mi loue no schaltow haue</L>
<L>For no&thorn;ing &thorn;atow may craue,</L>
<L>Er &thorn;ou perles holden be</L>
<L>&amp; best doand in &thorn;is cuntre,</L>
<L N="1155">&THORN;at nowhar bi lond no w[e]ter</L>
<L>No be founde &thorn;i beter;</L>
<L>&amp; when &thorn;ou art hold best doinde</L>
<L>In armes &thorn;at animan mai finde,</L>
<L>&THORN;at vnder heuen &thorn;i beter no be,</L>
<L N="1160">Mi loue ichil &thorn;an graunti &thorn;e.'</L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="section">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1165">When Gij herd Felice speke so,<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="821"></L>
<L>Wel depe he gan to sike &thorn;o:<MILESTONE N="113b:1" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>'Now ichot, &thorn;ou scornest me:</L>
<L>Swiche answer ichaue of &thorn;e,</L>
<L>&THORN;at y schuld be &thorn;e best y-teld,</L>
<L N="1170">&THORN;at be fi&yogh;tand wi&thorn; spere &amp; scheld.</L>
<L>Swiche no mi&yogh;t y neuer wer&thorn;e</L>
<L>To be &thorn;e best on &thorn;is er&thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>on &thorn;is er&thorn;e</I> on an erasure.</NOTE>;</L>
<L>Into o&thorn;er cuntres ichil go,</L>
<L>For &thorn;i loue to wirche me wo.</L>
<L N="1175">For dout of de&thorn; nil y nou&yogh;t fle:</L>
<L>&YOGH;if y dye, it is for &thorn;e.'</L>
<L>Sir Gij of hir toke his leue,<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="831"></L>
<L>&amp; kist hir wi&thorn; wepeand eye.
<PB REF="00000072.tif" N="68"></L>
<L>Unto his in he go&thorn; snelle;</L>
<L N="1180">&THORN;er nil he no lenger duelle.</L>
<L>To &thorn;erl he wil gon,</L>
<L>&amp; tak his leue sone anon.</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="section">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Gij him com to court &thorn;ore,<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="835"></L>
<L>&amp; ali&yogh;t atte halle dore;</L>
<L N="1185">&amp; to &thorn;erl he went &thorn;o,</L>
<L>&amp; schewed him wat he wald do.</L>
<L>'Sir erl,' quod Gij, 'y bid &thorn;e,</L>
<L>Leue to wende &yogh;if &thorn;ou me.</L>
<L>Ouer &thorn;e se ichil now wende;</L>
<L N="1190">God to gode hauen me sende!</L>
<L>Time it is &thorn;at ich fond</L>
<L>To winne priis in vncou&thorn;e lond;</L>
<L>Al &thorn;e glader &yogh;e mow be</L>
<L>&YOGH;if we of armes preised be.</L>
<L N="1195">&amp; &yogh;if &thorn;ou hast folk of grete mi&yogh;t,</L>
<L>It is te gret wor&thorn;schip, y pli&yogh;t,</L>
<L>For al &thorn;e more men schal &thorn;e dout</L>
<L>Wi&thorn;-in &thorn;i lond &amp; eke wi&thorn;-out.'</L>
<L>&para; 'Sir Gij,' quod &thorn;erl &thorn;o,<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="847"></L>
<L N="1200">'Faile&thorn; &thorn;e out &thorn;at y mai do?</L>
<L>Gold o&thorn;er siluer, o&thorn;er heye stede?</L>
<L>To passe &thorn;e se hastow no nede.</L>
<L>Sir Gij,' he seyd, 'lete ben al &thorn;is,</L>
<L>Anou&yogh; &thorn;e wor&thorn; &thorn;at &thorn;e nede is;</L>
<L N="1205">&amp; to pleyn vnder &thorn;e linde,</L>
<L>&THORN;e hert to chacen and &thorn;e hinde:</L>
<L>Of al &thorn;inges &thorn;ou schalt haue plente.</L>
<L>Bileue at hom, sir Gi, wi&thorn; me.</L>
<L>We schul wende bo&thorn;e y-fere<MILESTONE N="113b:2" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="1210">To play bi wode &amp; bi riuer;</L>
<L>Al bi times &thorn;ou mi&yogh;t wende;</L>
<L>&YOGH;ete no hastow ben here a mone&thorn; to &thorn;ende<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>&THORN;ende</I> added over the line.</NOTE>.</L>
<L>&para; 'Miche &thorn;ank, sir,' quod Gij &thorn;o;</L>
<L>'For so&thorn;e so no may [y] nou&yogh;t do.'
<PB REF="00000074.tif" N="70"></L>
<L N="1215">His leue he toke wi&thorn;-outen more;</L>
<L>&THORN;erl it of-&thorn;ou&yogh;t swi&thorn;e sore.</L>
<L>He go&thorn; him to his fader &thorn;o,<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="865"></L>
<L>&THORN;at for his wending was ful wo:</L>
<L>'Gon, fader,' quod he, 'ich-ille;</L>
<L N="1220">For no&thorn;ing leten y nille;</L>
<L>&YOGH;if me leue, icham al &yogh;are</L>
<L>Ouer &thorn;e se for to fare,</L>
<L>To winne pris and los al-so,</L>
<L>So &yogh;ong man schal in &yogh;ou&thorn;e do.</L>
<L N="1225">Long to bileuen in &thorn;is cunt[r]e</L>
<L>Nis it nou&yogh;t wor&thorn; for me;</L>
<L>For &yogh;ong man &thorn;at is mi&yogh;ti</L>
<L>In his &yogh;ou&thorn;e schal fondi,</L>
<L>So &thorn;at men may him in er&thorn;e preyse,</L>
<L N="1230">And in eld liue in mir&thorn;e &amp; ayse.</L>
<L>&THORN;er-whiles icham &yogh;ong &amp; li&yogh;t,</L>
<L>Los ichil winne bi mi mi&yogh;t.'</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="section">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'Leue sone,' he seyd, 'leue &thorn;at &thorn;ou&yogh;t:<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="879"></L>
<L>Bi mi wil schaltow wende nou&yogh;t.</L>
<L N="1235">&THORN;ou schalt bileue here wi&thorn; me;</L>
<L>Al &thorn;e bli&thorn;er we wille be.'</L>
<L>'Leue sone,' his moder him sede,</L>
<L>'&THORN;ou do bi &thorn;i faders rede:</L>
<L>Soiourne wi&thorn; ous to &yogh;er mo,</L>
<L N="1240">Y rede &thorn;e, sone, &thorn;at it be so.</L>
<L>Ano&thorn;er &yogh;er &thorn;ou mi&yogh;t ouer fare.</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;ou bileue, y dye for care,</L>
<L>For we ne haue sonis no mo:</L>
<L>&YOGH;if we &thorn;e schul now for-go,</L>
<L N="1245">Glad no wor&thorn; we neuer mo,</L>
<L>For sorwe schul ous<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>o</I> of <I>ous</I> all but illegible.</NOTE> selue slo.'</L>
<L>&para; Gij answerd wi&thorn; &thorn;at speche,</L>
<L>'Fader, god y &thorn;e biteche,</L>
<L>&amp; mi leue moder al-so;</L>
<L N="1250">For hastiliche ichil nov go.'
</L>
</LG>

</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="section"><PB REF="00000076.tif" N="72">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Gij for&thorn; go&thorn;, &amp; &thorn;ai bileue &thorn;are,<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="899"></L>
<L>&THORN;at for hym hadde miche care.</L>
<L>To &thorn;e se he is y-come,<MILESTONE N="114a:1" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Gode winde he ha&thorn; atte frome.</L>
<L N="1255">Y-comen he is in-to Normundye,</L>
<L>Kni&yogh;tschip he schewed on hye.</L>
<L>&THORN;ennes he went in-to Speyne;</L>
<L>Nis turnament non in-to Almeyne,</L>
<L>&THORN;at Gij no ha&thorn; &thorn;er-at y-be,</L>
<L N="1260">&amp; michel y-preised so is he.</L>
<L>&THORN;ennes to Lombardye he went;</L>
<L>&THORN;er ben &thorn;e iustes &amp; &thorn;e turnament,</L>
<L>&THORN;er he dede him preyse miche,</L>
<L>&THORN;e Lombardes him loued inliche;</L>
<L N="1265">He was large, curteys, &amp; fre:</L>
<L>Of miche mi&yogh;t so was he.<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="918"></L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="section">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Of an vnsele y may &yogh;ou telle,</L>
<L>&amp; &yogh;e wil a stounde<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. <I>astounde</I></NOTE> duelle:</L>
<L>As he cam fram a turnament</L>
<L N="1270">&THORN;at was biside Bonevent,</L>
<L>In &thorn;e bodi wounded he was:</L>
<L>&THORN;at sore him greued<NOTE PLACE="marg">The second <I>e</I> of <I>greued</I> over the line.</NOTE> no wonder it nas.</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;an bithou&yogh;t him &thorn;e douk Otoun,<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. <I>of toun.</I></NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at vnwrast was, &amp; feloun,</L>
<L N="1275">&THORN;at he wald ben awreke &thorn;at day</L>
<L>Of Gij of Warwike, &yogh;if he may;</L>
<L>For he him wounded in a turnament,</L>
<L>As ichaue herd telle verrament;</L>
<L>&THORN;er-fore Gij him was swi&thorn;e lo&thorn;,</L>
<L N="1280">&amp; wel depe he swore his o&thorn;</L>
<L>&THORN;at he of him awreke wald be</L>
<L>Er &thorn;an he wende out of &thorn;at cuntre.</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="section">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>When &thorn;e douke Otus y-seye &thorn;at cas,<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="927"></L>
<L>&THORN;at Gij so sore wounded was,</L>
<L N="1285">&THORN;erl Lambard he cleped to him</L>
<L>(A kni&yogh;t he was stout &amp; grim),
<PB REF="00000078.tif" N="74"></L>
<L>&amp; fiftene<NOTE PLACE="marg">looks like <I>fi&yogh;tene</I></NOTE> kni&yogh;tes in his compeynie,</L>
<L>&THORN;at were strong men and hardie.</L>
<L>On a dern stede he dede hem hide,</L>
<L N="1290">&THORN;er as Gij schuld cum ride;</L>
<L>'Lordinges,' &thorn;an seyd &thorn;e douk Otoun,<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>of toun</I> MS.</NOTE><MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="935"></L>
<L>'Under-stond to mi resoun:</L>
<L>Mine men &yogh;e be&thorn; &amp; to me swore,</L>
<L>Omage &yogh;e schul me &thorn;er-fore.</L>
<L N="1295">Mine hest &yogh;e schul ful-fille,</L>
<L>&THORN;at ich &yogh;ou bid, wi&thorn; gode wille.</L>
<L>Me to wreken &yogh;e schul go<MILESTONE N="114b:2" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Of a treytour &thorn;at is mi fo,</L>
<L>&THORN;at is y-comen vp mi lond</L>
<L N="1300">(Wer he &thorn;enke&thorn; to bring me an hond),</L>
<L>Gij of Warwike &thorn;at wounded is</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; a swerd &thorn;urch &thorn;e bodi y-wis.</L>
<L>On &thorn;e halidom &yogh;e schul me sweri:</L>
<L>In &thorn;e forest of Pleyns &thorn;at is so miri,</L>
<L N="1305">&THORN;er<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>&amp; &thorn;er</I> MS.</NOTE> &yogh;e schul &yogh;ou al hide,</L>
<L>&THORN;er Gij of Warwike schal cum ride:</L>
<L>His bodi oliue &yogh;e schul me bring,</L>
<L>And slen his feren eld &amp; &yogh;ing.</L>
<L>Y schal him in mi prisoun do;</L>
<L N="1310">Out no come&thorn; he neuer mo.</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; sorwe and wo<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>and wo</I> indis|tinct, but perfectly certain.</NOTE> he schal &thorn;er ende:</L>
<L>&THORN;ennes no schal he neuer wende.'<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="956"></L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="section">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'Sir,' &thorn;ai seyd, 'we schul go,</L>
<L>&amp; al &thorn;ine hest we schul do.'</L>
<L N="1315">&THORN;ai dede hem arme swi&thorn;e wel</L>
<L>Bo&thorn;e in iren &amp; in stiel;</L>
<L>Vnto &thorn;e pas &thorn;ai wenten snelle,</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;er &thorn;ai houed swi&thorn;e stille,</L>
<L>As Gij schuld cum sone.</L>
<L N="1320">No wist he nou&yogh;t of &thorn;at tresone,</L>
<L>No of &thorn;at sorwe neuer the mo,</L>
<L>&THORN;at him was comand to;
<PB REF="00000080.tif" N="76"></L>
<L>For al his felawes &thorn;at gode were,</L>
<L>Al he for-les hem &thorn;ere;</L>
<L N="1325">&amp; his owhen liif he hadde for-lore,</L>
<L>No hadde goddes help ben bifore,</L>
<L>&THORN;urch &thorn;e traitours &thorn;at were her fon,</L>
<L>&THORN;at kept hem &thorn;ere for to slon.<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="964"></L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="section">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Now come&thorn; Gij soft rideing</L>
<L N="1330">Opon a mulet ambling.</L>
<L>His wounde him greue&thorn; swi&thorn;e sore,</L>
<L>&amp; smert him euer &thorn;e lenger &thorn;e more.</L>
<L>In pais he wende for to wende,</L>
<L>Ac &thorn;e traitours Lombardes vnhende,</L>
<L N="1335">&THORN;e helmes &thorn;ai seyen bri&yogh;t schine,</L>
<L>&THORN;e stedes nyen, and togider whine.</L>
<L>'God,' quod Gij, 'we ben y-nome!</L>
<L>Al we be ded &thorn;urch tresone.'</L>
<L>Sir Gij of &thorn;at mulet ali&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="1340">&amp; asked his stede, his armes bri&yogh;t,</L>
<L>&amp; seyd to his felawes snelle,<MILESTONE N="114b:1" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>'Dere we schul our de&thorn;<NOTE PLACE="marg">looks like <I>ded</I> with the second <I>d</I> erased.</NOTE> selle.</L>
<L>Our de&thorn; is now al bispeke,</L>
<L>Bot we ous manliche awreke;</L>
<L N="1345">Ich kepe him selue, se&thorn;&thorn;e it so is,</L>
<L>&amp; ichil, while y liue, y-wis:</L>
<L>So dere so y may, ich wille</L>
<L>To &thorn;e treytours mi liif selle.'</L>
<L>&para; 'Sir,' seyd Herhaud &thorn;o,<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="985"></L>
<L N="1350">'For godes loue hennes &thorn;ou go.</L>
<L>For &thorn;ine loue we schul her dye,</L>
<L>&amp; defende &thorn;is pas, y seye:</L>
<L>Leuer ous were her-on be ded,</L>
<L>&THORN;an &thorn;ou wer ded in our ferred.'</L>
<L N="1355">&para; &THORN;an answerd Gij anon ri&yogh;t,</L>
<L>As gode kni&yogh;t &amp; ful of mi&yogh;t:</L>
<L>'&YOGH;if &yogh;e dye, ichil<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>Iichil</I> MS.</NOTE> al-so;</L>
<L>Nil ich neuer fram &yogh;ou go!'
</L>
</LG>

</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="section"><PB REF="00000082.tif" N="78">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Wi&thorn; &thorn;at come a Lombard ride,<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="997"></L>
<L N="1360">A modi man &amp; ful of pride.</L>
<L>'Gij,' quod he, '&yogh;eld &thorn;e anon!</L>
<L>&YOGH;e ben ded now euerichon;</L>
<L>To &thorn;e douke we han trew&thorn;e pli&yogh;t</L>
<L>To bring him &thorn;i bodi &thorn;is ni&yogh;t.'</L>
<L N="1365">With &thorn;at ich word wel smert</L>
<L>Gij him smot vn-to &thorn;e hert;</L>
<L>No spard he for no drede,</L>
<L>&THORN;at ded he feld him in &thorn;e mede.</L>
<L>'Bi &thorn;e trew&thorn;e y schal mi leman &yogh;eld,</L>
<L N="1370">To day no schaltow &thorn;i trew&thorn;e held!'</L>
<L>Ano&thorn;er Lombard he smot anon,</L>
<L>&THORN;urch &thorn;e bodi &thorn;e swerd gan gon:</L>
<L>'No &thorn;ou, treytour, no schalt me lede</L>
<L>To &thorn;e douke that is ful of qued;</L>
<L N="1375">To his presoun no wor&thorn; y for &thorn;e brou&yogh;t.'</L>
<L>Herhaud smot ano&thorn;er and spared nou&yogh;t</L>
<L>&THORN;urch &thorn;e bodi his swerd glod,</L>
<L>Ded he fel wi&thorn;-outen abod.</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;an com Torald, a gode kni&yogh;t,<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="1015"></L>
<L N="1380">Swi&thorn;e gode &amp; hardi in fi&yogh;t;</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; a Lombard &thorn;er he mett,</L>
<L>&amp; so wele his strok he sett</L>
<L>&THORN;at his heued fram &thorn;e bodi flei;</L>
<L>He &yogh;ede him laweliche neye.</L>
<L N="1385">Wi&thorn; &thorn;at come Urri prikeinde</L>
<L>(A better kni&yogh;t no mi&yogh;t man finde),<MILESTONE N="114b:2" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>A Lombard he smot &thorn;o,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;urch his bodi &thorn;e swerd gan go;</L>
<L>So he smot him, for so&thorn; to say,</L>
<L N="1390">&THORN;at ded he feld him in &thorn;e way.</L>
<L>Se&thorn;&thorn;e he seyd, '&thorn;urch no toun</L>
<L>Schal &yogh;e ous lede to no prisoun.</L>
<L>Than mi&yogh;t men se<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>fi</I> expunged before <I>8e.</I></NOTE> fi&yogh;t aginne,</L>
<L>Heuedes cleue vnto &thorn;e chinne.
<PB REF="00000084.tif" N="80"></L>
<L N="1395">Euerich &thorn;at day &thorn;at Gij oftoke,</L>
<L>Sone anon his liif forsoke.</L>
<L>Sum he smot opon &thorn;e hode,</L>
<L>At &thorn;e girdel &thorn;e swerd astode;</L>
<L>And sum he smot &thorn;urch &thorn;e side,</L>
<L N="1400">&THORN;at mi&yogh;t he neuer go no ride.</L>
<L>Was &thorn;er non that mi&yogh;t astond</L>
<L>Dint &thorn;at come of Gyes hond.</L>
<L>So mi&yogh;ti strokes &thorn;er wer &yogh;iuen,</L>
<L>&THORN;at strong schaftes al to-driuen;<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. <I>alto driuen</I></NOTE></L>
<L N="1405">No was &thorn;er non in &thorn;at ferrede</L>
<L>&THORN;at of his liif him mi&yogh;t adrede.</L>
<L>&para; Wi&thorn; &thorn;at come ride &thorn;erl Lambard,<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="1033"></L>
<L>A sterne kni&yogh;t and a Lombard;</L>
<L>Vrri anon he slou&yogh; &thorn;ar,</L>
<L N="1410">It o&thorn;ou&yogh;t Gij &thorn;o he was war;</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; &thorn;erl Lambard he wald iusti,</L>
<L>&amp; awreke &thorn;e gode Vrri.</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; swiche hete he smot him to,</L>
<L>His armour no was him wor&thorn; a slo;</L>
<L N="1415">&THORN;urch out his hert &thorn;e launce he bar,</L>
<L>Adoun he feld him ded ri&yogh;t &thorn;ar.</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; &thorn;at him come for&thorn; Hougoun,</L>
<L>&THORN;at was &thorn;e doukes neve Otoun:</L>
<L>A kni&yogh;t he was of gret mi&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="1420">Swi&thorn;e gode &amp; hardi in fi&yogh;t.</L>
<L>Torald<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>torlard</I> MS.</NOTE> he ha&thorn; aqueld;</L>
<L>Herhaud anon &thorn;at biheld.</L>
<L>When Herhaud<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>her herhaud</I> MS.</NOTE> y-seye &thorn;is,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he doun fel &amp; ded he is,</L>
<L N="1425">For his de&thorn; he was sori:</L>
<L>Him to awreke he ha&thorn; gret hy.</L>
<L>Neuer &yogh;ete so sori he no was,</L>
<L>To-ward Hugoun he made a ras,</L>
<L>Als a lyoun he heyed him fast,<MILESTONE N="115a:1" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="1430">&THORN;at his prey wold haue on hast.
<PB REF="00000086.tif" N="82"></L>
<L>&THORN;urch &thorn;e body he him smot</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; gret streng&thorn;e, god ytot,</L>
<L>&THORN;at biforn &thorn;e Lombardes alle</L>
<L>Of his hors ded he gan falle.</L>
<L N="1435">&para; When dan Gauter &thorn;at y-seye,<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="1053"></L>
<L>To Herhaud he stert wel an heye,</L>
<L>And wi&thorn; his swerd he smot him so</L>
<L>&THORN;at his hauberk rent ato;</L>
<L>&THORN;urch his bodi &thorn;at swerd &yogh;ede,</L>
<L N="1440">Al &thorn;ai wende &thorn;at he wer ded.</L>
<L>&para; When Gij seye Herhaud y-feld,</L>
<L>To-hewen his hauberk &amp; his scheld</L>
<L>(&amp; of his hors feld he was,</L>
<L>As ded man lay on &thorn;e gras;</L>
<L N="1445">He seye &thorn;e blod &thorn;at cam him fro),</L>
<L>Wonder him &thorn;ou&yogh;t, &amp; seyd &thorn;o:</L>
<L>'&THORN;ou lording, to &thorn;e y sigge,</L>
<L>His de&thorn; &thorn;ou schalt wel sore abigge!</L>
<L>So mot ich euer word speke,</L>
<L N="1450">Mi maisters de&thorn; ichil awreke,</L>
<L>&amp; for a couward ich held &thorn;e:</L>
<L>&THORN;ou slou&yogh; him, &amp; lete me be.</L>
<L>Bi him &thorn;at made sonne &amp; mone,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou schalt it wite swi&thorn;e sone,<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. <I>sonne</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L N="1455">&THORN;at tow schalt it bi&yogh;elp nou&yogh;t</L>
<L>&THORN;at he is to de&thorn; y-brou&yogh;t.'</L>
<L>&para; Gij wi&thorn; spors smot &thorn;e stede,</L>
<L>As a man &thorn;at hadde nede,</L>
<L>&THORN;at fire vnder &thorn;e fet aros;</L>
<L N="1460">Nas &thorn;er non &thorn;at him agros.</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; al his mi&yogh;t he smot him to,</L>
<L>Wel euen he clef his scheld &thorn;o,</L>
<L>&THORN;urch his bodi &thorn;e swerd he &thorn;riste:</L>
<L>&THORN;o at arst fi&yogh;t him liste.</L>
<L N="1465">In &thorn;e sond he feld him doun,</L>
<L>&amp; bede him Cristes malisoun,
<PB REF="00000088.tif" N="84"></L>
<L>For &thorn;at he wald Herhaud slen,</L>
<L>And lete him oliues ben.</L>
<L>&para; Now is Gij<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. repeats <I>is gij</I>, but the second <I>is gij</I> is underdotted.</NOTE> wel hard bifalle,<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="1067"></L>
<L N="1470">Y-lorn he ha&thorn; his felawes alle;</L>
<L>So sori he is, he not what to do,</L>
<L>He no ha&thorn; no wi&yogh;t to bimen him to.</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;re Lombard[es] oliue &thorn;er nere,<MILESTONE N="115a:2" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Opon Gij hastiliche &thorn;ai were;</L>
<L N="1475">&THORN;e tvay ben hole &amp; sounde,</L>
<L>&THORN;e &thorn;ridde hadde &thorn;urch &thorn;e bodi a wounde.</L>
<L>&para; Gij &thorn;at on wi&thorn; his swerd rau&yogh;t,</L>
<L>His heued of fleye wi&thorn; &thorn;at drau&yogh;t.</L>
<L>&THORN;an com prikeing dan Gwissard,</L>
<L N="1480">A duhtti kni&yogh;t and no couward.</L>
<L>&para; 'Gij,' quod he, '&yogh;eld now &thorn;e!<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="1077"></L>
<L>It no may no no&thorn;er be:</L>
<L>On &thorn;e er&thorn;e li&thorn;e &thorn;i scheld to-dreued,</L>
<L>Nou&yogh;t o pece is wi&thorn; o&thorn;er bileued,</L>
<L N="1485">&amp; &thorn;ine helme is al to-hewe,<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. <I>alto hewe</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;ine hauberk to-rent &thorn;at was newe;</L>
<L>&amp; wounded &thorn;ou art, &thorn;ou mi&yogh;t well se,</L>
<L>Long mi&yogh;t tow nou&yogh;t oliues be.</L>
<L>To day ichil &yogh;eld &thorn;e to &thorn;e douk Otoun,</L>
<L N="1490">&amp; he &thorn;e schal do in his prisoun.</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="section">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;an seyd Gij, 'Gwichard, y nille:<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="1089"></L>
<L>To &yogh;eld me to &thorn;e is nou&yogh;t mi wille,</L>
<L>&THORN;er-whiles ichaue mi swerd y-grounde,</L>
<L>&amp; mi bodi wi&thorn;outen wounde.'</L>
<L N="1495">Gwichard smot Gij wi&thorn; michel mi&yogh;t</L>
<L>Opon &thorn;e helme &thorn;at schon so bri&yogh;t,</L>
<L>&THORN;at a quarter out fleye;</L>
<L>&THORN;e kni&yogh;t was bo&thorn;e queynt &amp; sleye.</L>
<L>Opon his scholder &thorn;at swerd glod,</L>
<L N="1500">Of his hauberk it tok a pece brod;</L>
<L>God saued Gij &thorn;at he nas ded,</L>
<L>No for &thorn;at dint hadde no qued.
</L>
</LG>

</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="section"><PB REF="00000090.tif" N="86">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>When Gij seye him so smite,<NOTE PLACE="marg">The <I>i</I> of <I>smite</I> added over the line.</NOTE><MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="1103"></L>
<L>He was wro&thorn;, &yogh;e may wele wite;</L>
<L N="1505">Gwichard he wald fond to smite</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; his swerd &thorn;at wold wele bite;</L>
<L>To him he smot swi&thorn;e smert</L>
<L>&THORN;urch &thorn;e bodi ful ney &thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. <I>ney &thorn;e &thorn;e</I></NOTE> hert:</L>
<L>&THORN;at gode swerd &thorn;urchim &thorn;rang,</L>
<L N="1510">Gwichard wald abide nou&yogh;t lang;</L>
<L>He turned his stede &amp; gan to fle,</L>
<L>&amp; Gij after him, bi mi leute.</L>
<L>Gode was &thorn;e hors &thorn;at Gwichard rod on,</L>
<L>&amp; so fast his stede gan gon,</L>
<L N="1515">&THORN;at Gij mi&yogh;t him nou&yogh;t atake,</L>
<L>&THORN;er-fore he gan sorwe make.</L>
<L>Gwichard fleye in his way<MILESTONE N="115b:1" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Toward Paui, so swi&thorn;e he may.</L>
<L>&THORN;e douk Otous fram hunting com,<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="1115"></L>
<L N="1520">&amp; with him erles mani on;</L>
<L>A kni&yogh;t he seye cum prikeing,</L>
<L>His armes to-rent, his woundes bledeing.</L>
<L>&THORN;e douk Otous duelled a&thorn;rowe,</L>
<L>What he hadde Gwichard y-knowe:</L>
<L N="1525">Wele he semed man aferd,</L>
<L>&THORN;at hard tiding hadde y-herd.</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; &thorn;at is Gwichard to him come;</L>
<L>&THORN;e douke him oxed atte frome,</L>
<L>'Gwichard, who ha&thorn; wret&thorn;ed &thorn;e,</L>
<L N="1530">&amp; where hastow in bateyle be?</L>
<L>&para; Where is Gij? is he nome?</L>
<L>Liues or de&thorn;[es] do him come.'</L>
<L>'Ichil &yogh;ou sigge sikerly<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="1127"></L>
<L>So michel so y wot of Gij:</L>
<L N="1535">At a ford we him mett,</L>
<L>&amp; strongliche we him bisett,</L>
<L>Bot his bodi no nom we nou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>Ac al to de&thorn; we ben y-brou&yogh;t;
<PB REF="00000092.tif" N="88"></L>
<L>Bot icham passed as &yogh;e may se.'</L>
<L N="1540">'Mi nevou Hougoun, whar is he?'</L>
<L>Quod &thorn;e douk Otous, 'tel me ra&thorn;e.'</L>
<L>'Sir, in &thorn;e sond he li&thorn;e, &amp; &thorn;at is sca&thorn;e.'</L>
<L>'&amp; &thorn;erl Lambard, &thorn;at gode kni&yogh;t?'</L>
<L>'Ded he li&thorn;e in &thorn;at fi&yogh;t.'</L>
<L N="1545">When douk Otus herd &thorn;at,</L>
<L>Sori he was &amp; no-&thorn;ing glad:</L>
<L>&THORN;at he ha&thorn; his folk for-lore,</L>
<L>Sorweful man he was &thorn;erfore.</L>
<L>Ney&yogh;e his hert brast for mode,</L>
<L N="1550">&amp; for sorwe<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. <I>For sorwe &amp;.</I></NOTE> &yogh;ede ner wode,</L>
<L>When he wist his folk y-slawe,</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;urch him brou&yogh;t o liue<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. <I>oliue.</I></NOTE> dawe.</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="section">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>NOW ha&thorn; Gij miche sorwe made,<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="1143"></L>
<L>For his felawes he is vnglade.</L>
<L N="1555">'Allas,' quod Gii, 'felawes dere!</L>
<L>So wele doand kni&yogh;tes &yogh;e were.</L>
<L>Al to iuel it fel to me,</L>
<L>Felice, &thorn;o y was sent to serue &thorn;e;</L>
<L>For &thorn;i loue, Felice, the feir may,</L>
<L N="1560">&THORN;e flour of kni&yogh;tes is sleyn &thorn;is day.</L>
<L>Ac for &thorn;ou art a wiman,<MILESTONE N="115b:2" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Y no can nou&yogh;t blame &thorn;e for &thorn;an;</L>
<L>For &thorn;e last no wor&thorn; y nou&yogh;t</L>
<L>&THORN;at wimen han to gronde y-brou&yogh;t.</L>
<L N="1565">Ac alle o&thorn;er may bi me,</L>
<L>&YOGH;if &thorn;ai wil, y-warned be.</L>
<L>Allas, Herhaud, mi dere frende,</L>
<L>What &thorn;ou were curteys &amp; hende!</L>
<L>Who schal me now help in fi&yogh;t?</L>
<L N="1570">Neuer no was no better kni&yogh;t.</L>
<L>In ich fi&yogh;t wele halp thou me,</L>
<L>Ful iuel ichaue y-&yogh;olden it &thorn;e;</L>
<L>For me &thorn;ou hast &thorn;i liif forgon,</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e no tit me neuer help non.
<PB REF="00000094.tif" N="90"></L>
<L N="1575">How mai ich now fram &thorn;e wende?</L>
<L>That y no mai dye &thorn;e hende!</L>
<L>Acursed be &thorn;e Lombardes ichon,</L>
<L>That slowen &thorn;e, and lete me gon!</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;at &thorn;ai hadde y-slawe me,</L>
<L N="1580">&amp; leten &thorn;e oliue be!</L>
<L>Wharto lete &thorn;ai me alon?'</L>
<L>&THORN;us sir Gij biment his mone.</L>
<L>&para; 'Allas! allas! Rohaut, mi lord,<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="1179"></L>
<L>&THORN;at y no hadde leued &thorn;i word!</L>
<L N="1585">&THORN;an hadde y nou&yogh;t y-passed &thorn;e se,</L>
<L>Ich hadde bileued at hom wi&thorn; &thorn;e;</L>
<L>&THORN;us yuel nere me nou&yogh;t bifalle,</L>
<L>Y no hadde nou&yogh;t lorn min felawes alle.</L>
<L>Who so nil nou&yogh;t do bi his faders red,</L>
<L N="1590">Oft-si&thorn;es it falle&thorn; him qued;</L>
<L>For often ichaue herd it say,</L>
<L>&amp; y<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>y</I> illegible in MS.</NOTE> me self it sigge may,</L>
<L>"Who &thorn;at nil nou&yogh;t leue his fader,</L>
<L>He schel leue his steffader." '</L>
<L N="1595">What for his woundes &thorn;at strong blede&thorn;,</L>
<L>What for his sorwe &thorn;at he lede&thorn;,</L>
<L>Al for sorwe &amp; for wo<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="1195"></L>
<L>Adoun he fel aswon &thorn;o.</L>
<L>When he of swoning vp stod,</L>
<L N="1600">His feren he biheld wi&thorn; drery mod;</L>
<L>&THORN;an he lepe opon his stede,</L>
<L>To an ermitage he wold ride.</L>
<L>'Ermite,' quod he, 'com wi&thorn; me;</L>
<L>&THORN;is hors of priis &yogh;iue y &thorn;e;</L>
<L N="1605">To bodis &thorn;ou schalt in er&thorn;e graue,<MILESTONE N="116a:1" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&THORN;at in &thorn;is forest ben y-slawe.'</L>
<L>'Ble&thorn;eliche, sir,' &thorn;an seyd he;</L>
<L>'Wende bifore, y folwe &thorn;e.'</L>
<L>&THORN;e bodis him schewe&thorn; sir Gij,</L>
<L N="1610">Bo&thorn;e Toraud &amp; sir Urry.
<PB REF="00000096.tif" N="92"></L>
<L>Se&thorn;&thorn;e he lepe opon his stede,</L>
<L>Herhaud he wil wi&thorn; him lede;</L>
<L>&amp; so he dede sikerliche,</L>
<L>&amp; se&thorn;&thorn;e he was heled softliche,</L>
<L N="1615">Ac no for &thorn;an Gij wend wele &thorn;ere</L>
<L>&THORN;at Herhaud to de&thorn; y-wounded were.</L>
<L>&para; Now is Gij &thorn;ennes y-fare;<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="1215"></L>
<L>For his felawes he ha&thorn; gret care.</L>
<L>Herhaudes bodi wi&thorn; him he bar,</L>
<L N="1620">For he nold it nou&yogh;t lete &thorn;ar.</L>
<L>He went him to an abbay</L>
<L>&THORN;at was bisiden on the way.</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; &thorn;e gode abbot &thorn;er he mett,</L>
<L>&amp; pitouseliche he him gret:</L>
<L N="1625">'Sir abbot, he &thorn;e haue &amp; weld,</L>
<L>&THORN;at made man wex in-to eld!</L>
<L>&amp; for &thorn;e loue of &thorn;e trinite,<NOTE PLACE="marg">The first <I>i</I> in <I>trinite</I> added over the line.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ich &thorn;e bidde, par charite,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ou &thorn;is bodi vnder-fo,</L>
<L N="1630">&amp; feir biry &thorn;ou it do.</L>
<L>Ful wele y schal &yogh;eld it &thorn;e,</L>
<L>&amp; y mot haue hele, &amp; liues be.'</L>
<L>'Who artow?' seyd &thorn;e abbot, 'telle it me.'</L>
<L>'Ble&thorn;eliche,' seyd Gij, 'bi mi leute:</L>
<L N="1635">A kni&yogh;t icham of fer cuntre;<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="1237"></L>
<L>At a pas asailed wer we</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; strong &thorn;eues &amp; mani outlawe,</L>
<L>&THORN;at mine feren haue y-slawe;</L>
<L>&amp; ich me-self am iuel y-wounde,</L>
<L N="1640">Y wene y liue no<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. originally <I>leue non.</I></NOTE> stounde;</L>
<L>Ac &yogh;if y liue, y &yogh;eld it &thorn;e,</L>
<L>&THORN;e trauail &thorn;at tow dost for me.'</L>
<L>&THORN;abbot answerd &thorn;o:</L>
<L>'Al &thorn;i wille it schal be do.'</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="section">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1645">Now go&thorn; Gij sore desmaid,</L>
<L>His woundes him han iuel afreyd.
<PB REF="00000098.tif" N="94"></L>
<L>To an ermite he is y-go,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he was ere aqueynted to;</L>
<L>His woundes &thorn;er hele he dede<MILESTONE N="116a:2" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="1650">Wi&thorn;outen noise in that stede.</L>
<L>Miche he him dradde &thorn;e douk Otoun,<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. <I>of toun.</I></NOTE></L>
<L>So ful he was of tresoun.</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;abot of whom ich er of teld,<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="1253"></L>
<L>On Herhaud he hadde gret rew&thorn;e to biheld;</L>
<L N="1655">He dede beren his body</L>
<L>Into a chamber to vnarmy.</L>
<L>A monk of &thorn;e house biheld him,</L>
<L>Bodi &amp; heued &amp; ich a lim.</L>
<L>&THORN;ilke monk sorgien was,</L>
<L N="1660">&THORN;e vertu he knewe of mani a gras;</L>
<L>&THORN;e wounde he biheld stedefastliche,</L>
<L>&THORN;at in his body was so griseliche.</L>
<L>Bi the wounde he seye y-wis</L>
<L>&THORN;at to &thorn;e de&thorn; wounded he nis,</L>
<L N="1665">&amp; seye &thorn;at he hym hele mi&yogh;t;</L>
<L>&amp; so he dede ful wele, y pli&yogh;t.</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="section">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bi &thorn;e mone&thorn; ende at eue</L>
<L>Gij was al hole &amp; toke his leue</L>
<L>From &thorn;e gode ermite, he went his way</L>
<L N="1670">Toward Poile, also &thorn;e way lay.<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="1272"></L>
<L>To &thorn;e king he is icome</L>
<L>&THORN;at him bede mani warisone,</L>
<L>&amp; miche tresour of siluer &amp; of gold;</L>
<L>Ac Gij &thorn;erof non haue no wold.</L>
<L N="1675">At ich plas &amp; turnament</L>
<L>Gij hadde &thorn;e priis verrament.<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="1286"></L>
<L>Was &thorn;er non in al &thorn;at lond,</L>
<L>&THORN;at his dent mi&yogh;t astond.</L>
<L>&THORN;er-fore men loued him swi&thorn;e miche,</L>
<L N="1680">&amp; vnder-fenge him ble&thorn;eliche;</L>
<L>Alle gode men he was leue &amp; dere,</L>
<L>&amp; wi&thorn; hem alle pleye-fere.
<PB REF="00000100.tif" N="96"></L>
<L>Atte king he toke leue &thorn;o;</L>
<L>Into Sessoyne he is ygo.</L>
<L N="1685">&para; Now he is comen to &thorn;e douk Reyner,</L>
<L>&THORN;at him loued and held dere;</L>
<L>He him vnder-feng wi&thorn; wor&thorn;schipe,</L>
<L>&amp; dede him miche manschipe.</L>
<L>So long in &thorn;at cuntre bileued he is,</L>
<L N="1690">&THORN;at ouer alle o&thorn;er he is praised y-wis.</L>
<L>Gij him bi&thorn;ou&yogh;t &thorn;o</L>
<L>&THORN;at he hadde &thorn;er y-nou&yogh; ydo:</L>
<L>Into Inglond he wald wende,<MILESTONE N="116b:1" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>For to speke wi&thorn; his frende;</L>
<L N="1695">For it was ago fif &yogh;er</L>
<L>&THORN;at he was last &thorn;er;<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="1290"></L>
<L>In lasse while &thorn;an &thorn;at was</L>
<L>Might falle mani wonder cas.</L>
<L>&THORN;urch cuntres has he hadde y-went,</L>
<L N="1700">Quens and cuntas him ha&thorn; of-sent,</L>
<L>Ac non of hem he nold sikerliche</L>
<L>Bot Felice &thorn;at he loued so miche.</L>
<L>What for his mi&yogh;t and his godenisse,</L>
<L>For his nortour and his largesse,</L>
<L N="1705">&THORN;er nis kni&yogh;t &thorn;at so miche preysed be</L>
<L>Unto Antiage, &thorn;at riche cite.</L>
<L>&para; Gij him spedde ni&yogh;t &amp; day;</L>
<L>Into Inglond he toke &thorn;e way.</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="section">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Of Gij ichil lete now,</L>
<L N="1710">And more after y schal tel &yogh;ou;</L>
<L>Of Herhaud ichil telle astounde</L>
<L>&THORN;at wele is heled of his wounde.</L>
<L>When he feld him hole &amp; fere,</L>
<L>Of &thorn;abot he tok his leue &thorn;er;</L>
<L N="1715">His lord Gij he go&thorn; secheing</L>
<L>Ni&yogh;t &amp; day, him for to finde:</L>
<L>Toward Inglond he tok his way,</L>
<L>Crist him saue, so wele he may!
<PB REF="00000102.tif" N="98"></L>
<L>At a pinacle bi &thorn;e se<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="1315"></L>
<L N="1720">Gij seye a man of rewly ble</L>
<L>Go in pilgrims wede:</L>
<L>&THORN;at was Herhaud, so god me spede!</L>
<L>Gij him cleped wel swi&thorn;e to him,</L>
<L>&amp; seyd, 'wen comestow, pilgrim?'</L>
<L N="1725">'Sir,' he seyd, 'y com fram Lombardy,</L>
<L>Of hard y-schaped<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>Of hardschipe?</I></NOTE> for &thorn;e maistrie;</L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L>&amp; lorn ichaue mi kinde lord:</L>
<L N="1730">Gode kni&yogh;t he was and bold.</L>
<L>Bitraid ous hadde &thorn;e douk Otoun<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. <I>of toun.</I></NOTE>:</L>
<L>Haue he Cristes malisoun!</L>
<L>In &thorn;is wise ichil go,</L>
<L>&amp; bid for mi lord euer mo.'</L>
<L N="1735">'Pilgrim, say me trewelich,</L>
<L>What hete &thorn;e man &thorn;ou loued so miche?'</L>
<L>'Gij of Warwike was his name:</L>
<L>A kni&yogh;t he was wi&thorn;-outen blame.'<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="1336"></L>
<L>Wi&thorn; &thorn;at he gan to sike sore,<MILESTONE N="116b:2" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="1740">&amp; wepe wi&thorn; his ey&yogh;en &thorn;erfore;</L>
<L>He him mi&yogh;t no lenge at-held.</L>
<L>Gij him gan reweliche biheld:</L>
<L>'Gode man,' quod Gij, 'for &thorn;i leute,</L>
<L>What is &thorn;i name? telle thou me.'</L>
<L N="1745">'Herhaud of Ardern, bi mi leute,</L>
<L>Ich was y-born in &thorn;at cuntre;</L>
<L>Fif &yogh;er &thorn;us ichaue y-go</L>
<L>To seche Gij y loued so.'</L>
<L>When Gij herd Herhaud speke,<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="1343"></L>
<L N="1750">Him thou&yogh;t his hert wald to-breke,</L>
<L>&amp; in his armes he ha&thorn; him take,</L>
<L>&amp; gret ioie wi&thorn; him gan make;</L>
<L>Him he kist wel mani si&thorn;e:</L>
<L>For ioie he wepe, so was he bli&thorn;e.
<PB REF="00000104.tif" N="100"></L>
<L N="1755">'Hayl, Herhaud, maister min!</L>
<L>No knowestow nou&yogh;t norri &thorn;ine?'</L>
<L>'Certes,' quod Herhaud, 'sir, nay:</L>
<L>Ded he was for mani a day.'</L>
<L>He him answerd, 'icham Gij!'</L>
<L N="1760">'Sir,' quod Herhaud, 'merci!'</L>
<L>Sone so Herhaud vnder-stode</L>
<L>&THORN;at it was Gij &thorn;at was so gode,</L>
<L>For ioie he fel aswon anon;</L>
<L>Gij him in his armes nome.</L>
<L N="1765">&THORN;er men mi&yogh;t se ioie make</L>
<L>Ai&thorn;er kni&yogh;t for o&thorn;er sake;</L>
<L>&THORN;er nas non &thorn;at it y-seye,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he no wepe wi&thorn; his ey&yogh;e.</L>
<L>&para; Adoun &thorn;ai sett hem bo&thorn;e &thorn;are,<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="1357"></L>
<L N="1770">&amp; ai&thorn;er teld of o&thorn;eres care.</L>
<L>Sir Gij ha&thorn; Herhaud y-teld</L>
<L>Hou he him ladde out of &thorn;e feld,</L>
<L>For to birry him at on abbay</L>
<L>&THORN;at was bisiden on &thorn;e way.</L>
<L N="1775">&amp; se&thorn;&thorn;en<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>n on erasure.</I></NOTE> ha&thorn; Herhaud y-teld</L>
<L>Hou his woundes weren y-heled,</L>
<L>And &thorn;at mani lond he hadde ouergo,</L>
<L>To seche his lord wi&thorn; sorwe &amp; wo.</L>
<L>On hors &thorn;ai lopen anon wi&thorn; &thorn;is</L>
<L N="1780">Vnto a cite wi&thorn; ioie and blis;</L>
<L>&THORN;an dede Gij Herhaud ba&thorn;ey</L>
<L>&amp; wi&thorn; riche metes comforti.</L>
<L>From &thorn;ennes &thorn;ai went to &thorn;e douk Miloun,<MILESTONE N="117a:1" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And to him &thorn;ai ben ful welcome;</L>
<L N="1785">Of her auentours &thorn;ai teld him &thorn;ere:</L>
<L>Hou &thorn;o was gode &thorn;at wicke was ere!</L>
<L>&THORN;er &thorn;ai maden her dueling</L>
<L>Long anou&yogh; to her likeing.</L>
<L>&para; At the douke &thorn;ai token leue &thorn;o,<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="1383"></L>
<L N="1790">For in-to Inglond &thorn;ai wald go.
<PB REF="00000106.tif" N="102"></L>
<L>&THORN;e douke hem wald lenger duelle,</L>
<L>Ac it nas no-thing in her wille</L>
<L>&THORN;er to bileue wi&thorn; him no more,</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;at bi&thorn;ou&yogh;t &thorn;e douke wel sore.</L>
<L N="1795">Toward Seynt Omer<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. <I>seyntomer</I>.</NOTE> he is y-go,</L>
<L>Herhaud &thorn;e gode wi&thorn; him also;</L>
<L>Toward &thorn;e se &thorn;ai token her way,</L>
<L>So swi&thorn;e her hors hem bere may.</L>
<L>When &thorn;ai ben to toun y-come,</L>
<L N="1800">Her in &thorn;ai han sone y-nome.</L>
<L>To a windowe sir Gij is go,<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="1395"></L>
<L>In-to &thorn;e strete he loked &thorn;o;</L>
<L>A palmer he se&yogh;e cominge,</L>
<L>Messaisliche bi &thorn;e strete walkinge.</L>
<L N="1805">To him ha&thorn; y-cleped sir Gij,</L>
<L>&amp; curteysliche gan him axi,</L>
<L>'Weltow herberwe? for it is ni&yogh;t;</L>
<L>For fer&thorn;er go &thorn;ou no mi&yogh;t.'</L>
<L>&THORN;e pilgrim answerd Gij,</L>
<L N="1810">'Swete sir, gramerci!'</L>
<L>Gij do&thorn; him &thorn;an bileue,</L>
<L>Fer&thorn;er he no may, for it was eue;</L>
<L>&amp; se&thorn;&thorn;e he badde he schuld him say</L>
<L>Sum so&thorn; tidinges of &thorn;e way,</L>
<L N="1815">&YOGH;if he herd neye o&thorn;er fer</L>
<L>Speken of batayle &amp; of wer.</L>
<L>'Ichil &thorn;e telle,' he seyd, 'fot hot</L>
<L>Of al &thorn;e wer &thorn;at y wot:</L>
<L>&THORN;erof is mani man aferd;</L>
<L N="1820">Of stronger sorwe no haue &yogh;e herd.'</L>
<L>&para; Gij seyd to him, 'telle it me.'</L>
<L>'For so&thorn;e y graunt,' &thorn;an seyd he.</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="section">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Of Almaine &thorn;e riche emperour,<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="1413"></L>
<L>Reyner, &thorn;at welde&thorn; &thorn;at anour,</L>
<L N="1825">&THORN;e douke of Lowayn he<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>he</I> dotted before <I>he</I>.</NOTE> ha&thorn; bisett,</L>
<L>His men slain, &amp; &thorn;at is vnnett;
<PB REF="00000108.tif" N="104"></L>
<L>For his nevou &thorn;at he slou&yogh;,<MILESTONE N="117a:2" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Wi&thorn; wer he do&thorn; him wo anou&yogh;.</L>
<L>Almost a &yogh;er it is ago,</L>
<L N="1830">A turnament &thorn;er was y-do;</L>
<L>&THORN;e douke Segyn was &thorn;er &thorn;o,<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="1425"></L>
<L>&THORN;at al Lowayn<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. <I>alowayn.</I></NOTE> bilonge&thorn; to,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; his<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>&thorn;e</I>?</NOTE> kni&yogh;tes of his lond,</L>
<L>&THORN;ider come her mi&yogh;t to fond.</L>
<L N="1835">When &thorn;e turnament com to &thorn;ende,</L>
<L>&THORN;e douke Segyn &thorn;ennes wald wende:</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; &thorn;at come Sadok<NOTE PLACE="marg">on erasure.</NOTE> prikeing,</L>
<L>&THORN;e douke Segyn vnder-secheing;</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; &thorn;e douke he hadde gret envie,</L>
<L N="1840">For he was gode kni&yogh;t for &thorn;e maistrie.</L>
<L>Sadok was y-hoten &thorn;at gome,</L>
<L>Out of Mirabel he was y-come;</L>
<L>Of turnamens he was praised &thorn;o.</L>
<L>His hauberk was of y-do;</L>
<L N="1845">In sengle armes he was y-di&yogh;t.</L>
<L>Y-preysed he was for a gode kni&yogh;t.</L>
<L>To &thorn;e douke he seyd, 'wende tow &thorn;e;</L>
<L>Ones &thorn;ou schalt justi wi&thorn; me,</L>
<L>As kni&yogh;t that wele alosed is;</L>
<L N="1850">Sone it wor&thorn; sen y-wis.'</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="section">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'Sadok,' seyd Segyn, 'lete me be,<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="1449"></L>
<L>Wi&thorn; gode loue y pray &thorn;e;</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; &thorn;e to justi haue y no wille,</L>
<L>For y &thorn;e loue, and &thorn;at is skille,</L>
<L N="1855">&amp; to eken &thorn;at &thorn;ou art mi lordes nevou:</L>
<L>His soster sone so artow;</L>
<L>Unwor&thorn;schip it wer to me</L>
<L>&YOGH;if y schuld iusti wi&thorn; &thorn;e.</L>
<L>Ac go in, and arme &thorn;e snelle,</L>
<L N="1860">And y com anon, y nil nou&yogh;t duelle.'</L>
<L>Seyd Sadok, 'to arwe artow,</L>
<L>When ones justi no darstow now.
<PB REF="00000110.tif" N="106"></L>
<L>Now ichil &thorn;e for a couward held,</L>
<L>&amp; for a kni&yogh;t vnwrast in feld:</L>
<L N="1865">Bot &thorn;ou wilt wi&thorn; me justi,</L>
<L>Ichil<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. Iichil.</NOTE> &thorn;e don a vilani.</L>
<L>Hennes forward war &thorn;e fro me,</L>
<L>&THORN;i dedliche fo ichil now be!'</L>
<L>Now Sadok smot to Segyn,<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="1465"></L>
<L N="1870">&amp; nothing he no spared him;<MILESTONE N="117b:1" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Sadok toforn ha&thorn; him smete</L>
<L>Of his scheld a quarter wi&thorn; gret hete,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he him wounded &thorn;urch &thorn;at arm,</L>
<L>&amp; he him wre&thorn;ed for that harm;</L>
<L N="1875">So strong is &thorn;at strok y-&yogh;iue,</L>
<L>&THORN;at his helme is al to-driue.</L>
<L>&THORN;e douke him wre&thorn;&thorn;ed for &thorn;at smite,</L>
<L>&amp; was ful wro&thorn;, &yogh;e mow wele wite,</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;urch &thorn;e bodi he Sadok smot,</L>
<L N="1880">&THORN;at ded he fel doun fot hot.</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; &thorn;at he is out of the place y-went,</L>
<L>For &thorn;er was &yogh;iuen a sorwe-ful dent.</L>
<L>With him he dede &thorn;at bodi lede</L>
<L>Unto an abbay, and biri it dede.</L>
<L N="1885">&THORN;e douke Segin anon ri&yogh;t</L>
<L>Into the cite of Arrascoun him ha&thorn; y-di&yogh;t:</L>
<L>&THORN;er-in he holt him soiourninge</L>
<L>For drede of &thorn;emperours cominge.</L>
<L>&para; &amp; when &thorn;emperour herd &thorn;is cas,<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="1497"></L>
<L N="1890">&THORN;at his nevou y-slawe was,</L>
<L>Ouer al his lond his hest he bede</L>
<L>To com to him for grete nede.</L>
<L>&amp; when &thorn;ai al icomen be&thorn;,</L>
<L>&THORN;e douke of Lowayn he sege de&thorn;;</L>
<L N="1895">No wil he neuer &thorn;ennes come,</L>
<L>Er the douke be ded or nome.'</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="section">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>When &thorn;e pilgrim hadde al y-teld,<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="1531"></L>
<L>Gij him herkened &amp; biheld;
<PB REF="00000112.tif" N="108"></L>
<L>He stont &amp; bi&thorn;ou&yogh;t him &yogh;erne,</L>
<L N="1900">Whe&thorn;er he for&thorn; go o&thorn;er o&yogh;ain terne.</L>
<L>He seyd to Herhaud, 'what rede [&yogh;e]?</L>
<L>Sum gode conseyl &yogh;if &thorn;ou me,</L>
<L>&YOGH;if we for&thorn; in our wai go,</L>
<L>O&thorn;er to &thorn;e douke him socour to do.</L>
<L N="1905">&THORN;at tow me redest, don y wille;</L>
<L>&THORN;i conseyl forsake y nille.'</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;an seyd Herhaud i-wis,<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="1543"></L>
<L>'Y &yogh;if conseyl, &amp; gode it is;</L>
<L>Hem to help men schul spede</L>
<L N="1910">&THORN;at to help han gret nede.</L>
<L>For los and priis &thorn;ou mi&yogh;t &thorn;er winne,</L>
<L>&amp; manschip to &thorn;e &amp; al &thorn;i kinne.'</L>
<L>'Sir Herhaud,' quod Gij &thorn;e gode,</L>
<L>'&THORN;ilke lord &thorn;at died on rode</L>
<L N="1915">&THORN;e blisse, &amp; saue &thorn;e,<MILESTONE N="117b:2" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>For gode conseyl &yogh;if[es]tow me.'</L>
<L>Gij him grai&thorn;ed &amp; made him &yogh;are</L>
<L>Into Loweyne<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. <I>loreynie.</I></NOTE> for to fare;</L>
<L>&amp; wi&thorn; him o&thorn;er fifti kni&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="1920">In feld &thorn;e best &thorn;at mi&yogh;t fi&yogh;t.</L>
<L>Y-comen &thorn;ai ben to Arascoun,</L>
<L>To &thorn;e douke &thorn;ai ben wel-com.</L>
<L>In &thorn;e cite &thorn;ai han her in y-take;</L>
<L>Mani wer bli&thorn;e for her sake.</L>
<L N="1925">Gij bi &thorn;e morwe aros &thorn;o,<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="1569"></L>
<L>Ri&yogh;t to chirche he is y-go:</L>
<L>Matins &amp; masse he herd &thorn;ere,</L>
<L>&amp; se&thorn;&thorn;e went hom wi&thorn; his fere.</L>
<L>Bi &thorn;e strete he seye miche folk erne,</L>
<L N="1930">Hemself to were &thorn;ai most lerne.</L>
<L>Sir Gij to his ost sede,</L>
<L>'What is al &thorn;is? so god &thorn;e rede,</L>
<L>Bele ost,<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>ost</I> added over the line.</NOTE> y bidde, say &thorn;ou me,</L>
<L>What may al &thorn;is erning be?'
<PB REF="00000114.tif" N="110"></L>
<L N="1935">'Sir, ichil &thorn;e telle,' &thorn;an seyd he,</L>
<L>'No word nil ich ly&yogh;e &thorn;e;</L>
<L>It is &thorn;emperours steward,</L>
<L>A gode kni&yogh;t and no coward</L>
<L>(Anon to Speyne his better nis),</L>
<L N="1940">&amp; with him gret compeynie y-wis,</L>
<L>An hundred kni&yogh;tes gode of ker,</L>
<L>Her better no may wepen ber.</L>
<L>&THORN;e cite &thorn;ai han bisett:</L>
<L>&YOGH;if ani kni&yogh;t be out y-mett,</L>
<L N="1945">He no mai nou&yogh;t passe vn-y-nome,</L>
<L>O&thorn;er y-slayn atte frome.'</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="section">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;an seyd Gij, 'lordinges, kni&yogh;t,</L>
<L>O&yogh;ains hem we wil ous di&yogh;t.'</L>
<L>Sone &thorn;ai ben in &thorn;e way y-don.</L>
<L N="1950">&THORN;e steward se&thorn; hem anon:<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="1605"></L>
<L>&THORN;ider-ward he him di&yogh;t,</L>
<L>Also a kni&yogh;t<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. <I>akni&yogh;t</I>.</NOTE> of gret mi&yogh;t.</L>
<L>His armes &thorn;an he ginne&thorn; ri&yogh;t,</L>
<L>O&yogh;aines Gij he ritt apli&yogh;t;</L>
<L N="1955">Anon to-gider &thorn;ai gun smite,</L>
<L>Ai&thorn;er spard o&thorn;er bot lite.</L>
<L>Gij &thorn;e steward so hard smot,</L>
<L>Of his stede he feld him fot hot;</L>
<L>&THORN;an he smot him wi&thorn; his swerd broun</L>
<L N="1960">A quarter of his helme adoun.<MILESTONE N="118a:1" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&THORN;urch grete streng&thorn;e he him wan,</L>
<L>&amp; hom wi&thorn; him ladde him &thorn;an.</L>
<L>When &thorn;e Almaines &thorn;at y-seye<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="1631"></L>
<L>&THORN;at strong wer, and of fi&yogh;t sleye,</L>
<L N="1965">Her lord nomen in &thorn;at fi&yogh;t,</L>
<L>Owai &thorn;ai priked wi&thorn; al her mi&yogh;t.</L>
<L>&THORN;er was &thorn;irled mani a scheld,<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. <I>ascheld.</I></NOTE></L>
<L>Mani a kni&yogh;t lay in &thorn;e feld;</L>
<L>Gij is o&yogh;ain went wel sone,</L>
<L N="1970">&amp; al his feren mid-y-done.
<PB REF="00000116.tif" N="112"></L>
<L>&THORN;e Lombardes<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>Almaines?</I></NOTE> &thorn;ai leggen fast opon,</L>
<L>Nil &thorn;ai spare neuer on.</L>
<L>When &thorn;e kni&yogh;tes of &thorn;at cite</L>
<L>&THORN;is dede alle y-sey&yogh;en he,</L>
<L N="1975">To army he[m] wel fast hy go&thorn;,</L>
<L>Gij wel gode socour hij do&thorn;;</L>
<L>&amp; se&thorn;&thorn;en &thorn;ai went for&thorn; ari&yogh;t,</L>
<L>&amp; Gij socourd ful wele apli&yogh;t.</L>
<L>Swiche strokes men mi&yogh;t &thorn;er se</L>
<L N="1980">Togider smiten &thorn;o kni&yogh;tes fre:</L>
<L>Bo&thorn;e wi&thorn; launce and wi&thorn; swerd</L>
<L>Thai &yogh;iuen mani strokes herd.</L>
<L>&THORN;er mi&yogh;t men se stray &thorn;e steden,</L>
<L>So mani kni&yogh;t cri &amp; greden,</L>
<L N="1985">&THORN;at wer &thorn;urch &thorn;e bodi wounde,</L>
<L>&amp; ded fellen on &thorn;e grounde.</L>
<L>&para; Michel him peyned sir Gij,<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="1657"></L>
<L>&amp; Herhaud of Ardern sikerly:</L>
<L>&THORN;is Almayns &thorn;ai han ouercome,</L>
<L N="1990">Sum y-slawe and sum y-nome.</L>
<L>&THORN;an sir Gij anon ri&yogh;t</L>
<L>Into &thorn;e cite he him di&yogh;t,</L>
<L>Bo&thorn;e he &amp; his ferred:</L>
<L>&THORN;e prisouns wi&thorn; hem &thorn;ai lede.</L>
<L N="1995">Into &thorn;e cite &thorn;ai ben y-gon,</L>
<L>&amp; to her innes &thorn;ai wenten ichon.</L>
<L>Proude &thorn;ai ben alle &amp; some</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;e Almains ben ouer-come,</L>
<L>When &thorn;e douke yherd &thorn;is tidinge,</L>
<L N="2000">For blis his hert bigan to springe,</L>
<L>&THORN;at Gii of Warwike was y-come</L>
<L>&amp; hadde &thorn;e steward y-nome.</L>
<L>On his stede he lepe anon,<MILESTONE N="118a:2" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>To Gyes in he is y-gon;</L>
<L N="2005">'Gij,' he seyd, '&thorn;ou art welcome,</L>
<L>As of the warld &thorn;e best gome.
<PB REF="00000118.tif" N="114"></L>
<L N="1905">Toforn al o&thorn;er ichaue desired &thorn;e:</L>
<L>God y-thanked mot he be</L>
<L>&THORN;at tow art come wi&thorn; me to ben at nede,</L>
<L>For now ich wor&thorn; &thorn;e more loued &amp; drede</L>
<L>Al of mi dedelich fo,</L>
<L N="1910">&THORN;at al &thorn;is lond ha&thorn; brou&yogh;t in wo.</L>
<L>Sire &amp; lord now ichil make &thorn;e</L>
<L>Of mi court and of mi cite,</L>
<L>Mine castels &amp; mine londes &thorn;er-to eke;</L>
<L>&amp; hennes forward y &thorn;e biseke</L>
<L N="1915">&THORN;atow &thorn;e wor&thorn;schipe vnder-fo,</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;ine hest &thorn;erof &thorn;ou do.</L>
<L>Bi &thorn;i conseyl ichil nov don,</L>
<L>For to greue mi<NOTE PLACE="marg">originally <I>&THORN;i</I>, but crossed out and <I>mi</I> written over it in the same hand.</NOTE> dedli fon.'</L>
<L>&para; Wel curteysliche answerd Gij<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="1700"></L>
<L N="1920">&amp; seyd, 'sir, gramerci.</L>
<L>Bi mi mi&yogh;t ichil help &thorn;e</L>
<L>On ich stede where &thorn;at y be.'</L>
<L>&THORN;e steward he &yogh;elt him &thorn;an swi&thorn;e,</L>
<L>Of whom &thorn;at he was glad &amp; bli&thorn;e;</L>
<L N="1925">&THORN;urch him he wende acorded be</L>
<L>Of &thorn;emperour, his lord so fre.</L>
<L>Bitvene hem &thorn;ai tolden tale</L>
<L>Of her gode frendes fale.</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="section">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Now sent Gij his sondes about,</L>
<L N="1930">&YOGH;epe men wi&thorn;-outen dout,</L>
<L>To cuntres &thorn;at he ha&thorn; &thorn;urch-went.</L>
<L>Grete frendes he ha&thorn; of-sent,</L>
<L>Of barouns and of kni&yogh;tes beld</L>
<L>&THORN;e best &thorn;at mi&yogh;t wepen weld,</L>
<L N="1935">Bi hundred and bi &thorn;ousinde,</L>
<L>&THORN;at al wil ben his helpinde.</L>
<L>&THORN;e castels and &thorn;e borwes &thorn;at lorn were,</L>
<L>&THORN;e douke o&yogh;ain wan hem &thorn;ere</L>
<L>&THORN;urch Gyes help &amp; his ferrede,</L>
<L N="1940">&THORN;at wele wer helpeand at nede,
<PB REF="00000120.tif" N="116"></L>
<L>Bi him &amp; bi his conseyl also,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ennes forward him trewe&thorn;e wil do.</L>
<L>&para; When &thorn;emperour yherd &thorn;is,</L>
<L>&THORN;at Gij to &thorn;e douke ycomen is,</L>
<L N="1945">&amp; &thorn;at he ha&thorn; his men ouercome,<MILESTONE N="118b:1" UNIT="folio"><MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="1700"></L>
<L>Y-slawe &amp; his steward nome,</L>
<L>Wro&thorn; &amp; sori he is &thorn;er-fore,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he ha&thorn; so his men forlore.</L>
<L>To his barouns &thorn;an he sede:</L>
<L N="1950">'Lordinges, what schal me to rede?</L>
<L>Neuer no wor&thorn; ich glad no bli&thorn;e,</L>
<L>Bot ich be awreken swi&thorn;e</L>
<L>Of Segyn &amp; Gij &thorn;at is our fo,</L>
<L>&THORN;at mi folk ha&thorn; brou&yogh;t in wo.'</L>
<L N="1955">'Sir,' the douk Paui sede,</L>
<L>'Ther-of &thorn;arf &thorn;e haue no drede.</L>
<L>Ar &thorn;e &thorn;ridde day wor&thorn; to ende y-brou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>&THORN;at play wor&thorn; wel dere abou&yogh;t;</L>
<L>For of &thorn;ine folk take we wille,</L>
<L N="1960">&THORN;at gode ben &amp; snelle,</L>
<L>&THORN;e best doand at swiche nede</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; scheld &amp; spere armed on stede:</L>
<L>Of Sessoine &thorn;e douke Reyner,</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;e constable Gaudiner,</L>
<L N="1965">&amp; ich wi&thorn; hem wil be,</L>
<L>&amp; gret ferred lede wi&thorn; me.</L>
<L>To Arascoun we schul fare,</L>
<L>&YOGH;if we &thorn;e douk finde &thorn;are.</L>
<L>Bot we &thorn;e treytours &thorn;e &yogh;elde,</L>
<L N="1970">We wil &thorn;atow in prisoun ous held.</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;emperour answerd: 'y-wis,<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="1749"></L>
<L>A gode conseyl so is &thorn;is.</L>
<L>Sir douk Reyner, &thorn;ou schalt go,</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;ou, constable, al-so;</L>
<L N="1975">Al-so schal &thorn;e douke of Pauie</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; his grete cheualrie
<PB REF="00000122.tif" N="118"></L>
<L>To Arascoun, &thorn;at gode cite:</L>
<L>&THORN;e douke &amp; Gij bring to me.</L>
<L>Who so to me bring hem to,</L>
<L N="1980">Mi loue he schal haue for euer mo.'</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="section">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'Sir,' &thorn;ai seyd, 'we willen go</L>
<L>Al &thorn;ine hest for to do.'</L>
<L>Now hij han her way y-nome,</L>
<L>To Arascoun &thorn;at ben y-come.</L>
<L N="1985">When &thorn;ai of &thorn;e cite wist hem &thorn;are,</L>
<L>O&yogh;aines hem &thorn;ai di&yogh;t hem &yogh;are;</L>
<L>Hastiliche to armes &thorn;ai ben y-go,</L>
<L>Kni&yogh;tes and squiers wi&thorn; hem also.</L>
<L>When &thorn;ai wer al redi,<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. <I>alredi</I></NOTE><MILESTONE N="118b:2" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="1990">&amp; wele y-di&yogh;t in her parti,</L>
<L>&THORN;e douke cleped Herhaud him to,</L>
<L>&amp; swetely seyd to him &thorn;o:</L>
<L>'Sir Herhaud, &thorn;ou schalt afong</L>
<L>Four hundred kni&yogh;tes wi&yogh;t and strong</L>
<L N="1995">(&THORN;ou schalt &yogh;if &thorn;e first asaut</L>
<L>Opon &thorn;e Almaundes, sir Herhaud);</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;ou, sir Gij, an hundred to &thorn;e</L>
<L>Of mi londe &thorn;at best be;</L>
<L>And &yogh;if &thorn;at Herhaud haue nede,</L>
<L N="2000">Him to help &thorn;atow spede,</L>
<L>&amp; ichil com wi&thorn;outen delay</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; al &thorn;e streng&thorn;e &thorn;at y may.</L>
<L>Togider wi&thorn; hem we schul fi&yogh;t,</L>
<L>&amp; hem ouer-com &thorn;urch godes mi&yogh;t.<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="1792"></L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="section">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="2005">As ichaue seyd, loke ye don,</L>
<L>&amp; go&thorn; and asaile&thorn; hem anon.'</L>
<L>Herhaud ginne&thorn; hem to asaily.<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. originally <I>asaile</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at fi&yogh;t he wil comenci.</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e douk Otus Herhaud is vnder-nome</L>
<L N="2010">In &thorn;e alder first scheltrome;</L>
<L>His fo he is euen for&thorn; his mi&yogh;t,</L>
<L>For he it ha&thorn; deserued &thorn;urch ri&yogh;t.
<PB REF="00000124.tif" N="120"></L>
<L>Herhaud him seyd, 'Otus of Pauie,</L>
<L>Understond tow of &thorn;at felonie<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="1804"></L>
<L N="2015">&THORN;at tow in Lombardi ous dedest,</L>
<L>When &thorn;ou mi lord betreydest.</L>
<L>Wele we schul &thorn;er-of awreke be,</L>
<L>&YOGH;if god wil, er &thorn;e sonne doun te.'</L>
<L>&para; Otus answerd, '&thorn;ou lexst on me,</L>
