<DIV2 TYPE="section"><PB REF="00000136.tif" N="132">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Wi&thorn; &thorn;at come prikeand Tirri,</L>
<L N="2230">Of Gurmoise &thorn;erl sone Aubri;</L>
<L>Wel sternliche he smitt a kni&yogh;t,</L>
<L>&THORN;at ded he fel anon ri&yogh;t.</L>
<L>So sone so douke Segyn se&thorn; &thorn;is,<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="2091"></L>
<L>Wel wro&thorn; he was wi&thorn; him y-wis;</L>
<L N="2235">Wro&thorn;lich he seyd to Gij,</L>
<L>'Here is gret scorn sikerly,</L>
<L>When &thorn;at olepi kni&yogh;t</L>
<L>Schal ous do so michel vnri&yogh;t,</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;an wi&thorn; his saut owai flen.'</L>
<L N="2240">Gij answerd, 'turn we o&yogh;en,</L>
<L>&amp; hardiliche aseyl we hem:</L>
<L>Anon turn we o&yogh;en.'</L>
<L>&THORN;e Almauns &thorn;ai go to asayl<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="2101"></L>
<L>Wi&thorn; gret streng&thorn;e in batayl;</L>
<L N="2245">Sorweful of hem was &thorn;e meteinge</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; brondes of stiel wele kerueinge.</L>
<L>Anon &thorn;e Almaundes gin flen,</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;e o&thorn;er turnen o&yogh;en.</L>
<L>&THORN;e douk Segyn o&yogh;ain come,</L>
<L N="2250">Ri&yogh;t to his cite &thorn;e way he nome,</L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L N="2255">&amp; Gij afterward wi&thorn; him is go,<MILESTONE N="119a:b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&amp; eke his feren also.</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; hem &thorn;ai habben her prisouns,</L>
<L>Doukes, erls, &amp; barouns;</L>
<L>Wel glad &amp; bli&thorn;e &thorn;an ben he,</L>
<L N="2260">&amp; al &thorn;at weren in &thorn;at cite.</L>
<L>To her innes &thorn;ai ben y-gon,</L>
<L>Wel glad ben hij euerichon.</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="section">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;e douke go&thorn; in-to &thorn;e tour:<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="2137"></L>
<L>His prisouns he do&thorn; gret anour,
<PB REF="00000138.tif" N="134"></L>
<L N="2265">&THORN;erl Reyner of Sessoyne,</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;erl Gaudiner of Coloyne,</L>
<L>&amp; wi&thorn; hem &thorn;e stewerd,</L>
<L>&THORN;at gode kni&yogh;t was &amp; wel y-herd.</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; him eten he hem dede,</L>
<L N="2270">&amp; more &thorn;an himself hem wor&thorn;schipede.</L>
<L>&THORN;e douke his soster cleped him to,</L>
<L>&THORN;e fairest maiden &thorn;at mi&yogh;t go.</L>
<L>'&THORN;e prisouns &thorn;ou nim to &thorn;e,</L>
<L>In &thorn;i chamber wi&thorn; &thorn;e to be;</L>
<L N="2275">In &thorn;i chaumber<NOTE PLACE="marg">the <I>u</I> has a stroke too much.</NOTE> kepes me</L>
<L>&THORN;is gentil kni&yogh;tes hende &amp; fre;</L>
<L>&amp; ouer alle o&thorn;er &thorn;e douke Reyner:</L>
<L>In hert he is me lef &amp; dere.'</L>
<L>'Sir,' sche seyd, 'ichil so</L>
<L N="2280">Hem to kepe my mi&yogh;t y-do.'</L>
<L>&para; Ac &thorn;e riche emperour fre,<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="2153"></L>
<L>Of &thorn;is comberment nist he.</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; a kni&yogh;t he pleyd atte ches</L>
<L>Of Hungri, &thorn;at he loved y-wis.</L>
<L N="2285">Wi&thorn; &thorn;at com Tirri prikeinge,</L>
<L>In his fest his brond bereinge:</L>
<L>His hauberk was al to-tore,</L>
<L>&amp; his nasel avaled bifore.</L>
<L>&THORN;urch his bodi &thorn;e blod ran;</L>
<L N="2290">Tirri made no semblaunt of &thorn;an;</L>
<L>His strong scheld al to-hewen<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. <I>alto hewen.</I></NOTE> was,</L>
<L>Nou&yogh;t a fot hole &thorn;er-of<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. <I>of &thorn;er.</I></NOTE> nas.</L>
<L>&para; 'Emperour,' he seyd, 'vnder-stond to me:<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="2165"></L>
<L>Hard tidinges may y telle &thorn;e</L>
<L N="2295">Of &thorn;ine barouns &thorn;at y-nome be;</L>
<L>No schal &thorn;ai neuer com to &thorn;e.</L>
<L>Sum be ded &amp; brou&yogh;t to grounde,</L>
<L>&amp; sum be nomen, &amp; sum be wounde:</L>
<L>Y-nomen is &thorn;e douk Reyner,<MILESTONE N="119b:a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="2300">&amp; &thorn;e constable Gaudiner;
<PB REF="00000140.tif" N="136"></L>
<L>&THORN;e douke of Pauie wounded is</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; a swerd &thorn;urch &thorn;e bodi y-wis:</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e de&thorn; he drat him sore,</L>
<L>Hele no wor&thorn; him neuer more.'</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="section">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="2305">When &thorn;emperour herd &thorn;o<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="2177"></L>
<L>What &thorn;erl Tirri seyd him to,</L>
<L>Wel sori he was, &amp; wro&thorn; &thorn;er-fore,</L>
<L>&THORN;at ney&yogh;e he ha&thorn; his witt forlore.</L>
<L>Y-sworn he ha&thorn; a wel gret o&thorn;</L>
<L N="2310">Bi god almi&yogh;ti al for-so&thorn;,</L>
<L>&THORN;at neuer bli&thorn;e no wor&thorn; he,</L>
<L>Al what &thorn;at cite y-nomen be,</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;at &thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="marg">not quite distinct.</NOTE> traitours ben y-slawe,</L>
<L>O&thorn;er for-brent, o&thorn;er y-flawe.</L>
<L N="2315">&para; His<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>ost</I> underdotted.</NOTE> heste he dede cri anon,<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="2187"></L>
<L>His men to arme hem euerichon;</L>
<L>His scheltromes anon he di&yogh;t,</L>
<L>&amp; redi &thorn;ai ben al to fi&yogh;t.</L>
<L>&THORN;e feldes &thorn;ai ben sone ouer-gon</L>
<L N="2320">&THORN;at were &thorn;e tounes bisiden on,</L>
<L>Al what hij comen to &thorn;e cite.</L>
<L>Gaier<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>Gaier</I> on an erasure.</NOTE> &thorn;an for&thorn; &yogh;ede he</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; fif hundred armed kni&yogh;tes,</L>
<L>Hardi &amp; wele doand in fi&yogh;tes.</L>
<L N="2325">&THORN;o &thorn;at weren in &thorn;e cite,</L>
<L>On &thorn;e Almaynes bihelden he,</L>
<L>&amp; seye &thorn;e cuntres &amp; al &thorn;e feldes,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; white hauberkes &amp; wi&thorn; scheldes.<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="2200"></L>
<L>&THORN;e douke him com for&thorn; wi&thorn; &thorn;at,</L>
<L N="2330">Wele y-armed on stede he sat:</L>
<L>'Gij,' he seyd, 'what schal we do?</L>
<L>&YOGH;if we go &amp; smite hem to,</L>
<L>Or we gon our walles to were,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;e Almayns ous nou&yogh;t dere?'</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="section">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="2335">&THORN;an spac Sir Gij fot hot,</L>
<L>'Wele schaltow do, for-so&thorn;e y wot:
<PB REF="00000142.tif" N="138"></L>
<L>Nim we now an hundred kni&yogh;tes,</L>
<L>&amp; go asayl hem anon ri&yogh;tes.</L>
<L>Bifor &thorn;e cite y se stond here</L>
<L N="2340">Gaier, &thorn;emperour sone Reyner,</L>
<L>&amp; fif hundred<NOTE PLACE="marg">originally <I>hundered</I>, but the first <I>e</I> under|dotted.</NOTE> kni&yogh;tes in her ferred,</L>
<L>Wele y-armed on heye stede.</L>
<L>Biforn her ost &thorn;ei ben y-comen,<MILESTONE N="119b:b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Angwisous ous to nimen;</L>
<L N="2345">&amp; &yogh;if we habbe&thorn; gret nede,</L>
<L>O&yogh;ain-ward we mai ous spede.'<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="2218"></L>
<L>Anon &thorn;ai nomen an hundred kni&yogh;tes,</L>
<L>Hardi &amp; of most mi&yogh;tes;</L>
<L>&THORN;ai wenten out of &thorn;at cite,</L>
<L N="2350">Wel modi men weren he.</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; &thorn;e Almauns &thorn;ai wil iusti,</L>
<L>Nil hii nou&yogh;t wi&thorn; hem acordi;</L>
<L>Togider &thorn;ai smiten hard &amp; swi&thorn;e,</L>
<L>Of hors &thorn;ai fellen mani a si&thorn;e.</L>
<L N="2355">&para; Sir Gij him smot to Gaier,</L>
<L>&amp; feld him doun of his destrer,</L>
<L>&amp; se&thorn;&thorn;en he wan him in &thorn;at fi&yogh;t;</L>
<L>&THORN;e o&thorn;er oway flowen<NOTE PLACE="marg">originally <I>blowen</I>.</NOTE> anon ri&yogh;t.</L>
<L>Toward &thorn;e ost &thorn;ai flowen snelle,</L>
<L N="2360">&THORN;e hete was swi&thorn;e strong wi&thorn; alle.</L>
<L>Mani &thorn;ai nomen &amp; bounden fast,</L>
<L>&amp; ladde into &thorn;e cite on hast.</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="section">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>When &thorn;ai of &thorn;e ost y-seye &thorn;is,<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="2235"></L>
<L>&THORN;at her folk ouercomen is,</L>
<L N="2365">&amp; &thorn;at was in &thorn;at fi&yogh;t y-nome</L>
<L>Gaier, &thorn;at was &thorn;emperour sone,</L>
<L>&THORN;an<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>an</I> not quite distinct.</NOTE> hastiliche &thorn;e ost ichon</L>
<L>Opon Segyn &thorn;at smiten anon.</L>
<L>&THORN;er bigan a newe fi&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="2370">Whar-&thorn;urch died mani a kni&yogh;t.</L>
<L>On ai&thorn;er side mani on dyed y-wis;</L>
<L>Ac &thorn;e douke wers bifallen is,
<PB REF="00000144.tif" N="140"></L>
<L>For miche of his folk he les.</L>
<L>Al auntreousliche &thorn;er he comen wes.</L>
<L N="2375">&THORN;urch pride &thorn;an ferd he</L>
<L>Fram his ost, and fram his cite.</L>
<L>Wele hii deden no &thorn;e les,</L>
<L>He and Gii &thorn;at mi&yogh;ti wes,</L>
<L>&amp; wi&thorn; hem Herhaud of Arderne;</L>
<L N="2380">To hem &thorn;ai smiten swi&thorn;e &yogh;erne.<NOTE PLACE="marg">originally <I>&yogh;ernne</I>, but the second <I>n</I> under|dotted.</NOTE></L>
<L>&para; Wi&thorn; &thorn;at com prikeing Tirri,<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="2253"></L>
<L>&THORN;at gode kni&yogh;t was &amp; hardi;</L>
<L>To &thorn;e douk Segyn he smot,</L>
<L>&amp; of his hors feld him fot hot;</L>
<L N="2385">Ac &thorn;e douk anon vp stert,</L>
<L>As he &thorn;at was agremed in hert,</L>
<L>&amp; out he drou&yogh; his swerd of stiel,<MILESTONE N="120a:a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&amp; defended him swi&thorn;e wel.</L>
<L>Whom &thorn;at he rau&yogh;t, ded he fel;</L>
<L N="2390">Strong kni&yogh;t he was, hardi &amp; snel.</L>
<L>&THORN;er he defended him asperliche;</L>
<L>&THORN;e Almaunis him asayl hastiliche:</L>
<L>Y-loken he was hem amidwerd,</L>
<L>To him &thorn;ai launced bo&thorn;e spere and swerd.</L>
<L N="2395">In mani stede wounded is he;</L>
<L>Wele he wer&thorn;e him &thorn;ei he sailed be.<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="2268"></L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="section">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>When Gij seye &thorn;e douke of fot,</L>
<L>For sorwe no wist he no bot;</L>
<L>Wel hardiliche he smot a kni&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="2400">&THORN;at ded he feld him anon ri&yogh;t.</L>
<L>His swerd of stiel he ha&thorn; up pli&yogh;t,</L>
<L>&amp; smot so ano&thorn;er kni&yogh;t</L>
<L>&THORN;at asailed &thorn;e douke Segin,</L>
<L>&THORN;at heued sone binam him,</L>
<L N="2405">&amp; se&thorn;&thorn;e he sett him his stede opon,</L>
<L>&amp; fast hii asailed her fon;</L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L>
<PB REF="00000146.tif" N="142">. . . . . </L>
<L>&THORN;ennes nil hii neuer gon</L>
<L N="2410">Er hii han slawe mani on.<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="2280"></L>
<L>&para; 'Sir douk,' seyd Gyoun,</L>
<L>'Vnderstond to mi resoun:</L>
<L>To &thorn;e cite o&yogh;ain we wil go,</L>
<L>Ful wele we may it now do;</L>
<L N="2415">A &thorn;ousand &thorn;er be&thorn; of armed kni&yogh;tes</L>
<L>&THORN;at sone wi&thorn; ous wil holde fi&yogh;tes;</L>
<L>&amp; we here lenger duelle</L>
<L>For foles we schullen ous telle.'</L>
<L>Into her cite &thorn;ai ben y-gon,</L>
<L N="2420">Togider &thorn;ai asembled hem ichon,</L>
<L>&amp; at &thorn;e alours &thorn;ai<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>i</I> on an erasure.</NOTE> defended hem,</L>
<L>&amp; abiden bataile of her fomen.</L>
<L>&para; When &thorn;emperour y-herd &thorn;is,<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="2293"></L>
<L>&THORN;at his sone y-nomen is,</L>
<L N="2425">Wi&thorn; loude steuen &thorn;an hete he</L>
<L>His folk asayl &thorn;at cite</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; schot of bowe and alblast,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; swerdes, speres schete &amp; cast,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; laddren steye, &thorn;at cou&thorn;e best.</L>
<L N="2430">&THORN;e cite to asail haue &thorn;ai no rest,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; stones &amp; mangunels fast to cast:</L>
<L>&THORN;e fair walles al to-dast.<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. <I>alto dast.</I></NOTE></L>
<L>&amp; hii wi&thorn;-in fended hem wele apli&yogh;t,<MILESTONE N="120a:b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&amp; hii wi&thorn;-outen &yogh;eld hem gret fi&yogh;t;</L>
<L N="2435">&THORN;e Almayns &thorn;at ilke day &thorn;ere</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; gret sorwe y-slawe were.</L>
<L>Strongliche &thorn;ai asail &thorn;e cite,</L>
<L>Ac &thorn;at day no&thorn;ing no speden he;</L>
<L>At euen &thorn;at wi&thorn;-drou&yogh; hem o&yogh;an.</L>
<L N="2440">&THORN;emperour was &thorn;er-fore a sori<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. <I>asori</I></NOTE> man,<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="2311"></L>
<L>&THORN;at he no mi&yogh;t<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>nomight</I> MS., not <I>nought.</I></NOTE> of &thorn;at cite spede,</L>
<L>No awreken him for no nede.</L>
<L>&THORN;e cite ich day what ni&yogh;t</L>
<L>&THORN;ai asailed wi&thorn; gret mi&yogh;t;
<PB REF="00000148.tif" N="144"></L>
<L N="2445">Ac &thorn;e douk, Gij, and Herhaud,</L>
<L>Oft hem make&thorn; mani asaut,</L>
<L>&amp; miche of his folk &thorn;an slou&yogh; hii,</L>
<L>Wharfore he was in hert sori.</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="section">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Lordinges, listene&thorn; to me now!</L>
<L N="2450">Of a tresoun ichil telle &yogh;ou:</L>
<L>It was opon a somers day,</L>
<L>&THORN;emperour hadde eten, so&thorn; to say;</L>
<L>His huntes he of-sent &thorn;o,<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>&thorn;o</I> altered from <I>so</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>&amp; seyd he wald on hunting go</L>
<L N="2455">Into &thorn;e forest erlike,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;e douk Segyn nou&yogh;t no wite,</L>
<L>No his kni&yogh;tes neuer &thorn;e mo.</L>
<L>&THORN;at him herd a spie &thorn;o,</L>
<L>&THORN;at out of &thorn;at ost dede him fast,</L>
<L N="2460">To &thorn;e douke Segyn he com an hast.<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="2336"></L>
<L>&para; &THORN;e douke Segyn oxed him snelle</L>
<L>What newe tidinges he cou&thorn;e telle:</L>
<L>'Sir,' quod [he<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>he</I> omitted in MS.</NOTE>], 'herken to me:</L>
<L>Gode tidinges y telle &thorn;e,</L>
<L N="2465">&THORN;at &thorn;emperour, sikerliche,</L>
<L>Wille huntte to morwe arliche</L>
<L>In his forest priueliche</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; litel folk &amp; nou&yogh;t wi&thorn; miche,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; also litel als he may.</L>
<L N="2470">Y no gabbe nou&yogh;t, for so&thorn;e to say.'</L>
<L>&THORN;an he hade seyde &thorn;us to Segyn,</L>
<L>'Bi Seyn Richer! leue frende mine,'</L>
<L>Seyd &thorn;e douke, 'and it so be,</L>
<L>An hundred bessauns &yogh;if y &thorn;e.'</L>
<L N="2475">&THORN;e spie seyd, 'so&thorn;e y sigge:</L>
<L>My bodi &thorn;erfore in ostage y legge.'</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;an ha&thorn; &thorn;e douk y-cleped Gij,<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="2355"></L>
<L>&amp; Herhaud of Arderne sikerlij,<MILESTONE N="120b:a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Dan Belin, &amp; dan Gauter,</L>
<L N="2480">&amp; &thorn;e &thorn;ridde dan Holdimer,
<PB REF="00000150.tif" N="146"></L>
<L>&amp; Joceran &thorn;at was of Speyne</L>
<L>(Was non wiser in-to Almayne</L>
<L>A gode conseyl for to &yogh;iue;</L>
<L>&THORN;er-fore he was michel to leue).</L>
<L N="2485">'Lordinges,' he seyd, 'what rede &yogh;e,<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="2361"></L>
<L>Se&thorn;&thorn;e &thorn;at &yogh;e be sworn to me<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. <I>tome</I></NOTE>?</L>
<L>What is ous best for to done</L>
<L>Of our king Reyner? telle me sone.'</L>
<L>Gij to him answerd snelle,</L>
<L N="2490">'&THORN;e best rede ichil &thorn;e telle:</L>
<L>Kni&yogh;tes we schul han a &thorn;ousinde,</L>
<L>&amp; bi &thorn;e morwe, &yogh;if we him finde,</L>
<L>Ichil him bidde wi&thorn; hert fre</L>
<L>&THORN;at he wil acord wi&thorn; &thorn;e,</L>
<L N="2495">&amp; &thorn;at he cum wi&thorn; &thorn;e at ete;</L>
<L>&amp; &yogh;if he sey&thorn; ou&yogh;t wi&thorn; hete,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he it wil graunt for no &thorn;ing,</L>
<L>Hider we schul bring &thorn;e king.</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;ou schalt here bileue now,</L>
<L N="2500">Opon &thorn;i lord go no schaltow;</L>
<L>&THORN;i palays &thorn;ou schalt gray&thorn;i,</L>
<L>&amp; riche metes di&yogh;t redi.'</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="section">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;e douk answerd anon ri&yogh;t:</L>
<L>'So help me god, ful of mi&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="2505">Also &thorn;ou wilt, &thorn;ou schalt do.'</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; &thorn;at is Gij &thorn;ennes y-go;</L>
<L>In-to &thorn;e way he dede him anon</L>
<L>&THORN;er &thorn;emperour schuld for&thorn; gon.<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="2400"></L>
<L>&THORN;emperour bi &thorn;e morwe aros,</L>
<L N="2510">Into his forest he ride&thorn; &amp; gos:</L>
<L>A gret bore &thorn;ai founden, y-wis,</L>
<L>&amp; hij vncopled her houndis;</L>
<L>Her hornes &thorn;ai blewe loude &amp; stille,<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>schrille?</I></NOTE></L>
<L>Her houndes vrn wi&thorn; gode wille.</L>
<L N="2515">&para; &THORN;emperour biheld sone wi&thorn; &thorn;an</L>
<L>Unto a diche<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. <I>adiche</I></NOTE> &thorn;at water in ran;
<PB REF="00000152.tif" N="148"></L>
<L>He seyd, 'y-treyst we ben here:</L>
<L>Sir Tirri, mi frende dere,</L>
<L>No sestow hou<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. <I>&yogh;ou</I></NOTE> &thorn;at &yogh;onder ride</L>
<L N="2520">Kni&yogh;tes? &thorn;ai ben of gret pride.</L>
<L>On ich halue bisett we be&thorn;,<MILESTONE N="120b:b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Nis her nou&yogh;t bot &thorn;e de&thorn;.</L>
<L>Felawes &thorn;ai be &thorn;e douke Segyn,</L>
<L>Whom &thorn;at god &yogh;if iuel fin!</L>
<L N="2525">Gij of Warwike &thorn;er y sey,</L>
<L>Y-armed on his stede an hey.'</L>
<L>'Sir emperour,' quod Tirri anon,</L>
<L>'For &thorn;e rode loue &thorn;at god was on don,</L>
<L>Ich &thorn;e bidde, hennes go now,</L>
<L N="2530">For godes loue no lenge bileue &thorn;ou!</L>
<L>&amp; ichil here bileuen ay,</L>
<L>&amp; &yogh;if ich Gij mete may,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; meschaunce y schal him gret,<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="2436"></L>
<L>&amp; al his feren &thorn;at y mete.</L>
<L N="2535">Ar ich be ded or nomen be</L>
<L>&THORN;ou schalt passe al &thorn;is cuntre.'</L>
<L>&THORN;emperour seyd, 'for so&thorn;e, y nille:</L>
<L>Here ichil wi&thorn;<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>w</I> in <I>wi&thorn;</I> altered from <I>&yogh;.</I></NOTE> &yogh;ou duelle.'</L>
<L>Hastiliche &thorn;ai armed hem anon,</L>
<L N="2540">&amp; lepe her gode stedes opon.</L>
<L>&para; Wi&thorn; &thorn;at come Gij prikeinde,</L>
<L>&amp; a smal tvige in his hond bereinde</L>
<L>Of oliue, in token of pais:</L>
<L>To &thorn;emperour he grad as curteys,</L>
<L N="2545">&amp; seyd, 'god, &thorn;at alle &thorn;ing may se,</L>
<L>Sir emperour, so loke &thorn;e<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="2452"></L>
<L>&THORN;iselue, &amp; al &thorn;i meyne,</L>
<L>&THORN;at in place wi&thorn; &thorn;e be!</L>
<L>&THORN;e douke Segyn &thorn;e sent bi me</L>
<L N="2550">&THORN;at trew&thorn;e &amp; loue he wil to &thorn;e,</L>
<L>&amp; bidde&thorn; &thorn;e als his lord dere,</L>
<L>&THORN;eselue, &amp; alle &thorn;ine fere,
<PB REF="00000154.tif" N="150"></L>
<L>&THORN;at wi&thorn; &thorn;e ben togider here,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &yogh;e come to him to &thorn;e dinere;</L>
<L N="2555">And his gode cite he wil &thorn;e &yogh;elde</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; al his castels he ha&thorn; in welde;</L>
<L>&amp; &yogh;if he haue don o&yogh;ain skille,</L>
<L>He wille amende it to &thorn;i wille.'</L>
<L>&para; When &thorn;emperour herd him speke so,</L>
<L N="2560">&amp; so gret loue bede him to,</L>
<L>&THORN;e king of Hongrie<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>o</I> in <I>Hongrie</I> altered from <I>u.</I></NOTE> he cleped &thorn;o,</L>
<L>And sir Tirri he dede also:</L>
<L>'Lordinges,' he seyd, 'what schal we do?</L>
<L>Rede &yogh;e &thorn;at we &thorn;ider go?'<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="2472"></L>
