<L>. . . . . </L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L>'Sir emperour, wat hastow do?<MILESTONE N="121a:a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Is &thorn;e acord made bitven &yogh;ou to?<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="2633"></L>
<L>Astow &thorn;e douke Segyn y-kist,</L>
<L N="2720">&THORN;e strong traitour &amp; vnwrest?</L>
<L>&amp; ha&thorn; for-&yogh;if al in loue</L>
<L>Sadok de&thorn;, &thorn;i suster sone?</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;e wil dred, say me on;</L>
<L>&THORN;e misdo &thorn;ai willen ichon;</L>
<L N="2725">When her wret&thorn;e and her gilt</L>
<L>So li&yogh;tliche for-&yogh;if &thorn;ou wilt,</L>
<L>Hennes forward wil &thorn;e dred non,</L>
<L>Schame anou&yogh; &thorn;ai wil &thorn;e don;</L>
<L>&amp; &yogh;if &thorn;ou haddest &thorn;e douk anhong,</L>
<L N="2730">In &thorn;i lond men wold<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. <I>wil</I></NOTE> &thorn;e dred strong,</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;an after-ward &thorn;e treytour Gij,</L>
<L>&THORN;at neuer dede ous bot vilayni.
<PB REF="00000164.tif" N="160"></L>
<L>Ac now &thorn;ai wor&thorn; wi&thorn; &thorn;e priue,</L>
<L>&amp; better &thorn;an alle we.</L>
<L N="2735">&amp; topen al &thorn;is, &yogh;if Gij wer ded,</L>
<L>We mi&yogh;ten haue &thorn;e lesse dred.'</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="section">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>When Gij herd Otus speke so,<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="2645"></L>
<L>Als a wilde bore he lepe him to:</L>
<L>'Otus!' qua&thorn; Gij, '&thorn;ou schalt daye,</L>
<L N="2740">When &thorn;ou of tresoun clepes ous baye,</L>
<L>Bo&thorn;e Segyn &amp; eke me:</L>
<L>&THORN;ou it schal abie, bi mi leute!'</L>
<L>Him he smot wi&thorn; his fest</L>
<L>Amide the te&thorn;, ri&yogh;t al in<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>al in</I> on an erasure.</NOTE> ernest.</L>
<L N="2745">Ac &thorn;e barouns bitvene hem go&thorn;,</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;emperour swore his o&thorn;,</L>
<L>&YOGH;if ani &thorn;er were so hardy</L>
<L>&THORN;at dede o&thorn;er schame o&thorn;er vilanie,</L>
<L>Bren men him scholde, o&thorn;er to-hewe,<NOTE PLACE="marg">a letter erased before <I>hewe.</I></NOTE></L>
<L N="2750">O&thorn;er al to-hewe<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>to-drawe</I>?</NOTE> at wordes fewe.</L>
<L>&THORN;an do&thorn; &thorn;ai crie &thorn;urch &thorn;e cuntraye,</L>
<L>&THORN;at of &thorn;o wordes no man schuld saye;</L>
<L>'&amp; &yogh;if &thorn;er do&thorn;, wi&thorn;-outen no,</L>
<L>Hond o&thorn;er fot he schal for-go.'</L>
<L N="2755">&para; Than seyd &thorn;emperour on &thorn;is maner<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="2675"></L>
<L>To &thorn;e douke Segyn oforn hem &thorn;er:</L>
<L>'Sir douke, ichil loue &thorn;e:</L>
<L>Wiif &thorn;ou schalt haue bi me.</L>
<L>A feir soster ich haue in mi bour</L>
<L N="2760">Ichil &thorn;e &yogh;if,' qua&thorn; &thorn;emperour:</L>
<L>'Erneborwe hat &thorn;at may.'<MILESTONE N="121a:b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Anon he hir spoused &thorn;at day.</L>
<L>&THORN;e bridale was holden wi&thorn; game, y pli&yogh;t.</L>
<L>Neuer &yogh;et nas non fairer in si&yogh;t.</L>
<L N="2765">He loued hir, &amp; wor&thorn;-schiped swi&thorn;e:</L>
<L>To his cite he ladde hir si&thorn;e,</L>
<L>He and Ernneborwe his leuedi</L>
<L>&THORN;er hii wold soiornij.<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. <I>soiormij</I></NOTE>
<PB REF="00000166.tif" N="162"></L>
<L>Anon after &thorn;e tende day</L>
<L N="2770">Of her soiourn, so&thorn;e to say,</L>
<L>&para; Gij is to &thorn;e douke y-go,<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="2685"></L>
<L>&amp; at him asked leue &thorn;o:</L>
<L>'Sir douk,' he seyd, 'gon ich-ille,</L>
<L>In &thorn;is cuntre bileue y nille.</L>
<L N="2775">In wer ich haue serued &thorn;e:</L>
<L>&YOGH;if &thorn;ou haue euer eft nede to me,</L>
<L>After me &thorn;ou sende sikerliche,</L>
<L>&amp; ich com to &thorn;e hastiliche.'</L>
<L>'Sir,' qua&thorn; &thorn;e douk, 'gramerci!</L>
<L N="2780">&YOGH;ete haue y nou&yogh;t serued &thorn;e, sir Gij.</L>
<L>Here, ich bid &thorn;e, bileue wi&thorn; me:</L>
<L>Half mine castels, &amp; half mi cite,</L>
<L>&THORN;e wor&thorn;schip of Lowayn haluen-del,</L>
<L>Ich it &thorn;e graunt, Gij, fair &amp; wel.'</L>
<L N="2785">Gij tok his leue; oway went he:</L>
<L>&THORN;e douke wepe sore, &amp; hadde pite.<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="2700"></L>
<L>&THORN;emperour &thorn;at was so fre,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; him Gij &thorn;an ladde he;</L>
<L>Castels him bede, &amp; cites,</L>
<L N="2790">Gret wor&thorn;schip, &amp; riche fes,</L>
<L>Ac he &thorn;erof nold afo,</L>
<L>For no&thorn;ing &thorn;at he mi&yogh;t do.</L>
<L>To Almayn went ben he,</L>
<L>To Espire &thorn;at riche cite.</L>
<L N="2795">&para; &THORN;emperour wor&thorn;schiped Gij &thorn;e fre;</L>
<L>A while wi&thorn; him bileft he.</L>
<L>To pleyn hem &thorn;ai went bi riuer</L>
<L>&THORN;at of wilde foule ful were;</L>
<L>To her wille an hunting hij gos,</L>
<L N="2800">To chace &thorn;e hert &amp; &thorn;e ros.</L>
<L>On a day as he cam fram hunting</L>
<L>A dromond he seye ariueing.</L>
<L>&THORN;ider-ward sir Gij is y-gon,</L>
<L>&amp; gret &thorn;e marchandes euerichon.
<PB REF="00000168.tif" N="164"></L>
<L N="2805">'Lordinges, whennes com &yogh;e,<MILESTONE N="121b:a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&THORN;at in &thorn;is riuer ariued be?</L>
<L>Bi &yogh;our semblant y se, y-wisse,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &yogh;e ledde gret richesse.'</L>
<L>Among hem alle &thorn;er spac on,</L>
<L N="2810">&THORN;at cou&thorn;e speke for hem euerichon:</L>
<L>'Fram Costentine &thorn;e noble y-comen we be:</L>
<L>Lond of peys &thorn;an seche we.</L>
<L>Marchandes we ben of &thorn;at lond,</L>
<L>&amp; out y-driuen wi&thorn; michel wrong:</L>
<L N="2815">Out of Coyne &thorn;e riche soudan,</L>
<L>So prout he is, &amp; of so gret boban,</L>
<L>&THORN;at wi&thorn; .xv. he&thorn;en kinges,</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;ritti emeraus, wi&thorn;-outen lesinges,</L>
<L>&para; In Costentyn &thorn;e noble emperour Ernis</L>
<L N="2820">&THORN;ai han strongliche bisett, y-wis.</L>
<L>Castel no cite nis him non bileued,</L>
<L>&THORN;at altogider &thorn;ai han to-dreued,</L>
<L>&amp; for-brant, &amp; strued, y-wis.</L>
<L>Into Costentyn flowen he is;</L>
<L N="2825">&THORN;er he wer&thorn; him o&yogh;aines his fon,</L>
<L>&THORN;at seche&thorn; on him for to slon.</L>
<L>&THORN;ritti mile men may riden &amp; gon,</L>
<L>Ne schal men finde man non;</L>
<L>&amp; we ben aschaped vnne&thorn;e,</L>
<L N="2830">&THORN;at we no were to-hewen to de&thorn;e.</L>
<L>Y-comen we ben into &thorn;is cuntre:</L>
<L>Fowe &amp; griis anou&yogh; lade we,</L>
<L>Gold and siluer, &amp; riche stones,</L>
<L>&THORN;at vertu bere mani for &thorn;e nones,</L>
<L N="2835">Gode clo&thorn;es of sikelatoun &amp; Alisaundrinis,</L>
<L>Peloure of Matre, &amp; pu[r]per &amp; biis,</L>
<L>To &yogh;our wille as &yogh;e may se;</L>
<L>Swiche be &thorn;e tidinges of &thorn;at cuntre.'</L>
<L>Gij answerd, 'mi frende fre,</L>
<L N="2840">For &yogh;our tidinges blisced &yogh;e be!
<PB REF="00000170.tif" N="166"></L>
<L>God, for his name seuene,</L>
<L>He bring &yogh;ou to gode heuene!'</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="section">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>When &thorn;e marchaundes hadde seyd as y say,</L>
<L>Gij bitau&yogh;t hem god &amp; gode day.<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>a</I> altered from <I>e</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L N="2845">Vnto his in he is y-go,</L>
<L>And Herhaud he cleped anon him to.</L>
<L>'Herhaud, mi frende, wille we gon?</L>
<L>At &thorn;emperour take we leue anon.</L>
<L>Into Costentyn-noble ichil go<MILESTONE N="121b:b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="2850">To help &thorn;emperour of his wo:</L>
<L>&THORN;at wi&thorn; &thorn;e soudan biseged is he,</L>
<L>So sigge&thorn; men of &thorn;at cuntre;</L>
<L>&THORN;at lond destrud &amp; men aqueld,</L>
<L>&amp; cristendom &thorn;ai han michel afeld.'</L>
<L N="2855">Herhaud answerd, 'y graunt it be:</L>
<L>Miche wor&thorn;schipe it wor&thorn; to &thorn;e.'</L>
<L>At &thorn;emperour &thorn;ai toke leue to go,</L>
<L>&amp; he hem graunted vnne&thorn;e &thorn;o;</L>
<L>Anou&yogh; he bede&thorn; hem castels &amp; tours,</L>
<L N="2860">Riche cites, halles, &amp; bours.</L>
<L>Sir Gij toke an hundred of his kni&yogh;tes,</L>
<L>Strongest and best in fi&yogh;tes,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he mi&yogh;t in Almayne finde,</L>
<L>Mest y-preised &amp; best doinde.</L>
<L N="2865">Now &thorn;ai ben to schippe y-went:</L>
<L>Gode winde god ha&thorn; hem lent.</L>
<L>To Costentyn-noble &thorn;ai ben y-come,</L>
<L>&amp; in &thorn;e cite her in y-nome.</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="section">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ac when &thorn;emperour wist atte frome</L>
<L N="2870">&THORN;at Gij of Warwike was y-come,</L>
<L>Tvay erls he dede after him go,</L>
<L>&amp; loueliche he bad hem com him to.</L>
<L>&amp; sir Gij him go&thorn; to &thorn;emperour fre:</L>
<L>'Welcome, sir Gij,' &thorn;an seyd he.</L>
<L N="2875">'Of &thorn;ine help gret nede haue we.</L>
<L>Michel ich haue herd speke of &thorn;e.
<PB REF="00000172.tif" N="168"></L>
<L>Mine men ben sleyn in &thorn;is tide,</L>
<L>&amp; mi lond destrud in ich a side:<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. <I>aside</I></NOTE></L>
<L>Al bot &thorn;is ich selue cite</L>
<L N="2880">Destrud &amp; brent hauen he.</L>
<L>Fourti &thorn;ousand &thorn;ai<NOTE PLACE="marg">originally <I>&thorn;ai &thorn;ai</I>, but the second <I>&thorn;ai</I> crossed out.</NOTE> slowe on a day</L>
<L>Of mine men, as ich &yogh;ou telle may.</L>
<L>Mine men &thorn;ai slowe, mi sone also,</L>
<L>Wharfore, leue frende, y bede &thorn;e to,</L>
<L N="2885">&YOGH;if &thorn;ou mi&yogh;t me of hem wreke,</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;e felouns out of mi lond do reke,</L>
<L>Mine feyr<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. <I>feyir</I> with the <I>i</I> underdotted.</NOTE> douhter &thorn;ou schalt habbe,</L>
<L>&amp; half mi lond, wi&thorn;-outen gabbe.'<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="2800"></L>
<L>&THORN;an answerd anon sir Gij,</L>
<L N="2890">'Sir,' he seyd, 'gramercij!</L>
<L>&amp; y &thorn;e sigge, bi mi leute,</L>
<L>&THORN;at treweliche ichil serue &thorn;e</L>
<L>Al &thorn;e while &thorn;at ich wi&thorn; &thorn;e be:<MILESTONE N="122a:a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&THORN;erof, sir, &thorn;ou mi&yogh;t leue me.'</L>
<L N="2895">At &thorn;emperour he toke leue anon,</L>
<L>Vnto his in he gan to gon.</L>
<L>Noyse &amp; cri he herd in &thorn;at cite:</L>
<L>He gan oxy what it mi&yogh;t be.</L>
<L>He hem oxed what it were,</L>
<L N="2900">&amp; what was al &thorn;at noise &thorn;ere.</L>
<L>So mani kni&yogh;tes he seye to armes go,</L>
<L>So mani seriaunce steye to kernels &thorn;o.</L>
<L>'Sir,' qua&thorn; a burieys, 'bi seyn Martin,</L>
<L>It be&thorn; &thorn;e li&thorn;er Sarrazin:</L>
<L N="2905">It is &thorn;e amiral Costdram,</L>
<L>&THORN;e nevou of &thorn;e riche soudan.</L>
<L>So strong he is, &amp; of so gret mi&yogh;t,</L>
<L>In world y wene no better kni&yogh;t;</L>
<L>For &thorn;er nis man no kni&yogh;t non</L>
<L N="2910">&THORN;at wi&thorn; wret&thorn;e dar loken him on.</L>
<L>His armes alle avenimed be&thorn;:<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="2824"></L>
<L>&THORN;at venim is strong so &thorn;e de&thorn;:
<PB REF="00000174.tif" N="170"></L>
<L>In &thorn;is world nis<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. <I>is</I></NOTE> man &thorn;at he take mi&yogh;t</L>
<L>&THORN;at he ne<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. omits <I>ne</I></NOTE> schuld dye anon ri&yogh;t.</L>
<L N="2915">&THORN;at o&thorn;er day he dede ous sorwe anou&yogh;</L>
<L>Of &thorn;emperour sone &thorn;at he slou&yogh;,</L>
<L>&THORN;at was<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>was</I> at end of line in MS.</NOTE> so gode and stalwor&thorn; kni&yogh;t,</L>
<L>&THORN;at opon hem had &yogh;euen mani fi&yogh;t.</L>
<L>In &thorn;is cite so gode kni&yogh;t was non,</L>
<L N="2920">&THORN;at with wret&thorn;e durst loke him on.</L>
<L>Comen he is wi&thorn; grete cheualrie,<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>cleualrie</I> MS.</NOTE></L>
<L>&amp; wi&thorn; him &thorn;e riche king of Turkye</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; an hundred Turkes strong:</L>
<L>Be&thorn; non better in non lond.'</L>
<L N="2925">&para; &amp; when sir Gij herd &thorn;is</L>
<L>&THORN;at his ost seyd to him, y-wis,</L>
<L>To his felawes he seyd anon,</L>
<L>'To armes,' he seyd, 'euerichon!<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="2836"></L>
<L>&THORN;e Sarrazins we willen agast.</L>
<L N="2930">For godes loue, smite&thorn; on fast!'</L>
<L>Hastiliche y-armed hij be&thorn;,</L>
<L>Opon her stedes as foule &thorn;ai fle&thorn;.</L>
<L>For&thorn; &thorn;ai went &amp; on hem smite</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; her swerdes &thorn;at wil wel bite.</L>
<L N="2935">Gij to &thorn;e amiral smot so,</L>
<L>Scheld no hauberk nas him wor&thorn; a slo:</L>
<L>&THORN;urch &thorn;e body he &yogh;af him wounde,<MILESTONE N="122a:b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&amp; dede he feld him on &thorn;e grounde.</L>
<L>Sir Gij his gode swerd out drou&yogh;,</L>
<L N="2940">&THORN;at heued fram &thorn;e bodi he slou&yogh;.</L>
<L>To &thorn;emperour he it ha&thorn; y-sent,</L>
<L>&THORN;at wel glad was of &thorn;at present.</L>
<L>&para; Herhaud smot &thorn;e king of Turkie</L>
<L>(Was non feller into<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>nto</I> MS.</NOTE> Surrie):</L>
<L N="2945">&THORN;urch &thorn;e bodi he him smot,</L>
<L>Ded he feld him doun fot hot.</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; &thorn;at com Tebaud prikeinde,</L>
<L>In Fraunce y-bore, a kni&yogh;t wel kinde:
<PB REF="00000176.tif" N="172"></L>
<L>Wi&thorn; swiche streng&thorn;e he smot Helmadan,</L>
<L N="2950">Al was nou&yogh;t wor&thorn; he hadde opan.</L>
<L>&THORN;urch his bodi &thorn;e launce glod;</L>
<L>Ded he fel wi&thorn;-outen a-bod.</L>
<L>Gauter come prikeing anon ri&yogh;t,</L>
<L>Of Almayne a wel gode kni&yogh;t.</L>
<L N="2955">Heteliche he smot Redmadan</L>
<L>(&YOGH;e no haue herd speke of no swiche man):<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="2856"></L>
<L>&THORN;e bodi atvo he ha&thorn; to-deled,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he fel doun in &thorn;e feld.</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; &thorn;at come sir Morgadour,</L>
<L N="2960">&THORN;at was steward wi&thorn; &thorn;emperour.</L>
<L>Kni&yogh;t he was gode &amp; hardi,</L>
<L>Ac traitour he was, ful of envie.</L>
<L>He smot vnto a Sarrazin,</L>
<L>No halp him nou&yogh;t his Apolin.</L>
<L N="2965">Now &thorn;ai smitte togider comonliche,</L>
<L>&amp; fi&yogh;t &thorn;ai agin ardiliche.</L>
<L>&THORN;er men mi&yogh;t se Gij smite,</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;e Sarrazins heuedes of strike,</L>
<L>&amp; wi&thorn; him Herhaud also:</L>
<L N="2970">Bo&thorn;e &thorn;ai streng&thorn;ed hem wele to do.</L>
<L>&THORN;e Sarrazins &thorn;ai streng&thorn;ed hem for to sle,</L>
<L>To-hewen, &amp; iuel to bise.</L>
<L>&THORN;e Sarrazins hem &yogh;eld gret fi&yogh;t,</L>
<L>For strong &thorn;ai ben, &amp; of gret mi&yogh;t.</L>
<L N="2975">Wi&thorn; &thorn;at come Esclandar prikeinde,</L>
<L>A Sarrazin &amp; of foule kinde,</L>
<L>&THORN;e kinges sone of Birrie,</L>
<L>Strong he was for &thorn;e maistrie.</L>
<L>Dan Tebaud he felled &thorn;o,</L>
<L N="2980">&THORN;urch &thorn;e bodi he dede &thorn;e launce go;</L>
<L>&amp; se&thorn;&thorn;e he slou&yogh; a Freyns kni&yogh;t,<MILESTONE N="122b:a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>In Bleyues he was born ari&yogh;t.</L>
<L>Romiraunt com for&thorn; snelle,</L>
<L>A Sarrazin a strong wi&thorn; elle,
<PB REF="00000178.tif" N="174"></L>
<L N="2985">Y-slawe he ha&thorn; dan Guinman,</L>
<L>A strong kni&yogh;t he was &amp; an Aleman.</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; &thorn;at come for&thorn; an amireld,</L>
<L>A Sarrazin of wicked erd,</L>
<L>Dan Gauter he ha&thorn; y-slawe,</L>
<L N="2990">&amp; gode Gilmin his felawe.</L>
<L>When Herhaud &thorn;at of-seye &thorn;o,</L>
<L>In his hert him was ful wo;</L>
<L>An amiral he smot so,</L>
<L>Ded he feld him an hast<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. <I>anhast</I></NOTE> &thorn;o,</L>
<L N="2995">&amp; mani ano&thorn;er he ha&thorn; aqueld,</L>
<L>&amp; adoun feld in &thorn;e feld.</L>
<L>Sone so Esclandar y-seye &thorn;is,</L>
<L>To awreke &thorn;e amiral lef him is.</L>
<L>To Herhaud he smot heteliche,</L>
<L N="3000">&amp; he him mett hardiliche;</L>
<L>Heteliche &thorn;ai smiten togider &thorn;o,</L>
<L>&THORN;at of her hors &thorn;ai fellen bo.</L>
<L>Se&thorn;&thorn;en &thorn;ai drou&yogh; her brondes of stiel,</L>
<L>&amp; smiten togider hard &amp; wel,</L>
<L N="3005">To-hewe hauberk &amp; scheldes also,</L>
<L>Gode bodis &thorn;ai ben bo&thorn;e to.</L>
<L>Of her helmes &thorn;e flours gan fle,</L>
<L>So heteliche togider smiten he.</L>
<L>Herhaud go&thorn; him driueand fast,</L>
<L N="3010">His heued to smiten of on hast.<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="2900"></L>
<L>Ac so gret socour him com &thorn;er,</L>
<L>An hundred Turkes &amp; her pouer;</L>
<L>Herhaud &thorn;ai gin alle asaile,</L>
<L>&amp; neye hadde slain him in &thorn;at bataile,</L>
<L N="3015">No hadde Gij<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>Gij</I> added over the line.</NOTE> &thorn;at y-seye, &thorn;at was sorij;</L>
<L>Hastiliche he com him to socourey.</L>
<L>His gode brond &thorn;an drou&yogh; he,</L>
<L>&THORN;e heued of a Sarrazin he dede of fle,</L>
<L>&amp; ano&thorn;er he dede also;</L>
<L N="3020">&THORN;e &thorn;ridde to de&thorn; he dede do.
<PB REF="00000180.tif" N="176"></L>
<L>Herhaud he socourd in &thorn;at nede,</L>
<L>&amp; dede him lepe opon his stede.</L>
<L>&THORN;e Sarrazins anon gun &thorn;ai mete,</L>
<L>Mani on &thorn;er her liif &thorn;ai lete,</L>
<L N="3025">Mani on &thorn;er dyed in ai&thorn;er<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. <I>inai&THORN;er</I></NOTE> side,<MILESTONE N="122b:b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Ac &thorn;e Sarrazins wers gan bi-tide.</L>
<L>Sir Gij &amp; alle his feren,</L>
<L>&THORN;e Griffouns &thorn;at gode weren,</L>
<L>Han ouer-comen &amp; aqueld;</L>
<L N="3030">To-hewen &thorn;ai leyen in the feld.</L>
<L>Toward her ost &thorn;ai ben fleinge,</L>
<L>&amp; Gij hem after fast folweinge;</L>
<L>Ar hij &thorn;e doun were ouer gon,</L>
<L>Y-slawe hij ben &amp; to-hewen ichon.</L>
<L N="3035">Esclandar is oway fleinde,</L>
<L>Ouer &thorn;e dounes fast erninde,</L>
<L>&amp; al to-broken<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. <I>alto broken</I></NOTE> his scheld is,</L>
<L>His helme al to-dassched<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. <I>alto dassched</I></NOTE>, y-wis.<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="2926"></L>
<L>Gij it of-&thorn;ou&yogh;t when he it seye,</L>
<L N="3040">&THORN;at he so li&yogh;teliche oway fleye:</L>
<L>'Esclandar,' seyd Gij, 'wende o&yogh;ain to me,</L>
<L>&amp; forso&thorn;e al siker &thorn;ou be;</L>
<L>Drede &thorn;e of no no&thorn;er &thorn;an of me,</L>
<L>Ones to iusti ich oxi of &thorn;e.'</L>
<L N="3045">Esclandar seyd, 'artow Gij?</L>
<L>Ich &thorn;e defende sikerly.</L>
<L>Bi Mahoun &thorn;at ich leue opon,</L>
<L>Neuer no schal ich oway gon,</L>
<L>No neuer schal y bli&thorn;e be,</L>
<L N="3050">Til ich &thorn;at heued binim &thorn;e;</L>
<L>Bihoten ich it haue a maiden of pris,</L>
<L>&THORN;e soudans douhter &thorn;at wel fair is.'</L>
<L>Her steden &thorn;ai turned snelle,<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="2943"></L>
<L>&amp; to-gider &thorn;ai smiten wi&thorn; gode wille;</L>
<L N="3055">Esclandar first smot Gij</L>
<L>&THORN;urch &thorn;e scheld as kni&yogh;t hardi;
<PB REF="00000182.tif" N="178"></L>
<L>Gij smot him anon ri&yogh;t,</L>
<L>Scheld no hauberk halp him no wi&yogh;t;</L>
<L>He smot him &thorn;urch at &thorn;at chaunce</L>
<L N="3060">&THORN;urch &thorn;e bodi wi&thorn; his launce.</L>
<L>Esclandar fleye for&thorn; a wel gode pas,</L>
<L>Sir Gij of-toke him nou&yogh;t, &thorn;erfor wo him was;</L>
<L>To his felawes he is y-go,</L>
<L>Ri&yogh;t to &thorn;e cite he &yogh;ede him &thorn;o.</L>
<L N="3065">&THORN;e Sarrazins were ouer-come,</L>
<L>&THORN;erfore &thorn;ai were bli&thorn;e, all and some.</L>
<L>&THORN;emperour of-sent Gij him to,</L>
<L>&amp; miche honour he ha&thorn; him do.</L>
<L>'Gij,' qua&thorn; he, '&thorn;ou art me dere,<MILESTONE N="123a:a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="3070">&THORN;ou schalt bileue wi&thorn; me here:</L>
<L>Mi feir douhter, &thorn;at is of pris,</L>
<L>Ichil &thorn;e &yogh;iue to spouse y-wis;</L>
<L>&THORN;ou schalt ben emperour after me,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou art a kni&yogh;t of gret bounte.</L>
<L N="3075">Al &thorn;o &thorn;at ben to me serueinde,</L>
<L>Ichil &thorn;ai be to &thorn;e boweinde.'</L>
<L>'Gramerci,' seyd sir Gij anon;</L>
<L>'A fair &yogh;ift is &thorn;is now on.'</L>
<L>&THORN;e steward come for&thorn; bliue,</L>
<L N="3080">More treytour nas non oliue;</L>
<L>His name was hoten Morgadour,</L>
<L>God &yogh;if him euel auentour!</L>
<L>Toward Gij he bar gret<NOTE PLACE="marg">a dot over the <I>t</I> in <I>gret</I>.</NOTE> ond,</L>
<L>&amp; se&thorn;&thorn;e he died &thorn;urch his hond.</L>
<L N="3085">Qua&thorn; Morgadour, 'sir, &thorn;at wil wele be,</L>
<L>For Gij is curteys, gentil, &amp; fre;</L>
<L>When he schal &thorn;i douhter spousy,</L>
<L>Ri&yogh;t is &thorn;at we him onoury.'</L>
<L>Ac what so he seyd bifor Gij &thorn;o,</L>
<L N="3090">&YOGH;if he may, to de&thorn; he wille him do.<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="2972"></L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="section">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Esclandar went oway fleinde,</L>
<L>Toward her ost fast prikeinde;
<PB REF="00000184.tif" N="180"></L>
<L>&THORN;urch &thorn;e bodi he bar a trounsoun,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; bo&thorn;e honden he held him to &thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>e</I> in <I>&thorn;e</I> added over the line.</NOTE> arsoun.</L>
<L N="3095">Bo&thorn;e bifore &amp; eke bihinde,</L>
<L>&THORN;e blod gan out fast winde,</L>
<L>His helme in &thorn;e on half honginde,</L>
<L>&amp; his visage al bledeinde.</L>
<L>His scheld to held hadde he no mi&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="3100">He drad him to dye anon ri&yogh;t.</L>
<L>To &thorn;e soudans pauiloun he come,</L>
<L>&THORN;e soudan him bi-knewe anon:</L>
<L>'Esclandar, when comestow?' seyd he;</L>
<L>'In strong fi&yogh;t &thorn;ou hast y-be.</L>
<L N="3105">Were &thorn;ou alon at &thorn;e cite?</L>
<L>Say me who ha&thorn; &thorn;us wounded &thorn;e?'</L>
<L>'Sir,' qua&thorn; he, 'ichil &thorn;e telle</L>
<L>Of hard tidinges wel snelle:</L>
<L>Y-lorn &thorn;ou hast &thorn;e amiral Cosdram<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>s</I> on an erasure.</NOTE></L>
<L N="3110">&THORN;at leuest &thorn;e was of ani man,</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;e king of Turkie &thorn;ou hast forgon,</L>
<L>Of hem no tit &thorn;e neuer help non.</L>
<L>&amp; alle &thorn;e best men y-bore<MILESTONE N="123a:b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Bifor &thorn;e cite &thorn;ou hast forlore.'</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="section">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="3115">&THORN;an answerd &thorn;e riche soudan,</L>
<L>&THORN;at hadde no gamen of &thorn;an:</L>
<L>'Him is &thorn;an sum socour y-come,</L>
<L>Whar-&thorn;urch mi Turkes be me binome?'</L>
<L>'Sir,' qua&thorn;e Esclandar, 'y-wis,</L>
<L N="3120">An onwrast gome y-comen &thorn;er is;</L>
<L>Socour he ha&thorn; gret &amp; beld,<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="2300"></L>
<L>In &thorn;e warld nis swiche a scheld<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. <I>ascheld.</I></NOTE>;</L>
<L>Gij of Warwike his name it is,</L>
<L>Sterner &thorn;an ani lyoun, y-wis.</L>
<L N="3125">His strokes no may noman dreye,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he ne most dye on hye.</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; him he ha&thorn; an hundred kni&yogh;tes</L>
<L>Of Almayne, &thorn;e best in fi&yogh;tes;
<PB REF="00000186.tif" N="182"></L>
<L>&THORN;urch &thorn;e bodi &thorn;us me he smot,</L>
<L N="3130">Dede ich am, wele y wot.'</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;an swore a gret o&thorn; &thorn;e soudan</L>
<L>Bi Mahoun &thorn;at he leued opan,</L>
<L>&THORN;at neuer glad no wor&thorn; he</L>
<L>What he haue y-nome &thorn;at cite;</L>
<L N="3135">For asayle he it wille do</L>
<L>Ar &thorn;e &thorn;ridde day be ago.</L>
<L>Anon a spie it herd<NOTE PLACE="marg">So MS. for <I>herd</I> or <I>iherd</I>?</NOTE> &thorn;is,</L>
<L>&THORN;at to Gij it nold for-hele y-wis.</L>
<L>Sone he com to &thorn;e cite;</L>
<L N="3140">Al &thorn;is to Gij &thorn;an teld he,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;e soudan wi&thorn; his men elle</L>
<L>&THORN;e cite wil aseyle snelle.</L>
<L>Ac &thorn;emperour wist &thorn;er-of nou&yogh;t</L>
<L>&THORN;at so strong tiding &thorn;er were y-brou&yogh;t.</L>
<L N="3145">Ac when he wist &thorn;e so&thorn;e herof,</L>
<L>Ernist him &thorn;ou&yogh;t, &amp; no scof.<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="3020"></L>
<L>&para; &THORN;emperour made him bli&thorn;e &thorn;o</L>
<L>&THORN;at ouer-comen weren his fo,</L>
<L>&amp; Gij to &thorn;emperour is y-go,</L>
<L N="3150">&amp; swi&thorn;e feyr he gret him &thorn;o.</L>
<L>'Sir,' qua&thorn; he, 'be bli&thorn;e &amp; glad;</L>
<L>Gode tidinges me ha&thorn; ben seyd.'</L>
<L>&THORN;emperour of-sent his foules &thorn;o,</L>
<L>Oscuriis, faucouns, &amp; ierfaukes also;</L>
<L N="3155">Gon he wil to &thorn;e riuer,</L>
<L>Him to solas &amp; play &thorn;er.</L>
<L>Se&thorn;&thorn;e he of-sent of his Gregeys,<MILESTONE N="123b:a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&THORN;at gode weren &amp; curteys.</L>
<L>To &thorn;e riuer &thorn;ai ben y-gon</L>
<L N="3160">Wher foules were mani on.</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; &thorn;at come for&thorn; sir Morgadour,</L>
<L>&THORN;at steward was wi&thorn; &thorn;emperour,</L>
<L>&amp; seyd to Gij, 'mi frende dere,</L>
<L>Y &thorn;e loue in gode manere.'
<PB REF="00000188.tif" N="184"></L>
<L N="3165">Ac alle &thorn;at he seyd, Gij to bitraye,</L>
<L>&THORN;at was wele sen in his last daye.</L>
<L>Non no may so wele tresoun do</L>
<L>So may he &thorn;at his trust is to.</L>
<L>&YOGH;ete seyd to him Morgadour,</L>
<L N="3170">'Castels ich haue, &amp; mani feir tour,</L>
<L>Riche cites, &amp; ful strong,</L>
<L>To &thorn;ine wille &thorn;ou hem afong;</L>
<L>Michel y desire &thorn;i loue to haue.<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="3038"></L>
<L>Go we togider wi&thorn; game &amp; plawe:</L>
<L N="3175">Into &thorn;e chaumber go we baye,</L>
<L>Among &thorn;e maidens for to playe;</L>
<L>At tables to pleye, &amp; at ches;</L>
<L>Wele we may don it y-wis</L>
<L>Bifor &thorn;i leman Clarice so fre,</L>
<L N="3180">&THORN;emperours douhter bri&yogh;t of ble.</L>
<L>&amp; lete we &thorn;emperour to wode go,</L>
<L>To chace &thorn;e hert &amp; &thorn;e ro.'</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="section">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'Sir,' qua&thorn; Gij, 'wille we go?</L>
<L>When &thorn;ou it wilt, it schal be do.'</L>
<L N="3185">Into &thorn;e chaumber &thorn;ai &yogh;ede &thorn;o</L>
<L>Hond in hond y-fere bo.</L>
<L>To &thorn;e mayden &thorn;ai come wel sket,</L>
<L>&THORN;at curteysliche hem ha&thorn; y-gret.</L>
<L>'Sir Gij,' sche seyd, 'welcome &thorn;ou be!</L>
<L N="3190">Cum sitt &amp; pleye &thorn;e here wi&thorn; me.'</L>
<L>He toke &thorn;e maiden &amp; hir kiste:<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="3050"></L>
<L>&THORN;at of-&thorn;ou&yogh;t &thorn;e steward vnwreste.</L>
<L>He hir hadde loued mani a day,</L>
<L>&amp; wende haue spoused &thorn;at feir may.</L>
<L N="3195">&THORN;e cheker &thorn;ai oxy &amp; &thorn;e meyne;</L>
<L>Bifor &thorn;e maiden &thorn;an pleyen he.</L>
<L>Y-sett &thorn;ai han &thorn;e first game,</L>
<L>&THORN;e steward it les, bi godes name.</L>
<L>Se&thorn;&thorn;e &thorn;ai han ano&thorn;er y-gonne,</L>
<L N="3200">Anon it ha&thorn; Gij y-wonne,
<PB REF="00000190.tif" N="186"></L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;e &thorn;ridde ful hastiliche.<MILESTONE N="123b:b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&THORN;e steward was sori sikerliche;</L>
<L>Al mody he ros vp &thorn;o:</L>
<L>Wro&thorn; &amp; sori he was bo.</L>
<L N="3205">'Gij,' qua&thorn; he, 'bi-leue &thorn;ou here,</L>
<L>&THORN;iself &amp; Clarice, &thorn;i pleye-fere,</L>
<L>Al what ich come now son o&yogh;e.'</L>
<L>'Anon,' seyd Gij, 'it schal so be.'</L>
<L>Out him went Morgadour,</L>
<L N="3210">At his in he tok a chasour,</L>
<L>To &thorn;emperour he go&thorn; ri&yogh;t.</L>
<L>When &thorn;emperour hadde of him si&yogh;t,</L>
<L>O&yogh;aines him he is y-gon,</L>
<L>&amp; tidinges he oxed him anon.</L>
<L N="3215">'Now for&thorn;, sir steward,' he sede,<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="3066"></L>
<L>'Comestow for gode or for qued?</L>
<L>Whi comestow so prikiinge?</L>
<L>Tel it me wi&thorn;-outen lesinge.</L>
<L>&YOGH;if &thorn;ou of Sarrazins hast herd ou&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="3220">Tel it me; for-hele it nou&yogh;t.'</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="section">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'Sir,' qua&thorn; he, 'y schal &thorn;e telle:</L>
<L>&THORN;i schame forhele y nille.</L>
<L>An soudour &thorn;ou hast wi&thorn; &thorn;e,</L>
<L>&amp; wil &thorn;at &thorn;ou y-schent be.</L>
<L N="3225">&THORN;i douhter, &thorn;at so feir is,</L>
<L>Forlay he ha&thorn;, for-so&thorn;e y-wis.</L>
<L>Into hir bour wi&thorn; streng&thorn;e he &yogh;ede,</L>
<L>&amp; bi &thorn;i douhter his wille he dede.'</L>
<L>&YOGH;if &thorn;ou ne me leuest, hom &thorn;ou fare,</L>
<L N="3230">&YOGH;ete &thorn;ou schalt him finde &thorn;are.</L>
<L>&THORN;er &thorn;ou mi&yogh;t him finde, y-wis,</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;i douhter clippe &amp; kisse.<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="3080"></L>
<L>&THORN;erfore y com &thorn;e to say,</L>
<L>For &thorn;i schame forhele y no may.</L>
<L N="3235">&YOGH;if &thorn;ou him finde in &thorn;at stede,</L>
<L>Into &thorn;i prisoun &thorn;ou him lede,
<PB REF="00000192.tif" N="188"></L>
<L>&amp; in &thorn;i court &thorn;ou deme him do;</L>
<L>For treitour he is, y telle &thorn;e to:</L>
<L>&THORN;e more adouted &thorn;ou schalt be</L>
<L N="3240">Of alle &thorn;i regne, y telle &thorn;e.</L>
<L>&THORN;er-fore ne wonde &thorn;ou no-&thorn;ing</L>
<L>Nou&yogh;t for him no his helping;</L>
<L>After-ward &thorn;at he demed is,</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;i court of &thorn;at treytour deliuerd is,</L>
<L N="3245">Into Almayne ichil gon<MILESTONE N="124a:a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>To &thorn;emperour Reyner anon;</L>
<L>Socour fram him ichil bringe,</L>
<L>&amp; deliuer &thorn;i lond, wi&thorn;outen lesinge,</L>
<L>Of alle &thorn;ine dedeliche fon,</L>
<L N="3250">&THORN;at &thorn;ine men haue sleyn ichon.'</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="section">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'Who is &thorn;at?' &thorn;emperour sede.</L>
<L>'Gij of Warwike, so god me rede!</L>
<L>&THORN;ou do him nim, &amp; binde fast,</L>
<L>&amp; in &thorn;i prisoun &thorn;ou do him cast.'</L>
<L N="3255">Qua&thorn; &thorn;emperour, 'lat now be,</L>
<L>No speke nou&yogh;t so of him to me:</L>
<L>O&yogh;aines me misdo he nold</L>
<L>Nou&yogh;t for tventi somers of gold,</L>
<L>No for to ben al to-hewe:<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="3100"></L>
<L N="3260">So gode a kni&yogh;t he is &amp; trewe.</L>
<L>&amp; &yogh;if he is &thorn;er-in, wele be it so:</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; hir his wille he may do;</L>
<L>For mi douhter ichim bi-hote habbe,</L>
<L>Nil ich nou&yogh;t of couenant gabbe.'</L>
<L N="3265">&para; When &thorn;e steward him ha&thorn; bi-&thorn;ou&yogh;t</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;emperour nold here him nou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>Hom to his in he is y-go,</L>
<L>&amp; ali&yogh;t of his palfrey &thorn;o.</L>
<L>Anon in-to chaumber he &yogh;ede,</L>
<L N="3270">&amp; to Gij of Warwike he sede,</L>
<L>'Gij, &thorn;ou art ful wele wi&thorn; me,</L>
<L>&THORN;erfore ich-il ki&thorn;en it &thorn;e:
<PB REF="00000194.tif" N="190"></L>
<L>To &thorn;emperour y-teld it is,</L>
<L>Bi &thorn;e lord seyn Denis,</L>
<L N="3275">&THORN;at wi&thorn; streng&thorn;e &thorn;ou com in<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>in</I> added over the line.</NOTE>-to his bour</L>
<L>&amp; has forleyn his douhter wi&thorn; desonour.</L>
<L>&amp; &yogh;if he &thorn;e may ouer-go,</L>
<L>He wil &thorn;e bren o&thorn;er slo.</L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L N="3280">&amp; ich hot &thorn;e &thorn;at &thorn;ou hennes fle,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he nou&yogh;t of-take &thorn;e.'</L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L>'Bi god,' qua&thorn; Gij, '&thorn;at were wrong,<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="3129"></L>
<L>&THORN;at y schold here mi de&thorn; afong</L>
<L N="3285">For &thorn;ing &thorn;at ich haue gilt non,</L>
<L>No neuer &thorn;ou&yogh;t it to don.</L>
<L>An arnemorwe, when he out &yogh;ede,</L>
<L>Miche he me o loue bede;</L>
<L>Hou schuld ich euer siker be</L>
<L N="3290">Of ani bi-hest men hotes me?</L>
<L>For &thorn;emperour me seyd &thorn;o,<MILESTONE N="124a:b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And trewelich me bihete &thorn;erto,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he me wold gret wor&thorn;schipe,</L>
<L>&amp; now he me wil sle wi&thorn; schenschipe</L>
<L N="3295">For &thorn;e speche of a losanger,</L>
<L>&amp; of a feloun pautener.'</L>
<L>Out of &thorn;e chaumber he is y-go:</L>
<L>Sori &amp; dreri he was &thorn;o.</L>
<L>To his in he &yogh;ede swi&thorn;e,</L>
<L N="3300">And cleped his felawes bliue.</L>
<L>'Lordinges,' he seyd, 'to armes snelle!</L>
<L>Here wil we no longer duelle:</L>
<L>To &thorn;emperour y-wraid we be&thorn;,</L>
<L>Alle he wil don ous to &thorn;e de&thorn;.</L>
<L N="3305">Bi &thorn;e treu&thorn;e y schal our lord &yogh;eld,</L>
<L>&THORN;at heuen and er&thorn;e haue&thorn; in weld,</L>
<L>Er &thorn;an we be nomen &amp; ded,<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="3153"></L>
<L>So mani schal dye of her ferred,
<PB REF="00000196.tif" N="192"></L>
<L>&THORN;at it wor&thorn; abou&yogh;t wel strong</L>
<L N="3310">&THORN;at ich am bi-wrayd wrong!'</L>
<L>To armes &thorn;ai went wi&thorn; &thorn;at ichon;</L>
<L>Out of &thorn;e cite &thorn;ai ben y-gon,</L>
<L>&amp; went toward &thorn;e he&thorn;en men,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; &thorn;em to holden &amp; to ben,</L>
<L N="3315">To help &thorn;e he&thorn;en men ichon.</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; &thorn;at com &thorn;emperour anon:</L>
<L>Fram &thorn;e riuer he come rideinge,</L>
<L>&amp; wi&thorn; his folk fast prikeinge;</L>
<L>Feir weder it was, &amp; miri also,</L>
<L N="3320">&THORN;e bri&yogh;t armes he seye &thorn;o.</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;emperour hem seye, &amp; knewe Gij,</L>
<L>For he come hem swi&thorn;e neye.</L>
<L>At an herhaud &thorn;an asked he,</L>
<L>'This armed folk, what may &thorn;is be?'</L>
<L N="3325">'Sir,' qua&thorn; he, 'it is Gij,</L>
<L>&THORN;at in wret&thorn;e fram &thorn;e wil parti;</L>
<L>Vnto &thorn;e soudan he wil fare,</L>
<L>&amp; wirche &thorn;e sorwe &amp; michel care</L>
<L>&THORN;urch wraying &thorn;at teld him is:</L>
<L N="3330">Wele y wot &thorn;at so&thorn;e it nis.</L>
<L>Wele it seme&thorn; &thorn;at wro&thorn; is he;</L>
<L>Al armed on his stede ich him se.'</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="section">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>When &thorn;emperour herd &thorn;is,<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="3175"></L>
<L>Alle droupeninde he was y-wis,</L>
<L N="3335">He gan to prike, &amp; &thorn;at anon:<MILESTONE N="124b:a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>As hauk &thorn;at fley&thorn;e his hors gan gon.</L>
<L>After Gij loude he gradde &thorn;o:</L>
<L>'Abide &amp; speke me now to!</L>
<L>For godes loue lete now be;</L>
<L N="3340">Whi wiltow, sir, go fro me?</L>
<L>&YOGH;if ich ou&yogh;t haue agilt to &thorn;e,</L>
<L>For godes loue &thorn;ou say it me;</L>
<L>Be it in dede o&thorn;er in speche</L>
<L>That ani &thorn;e han agilt, y &thorn;e biseche,
<PB REF="00000198.tif" N="194"></L>
<L N="3345">To &thorn;i wille it schal amended be,</L>
<L>&amp; topon al o&thorn;er y loue &thorn;e.</L>
<L>Wele ich wene &thorn;at &thorn;e soudan, y-wis,</L>
<L>To whom al Percie atended is,</L>
<L>After &thorn;e ha&thorn; sent: ich vnderstond so.</L>
<L N="3350">He &thorn;e schal habbe, &amp; y forgo.</L>
<L>Gold &amp; siluer he may &yogh;iue &thorn;e,</L>
<L>&amp; feffe &thorn;e wi&thorn; mani a riche cite;</L>
<L>&THORN;er-fore &thorn;ou wilt wi&thorn; him be,</L>
<L>&amp; strongliche holden o&yogh;aines me.'</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="section">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="3355">'Sir,' qua&thorn; sir Gij to &thorn;emperour,</L>
<L>'No was ich neuer &thorn;i traitour,<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="3200"></L>
<L>And &yogh;if god wil, y nil nou&yogh;t be,</L>
<L>&THORN;erwhiles &thorn;e lif is in me.</L>
<L>Me was y-teld biforn now ri&yogh;t</L>
<L N="3360">Of on &thorn;at is &thorn;i priue kni&yogh;t,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ou no hadest to don wi&thorn; mi seruise,</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;at y &thorn;e serue wi&thorn; feyntise;</L>
<L>And &thorn;at ich was biwrayd to &thorn;e</L>
<L>(For &thorn;i nold ich no longer here be),</L>
<L N="3365">And &thorn;at &thorn;ou wost do me to-hewe,</L>
<L>&amp; mine barouns, &thorn;at ben so trewe.</L>
<L>For &thorn;i y &thorn;ou&yogh;t &thorn;at y go scholde</L>
<L>To hem &thorn;at mi seruise &yogh;eld me wold;</L>
<L>Ac for al Damas &amp; &thorn;at cuntre</L>
<L N="3370">Nold ich haue holden o&yogh;aines te.'</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;emperour &thorn;an him nome</L>
<L>Bitvene his armes, &amp; seyd anon,</L>
<L>'Nay, sir Gij,' he seyd, 'bi seyn Denis,</L>
<L>It no was nou&yogh;t so, y-wis.</L>
<L N="3375">Mi dere frende Gij, o&yogh;ain &thorn;ou go</L>
<L>(Lordinges, barouns, bidde&thorn; him so);</L>
<L>For to &thorn;ine wille it is alle,</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;at min is, and ben schal.</L>
<L>Ac biwrayed &thorn;ou war to me,<MILESTONE N="124b:b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="3380">&amp; &thorn;er-fore haue he maugre!
<PB REF="00000200.tif" N="196"></L>
<L>Neuer eft wor&thorn; non loued of me</L>
<L>&THORN;at ou&yogh;t sigge bot gode of &thorn;e.'</L>
<L>&THORN;emperour &thorn;an to Gij seyd,</L>
<L>'&THORN;i wille &thorn;ou do bi &thorn;at mayde.'</L>
<L N="3385">Sir Gij kist &thorn;emperour &thorn;o,</L>
<L>&amp; to &thorn;e cite &thorn;ai ben y-go.</L>
<L>&THORN;o wist wele Gij bi &thorn;an,</L>
<L>Bitreyd<NOTE PLACE="marg">or <I>Bitrayd, a</I> being altered from <I>e?</I></NOTE> him hadde his foman;</L>
<L>Ac no semblaunt &thorn;erof he no made,</L>
<L N="3390">No no &thorn;ing to him seyde.<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="3222"></L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="section">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>An armorwe erliche</L>
<L>&THORN;emperour aros, sikerliche;</L>
<L>Anon he seyd to Gij his speche:</L>
<L>'Herken to me, y &thorn;e biseche.</L>
<L N="3395">In &thorn;is morning anon</L>
<L>We wor&thorn; aseyled of our fon,</L>
<L>Of Sarrazins &thorn;at misbileued be;</L>
<L>Alle for so&thorn;e y telle it to &thorn;e.</L>
<L>&THORN;e soudan himselue wil &thorn;er be.</L>
<L N="3400">A spie for so&thorn;e teld it me,</L>
<L>&THORN;at hij &thorn;e cite wil asayli,</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;at hij &thorn;ennes nil parti,</L>
<L>Al fort he haue nome &thorn;is cite,</L>
<L>Or &thorn;at it destrued be.'</L>
<L N="3405">&THORN;emperour seyd, 'sir Gij &thorn;e fre,</L>
<L>Als so &thorn;ou wilt it schal be.</L>
<L>&THORN;e cite alle op &thorn;e y do</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; Cristes blisceing &thorn;er-to.</L>
<L>&YOGH;if hij ous seyl we schul ous were;</L>
<L N="3410">&THORN;e cite is strong, &thorn;ai mow it nou&yogh;t dere.'</L>
<L>Gij &thorn;at constable cleped him to,</L>
<L>&THORN;at gode kni&yogh;t was, &amp; wise also:</L>
<L>Tristor he hete wi&thorn; &thorn;e berd blowe,</L>
<L>Lord &amp; douke of Almayne, y trowe.</L>
<L N="3415">'Sir Tristor,' he seyd, 'listen to me:</L>
<L>Aseyled we wor&thorn;, siker &thorn;ou be.
<PB REF="00000202.tif" N="198"></L>
<L>&THORN;er-of &thorn;ou most birede &thorn;e,</L>
<L>&YOGH;if we wille were &thorn;is cite,</L>
<L>O&thorn;er we wille o&yogh;ain hem te,</L>
<L N="3420">At pa&thorn;es that destrued be,</L>
<L>&amp; mete we hem &thorn;er on &thorn;e doune,</L>
<L>Acumbre hem &amp; legge hem doune.'</L>
<L>'Sir,' anon seyd the constable,<MILESTONE N="125a:a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>'&THORN;is ich speche schal be stable.<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="3254"></L>
<L N="3425">Do &thorn;an grede &thorn;urch &thorn;e cite</L>
<L>&THORN;at alle redy armed be,</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;at armes may welde,</L>
<L>And who so &thorn;at feyne&thorn; for couward be helde.'</L>
<L>Bi &thorn;e morwe &thorn;ai ben armed wel,</L>
<L N="3430">Bi tale .xx. thousend hauberks of stiel,</L>
<L>Out of &thorn;e cite &thorn;ai ben y-go</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; gret noise &amp; din also.</L>
<L>'Lordinges,' qua&thorn; Gij, 'herkene&thorn; to me</L>
<L>&YOGH;e &thorn;at here asembled be,</L>
<L N="3435">Of &yogh;our kinde &thorn;at is y-slawe,</L>
<L>Of edwite &amp; of missawe,</L>
<L>&THORN;at ous is don, thenke we &thorn;er-on,</L>
<L>&amp; baldeliche aseyl we our fon;</L>
<L>For Sarrazins ous aseyle wille,</L>
<L N="3440">Alle for so&thorn;e y &yogh;ou telle.</L>
<L>We wil hem mete wi&thorn; spere &amp; scheld</L>
<L>At &thorn;e narwe pa&thorn;e bi-tven &thorn;e held.</L>
<L>Now bi&thorn;enke&thorn; &yogh;ou wele to don,</L>
<L>&amp; awreke &yogh;our lond of &yogh;our fon.</L>
<L N="3445">Of &yogh;our londes &amp; &yogh;our citez,</L>
<L>&THORN;at destrud &amp; wasted be&thorn;,</L>
<L>&YOGH;ou to awreke bi-&thorn;enke&thorn; &yogh;ou,</L>
<L>&amp; strongliche aseyle&thorn; hem now.</L>
<L>Bot &yogh;e were &yogh;ou wele &amp; bliue,</L>
<L N="3450">&amp; hij mow &yogh;ou of &thorn;e feldes driue,</L>
<L>Alle we ben ded o&thorn;er nome,</L>
<L>&amp; in &thorn;raldome euer more wone.
<PB REF="00000204.tif" N="200"></L>
<L>For &thorn;i mete we wi&thorn; hem<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. <I>hen</I></NOTE> sone,</L>
<L>&amp; streng&thorn;e ous alle wele to done;</L>
<L N="3455">&amp; ich me self wil wi&thorn; &yogh;ou go;<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="3276"></L>
<L>Y nil &yogh;ou feyle neuer mo.'</L>
<L>Wele speke&thorn; now Sir Gij,</L>
<L>&amp; alle &thorn;ai sigge&thorn;, 'gramerci!'</L>
<L>To &thorn;e pas of &thorn;e hulles &thorn;ai ben y-come,</L>
<L N="3460">&amp; &thorn;e Sarrazins han vnder-nome,</L>
<L>&amp; seye &thorn;e cuntres &amp; &thorn;e feld</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; bri&yogh;t brini and wi&thorn; scheld.</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="section">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;e soudan cleped after Helman,</L>
<L>&THORN;at deined fle for no man;</L>
<L N="3465">He was coraious &amp; gode kni&yogh;t,</L>
<L>&amp; michel adouted in euerich fi&yogh;t.</L>
<L>'Sir king,' qua&thorn; he, 'come to me.<MILESTONE N="125a:b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Wi&thorn; .xx. &thorn;ousende Turkes, ich hot &thorn;e,</L>
<L>The Cristen &yogh;e schul aseyle anon.</L>
<L N="3470">Loke &yogh;e nim hem o&thorn;er slen ichon;</L>
<L>Opon &yogh;on hulle &thorn;ai ben, lo;</L>
<L>Gret harm &thorn;ai han ous y-do.'</L>
<L>&THORN;e king for&thorn; went wi&thorn; his men ichon,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; streng&thorn;e &thorn;e helde &thorn;ai vnder-nome;</L>
<L N="3475">Wi&thorn; streng&thorn;e &thorn;ai wene &thorn;e slade ouer-go;</L>
<L>Ac gret combraunce hem com furst to.</L>
<L>At &thorn;e entring of &thorn;e pas Gij<NOTE PLACE="marg">added over the line in another hand.</NOTE> gan to grede,<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="3300"></L>
<L>'Helpe&thorn;, lordinges, alle our ferrede!</L>
<L>Bi&thorn;enke&thorn; &yogh;ou to winnen wele.</L>
<L N="3480">&amp; hij o&yogh;aines &yogh;ou vndernim &thorn;e hille,</L>
<L>Yuel ous wor&thorn; &thorn;an bi-go,</L>
<L>Bot god ous on &thorn;enke<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. <I>on&thorn;enke</I>.</NOTE> &thorn;at al may do;</L>
<L>&THORN;ai ben bi-ne&thorn;en<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>ne</I> on an erasure.</NOTE> &amp; we aboue.</L>
<L>Amidde &thorn;e pas &thorn;ai ben to-gider come,</L>
<L N="3485">&amp; asaile&thorn; hem smerteliche;</L>
<L>&amp; to-gider we go now commonliche:</L>
<L>&THORN;rowe&thorn; wi&thorn; stones, and bowes scheteinge,</L>
<L>Launces, swerdes, &amp; dartes kerueinge,
<PB REF="00000206.tif" N="202"></L>
<L>Smite&thorn; wi&thorn; swerdes &amp; speres y-grounde,</L>
<L N="3490">Schete&thorn; wi&thorn; piles &amp; &yogh;if hem de&thorn; wounde.'</L>
<L>Mani Sarrazin &thorn;er y-slawe is;</L>
<L>&THORN;er do&thorn; Gij as &thorn;e ri&yogh;t wise.</L>
<L>Into &thorn;e narwe hij come, hem to lett,</L>
<L>Bi hundredes foure<NOTE PLACE="marg">Read <I>Bihinde and bifore.</I></NOTE> &thorn;ai aseyl hem sket;</L>
<L N="3495">Bi hundred &amp; bi &thorn;ousende,<NOTE PLACE="marg">originally <I>thou|sinde</I>, it seems.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;ai ben &thorn;e Sarrazins quellinde.</L>
<L>Gij smot on &thorn;is side &amp; on &thorn;at:</L>
<L>Nas &thorn;er non &thorn;at his dint sat.</L>
<L>&para; Ermine he smot on<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>on</I> added over the line.</NOTE> &thorn;urch &thorn;e scheld;</L>
<L N="3500">Almost he feld him in &thorn;e feld.</L>
<L>&THORN;an come Au&thorn;er ouer &thorn;uert,</L>
<L>A Sarrazin modi of hert:</L>
<L>Ermine<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>Herhaud</I>?</NOTE> smot him on &thorn;e helme an hey&yogh;e,<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>hey &yogh;e</I> on an erasure, the last <I>e</I> being indistinct.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at he cleue him to &thorn;e te&thorn;;</L>
<L N="3505">Al ded he made him on &thorn;e grounde to lie.</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; &thorn;at come &thorn;e king of Nubie;</L>
<L>Toward Herhaud he come prikeinde,</L>
<L>&amp; Gij him was o&yogh;ain cominde.</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; grete streng&thorn;e sir Gij him smot</L>
<L N="3510">&THORN;at he feld him anon fot hot.</L>
<L>When &thorn;e douke of Tire &thorn;at y-se&thorn;,<MILESTONE N="125b:a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>His men dye on so reweliche de&thorn;</L>
<L>(An hond he held a dart kerueinde,</L>
<L>&THORN;e Cristen &thorn;er-wi&thorn; &thorn;reteninde),</L>
<L N="3515">He for&thorn; &yogh;ede, &amp; smot a kni&yogh;t,</L>
<L>&THORN;at ded he feld him anon ri&yogh;t.</L>
<L>When Gij o Warwike &thorn;at y-seye,</L>
<L>&THORN;iderward he drou&yogh; him swi&thorn;e neye:</L>
<L>A gode dart on hond he bar,</L>
<L N="3520">&amp; to him he launced heteliche &thorn;ar.</L>
<L>&THORN;er-wi&thorn; he smot Ebban &thorn;e king,</L>
<L>&THORN;at ded he fel wi&thorn;outen letting.</L>
<L>&THORN;e Sarrazines hij to-hewe&thorn; &amp; quelle&thorn;,</L>
<L>Bi &thorn;e doun hij grede&thorn; &amp; &yogh;elle&thorn;.
</L>
</LG>

</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="section"><PB REF="00000208.tif" N="204">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="3525">When &thorn;e soudan seye his folk dye,<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="3331"></L>
<L>Bi ten, bi tvelue, in &thorn;e waye,</L>
<L>He cleped to him &thorn;e king of Nubye,</L>
<L>&THORN;at was ful of felonie.</L>
<L>'Sir king,' he seyd, 'sest tow nou&yogh;t</L>
<L N="3530">Hou mine men ben to de&thorn; y-brou&yogh;t?</L>
<L>Descumfit &amp; y-slawe hij be&thorn;,</L>
<L>&THORN;e bodis ded wele &yogh;e se&thorn;.</L>
<L>&THORN;is Cristen our men to de&thorn; do&thorn;;</L>
<L>Ac bi Cariot y swere mi no&thorn;,</L>
<L N="3535">&amp; bi Apolyn &thorn;e grete,</L>
<L>Bi Ternagaunt, &amp; bi Mahoun &thorn;e swete,</L>
<L>Bot we of hem be wreken swi&thorn;e,</L>
<L>No wor&thorn; y neuer glad no bli&thorn;e,</L>
<L>Bot we hem aseyle biginne,</L>
<L N="3540">&amp; &thorn;e hille wi&thorn; streng&thorn;e awinne.</L>
<L>An hundred we ben o&yogh;ain hem on,</L>
<L>&amp; al we schul hem nimen anon.'<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="3346"></L>
<L>&THORN;e helden &thorn;ai nime&thorn; about strongliche,</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;e Cristen aseyl stalwor&thorn;liche</L>
<L N="3545">At &thorn;e brode pa&thorn;e &amp; narwe also;</L>
<L>&THORN;e Gregeys wele werd hem &thorn;o.</L>
<L>On &thorn;e Cristen &thorn;ai gun smite,</L>
<L>&THORN;e Sarrazins, bo&thorn;e miche &amp; lite,</L>
<L>&amp; our men hem werd wel</L>
<L N="3550">Wi&thorn; scharpe speres &amp; grounden<NOTE PLACE="marg">the <I>r</I> added over the line.</NOTE> stiel:</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; axes &amp; swerdes y-grounde,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; gisarmes &thorn;ai &yogh;if de&thorn;es wounde.</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;e soudan for&thorn;wi&thorn; alder-farst</L>
<L>On &thorn;e Cristen smot wel fast;</L>
<L N="3555">On heye on helmes he hem smot<MILESTONE N="125b:b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Wi&thorn; his fauchon &thorn;at wele bot.</L>
<L>To&yogh;aines Gij he smot &thorn;o,</L>
<L>&amp; seyd 'war, ich-il &thorn;e slo!'</L>
<L>Gij he smot so ouer &thorn;uert,</L>
<L N="3560">&THORN;at he was sumdel y-hert;
<PB REF="00000210.tif" N="206"></L>
<L>Ac Gij wi&thorn; streng&thorn;e to him smot</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; his swerd &thorn;at wele bot.</L>
<L>Wel strong was &thorn;at ich fi&yogh;t,</L>
<L>Ac &thorn;e soudan wered him wi&thorn; mi&yogh;t.</L>
<L N="3565">Wharto schuld ich &yogh;ou telle more?</L>
<L>&THORN;e Sarrazins ouer-comen wore:</L>
<L>Wele ha&thorn; Gij don &thorn;at day,<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="3355"></L>
<L>As gode kni&yogh;t &amp; verray.</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="section">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>At a pas he houed ri&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="3570">As a kni&yogh;t of gret mi&yogh;t;</L>
<L>A gisarme he bar kerueinde,</L>
<L>He smot bifore &amp; bi-hinde.</L>
<L>&THORN;e Sarra&yogh;ins so he agast,</L>
<L>Al &thorn;at he smot to grounde he cast.</L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L>His scheld he hadde forlore,</L>
<L>To-hewe it lay his fet bifore.</L>
<L>So mani Sarrazin he slou&yogh; &thorn;at day,</L>
<L N="3580">&THORN;at ich on o&thorn;er ded lay;</L>
<L>So mani to ded &thorn;er he dede,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;e hepe lay to his girdel stede.</L>
<L>&para; Who so seye &thorn;an Herhaud fi&yogh;t,<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="3369"></L>
<L>Of a gode kni&yogh;t &yogh;elp he mi&yogh;t.</L>
<L N="3585">A damsax he bar on his hond:</L>
<L>Al &thorn;at he rau&yogh;t to grounde he wond;</L>
<L>Sarrazins he slou&yogh; mo &thorn;an sexti,</L>
<L>&amp; Gij an hundred &amp; fourti.</L>
<L>Herhaud &thorn;at day so sore swong,</L>
<L N="3590">&THORN;at &thorn;urch his mou&thorn;e &thorn;e fom it sprong;</L>
<L>Al to-hewe<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. <I>alto hewe</I></NOTE> was his helme,</L>
<L>&THORN;e blod ran out als a welme.</L>
<L>What schuld y make tale muche?</L>
<L>&THORN;e Sarrazins &thorn;ai slowen strongliche;</L>
<L N="3595">Ac euer he was gode, apli&yogh;t,</L>
<L>Gij of Warwike michel of mi&yogh;t,
<PB REF="00000212.tif" N="208"></L>
<L>More dede &thorn;an ani o&thorn;er:</L>
<L>His stroke was heui so a fo&thorn;er.</L>
<L>Gij and his feren also</L>
<L N="3600">Als lyouns &thorn;ai fou&yogh;ten &thorn;o,</L>
<L>&amp; the Gregeys for&thorn; wi&thorn; hem,<MILESTONE N="126a:a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&THORN;ai wered hem as douhti men.<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="3382"></L>
<L>Weynes &amp; cartes &thorn;ai han y-nome</L>
<L>Mo &thorn;an fiften &thorn;ousende atte frome.</L>
<L N="3605">Y-ioined hij han &thorn;e gret piles,</L>
<L>Ginnes &thorn;ai made on selcou&thorn;e wise,</L>
<L>Sum piles scharpe kerueinde,</L>
<L>Al aboute so mani stondinde,</L>
<L>&THORN;at ich ne can &thorn;e noumbre telle,</L>
<L N="3610">Noi&thorn;er in rime no in spelle.</L>
<L>&THORN;er nas man &thorn;at &thorn;er neye come,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he ne was to-corwen anon.</L>
<L>So griseliche be &thorn;e engins,</L>
<L>For to sle &thorn;e Sarrazines,</L>
<L N="3615">In ich half y-sett arawe,</L>
<L>Scharpe soules doun of &thorn;e hulle y-drawe.<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>r</I> added over the line.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;er-mid &thorn;ai hewe &thorn;e gret stonis,</L>
<L>Bi-hewe quarre for &thorn;e nonis,</L>
<L>So gret so tventie men mi&yogh;t drawe,</L>
<L N="3620">To slen hem of &thorn;e he&thorn;en lawe.</L>
<L>Swiche a &thorn;ousende for-smiten &thorn;ai be,</L>
<L>&THORN;at neuer after schullen y-the;</L>
<L>Wel iuel hem is bifallen &thorn;are,</L>
<L>Ded &thorn;ai ben wi&thorn; sorwe &amp; care.<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="3404"></L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="section">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="3625">Wharto schuld ich tale telle?</L>
<L>&THORN;e soudan lepe on hors ful snelle.</L>
<L>Gret onde he hadde to Gyoun,</L>
<L>&amp; to Herhaud, his compaynoun,</L>
<L>For hij han slawe so fel of his.</L>
<L N="3630">He sat on an hors of pris,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; gret hete he smot to Gij,</L>
<L>Opon his helme, sikerly,
<PB REF="00000214.tif" N="210"></L>
<L>&THORN;at he feld &thorn;at o quarter.</L>
<L>To Gij he seyd a bismer:</L>
<L N="3635">'Y-sestow, lord? bi Apolin,</L>
<L>&THORN;at was a strok of a Sarrazin!'</L>
<L>Gij to &thorn;e soudan smot &thorn;o,</L>
<L>His helme no was him wor&thorn; a slo:</L>
<L>Resares euen for&thorn; &thorn;e breyn</L>
<L N="3640">Helme &amp; flesse he carf wi&thorn; meyn.</L>
<L>&THORN;an he seyd to him a bismer:</L>
<L>'Mahoun halp &thorn;e litel &thorn;er!</L>
<L>Bodi &amp; soule no nou&yogh;t &thorn;er-of</L>
<L>No is nou&yogh;t wor&thorn; a lekes clof.</L>
<L N="3645">Hou so it go of mi wounde,<MILESTONE N="126a:b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Of Mahoun &thorn;ou hast litel help y-founde.</L>
<L>Er &thorn;ou scorndest me,</L>
<L>Of mi wounde &thorn;ou madest &thorn;i gle:</L>
<L>Leche gode schal ich haue,</L>
<L N="3650">&THORN;at mi wounde schal to hele drawe;</L>
<L>&THORN;ou hast a croun schauen to &thorn;e bon;</L>
<L>Tomerwe &thorn;ou mi&yogh;t sing anon.</L>
<L>Wele &thorn;ou &thorn;ou&yogh;test to ben a prest,</L>
<L>When &thorn;ou of swiche a bischop order berst!'</L>
<L N="3655">Now biginne&thorn; &thorn;at gret fi&yogh;t;</L>
<L>Bi &thorn;re, bi four, adoun ri&yogh;t,</L>
<L>&THORN;e Sarrazins ben ouer-come,</L>
<L>Oway fleinde &thorn;ai ben some.<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="3405"></L>
<L>&THORN;e ni&yogh;t come&thorn;, &thorn;e day is go,</L>
<L N="3660">&THORN;e Sarrazins han ful michel wo;</L>
<L>For so mani y-slawe &thorn;er be</L>
<L>(So seyd &thorn;e folk of &thorn;at cuntre),</L>
<L>&THORN;at men mi&yogh;t wade ouer &thorn;e scho hem</L>
<L>In &thorn;e blod &thorn;at of hem kem.</L>
<L N="3665">So miche folk &thorn;er was y-slawe &thorn;o,</L>
<L>&THORN;at fiftene forlong men mi&yogh;t go,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ei he kept him neuer so,</L>
<L>He most nedes opon men go,
<PB REF="00000216.tif" N="212"></L>
<L>O&thorn;er on fot, o&thorn;er on hond,</L>
<L N="3670">O&thorn;er opon arm coruen wi&thorn; brond.</L>
<L>&para; Wi&thorn; &thorn;at come an amiral prikeinge,</L>
<L>Newe dubbed he was, wi&thorn;-outen lesing;</L>
<L>To &thorn;e soudan he is y-come,</L>
<L>&THORN;urch &thorn;e bodi he ha&thorn; woundes some.</L>
<L N="3675">'Sir,' he seyd, 'hennes we go:</L>
<L>No sestow al our folk slo?</L>
<L>Bi &thorn;ousendes &thorn;ou sest hem to de&thorn; ligge;</L>
<L>Our godes ous hate&thorn;, for so&thorn;e to sigge.</L>
<L>&THORN;ou sest Mahoun ne Apolin</L>
<L N="3680">Be nou&yogh;t wor&thorn; &thorn;e brestel of a swin.</L>
<L>Anon ri&yogh;tes wi&thorn;drawe &thorn;ou &thorn;e,</L>
<L>&amp; to &thorn;i pauiloun &thorn;ou fle;</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;e wounded &thorn;ou do wi&thorn; &thorn;e lede;</L>
<L>&YOGH;ete &thorn;ai may &thorn;e help &amp; rede.</L>
<L N="3685">&THORN;i rereban &thorn;ou do of-sende;</L>
<L>To awreke [&thorn;e] &thorn;ou haue in mende.'</L>
<L>Anon &thorn;ai hem wi&thorn;drawe and ben ouer-come;</L>
<L>Sori &thorn;ai ben alle &amp; some.</L>
<L>&THORN;e soudan dede biforn him bring<MILESTONE N="126b:a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="3690">Alle his godes, wi&thorn;outen lesing:</L>
<L>Toward hem he is wel wro&thorn;,</L>
<L>Do he wil hem harm &amp; lo&thorn;:</L>
<L>'A &yogh;e<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>&yogh;e</I> on an erasure.</NOTE> fals godes vnwreste!</L>
<L>Sone &yogh;ou tit a li&thorn;er<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. <I>alither</I></NOTE> feste.</L>
<L N="3695">O&yogh;ain ous &yogh;e ben of wicked mode:</L>
<L>Schame &yogh;e don ous &amp; no gode.</L>
<L>&YOGH;e don ous alder-werst to spede</L>
<L>When &thorn;at we han mest nede.</L>
<L>Fy, fy,' he seyd, 'on [&thorn;e], Apolin!</L>
<L N="3700">&THORN;ou schalt haue wel iuel fin,</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;ou, Ternagaunt, also:</L>
<L>Michel schame schal com &yogh;ou to;</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;ou, Mahoun, her alder lord,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou nart nou&yogh;t wor&thorn; a tord!
<PB REF="00000218.tif" N="214"></L>
<L N="3705">&THORN;er-fore &thorn;ou it schalt abigge</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; staues gret opon &thorn;i rigge.'</L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L>So he gan his godes to cloute,</L>
<L N="3710">&THORN;at &thorn;e er&thorn;e dined aboute.</L>
<L>Her armes &amp; legges he to-ti&yogh;t,</L>
<L>&amp; cleped hem wroches anon ri&yogh;t:</L>
<L>'Godenes in &yogh;ou nas neuer y-founde,</L>
<L>No more mi&yogh;t &thorn;an in an hounde.'</L>
<L N="3715">Bi &thorn;e fet he hem out drou&yogh;,</L>
<L>And dede hem schame ri&yogh;t anou&yogh;.</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="section">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Gij dede clepe her cheueteyn</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; gode will &amp; hert feyn:</L>
<L>'Lordinges,' he seyd, 'god y-&thorn;onked be!<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="3450"></L>
<L N="3720">Feir grace so habbe we,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;e Sarrazins ben ouercome.</L>
<L>Wende we to &thorn;e cite atte frome.'</L>
<L>&amp; when &thorn;ai ben comen o&yogh;en,</L>
<L>To &thorn;emperour welcom &thorn;ai ben,</L>
<L N="3725">&amp; nameliche Gij, &thorn;e gode kni&yogh;t,</L>
<L>Mest was wor&thorn;schiped in &thorn;at fi&yogh;t.</L>
<L>&para; When &thorn;at y-seye Morgadour,</L>
<L>&THORN;at steward was wi&thorn; &thorn;emperour,</L>
<L>&THORN;at Gij biwreyed vnwrastliche,</L>
<L N="3730">&THORN;at &thorn;emperour loued so miche,</L>
<L>He bigan for to asay</L>
<L>Hou he mi&yogh;t Gij bi-tray.</L>
<L>O felonie he ha&thorn; him bi-&thorn;ou&yogh;t;</L>
<L>Of swiche no haue &yogh;e herd nou&yogh;t:</L>
<L N="3735">He &thorn;ou&yogh;t in his wille &thorn;o,<MILESTONE N="126b:b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&THORN;at Gij o message schuld go.</L>
<L>In swiche &thorn;ou&yogh;t &amp; swiche wille</L>
<L>An while he held him stille;</L>
<L>Anon he went to &thorn;emperour,</L>
<L N="3740">&amp; seyd, 'sir, par amour,
<PB REF="00000220.tif" N="216"></L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L N="3745">&THORN;e soudan ha&thorn; his folk y-sent:</L>
<L>Into al peyni his sond is sent.</L>
<L>&THORN;er nis noi&thorn;er &yogh;ing no eld</L>
<L>&THORN;at armes may bere &amp; wepen weld,</L>
<L>Alle he is haue&thorn; of-sent,</L>
<L N="3750">&THORN;e to bisege verrament.</L>
<L>&para; To him &thorn;ou &thorn;i sond sende,</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;i wille, word &amp; ende.'</L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L N="3755">'Who,' he seyd, 'durst &thorn;ider wende?'</L>
<L>'Sir Gij, a kni&yogh;t hardi &amp; hende</L>
<L>Of &thorn;ine house, &amp; &thorn;at y plight:</L>
<L>Gij of Warwike of gret mi&yogh;t,</L>
<L>Herhaud of Arderne, &thorn;at o&thorn;er best:</L>
<L N="3760">On hem tveye &yogh;e mow &yogh;ou trest.</L>
<L>To &thorn;e soudan &thorn;ou sende &thorn;ine kni&yogh;tes bold,</L>
<L>&amp; say &thorn;ou wilt wi&thorn; him a day hold<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="3500"></L>
<L>Of acord in swiche manere.'</L>
<L>'Sir steward,' seyd &thorn;emperere,</L>
<L N="3765">'Toward Gij &thorn;ou berst iuel wille:</L>
<L>He no schal nou&yogh;t go; &thorn;erof be stille.</L>
<L>Ac mine barouns ichil of-sende,</L>
<L>&amp; wite who wille &thorn;ider wende.'</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="section">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>His barouns he ha&thorn; of-sent:</L>
<L N="3770">Ouer alle his lond &thorn;ai ben y-went,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ai schuld to &thorn;emperour wende.</L>
<L>To hem he seyd, 'mi leue frende,</L>
<L>Ich wold sende to the soudan,</L>
<L>&YOGH;if ich wist euer bi wham.</L>
<L N="3775">To him to sende ich am in wille,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; him to acord loude o&thorn;er stille,
<PB REF="00000222.tif" N="218"></L>
<L>&YOGH;if ani of &yogh;ou so hardi were,</L>
<L>&THORN;at to him &thorn;e message bere.'</L>
<L>When &thorn;emperour had seyd his resoun,</L>
<L N="3780">&THORN;er nas noi&thorn;er kni&yogh;t no baroun</L>
<L>&THORN;at him a word answerd &thorn;o:</L>
<L>Nas &thorn;er non &thorn;e message durst do.</L>
<L>&para; A baroun of &thorn;e benche aros:</L>
<L>Sir Tristor his name was.</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="section">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="3785">'Sir emperour, vnder-stond me,<MILESTONE N="127a:a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>For leyer no schal ich holden be;<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="3555"></L>
<L>For ich it sigge for gret loue,</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;ine wor&thorn;schipe to held aboue:</L>
<L>Fif thousende si&thorn;e haue he maugre</L>
<L N="3790">&THORN;at &thorn;e conseyl &yogh;af to &thorn;e!</L>
<L>For he &thorn;e loue&thorn; ri&yogh;t nou&yogh;t</L>
<L>&THORN;at in &thorn;at wille &thorn;e ha&thorn; y-brou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ou to him &yogh;elde scholdest,</L>
<L>Bot<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>&thorn;at</I>?</NOTE> &thorn;ou &thorn;i sonde sende woldest.</L>
<L N="3795">No &thorn;enkestow nou&yogh;t of &thorn;at baroun</L>
<L>&THORN;at was of so gret renoun,</L>
<L>Hou &thorn;ou sendest him to?</L>
<L>O&yogh;ain no come he neuer mo.</L>
<L>He &thorn;e sent &thorn;e heued wi&thorn;-outen more,</L>
<L N="3800">No durst neuer eft non com &thorn;ore;</L>
<L>In &thorn;e world is kni&yogh;t non</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;e message durst don.</L>
<L>For arwe no sigge ich it no-wi&yogh;t:<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="3565"></L>
<L>&YOGH;if in min armes were so gret mi&yogh;t</L>
<L N="3805">Also ich hadde, &amp; as &yogh;ong were</L>
<L>As ich was hennes an hundred &yogh;ere,</L>
<L>&THORN;is ich message don ich wold,</L>
<L>For drede of de&thorn; lete y nold.</L>
<L>Ac icham now a neld man,</L>
<L N="3810">Alle mine mi&yogh;tes ben now gan;</L>
<L>It is now gon mo &thorn;an fifti &yogh;er</L>
<L>&THORN;at ich on rigge hauberk ber.
<PB REF="00000224.tif" N="220"></L>
<L>Ich<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>jich</I>, but the <I>j</I> underdotted.</NOTE> &yogh;ou sigge for so&thorn;e y-wis,</L>
<L>To lese a good man gret harm it is,</L>
<L N="3815">For &yogh;if he ani sende&thorn; &thorn;ider,</L>
<L>His heued him schal comen hider.</L>
<L>Now ich haue mi wille y-sede;</L>
<L>Now &yogh;iue ano&thorn;er better rede.'</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="section">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>When Tristor hadde y-seyd &thorn;is,</L>
<L N="3820">Wi&thorn;-outen ani o&thorn;er abod y-wis,</L>
<L>&THORN;er nas nou&yogh;t on, litel no miche,</L>
<L>&THORN;at durst speke sikerliche.</L>
<L>Gij of Warwike vp arist:</L>
<L>'Sir emperour, bi mi lord Iesu<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>jhus</I> originally, but the <I>s</I> under|dotted.</NOTE> Crist,</L>
<L N="3825">&THORN;is message ichil afo,</L>
<L>&amp; it &thorn;urch godes help do.'</L>
<L>Seyd &thorn;emperour, '&thorn;at schaltow nou&yogh;t:</L>
<L>&THORN;ider to go haue &thorn;ou no &thorn;ou&yogh;t;</L>
<L>Ich it<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. <I>ichit</I></NOTE> dede mine men to fond,<MILESTONE N="127a:b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="3830">To whom ich mi&yogh;t trust in mi lond.'</L>
<L>&THORN;an answerd Gij wel snelle,</L>
<L>'For so&thorn;e, sir, leten y nille,</L>
<L>&THORN;at ich &thorn;e message wil do,</L>
<L>To dye er ich &thorn;ennes go.'<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="3600"></L>
<L N="3835">Wi&thorn; &thorn;at he went out of &thorn;e halle.</L>
<L>&THORN;e Gregeys siked among hem alle,</L>
<L>'God! what Gij is noble baroun!</L>
<L>Iesu, &thorn;at suffred passioun,</L>
<L>Saue him fram cumberment,</L>
<L N="3840">&amp; him o&yogh;ain bring in sauement.'</L>
<L>Gij cam to his in in a stounde,</L>
<L>His felawes droupeing he founde.</L>
<L>'Lordinges,' he seyd, 'hou is it now?</L>
<L>Almi&yogh;ti god y bi-teche &yogh;ou.'</L>
<L N="3845">'Sir,' qua&thorn; Herhaud, 'ich-il go</L>
<L>Bi &thorn;ine wille wi&thorn; &thorn;e also.'</L>
<L>Gij answerd, 'so no schal it be.</L>
<L>Icham y-go: bidde&thorn; for me.'
<PB REF="00000226.tif" N="222"></L>
<L>He oxed his armes hastiliche,</L>
<L N="3850">And men es him brou&yogh;t sikerliche.</L>
<L>Hosen of iren he ha&thorn; on drawe,</L>
<L>Non better<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>bertter</I>, but the first <I>r</I> under|dotted.</NOTE> nar bi &thorn;o dawe.</L>
<L>In a strong hauberk he gan him schrede,</L>
<L>Who so it wered, &thorn;e ded no &thorn;urt him drede.</L>
<L N="3855">An helme he ha&thorn; on him don:</L>
<L>Better no wered neuer kni&yogh;t non;</L>
<L>The sercle<NOTE PLACE="marg">the <I>r</I> added over the line.</NOTE> of gold &thorn;er-on was wrou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>For half a cite no wor&thorn; it bou&yogh;t:</L>
<L>So mani stones &thorn;er-in were,</L>
<L N="3860">&THORN;at were of vertu swi&thorn;e dere.</L>
<L>Se&thorn;&thorn;e he gert him wi&thorn; a brond</L>
<L>&THORN;at was y-made in eluene lond.</L>
<L>His scheld about his nek he tok,</L>
<L>On hors he lepe wi&thorn;-outen stirop,</L>
<L N="3865">On hond he nam a spere kerueinde,</L>
<L>Out of &thorn;e cite he was rideinde.</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;at weren of &thorn;at cite</L>
<L>For him wel sori weren he;</L>
<L>No wene &thorn;ai neuer his &yogh;ain-cominge,</L>
<L N="3870">Alle &thorn;ai wene &thorn;er his endinge.</L>
<L>Now is Gij in &thorn;e ri&yogh;t way<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="3635"></L>
<L>Toward &thorn;e Sarrazins, y say,</L>
<L>Wele y-armed on his stede,<MILESTONE N="127b:a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>A launce he bar gode at nede.</L>
<L N="3875">Smerteliche he dede him in &thorn;e ways,</L>
<L>Ouer &thorn;e dounes &amp; &thorn;e valeys</L>
<L>To the Sarrazins y-comen he is,</L>
<L>&amp; her pauilouns he se&thorn; y-wis.</L>
<L>A real pauiloun he &thorn;er seye</L>
<L N="3880">Wi&thorn; an eren of gold an heye.</L>
<L>&THORN;at was &thorn;e soudans<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>soudanes</I>, but the <I>e</I> underdotted.</NOTE> pauiloun:</L>
<L>Haue he Cristes malisoun!</L>
<L>In-to &thorn;e pauiloun Gij him wond,</L>
<L>&amp; an hast &thorn;er he fond
<PB REF="00000228.tif" N="224"></L>
<L N="3885">Alle atte mete &thorn;at &thorn;er was,</L>
<L>&amp; nou&yogh;t michel noise &thorn;er nas.</L>
<L>At &thorn;e heye bord eten kinges ten,</L>
<L>&THORN;at alle were Gyes fomen.</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="section">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;an seyd Gij &thorn;e Englisse,</L>
<L N="3890">'Vnderstond to mi speche:</L>
<L>&THORN;ilke lord &thorn;at wone&thorn; an heye,</L>
<L>&THORN;at al &thorn;ing walt fer &amp; neye,</L>
<L>&amp; in &thorn;e rode lete him pini,</L>
<L>Al cristen men to saui,<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>sauei</I>, but the <I>e</I> underdotted.</NOTE></L>
<L N="3895">&amp; in &thorn;e se made &thorn;e sturioun,</L>
<L>So &yogh;if &yogh;ou alle his malisoun,</L>
<L>&amp; alle &thorn;ilk &thorn;at ich here se,</L>
<L>&THORN;at mis-bileued men be;</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;e at &thorn;e first, sir soudan,</L>
<L N="3900">Cristes wreche &thorn;e come opan!</L>
<L>Yuel fure breninde fast &thorn;e opon,</L>
<L>&amp; cleue &thorn;i brest doun to &thorn;i ton!</L>
<L>For icham Gij &yogh;e mow wel<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>l</I> added over the line with another ink.</NOTE> se,</L>
<L>Yuel mot &yogh;e alle y-the!</L>
<L N="3905">Vnder-stond, treitour, mi resoun:</L>
<L>Haue &thorn;ou Cristes malisoun,</L>
<L>&amp; alle &thorn;ilke for&thorn; mitt te,</L>
<L>&THORN;at ich her<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>r</I> added over the line (with another ink?).</NOTE> about &thorn;e se.</L>
<L>&THORN;e heye god &thorn;at is ful of mi&yogh;t</L>
<L N="3910">Binim &yogh;ou &yogh;our limes &amp; &yogh;our si&yogh;t!</L>
<L>Bi me &thorn;e sent word &thorn;emperour Garioun,</L>
<L>&THORN;at mi&yogh;ti men ha&thorn; in his bandoun,<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="3660"></L>
<L>&THORN;urch wham &thorn;ou art y-brou&yogh;t to schond,</L>
<L>&amp; hote&thorn; &thorn;e wende out of his lond,</L>
<L N="3915">For here has tow no ri&yogh;t.</L>
<L>Finde a Sarrazin o&thorn;er a kni&yogh;t,</L>
<L>&amp; he schal ano&thorn;er finde,<MILESTONE N="127b:b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&THORN;at schal deray[ne] his ri&yogh;t kinde.</L>
<L>Y schal wi&thorn; &thorn;e glotoun fi&yogh;t;</L>
<L N="3920">&amp; &yogh;if &thorn;ine haue &thorn;e more mi&yogh;t,
<PB REF="00000230.tif" N="226"></L>
<L>&amp; ouer-come&thorn; our champioun,</L>
<L>Mi lord &thorn;e schal &yogh;iue ransoun,</L>
<L>&amp; als his lord serue wille</L>
<L>Euer more, &amp; &thorn;at is skille.</L>
<L N="3925">&amp; &yogh;if it so bitide &thorn;at our kni&yogh;t</L>
<L>Ouer-come &yogh;our in feld in fi&yogh;t,</L>
<L>Hastiliche &thorn;an, y rede &thorn;e,</L>
<L>Out of &thorn;is lond &thorn;at &thorn;ou fle.</L>
<L>&THORN;er-of &thorn;ou take a day:</L>
<L N="3930">On mi lordes word, y &thorn;e say,</L>
<L>To &thorn;i pauiloun ich am y-come,</L>
<L>To do &thorn;e bateyle atte frome.</L>
<L>Onswere me wi&thorn;-outen lesing,</L>
<L>What word y schal mi lord bring.'</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="section">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="3935">Qua&thorn; &thorn;e soudan, 'whennes artow,<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="3683"></L>
<L>Into mi court<NOTE PLACE="marg">added at the end of the line.</NOTE> comen art now,</L>
<L>&amp; misseyst me so schameliche,</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;retest me so dedeliche?'</L>
<L>Gij answerd, 'ich-il &thorn;e telle:</L>
<L N="3940">Mi name for-hele y nille.</L>
<L>Gij of Warwike mi name is;</L>
<L>In &thorn;at cuntre y was born y-wis.'</L>
<L>&THORN;e soudan answerd &thorn;o:</L>
<L>'Artow Gij, so mot &thorn;ou go,</L>
<L N="3945">&THORN;ou slou&yogh; mi nevou Cosdram:</L>
<L>His heued &thorn;ou smot &thorn;e bodi fram;</L>
<L>&THORN;ou it schalt abigge, bi Apolin!</L>
<L>Today is comen ending &thorn;in!'<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="3700"></L>
<L>He hete anon &thorn;at Gij wer nome</L>
<L N="3950">&amp; y-cast in his prisoun,</L>
<L>Fort &thorn;e clo&thorn; ben y-drawe,</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;an reweliche ben y-slawe.</L>
<L>Gij drou&yogh; out his swerd anon,</L>
<L>&amp; priked his stede wel gode won.</L>
<L N="3955">Bi seyn Denis he gan to swere,</L>
<L>&YOGH;if ani man so hardi were,
<PB REF="00000232.tif" N="228"></L>
<L>&THORN;at him ney&yogh;ed wi&thorn; schond,</L>
<L>He schuld dye &thorn;urch his hond.</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="section">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bifor &thorn;e soudan com Gyoun,</L>
<L N="3960">&amp; him biheld als a lyoun,<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. <I>alyoun</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>&amp; seyd, 'soudan, &thorn;ou schalt abigge:<MILESTONE N="128a:a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&THORN;ine heued &thorn;ou schalt forgon, y sigge.'</L>
<L>Opon &thorn;e cheyer &thorn;er he sat</L>
<L>Gij toke him bi &thorn;e top wi&thorn; &thorn;at,</L>
<L N="3965">&amp; &thorn;at heued he dede of fle</L>
<L>Opon &thorn;e bord of appel tre.</L>
<L>&THORN;e heued he toke in his hond,<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="3713"></L>
<L>&amp; in his lappe he it wond.</L>
<L>Wel hastiliche he went him, y-wis,</L>
<L N="3970">Of &thorn;e Sarra&yogh;ins adrede he is.</L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L>An hundred heuedes he dede of flen</L>
<L>Of &thorn;ilke &thorn;at him stode o&yogh;en.</L>
<L N="3975">Wi&thorn; him he for&thorn; &thorn;at heued bar,</L>
<L>Maugre alle &thorn;at &thorn;er war.</L>
<L>&THORN;urch &thorn;at ost he rode smartliche,</L>
<L>His hors him bar hastiliche.</L>
<L>&THORN;er mi&yogh;t men se &thorn;e Sarrazin</L>
<L N="3980">Bi on &amp; on wende to Apolin.</L>
<L>Wel fast after him &thorn;ai come,</L>
<L>&amp; alle &thorn;ai wold han him nome.</L>
<L>Gij to aseylen &thorn;ai wer &yogh;ep;</L>
<L>Vnarmed were &thorn;e most hep.</L>
<L N="3985">Gij drou&yogh; him toward an hulle,</L>
<L>&THORN;e Sarrazins him driuen snelle:</L>
<L>Bo&thorn;e bi<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>bi</I> on an erasure.</NOTE> hundred &amp; &thorn;ousende</L>
<L>Him go &thorn;e Sarrazins driueinde.</L>
<L>On ich half &thorn;ai smiten him to,</L>
<L N="3990">&amp; he o&yogh;ain to hem also:</L>
<L>Neuer no was an-lepy kni&yogh;t</L>
<L>&THORN;at so mani stond mi&yogh;t.
<PB REF="00000234.tif" N="230"></L>
<L>Bot god nim of him &yogh;eme,</L>
<L>His liif it is michel awene.</L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="section">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Listene&thorn; now &amp; sitte&thorn; stille:<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="3731"></L>
<L>Of Herhaud ich &yogh;ou telle wille,</L>
<L>&THORN;at of swoning no may him duelle.</L>
<L N="4000">For his lord Gij, y &yogh;ou telle,</L>
<L>So michel sorwe him was an,</L>
<L>&THORN;at telle no mi&yogh;t he it noman.</L>
<L>Euerich man is swi&thorn;e wo</L>
<L>When he schal a gode<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. <I>agode</I></NOTE> frende for-go:</L>
<L N="4005">So was Herhaud for his lord fre;</L>
<L>No wende he him neuer more y-se.</L>
<L>&THORN;an bigan his sorweinge,</L>
<L>His her<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>r</I> in <I>her</I> added over the line.</NOTE> he<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>he</I> omitted in MS.</NOTE> tar, his honden gan wring.</L>
<L>'Allas!' he seyd, 'sir Gij!<MILESTONE N="128a:b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="4010">Now ich wot wele siker-lye</L>
<L>&THORN;at y no schal &thorn;e neuer y-se;</L>
<L>Allas! for sorwe wo is me!'</L>
<L>For grete sorwe &thorn;at he hedde</L>
<L>He fel adoun on his bedde,</L>
<L N="4015">&THORN;er he is y-falle on slepe,</L>
<L>As a man weri of wepe.</L>
<L>A sweuen him mett wel ferly,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he seye his lord sir Gij</L>
<L>On his stede swi&thorn;e cominge,</L>
<L N="4020">&amp; on his hond his swerd kerueing;</L>
<L>Aseyled he was wi&thorn; wolues &amp; bere:</L>
<L>Vnne&thorn;e he mi&yogh;t him fram hem were<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="3750"></L>
<L>Alle &thorn;ai hadde to-broken his scheld,</L>
<L>&amp; his brini to-rent manifeld.</L>
<L N="4025">Vnne&thorn;e he mi&yogh;t him were,</L>
<L>So &thorn;ai gun on him to tere.</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; &thorn;at is Herhaud awaked,</L>
<L>&amp; of his sweuen gret sorwe maked,
<PB REF="00000236.tif" N="232"></L>
<L>&amp; seyd anon to alle his compeynie,</L>
<L N="4030">'Felawes, wil we ous armi?</L>
<L>Gij to help we ou&yogh;t to spede;</L>
<L>For to help he ha&thorn; gret nede,</L>
<L>Wele ich wot bi mi sweuen.</L>
<L>Now help ous god &thorn;at is in heuen!'</L>
<L N="4035">Y-armed &thorn;ai ben sone anon,</L>
<L>&amp; on hors &thorn;ai lopen ichon,</L>
<L>&amp; wende&thorn; for&thorn; wi&thorn; gode wille</L>
<L>Ouer &thorn;e dounes &amp; &thorn;e dales snelle.</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; alle her mi&yogh;t &thorn;ai heye fast</L>
<L N="4040">For to socour Gij on hast.</L>
<L>&THORN;e Sarrazins &thorn;ai gun &thorn;retni,</L>
<L>&amp; made gret sorwe for Gij.</L>
<L>&THORN;ai seyd alle &thorn;at &thorn;er were,</L>
<L>Hem dred &thorn;ai him seye neuere;</L>
<L N="4045">O&thorn;er ded he was o&thorn;er y-nome,</L>
<L>For him &thorn;ai were sori alle &amp; some.</L>
<L>Sone &thorn;ai ney&yogh;ed toward &thorn;at ost,</L>
<L>Of Sarrazins &thorn;ai herd gret bost;</L>
<L>Of hem was wrin al &thorn;e feld,</L>
<L N="4050">On hors &thorn;ai were wi&thorn; spere &amp; scheld,</L>
<L>&THORN;at euerichon &thorn;ai &thorn;retten Gij:</L>
<L>Him to slen &thorn;ai han gret envie.</L>
<L>Amonges hem &thorn;ai seye Gyoun<MILESTONE N="128b:a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&THORN;at him wered als a lyoun.<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. <I>alyoun.</I></NOTE></L>
<L N="4055">On ich half &thorn;ai him aseyle,</L>
<L>&amp; he him wer&thorn; wi&thorn;-outen feyle.</L>
<L>Bi &thorn;e reynes &thorn;ai ben him neye niminge,</L>
<L>Ac he him wer&thorn; wi&thorn; swerd kerueing;</L>
<L>Mani he smot of fot &amp; fest;</L>
<L N="4060">He hadde al nede, la, wite Crist!<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="3780"></L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="section">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Now &thorn;ai bigin to prike swi&thorn;e,</L>
<L>To socour Gij &thorn;ai han gret hye.</L>
<L>Herhaud him smot a Sarrazin,</L>
<L>&THORN;at litel him halp his Apolin.
<PB REF="00000238.tif" N="234"></L>
<L N="4065">&THORN;ai smiten togider &amp; fast &thorn;rung,</L>
<L>&THORN;ai corwen &thorn;urch liuer &amp; &thorn;urch lunge;</L>
<L>&THORN;e Sarrazins &thorn;ai teche an iuel play,</L>
<L>Euerich on o&thorn;er y-slawe lay.</L>
<L>Herhaud is ful wele bifalle,</L>
<L N="4070">He socour&thorn;e Gij wi&thorn; his felawes alle.</L>
<L>Amonges hem was gret gladn-esse:</L>
<L>&THORN;e most hepe<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>&yogh;epe?</I></NOTE> wepen for blis;</L>
<L>&THORN;ai kisten Gij alle for blis,</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;onked god ful &yogh;ern, y-wis.</L>
<L N="4075">&para; &THORN;e Sarrazins wenten alle o&yogh;en,</L>
<L>Sori &amp; dreri alle &thorn;ai ben.</L>
<L>&THORN;ai token her lordes bodi &thorn;ere,</L>
<L>As sori wreches oway it bere;</L>
<L>To Ascone &thorn;ai ben &thorn;er-wi&thorn; y-come,</L>
<L N="4080">Y-schent &thorn;ai ben alle &amp; some.</L>
<L>Gij, &amp; Herhaud, &amp; her meyne</L>
<L>Glad &amp; bli&thorn;e alle ben he.<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="3800"></L>
<L>&THORN;at heued &thorn;ai han on a spere y-sett</L>
<L>(&THORN;er mi&yogh;t men se &thorn;at Gij was wel net),</L>
<L N="4085">Bifore him bere &thorn;at it ha&thorn; y-do.</L>
<L>Mani on pelt her finger &thorn;er-to.</L>
<L>Into &thorn;e cite &thorn;ai gun it bring,</L>
<L>For ioie &thorn;ai gun &thorn;e belles ring.</L>
<L>Sir Gij to &thorn;emperour y-comen is,</L>
<L N="4090">&THORN;e heued he him &yogh;alt, y-wis:</L>
<L>&THORN;emperour gret &thorn;anke him can,</L>
<L>&amp; in &thorn;at cite he do&thorn; make onan</L>
<L>A piler of gray marbel ston:</L>
<L>&THORN;at heued he sett anon &thorn;er-on.</L>
<L N="4095">In swiche wise deuised it was,</L>
<L>&THORN;at it was biwreyen in bras,</L>
<L>Whar-&thorn;urch &thorn;at o&thorn;er mi&yogh;t ben war<MILESTONE N="128b:b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>To come wi&thorn; ani ost more &thorn;ar.<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="3832"></L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="section">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;an Gij hadde y-don so</L>
<L N="4100">&THORN;emperour cleped Gij him to:
<PB REF="00000240.tif" N="236"></L>
<L>'Welcome be &thorn;ou to me, sir Gij!</L>
<L>Hennes for dayes &thorn;ritti</L>
<L>Michel monschip ichil &thorn;e do,</L>
<L>Mi feir douhter &yogh;iue &thorn;e to.'</L>
<L N="4105">To &thorn;emperour onswerd sir Gij,</L>
<L>'An hundred si&thorn;e, sir, gramerci!'</L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L>&THORN;emperour aros amorwe &thorn;o,<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="3843"></L>
<L N="4110">To sen &thorn;e cuntre &thorn;ai ben y-go;</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;at day &thorn;ai riden hem so</L>
<L>Alle what euen, &thorn;ai rested hem &thorn;o.</L>
<L>&THORN;ai seye toward a pleyn plas</L>
<L>&THORN;at bisiden a doun<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. <I>adoun</I></NOTE> was.</L>
<L N="4115">A lyoun &thorn;ai seye cominde &thorn;o,</L>
<L>Bot a smal pas no mi&yogh;t he go,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; &yogh;enende mou&thorn;e, &amp; weri he was.</L>
<L>Gij &thorn;at seye &amp; seyd, 'allas!</L>
<L>Whi, no haddestow help non?'</L>
<L N="4120">Ac &thorn;at lyon<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. <I>foly</I></NOTE> &thorn;ai dradden ichon,</L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L N="4125">For wi&thorn; a dragoun he hade y-fou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>&amp; ouercomen he was nere him &thorn;ou&yogh;t.</L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L>Gij anon asked his stede &thorn;o,</L>
<L N="4130">His spere, &amp; his swerd also:</L>
<L>In his hond a gode swerd he bar;</L>
<L>&THORN;at y-seye alle &thorn;at &thorn;er war.</L>
<L>When &thorn;e dragoun seye com Gij</L>
<L>&THORN;e lyoun he forlett, &amp; gan him sayly.</L>
<L N="4135">Wi&thorn; open mou&thorn;e o&yogh;aines him he come;</L>
<L>Gij bar his spere o&yogh;aines him anon:
<PB REF="00000242.tif" N="238"></L>
<L>In-to his &thorn;rote he it &thorn;rest wi&thorn; streng&thorn;e;</L>
<L>In his bodi was alle his schaft leng&thorn;e,</L>
<L>&THORN;at ded to grounde he feld him &thorn;o.</L>
<L N="4140">What schuld y make tales mo?</L>
<L>He smot of &thorn;e heued, &amp; went oway,</L>
<L>&amp; come to &thorn;emperour so sone so he may,</L>
<L>Gyoun, wi&thorn; ri&yogh;t gode wille:</L>
<L>&THORN;e lyoun after him folwe&thorn; snelle.<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="3890"></L>
<L N="4145">Biforn him he go&thorn; swi&thorn;e sket,</L>
<L>&amp; folwed him at his stede fet.</L>
<L>His fet he licked, so &yogh;ede he neye,</L>
<L>&amp; lepe vp on his stede an heye,</L>
<L>&amp; se&thorn;&thorn;e he lepe adoun anon,<MILESTONE N="129a:a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="4150">&amp; made him gret joie opon.</L>
<L>To &thorn;emperour is comen Gij,</L>
<L>&THORN;at of him was glad, sikerli.</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;ai bihelden &thorn;e lyoun,</L>
<L>&amp; hadde gret joie bot &thorn;e feloun,</L>
<L N="4155">Morgadour &thorn;e steward,</L>
<L>&THORN;at euer was Gij o&yogh;einward.</L>
<L>A li&thorn;er tresoun &thorn;an &thorn;ou&yogh;t he,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he wold &thorn;e lyoun sle.</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; &thorn;at into &thorn;e cite &thorn;ai ben y-gon;</L>
<L N="4160">&THORN;emperour went vnto his tour of ston,<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="3913"></L>
<L>&amp; Gij is to his in y-go:</L>
<L>&THORN;e lyoun him folwed euer mo.</L>
<L>Biforn his bed he go&thorn; to ligge,</L>
<L>Fram him he nold, for so&thorn;e to sigge.</L>
<L N="4165">So long &thorn;ai riden her jurneys,</L>
<L>And &thorn;urch riden &thorn;e cuntreys,</L>
<L>&THORN;at to Costentin &thorn;ai ben y-come.</L>
<L>&THORN;emperour ha&thorn; Gij on speche y-nome,</L>
<L>&amp; seyd, 'Gij, make &thorn;e redi:</L>
<L N="4170">Tomorwe &thorn;ou schalt mi douhter weddi.'</L>
<L>Wel sweteliche him answerd sir Gij,</L>
<L>'Sir emperour, mow gramerci!'
</L>
</LG>

</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="section"><PB REF="00000244.tif" N="240">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>A morwe, so sone so it was day,<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="3935"></L>
<L>Gij him schred in fou &amp; gray;</L>
<L N="4175">Wi&thorn; him his felawes also,</L>
<L>To chirche &thorn;ai gon euer to &amp; to.</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; &thorn;at &thorn;ai ben to chirche y-come</L>
<L>Wor&thorn;schiplich alle &amp; some,</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;at maiden was also;</L>
<L N="4180">Gret joie hadde al her kin &thorn;o.</L>
<L>&THORN;e erchebischop was comen also,</L>
<L>Redi &thorn;e spouseing for to do.</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;emperour seyd to Gij &thorn;ere:<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="3949"></L>
<L>'Mi douhter ich &yogh;iue &thorn;e here,</L>
<L N="4185">And &thorn;ritti castels wi&thorn; hir also,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; &thorn;e wor&thorn;schip &thorn;at li&thorn; &thorn;er-to,</L>
<L>And half mi lond ich &yogh;iue &thorn;e,</L>
<L>Bifor mi barouns &thorn;at here be.</L>
<L>&THORN;ou schalt ben emperour after me:</L>
<L N="4190">Biforn hem alle y graunt it &thorn;e.'</L>
<L>'Alle,' he seyd, '&thorn;at &thorn;ou bedest me</L>
<L>Ichil afong,' qua&thorn; Gij, 'wi&thorn; hert fre.'</L>
<L>&THORN;e erchebischop<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. <I>erchebus|chop.</I></NOTE> come for&thorn;<MILESTONE N="129a:b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Wi&thorn; a ring, &thorn;at miche was wor&thorn;;</L>
<L N="4195">He tok it Gij, &amp; he it gan afong,</L>
<L>&amp; Gij bi-&thorn;ou&yogh;t him &thorn;an wel strong:</L>
<L>He bi&thorn;ou&yogh;t &thorn;an in his wille</L>
<L>&THORN;at Felice he schuld don vnskille;</L>
<L>He &thorn;ou&yogh;t him repent &amp; wi&thorn;-drawe,</L>
<L N="4200">Whe&thorn;er he mi&yogh;t hir<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>her</I> originally intended?</NOTE> lete o&thorn;er haue.</L>
<L>Leuer him &thorn;ou&yogh;t to han hir bodi on</L>
<L>Wi&thorn;-outen siluer &amp; gold &amp; precious ston,</L>
<L>&THORN;an alle o&thorn;er &thorn;at were o liue</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; alle &thorn;e gode men mi&yogh;t him &yogh;iue.</L>
<L N="4205">Gij sett him adoun anon,</L>
<L>&amp; seyd swiche iuel is comen him on,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he no may of &thorn;e stede gon,</L>
<L>Him &thorn;enke&thorn; his hert breke&thorn; ato.
<PB REF="00000246.tif" N="242"></L>
<L>Gij fel aswoning in &thorn;at plas,<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="3969"></L>
<L N="4210">&amp; aros vp sone after &thorn;as;</L>
<L>Gij seyd an heye to &thorn;emperour:</L>
<L>'Sir, y &thorn;e pray paramour,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;is fest deleyed be</L>
<L>Fort efsones, y bidde &thorn;e,</L>
<L N="4215">&THORN;at ich am apassed &thorn;is hache,</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;at i&cmacr;h in gode hele be.'</L>
<L>Qua&thorn; &thorn;emperour, '&thorn;at rewe&thorn; me,</L>
<L>&THORN;is sposayl schal delayed be.'</L>
<L>&THORN;ennes hij gon alle y-fere,</L>
<L N="4220">Alle sone wi&thorn; droupeand chere.</L>
<L>&THORN;at maiden wepe &amp; was sori,<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="3983"></L>
<L>For Gij no mi&yogh;t hir spousi,</L>
<L>For neuer more hij no wende</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; loue com him hende;</L>
<L N="4225">No ioie ne may comen hir inne,</L>
<L>For hij no wende him neuer winne.</L>
<L>Sche wrong hir honden &amp; wepe sore,</L>
<L>Sorwe made neuer wiman more;</L>
<L>Sche wrong hir fingres &amp; tar hir here,</L>
<L N="4230">&amp; curssed &thorn;e time &thorn;at moder hir ber,</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;e time &thorn;at hye bi&yogh;eten was;</L>
<L>Neuer woman wers nas.</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="section">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Gij is to his in y-go,<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="3987"></L>
<L>No wist noman of his wo</L>
<L N="4235">Bot him self: bi ni&yogh;t and day</L>
<L>Al a fourten ni&yogh;t sike he lay,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he no com his bed fram,<MILESTONE N="129b:a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>No out atte dore he no cam.</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="section">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Now wille we of Gij duelle,</L>
<L N="4240">&amp; of his lyoun ichil &yogh;ou telle;</L>
<L>Of his lyoun, hou he fard:</L>
<L>&THORN;er while &thorn;at Gij lay sike so hard</L>
<L>Nold he noi&thorn;er ete no drink,</L>
<L>Ac sorwe he made and gret morning.
<PB REF="00000248.tif" N="244"></L>
<L N="4245">Gij<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>j</I> in <I>Gij</I> seems altered from <I>f.</I></NOTE> cleped Herhaud him to,<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="3997"></L>
<L>&amp; alle his conseyl schewed him &thorn;o.</L>
<L>'Sir Herhaud,' he seyd, 'conseyl me:</L>
<L>Of mi<NOTE PLACE="marg">Qy. <I>&thorn;i</I>?</NOTE> conseyl ich oxi &thorn;e,</L>
<L>&YOGH;if y schal &thorn;emperours douhter take,</L>
<L N="4250">Or &yogh;ete abide for&thorn; &amp; hir for-sake.</L>
<L>Ich haue a leman in Inglond</L>
<L>(To telle &thorn;e nil y nou&yogh;t wond),</L>
<L>&THORN;erls douhter Rohaut y-wis,</L>
<L>Felice, &thorn;at feir maiden of pris.</L>
<L N="4255">O&thorn;er &thorn;an hir loue y no may,</L>
<L>Sir Herhaud, for so&thorn;e to say.'</L>
<L>Herhaud onswerd: 'ichil &yogh;ou telle</L>
<L>&THORN;e best conseyl ich haue in wille.</L>
<L>&YOGH;if &thorn;ou &thorn;emperours douhter afo</L>
<L N="4260">Riche &thorn;ou best euer mo:</L>
<L>After him &thorn;ou best emperour.</L>
<L>God ha&thorn; y-don &thorn;e gret anour:</L>
<L>In &thorn;e world ne wor&thorn; man of so gret mi&yogh;t,</L>
<L>No of so gret pouer, y pli&yogh;t.</L>
<L N="4265">More riches &thorn;e wor&thorn; bi a &thorn;ousandel</L>
<L>Bo&thorn;e of cites &amp; of riche castel,</L>
<L>Forestes ful of hertes beld,</L>
<L>&THORN;an &thorn;erl Rohaut ha&thorn; in weld.'</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="section">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'Stille be &thorn;ou,' qua&thorn; Gij, 'of &thorn;at &thorn;ou&yogh;t.<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="4023"></L>
<L N="4270">Now ich wot &thorn;ou louest me nou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>When &thorn;ou conseyls me mi leman fro.</L>
<L>Mi liif to lese, nil ich it do.'</L>
<L>'Sir,' qua&thorn; Herhaud, 'ich-il be stille,</L>
<L>When it is o&yogh;ain &thorn;i wille.</L>
<L N="4275">&THORN;at &thorn;ou hir louedest wist y nou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;o &thorn;ou of conseyl me bisou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>&THORN;e best ich wold &yogh;iue &thorn;e</L>
<L>&THORN;at ich hadde wi&thorn;-in me.</L>
<L>When &thorn;ou Felice loues so,</L>
<L N="4280">Vn-ri&yogh;t it were &amp; &thorn;ou hir for-go.'
</L>
</LG>

</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="section"><PB REF="00000250.tif" N="246">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Gij aros after &thorn;e fourtenni&yogh;t<MILESTONE N="129b:b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Glad &amp; bli&thorn;e wi&thorn; hert li&yogh;t.<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="4035"></L>
<L>He is to &thorn;e court y-come,</L>
<L>&amp; ful welcome to alle &amp; some.</L>
<L N="4285">Wi&thorn; him his lyoun to court &yogh;e[de] &thorn;o,<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. <I>&yogh;e&thorn;o.</I></NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;urch whom aros gret sorwe &amp; wo.</L>
<L>&THORN;emperour of Gij wel bli&thorn;e he was;</L>
<L>Into al &thorn;e court no no&thorn;er &thorn;er nas</L>
<L>Al bot Morgadour, sikerliche:</L>
<L N="4290">He hated Gij wel inliche.</L>
<L>For &thorn;e maiden he hadde Gij in hete.</L>
<L>Gij bileft in court atte mete,</L>
<L>Him to play &amp; solanci.</L>
<L>&THORN;o at &thorn;e court bileft sir Gij,</L>
<L N="4295">&THORN;er whiles &thorn;e king ate mete sat,</L>
<L>&THORN;e lyoun go&thorn; to play wi&thorn;-outen &thorn;e &yogh;at</L>
<L>In pais wi&thorn;-outen vilanie.</L>
<L>Herkene&thorn; now, lordinges, gladli:</L>
<L>When &thorn;emperour hadde y-hete,</L>
<L N="4300">Gode while Gij ha&thorn; bi him sete,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; him to pley in compeynie:</L>
<L>Solas he loued wi&thorn;outen vilanie.</L>
<L>&THORN;at ich while his lyoun</L>
<L>&YOGH;ede out of &thorn;e pauiloun:</L>
<L N="4305">Al abouten he is y-go,</L>
<L>For to resten him in a wro:</L>
<L>O&yogh;ain &thorn;e sonne he slepe in a stede,</L>
<L>Gret while of &thorn;e day &amp; so he dede.</L>
<L>When Gij wold his way he nam,<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="4057"></L>
<L N="4310">Vnto his in &thorn;at he cam.</L>
<L>&THORN;e lyoun no folwed him nou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>In an erber he slepe wel soft.</L>
<L>&THORN;an was &thorn;e steward goinde,</L>
<L>In-to an orchard al-on cominde.</L>
<L N="4315">Vnder a windowe he him seye</L>
<L>Wher &thorn;e lyoun lay wel neye,
<PB REF="00000252.tif" N="248"></L>
<L>For to resten him in a wro.</L>
<L>'Bi god,' qua&thorn; &thorn;e steward &thorn;o,</L>
<L>'&THORN;e lyoun li&thorn; here now slepeing,'</L>
<L N="4320">Seyd Morgadour in his &thorn;ou&yogh;t &thorn;enking.</L>
<L>A scharpe wepen &thorn;er for&thorn; he drou&yogh;,</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;e lyoun &thorn;er-wi&thorn; he slou&yogh;.</L>
<L>&THORN;e lyoun afrayd vp stert,</L>
<L>As he &thorn;at was to de&thorn; y-hert.</L>
<L N="4325">Ac a maiden &thorn;at y-seye,<MILESTONE N="130a:a" UNIT="folio"><MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="4069"></L>
<L>&amp; grad to &thorn;e steward an heye:</L>
<L>'Sir steward, &thorn;at was iuel y-smite.</L>
<L>In vnwor&thorn;schip it wor&thorn; &thorn;e at-wite.'</L>
<L>&THORN;e lyoun him go&thorn; for&thorn; groning,</L>
<L N="4330">His guttes after him draweing.</L>
<L>To Gyes in he is y-go,</L>
<L>In a chaumber he fond him &thorn;o:</L>
<L>At his fete he fel doun in &thorn;at stede,</L>
<L>To hauen of him socour at nede.</L>
<L N="4335">His hondes he gan to licky:</L>
<L>&THORN;at was his loue, sikerly.</L>
<L>When Gij &thorn;at lyoun wounded se&thorn;,<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="4085"></L>
<L>For sorwe him &thorn;ou&yogh;t his hert clef.</L>
<L>'O lord,' he seyd, 'god almi&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="4340">Who ha&thorn; &thorn;e so iuel y-di&yogh;t?</L>
<L>&THORN;at mi lyoun ha&thorn; y-slawe me,</L>
<L>Y nold it wer don for &thorn;is cite,</L>
<L>No &thorn;at &thorn;er-to bilonge.</L>
<L>So michel sorwe me ha&thorn; afong.'</L>
<L N="4345">In swiche wret&thorn;e &amp; grame anou&yogh;</L>
<L>His gode swerd wi&thorn; streng&thorn;e he drou&yogh;;<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="4107"></L>
<L>Se&thorn;&thorn;en on his stede he wond,</L>
<L>His swerd y-drawe in his hond:</L>
<L>To &thorn;e court he com prikeing.</L>
<L N="4350">Wele hij seyen bi his lokeing</L>
<L>&THORN;at he is sori &amp; swi&thorn;e wro&thorn;:</L>
<L>Alle o&yogh;aines him &thorn;ai go&thorn;.
<PB REF="00000254.tif" N="250"></L>
<L>'Lordinges,' qua&thorn; Gij, 'ich &yogh;ou biseche,</L>
<L>&YOGH;if ani of &yogh;ou me can teche,</L>
<L N="4355">Who slou&yogh; mi lyoun to-day.'</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;ai seyd, 'sir, certes, nay.'</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; &thorn;at into &thorn;e halle he come,</L>
<L>A maiden he mett &thorn;er anon.<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="4126"></L>
<L>&para; 'Sir Gij,' she seyd, 'leue swete,</L>
<L N="4360">Is &thorn;i lyoun ded, or liues &yogh;ete?</L>
<L>For &thorn;urchout smite ichim seye.'</L>
<L>&THORN;o seyd Gij: 'mi swete lef, ney,</L>
<L>Ich &thorn;e bidde, for-hele it nou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>Who ha&thorn; mi lyoun to de&thorn; y-brou&yogh;t?'</L>
<L N="4365">'Sir,' sche seyd, 'Morgadour,</L>
<L>&THORN;at is steward wi&thorn; &thorn;emperour:</L>
<L>&THORN;urch &thorn;e bodi he him smot.</L>
<L>His de&thorn; it wor&thorn;, wele y wot.'<MILESTONE N="130a:b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>When he herd &thorn;at ich feloun<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="4139"></L>
<L N="4370">Hadde y-slawe his lyoun,</L>
<L>Out of halle he gan driue</L>
<L>Fram chaumber to chaumber al-so swi&thorn;e,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; naked swerd in his hond:</L>
<L>&YOGH;if he him finde&thorn; he go&thorn; to schond.</L>
<L N="4375">Into a chaumber he com &thorn;at stounde,</L>
<L>&amp; Morgadour sone he founde</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; his nevou in conseyl fast:</L>
<L>When &thorn;ai seye Gij &thorn;ai weren agast.</L>
<L>Gij seyd: '&thorn;ou me hast bitreyd</L>
<L N="4380">When &thorn;ou to grounde mi lyoun leyd.</L>
<L>No dede ich &thorn;e neuer bot gode,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou fel treytour, vnkinde blod.'</L>
<L>&para; Morgadour answerd anon,</L>
<L>Stalwor&thorn; kni&yogh;t as he was on:</L>
<L N="4385">'&THORN;ou lexst amidward &thorn;i te&thorn;,</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;er-fore haue &thorn;ou maugre&thorn;.</L>
<L>Whi berstow me on treysoun,</L>
<L>&THORN;at ich haue sleyn &thorn;i lioun?'
<PB REF="00000256.tif" N="252"></L>
<L>Gij wi&thorn; his kniif smite he wold,</L>
<L N="4390">Ac Gij him suffri nold:</L>
<L>His swerd anon vp he hef,</L>
<L>Morgadour doun ri&yogh;t he clef</L>
<L>Fram &thorn;e heued doun to &thorn;e fot:</L>
<L>Of &thorn;at stroke no com him neuer bot.</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="section">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="4395">When his nevou y-seye &thorn;at cas,<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="4155"></L>
<L>&THORN;at his em<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>nevou</I> MS, <I>eme</I> Turnbull.</NOTE> so smiten was,</L>
<L>Him to awreke him &thorn;ou&yogh;t long,</L>
<L>&amp; as he schuld his dart afong,</L>
<L>His arme atvo smot Gij,</L>
<L N="4400">&amp; he him anon crid merci.</L>
<L>Gij for rew&thorn;e is &thorn;ennes y-gcn,</L>
<L>&amp; cam to &thorn;emperour anon,</L>
<L>&amp; se&thorn;&thorn;e he seyd to &thorn;emperour:</L>
<L>'Ich haue &thorn;e serued wi&thorn; gret honour;</L>
<L N="4405">&YOGH;olden &thorn;ou hast me iuel mi while,</L>
<L>When &thorn;i folk &thorn;urch tresoun &amp; gile</L>
<L>Haue mi lyoun to de&thorn; y-brou&yogh;t.</L>
<L>Mi while is iuel &yogh;alt: he it ha&thorn; abou&yogh;t.</L>
<L>For so&thorn;e he me to &thorn;e biwreyd,</L>
<L N="4410">&amp; now to grounde mi lyoun is leyd.</L>
<L>Ded he li&thorn;e al to-hewe<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>alto hewe</I> MS.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;i steward, at wordes fewe:</L>
<L>Wele ich haue &yogh;olden him his treysoun,<MILESTONE N="130b:a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;at he slou&yogh; mi lyoun.</L>
<L N="4415">Se&thorn;&thorn;e &thorn;ou no mi&yogh;t nou&yogh;t waranti me,</L>
<L>Whar-to schuld y serui &thorn;e,</L>
<L>On oncou&thorn;e man in thi lond,</L>
<L>When &thorn;ou no dost him bot schond?</L>
<L>Harm me is, &amp; michel misdo;</L>
<L N="4420">&THORN;er-fore ichil fram &thorn;e go,</L>
<L>&amp; in o&thorn;er cuntres serue y wile,</L>
<L>&THORN;er men wille &yogh;eld me mi while.'</L>
<L>'Merci, sir Gij,' seyd &thorn;emperour &thorn;o.</L>
<L>'&YOGH;if ani of our ha&thorn; &thorn;e misdo,<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="4185">
<PB REF="00000258.tif" N="254"></L>
<L N="4425">Swiche ri&yogh;t do als tow wilt,</L>
<L>&amp; take &thorn;e amendes after &thorn;e gilt;</L>
<L>For alle &thorn;ai schul be &thorn;ine men [an]on,</L>
<L>In &thorn;i nede serue &thorn;e ichon,</L>
<L>&amp; at &thorn;i wille take her catel.</L>
<L N="4430">Wi&thorn;-drawe &thorn;i mod, sir, y bidde<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>i</I> in <I>bidde</I> altered from <I>e?</I></NOTE> &thorn;e wel:</L>
<L>Ich wil &thorn;atow to-morwen arly</L>
<L>Mi douhter at &thorn;e chirche spousy.'</L>
<L>&para; Gij answerd: '&thorn;erof speke nou&yogh;t:<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="4193"></L>
<L>Hir to nim nam ich nou&yogh;t bi&thorn;ou&yogh;t;</L>
<L N="4435">For, &yogh;if &thorn;ou haddest me hir &yogh;iue,</L>
<L>&amp; ich hir toke &thorn;er whiles y liue,</L>
<L>&THORN;an wold &thorn;i men anon,</L>
<L>&THORN;at wonderful be mani on,</L>
<L>&THORN;e seggen wi&thorn; deshonour</L>
<L N="4440">&THORN;ou haddest made a pouer man emperour,</L>
<L>&amp; vnwor&thorn; &thorn;ai wold holden of me,</L>
<L>&amp; sum edwite &thorn;er wold be</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;i douhter desperplid were,</L>
<L>&YOGH;if &thorn;ou to me hadde &yogh;iuen <NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>me h.</I> <I>&yogh;</I>. on an erasure.</NOTE>her here.</L>
<L N="4445">Leuer ich hadde litel wi&thorn; wor&thorn;schipe</L>
<L>&THORN;an michel welden wi&thorn; schenschipe.</L>
<L>&THORN;er-fore, sir emperour, y &thorn;e telle,</L>
<L>In non maner bileuen y nille.</L>
<L>Whende ichil in-to mi cuntre,</L>
<L N="4450">Mine frendes to visite &amp; to se.'</L>
<L>Leue he toke wi&thorn; &thorn;at speche,</L>
<L>&amp; seyd, 'godes sone y &thorn;e biteche.'</L>
<L>When &thorn;emperour wi&thorn;-holden him no may<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="4209"></L>
<L>(He se&thorn; his wille is to wende o-way),</L>
<L N="4455">Wepen he gan wi&thorn; his ey&yogh;en tvo:</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;o of &thorn;e court dede al-so.</L>
<L>His grete tresour he dede for&thorn; bring,<MILESTONE N="130b:b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&amp; bede it Gij to his likeing,</L>
<L>Ac &thorn;erof liked him nou&yogh;t to take:</L>
<L N="4460">Anou&yogh; he hadde of<NOTE PLACE="marg">One letter erased after <I>of.</I></NOTE> Sarrazins blake.
<PB REF="00000260.tif" N="256"></L>
<L>Al-so a gode man dede &thorn;emperour &thorn;ere:</L>
<L>&THORN;er-after to alle Gyes fere</L>
<L>Riche tresour &thorn;an &yogh;af he,</L>
<L>Gold and siluer gret plente,</L>
<L N="4465">As miche as &thorn;ai wold vnder-fo;</L>
<L>For &thorn;emperour it comend so.</L>
<L>Gret [pris] &thorn;ai &yogh;eue &thorn;emperour,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he was man of gret honour.</L>
<L>Gij di&yogh;t him wi&thorn; riche dubbeing,</L>
<L N="4470">Riche wede he dede for him bring.</L>
<L>Of &thorn;emperour he toke his leue,</L>
<L>&amp; he al wepend it him &yogh;eue,</L>
<L>&amp; alle &thorn;e kni&yogh;tes of the cite,</L>
<L>Of euerichon leue nam he.</L>
<L N="4475">&THORN;er mi&yogh;t men se sorwe make,</L>
<L>For sir Gij wold fram hem rake;</L>
<L>Wimen &amp; children mani on,</L>
<L>For him &thorn;ai wepen euerichon:</L>
<L>&THORN;er whiles he was in her ferred,</L>
<L N="4480">Of no wer no stode hem drede.</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;emperour cleped Herhaud him to,<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="4229"></L>
<L>&amp; aresound him tvene hem tvo:</L>
<L>'Sir Herhaud, &thorn;ou schalt bileue wi&thorn; me.</L>
<L>Wele ich &thorn;e sigge, &amp; siker &thorn;ou be,</L>
<L N="4485">&THORN;at ich in &thorn;is &yogh;ere wille &yogh;iue &thorn;e</L>
<L>&THORN;e richest honour &thorn;at in mi lond be.'</L>
<L>'Sir,' qua&thorn; Herhaud, 'gramerci!</L>
<L>Wele &yogh;e wite icham wi&thorn; sir Gij.</L>
<L>Y no wil depart him fro</L>
<L N="4490">For non honour men may me do.'</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="section">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Sir Gij to his in is y-go,</L>
<L>&amp; areliche amorwe he aros &thorn;o:</L>
<L>Into Inglond he went, god itot,</L>
<L>Ac when &thorn;emperour &thorn;at so&thorn;e wot,</L>
<L N="4495">&THORN;at Gij &thorn;e curteys is y-go,</L>
<L>At his hert him was ful wo;
<PB REF="00000262.tif" N="258"></L>
<L>So was Blauncheflour<NOTE PLACE="marg">So MS.</NOTE> &thorn;e schene:</L>
<L>For his loue sche &thorn;oled tene.</L>
<L>Toward Inglond is Gij y-drawe,</L>
<L N="4500">&amp; wi&thorn; him Herhaud, his gode felawe.</L>
<L>Swi&thorn;e hastiliche &thorn;ai gun ride,<MILESTONE N="131a:a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&THORN;e weder was hot in somers tide.</L>
<L>&para; In May it was also ich wene,<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="4255"></L>
<L>When floures sprede &amp; springe&thorn; grene:</L>
<L N="4505">Into a forest sir Gij is go</L>
<L>Neye a cite, nou&yogh;t fer &thorn;er-fro.</L>
<L>&THORN;an seyd Gij to his meyney:</L>
<L>'Wende&thorn; swi&thorn;e wel an heye,</L>
<L>Mine in to nim<NOTE PLACE="marg">There seems to be a stroke too many (<I>ninn</I> or <I>niun</I>) in the MS.</NOTE> in &thorn;e cite;</L>
<L N="4510">Ich wil a while here pleye me,</L>
<L>For to here &thorn;e foules singe.'</L>
<L>&THORN;er-in was &thorn;o his likeinge.</L>
<L>His folk he do&thorn; fram him go,</L>
<L>Alon bileft sir Gij &thorn;o:</L>
<L N="4515">Hadde he noi&thorn;er knaue no grome,</L>
<L>Seriaunt no squier non.</L>
<L>Selcou&thorn;e it was for to here:</L>
<L>In priue stede stode Gij &thorn;ere;</L>
<L>So michel he herd &thorn;o foules sing,</L>
<L N="4520">&THORN;at him &thorn;ou&yogh;t he was in gret longing.</L>
<L>So mani &thorn;inges he of &thorn;ou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>&THORN;at out of his ri&yogh;t way him brou&yogh;t.</L>
<L>So long for&thorn; he is rideing,</L>
<L>In his weye for&thorn; secheing,</L>
<L N="4525">&THORN;at o groning fram fer he herd:</L>
<L>He of-list, &amp; thider he ferd.</L>
<L>&THORN;e mening seyd, 'allas, allas,</L>
<L>&THORN;at ich was born for swiche trespas!</L>
<L>Ac now is me iuel bifelle:</L>
<L N="4530">De&thorn;, whi wiltow so long duelle?'</L>
<L>&THORN;iderward sir Gij him drou&yogh;,</L>
<L>And loked vnder an hawe-&thorn;orn bou&yogh;.<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="4275">
<PB REF="00000264.tif" N="260"></L>
<L>&THORN;e bodi he seye of a kni&yogh;t:</L>
<L>&THORN;erof he hadde wonder, apli&yogh;t.</L>
<L N="4535">Feir &amp; michel he him se&thorn;:</L>
<L>Gij &thorn;enke&thorn; michel, &amp; nou&yogh;t no sey&thorn;.</L>
<L>&THORN;at hors he prike&thorn;, &amp; for&thorn; he go&thorn;:</L>
<L>&THORN;at bodi he bihalt inliche forso&thorn;.</L>
<L>His barbel first adoun he de&thorn;,</L>
<L N="4540">Wi&thorn;-outen colour his neb he se&thorn;</L>
<L>For &thorn;e blod he hadde for-lore,</L>
<L>&THORN;at of his bodi he hadde for&thorn; bore.</L>
<L>Y-girt he was wi&thorn; a gode swerd,</L>
<L>&THORN;at was wele kerueand doun to &thorn;e uerd.<NOTE PLACE="marg">Read <I>nerd</I>?</NOTE></L>
<L N="4545">Wele he was y-armed gentilliche.<MILESTONE N="131a:b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Gij of him hadde reu&thorn;e miche:<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="4303"></L>
<L>His name he asked sweteliche,</L>
<L>Who him biseye so reweliche.</L>
<L>'What is &thorn;i name? where wer &thorn;ou bore?</L>
<L N="4550">&amp; who ha&thorn; y-wounded &thorn;e so sore?</L>
<L>Ich &thorn;e bidde &thorn;atow say me,</L>
<L>&amp; for so&thorn;e y pli&yogh;t &thorn;e</L>
<L>For me schaltow harm haue non.</L>
<L>Who ha&thorn; &thorn;e &thorn;us iuel bi-gon?'</L>
<L N="4555">He answerd, '&thorn;at wille y nou&yogh;t.</L>
<L>In mine hert is swiche sorwe brou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>&THORN;at y dar schewe &thorn;e no speche.</L>
<L>Lete me dye, y &thorn;e biseche.</L>
<L>So michel sigge y &thorn;e, sir kni&yogh;t,<NOTE PLACE="marg">The <I>k</I> looks as if the scribe had begun to write a <I>g</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L N="4560">&YOGH;if &thorn;ou wilt pli&yogh;t me anon ri&yogh;t</L>
<L>&THORN;i treu&thorn;e in hond mine,</L>
<L>Siker &thorn;ou be &thorn;at al mi pine</L>
<L>&amp; alle mine estris ichil telle &thorn;e;</L>
<L>Elles no wostow it nou&yogh;t for me.'</L>
<L N="4565">His treu&thorn;e sone he him pli&yogh;t,</L>
<L>His liif he teld him anon ri&yogh;t.</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="section">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Now he seyd: 'sir kni&yogh;t fre,<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="4337"></L>
<L>Mi name<NOTE PLACE="marg">added above the line in the same hand.</NOTE> y &thorn;e telle, &amp; whennes y be.
<PB REF="00000266.tif" N="262"></L>
<L>Of Gormoise icham cleped Tirri,</L>
<L N="4570">&THORN;eld erls sone Aubri.</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; &thorn;e douke of Loreyne ichaue y-be.</L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L>A feir douhter &thorn;an hadde he:</L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L N="4575">Ouer alle o&thorn;er we loueden ous,</L>
<L>&amp; for loue treu&thorn;e pli&yogh;ten &thorn;us.</L>
<L>For non o&thorn;er sche nold me lete,</L>
<L>No y no loued<NOTE PLACE="marg">The <I>d</I> above the line in the same hand.</NOTE> non bot &thorn;at swete</L>
<L>In godes lawe, for so&thorn;e y-wis:</L>
<L N="4580">Swiche a<NOTE PLACE="marg">A letter erased before <I>a</I>, and another after it.</NOTE> treu&thorn;e bitvix ous is.</L>
<L>Armes for hir loue y nam,</L>
<L>&amp; now y thou&yogh;t to han went ham.</L>
<L>Mi priis ichaue wide y-sou&yogh;t</L>
<L>Fram stede to o&thorn;er, no wond y nou&yogh;t.</L>
<L N="4585">&para; &THORN;an come fram hir to me a sond<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="4371"></L>
<L>&THORN;at brou&yogh;t me miche sorwe an hond,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;e douke Otus of Paui</L>
<L>Wald mi leman spousey,</L>
<L>To wham ich was treu&thorn;e-pli&yogh;t:</L>
<L N="4590">Oisel was hir name ful ri&yogh;t;</L>
<L>&THORN;at bi letters sche sent to me,<MILESTONE N="131b:a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&amp; bi toknes &thorn;at wer so fre,</L>
<L>&THORN;at, &yogh;if ich hir habbe wold,</L>
<L>&THORN;at to hir comen y schold</L>
<L N="4595">To on day &thorn;at was y-sett,</L>
<L>O&thorn;er sche wor&thorn; fro me fett.</L>
<L>To hir ward y gan spede</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; &thorn;ritti kni&yogh;tes in mi ferred:</L>
<L>Eueriche of ous his stede bistrode,</L>
<L N="4600">&amp; riden ous for&thorn; wi&thorn;outen abode,</L>
<L>Wher &thorn;e douke Otus was &amp; his ferred</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; an hundred kni&yogh;tes of gret pride,</L>
<L>&amp; wele to hundred of seriaunce</L>
<L>Of Lombardy &amp; of Fraunce,
<PB REF="00000268.tif" N="264"></L>
<L N="4605">For to spouse min owhen wiif,</L>
<L>&THORN;at y loued more &thorn;an mi liif.</L>
<L>When y &thorn;at wist y sent hir to</L>
<L>So priueliche so ich mi&yogh;t it do,</L>
<L>&THORN;at hij schuld come to me:</L>
<L N="4610">For gret loue so dede sche;</L>
<L>To me sche come &thorn;urch queyntise</L>
<L>Doun of &thorn;e castel in selcou&thorn;e wise</L>
<L>Bi on cable alle sleyeliche,</L>
<L>&THORN;at folk it no founde, sikerliche.</L>
<L N="4615">Y sett hir on a mule amblinde,</L>
<L>In &thorn;e way we dede ous rideinde.</L>
<L>Ac &thorn;er ich dede gret child-hod,</L>
<L>&THORN;at alto long y &thorn;er a-bod.</L>
<L>At our wending of &thorn;at cite</L>
<L N="4620">&THORN;e li&yogh;t day we mi&yogh;ten se:</L>
<L>&THORN;er we were y-knowen &thorn;o</L>
<L>At a brigge as we hadde go.</L>
<L>&THORN;at ich for Oisel was y-come,</L>
<L>Hir fader it was teld atte frome.</L>
<L N="4625">&THORN;urch &thorn;e cite &thorn;e crie was gradde<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="4397"></L>
<L>&THORN;e maiden was oway ladde.</L>
<L>&THORN;er mi&yogh;t men se kni&yogh;tes on hors wende,</L>
<L>&amp; me &thorn;ai of-token at &thorn;e brugge ende.</L>
<L>&THORN;er we stronglich mett wi&thorn; hem:</L>
<L N="4630">Mani we slowen of her men.</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;ai slou&yogh; mine feren,</L>
<L>&THORN;at swi&thorn;e gode kni&yogh;tes weren.</L>
<L>Me &thorn;ai come to nim snelle,</L>
<L>Ac y nold no longer duelle:</L>
<L N="4635">Ich toke mi leman on mi stede,<MILESTONE N="131b:b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&amp; ouer &thorn;at water wi&thorn; hir ich &yogh;ede.</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;at day &thorn;ai driuen me,</L>
<L>Alle fort &thorn;ai no mi&yogh;t for ni&yogh;t y-se.</L>
<L>When y was passed &thorn;e riuer ari&yogh;t</L>
<L N="4640">In hert y was glad &amp; li&yogh;t:
<PB REF="00000270.tif" N="266"></L>
<L>&THORN;at water passi &thorn;ai no durstin,</L>
<L>&THORN;an owayward turn &thorn;ai mostin.</L>
<L>In &thorn;is forest y come rideinde,<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="4441"></L>
<L>Bifor me mi leman ledeinde:</L>
<L N="4645">Y no dred robours no thef non,</L>
<L>Ac al siker ich wende for&thorn; gon.</L>
<L>What of wakeing, &amp; of fasting,</L>
<L>&amp; eke &thorn;at o&thorn;er treueyling,</L>
<L>Osleped swi&thorn;e sore ich was,</L>
<L N="4650">&amp; lay &amp; slepe in &thorn;is plas.</L>
<L>&THORN;an com fiftene outlawes strong</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; her men, &amp; here me afong.</L>
<L>Alle slepende &thorn;ai wounded me.</L>
<L>Anon ri&yogh;t nomen he</L>
<L N="4655">Mi leman, &amp; &thorn;ai han hir ladde fro me.</L>
<L>Now, sir, take &thorn;erof pite:</L>
<L>Bi &thorn;e treu&thorn;e &thorn;ou hast me pli&yogh;t,</L>
<L>Socour mi leman &yogh;if &thorn;ou mi&yogh;t,</L>
<L>&amp;, when &thorn;at ich dede be,</L>
<L N="4660">Do me birij, ich bidde &thorn;e.</L>
<L>To &thorn;at hulle &thorn;ou wende anon:<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="4471"></L>
<L>&THORN;ou hem findes &thorn;er ichon.</L>
<L>&amp; &yogh;if &thorn;at &thorn;ou so mi&yogh;ti be,</L>
<L>&THORN;atow may hem alle sle,</L>
<L N="4665">Winne &thorn;ou mi&yogh;t a maiden fre:</L>
<L>In &thorn;e warld may non feirer be.</L>
<L>&amp; &yogh;ete y may &thorn;e more telle:</L>
<L>Mi stede &thorn;ai han, &thorn;at is so snelle,</L>
<L>&THORN;at wi&thorn; streng&thorn;e in Peyneme ich wan</L>
<L N="4670">Of Solagimis, &thorn;e sone soudan.</L>
<L>&THORN;er-fore men han y-boden me</L>
<L>.Xv. castels, &amp; touns, &amp; riche cite,<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>s</I> erased after <I>cite.</I></NOTE></L>
<L>And .xv. somers of siluer &amp; of gold,</L>
<L>Ac for an hundred &yogh;iuen ichit nold.</L>
<L N="4675">Now &thorn;ou hast, sir, alle y-her<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>s</I> erased after <I>cite.</I></NOTE>,</L>
<L>Hou ich am bitreyd &amp; amerd.
<PB REF="00000272.tif" N="268"></L>
<L>Take mi scheld, &amp; mi hauberk of stiel</L>
<L>&amp; mi swerd, &thorn;at bite&thorn; wel,</L>
<L>&amp; mine armes ich am in di&yogh;t<MILESTONE N="132a:a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="4680">(For ich &thorn;e se man of miche mi&yogh;t),</L>
<L>To quite &thorn;i treu&thorn;e &thorn;ou hast y-pli&yogh;t.'</L>
<L>&THORN;an stode &thorn;er sir Gij vp-ri&yogh;t:<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="4491"></L>
<L>Wel depe in hert he ha&thorn; y-si&yogh;t.</L>
<L>Grete pite he ha&thorn; of &thorn;at kni&yogh;t:</L>
<L N="4685">He knewe Tirri for his frende,</L>
<L>&THORN;at lay &thorn;er in hard bende.</L>
<L>'Sir,' he seyd, 'bi treu&thorn;e mine</L>
<L>&THORN;at ich haue pli&yogh;t in hond &thorn;ine,</L>
<L>Euen for&thorn; mi mi&yogh;t ich-il help &thorn;e:</L>
<L N="4690">More mi&yogh;t &thorn;ou nou&yogh;t oxi me.'</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; &thorn;at ha&thorn; Gij his brond y-nome,</L>
<L>&amp; his hauberk atte frome,</L>
<L>His scheld, &amp; his o&thorn;er wede,</L>
<L>&amp; to &thorn;e hulle in gret periil he &yogh;ede.</L>
<L N="4695">A loge stonden &thorn;er he seye,</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;er wi&thorn;-outen a gode stede &amp; heye,</L>
<L>&THORN;at was to a bou&yogh; y-teyd.</L>
<L>Gij &thorn;eron his talent leyd:</L>
<L>Sterneliche prikeing he come,</L>
<L N="4700">His swerd he drou&yogh; out anon.</L>
<L>He ali&yogh;t, &amp; seyd at his cominge:</L>
<L>'&THORN;eues, &yogh;e be ded, wi&thorn;outen lesinge.<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="4507"></L>
<L>Awarid wor&thorn; &yogh;e ichon,</L>
<L>Bo&thorn;e &yogh;our flessche &amp; &yogh;our bon.</L>
<L N="4705">Whi slou&yogh; &yogh;e &thorn;at ich kni&yogh;t?</L>
<L>Alle &yogh;e schul die anon ri&yogh;t.</L>
<L>&amp; &yogh;if ani so hardi be,</L>
<L>&THORN;at hennes stir toward me,</L>
<L>Ich<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>i</I> underdotted after <I>I</I>.</NOTE> wille &yogh;ou for so&thorn;e say</L>
<L N="4710">He bes &thorn;e first &thorn;at schal day.'</L>
<L>An Almaunde he arau&yogh;t:</L>
<L>His heued of at &thorn;e first drau&yogh;t.
<PB REF="00000274.tif" N="270"></L>
<L>Ar ani of hem hem were mi&yogh;t,</L>
<L>Alle he hem slou&yogh;, y &yogh;ou pli&yogh;t.</L>
<L N="4715">&THORN;o he hadde hem slaun ichon,</L>
<L>He lepe opon his stede anon.</L>
<L>Comen he is to &thorn;at mayde,</L>
<L>Wel sweteliche to hir he seyde,</L>
<L>'Na more sori &thorn;ou no be,</L>
<L N="4720">Ac arise vp, &amp; com wi&thorn; me:</L>
<L>To &thorn;i leman y bringe &thorn;e sket</L>
<L>Vnder &thorn;e &thorn;orn &thorn;er &thorn;ou him let.'</L>
<L>Opon a mule sche war&thorn; anon,<MILESTONE N="132a:b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>To &thorn;e hawe-&thorn;orn &thorn;ai ben y-gon,<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="4525"></L>
<L N="4725">Ac &thorn;ai no haue nou&yogh;t &thorn;e kni&yogh;t y-founde:</L>
<L>Y-ladde he was owai &thorn;at stounde.</L>
<L>&THORN;o he fond him nou&yogh;t, he was sori;</L>
<L>For he wend wel sikerli</L>
<L>&THORN;at lyouns him hadde to-drawe.</L>
<L N="4730">He loked adoun vnder &thorn;e wode schawe,</L>
<L>If he ou&yogh;t y-herd loude or heye:</L>
<L>Of hors traces hy &thorn;er seye.</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;at maiden he lete &thorn;are,</L>
<L>&amp; after swi&thorn;e he is y-fare.</L>
<L N="4735">So fast he rode, &thorn;at he com neye</L>
<L>Four kni&yogh;tes he &thorn;er seye.</L>
<L>Gij of-toke sone &thorn;at ferrede,</L>
<L>&amp; seye &thorn;an kn[i]&yogh;t wi&thorn; hem lede.</L>
<L>Gij,<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>j</I> altered from <I>&thorn;</I>.</NOTE> &thorn;at heye rode on his stede,</L>
<L N="4740">&YOGH;ernne he bad &yogh;if he mi&yogh;t spede.</L>
<L>To &thorn;e kni&yogh;tes sir Gij him sade:</L>
<L>'Lordinges, &thorn;ilke lord &thorn;at &yogh;ou made,</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;e ni&yogh;t &amp; &thorn;e bri&yogh;t day,</L>
<L>&YOGH;ou do wor&thorn;schipe so wele he may.</L>
<L N="4745">&YOGH;if it be &yogh;our wille speke wi&thorn; me:</L>
<L>To mi speche vnder-stond &yogh;e.</L>
<L>Lordinges, ich haue mi treu&thorn;e y-pli&yogh;t</L>
<L>To him &thorn;at &yogh;e lede, &thorn;[i]lke kni&yogh;t,
<PB REF="00000276.tif" N="272"></L>
<L>&THORN;at biri y schal his bodi:</L>
<L N="4750">Mi treu&thorn;e y him pli&yogh;t, sikerly.</L>
<L>Al for loue ich &yogh;ou biseche</L>
<L>His bodi &thorn;at &yogh;e me biteche.'</L>
<L>&THORN;at o kni&yogh;t went to him ward,<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="4553"></L>
<L>&THORN;at was &thorn;e douke Otus steward,</L>
<L N="4755">&THORN;at hadde y-passed &thorn;e riuere</L>
<L>In a bot &thorn;at he fond &thorn;ere,</L>
<L>&amp; seyd to Gij, 'who artow?</L>
<L>Als a fole comen artow now.</L>
<L>Comestow now to aski ri&yogh;t</L>
<L N="4760">To haue &thorn;e bodi of our kni&yogh;t,</L>
<L>For his fere we nim &thorn;e snelle,</L>
<L>To &thorn;e douke Otous lede we &thorn;e wille,</L>
<L>&amp; &yogh;e schul bo&thorn;e demed be,</L>
<L>&amp; heye hong on galwe tre.'</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="section">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="4765">Gij him seyd, '&thorn;ou miseyst,<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="4565"></L>
<L>&amp;, bi mine heued, &thorn;ou it abeyst.'</L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L>Opon &thorn;e heued Gij him smot,<MILESTONE N="132b:a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="4770">Vnto &thorn;e girdel stede &thorn;at swerd bot.</L>
<L>Ano&thorn;er he smot ri&yogh;t anon,</L>
<L>Spare nold [he] neuer on.</L>
<L>Of his hors he has him feld,</L>
<L>His heued he dede fleye in &thorn;e feld.</L>
<L N="4775">Wi&thorn; &thorn;at come &thorn;e gode Hogoun,</L>
<L>&THORN;e doukes nevou Otoun<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. <I>of toun</I>.</NOTE>:</L>
<L>He smot Gij on &thorn;e scheld bifore,</L>
<L>&THORN;at neye he ha&thorn; his swerd forlore.</L>
<L>For schame he hadde of &thorn;e stroke &thorn;are</L>
<L N="4780">Gij smot Hogoun, and nou&yogh;t him for-bare:</L>
<L>Ouer-&thorn;uert &thorn;at swerd glod,</L>
<L>&amp; to-clef him wi&thorn;outen abod.</L>
<L>Wharto schuld y make tale of nou&yogh;t?</L>
<L>Alle he ha&thorn; hem to de&thorn; y&middot;brou&yogh;t.
<PB REF="00000278.tif" N="274"></L>
<L N="4785">He nam Tirri in his armes anon,</L>
<L>&amp; sett him his hors opon.</L>
<L>To &thorn;at hawe-&thorn;orn he is y-fare,</L>
<L>&THORN;an<NOTE PLACE="marg">Looks like <I>an</I> at first sight, the <I>&THORN;</I> being partially covered by the ornaments of the large <I>L</I> in the next line.</NOTE> fond he nou&yogh;t &thorn;at maiden &thorn;are.</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="section">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Lete we now of Gij be stille:<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="4587"></L>
<L N="4790">More &yogh;e schul here &yogh;if &yogh;e wille</L>
<L>Of &thorn;at maiden, hou sche was nome:</L>
<L>&THORN;an schal we til our tale come.</L>
<L>Of Gyes felawes y wille &yogh;ou telle</L>
<L>So y finde in mi spelle,</L>
<L N="4795">&THORN;at so long were in &thorn;e cite,</L>
<L>Wonder hem &thorn;enke&thorn; where Gij be;</L>
<L>For &thorn;e mete was alle &yogh;are,</L>
<L>Wonder hem &thorn;ou&yogh;t wer Gij ware.</L>
<L>&para; Herhaud of Ardern &amp; o&thorn;er mo<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="4597"></L>
<L N="4800">In-to &thorn;e forest &thorn;ai ben y-go:</L>
<L>&THORN;ai mi&yogh;t [him] finde for no secheing.</L>
<L>Herhaud cast sone his lokeing:</L>
<L>Biside him he herd<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>a wiman</I> under|dotted after <I>herd</I></NOTE> a<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>a</I> above the line</NOTE> mening,</L>
<L>Also it were a woman schricheing.</L>
<L N="4805">Hye bi-gan loude to grede:</L>
<L>Herhaud ney&yogh;ed &amp; his ferrede.</L>
<L>&THORN;e hawe&thorn;orn &thorn;ai &yogh;ede wel neye,</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;e maiden &thorn;er &thorn;ai seye.</L>
<L>Herhaud hir oxed what hij was;</L>
<L N="4810">Sche no told him nou&yogh;t al her cas,</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;at sche was a wriche wiman</L>
<L>&THORN;at michel sorwe so was an;</L>
<L>For alle &thorn;at sorwe &thorn;an hade he,<MILESTONE N="132b:b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>For sche no mi&yogh;t hir leman se.</L>
<L N="4815">Sche forbede him anon ri&yogh;t</L>
<L>&THORN;at noman sett on hir si&yogh;t.</L>
<L>Herhaud tok &thorn;at mayde wi&thorn; him,</L>
<L>&amp; ladde hir hom to his in.</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="section">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Now wende we o&yogh;ain to our spelle,<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="4617"></L>
<L N="4820">&THORN;at &yogh;e me herd er &thorn;an telle
<PB REF="00000280.tif" N="276"></L>
<L>Of Gij and Tirri, &thorn;erls sone,</L>
<L>Hou &thorn;ai ben to &thorn;e hawe-&thorn;orn come.</L>
<L>When hij &thorn;ider y-comen were,</L>
<L>No fond hij nou&yogh;t &thorn;e maiden &thorn;ere.</L>
<L N="4825">Gij bileft &thorn;er sir Tirri,</L>
<L>&amp; sou&yogh;t &thorn;at maiden bi &amp; bi:</L>
<L>Op and doun he &yogh;ede hir secheinde,</L>
<L>&amp; sorwefulliche hir bimeninde.</L>
<L>He wende sche were stole wi&thorn; outlawe,</L>
<L N="4830">O&thorn;er wi&thorn; wilde bestes y-drawe.</L>
<L>For hir in hert him was ful wo,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he no wist what to do:</L>
<L>No wist he what do he mi&yogh;t,</L>
<L>To &thorn;e cite he went anon ri&yogh;t;</L>
<L N="4835">When he hir finde no may,</L>
<L>Homward he most take &thorn;e way.</L>
<L>&THORN;an toke he &thorn;at kni&yogh;t:</L>
<L>On his stede nek he sett him ri&yogh;t.</L>
<L>Y-comen he is to &thorn;e cite:</L>
<L N="4840">His men al sori finde&thorn; he,</L>
<L>&amp;, when hij her lord seye come,</L>
<L>Bli&thorn;e &thorn;ai were alle &amp; some.</L>
<L>'Lordinges,' he seyd, 'nime&thorn; &thorn;is bodi,</L>
<L>&amp; to &thorn;e grounde it lay wel softli.'</L>
<L N="4845">&THORN;e bodi &thorn;ai toke of &thorn;at kni&yogh;t,</L>
<L>Opon a pal leyd it anon ri&yogh;t.</L>
<L>Gij ha&thorn; of-sent leches &thorn;ere,</L>
<L>&THORN;e wisest &thorn;at in &thorn;at cite were.</L>
<L>'Lordinges,' he seyd, 'vnderstond to me.</L>
<L N="4850">&YOGH;if &yogh;e &thorn;is kni&yogh;t &thorn;at &yogh;e here se,</L>
<L>May on him his woundes hele,</L>
<L>It wor&thorn; &yogh;ou &yogh;olden eueridele.</L>
<L>&YOGH;if he dede or liues be,</L>
<L>Ich bi-hot &yogh;ou, min frende fre,</L>
<L N="4855">Him to hele &yogh;our mi&yogh;t &yogh;e do:</L>
<L>An hundred besaunce y &yogh;if &thorn;er-to.'
<PB REF="00000282.tif" N="278"></L>
<L>&THORN;ai groped his veynes &amp; his wounde,<MILESTONE N="133a:a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&THORN;ai feld hem bo&thorn;e hole &amp; sounde:</L>
<L>Wele hii se&thorn; he nis nou&yogh;t dede.</L>
<L N="4860">&THORN;e leches taken hem to rede,</L>
<L>In forward hele him &thorn;ai wille,</L>
<L>In non maner lete &thorn;ai nille.</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;erwhiles of-herd sir Gij<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="4631"></L>
<L>Noise, &amp; wepe, &amp; wel gret crie.</L>
<L N="4865">His chaumberleyn he cleped him to,</L>
<L>&amp; alle in wret&thorn;e he oxed him &thorn;o</L>
<L>Who it was &thorn;at noise made.</L>
<L>'Bid hem alle be bli&thorn;e &amp; glade.'</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="section">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'Sir,' he seyd, 'a maiden it is</L>
<L N="4870">&THORN;at Herhaud fond, wel feir, y-wis,</L>
<L>Vnder an hawe-&thorn;orn in &thorn;e forest.'</L>
<L>Qua&thorn; Gij, 'fete hir to me in hast,</L>
<L>Swi&thorn;e &thorn;at ich mi&yogh;t hir se.</L>
<L>Now hastiliche bringe&thorn; hir to me.'</L>
<L N="4875">&THORN;e chaumberleyn is for&thorn; y-gon,</L>
<L>&amp; brou&yogh;t hir bi-forn hem anon.</L>
<L>Gij hir knewe, &amp; gan hir gret,</L>
<L>'Welcome be &thorn;ou, mi lef swete,'</L>
<L>As sche was into &thorn;e halle y-come,</L>
<L N="4880">Wepeinde &amp; sorwende vnder-nome.</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; &thorn;at hij seye &thorn;at bodi, y-wis,<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="4645"></L>
<L>Liggend on a pal of pris.</L>
<L>&para; 'A, leman Tirri,' qua&thorn; sche &thorn;o,</L>
<L>'What, y se &thorn;i neb al blo,</L>
<L N="4885">&THORN;at so white of colour was:</L>
<L>&THORN;i better neuer y-born nas.</L>
<L>In wroched time mi bodi &thorn;ou say,</L>
<L>When &thorn;ou schalt for me day.</L>
<L>Dye ich-il for&thorn; wi&thorn; &thorn;e:</L>
<L N="4890">For sorwe liues no may y be.</L>
<L>Bot y may dye ichil me quelle:</L>
<L>Leng<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>e</I> seems altered from <I>i</I>.</NOTE> to libbe is nou&yogh;t mi wille.
<PB REF="00000284.tif" N="280"></L>
<L>Se&thorn;&thorn;en &thorn;ou hast &thorn;i de&thorn; for me,</L>
<L>For so&thorn;e dye ich-il for &thorn;e.'</L>
<L N="4895">When sche seye Tirri, hir leman,</L>
<L>Ouer him sche fel aswon onan.</L>
<L>Gij hir in his armes nam,</L>
<L>&amp; seyd to hir, 'mi leue leman,</L>
<L>No make &thorn;ou nou&yogh;t sorwe so miche:</L>
<L N="4900">&THORN;i leman wor&thorn; hole hastiliche.'</L>
<L>In &thorn;at cite &thorn;ai bi-leued &thorn;ere<MILESTONE N="133a:b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>What Tirry was hole &amp; fere.</L>
<L>To &thorn;e wode &thorn;ai ben y-go:</L>
<L>Miche loue was bitven hem to.</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="section">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="4905">On a day, as &thorn;ai com fram hunting,<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="4691"></L>
<L>Gij seyd to Tirry, wi&thorn;-outen lesing:</L>
<L>'Ich wil &thorn;at we be treu&thorn;e-pli&yogh;t</L>
<L>&amp; sworn bre&thorn;er anon ri&yogh;t.</L>
<L>Tirri,' seyd to sir Gyoun,</L>
<L N="4910">'Vnder-stond now to mi resoun,</L>
<L>&THORN;at noi&thorn;er o&thorn;er<NOTE PLACE="marg">Read <I>oure</I>?</NOTE> after &thorn;is</L>
<L>No faile o&thorn;er while he liues is.'</L>
<L>&para; Wi&thorn; &thorn;at answerd &thorn;erl Tirri,</L>
<L>&amp; seyd, 'wel ble&thorn;elich, sir Gij.</L>
<L N="4915">Now &thorn;ou louest so miche me,</L>
<L>&THORN;at tow mi sworn bro&thorn;er wil be,</L>
<L>No wille ich neuer feyle &thorn;e</L>
<L>For nou&yogh;t &thorn;at mai bi-falle me.</L>
<L>Gret wor&thorn;schip &thorn;ou hast don me:</L>
<L N="4920">God leue me &yogh;ete &thorn;an day y-se</L>
<L>&THORN;at ichit &thorn;e mow wele &yogh;eld.</L>
<L>For gode baroun &thorn;ou art y-held;</L>
<L>Fram de&thorn; &thorn;ou hast y-warist me;</L>
<L>Wel gret wrong it schuld be</L>
<L N="4925">Bot ich &thorn;e loued as mi lord fre.</L>
<L>Wel gret wor&thorn;schip ich ou&yogh;t bere &thorn;e.'</L>
<L>Treu&thorn;e bitven hem is pli&yogh;t,</L>
<L>&amp; after kist anon ri&yogh;t.
<PB REF="00000286.tif" N="282"></L>
<L>Se&thorn;&thorn;en &thorn;ai went in-to &thorn;e cite</L>
<L N="4930">Wi&thorn; ioye &amp; mir&thorn;e, gamen &amp; gle.</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="section">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Now Gij him make&thorn; him alle &yogh;are<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="4721"></L>
<L>Into Inglond for to fare.</L>
<L>Tirri he wald lede wi&thorn; him &thorn;e</L>
<L>&amp; Oysel, his leman, &thorn;at he loued so.</L>
<L N="4935">To &thorn;e king &thorn;ai wold hem aqueynti,</L>
<L>&amp; gode &thorn;rowe wi&thorn; him soiornni.</L>
<L>Biteche he him wille his castels alle,</L>
<L>So he him bi&thorn;ou&yogh;t, &yogh;if it mi&yogh;t falle.</L>
<L>&para; It was opon a somers day,<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="4729"></L>
<L N="4940">Gij out at a windowe lay.</L>
<L>To Tirri he spac of her fare,</L>
<L>Of her wele &amp; of her care.</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; &thorn;at com prikeing anon ri&yogh;t</L>
<L>A kni&yogh;t: he semed wele, apli&yogh;t,<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>apli&yogh;t</I> not quite distinct.</NOTE><MILESTONE N="133b:a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="4945">Wele he semed he treuaild were.</L>
<L>Gij anon clept to him &thorn;ere:</L>
<L>'Sir kni&yogh;t,' he seyd, 'whennes comestow?</L>
<L>&amp; what &thorn;ou sechest telle me now.'</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;e kni&yogh;t answerd, 'ich-il<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>jich il</I> MS.</NOTE> &thorn;e telle,</L>
<L N="4950">&amp; nou&yogh;t &thorn;erof ley&yogh;en y nille.</L>
<L>Tirri of Gurmoise y go secheinde,</L>
<L>&THORN;erl sone Aubri wele doinde.</L>
<L>In mani londes ich haue him sou&yogh;t.'</L>
<L>'Wharto?' qua&thorn; Gij, 'hele it nou&yogh;t.'</L>
<L N="4955">'Sir,' qua&thorn; he, 'y telle &thorn;e sone</L>
<L>Of a gret sorwe, &thorn;at is y-done.</L>
<L>Tirri serued &thorn;e douke Loyere:</L>
<L>&THORN;e douke him loued, and held him dere,</L>
<L>&amp; &yogh;af him armes wi&thorn; gret honour:</L>
<L N="4960">Kni&yogh;t he bicome of gret valour.</L>
<L>&THORN;e douke hadde a feir douhter for &thorn;e meistri,</L>
<L>&THORN;at was y-&yogh;ouen to &thorn;e douke of Paui:</L>
<L>Tirri hir loued &amp; oway ladde,</L>
<L>Whar-&thorn;urch mani man &thorn;e de&thorn; hadde.
<PB REF="00000288.tif" N="284"></L>
<L N="4965">Wi&thorn; streng&thorn;e him folwed kni&yogh;tes bliue:</L>
<L>Y not wher he be &yogh;ete oliue.</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;e douke Loyer bi&thorn;ou&yogh;t him &thorn;o<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="4765"></L>
<L>Opon his fader for to go.</L>
<L>&THORN;e douke Loyer wi&thorn; him ladde</L>
<L N="4970">&THORN;e douke of Paui &thorn;ider he hadde</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; his gode cheualrie,</L>
<L>&THORN;e best of al Lombardye.</L>
<L>In Gormoise &thorn;erl bisett han he,</L>
<L>And destrud alle his cuntre.</L>
<L N="4975">Bot god me leue Tirri finde,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he be his fader helpinde,</L>
<L>Al his lond him tit for-go:</L>
<L>No schal he it o&yogh;ain win neuer mo.</L>
<L>His fader no may armes weld,</L>
<L N="4980">No no lenge help himself for eld.'</L>
<L>&para; 'Sir kni&yogh;t,' &thorn;an seyd sir Gij,<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="4777"></L>
<L>'Her wi&thorn; ous &thorn;ou schalt herberwei,</L>
<L>&amp; of &thorn;erl Tirri telle y &thorn;e</L>
<L>&YOGH;if ich ou&yogh;t can, mi frende fre.'</L>
<L N="4985">'Gramerci, sir,' &thorn;an seyd he.</L>
<L>'Of him to here leue war me.'</L>
<L>Gij hete his folk hastiliche</L>
<L>&THORN;at hye him vnder-feng curteysliche.</L>
<L>'Ich-il &thorn;e telle,' qua&thorn; sir Gij,<MILESTONE N="133b:b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="4990">'&THORN;at y can of &thorn;erl Tirri.'</L>
<L>When &thorn;ai hadde d[r]onken in &thorn;e halle,</L>
<L>&amp; glad &thorn;ai were, y telle &yogh;ou, alle,</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;an seyd &thorn;erl Tirri:</L>
<L>'For loue y bidde &thorn;e, sir Gij,</L>
<L N="4995">O&yogh;ain to mi cuntre com wi&thorn; me,</L>
<L>Als-so we sworn bre&thorn;er be,</L>
<L>Mi fader to help &thorn;at we spede;</L>
<L>For of help he ha&thorn; gret nede.'</L>
<L>'Be stille,' seyd Gij, 'what seystow me?</L>
<L N="5000">&THORN;at day to god vnwor&thorn;i y be,
<PB REF="00000290.tif" N="286"></L>
<L>&YOGH;if y, sir Tirri, feyle &thorn;e,</L>
<L>&THORN;erwhiles &thorn;at ich haue liif in me.'</L>
<L>'Sir Gij,' he seyd, 'gramerci:</L>
<L>&THORN;ilke y sigge &thorn;e, sikerly.'</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="section">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="5005">Now sende&thorn; Gij after kni&yogh;tes snelle,<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="4801"></L>
<L>Almaines swi&thorn;e &amp; of gode wille</L>
<L>To him &thorn;er come gret plente:</L>
<L>Er &thorn;e twenti day y-comen be,</L>
<L>Fif hundred kni&yogh;tes hardi &amp; hende</L>
<L N="5010">To Tirri come for his frende,</L>
<L>&amp; seyd to Tirri, 'to &thorn;i fader we wil gon:</L>
<L>Wele we it au&yogh;t to don;</L>
<L>Wel redi we ben ichon.'</L>
<L>So long &thorn;ai han for&thorn; y-gon,</L>
<L N="5015">Y-comen &thorn;ai ben to Gormoise.<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="4809"></L>
<L>In &thorn;at cite was gret noise.</L>
<L>In an euening &thorn;ai com to &thorn;e cite,</L>
<L>&THORN;at hye wi&thorn;-outen aperceiued nar he.</L>
<L>Wel glad him was &thorn;erl Aubri</L>
<L N="5020">Of the cominge of his sone Tirri,</L>
<L>&amp; of sir Gyes coming,</L>
<L>&THORN;at gode kni&yogh;t was, wi&thorn;-outen lesing.</L>
<L>Her ey&yogh;en watred for gladnesse,</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;ai &yogh;ede o&yogh;ain him to kisse.</L>
<L N="5025">'Leue fader,' seyd sir Tirri,</L>
<L>'Wor&thorn;schip wele now sir Gij:</L>
<L>Felawes we ben treu&thorn;e-y-pli&yogh;t.</L>
<L>Y wil &thorn;at &yogh;e it wite now ri&yogh;t:</L>
<L>Fram de&thorn; he ha&thorn; y-heled me.'</L>
<L N="5030">Qua&thorn; &thorn;erl: 'god<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>god</I> added above the line.</NOTE> y-&thorn;onked mot it be.</L>
<L>Hennes forward alle &thorn;at min is</L>
<L>To his wille schal ben, y-wis,</L>
<L>His hest to don &amp; his wille<MILESTONE N="134a:a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Erliche &amp; lat, loude &amp; stille.</L>
<L N="5035">A wel eld man ich am, y-wis:</L>
<L>&THORN;at y bar armes tventi &yogh;er it is;
<PB REF="00000292.tif" N="288"></L>
<L>Y-lorn ich haue cheualrie:</L>
<L>Of mi lond haue &thorn;ou &thorn;e meistrie.'</L>
<L>&THORN;an y-herberwed weren he<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="4833"></L>
<L N="5040">Wor&thorn;schipliche in &thorn;at cite.</L>
<L>In &thorn;e cite gret noise is made:</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e barouns com &thorn;ai ben wel glade.</L>
<L>&THORN;er-in is now &thorn;erl Aubri,</L>
<L>So is sir Gij &amp; sir Tirri.</L>
<L N="5045">An arnmorwe aros sir Gij,</L>
<L>&amp; cleped to him his compeynie.</L>
<L>Bifor &thorn;erl &thorn;an &thorn;ai ferden,</L>
<L>&amp; a gret crie &thorn;ai herden</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e barouns of &thorn;e cite.</L>
<L N="5050">Anon oxed Gij &thorn;e fre</L>
<L>Of &thorn;at noise what it was.</L>
<L>A squier told him al &thorn;at cas:</L>
<L>'&THORN;e douke steward Loyer</L>
<L>For present he come&thorn; to iusti here</L>
<L N="5055">&YOGH;if he finde wi&thorn; whom to do,</L>
<L>&THORN;at ani kni&yogh;t durst cum him to.'</L>
<L>Sir Gij answer[d], '&yogh;if y may</L>
<L>&THORN;erof him wor&thorn; his fille to day.</L>
<L>Lordinges,' he seyd, 'ginne&thorn; &yogh;ou armi,</L>
<L N="5060">&amp; gin whe hem to asaily.</L>
<L>Sir erl Tirri,' Gij him sede,<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="4857"></L>
<L>'Take to hundred kni&yogh;tes in &thorn;i ferred:</L>
<L>&THORN;e lordinges to aseyl &yogh;e go.<NOTE PLACE="marg">This line added in the same hand at the end of the column (after l. 5076).</NOTE></L>
<L>In Herhaud &amp; in me trist also.</L>
<L N="5065">We wil abide in &thorn;is cite,</L>
<L>In &thorn;i nede we schul socour &thorn;e.'</L>
<L>Tirri nime&thorn; wi&thorn; him kni&yogh;tes</L>
<L>To hundred armed in fi&yogh;tes.</L>
<L>Out of &thorn;e cite he nam his way,</L>
<L N="5070">Mani scheld he to-drof &thorn;at day.</L>
<L>Tirri smot wi&thorn; gret mi&yogh;t</L>
<L>Opon &thorn;e helmes, &thorn;at schine bri&yogh;t.
<PB REF="00000293.tif" N="289"></L>
<L>&THORN;urch &thorn;e bodi a kni&yogh;t he bar,</L>
<L>Ded he feld him adoun &thorn;ar.</L>
<L N="5075">Ano&thorn;er lording he smot &thorn;o,</L>
<L>His hauberk nas him wor&thorn; a slo.</L>
<L>&THORN;urch his bodi &thorn;e brond went:<MILESTONE N="134a:b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Ded he feld him verrament.</L>
<L>Ich on of hem &thorn;at he toke, he slou&yogh;,</L>
<L N="5080">Were it wi&thorn; ri&yogh;t, were it wi&thorn; wou&yogh;.</L>
<L>Wel fel kni&yogh;tes &thorn;er weren y-feld,</L>
<L>&THORN;at lay long stre&yogh;te in &thorn;e feld:</L>
<L>Sum were &thorn;urch &thorn;e bodi wounde,</L>
<L>And sum lay ded opon &thorn;e grounde.</L>
<L N="5085">So wele dede &thorn;erl Tirri,</L>
<L>&amp; wi&thorn; him alle his compeynie.</L>
<L>&THORN;e lordinges &thorn;ai han so &thorn;urch-gon,</L>
<L>&THORN;at ded &thorn;ai fel mani on.</L>
<L>Tirri smot to &thorn;e constable:<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="4878"></L>
<L N="5090">Of his stede he feld him, wi&thorn;-outen fable,</L>
<L>&amp; ney he hadde him wonne in fi&yogh;t.</L>
<L>&THORN;er com an hundred kni&yogh;tes of gret mi&yogh;t:</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;ai folwed him abaundoun,</L>
<L>&amp; he mett wi&thorn; hem als a lyoun.</L>
<L N="5095">Mani heuedes he dede of fle:</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;at he smot ded most be.</L>
<L>Tirri mis-dede nou&yogh;t for &thorn;an:</L>
<L>&THORN;er he les his feren euerich man.</L>
<L>&THORN;urch streng&thorn;e of &thorn;e lordinges snelle,</L>
<L N="5100">Fif hundred of kni&yogh;tes felle,</L>
<L>Tirries felawes ben ouer-come,</L>
<L>Of-held, y-slawe, o&thorn;er y-nome.</L>
<L>Ac Tirri hem go&thorn; &thorn;an meteing</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; mani strok of his brond kerueing:</L>
<L N="5105">A fot no deyned him nou&yogh;t to fle,</L>
<L>No his stede wi&thorn;-wende o&yogh;e.</L>
<L>His feren he rescoud as a gode kni&yogh;t:</L>
<L>Mani on he feld ded anon ri&yogh;t.
</L>
</LG>

</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="section"><PB REF="00000294.tif" N="290">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;an seyd Herhaud, 'leue sir Gij,<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="4899"></L>
<L N="5110">Sestow now &thorn;e gode erl Tirri?</L>
<L>Of grete valour now so is he:</L>
<L>His better wot y non bot te.</L>
<L>Him to socour we au&yogh;t to go.'</L>
<L>Gij him answerd, 'we schul so.'</L>
<L N="5115">For&thorn; &thorn;ai &yogh;ede wi&thorn; gode welle:</L>
<L>&THORN;e lordinges hij astounded snelle.</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; &thorn;at com for&thorn; sir Gij,</L>
<L>In his hond his swerd blodi.</L>
<L>Wel heteliche he smot a kni&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="5120">His bodi he clef adoun ri&yogh;t.</L>
<L>Ano&thorn;er kni&yogh;t he smot anon,<MILESTONE N="134b:a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&THORN;at ded he feld him on &thorn;e ston.</L>
<L>Sir Gij<NOTE PLACE="marg">Added above the line.</NOTE> him smot to Gayer,</L>
<L>&THORN;at was &thorn;e doukes nevou Loyer:</L>
<L N="5125">Of his hors he ha&thorn; him feld</L>
<L>&THORN;urch Tirries<NOTE PLACE="marg">The second <I>i</I> added above the line.</NOTE> help in &thorn;e feld.</L>
<L>For he smot his felawe,</L>
<L>In &thorn;e sond he ha&thorn; him slawe.</L>
<L>Herhaud smot ano&thorn;er for&thorn;,</L>
<L N="5130">His armes was him nou&yogh;t wor&thorn;:</L>
<L>&THORN;urch his bodi &thorn;e swerd &yogh;ede;</L>
<L>Ded he feld him of his stede.</L>
<L>Ano&thorn;er he smot him as gode kni&yogh;t,</L>
<L>Of his stede he feld him doun ri&yogh;t.</L>
<L N="5135">Now &thorn;ai ginne togider smite:</L>
<L>Non no spared o&thorn;er bot lite.</L>
<L>Togider &thorn;ai smite hard wi&thorn; alle,</L>
<L>Mani on &thorn;er was ded &amp; doun falle.</L>
<L>Who &thorn;at seye &thorn;an &thorn;erl Tirri</L>
<L N="5140">Wi&thorn; his felawe sir Gi,</L>
<L>&amp; Herhaud of Arderne &thorn;e gode,</L>
<L>&THORN;at wele to smite was in his mode,</L>
<L>So mani &thorn;ai nomen &amp; feld &thorn;at day,</L>
<L>Is non &thorn;e best chese may
<PB REF="00000295.tif" N="291"></L>
<L N="5145">Of &thorn;re kni&yogh;tes so wele doinde,</L>
<L>O&yogh;ain &thorn;e Loreyns fi&yogh;ting.</L>
<L>Gij to &thorn;e steward ha&thorn; y-smite,<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="4927"></L>
<L>Of his hors he feld him wi&thorn; hete:</L>
<L>&THORN;urch streng&thorn;e of fi&yogh;t he him wan.</L>
<L N="5150">&THORN;e o&thorn;er oway fleye ich man:</L>
<L>Gij &amp; Tirri hem folwe&thorn; stron[g]liche</L>
<L>&amp; her feren,<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. <I>ferren.</I></NOTE> hardiliche.</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;ai ben ded o&thorn;er ouer-come:</L>
<L>&THORN;er bileued non vnnome.</L>
<L N="5155">Gij &amp; Tirri o&yogh;ain ben y-gon:</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; hem &thorn;ai ladde her prisouns ichon.</L>
<L>Whar-to schuld y &thorn;er-of lye?</L>
<L>&THORN;at day &thorn;ai hadde &thorn;e maistrie.</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="section">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;an com for&thorn; a kni&yogh;t &thorn;er,<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="4937"></L>
<L N="5160">&THORN;e tiding teld &thorn;e douke Loyer:</L>
<L>'Sir douk,' he seyd, 'vnder-stond to me.</L>
<L>To ben awreken now bi&thorn;enke &thorn;e.</L>
<L>Bifor Gormoise &thorn;at cite</L>
<L>On arnemorwe &thorn;an come we</L>
<L N="5165">Wi&thorn; fif hundred of gode kni&yogh;tes:<MILESTONE N="134b:b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>An acumbraunce ous come anon ri&yogh;tes.</L>
<L>Alle nomen &amp; slawen ben hye:</L>
<L>O&yogh;ein ne be&thorn; nou&yogh;t comen fourti.</L>
<L>Repeired is &thorn;erl sir Tirri,</L>
<L N="5170">Wi&thorn; him of Warwike sir Gij,<NOTE PLACE="marg">l. 5170 before 5168 in MS.</NOTE></L>
<L>Herhaud of Ardern, &thorn;e gode marchis,</L>
<L>&amp; wi&thorn; hem fif hundred kni&yogh;tes of pris,</L>
<L>&THORN;at gode ben to fi&yogh;t &amp; modi.</L>
<L>&THORN;ine kni&yogh;tes &thorn;ai han slayn bi &amp; bi.'</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="section">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="5175">&THORN;e douk answerd, 'is it so&thorn;e &thorn;is,<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="4953"></L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;erl Tirri repeired is,</L>
<L>Gij of Warwike, &amp; Herhaud also,</L>
<L>&amp; her feren, &thorn;at gode ben, mo:</L>
<L>&THORN;e fende hem ha&thorn; &thorn;ider y-brou&yogh;t.</L>
<L N="5180">To slen ous alle &thorn;ai han in &thorn;ou&yogh;t.'
<PB REF="00000296.tif" N="292"></L>
<L>&para; &THORN;an bi-spac Otus of Paui</L>
<L>(To Gij he bar gret envie):</L>
<L>'No-&thorn;ing, sir, desmay &thorn;ou &thorn;e:</L>
<L>Ful wel we schul awreken be.</L>
<L N="5185">To morwe we schal to &thorn;e cite go</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; a &thorn;ousend kni&yogh;tes &amp; mo:</L>
<L>&amp; &yogh;if &thorn;e treytours y-founden be,</L>
<L>We schul hem aseyle, y telle &thorn;e.</L>
<L>Euerichon &thorn;ai wor&thorn;en ded.'</L>
<L N="5190">Qua&thorn; &thorn;e douk, '&thorn;at is a gode red.'</L>
<L>Wel erliche &thorn;ai arisen &thorn;o,<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="4957"></L>
<L>&amp; to the cite &thorn;ai ben y-go,</L>
<L>&amp; a &thorn;ousend kni&yogh;tes in her compeynie,</L>
<L>&THORN;e best &thorn;at were in Lombardye.</L>
<L N="5195">Alle &thorn;ai &thorn;reten sir Gij,</L>
<L>Him for to slen &amp; sir Tirri.</L>
<L>To-gider fast &thorn;ai gun smite</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; swerdes &thorn;at wil wele bite.</L>
<L>Als Gij com fro chirche go,<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="4963"></L>
<L N="5200">Into a pleyne he loked &thorn;o:</L>
<L>He seye &thorn;e doukes ost was neye:</L>
<L>So mani kni&yogh;tes &thorn;er he seye.</L>
<L>&THORN;an &thorn;erl Tirri he cleped him to,</L>
<L>&amp; to him wi&yogh;tliche spac &thorn;o:</L>
<L N="5205">'Sir erl,' he seyd, 'what schal we do?</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;e ost of Loreine y se, lo,<NOTE PLACE="marg">An erasure before <I>lo</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;e ost of Loreyne wele y-di&yogh;t</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; scheldes &amp; wi&thorn; brinis bri&yogh;t.</L>
<L>&THORN;e douk of Paui is y-come,<MILESTONE N="135a:a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="5210">By his armes y knowe &thorn;at gome.</L>
<L>Y no may him<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>he</I> struck out after <I>him</I>.</NOTE> loue, he is mi fo:</L>
<L>Gret wille me come&thorn; o&yogh;ain him go.'</L>
<L>&THORN;erl seyd, 'arme we ous euerichon:</L>
<L>A &thorn;ousend kni&yogh;tes schul wi&thorn; ous gon.'</L>
<L N="5215">Gij him mett wi&thorn; &thorn;erl Iordan,<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="4995"></L>
<L>Lord he was of alle Melan.
<PB REF="00000297.tif" N="293"></L>
<L>He smot him ouer &thorn;e gilden scheld,</L>
<L>Ded he feld him in &thorn;e feld.</L>
<L>Anon he smot ano&thorn;er kni&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="5220">&THORN;at ded he feld him anon ri&yogh;t.</L>
<L>&para; Wi&thorn; &thorn;at come prike &thorn;erl Tirri,</L>
<L>&amp; mett wi&thorn; a kni&yogh;t hi&yogh;t Amori,</L>
<L>&THORN;at was &thorn;e doukes constable Otoun:</L>
<L>To de&thorn; he him smot wi&thorn; his swerd broun.</L>
<L N="5225">Ano&thorn;er he smot wi&thorn; his brond,</L>
<L>&THORN;at ded he feld him on &thorn;e sond.</L>
<L>&para; Wi&thorn; &thorn;at com prike Herhaud,</L>
<L>&amp; mett wi&thorn; Gwishard &thorn;e Mouhaut.</L>
<L>Herhaud him ha&thorn; &thorn;er afeld,</L>
<L N="5230">&THORN;at dede he lay in &thorn;e feld.</L>
<L>&THORN;emperour<NOTE PLACE="marg">Read <I>&THORN;e douk?</I></NOTE> wi&thorn; &thorn;at ginne&thorn; fle:</L>
<L>On euerich half driuen ben he.</L>
<L>Swi&thorn;e hij hem nime&thorn; &amp; quel[l]e&thorn;,</L>
<L>Bi &thorn;e pleynes &thorn;ai grede&thorn; &amp; &yogh;elle&thorn;.</L>
<L N="5235">Wel gret it was &thorn;e scomfitour:</L>
<L>To &thorn;e Lombardes bifel iuel auentour.</L>
<L>Bi &thorn;at side was Otous fleinde,</L>
<L>In his hond his swerd kerueing.</L>
<L>Now folwe&thorn; him Herhaud alle on</L>
<L N="5240">So swi&thorn;e so &thorn;e stede mi&yogh;t gon.</L>
<L>Als-so &thorn;e douk was flowen him fro,</L>
<L>&THORN;at no moder bern no seye him &thorn;o;</L>
<L>Bot Herhaud him folwed stouteliche;</L>
<L>His bodi no drad he nou&yogh;t miche.</L>
<L N="5245">Bihinden him he smewe his wede:</L>
<L>&THORN;e lasse of him was his drede.</L>
<L>'Biwende &thorn;e,' seyd Herhaud fre,</L>
<L>'&THORN;e douke of Paui, &amp; wer &thorn;ou &thorn;e</L>
<L>Of &thorn;at ich wicked felonie</L>
<L N="5250">&THORN;at &thorn;ou ous dede in Lonbardye.'</L>
<L>When &thorn;e douke Otous &thorn;is y-seye,</L>
<L>It was<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>douke</I> struck out after <I>was</I>.</NOTE> Herhaud &thorn;at after him fleye,
<PB REF="00000298.tif" N="294"></L>
<L>Hastiliche he ha&thorn; him mett,<MILESTONE N="135a:b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&amp; at a diche him bisett.</L>
<L N="5255">He smot him on &thorn;e helme bri&yogh;t,</L>
<L>A quarter of his helme doun ri&yogh;t.</L>
<L>&THORN;an seyd &thorn;e treytour, 'glotoun,</L>
<L>Dye &thorn;ou schalt wi&thorn; resoun:</L>
<L>Ich &thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>de</I> under-dotted after <I>&THORN;e</I>; read <I>do?</I></NOTE> abie in &thorn;is stede.'</L>
<L N="5260">Herhaud anon to him sede:</L>
<L>&para; '&THORN;ou lexst,' he seyd, 'vile losaniour:</L>
<L>&THORN;ou it abist, bi seyn Sauour.'</L>
<L>Herhaud a strok him rau&yogh;t</L>
<L>Opon his scheld wi&thorn; gret mau&yogh;t:</L>
<L N="5265">On &thorn;e helme &thorn;at strok glod,</L>
<L>&amp; fel on &thorn;e stede &thorn;at he on rode.</L>
<L>So he mett him in &thorn;at stede,</L>
<L>&THORN;at his stede knewele he dede.</L>
<L>Vp stirt &thorn;e stede &thorn;at was snelle:</L>
<L N="5270">&THORN;an come &thorn;er<NOTE PLACE="marg">The <I>r</I> added above the line.</NOTE> bi an hongend hille</L>
<L>&THORN;e mi&yogh;ti and &thorn;e hardi Gyoun:</L>
<L>In his hond he bar a trounsoun.</L>
<L>Otus he smot &thorn;er-wi&thorn;<NOTE PLACE="marg">The <I>r</I> added above the line.</NOTE> so,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he les his stiropes to.</L>
<L N="5275">&THORN;an seyd Gij to Otus so vnwrast:</L>
<L>'To me ward &thorn;ou wende on hast,</L>
<L>&amp; were &thorn;e of &thorn;at felonie</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ou dest me in Lombardye.'</L>
<L>Otus him went wi&thorn; gret hete:</L>
<L N="5280">&THORN;urch &thorn;e thei Gij he ha&thorn; y-smite.</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; gret hete he smot Gyoun,</L>
<L>&THORN;at his stede knewled adoun.</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="section">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&thorn;an bi&thorn;ought him sir Gij,</L>
<L>To awreke him he hadde gret hye.</L>
<L N="5285">&THORN;e douke he seyle&thorn; &thorn;ere,</L>
<L>&amp; of his helme he carf a quarter.</L>
<L>He made him a croun<NOTE PLACE="S"><I>a croun</I> written twice originally.</NOTE> brod &thorn;ere</L>
<L>As a monke &thorn;at orderd were.
<PB REF="00000299.tif" N="295"></L>
<L>Of &thorn;at helme &thorn;at swerd glod</L>
<L N="5290">Wi&thorn; &thorn;at strok wi&thorn;-outen abod.</L>
<L>Allas &thorn;at reu&thorn;e &amp; &thorn;at sorwe,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he no hadde his bodi for-corue!</L>
<L>Ac in &thorn;at maner &yogh;ete it schal wende,</L>
<L>Who so here&thorn; &thorn;is tale to &thorn;ende.</L>
<L N="5295">&THORN;er him hadde Gij his heued binome,</L>
<L>No hadde gret socour to him come,</L>
<L>An hundred kni&yogh;tes &amp; fifti,<MILESTONE N="135b:a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&THORN;at stalwor&thorn; were &amp; hardi:</L>
<L>&THORN;e douke &thorn;ai ben to socour y-come.</L>
<L N="5300">Mani Gij ha&thorn; her heuedes binome.<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>bi</I> altered from <I>y</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>Wi&thorn; &thorn;at &thorn;er com a stout Lombard,</L>
<L>Of Mohaut he was y-hoten Grimbald.</L>
<L>Gij he smot in &thorn;at stounde</L>
<L>&THORN;urch &thorn;e scholder a grete wounde.</L>
<L N="5305">Gij wold awreke him anon:</L>
<L>Opon his helme he hewe gode won.</L>
<L>&THORN;an com ten kni&yogh;tes prout,</L>
<L>&amp; Gij &thorn;ai bisett about,</L>
<L>&amp; Gij him wered wi&thorn; his brond,</L>
<L N="5310">Til &thorn;at it brac vnto his hond.</L>
<L>'Allas,' qua&thorn; Gij, '&thorn;is vn&thorn;ang!</L>
<L>Were no may y me nou&yogh;t lang.'</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;er come prikeand a prout Lombard,</L>
<L>Atte last he held him, a musard.<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. <I>auuisard</I>?</NOTE></L>
<L N="5315">Bi &thorn;e nasel he tok Gij,</L>
<L>&amp; seyd him a gret vilainie:</L>
<L>'&THORN;ou wroche glotoun losaniour,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou schalt &thorn;e &yogh;eld, bi seyn Sauour.</L>
<L>Now ichil &yogh;eld &thorn;e to prisoun</L>
<L N="5320">To mi lordes wille, &thorn;e douke Otoun.'<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. <I>of toun</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>'&THORN;ou lext,' &thorn;an Gij sede,</L>
<L>'&THORN;ou li&thorn;er bodi, so god me rede.</L>
<L>Erst &thorn;ou it schalt abigge,</L>
<L>Er &thorn;ou me in prisoun legge.'
<PB REF="00000300.tif" N="296"></L>
<L N="5325">Gij him smot so wi&thorn; his fest,</L>
<L>&THORN;at his nek-bon to-brest.</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; &thorn;at come ano&thorn;er kni&yogh;t</L>
<L>Of Fraunce y-bore, Amori he hi&yogh;t:</L>
<L>Douke Otus soudour was he,</L>
<L N="5330">For his warisoun wi&thorn; him to be.</L>
<L>'Gij,' he seyd, 'now &yogh;eld &thorn;ou &thorn;e,</L>
<L>Al sikerliche, now to me.</L>
<L>&THORN;e no tit harm litel no miche.'</L>
<L>'Y nil,' qua&thorn; Gij, 'sikerliche.</L>
<L N="5335">&YOGH;ete no drede y nou&yogh;t alle &yogh;ou.</L>
<L>Sey me, wreche, what seistow?'</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; &thorn;at come Herhaud prikeinde,</L>
<L>&amp; in his hond a swerd wele kerueinde;</L>
<L>He it brou&yogh;t to gode Gyoun.</L>
<L N="5340">&THORN;erwi&thorn; he him werd as a lyoun.</L>
<L>Gij was socourd swi&thorn;e wel,<MILESTONE N="135b:b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>When he hadde &thorn;e brond of stiel.</L>
<L>Neuer &thorn;er nas non so hardi,</L>
<L>&THORN;at enes durst com him bi.</L>
<L N="5345">Wharto schuld ich held long tale,</L>
<L>And michel speke about dualle?</L>
<L>Ac sigge ich-il so&thorn;eliche</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; fewe wordes simpeliche,</L>
<L>Gij, &amp; Herhaud, &amp; Tirri &thorn;e fre</L>
<L N="5350">Wi&thorn; her felawes, &thorn;at gode be,</L>
<L>Han ouercomen &thorn;e batayle</L>
<L>Atte nende, wi&thorn;outen faile:</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;e Lombard ben ouer-come,</L>
<L>Oway y-flowen &thorn;er be some.</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="section">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="5355">&THORN;e douk Otus oway fleye snelle,</L>
<L>Gij him drof wi&thorn; gode wille.</L>
<L>Otus him went &amp; smot sir Gij,</L>
<L>&amp; Gij opon him, sikerly.</L>
<L>Gij fonded to smite wel,</L>
<L N="5360">Ac &thorn;at swerd glod sumdel:
<PB REF="00000301.tif" N="297"></L>
<L>Bitvene &thorn;e bodi &amp; &thorn;e arsoun</L>
<L>Gyes swerd glod adoun,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;e sadel &amp; &thorn;e stede also</L>
<L>Al-to-gider he smot atvo.</L>
<L N="5365">&THORN;at he no hadde, allas, allas,</L>
<L>&YOGH;ouen him swiche ano&thorn;er so &thorn;at was!</L>
<L>Ac for vp-coming he no mi&yogh;t:</L>
<L>So gret socour him com of kni&yogh;t,</L>
<L>&THORN;at han y-socourd &thorn;e douke sone.</L>
<L N="5370">Wi&thorn; &thorn;at anon ri&yogh;t mididone</L>
<L>Gij &amp; Tirri wi&thorn;-went ben he,</L>
<L>&amp; gon o&yogh;ain to &thorn;at cite.</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; &thorn;at come Herhaud prikeinde<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="5011"></L>
<L>After &thorn;e douke, loude gredeinde.</L>
<L N="5375">'Douk,' he seyd, 'wende, &amp; were &thorn;e</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e tresoun &thorn;ou dest Gij &amp; me,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ou ous dede in Lombardye;</L>
<L>Were &thorn;e now of &thorn;at felonie.'</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="section">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;e douk wi&thorn;-went him fot hot,<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="5021"></L>
<L N="5380">&amp; wi&thorn; his brond he him smot.</L>
<L>&THORN;er &thorn;ai fou&yogh;ten togider snelle,</L>
<L>&amp; smiten strokes wi&thorn; gode wille.</L>
<L>&THORN;ai hewe on armes &amp; brini bri&yogh;t:</L>
<L>&THORN;e blod sprang out anon ri&yogh;t.</L>
<L N="5385">Bitvene hem<NOTE PLACE="marg">An erasure after hem.</NOTE> was strong fi&yogh;t;<MILESTONE N="136b:a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Ai&thorn;er no spard o&thorn;er no-wi&yogh;t.</L>
<L>&THORN;an biginne&thorn; Herhaud swi&thorn;e:</L>
<L>Bot he him wreke he is vnbli&thorn;e.</L>
<L>Fast he sayle&thorn; &thorn;e douk Otoun,</L>
<L N="5390">A quarter of his helme he smot adoun:</L>
<L>Opon his scholder &thorn;at swerd glod,</L>
<L>&amp; in he it schef an hand brod.</L>
<L>Opon his honden he dede him falle,</L>
<L>&amp; se&thorn;&thorn;e he tok him bi &thorn;e naselle:</L>
<L N="5395">Ble&thorn;eliche he wold &thorn;e heued haue nom,</L>
<L>Ac so mani kni&yogh;tes to him come,
<PB REF="00000302.tif" N="298"></L>
<L>&amp; on Herhaud &thorn;ai smiten snelle:</L>
<L>&YOGH;ernne &thorn;ai streng&thorn;ed him to quelle.</L>
<L>Herhaud mett wi&thorn; hem &thorn;ere:</L>
<L N="5400">Made he no semblaunt &thorn;at he wounded were.</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; a Lombard so mett he,<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="5045"></L>
<L>&THORN;e heued he dede fram &thorn;e bodi fle.</L>
<L>As a gode kni&yogh;t he werd him, y-wis,</L>
<L>Ac swi&thorn;e li&thorn;er bifallen him is:</L>
<L N="5405">Also he wald to &thorn;e cite go,</L>
<L>His stede dyed vnder him &thorn;o.</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; swerdes &thorn;ai smiten him &thorn;an about,</L>
<L>&amp; on his helme hard him clout.</L>
<L>&THORN;ai hewe on his helme, &thorn;at blod out ran,</L>
<L N="5410">Ac he werd him as a man.</L>
<L>Mani on he made blodi, y pli&yogh;t,</L>
<L>Of<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>f</I> altered from <I>b.</I></NOTE> Lombardes in &thorn;at fi&yogh;t.</L>
<L>A Lombard come for&thorn; wi&thorn; &thorn;an,<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="5057"></L>
<L>Richard he hete, an onwrast<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>annwrast</I> originally, but <I>o</I></NOTE> man:</L>
<L N="5415">To Herhaud he smot a strok grim</L>
<L>&THORN;urch &thorn;e scholder wi&thorn; a swerd in.</L>
<L>Herhaud wold of him be wreke:</L>
<L>On his<NOTE PLACE="marg">Two or three letters erased after <I>his</I>.</NOTE> helme a stroke he gan reke,</L>
<L>Ac he failed of him &thorn;o:</L>
<L N="5420">Opon &thorn;e arsoun &thorn;e strok gan go;</L>
<L>Ac hetelich he pli&yogh;t out &thorn;at brond,</L>
<L>&THORN;at it brak in his hond.</L>
<L>'God, what schal y do?' &thorn;an seyd he,</L>
<L>'No lenger may ich weri me.</L>
<L N="5425">A, swerd, he &thorn;at made &thorn;e</L>
<L>Of godes mou&thorn;e acursed he be.</L>
<L>Why feylestow so sone me?</L>
<L>Iuel biseyn wor&thorn; y for &thorn;e.</L>
<L>Leuer me is her to be ded,<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="5079"><MILESTONE N="136a:b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="5430">&THORN;an hy my bodi wi&thorn; hem led.'</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; &thorn;at come driuend a Lombard,</L>
<L>Attelast he held him, a couward.
<PB REF="00000303.tif" N="299"></L>
<L>By &thorn;e nasel he rau&yogh;t him &thorn;o,</L>
<L>&amp; sternliche he seyd him to,</L>
<L N="5435">'Feloun, &thorn;ou schalt it abigge:</L>
<L>Today &thorn;ou schal &thorn;ine heued her ligge.'</L>
<L>Herhaud smot him wi&thorn; his fest &thorn;o,</L>
<L>&THORN;at his nek-bon brac atvo.</L>
<L>'Ded no wor&thorn; y nou&yogh;t for &thorn;e:</L>
<L N="5440">Alle to heteliche &thorn;ou com to me.'</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="section">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>O&yogh;ainward him went sir Gij</L>
<L>So is &thorn;e gode erl Tirri.<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="5103"></L>
<L>&THORN;e Lombardes &thorn;ai han ouercome,</L>
<L>What y-slawe<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>a</I> added above the line.</NOTE> &amp; y-nome.</L>
<L N="5445">After Herhaud he asked &thorn;o,</L>
<L>Whare he is, &amp; whider y-go.</L>
<L>A kni&yogh;t it seyd him anon</L>
<L>Out of &thorn;e scomfite he was y-gon</L>
<L>Strongliche a kni&yogh;t driueing,</L>
<L N="5450">&THORN;e douk Otus bi his witeing.</L>
<L>'God, merci,' &thorn;an Gij seyd,</L>
<L>'Be mi frende ded, icham bitreyd,</L>
<L>Herhaud &thorn;at so loued me:</L>
<L>For no &thorn;ing may y comfort be.</L>
<L N="5455">Lordinges,' he seyd, 'ginne&thorn; &yogh;e to gon,</L>
<L>&amp; lede &yogh;our prisouns wi&thorn; &yogh;ou anon,</L>
<L>&amp; Herhaud ich seche wille;</L>
<L>Ni&yogh;t no day swiken y nille,</L>
<L>Liues or de&thorn;es &thorn;at ich him se:</L>
<L N="5460">&YOGH;if ich him lese wo is me.</L>
<L>Com wi&thorn; me, felawe Tirri,</L>
<L>Hastiliche Herhaud to socouri.'</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; scharp spors &thorn;ai smiten her stede,<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="5125"></L>
<L>&amp; sprongen for&thorn; so spark on glede.</L>
<L N="5465">Swi&thorn;e &thorn;ai priked, for so&thorn;e to sigge,</L>
<L>Chalaunge on Herhaud to legge.</L>
<L>At an ende of &thorn;e ost bihalt Gij &thorn;o</L>
<L>&THORN;e douk of Paui, hou he is y-go,
<PB REF="00000304.tif" N="300"></L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;at Herhaud was y-nome:</L>
<L N="5470">Gret sor was<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>sorwas</I> MS.</NOTE> at his hert y-come.</L>
<L>'God,'<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>bi</I> added before <I>god</I> in a later hand.</NOTE> qua&thorn; Gij, 'Herhaud y se</L>
<L>Among his fon: nomen is he.</L>
<L>Go we smite to hem, Tirri:<MILESTONE N="136b:a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>For dout of de&thorn; spare nil y.</L>
<L N="5475">So gode a kni&yogh;t leten y nille.'</L>
<L>Herhaud &thorn;ai socourd snelle.</L>
<L>To a Lombard smot sir Gij,<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="5139"></L>
<L>&amp; feld him &amp; his fere him by.</L>
<L>Tirri ano&thorn;er smite bigan,</L>
<L N="5480">&THORN;at ded he feld bo&thorn;e hors &amp; man.</L>
<L>Swerdes &thorn;ai drowen, wi&thorn;-outen feyle,</L>
<L>Wharwi&thorn; was wrou&yogh;t mani batayle.</L>
<L>&THORN;ai hewe and slou&yogh; wi&thorn; gret hete:</L>
<L>So mani &thorn;er &thorn;e liif forlete.</L>
<L N="5485">Herhaud &thorn;ai socourd mididone,</L>
<L>A gode swerd &thorn;ai toke him sone.</L>
<L>Toward his ost &thorn;e douke heye&thorn; bliue,<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="5151"></L>
<L>&amp; Gij after him gan driue.</L>
<L>A strok him &yogh;af sir Gyoun:</L>
<L N="5490">Bitvene &thorn;e bodi &amp; &thorn;e arsoun</L>
<L>&THORN;e dint of &thorn;at strok ali&yogh;t:</L>
<L>&THORN;e stede he smot adoun ri&yogh;t.</L>
<L>Kni&yogh;tes &thorn;an out of &thorn;at ost</L>
<L>To Gij lopen wi&thorn; michel bost:</L>
<L N="5495">&THORN;urch &thorn;at gret ost went Gij snelle</L>
<L>&THORN;e Lombardes him folwed wi&thorn; gode wille.</L>
<L>Tirri &amp; Herhaud her ost metten &thorn;ere,</L>
<L>&amp; of hem michel awonderd were,</L>
<L>Hou hij<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>hij</I> seems altered from <I>he</I>.</NOTE> fram &thorn;e ost aschaped is:</L>
<L N="5500">Of hem &thorn;ai hadden gret blis.</L>
<L>Gij, &amp; Tirri, and Herhaud also</L>
<L>O&yogh;ain to &thorn;e cite &thorn;ai ben y-go,</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;e citiseins of &thorn;at cite</L>
<L>Wel often god &thorn;onkeden he.
</L>
</LG>

</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="section"><PB REF="00000305.tif" N="301">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="5505">&THORN;e douke Otus to his pauiloun he &yogh;ede,<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="5195"></L>
<L>&amp; vnarmed him of his wede,</L>
<L>&amp; lete loken to his wounde,</L>
<L>&amp; went to &thorn;e douke Loyer in &thorn;at stounde,</L>
<L>His gret encumbraunce him telde:</L>
<L N="5510">Conseyl &thorn;er-of he wold helde.</L>
<L>&para; Gij, Herhaud, &amp; Tirri also</L>
<L>To &thorn;e cite &thorn;ai ben y-go.</L>
<L>Ioie &thorn;ai make &amp; blisse also:</L>
<L>&THORN;e ni&yogh;t is comen, &thorn;e day is go.</L>
<L N="5515">&para; Herkene&thorn; me, &yogh;e &thorn;at ben in wille,</L>
<L>Of a tresoun y schal &yogh;ou telle:</L>
<L>&THORN;at was swi&thorn;e miche traisoun,<MILESTONE N="136b:b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&amp; y-wrou&yogh;t &thorn;urch &thorn;e douke Otoun<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. <I>of toun.</I></NOTE></L>
<L>Tellen ichil of &thorn;e douke Otoun<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. <I>of toun.</I></NOTE></L>
<L N="5520">&THORN;at cruwel was &amp; feloun.</L>
<L>To &thorn;e douk Loier he is y-gon,<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="5203"></L>
<L>&amp; seyd, 'sir, herken me anon.</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;ou gode conseyl chese</L>
<L>Al &thorn;i lond &thorn;ou schalt forlese</L>
<L N="5525">&THORN;urch treytours &thorn;at ben comen herin,</L>
<L>Gij, &amp; Tirri &amp; Herhaud wi&thorn; him.</L>
<L>&YOGH;if &thorn;ou wilt here me speke,</L>
<L>&THORN;urch gile &thorn;ou schalt ben awreke:</L>
<L>O&thorn;erliker winnen hem y no may,</L>
<L N="5530">No no&thorn;er rede no can y say.</L>
<L>Man schal ben awreken of his fo</L>
<L>In what maner he may com to.'</L>
<L>&para; 'Wel lef me were gode conseyl to here,'</L>
<L>&THORN;us him answerd &thorn;e douk Loyer.</L>
<L N="5535">'Sir douke, now y bidde &thorn;e,<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="5219"></L>
<L>To &thorn;erl Aubri sende &yogh;e,</L>
<L>&amp; to his sone Tirri also;</L>
<L>Sende to sigge to hem bo</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ou wilt him &thorn;i douhter &yogh;eue,</L>
<L N="5540">Wi&thorn; him to acord while &thorn;ou liue,
<PB REF="00000306.tif" N="302"></L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;at he com hider to &thorn;e:</L>
<L>Ri&yogh;t siker &thorn;er-of may &thorn;ai be;</L>
<L>&amp;, when &thorn;ai ben farn her iurne,</L>
<L>&amp; fer fram her cuntre,</L>
<L N="5545">&THORN;e treitours &thorn;ou schalt nimen icho[n],</L>
<L>&amp; dem hem in &thorn;i court anon.</L>
<L>&amp; so michel y bid &thorn;e,</L>
<L>Gij &amp; Herhaud &yogh;iue &thorn;ou me.</L>
<L>&amp; so &thorn;ou schalt awreke be</L>
<L N="5550">Of &thorn;ine enmis, as y telle &thorn;e,</L>
<L>&amp; bot &yogh;e wil &thorn;us don,</L>
<L>&THORN;ai wor&thorn; &thorn;i dedliche fon.'</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="section">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Wi&thorn; &thorn;at answerd &thorn;e douk Loer,<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="5246"></L>
<L>'Lat be, sir Otus, for seyn Richer.</L>
<L N="5555">&THORN;at felonie y nil hem nou&yogh;t do</L>
<L>For nou&yogh;t &thorn;at y mi&yogh;t afo.</L>
<L>Y nil bitray &thorn;erl Tirri</L>
<L>For loue &thorn;at he was mi norri</L>
<L>Fram childehed, now he is a man.</L>
<L N="5560">Now do &yogh;e &thorn;e best &thorn;at &yogh;e can,</L>
<L>&amp; he wil amend o&yogh;ines me.<MILESTONE N="137a:a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Bi him y<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>y</I> added above the line.</NOTE> nold no traysoun se,</L>
<L>No Herhaud no Gij &thorn;e fre</L>
<L>No wille ich nou&yogh;t bitreye, y telle &thorn;e,</L>
<L N="5565">For &thorn;ai ben gode men alle &thorn;re:</L>
<L>Amende &thorn;ai may o&yogh;aines me.'</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="section">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Otous answerd wi&thorn; wicked mod<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="5257"></L>
<L>&amp; seyd, 'sir, no seystow bot gode.</L>
<L>When &yogh;e &thorn;e traitours loue so,</L>
<L N="5570">&THORN;at ye no wille hem to de&thorn; do,</L>
<L>In prisoun &thorn;ou schalt hem legge,</L>
<L>So &thorn;at hij it schul dere abigge,</L>
<L>Alle fort &thorn;ai han y-founden &thorn;e ostage</L>
<L>&THORN;at hij no do &thorn;e non vtrage.'</L>
<L N="5575">So he glosed &thorn;e douk in &thorn;at stede,</L>
<L>&amp; so &yogh;ernne he ha&thorn; him bede,
<PB REF="00000307.tif" N="303"></L>
<L>&THORN;at he him graunted his talent,</L>
<L>&amp; in &thorn;at fourme he ha&thorn; of-sent.</L>
<L>An erchebischop &thorn;an sent he,</L>
<L N="5580">&THORN;e wisest<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>wissest</I> origin|ally, the second <I>s</I> being under|dotted.</NOTE> of alle &thorn;at cuntre:</L>
<L>&THORN;e message he schewed him &thorn;o,</L>
<L>&amp; to &thorn;e cite he dede him go.</L>
<L>&THORN;an he is to Gormoise come,</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;er ali&yogh;t, &thorn;e gentil gome,</L>
<L N="5585">&THORN;er fond he &thorn;erl Tirri,</L>
<L>&amp; his fader, &amp; eke sir Gij.</L>
<L>&para; 'Lordinges,' he seyd, 'herken&thorn; now:<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="5289"></L>
<L>&THORN;e douk me ha&thorn; y-sent to &yogh;ou,</L>
<L>&amp; grete&thorn; &yogh;ou wele, wil y nou&yogh;t hele.<NOTE PLACE="marg">Read <I>hille: wille</I>?</NOTE></L>
<L N="5590">&THORN;e douke wi&thorn; &yogh;ou acord he wele,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Read <I>hille: wille</I>?</NOTE></L>
<L>&amp; amenden &thorn;at he ha&thorn; misdo.</L>
<L>He bit &yogh;ou &thorn;at it be so.</L>
<L>Tirri he wille his douhter<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>douthter</I> origin|ally, the first <I>t</I> being under|dotted.</NOTE> &yogh;iue,</L>
<L>To haue hir while &thorn;at he liue.</L>
<L N="5595">Into &thorn;e cite of Lorein he wil &yogh;e hir lede,</L>
<L>&amp; spouse hir &thorn;er wi&thorn; gret ferrede,</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;er he wille &thorn;e bridal held:</L>
<L>&THORN;er-at schul ben his barouns beld.</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;e loue stedefast be</L>
<L N="5600">Bitvene mi lord &amp; &thorn;e</L>
<L>Hennes forward he seyd me</L>
<L>Schuld &thorn;e sposails cou&thorn;e be:</L>
<L>&THORN;an schul &yogh;e acordi,</L>
<L>&amp; togider sau&yogh;ten wele an hi.'</L>
<L N="5605">'Sir,' seyd &thorn;erl Aubri,<MILESTONE N="137a:b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>'Y-here now me, and gramerci.</L>
<L>&THORN;e douke y &thorn;anke for &thorn;e frendschip,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he wil mi sone so miche wor&thorn;schipe.</L>
<L>Ble&thorn;eliche we wil to him come</L>
<L N="5610">At a day y-sett alle and some.</L>
<L>Mi sone Tirri, kepe wele &thorn;e</L>
<L>&THORN;at bitrayed &thorn;ou no be:
<PB REF="00000308.tif" N="304"></L>
<L>Me doute&thorn; &thorn;e douke of Paui,</L>
<L>Lest he do &thorn;e sum felonie.'</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="section">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="5615">&THORN;e bischop answerd, '&thorn;er-of &thorn;ou no drede:<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="5321"></L>
<L>Al siker &yogh;e be&thorn; of &thorn;ilke dede.'</L>
<L>&THORN;e bischop o&yogh;ain y-farn he is,</L>
<L>Her answere he telle&thorn; hem, y-wis.</L>
<L>When &thorn;e day come &thorn;at was sett,</L>
<L N="5620">&THORN;erl com for&thorn; wi&thorn;outen lett</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; to hundred kni&yogh;tes &amp; mo,</L>
<L>&THORN;at bli&thorn;e were &thorn;ider to go;</L>
<L>Ac &thorn;erof &thorn;ai dede foliliche:</L>
<L>Was &thorn;er non of hem, sikerliche,</L>
<L N="5625">&THORN;at ani wepen wi&thorn; hem bere:</L>
<L>So siker &thorn;ai wende to be &thorn;ere.</L>
<L>In riche clo&thorn;es &thorn;ai were schred wele,</L>
<L>&THORN;at were gold-broiden eueridel.</L>
<L>To &thorn;emperour<NOTE PLACE="marg">Read <I>&THORN;e douke?</I></NOTE> &thorn;ai comen anon,</L>
<L N="5630">To<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>To</I> to be omitted?</NOTE> &thorn;erl Tirri &amp; his men ichon.</L>
<L>Y-comen &thorn;ai ben to &thorn;e douke Loer,</L>
<L>&amp; brou&yogh;t &thorn;e maide wi&thorn; ley&yogh;eand cher.</L>
<L>Y-comen &thorn;ai ben to &thorn;e parlement,</L>
<L>For to here &thorn;at iugement.</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="section">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="5635">'Lordinges,' seyd &thorn;e douke Otoun,<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>of toun</I> MS.</NOTE><MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="5349"></L>
<L>'Vnder-stond now to mi resoun.</L>
<L>&YOGH;e wite wel &thorn;at Tirri, &thorn;at is here,</L>
<L>Ha&thorn; agilt &thorn;e douk Loere,</L>
<L>&THORN;at him for&thorn; brou&yogh;t, &amp; armes him &yogh;af:</L>
<L N="5640">Iuel &yogh;olden he it him ha&thorn;,</L>
<L>Now he bringe&thorn; vncou&thorn;e folk miche</L>
<L>Opon his lond so dedliche.</L>
<L>Ac ichaue &thorn;e douke bisou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>&amp; mine feren hider brou&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="5645">&THORN;at for&yogh;if it be him euermo;</L>
<L>&amp; gret wor&thorn;schipe he wil him do:</L>
<L>His douhter he wille him &yogh;iue,</L>
<L>&amp; gret wor&thorn;schip while<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>i</I> in <I>while</I> above the line.</NOTE> &thorn;at he liue.
<PB REF="00000310.tif" N="306"></L>
<L>And ichil wi&thorn; Tirri wende:<MILESTONE N="137b:a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="5650">Henneforward we schul be frende.</L>
<L>&YOGH;ete vnderstond,' seyd sir Otoun,</L>
<L>'Bifor &yogh;ou alle y biseke sir Gyoun,</L>
<L>&YOGH;if ich him haue ou&yogh;t misdo,</L>
<L>Amenden ichil wele &thorn;erto:</L>
<L N="5655">Bi so &thorn;at he wille kisse me,</L>
<L>Euer eft we schul frendes be.'</L>
<L>'Lat be,' seyd sir Gij &thorn;e fre,</L>
<L>'No wille ichaue no cosse wi&thorn; &thorn;e:</L>
<L>In Lombardye &thorn;ou bitraydest me,</L>
<L N="5660">&amp; min men &thorn;ou dest sle.</L>
<L>Ac kisse &thorn;ou schalt &thorn;erl Aubri,</L>
<L>&amp; wi&thorn; him &thorn;ou schalt acordi.'</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;an seyd &thorn;e douk Loer:</L>
<L>'Vnderstond now, &yogh;e &thorn;at ben here,</L>
<L N="5665">&THORN;at &thorn;erl sir Tirri,</L>
<L>Aubri sone, &thorn;at is her bi,</L>
<L>He &thorn;at maiden Oysel schal spouse</L>
<L>In godes lawe vnto his house.</L>
<L>Acorded we ben of &thorn;at dede,</L>
<L N="5670">&amp; for&yogh;euen al hatrede.'</L>
<L>&THORN;an ha&thorn; &thorn;e douke y-kist Tirri</L>
<L>For gret traisoun, &amp; nou&yogh;t freli.</L>
<L>Gij &amp; Herhaud held hem in pays:</L>
<L>Hye no kist Lombard no Tyays,</L>
<L N="5675">Ac &thorn;e Loreins &thorn;ai kist,</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;e douke Loyer att<NOTE PLACE="marg">An erasure be|fore <I>att.</I></NOTE> first;</L>
<L>Ac Otus no kist &thorn;ai nou&yogh;t:</L>
<L>&THORN;ai no hadde to him no gode &thorn;ou&yogh;t.</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="section">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;an seyd to Loer &thorn;erl Aubri:</L>
<L N="5680">'&THORN;e ich biteche mi sone Tirri.</L>
<L>Alder-first Iesu heuen king</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;e y biteche mi &yogh;ongling.</L>
<L>No may ich for eld trauaily:</L>
<L>Hom ichil wende now an hye.'
<PB REF="00000312.tif" N="308"></L>
<L N="5685">He bitau&yogh;t hem god &amp; gode day,</L>
<L>He lete hem &thorn;ar, &amp; went his way.</L>
<L>Gij and Herhaud &thorn;e maiden gan for&thorn; lede,</L>
<L>Oysel sche hete wi&thorn; &thorn;e rode so rede.</L>
<L>Gret iurne &thorn;ai riden &thorn;at day,</L>
<L N="5690">Fram Gormoise &thorn;ai riden owai</L>
<L>Wele fiften mile o&thorn;er mo:</L>
<L>For gret hete &thorn;ai resten hem &thorn;o.</L>
<L>In a pleyne &thorn;ai li&yogh;ten hem snelle,<MILESTONE N="137b:b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&THORN;er &thorn;ai wald resten &amp; duelle.</L>
<L N="5695">When &thorn;ai ali&yogh;t &thorn;e kni&yogh;tes fre,</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;ai wende y-nomen to be.</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;an seyd Otus of Paui:</L>
<L>'Herkene&thorn; to me, al mi compeynie,</L>
<L>&THORN;e Loreins &amp; &thorn;e Lombardes ichon,</L>
<L N="5700">Alle &thorn;at in our side riden &amp; gon:</L>
<L>Bi &thorn;e rede of &thorn;e douke Loer</L>
<L>Ichot bo&thorn;e kni&yogh;t &amp; squier</L>
<L>&THORN;at &yogh;e Gij, Herhaud, &amp; Tirri binde</L>
<L>Fast her hondes hem bi-hinde.</L>
<L N="5705">In-to Loreine we lede hem snelle:</L>
<L>Tomorwe we schul hem hongen alle.</L>
<L>Who so him feyne&thorn; hem to nime</L>
<L>For&thorn; wi&thorn; hem men schal him blim.'</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="section">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;an lopen about hem &thorn;e Lombars</L>
<L N="5710">As wicked coltes out of haras</L>
<L>&amp; Loyers [men]<NOTE PLACE="marg">Or read <I>&thorn;e Loreyns?</I></NOTE> deden also,</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;erfore hem was ful wo.</L>
<L>Anon Tirri aseylden he,</L>
<L>&amp; nomen him (he no mi&yogh;t nou&yogh;t fle),</L>
<L N="5715">&amp; Herhaud, &thorn;at was gode of mi&yogh;t,</L>
<L>&THORN;ai nomen &thorn;er anon ri&yogh;t.</L>
<L>Gij vp stirt hastiliche,<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="5455"></L>
<L>&amp; to hem spac wel sternliche:</L>
<L>'Now &thorn;e deuel hong &yogh;ou ichon.</L>
<L N="5720">Is &thorn;is acord now alle agon?
<PB REF="00000314.tif" N="310"></L>
<L>Wor&thorn;schiped ous ha&thorn; &thorn;e douk Loer</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; alle &thorn;e tresoun &thorn;at is her.</L>
<L>No war we acorded bifor &thorn;e barnage,</L>
<L>&amp; kist wi&thorn;outen vtrage?</L>
<L N="5725">&THORN;is has made &thorn;e douke Otoun,<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. <I>of toun.</I></NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at is so ful of tresoun.</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;is tresoun he ha&thorn; bispeke</L>
<L>(God ous of him awreke);</L>
<L>For &thorn;urch &thorn;e no war it nou&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="5730">Bot it were first of him y-&thorn;ou&yogh;t.'</L>
<L>&THORN;e douk Loer was so wo:</L>
<L>O word no mi&yogh;t he speke &thorn;o.</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="section">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Wi&thorn; &thorn;at stirt for&thorn; anon ri&yogh;t<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="5469"></L>
<L>Otus cossyn, an vnwrast kni&yogh;t.</L>
<L N="5735">Gij bi his mantel he drou&yogh; so,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;e tassels brosten ato.</L>
<L>&THORN;an seyd a Tya[y]s to a Lombard:<MILESTONE N="138a:a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>'Now is Gij of Warwike a couward.</L>
<L>Lo, now he no ha&thorn; no mi&yogh;t:</L>
<L N="5740">Lorn he ha&thorn; contenaunce, apli&yogh;t.'</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; &thorn;at &thorn;ai speken hem &thorn;us bitven,</L>
<L>Gij seye it mi&yogh;t no no&thorn;er ben:</L>
<L>To him &thorn;at him held turned he,</L>
<L>And &yogh;af him swiche benedicite,</L>
<L N="5745">&THORN;at he brak his nek ato.</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;e o&thorn;er on him &thorn;resten &thorn;o.</L>
<L>&THORN;e mantel &thorn;at he had opon</L>
<L>To cloutes it was drawen anon,</L>
<L>So &thorn;at ichon oway bar</L>
<L N="5750">An pece of his mantel &thorn;ar.</L>
<L>Gij werd him fast in &thorn;at sturbing:</L>
<L>Now helpe him Iesu heuen king.</L>
<L>Smer[t]liche &thorn;ai gun him asaily:</L>
<L>He werd him as a kni&yogh;t hardy,</L>
<L N="5755">So &thorn;at he ney&yogh;ed his stede;</L>
<L>For to him he hadde nede.
<PB REF="00000316.tif" N="312"></L>
<L>Wi&thorn;outen stirop he lepe &thorn;er-on:</L>
<L>Mani on he made &thorn;at liif forgon.</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="section">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>When &thorn;e douk Otus &thorn;at y-seye<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="5491"></L>
<L N="5760">&THORN;at Gij on his hors oway fleye,</L>
<L>Anon he<NOTE PLACE="marg">Another <I>he</I> struck out.</NOTE> seyd to his kni&yogh;tes:</L>
<L>'Now to hors wi&thorn; alle &yogh;our mi&yogh;tes;</L>
<L>For, &yogh;if he passe ous in &thorn;is biker,</L>
<L>Of mi liif am y nou&yogh;t siker;</L>
<L N="5765">&amp; &thorn;erfore nime&thorn; him anon</L>
<L>Als &yogh;e wil haue mi loue ichon.</L>
<L>Bot &yogh;e bring him me to,</L>
<L>We ben y-schent for euer mo.'</L>
<L>An hors &thorn;ai lopen &thorn;an on hast,</L>
<L N="5770">And driuen Gij swi&thorn;e fast,</L>
<L>&amp; Gij no hadde wepen non:</L>
<L>Wold god of heuen, &thorn;at made man,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he hadde his brond kerueing!</L>
<L>He no hadde &thorn;er no frende him helping.</L>
<L N="5775">Bi &thorn;at o side oway he ginne&thorn; fle;</L>
<L>Bot god of him haue pite,</L>
<L>&THORN;er he wor&thorn; y-slawe anon:</L>
<L>Alle abouten him &thorn;ai ben y-gon.</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; &thorn;at &thorn;er come rideing a kni&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="5780">About his swere his scheld bri&yogh;t,<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="5513"></L>
<L>&amp; wi&thorn; a spere opon his hond:<MILESTONE N="138a:b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Toward Gij wel swi&thorn;e he wond,</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;urch &thorn;e bodi smite him wold,</L>
<L>Ac god of heuen it suffre nold:</L>
<L N="5785">&THORN;e strok of &thorn;e spere it gan glide</L>
<L>Bitven &thorn;e arsoun &amp; his side.</L>
<L>His blihaut he carf, his schert also.</L>
<L>Gij strongliche him mett &thorn;o:</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; his fest he him smot so,</L>
<L N="5790">&THORN;at to grounde he<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>he</I> added above the line.</NOTE> dede him go.</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; &thorn;at sir Gij for&thorn; him di&yogh;t,</L>
<L>Ac he mett wi&thorn; ano&thorn;er kni&yogh;t:
<PB REF="00000318.tif" N="314"></L>
<L>Swerd he bar &thorn;at wele wald bite,</L>
<L>In &thorn;e heued he wald Gij smite.</L>
<L N="5795">&THORN;e strok opon his hors glod</L>
<L>Opon &thorn;e croupe a fot brod.</L>
<L>&THORN;ei he war aferd no wonder nas:</L>
<L>Gij ferd fram him a<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>an</I> originally, the <I>n</I> being under|dotted.</NOTE> fast pas.</L>
<L>He seye wi&thorn; &thorn;at a grom cominde,<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="5533"></L>
<L N="5800">To him ward fast erninge:<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>erneinge</I> origin|ally, the second <I>e</I> being under|dotted.</NOTE></L>
<L>A gret soule in his hond he bar,</L>
<L>So wold god &thorn;at it war.</L>
<L>Gij wel feir him bisou&yogh;t</L>
<L>&YOGH;if him &thorn;e staf &thorn;at he brou&yogh;t.</L>
<L N="5805">'Ichil &yogh;eld it &thorn;e ful wel.'</L>
<L>'Haue here, sir, bi seyn Mi&yogh;hel.</L>
<L>Wele ich &thorn;i gret nede se:</L>
<L>Now god fram schame kepe &thorn;e.'</L>
<L>He tok &thorn;at soule in his hond,</L>
<L N="5810">Anon for&thorn; to hem he wond.</L>
<L>A Lombard wel sone he mett,</L>
<L>And wi&thorn; &thorn;e soule<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. <I>swerd.</I></NOTE> so him grett,</L>
<L>&THORN;at ded he feld him anon.</L>
<L>He tok his hors, &amp; gan to gon,</L>
<L N="5815">&amp; seyd to &thorn;e grom &thorn;o:</L>
<L>'&THORN;ou nim &thorn;is hors, &amp; gin to go.</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; gode wille y &yogh;iue it &thorn;e</L>
<L>For &thorn;e staf &thorn;ou lentest me.'</L>
<L>&THORN;e knaue him &thorn;onked bliue,</L>
<L N="5820">Oway wi&thorn; &thorn;e hors he gan to driue.</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="section">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;an went for&thorn; Gij &thorn;e gode,</L>
<L>Nas neuer man of his mode</L>
<L>&THORN;at better him werd in his ende.</L>
<L>Er he out of &thorn;at fi&yogh;t gan wende</L>
<L N="5825">&YOGH;ete he slou&yogh; on of her felawe.<MILESTONE N="138b:a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>In lasse while he hadde [him] y-slawe,</L>
<L>&THORN;en men schold sigge a pater-noster.</L>
<L>Y telle it &yogh;ou bi Peter &thorn;e apostel
<PB REF="00000320.tif" N="316"></L>
<L>&THORN;at neuer swiche nas<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>nas</I> on an erasure.</NOTE> y-seye non.</L>
<L N="5830">When he ha&thorn; ouer-comen ichon</L>
<L>Wel long he wer&thorn; him &thorn;at day.</L>
<L>When he no lenge doure ne may</L>
<L>&THORN;an seyd he to hem anon:</L>
<L>'&THORN;e deuel biteche ich &yogh;ou ichon,</L>
<L N="5835">&amp; namliche Otus of Pauie,</L>
<L>&THORN;at ha&thorn; y-don ous &thorn;is felonie;</L>
<L>&amp; &yogh;if ich a &yogh;er libbe may</L>
<L>He schal it<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. <I>ich</I></NOTE> abigge, for so&thorn;e to say.'</L>
<L>&THORN;an is<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>is</I> added above the line.</NOTE> he gon<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. <I>goand</I></NOTE> oway ful &yogh;ernne,</L>
<L N="5840">So &thorn;at he com to a water sterne.<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="5561"></L>
<L>In he him dede, &amp; ouer he go&thorn;.</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;ai wondred &thorn;er-of, for so&thorn;.</L>
<L>Non no durst after him wende</L>
<L>For drencheing at her liues ende.</L>
<L N="5845">O&yogh;ain &thorn;an &thorn;ai ben y-come</L>
<L>To &thorn;e douke Otus alle and some,</L>
<L>&amp; telden him wel sone anon</L>
<L>&THORN;at Gij was ouer &thorn;e water y-gon.<NOTE PLACE="marg">Lines 5847-8 written twice originally, but struck out the second time.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;e douke Otous is now wel sori,</L>
<L N="5850">For Gij is schaped so oway,</L>
<L>&amp; swore bi god &amp; seyn Gelen</L>
<L>Neuer eft nold he louen<NOTE PLACE="marg">looks more like <I>louen</I> than <I>leuen.</I></NOTE> his men,</L>
<L>For &thorn;at hii leten him oway fle:</L>
<L>Gret wille he hadde him to sle;</L>
<L N="5855">Ac Gij him werd wi&thorn; mani wrenche:</L>
<L>Hope<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>Bothe</I>, Turnbull, but the first letter, although not quite distinct, is cer|tainly not <I>b</I>, and the third, without any doubt, is <I>p</I>, not <I>&thorn;</I>.</NOTE> of fole may of-blenche.</L>
<L>'Sir douk Loer,' seyd Otoun,</L>
<L>'Y-schaped is &thorn;e felle Gyoun.<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="5569"></L>
<L>To Paui ichil now<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>n</I> and part of <I>o</I> struck out after <I>now.</I></NOTE> gon,</L>
<L N="5860">&amp; spouse &thorn;i douhter anon:</L>
<L>Riche bridal ichil maki.</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; me schal Herhaud &amp; Tirri;</L>
<L>&THORN;er &thorn;ai schul be don in prisoun:</L>
<L>Schul &thorn;ai neuer come to raunsoun.
<PB REF="00000322.tif" N="318"></L>
<L N="5865">Dye &thorn;ai schul wi&thorn; miche wo.</L>
<L>&amp; &yogh;ete to &yogh;er ichil now go</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; min men to sechen Gij,<MILESTONE N="138b:b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>What he be nome, sikerly.</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;is o&thorn;er prisouns wi&thorn; &thorn;e go,</L>
<L N="5870">&amp; &thorn;ine wil wi&thorn; hem &thorn;ou do.'</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="section">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'Sir,' seyd &thorn;e douk Loer,<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="5581"></L>
<L>'&THORN;at nil ich nou&yogh;t in non maner</L>
<L>&THORN;at tow Tirri no do sle:</L>
<L>Y nold in non wise, sir douk &thorn;e fre;</L>
<L N="5875">Ac, &yogh;if Tirri schal wi&thorn; &thorn;e go,</L>
<L>In fre prisoun &thorn;ou schalt him do.</L>
<L>&THORN;ou do him kepe wor&thorn;schipliche</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; gret plente manschipliche,</L>
<L>Alle fort he haue mi wille y-do.</L>
<L N="5880">Ichil now &thorn;at it be so,</L>
<L>&amp; ich-il lede Herhaud wi&thorn; me:</L>
<L>In mi fre prisoun schal he be.</L>
<L>Y nil nou&yogh;t he wi&thorn; &thorn;e go:</L>
<L>To michel iuel &thorn;ou wost him do.'</L>
<L N="5885">&THORN;an &thorn;ai token her leue &thorn;o:</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; gret loue &thorn;ai kisten hem bo.</L>
<L>To Lorein went &thorn;e douke Loer,</L>
<L>&THORN;at wi&thorn; wor&thorn;schipe dede kepe &thorn;er</L>
<L>Herhaud of Arderne, &thorn;e marchis:</L>
<L N="5890">Wele leuer him were be ded, y-wis.</L>
<L>When he to Gij com no mi&yogh;t,</L>
<L>Leue him were dye anon ri&yogh;t.</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="section">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Now is Otous to Paui gan,<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="5597"></L>
<L>Wi&thorn; him he ledde his feir leman,</L>
<L N="5895">Also he dede &thorn;erl sir Tirri</L>
<L>Fast y-fetred, sikerly,</L>
<L>Ri&yogh;t fast vnder &thorn;e hors fet</L>
<L>In-to Paui, and &thorn;er him let.</L>
<L>When Oysel seye him lede so</L>
<L N="5900">Sore sche wepe for his wo.
<PB REF="00000323.tif" N="319"></L>
<L>'Allas,' sche seyd, '&amp; wale-wo:</L>
<L>Sone is my ioie went me fro.'</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e hors sche fel aswon anon:</L>
<L>For sorwe almost hir hert to-chon.</L>
<L N="5905">When &thorn;e douk hir falle seye</L>
<L>Bi his o&thorn; he swore an heye,</L>
<L>'Iuel &thorn;ou dost, mi gode leman,</L>
<L>When &thorn;ou for swiche a man</L>
<L>Swiche sorwe schaltow make.</L>
<L N="5910">&amp; &yogh;if &thorn;ou more<NOTE PLACE="marg">Another <I>more</I> struck out.</NOTE> sorwe for his sake,</L>
<L>O&thorn;er euer eft make swiche sorweing,<MILESTONE N="139a:a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&amp; ich it perceiue bi ani &thorn;ing,</L>
<L>To-hewe he wor&thorn; bifor &thorn;e,</L>
<L>Or heye hong on galwe tre.</L>
<L N="5915">Glad &amp; bli&thorn;e, leman, &thorn;ou be:</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; ioie to Paui y lede &thorn;e,</L>
<L>&THORN;er ichil nim &thorn;e to wiue,</L>
<L>And wi&thorn; &thorn;e helden alle mi liue.</L>
<L>Tirri ichil in prisoun do:</L>
<L N="5920">He no schal haue sorwe no wo.</L>
<L>Ichim hate wel sore, sikerly,</L>
<L>For &thorn;e loue of Herhaud and Gij.</L>
<L>Richeliche he schal serued be:</L>
<L>&THORN;er-of nou&yogh;t no dred &thorn;ou &thorn;e.'</L>
<L N="5925">&para; 'Sir, gramerci of &thorn;i speche,<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="5623"></L>
<L>Ac of o &thorn;ing y &thorn;e biseche:</L>
<L>Fourti days respite &thorn;ou &yogh;if me,</L>
<L>Til &thorn;at mi sorwe aslaked be,</L>
<L>&amp; se&thorn;&thorn;en spouse me wi&thorn; wor&thorn;schipe.'</L>
<L N="5930">'Y graunt wele,' qua&thorn; &thorn;e douke, 'sikerlike.'</L>
<L>To Paui &thorn;ai ben &thorn;an ago,</L>
<L>Ac alle ano&thorn;er &thorn;ou&yogh;t &thorn;at maiden &thorn;o;</L>
<L>Ano&thorn;er sche sou&yogh;t<NOTE PLACE="marg">Read <I>&thorn;ou&yogh;t</I>?</NOTE> &thorn;an sche seyd:</L>
<L>Gret sorwe in hir hert sche leyd.</L>
<L N="5935">Ar sche wille to him spoused be,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; a kniif sche wil hir sle.
<PB REF="00000324.tif" N="320"></L>
<L>Ac o &thorn;ing hir glad, sikerliche:</L>
<L>Opon Gij sche trust miche.</L>
<L>Se&thorn;&thorn;e &thorn;at he aschaped was,</L>
<L N="5940">Wele sche &thorn;ou&yogh;t &thorn;urch sum cas</L>
<L>He schuld Tirri out of prisoun cast,</L>
<L>Hir swete leman, wel on hast.</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="section">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;ai com to Paui wi&thorn; &thorn;at:<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="5641"></L>
<L>&THORN;e douk Otus nou&yogh;t for&yogh;at,</L>
<L N="5945">&THORN;at erl Tirri he bond fast,</L>
<L>&amp; in-to &thorn;ester prisoun him cast,</L>
<L>&THORN;er he was in sorwe, apli&yogh;t:</L>
<L>He nist whe&thorn;er it wer day or ni&yogh;t.</L>
<L>Litel he hadde of mete or dring.</L>
<L N="5950">His leman lan neuer wepeing</L>
<L>Ani&yogh;t, when sche alon was,</L>
<L>&THORN;at noman wi&thorn; hir nas.</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="section">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Now to tel of Gij ichaue y-&thorn;ou&yogh;t<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="5651"></L>
<L>Hou god him ha&thorn; fram de&thorn; y-brou&yogh;t.</L>
<L N="5955">When he was passed &thorn;at water sternne<MILESTONE N="139a:b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>He loked about him wel &yogh;ernne,</L>
<L>Of his felawes him vnderstode:</L>
<L>Wel<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>welle</I> originally, but <I>le</I> underdot|ted.</NOTE> neye he was for sorwe wode.</L>
<L>'God,' he seyd, 'what schal y do?</L>
<L N="5960">Weri wreche, whider may y go?</L>
<L>Ichaue forlorn &thorn;e gode Tirri</L>
<L>&amp; Herhaud, for wham icham sori.</L>
<L>Amow,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Read <I>Ai now?</I></NOTE> sir douk Loer,</L>
<L>Hou mi&yogh;testow dreye &thorn;e bismer,</L>
<L N="5965">&THORN;at &thorn;e fals douk Otoun<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. <I>of toun.</I></NOTE></L>
<L>Dede bifor &thorn;e &thorn;at traisoun?</L>
<L>For traitour &thorn;ou worst euer i-held</L>
<L>When &thorn;ou comest in place or feld.</L>
<L>Lord,' he seyd, 'what may y do?</L>
<L N="5970">Into whiche lond may y go?</L>
<L>An arnemorwe no &thorn;ing y no dred me:</L>
<L>&THORN;o ich went out of &thorn;at cite
<PB REF="00000326.tif" N="322"></L>
<L>Wi&thorn; me ich hadde an hundred kni&yogh;tes</L>
<L>To mi wille for me in fi&yogh;tes,</L>
<L N="5975">&amp; now y no haue a grom to held mi stede.</L>
<L>&THORN;at so miche me mi&yogh;t help<NOTE PLACE="marg">Looks like helper.</NOTE> at nede,</L>
<L>For me &thorn;ai ben y-slawe ichon,</L>
<L>O&thorn;er in peine in prisoun don.</L>
<L>A, mi dere frende sir Tirri,</L>
<L N="5980">For our departing icham sori.</L>
<L>No schal y &thorn;e se neuer eft mo?</L>
<L>For &thorn;e ichil mi liif in periil do,</L>
<L>&THORN;at y<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>y ne schal</I> MS.</NOTE> schal his body smite ato</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;us &thorn;is traisoun ha&thorn; ous do,</L>
<L N="5985">&amp; so ichil awreke &thorn;e:</L>
<L>Dye ichil bot it so be.'</L>
<L>Gij rode for&thorn; in his way</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;at iche self day,<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="5687"></L>
<L>So long &thorn;at he a castel seye</L>
<L N="5990">Opon a roche stode an heye.</L>
<L>He &thorn;ou&yogh;t to herberwe &thorn;are;</L>
<L>For he no mi&yogh;t no fer&thorn;er fare.</L>
<L>Also he to &thorn;e gates come</L>
<L>A &yogh;ong kni&yogh;t he fond &thorn;er anon.</L>
<L N="5995">Michel he was, hende, &amp; fre:</L>
<L>Feren he hadde wi&thorn; him &thorn;re.</L>
<L>Gij sey bi his semblaunt anon</L>
<L>&THORN;at he was lord ouer hem ichon.</L>
<L>'Sir,' qua&thorn; Gij, 'vnderstond to me.<MILESTONE N="139b:a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="6000">&THORN;e lord, &thorn;at made me and te,</L>
<L>&THORN;e loke &yogh;if &thorn;i wille be,</L>
<L>And miche blisse he &yogh;if &thorn;e.</L>
<L>A kni&yogh;t icham deswarre,</L>
<L>&THORN;at in y bid par charite.'</L>
<L N="6005">&para; &THORN;e lord answerd sweteliche,</L>
<L>'&THORN;ou it schalt haue, ble&thorn;eliche.'</L>
<L>He dede vnder-fong his stede &thorn;o,</L>
<L>Bi his own<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>on</I> MS.</NOTE> he dede it do.
<PB REF="00000328.tif" N="324"></L>
<L>Bi &thorn;e ri&yogh;t hond he toke sir Gij,</L>
<L N="6010">&amp; went into his halle on hey.</L>
<L>A mantel of silk he of-sent on hast,</L>
<L>&amp; about him he dede it cast.</L>
<L>Wonderliche &thorn;ai bihelden him alle</L>
<L>Kni&yogh;tes &thorn;at weren in &thorn;e halle;</L>
<L N="6015">For he was michel &amp; wele y-sett.</L>
<L>&THORN;ai him bihelden wele &thorn;e bett.</L>
<L>&THORN;e lord wi&thorn; &thorn;at to him sede,</L>
<L>'Ich &thorn;e bidde for loue-rede</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;i name telle &thorn;ou me,</L>
<L N="6020">&amp; nou&yogh;t forhole it no be.'</L>
<L>Gij answerd wel sweteliche,</L>
<L>'Mi name y &thorn;e telle, sikerliche:</L>
<L>Gij of Warwike mi name is.</L>
<L>Iuel ich am acumbred, y-wis.'</L>
<L N="6025">When &thorn;e lord herd &thorn;at,</L>
<L>&THORN;at it was Gij &thorn;at to him spac,</L>
<L>'Sir,' he seyd, 'welcome &yogh;e be:</L>
<L>In &yogh;our owhen herberwe &yogh;e.</L>
<L>Ful welcome artow to me,</L>
<L N="6030">&amp; ful wele y knowe &thorn;e.</L>
<L>Ich au&yogh;t &thorn;e loue, so moti gon:</L>
<L>Wel michel gode &thorn;ou hast me don.</L>
<L>&THORN;o ich &thorn;e serued &thorn;ou louedest me:</L>
<L>Armes ich vnderfenge of &thorn;e,</L>
<L N="6035">And &thorn;ou me sendest ner &amp; fer</L>
<L>To turnamens &amp; to wer,</L>
<L>So &thorn;at gret word sprong of me,</L>
<L>&THORN;o y went hom to mi cuntre.</L>
<L>Amis of Mounteyn mi name it is:</L>
<L N="6040">Wele ou&yogh;t &yogh;e me knowe, y-wis.'</L>
<L>When Gij him seye he knewe &thorn;e kni&yogh;t,<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="5727"></L>
<L>He kist him &thorn;er anon ri&yogh;t.</L>
<L>'Sir,' qua&thorn; Amis, 'when comestow,<MILESTONE N="139b:b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&THORN;atow gost alle on now?
<PB REF="00000330.tif" N="326"></L>
<L N="6045">It seme&thorn; wele, so &thorn;enke&thorn; me,</L>
<L>Fram gret periil aschaped be &yogh;e.</L>
<L>Whare his Herhaud, &thorn;i kni&yogh;t so fre?</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;ine kni&yogh;tes where ben he?'</L>
<L>'Ich-il &thorn;e telle,' &thorn;an seyd sir Gij.</L>
<L N="6050">'Now vnder-stond ich am sori.'</L>
<L>&THORN;an teld he him al &thorn;at cas,</L>
<L>Hou &thorn;erl Tirri wounded was,</L>
<L>&amp; hou he hadde y-heled his wounde,</L>
<L>&amp; socurd his fader, &amp; ost him founde,</L>
<L N="6055">&amp; hou he passed him self vnnome,</L>
<L>&amp; hou &thorn;ai were &thorn;urch traisoun ouer-come,</L>
<L>&amp; hou his felawes weren y-nome,</L>
<L>&amp; hou &thorn;at he was &thorn;ider y-come,</L>
<L>&amp; hou Tirri was y-nomen &thorn;o</L>
<L N="6060">&amp; &thorn;e gode Herhaud also,</L>
<L>&amp; wi&thorn; hem fif hundred kni&yogh;tes,</L>
<L>Orped men &amp; gode in fi&yogh;tes.</L>
<L>'Y not &yogh;if &thorn;ai be liues or dede:</L>
<L>Al ich hem sey nimen &amp; lede.'</L>
<L N="6065">When Gij hadde y-teld &thorn;at cas,</L>
<L>Hou iuel him bifallen was,<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="5751"></L>
<L>'Suffre awhile, sir,' qua&thorn; he.</L>
<L>'&YOGH;if it is &thorn;i wille listen to me.</L>
<L>Ich haue castels &amp; cites strong</L>
<L N="6070">Mani and fele in mi lond:</L>
<L>Alle ichil bitake &thorn;e,</L>
<L>Mine kni&yogh;tes ichil<NOTE PLACE="marg">An <I>s</I> erased after the <I>ch.</I></NOTE> of-sende to me:</L>
<L>Fif hundred ich of-sende may,</L>
<L>&THORN;at schal do &thorn;i wille ni&yogh;t and day.</L>
<L N="6075">Alle &thorn;at to min erldom falle&thorn; y wil it be</L>
<L>To &thorn;ine wille so schal com to &thorn;e.</L>
<L>Wende we wille to &thorn;e douk Otoun,<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. <I>of toun</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>And bring him to destruccioun.</L>
<L>His londes we schul &thorn;urch-ernne,</L>
<L N="6080">&amp; his castels felle, &amp; his tounes bernne,
<PB REF="00000332.tif" N="328"></L>
<L>&amp; so &thorn;ou mi&yogh;t awreke be,</L>
<L>His londes destru, him seluen sle.</L>
<L>Of werre no swike wille we,</L>
<L>Al what he a-slawe be.'</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="section">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="6085">'Amis,' qua&thorn; Gij, 'god &yogh;eld it te:<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="5769"></L>
<L>To long schuld ich here be.</L>
<L>&YOGH;if ich orn on him so &thorn;ou speke,<MILESTONE N="140a:a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>To late ich wor&thorn; of him awreke.</L>
<L>For drede of de&thorn; nille y fle.</L>
<L N="6090">Hastiliche ichil awreken be.'</L>
<L>Al a day he bileft &thorn;are,</L>
<L>His hert was in michel care:</L>
<L>Amis emfor&thorn; his mi&yogh;t</L>
<L>Confort him bo&thorn;e day and ni&yogh;t.'</L>
<L N="6095">&para; Of him he toke his leue &thorn;o,</L>
<L>Toward Paui he is y-go.</L>
<L>Amis wi&thorn; him gon wold,</L>
<L>Ac he seyd &thorn;at he no schold.</L>
<L>Amis bileft, &thorn;at was sori,</L>
<L N="6100">&amp; often to god he bad for Gij,</L>
<L>&THORN;at for his swete moder loue</L>
<L>Leue him harmeles o&yogh;ain come.</L>
<L>&para; Gij him di&yogh;t in a-queyntise,<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="5785"></L>
<L>&amp; com to Paui in squier wise.</L>
<L N="6105">An vnement purchast he</L>
<L>&THORN;at made his visage out of ble:</L>
<L>His here, &thorn;at was &yogh;alu and bri&yogh;t,</L>
<L>Blac it bicome anon ri&yogh;t.</L>
<L>Nas no man in &thorn;is world so wise of si&yogh;t</L>
<L N="6110">&THORN;at afterward him knowe mi&yogh;t.</L>
<L>Now to Paui y-comen he is:</L>
<L>Of no man aferd he nis.</L>
<L>&THORN;e douk Otus he fond &thorn;ere,</L>
<L>&amp; gret him as &yogh;e may here:</L>
<L N="6115">'Sir douk Otus,' he seyd, 'god loke &thorn;e:</L>
<L>Al so ich it wold so mot it be.
<PB REF="00000334.tif" N="330"></L>
<L>A man icham o fer cuntre:</L>
<L>Hider ich come to seche &thorn;e.</L>
<L>Ich haue &thorn;e brou&yogh;t here a stede,</L>
<L N="6120">In &thorn;is world is better non at nede.</L>
<L>Noris it dede a Sarazin,</L>
<L>And me it &yogh;af, min owen cosyn:</L>
<L>In alle &thorn;e world is so swift a best,</L>
<L>Libard no ro, in no forest,</L>
<L N="6125">No dromedarie no is &thorn;er non</L>
<L>So swi&thorn;e goand so is he on.</L>
<L>No &thorn;arf &thorn;e drede non arme of &thorn;e se,</L>
<L>And tow opon &thorn;is stede be.</L>
<L>&YOGH;if &yogh;e nille &thorn;erof me leue</L>
<L N="6130">Ichil &thorn;at &yogh;e it asey<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>aseyle</I> origin|ally, <I>le</I> being erased.</NOTE> ar eue.</L>
<L>Ac on maner ha&thorn; &thorn;at hors,<MILESTONE N="140a:b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&THORN;erfore mani ha&thorn; fare &thorn;e wors:</L>
<L>In &thorn;e world nis<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. <I>is.</I></NOTE> man &thorn;at ney him come</L>
<L>&THORN;at he no wold him slon wel sone,</L>
<L N="6135">Bot &thorn;e man &thorn;at loked<NOTE PLACE="marg">The first letter seems to be <I>l</I>, although it looks a little like <I>b.</I></NOTE> it.</L>
<L>&THORN;er-fore y loue it out of witt.'</L>
<L>Qua&thorn; &thorn;e douk, 'mow gramerci.<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="5817"></L>
<L>&THORN;is is a fair &yogh;ift, sikerly.</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; &thorn;at hors ichil at-hold &thorn;e,</L>
<L N="6140">&amp; make &thorn;e riche of gold &amp; fe.</L>
<L>To swiche an hors ich hadde nede,</L>
<L>&THORN;at ich might &thorn;e better spede.</L>
<L>Of min fomen ich wold ben awreke,</L>
<L>&amp; som in min prisoun ben y-steke,</L>
<L N="6145">Ac on of hem is schaped fro me.</L>
<L>Now wold god, &thorn;at alle may se,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he were now in &thorn;is halle:</L>
<L>Wel iuel him schuld sone bifalle.</L>
<L>Wel sone he schuld an-honged be</L>
<L N="6150">Wi&thorn; gode ri&yogh;t, y telle it te.'</L>
<L>'Sir,' qua&thorn; Gij, 'who [may] &thorn;at be?<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="5827"></L>
<L>In gret periil now is he.'
<PB REF="00000336.tif" N="332"></L>
<L>'Ichil &thorn;e telle,' qua&thorn; &thorn;e douk &thorn;o:</L>
<L>'Gij of Warwike, &thorn;at is mi fo.</L>
<L N="6155">Siker no be ich neuer mo</L>
<L>&THORN;e whiles &thorn;at he oliues go.</L>
<L>Ich wold now he stode &thorn;e bi.'</L>
<L>'Sir,' qua&thorn; he, 'y knowe wele Gij:</L>
<L>He slou&yogh; on of mi neye kin;</L>
<L N="6160">&THORN;er-fore ich am ri&yogh;t wro&thorn; wi&thorn; him,</L>
<L>&amp; wi&thorn; &thorn;erl Tirri also:</L>
<L>He is mi dedliche fo.</L>
<L>&THORN;urch felonie mi fader he slou&yogh;,</L>
<L>Mi bro&thorn;er he deserited<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>desirit</I> MS.</NOTE> wi&thorn; wou&yogh;.</L>
<L N="6165">God lete me neuer ded be</L>
<L>Er ich him to mi wille se.'</L>
<L>'Mi dere frende,' seyd &thorn;e douk Otoun,<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>of toun</I> MS.</NOTE><MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="5843"></L>
<L>'Ichaue Tirri in mi prisoun.</L>
<L>Now ich-il &thorn;ou loke him to,</L>
<L N="6170">And alle schame &thorn;ou him do.'</L>
<L>'Sir,' qua&thorn; he, 'gramerci,</L>
<L>And y &thorn;e sigge sikerly</L>
<L>&THORN;at alle his liif ichil wende</L>
<L>Er &thorn;an come seuen ni&yogh;tes ende.'</L>
<L N="6175">&THORN;e douke do&thorn; him &thorn;e keyes take,<MILESTONE N="140b:a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Maister iaioler he do&thorn; him make.</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="section">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;e douk oxe&thorn; what his name be:<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="5853"></L>
<L>'Yon men clepet me in mi cuntre.'</L>
<L>'Yon,' he seyd, 'ichot now &thorn;e</L>
<L N="6180">&THORN;at &thorn;ou &thorn;at hors wele kepe me.'</L>
<L>An hous he deliuer[d] him &thorn;o</L>
<L>&THORN;at no &thorn;ing com in bot &thorn;ai to.</L>
<L>&THORN;e douk &thorn;at nou&yogh;t no wist,</L>
<L>&THORN;at Gij was &thorn;er-in, bi Crist.</L>
<L N="6185">Alle his wille he may now do,<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="5861"></L>
<L>Non vn-wor&thorn;schip men seyd him to.</L>
<L>Gij into a tour is y-go,</L>
<L>A strong prisoun fond he &thorn;o:
<PB REF="00000338.tif" N="334"></L>
<L>Fourti fadom depe it was.</L>
<L N="6190">He hadde y-herd cri, 'allas':</L>
<L>He oxed anon who &thorn;at were</L>
<L>&THORN;at made &thorn;er so reuly bere.</L>
<L>'Ich,' he seyd, 'a wreched man:</L>
<L>Me reuwe&thorn; sore &thorn;at y liues am.</L>
<L N="6195">Erl Tirri mi nam is:</L>
<L>Now icham a wreche, y-wis.</L>
<L>&THORN;e douk no misdede y neuer nou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>And in &thorn;is prisoun icham y-brou&yogh;t.</L>
<L>More iren about me is</L>
<L N="6200">&THORN;an a somer mi&yogh;t beren, y-wis,</L>
<L>On armes, on legges, on bodi also.</L>
<L>Mi de&thorn; ich wold were com me to.</L>
<L>For &thorn;an &thorn;at ich felawe was</L>
<L>To a kni&yogh;t &thorn;at neuer his better nas,</L>
<L N="6205">Whom &thorn;e douk Otus hated, y-wis,</L>
<L>On me &thorn;e wreche fallen now is.</L>
<L>&THORN;at ich ete &thorn;is is &thorn;e &thorn;ridde day:</L>
<L>Long liue y no may.'</L>
<L>&para; 'Tirri,' qua&thorn; Gij, 'no be nou&yogh;t wo:<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="5885"></L>
<L N="6210">Icham Gij &thorn;ou louedest so.</L>
<L>Out of prisoun y schal cast &thorn;e</L>
<L>So sone y may mi time se.'</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="section">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Sir Tirri spac to Gij &thorn;o,</L>
<L>'For godes loue, hennes &thorn;ou go.</L>
<L N="6215">Hou come &thorn;ou hider, sir Gij?</L>
<L>&THORN;ine hider-com wil me harmi.</L>
<L>&YOGH;if &thorn;e douk wite &thorn;at &thorn;ou it be</L>
<L>&THORN;is ich day he wil sle &thorn;e.</L>
<L>Leuer me were al-on to day<MILESTONE N="140b:b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="6220">&THORN;an wite &thorn;e ded, so&thorn;e to say.</L>
<L>&THORN;erfore, sir, hennes &thorn;ou go;</L>
<L>For godes loue, sir, do now so.'</L>
<L>Als &thorn;ai togider speken &thorn;is</L>
<L>A Lombard it of-herd, y-wis,<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="5899">
<PB REF="00000339.tif" N="335"></L>
<L N="6225">&THORN;at after into &thorn;e tour was y-go</L>
<L>To aspie what Gij wold do.</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; loude steuen he ha&thorn; him gred,</L>
<L>'Gij, &thorn;ou hast wel iuel y-sped.</L>
<L>Bo&thorn;e &yogh;e schul an-honged be,</L>
<L N="6230">Now ich &yogh;ou<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>&thorn;ou</I> MS.</NOTE> bo&thorn;e here y-se.'</L>
<L>&para; 'Lete be,' qua&thorn; Gij, 'so god &thorn;e amende:</L>
<L>So &thorn;ou mi&yogh;t ous bo&thorn;e schende.</L>
<L>What schuld &thorn;e &thorn;e better be</L>
<L>&YOGH;if &thorn;ou dest ous bo&thorn;e sle?</L>
<L N="6235">&THORN;ine owhen man ichil be,</L>
<L>&amp; as mi lord seruy &thorn;e,</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;erl Tirri bi his mi&yogh;t,</L>
<L>And &thorn;erto mi treu&thorn;e y &thorn;e pli&yogh;t.'</L>
<L>'Hold &thorn;i pes,' qua&thorn; &thorn;e Lombart,</L>
<L N="6240">'Haue neuer god of me part</L>
<L>Bot ich &thorn;e douk Otus it telle:</L>
<L>For no&thorn;ing leten y nille.'</L>
<L>Adoun of &thorn;e tour he go&thorn; erninde,</L>
<L>And Gij after him fast folweinde.</L>
<L N="6245">Ri&yogh;t bifor &thorn;e doukes fet</L>
<L>Gij arau&yogh;t him wi&thorn; a staf gret:</L>
<L>Swiche a strok he him &yogh;af,</L>
<L>&THORN;at his breyn fley about &thorn;e staf.</L>
<L>Seyd &thorn;e douk, 'whi destow &thorn;is?</L>
<L N="6250">Wi&thorn; hors tow wor&thorn; to-drawen, y-wis.</L>
<L>Whi hastow mi man y-slawe?</L>
<L>Hou dorstow bigin &thorn;at plawe?'</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="section">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'Sir,' qua&thorn; Gij, 'herken to me,<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="5931"></L>
<L>Anon ichil telle to &thorn;e:</L>
<L N="6255">Into &thorn;e tour ich was y-gon,</L>
<L>For to se &thorn;e esters ichon;</L>
<L>&THORN;er ich fond &thorn;is feloun,</L>
<L>&amp; spac to Tirri in &thorn;e prisoun,</L>
<L>&amp; mete him brou&yogh;t gret plente.</L>
<L N="6260">&THORN;o ich it seye it of-&thorn;ou&yogh;t me.
<PB REF="00000340.tif" N="336"></L>
<L>Wi&thorn; his fest he me smot,</L>
<L>&THORN;erfore ichim suwed, god it wot,</L>
<L>&amp; smot him so &thorn;ou mi&yogh;t se.<MILESTONE N="141a:a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&THORN;e gilt, sir, for-&yogh;iue &thorn;ou me.</L>
<L N="6265">So&thorn;e to sigge in &thorn;is stede,</L>
<L>For &thorn;ine anour ich it dede,</L>
<L>&THORN;at o&thorn;er bi him y-warned be</L>
<L>To fede &thorn;i prisoun wi&thorn;-outen &thorn;e.'</L>
<L>&THORN;e douk gret o&thorn; swore &thorn;o,</L>
<L N="6270">&THORN;at &yogh;if he o&thorn;er-loker had do</L>
<L>He wor&thorn; to-drawe, o&thorn;er an-hong,</L>
<L>Or o&thorn;er schames de&thorn; to afong;</L>
<L>'Ac now for&yogh;iuen it &thorn;e be.'</L>
<L>Gij him &thorn;onked on his kne.</L>
<L N="6275">Sone so &thorn;e ni&yogh;t him come,</L>
<L>Gij into &thorn;e cite nome:</L>
<L>Mete anou&yogh; he bou&yogh;t &thorn;ere,</L>
<L>And to Tirri he gan it bere.</L>
<L>&THORN;us he dede y not hou long,</L>
<L N="6280">Michel he slaked his pine strong,</L>
<L>Alle his bendes do&thorn; oway,</L>
<L>And slake&thorn; his pine so michel so he may.</L>
<L>Into a chaumber<NOTE PLACE="marg">The <I>u</I> in chaumber has a stroke too many.</NOTE> he go&thorn; on a day,<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="5967"></L>
<L>&THORN;erin he fond &thorn;at fair may,</L>
<L N="6285">&THORN;at biment hir strongliche</L>
<L>For hir leman sche loued so miche.</L>
<L>Gij seyd to hir, 'maiden fre,</L>
<L>Wele &thorn;ou owest to knowe me:</L>
<L>Gij of Warwike mi name is,</L>
<L N="6290">Icham &thorn;i lemanes felawe, y-wis.</L>
<L>In &thorn;is maner y-comen icham,</L>
<L>For y nold be knowen of no man,</L>
<L>And for to deliuer &thorn;i leman</L>
<L>&THORN;at ich michel gode an.'</L>
<L N="6295">When &thorn;e maiden herd &thorn;is,</L>
<L>&THORN;at it was Gij, for so&thorn;e y-wis,
<PB REF="00000342.tif" N="338"></L>
<L>For blisse sche fel aswon adoun,</L>
<L>And vp hir toke &thorn;e gode Gyoun.</L>
<L>'Maiden,' he seyd, 'lete now be:</L>
<L N="6300">Wiltow now schende me?</L>
<L>&YOGH;if ani me perceiue mi&yogh;t</L>
<L>Ich were y-honged anon ri&yogh;t.'</L>
<L>'Merci, sir Gij,' seyd &thorn;at may,</L>
<L>'Now wi&thorn;in &thorn;e &thorn;ridde day</L>
<L N="6305">To him spoused schal y be;</L>
<L>Ac o &thorn;ing ich haue bi&thorn;ou&yogh;t me,</L>
<L>&THORN;at ichil mi-selue sle<MILESTONE N="141a:b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&THORN;at day &thorn;at y schal spoused be.'</L>
<L>Gij seyd, 'no do nou&yogh;t so,</L>
<L N="6310">Ac alle his wille &thorn;ou schalt do,</L>
<L>And ar he to &thorn;e chirche come</L>
<L>Y schal mete him atte frome:</L>
<L>His heued fro &thorn;e bodi schal fle,</L>
<L>&amp; lede y schal &thorn;e for&thorn; wi&thorn; me.'</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="section">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="6315">Now is Gij &thorn;ennes y-gon hom,<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="5999"></L>
<L>And also swi&thorn;e so ni&yogh;t<NOTE PLACE="marg">The <I>n</I> in <I>ni&yogh;t</I> on a <I>c</I> only partially erased.</NOTE> come</L>
<L>To &thorn;e prisoun anon he &yogh;ede,</L>
<L>And deliuerd his felawe in &thorn;at stede.</L>
<L>'Sir Tirri,' he seyd, 'for&thorn; &thorn;ou go</L>
<L N="6320">(Ni&yogh;t no day no swike &thorn;ou no)</L>
<L>Ri&yogh;t to Amis of<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>to</I> MS.</NOTE> &thorn;e Mounteyne,</L>
<L>&THORN;at wone&thorn; in &thorn;e marche of Almeyne.</L>
<L>On mine half grete him wele bi me.</L>
<L>&THORN;ider &thorn;ou go, &amp; ful wele rest &thorn;e,</L>
<L N="6325">Fort<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>t</I> added above the line.</NOTE> ich com, or man for me.'</L>
<L>'Ble&thorn;eliche, sir,' &thorn;an seyd he.</L>
<L>Hye kisten hem, and for&thorn; &yogh;ede &thorn;o;</L>
<L>At her parting hem was ful wo.</L>
<L>Ai&thorn;er for o&thorn;er for gret pite</L>
<L N="6330">In gret periil hadde y-be.</L>
<L>Gi lete him of &thorn;e tour &thorn;o,</L>
<L>Bitau&yogh;t him god, &amp; lete him go.
<PB REF="00000344.tif" N="340"></L>
<L>Gij bileft, &amp; Tirri is for&thorn; y-fare:</L>
<L>Of alle ni&yogh;t no hadde he rest &thorn;are.</L>
<L N="6335">So long is Tirri for&thorn; y-gon,<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="6027"></L>
<L>To &thorn;e Mounteyn he com anon;</L>
<L>A castel &thorn;er was fair wi&thorn;alle,</L>
<L>And strong cite biloken wi&thorn; walle;</L>
<L>Fair halles &amp; toures also</L>
<L N="6340">In &thorn;e cite were mani &amp; mo.</L>
<L>In &thorn;at on half orn &thorn;e riuer,</L>
<L>In &thorn;at o&thorn;er half forest wi&thorn; wilde dere.</L>
<L>Into &thorn;e cite he is y-go,</L>
<L>And to &thorn;e maister palays he &yogh;ede &thorn;o.</L>
<L N="6345">He fond Amis atte ches pleyinge</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; his felawes, fair gamen giuing.</L>
<L>&THORN;ritti kni&yogh;tes were in halle also</L>
<L>His soudours were, his wil to do,</L>
<L>&THORN;at wi&thorn; Amis bileften he</L>
<L N="6350">For wer &thorn;at was in &thorn;at cuntre.</L>
<L>'Sir,' qua&thorn; Tirri, '&yogh;if it be &thorn;i wille,<MILESTONE N="141b:a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Vnder-stond &amp; speke me tille</L>
<L>Al priueliche, y &thorn;e biseche,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;i folk no here our speche.'</L>
<L N="6355">Amis answerd, 'wel ble&thorn;eliche</L>
<L>Wille ich it do &amp; loueliche.'</L>
<L>Fram &thorn;e cheker he is y-go,</L>
<L>And to a windowe he cleped him &thorn;o.</L>
<L>'Sir Amis,' seyd Tirri,<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="6043"></L>
<L N="6360">'Often &thorn;e grete&thorn; wele sir Gij;</L>
<L>&amp; hider to &yogh;ou he sent me,</L>
<L>For to soiourne here wi&thorn; &thorn;e,</L>
<L>Fort he may hider come,</L>
<L>O&thorn;er ano&thorn;er send for him atte frome.'</L>
<L N="6365">'Sir,' qua&thorn; Amis, 'miche &thorn;anke haue he,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he &thorn;e sent hider to me.</L>
<L>What is &thorn;i name? say &thorn;ou me.'</L>
<L>'Ichil &thorn;e telle, sir,' qua&thorn; he:
<PB REF="00000346.tif" N="342"></L>
<L>'Tirri of Gormoise mi name is,</L>
<L N="6370">Aschaped of strong prisoun, y-wis.'</L>
<L>'Sir Tirri,' &thorn;an seyd he,</L>
<L>'Welcome in-to &thorn;is cuntre!'</L>
<L>He kist him an hundred si&thorn;e,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; ey&yogh;en he wepe, so was he bli&thorn;e.</L>
<L N="6375">&amp; for he him so miseise<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>so miseise</I> looks like <I>sounseise</I> in MS.</NOTE> y-seye</L>
<L>Of prisoun aschaped, bli&thorn;e was hye.</L>
<L>He dede him ba&thorn;e, sikerly,</L>
<L>And al &thorn;ing di&yogh;t him redi.</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; riche clo&thorn;es<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>c</I> added above the line.</NOTE> he dede him schrede,</L>
<L N="6380">&amp; fond him alle &thorn;at him was nede.</L>
<L>He &yogh;af him armes and riche stede,</L>
<L>&amp; di&yogh;t him &thorn;er alle wi&thorn; prede.</L>
<L>&THORN;ennes no went he for no &thorn;ing,</L>
<L>Er he of Gij hadde tiding.</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="section">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="6385">Of &thorn;e douk ichil &yogh;ou telle,<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="6069"></L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;an of Gij, &yogh;if &yogh;e wille.</L>
<L>&THORN;e douk of-sent his barnage in hast,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ai com to him ri&yogh;t fast</L>
<L>Into &thorn;e cite of Pauie,</L>
<L N="6390">Alle &thorn;e Lombardes of Lombardie.</L>
<L>When &thorn;e time it comen was,</L>
<L>&THORN;e douk was bli&thorn;e &amp; glad in &thorn;at cas.</L>
<L>To &thorn;e maiden he come swi&thorn;e,</L>
<L>As he &thorn;at was glad &amp; bli&thorn;e,</L>
<L N="6395">And seyd, 'leman, glad make &thorn;e;<MILESTONE N="141b:b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Today &thorn;ou schalt y-spoused be.'</L>
<L>'Sir,' sche seyd, 'wi&thorn; gode wille</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;ine hest ichil fulfille.'</L>
<L>He schred hir swi&thorn;e wele, y-wis</L>
<L N="6400">Wi&thorn; riche clo&thorn;es alle of pris;</L>
<L>He sette hir on a palfrey, &thorn;at &yogh;ongling,</L>
<L>Better no bistrode neuer no king.</L>
<L>Riche anou&yogh; &thorn;at atire was</L>
<L>Of gold &amp; siluer: no no&thorn;er &thorn;er nas.
<PB REF="00000348.tif" N="344"></L>
<L N="6405">Toward a chirche went hye;</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; ioie he wend hir to spousi.</L>
<L>&para; Gij armed him wel richeliche</L>
<L>Alto his wille stalwor&thorn;liche</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; armes &thorn;e maiden him had bitou&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="6410">&THORN;at were &thorn;e douke to present brou&yogh;t.</L>
<L>His gode stede he bi-strod,</L>
<L>And of-tok hem wi&thorn;-outen abod.</L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L N="6415">'Douk Otus, vnder-stond to me:</L>
<L>No go no for&thorn;er, ich hot &thorn;e.</L>
<L>Vnder-stond &thorn;e of &thorn;at traisoun</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ou dest to sir Gyoun,</L>
<L>Also he com fram Boneuent:</L>
<L N="6420">&YOGH;ete is mi hert &thorn;er-fore in turment;</L>
<L>&amp; se&thorn;&thorn;en &thorn;ou dest me a gret traisoun,</L>
<L>&THORN;o &thorn;ou Tirri dest in &thorn;i prisoun.</L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L N="6425">Icham Gij &thorn;at to &thorn;e speke:</L>
<L>&YOGH;ete today y &thorn;enk to ben awreke.'</L>
<L>&THORN;urch &thorn;e bodi he smot him anon</L>
<L>Bifor &thorn;e Lombardes euerichon,</L>
<L>And swore bi god, heuen king,</L>
<L N="6430">&YOGH;if<NOTE PLACE="marg">The <I>f</I> on an erasure.</NOTE> him neyed ani &thorn;ing,</L>
<L>&THORN;at heued he schuld &thorn;er forgon.</L>
<L>To &thorn;at maiden he cam anon,</L>
<L>Bitven his armes &thorn;e maiden he nam,</L>
<L>&amp; sett hir biforn him: oway he ran.</L>
<L N="6435">Swi&thorn;e owaiward &thorn;an rod he:</L>
<L>&THORN;e noise aros in &thorn;at cite.<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="6121"></L>
<L>Wi&thorn; gret streng&thorn;e &thorn;ai driuen Gi:</L>
<L>He pase&thorn; hem: o&yogh;ain went hij.</L>
<L>O&yogh;ain &thorn;ai went to &thorn;at bodi ri&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="6440">Ac a child-&yogh;ong man, apli&yogh;t,
<PB REF="00000350.tif" N="346"></L>
<L>&THORN;at was &thorn;e doukes kinseman</L>
<L>(Berard was his ri&yogh;t nam),</L>
<L>Alle on he folwed sir Gij<MILESTONE N="142a:a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>(He no hadde felawe no frend him bi)</L>
<L N="6445">Wi&thorn; scheld &amp; spere opon his stede:</L>
<L>A gode kni&yogh;t he was at nede.</L>
<L>He folwed Gij fif mile,</L>
<L>&THORN;at Gij fore in a litel while.</L>
<L>'Gij,' he seyd, 'turn o&yogh;e,</L>
<L N="6450">So help &thorn;e Crist, &amp; iuste wi&thorn; me.'</L>
<L>Gij turned him wel an hast,</L>
<L>For he no was nou&yogh;t of him agast.</L>
<L>&THORN;e maiden he to grounde sett,</L>
<L>&amp; di&yogh;t his armes wi&thorn;-outen lett,</L>
<L N="6455">&amp; went to him wi&thorn; gret mi&yogh;t,</L>
<L>&amp; he to him anon ri&yogh;t.</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;e &yogh;ong man smot first Gij</L>
<L>&THORN;urch &thorn;e scheld, sikerli:</L>
<L>He carf &thorn;e brini &thorn;at newe was,</L>
<L N="6460">Nou&yogh;t wor&thorn; a botoun it nas.</L>
<L>Gij of &thorn;at strok wonder ha&thorn;.</L>
<L>Ano&thorn;er strok<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>Ano&thorn;er strok</I> on an erasure.</NOTE> sir Gij him &yogh;af:</L>
<L>Gij anon smot &thorn;at &yogh;ong man,</L>
<L>&THORN;urch his scheld anon it ran,</L>
<L N="6465">&amp; &thorn;urch &thorn;e scholder he &yogh;af him wounde,</L>
<L>&THORN;at hors &amp; man it fel to grounde.</L>
<L>&amp; when &thorn;e &yogh;ongman was y-falle<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="6145"></L>
<L>Vp he stert sone wi&thorn;-alle.</L>
<L>Anon his swerd he ha&thorn; out drawe,</L>
<L N="6470">His hors he wold habbe y-slawe.</L>
<L>'Hors,' he seyd, 'acursed &thorn;ou be,</L>
<L>When &thorn;ou no mi&yogh;t vp-hold me.</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ou dye it is ri&yogh;t,</L>
<L>Se&thorn;&thorn;en &thorn;ou in &thorn;e has no mi&yogh;t.</L>
<L N="6475">Gij,' qua&thorn; Berard,<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>berarnd</I> MS.</NOTE> 'wende to me,</L>
<L>&amp; of &thorn;ine hauberk vnarmi &thorn;e:
<PB REF="00000351.tif" N="347"></L>
<L>In pleyn armes wil we fi&yogh;t,</L>
<L>And so we may asay our mi&yogh;t.</L>
<L>Bot ich &thorn;ine heued binim &thorn;e,</L>
<L N="6480">Or ich out of &thorn;is place te,</L>
<L>Neuer honour ich no bidde,</L>
<L>No neuer a day lenger to libbe.'</L>
<L>'Frende,' qua&thorn; Gij, 'nil y nou&yogh;t so.</L>
<L>To bataile we schul &yogh;ete cum bo.'</L>
<L N="6485">&THORN;e maiden he nam &amp; for&thorn; ladde,</L>
<L>&amp; passed a riuer, &amp; nou&yogh;[t] no drad.</L>
<L>&THORN;e &yogh;ongman went him o&yogh;e<MILESTONE N="142a:b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Alle sori in-to &thorn;at cite.</L>
<L>&THORN;e douk &thorn;ai birid wor&thorn;schipliche</L>
<L N="6490">In a chirche of Paui, sikerliche.</L>
<L>&THORN;e &yogh;ongman to &thorn;emperour is gon,</L>
<L>&amp; told him of Otus de&thorn; anon.</L>
<L>&THORN;emperour alle his lond him &yogh;eld,</L>
<L>&amp; wi&thorn; &thorn;at<NOTE PLACE="marg">So MS., not <I>gret</I>. knighted him,</NOTE> wor&thorn;schip him at-held.</L>
<L N="6495">Armes he &yogh;af him hastiliche,</L>
<L>He loued him wel swi&thorn;e miche.</L>
<L>Of Almaine he made him steward,</L>
<L>&THORN;at fel mani a man swi&thorn;e hard.</L>
<L>Gij wi&thorn; &thorn;at maiden is for&thorn; y-go,<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="6175"></L>
<L N="6500">&amp; &thorn;an newed alle hir wo.</L>
<L>'Sir Gij,' sche seyd, 'what schal y do?</L>
<L>Mi leman no se y<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>sey</I> MS. as one word.</NOTE> neuer mo.</L>
<L>Dye y schal wi&thorn; sorwe &amp; care.</L>
<L>Now wold god ich wer &thorn;are:</L>
<L N="6505">Wi&thorn; him ded ich wold be;</L>
<L>&amp; it so were wele wer me.'</L>
<L>Gij answerd wele &thorn;at maide,<NOTE PLACE="marg">The <I>i</I> added above the line.</NOTE></L>
<L>And to hir sweteliche he seyd:</L>
<L>'Tirri nis bot gode, siker &thorn;ou be:</L>
<L N="6510">Alle in gode point &thorn;ou schalt him se.</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; &thorn;e iaioler ich haue speke so,</L>
<L>&THORN;at alle his wille he wil do.'
<PB REF="00000352.tif" N="348"></L>
<L>So long for&thorn; wenten he,<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="6187"></L>
<L>&THORN;at hij come to &thorn;at cite</L>
<L N="6515">Of<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>Of &thorn;at</I> MS.</NOTE> Mounteyne, &thorn;at feir was:</L>
<L>So &thorn;ai went [in] wi&thorn; ioie &amp; solas.</L>
<L>When he into &thorn;e halle come,</L>
<L>Amis him knew ri&yogh;t anon.</L>
<L>When he him seye &thorn;an seyd he,</L>
<L N="6520">'Sir Gij, welcom mot &thorn;ou be.'</L>
<L>When sir Tirri Gij y-se&thorn;</L>
<L>&amp; Oisel, &thorn;at him was so lef,</L>
<L>Michel ioie he made Gij &thorn;o,</L>
<L>&THORN;at maiden he nam in his armes to.</L>
<L N="6525">'Gij,' he seyd, 'welcome &thorn;ou be.</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;us asembled now be we!</L>
<L>Nold god &amp; our leuedi</L>
<L>&THORN;at mi lef be schent of hir bodi.'</L>
<L>&THORN;ai kisten hem togider anon,</L>
<L N="6530">For ioie &thorn;ai wepen euerichon.</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="section">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>When Oisel y-se&thorn; sir Tirri,<MILESTONE N="142b:a" UNIT="folio"><MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="6209"></L>
<L>&THORN;at was hir lef &amp; hir ami,</L>
<L>For ioie sche swoned omong hem.</L>
<L>&THORN;er wende sche nou&yogh;t to finden him.</L>
<L N="6535">Tirri nam hir in his armes tvo,</L>
<L>&amp; sweteliche seyd to hir &thorn;o,</L>
<L>'Mi swete leman, no drede &thorn;e nou&yogh;t:</L>
<L>Hole &amp; sounde icham hider brou&yogh;t.'</L>
<L>Amonges hem was ioie &amp; blis,</L>
<L N="6540">And soiournd &thorn;ere,<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>to her wille</I> MS.</NOTE> y-wis,</L>
<L>To her wille in &thorn;at palais:</L>
<L>Sir Amis was hende &amp; curteys.</L>
<L>So on a day bi&thorn;ou&yogh;t him sir Gij<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="6223"></L>
<L>&THORN;at long soiournd hadden hy.</L>
<L N="6545">Amis he cleped to him &amp; sir Tirri:</L>
<L>'Herkeni&thorn; to me,' seyd sir Gij.</L>
<L>'Soiournd we haue here anow:</L>
<L>Now is time we go fram &yogh;ou
<PB REF="00000354.tif" N="350"></L>
<L>To Gormoise to &thorn;erl Aubri:</L>
<L N="6550">Wele y wot he is for ous sori.</L>
<L>Of-sende ichil baroun &amp; kni&yogh;tes,</L>
<L>&amp; ern ichil opon &thorn;e douk wi&thorn; gret mi&yogh;tes,</L>
<L>&amp; mine felawes out of prisoun bring:<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>bring</I> Turnbull, <I>binde</I> MS.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ich no may hem for&yogh;ete for no &thorn;ing.</L>
<L N="6555">Ich man schal his mi&yogh;t don,</L>
<L>For to awreke him of his fon.'</L>
<L>'Sir,' qua&thorn; Amis, 'ichil go wi&thorn; &thorn;e,</L>
<L>And a &thorn;ousend kni&yogh;tes for&thorn; wi&thorn; me,</L>
<L>A &thorn;ousend seriauns also</L>
<L N="6560">Wele on hors, wi&thorn;-outen mo.'</L>
<L>'Gramerci, sir,' &thorn;an seyd Gij,</L>
<L>'On &thorn;e al mi trust is, sikerli.'</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="section">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Amis of-sent his kni&yogh;tes anon,</L>
<L>And ha&thorn; asembled hem euerichon,</L>
<L N="6565">His seriauns he dede also,</L>
<L>&THORN;e best &thorn;at mi&yogh;t to fi&yogh;t go.</L>
<L>When &thorn;at &thorn;ai wer al redi<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="6249"></L>
<L>for&thorn; &thorn;ai wenten hastily.</L>
<L>To-ward Gormoise hij go&thorn;,</L>
<L N="6570">Mani man &thorn;ai made wel wro&thorn;:</L>
<L>&THORN;ai nimen castels &amp; cites,</L>
<L>&amp; destruen alle &thorn;e cuntres.</L>
<L>To Gormoise &thorn;ai ben y-come:</L>
<L>Glad &thorn;ai ben alle &amp; some,</L>
<L N="6575">Ouer alle o&thorn;er &thorn;erl Aubri.<MILESTONE N="142b:b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>When he se&thorn; his sone Tirri</L>
<L>He fel aswon for ioie &thorn;o:</L>
<L>He wende he had ben forlorn for euer mo.</L>
<L>&THORN;er was ioie &amp; miche<NOTE PLACE="marg">The <I>m</I> in <I>miche</I> not quite distinct.</NOTE> blis</L>
<L N="6580">Bitven &thorn;e fader &amp; &thorn;e sone, y-wis.</L>
<L>Euerich told o&thorn;er, &amp; for&yogh;at nou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>Hou Gij hem ha&thorn; fram de&thorn; y-brou&yogh;t.</L>
<L>&para; Gij nou&yogh;t for-&yogh;ete nold,</L>
<L>Asembled he ha&thorn; his kni&yogh;tes bold.
<PB REF="00000356.tif" N="352"></L>
<L N="6585">&THORN;e douk he ha&thorn; a grete harm y-do,</L>
<L>He &thorn;ou&yogh;t for to awreke him so.</L>
<L>When &thorn;e douk Loer herd &thorn;is tiding,</L>
<L>&THORN;at Gij and Tirri were coming,<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="6273"></L>
<L>His douhte[r] Oysel also,</L>
<L N="6590">Wel glad &amp; bli&thorn;e he was &thorn;o.</L>
<L>Herhaud he cleped him to,</L>
<L>&amp; teld him &thorn;e so&thorn;e &thorn;o,</L>
<L>&THORN;at Gij and Tirri wer y-come,</L>
<L>&amp; hadde on hem wer y-nome,</L>
<L N="6595">Wi&thorn; hem was &thorn;erl Amis</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; ferred of miche pris.</L>
<L>When Herhaud y-herd &thorn;is,</L>
<L>&THORN;at Gij and Tirri comen is,</L>
<L>Neuer nas he so bli&thorn;e:</L>
<L N="6600">God he &thorn;onked mani si&thorn;e.</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="section">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'Sir Herhaud,' seyd &thorn;e douk Loer,</L>
<L>'Ichil &thorn;e make messanger:</L>
<L>To &thorn;erl Aubri &thorn;ou schal go,</L>
<L>&amp; Gij, &amp; Tirri, &amp; sigge hem so,</L>
<L N="6605">&THORN;at ich wi&thorn; hem acord wille</L>
<L>Of alle &thorn;at &thorn;ai cun to me telle.</L>
<L>Sir Tirri ichil mi douhter &yogh;iue,</L>
<L>&amp; half mi lond while &thorn;at y liue.</L>
<L>Ichil &thorn;at &thorn;ou wittnesse me</L>
<L N="6610">&THORN;at &thorn;e loue ste[de]fast be.'</L>
<L>'Sir,' qua&thorn; Herhaud, 'ichil so</L>
<L>Alle mi mi&yogh;t do &thorn;er-to.'</L>
<L>&THORN;e douke of-sent his prisouns alle,</L>
<L>&amp; dede hem arme swi&thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="marg">One or two letters erased after <I>swi&thorn;e</I>.</NOTE> snelle,</L>
<L N="6615">&amp; hete hem &thorn;at &thorn;ai failed nou&yogh;t<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="6305"></L>
<L>Of &thorn;at &thorn;ai hadde &thorn;ider y-brou&yogh;t.</L>
<L>'For&thorn; wi&thorn; Herhaud &yogh;e schal gon,</L>
<L>&THORN;e acord to make ri&yogh;t anon.'</L>
<L>Herhaud made him redi &thorn;o,</L>
<L N="6620">Ri&yogh;t into Gormoise he is y-go,<MILESTONE N="143a:a" UNIT="folio">
<PB REF="00000358.tif" N="354"></L>
<L>&amp; wi&thorn; him went alle &thorn;e kni&yogh;tes,</L>
<L>Acord to make anon ri&yogh;tes.</L>
<L>Gij cam on a day fram hunting,</L>
<L>&THORN;erl Amis, &amp; Tirri &thorn;e &yogh;ing,</L>
<L N="6625">&amp; mo &thorn;an an hundred kni&yogh;t,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; swerd bigirt, y &yogh;ou pli&yogh;t.</L>
<L>Toward Gormoise &thorn;ai ben y-go,</L>
<L>Bisiden hem &thorn;ai loked &thorn;o;</L>
<L>So mani kni&yogh;tes &thorn;ai seye coming,</L>
<L N="6630">Of traisoun &thorn;ai were dredeing.</L>
<L>&THORN;an seyd [of] &thorn;e Mountayn Amis,</L>
<L>'A gret ferd y se, y-wis.</L>
<L>Y not what folk it be:</L>
<L>Hiderward &thorn;ai com, so &thorn;enke&thorn; me.'</L>
<L N="6635">Opon his gode stede he wond</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; swerd &amp; spere in his hond.</L>
<L>&THORN;iderward he is y-go,</L>
<L>To hem he com wel sone &thorn;o.</L>
<L>&THORN;o he gan hem com neye</L>
<L N="6640">Herhaud of Ardern<NOTE PLACE="marg">The <I>d</I> altered from <I>t.</I></NOTE> &thorn;er he seye</L>
<L>He oxed him whennes he come.</L>
<L>'Where is Gij?' he seyd anon.</L>
<L>'Sir,' qua&thorn; he, 'ichil &thorn;e telle,</L>
<L>&amp; lade &thorn;e to him wi&thorn; gode wille.</L>
<L N="6645">Fram dere hunting y-comen he is:</L>
<L>Biside &thorn;anne hulle ichim lete, y-wis.'</L>
<L>Qua&thorn; Herhaud, 'felawes, wil we go.'</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; sporres hij smiten her stedes &thorn;o:</L>
<L>Swi&thorn;e &thorn;ai riden wi&thorn; gret hy.</L>
<L N="6650">When &thorn;ai seye Gij &amp; sir Tirri,</L>
<L>'God,' qua&thorn; Gij, 'Herhaud y se</L>
<L>&amp; alle min feren, so &thorn;enke&thorn; me:</L>
<L>&THORN;ai ben out of prisoun y-gon</L>
<L>O&thorn;er quite-cleymed ichon.'</L>
<L N="6655">To kissen Herhaud &thorn;ai hem do,<NOTE PLACE="marg">The <I>d</I> altered from <I>t.</I></NOTE><MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="6349"></L>
<L>Wel gret ioie &thorn;ai maden &thorn;o.
<PB REF="00000360.tif" N="356"></L>
<L>'Sir Tirri,' qua&thorn; Herhaud &thorn;e fre,</L>
<L>'Gode conseyl y telle to &thorn;e.</L>
<L>&THORN;e sent to grete &thorn;e douk Loer,</L>
<L N="6660">Whom ich loue wi&thorn; hert cler:</L>
<L>Wor&thorn;schiped he ha&thorn; me miche,</L>
<L>And ouer alle o&thorn;er loued, sikerliche.</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; &thorn;e he wil acorded be,<MILESTONE N="143a:b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And swi&thorn;e miche he loue&thorn; &thorn;e.</L>
<L N="6665">&THORN;ou schalt his douhter spousi:</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; half his lond he wille &thorn;e feffi;</L>
<L>And wi&thorn; &thorn;i fader he wil acordy,</L>
<L>And allso wi&thorn; &thorn;e, sir Gij:</L>
<L>In alle maner to &thorn;i wille</L>
<L N="6670">He wille amende, for so&thorn;e y telle.</L>
<L>Ichil &thorn;er-of his borwe be,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he do wil as y sigge to &thorn;e.'</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;ai bisou&yogh;ten sir Gij,</L>
<L>And so &thorn;ai dede &thorn;erl Tirri,</L>
<L N="6675">&THORN;at &thorn;ai schuld wi&thorn; him acordy,</L>
<L>For he was michel to praisy.</L>
<L>So long &thorn;ai bisou&yogh;t him<NOTE PLACE="marg">Read <I>hem</I>?</NOTE> so,</L>
<L>And wi&thorn; hem Amis, &thorn;at &thorn;er was &thorn;o.</L>
<L>&THORN;er of acord speken he,</L>
<L N="6680">&THORN;at it schuld treuwe be.</L>
<L>To &thorn;e cite &thorn;ai ben y-gon,</L>
<L>&amp; teld &thorn;erl Aubri anon</L>
<L>Hou &thorn;at Herhaud was y-come,</L>
<L>And hadde &thorn;e acord vnder-nome,</L>
<L N="6685">&THORN;erl graunted ra&thorn;e &amp; snelle</L>
<L>&THORN;e acord to Herhaudes wille.</L>
<L>No soiournd &thorn;ai nou&yogh;t long &thorn;o,<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="6383"></L>
<L>Bot ri&yogh;t to Loreyn &thorn;ai ben y-go:</L>
<L>&THORN;erl Aubri &amp; Tirri his sone,</L>
<L N="6690">Gij &amp; Herhaud ben<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>ben</I> a little indistinct.</NOTE> &thorn;ider y-come,</L>
<L>&amp; of o&thorn;er kni&yogh;tes mani also,</L>
<L>&THORN;at bli&thorn;e were &thorn;ider to go.
<PB REF="00000362.tif" N="358"></L>
<L>&THORN;erl Aubri, &amp; Tirri his sone,</L>
<L>Gij, Herhaud, &amp; Amis &thorn;ider come.</L>
<L N="6695">Mani was &thorn;e gentil kni&yogh;t</L>
<L>&THORN;at wi&thorn; hem went &thorn;o ri&yogh;t.</L>
<L>To Loreyne &thorn;ai ben comen, y-wis:</L>
<L>&THORN;e douke hem vnderfeng<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>vnderfende</I> MS.</NOTE> wi&thorn; blis.</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; him &thorn;ai were acorded alle,</L>
<L N="6700">&amp; &thorn;e misdede for&yogh;euen snelle.</L>
<L>Gret joie &thorn;ai maden in &thorn;e cite</L>
<L>&THORN;at hij so fair acorded be.</L>
<L>&THORN;e douk &yogh;af Tirri his douhter &thorn;o,</L>
<L>And half his lond wi&thorn; hir also,</L>
<L N="6705">Bifor barouns &amp; kni&yogh;tes fre,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;er were of mani cuntre:</L>
<L>Bridal sone &thorn;ai han y-hold:<MILESTONE N="143b:a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Of erls, &amp; of barouns bold,</L>
<L>&amp; of emperours, &amp; of king</L>
<L N="6710">Nas neuer non so riche gestening.</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;e kni&yogh;tes nomen her leue anon,<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="6403"></L>
<L>Vnto her cuntres &thorn;ai ben y-gon:</L>
<L>Sir Gij soiournd &thorn;are.</L>
<L>On a day he is &thorn;ennes y-fare:</L>
<L N="6715">&THORN;e douk Loer &amp; mani a man</L>
<L>In hunting &thorn;ai were toward Braban;</L>
<L>On hunting went &thorn;erl Tirri</L>
<L>&amp; mani in his compeynie.</L>
<L>&THORN;ai comen into a fair forest,</L>
<L N="6720">&THORN;er &thorn;ai fond a bore, a wilde best.</L>
<L>&THORN;ai vncoupled her houndes alle,</L>
<L>&amp; lete hem ern swi&thorn; snelle.</L>
<L>&THORN;e bore fleing swi&thorn;e he ge&thorn;,</L>
<L>&amp; mani of &thorn;e houndes harme he de&thorn;:</L>
<L N="6725">An hundred he slou&yogh; and mo,</L>
<L>Out of &thorn;at cuntre he is sone y-go.</L>
<L>&THORN;e wisest hunt folwe&thorn; fast,</L>
<L>Huwe&thorn; &amp; grede&thorn; wi&thorn; gret blast.
<PB REF="00000363.tif" N="359"></L>
<L>Of huntes ne of houndes adrad he:</L>
<L N="6730">He ouer-ernnes dounes &amp; cuntre,</L>
<L>&THORN;e brod lond, and &thorn;e valays:</L>
<L>Folwed he is ich weys.</L>
<L>Hij of-ernned her stedes &thorn;o,</L>
<L>Of him wondred kni&yogh;tes, huntes also.</L>
<L N="6735">Alle &thorn;e houndes &thorn;at folwed him &thorn;ere</L>
<L>O&yogh;ain turned, o&thorn;er ded were,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn;outen blod houndes &thorn;re:</L>
<L>Into Braban folwed he.</L>
<L>&THORN;er nas hunt no kni&yogh;t non,</L>
<L N="6740">Seriaunt no sweyn no grom</L>
<L>&THORN;at wist widerward &thorn;e bore gan te,</L>
<L>Into whiche lond no what cuntre.</L>
<L>Gij him folwed on his stede,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; swerd in hond after he &yogh;ede,</L>
<L N="6745">&amp; wi&thorn; horn oft bloweing,</L>
<L>&THORN;e bore swi&thorn;e driueing.<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="6445"></L>
<L>Gij drof<NOTE PLACE="marg">A letter erased before <I>d.</I></NOTE> &thorn;at swine wi&thorn; game &amp; gle<NOTE PLACE="marg">The <I>g</I> altered from <I>b.</I></NOTE></L>
<L>Right into Breteyne &thorn;an went he.</L>
<L>Into a forest &thorn;at<NOTE PLACE="marg">The <I>t</I> added above the line.</NOTE> swine him &yogh;ede,</L>
<L N="6750">Into a &thorn;icke hegges he gan him hede.</L>
<L>&THORN;er he stod at abay,<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>a bay</I> MS.</NOTE><MILESTONE N="143b:b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&amp; werd him while &thorn;at he may.</L>
<L>When Gij &thorn;at stern swine y sey</L>
<L>Adoun he lepe of his stede heye:</L>
<L N="6755">Wi&thorn; bo&thorn;e honden &thorn;at swerd he held,</L>
<L>&amp; cam to &thorn;e bore as a kni&yogh;t beld.</L>
<L>&THORN;at swine anon o&yogh;ain him com,</L>
<L>And Gij smertlich smot him anon,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;e hert he clef euen atvo:</L>
<L N="6760">Alle ded he fel to grounde &thorn;o.</L>
<L>He open[ed] &thorn;at swine &amp; blewe priis.</L>
<L>Alon he was, him mi&yogh;t agriis:</L>
<L>Alto fer he was fram his kni&yogh;t.</L>
<L>Bot on him &thorn;inke god almi&yogh;t,
<PB REF="00000364.tif" N="360"></L>
<L N="6765">Sone he wor&thorn; in a peril strong,</L>
<L>Be it wi&thorn; ri&yogh;t, be it wi&thorn; wrong.</L>
<L>&THORN;o Gij hadde opened &thorn;at swine snelle</L>
<L>He gan to blowe as y &yogh;ou telle.</L>
<L>'Bi god,' qua&thorn; &thorn;erl Florentin,</L>
<L N="6770">'Who mai &thorn;at be, for seyn Martin,<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="6467"></L>
<L>&THORN;at ich here in mi forest blowe?</L>
<L>Hert o&thorn;er bore he ha&thorn; doun &thorn;rowe.'</L>
<L>He cleped to him a kni&yogh;t &yogh;ing,</L>
<L>His sone he was, a feir &yogh;ongling.</L>
<L N="6775">'Sone,' he seyd, 'to hors &thorn;ou go,</L>
<L>&amp; who so it be, bring him me to.'</L>
<L>'Sir, y graunt &thorn;at it be so.'</L>
<L>Anon he lepe on hors &thorn;o:</L>
<L>Into &thorn;e forest he is y-fare,</L>
<L N="6780">&amp; Gij he fond ful sone &thorn;are.</L>
<L>An staf he bar of holin tre:</L>
<L>Gret wo &thorn;er-wi&thorn; wrou&yogh;t he.</L>
<L>'Lording,' he seyd, 'who artow</L>
<L>In mi lordes forest is comen now</L>
<L N="6785">Wi&thorn;-outen leue of mi lord?</L>
<L>In iuel time &thorn;ou come, at o word:</L>
<L>When &thorn;ou hast y-nomen his swin</L>
<L>No leue haddestow of him.</L>
<L>&THORN;at hors anon &thorn;ou take to me,</L>
<L N="6790">&THORN;er-on no schaltow ride, y telle &thorn;e.'</L>
<L>'Leue frende,' qua&thorn; Gij, '&thorn;at nille y do.</L>
<L>&THORN;at hors no tit &thorn;e, so mot y go.</L>
<L>Kni&yogh;tes ri&yogh;t is it non</L>
<L>&THORN;at he schuld fer o fot gon.</L>
<L N="6795">To &thorn;i wille ichil wende wi&thorn; &thorn;e,<MILESTONE N="144a:a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>To seche &thorn;e waiis of &thorn;is cuntre.</L>
<L>&THORN;is horn &thorn;ou mi&yogh;t wele haue,</L>
<L>And tow wi&thorn; loue it wille craue.'</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="section">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'Lording,' he seyd, 'o&thorn;er is mi &thorn;ou&yogh;t:<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="6493"></L>
<L N="6800">So astow wenest no schapestow nou&yogh;t.'
<PB REF="00000365.tif" N="361"></L>
<L>Gij bi &thorn;e reyne he ha&thorn; y-nome:</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; streng&thorn;e he wende to &thorn;e hors come.</L>
<L>&THORN;ei he war wro&thorn;, it was no ferly.</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; &thorn;at staf he smot sir Gij.</L>
<L N="6805">'Wicke man, &thorn;ou hast me smite:</L>
<L>&THORN;ou schalt it abigge, god it wite!'</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; his horn he him smot,</L>
<L>His breyn he schadde fot hot.</L>
<L>'Now, lording,'<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>lorging</I> MS.</NOTE> qua&thorn; Gij, '&thorn;e swin &thorn;ou nim,</L>
<L N="6810">&amp; alle &thorn;i wille do wi&thorn; him.</L>
<L>Na more smite &thorn;ou no kni&yogh;t:</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ou me smot, &thorn;ou dest vnri&yogh;t.'</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;ennes he is now y-ride,<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="6505"></L>
<L>&amp; bi &thorn;e forest so long he &yogh;ede,</L>
<L N="6815">&THORN;at vnne&thorn;e out wan he,</L>
<L>For he no knew nou&yogh;t &thorn;at cuntre.</L>
<L>He loked fer, he loked neye:</L>
<L>Castel no cite non he seye.</L>
<L>Him greued &thorn;e hete &amp; &thorn;e long day.</L>
<L N="6820">No rod he nou&yogh;t fer, so&thorn; to say,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he no sey a castel</L>
<L>Feir y-sett &amp; swi&thorn;e wel:</L>
<L>&THORN;ider-ward &yogh;ern &thorn;an rode he.</L>
<L>A man he mett of &thorn;at cuntre,</L>
<L N="6825">'Mi leue frende, telle &thorn;ou me,</L>
<L>&THORN;is feir castel wos it be.'</L>
<L>&THORN;e man seyd, 'y schal telle &thorn;e,</L>
<L>A better man no mi&yogh;t &thorn;ou se:</L>
<L>It is &thorn;e gode erl Florentin.</L>
<L N="6830">Better man drank neuer win.'</L>
<L>Gij anon &thorn;ider-ward he rod,</L>
<L>&amp; in he went wi&thorn;outen abod.</L>
<L>To &thorn;e halle gate he com ri&yogh;t,</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;er he is adoun y-li&yogh;t.</L>
<L N="6835">An hore y-blowe kni&yogh;t he seye</L>
<L>At &thorn;e des sitten an heye:
<PB REF="00000366.tif" N="362"></L>
<L>Long berd he hadde &amp; sterne si&yogh;t;</L>
<L>A man he semed of michel mi&yogh;t.</L>
<L>Biforn him anon Gij him dede,<MILESTONE N="144a:b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="6840">&amp; feir he gret him in &thorn;at stede.</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="section">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'Sir,' qua&thorn; Gij, 'vnderstond to me:<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="6535"></L>
<L>He &thorn;at &thorn;e warld made he blisce &thorn;e.</L>
<L>Icham a kni&yogh;t as &yogh;e may se:</L>
<L>Y bid &thorn;e mete par charite.</L>
<L N="6845">A meles mete &yogh;if &thorn;ou me,</L>
<L>&amp; se&thorn;&thorn;en hennes ichil te.'</L>
<L>'Leue frende,' he seyd, 'sikerly,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou schalt it haue gladly.'</L>
<L>&THORN;e water he axed &thorn;o anon,</L>
<L N="6850">To wasche his honden Gij is go[n].</L>
<L>To mete he sett him in &thorn;at stede,</L>
<L>Bred &amp; win biforn him &thorn;ai dede,</L>
<L>&amp; gret plente of o&thorn;er mete.</L>
<L>When he hadde sumdele y-ete</L>
<L N="6855">In &thorn;e toun he herd belles ring,</L>
<L>&amp; loude crie, &amp; miche wepeing,</L>
<L>Clo&thorn;es to-tere, her to-te:</L>
<L>More sorwe no mi&yogh;t non be.</L>
<L>'God,' qua&thorn; &thorn;erl, 'lord fre,</L>
<L N="6860">&THORN;is gret sorwe whi it be?'</L>
<L>Into &thorn;e halle come &thorn;ere</L>
<L>Tvai men, &amp; a bodi bere:</L>
<L>Amid &thorn;e flore &thorn;ai it leyden, y-wis.</L>
<L>Qua&thorn; &thorn;erl Florentin, 'mi sone &thorn;is is,'</L>
<L N="6865">Torent his here, his clo&thorn;es he drou&yogh;:</L>
<L>In his hert was sorwe anou&yogh;.</L>
<L>'Leue sone,' he seyd, 'who slou&yogh; &thorn;e?</L>
<L>Now wold god, &thorn;at is so fre,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he were here in mi beylie!</L>
<L N="6870">Nold ich it lete for al Romanie,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he no were anon y-slawe,</L>
<L>For-brent, &amp; &thorn;at dust to-blowe.'
<PB REF="00000367.tif" N="363"></L>
<L>&THORN;an seyd a squier biforn hem alle,</L>
<L>'Ichim se atte mete in &thorn;is halle,<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="6567"></L>
<L N="6875">He &thorn;at &thorn;i dere sone slou&yogh;.</L>
<L>Ich<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>Iich</I> MS. Hearing this,</NOTE> it seye, wi&thorn;-outen wou&yogh;.'</L>
<L>Anon &thorn;at &thorn;erl y-herd &thorn;is,</L>
<L>Fram &thorn;e bord he aros, y-wis:</L>
<L>An aundiren he kept in his honden &thorn;o,</L>
<L N="6880">Hetelich it haf, &amp; seyd him to,</L>
<L>'Traitour, &thorn;ou schalt dye here.</L>
<L>Why slou&yogh; &thorn;ou mi sone dere?'</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; &thorn;at aundiren he &thorn;ret sir Gij,<MILESTONE N="144b:a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&amp; wi&thorn; gret hate, sikerly,</L>
<L N="6885">Ac &thorn;at din<NOTE PLACE="marg">Read <I>dint?</I></NOTE> he feiled of him</L>
<L>(Gij vp stert wro&thorn; and grim):</L>
<L>Into &thorn;e wou&yogh; it fleye to fot &amp; more.</L>
<L>'Merci,' seyd Gij, 'for godes ore!</L>
<L>&YOGH;if ich &thorn;i sone owhar a-slou&yogh;,</L>
<L N="6890">It was me defendant anou&yogh;.'</L>
<L>Kni&yogh;t anon about him &thorn;rong,<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="6587"></L>
<L>To slen him, bo&thorn;e eld &amp; &yogh;ong.</L>
<L>Gij hent in hond anon ri&yogh;t</L>
<L>An ax &thorn;at was gode, apli&yogh;t.</L>
<L N="6895">Bi &thorn;at on ende of &thorn;e halle he him drou&yogh;,</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;er he werd him wele anou&yogh;.</L>
<L>&THORN;ai aseyld him strongliche,</L>
<L>&amp; he him werd stalwor&thorn;liche.</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; &thorn;at com for&thorn; &thorn;e steward li&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="6900">A Brabasone he was, a wel gode kni&yogh;t:</L>
<L>A strok he smot to sir Gij,</L>
<L>&amp; hewe on him ful felly.</L>
<L>Gij of him failed nau&yogh;t:</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; &thorn;e ax he ha&thorn; him rau&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="6905">&THORN;at his heued he him to-clef:</L>
<L>Al to ded to ground he dref.</L>
<L>&THORN;us Gij him were&thorn; manliche,</L>
<L>And hij him aseyle heteliche.
<PB REF="00000368.tif" N="364"></L>
<L>&THORN;e kni&yogh;tes he slou&yogh; &thorn;ere,</L>
<L N="6910">&THORN;e best &thorn;at in &thorn;at court were.</L>
<L>&para; 'Sir Florentin,' seyd sir Gij,<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="6605"></L>
<L>'For godes loue now merci!</L>
<L>&THORN;ou art y-hold so gode a man,</L>
<L>Hennes to Rome better nis nan:</L>
<L N="6915">&amp; &thorn;ou in &thorn;ine halle me sle,</L>
<L>For traisoun it wor&thorn; awist<NOTE PLACE="marg">So MS., not <I>atwist</I>.</NOTE> &thorn;e.</L>
<L>In edwite it wor&thorn; &thorn;e adrawe,<NOTE PLACE="marg">So MS., not <I>drawe</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>Swiche a man &thorn;ou schust haue slawe,</L>
<L>When &thorn;ou wi&thorn; &thorn;i wille fre</L>
<L N="6920">&THORN;e mete me &yogh;eue par charite.</L>
<L>Were it wi&thorn; wrong, were it wi&thorn; ri&yogh;t,</L>
<L>For tresoun it wor&thorn; &thorn;e witt, apli&yogh;t;</L>
<L>Opon alle &thorn;ing a &thorn;ing<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>a &thorn;ing</I> to be struck out?</NOTE> atte mete,</L>
<L>&THORN;er &yogh;e ou&yogh;t me to were fram hete.</L>
<L N="6925">For godes loue, sir, so michel do me,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &yogh;e &thorn;er-fore blamed no be:</L>
<L>Do me deliuer mi stede,<MILESTONE N="144b:b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&amp; lete me out at &thorn;e castel ride,</L>
<L>&amp; se&thorn;&thorn;en &thorn;ei y slawe be</L>
<L N="6930">No wor&thorn; &yogh;e nou&yogh;t y-blamed in &thorn;e cuntre.'</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="section">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;erl him wi&thorn;-drou&yogh; wi&thorn; &thorn;at:<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="6623"></L>
<L>At his hert gret sorwe sat,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he his sone seye ligge ded.</L>
<L>Of him no wor&thorn; him non o&thorn;er red.</L>
<L N="6935">'Sone,' he seyd, 'what schal y do,</L>
<L>Whenne ich &thorn;e haue &thorn;us forgo?</L>
<L>Who schal now weld after me</L>
<L>Mine<NOTE PLACE="marg">altered from <I>mune</I>.</NOTE> londes, &thorn;at brod be?</L>
<L>A man icham swi&thorn;e in eld:</L>
<L N="6940">Dye ichil, bi godes scheld.'</L>
<L>Opon &thorn;at bodi he fel anon:</L>
<L>Reu&thorn;e &thorn;ai hadden &thorn;er-of ichon,</L>
<L>Of his gret sorwe &thorn;at he made.</L>
<L>To his kni&yogh;tes no &thorn;e les he sade,
<PB REF="00000369.tif" N="365"></L>
<L N="6945">'Ichot &thorn;at non so hardi be,</L>
<L>&THORN;at him mis-do to-for me,</L>
<L>&THORN;er-while &thorn;at he in mi court is:</L>
<L>&THORN;at ich hot &yogh;ou alle, y-wis,</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;at his stede be him<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>to</I> underdotted after <I>him</I>.</NOTE> bitau&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="6950">&amp; out at &thorn;e gates &thorn;at he be brou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;at he be to-hewe flesche and bon.'</L>
<L>&THORN;ai deliuerd his stede anon:</L>
<L>He lepe opon him swi&thorn;e,</L>
<L>&amp; out at &thorn;e gat he gan driue.</L>
<L N="6955">His scheld wi&thorn; him &thorn;an he bar,</L>
<L>His gode swerd for&yogh;at he nou&yogh;t &thorn;ar.</L>
<L>Out of &thorn;e castel he is y-gon,</L>
<L>Toward Loreyne he went anon.</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="section">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;erl wi&thorn; &thorn;at armed is:<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="6647"></L>
<L N="6960">Gij he drof smertliche, y-wis,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; his kni&yogh;tes on heye stede</L>
<L>Redi armed to &thorn;at nede.</L>
<L>Sir Gij his stede bi-went &thorn;o:</L>
<L>On of her kni&yogh;tes he smot so,</L>
<L N="6965">&THORN;urch his bodi &thorn;e swerd is gon.</L>
<L>Ano&thorn;er he feld &thorn;er anon.</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; &thorn;at come &thorn;erl prikeinde</L>
<L>Opon his stede wele bereinde</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; a spere an hond y-armed<NOTE PLACE="marg">The <I>y</I> added above the line.</NOTE> wel:</L>
<L N="6970">Gij to smite he was ful fel.</L>
<L>Gij him wi&thorn;-went, wold he nou&yogh;t fle:<MILESTONE N="145a:a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>To &thorn;erl Florentin &thorn;an smot he.</L>
<L>Heteliche togider &thorn;ai smete</L>
<L>Opon her scheldes wi&thorn; gret hete.</L>
<L N="6975">&THORN;erl alder furst smot sir Gij</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; a gode spere, sikerly.</L>
<L>Gij him smot o&yogh;ain, no mi&yogh;t he as nau&yogh;t,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he ha&thorn; &thorn;e grounde y-rau&yogh;t.<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>ra</I> on an erasure.</NOTE></L>
<L>Bi &thorn;e reynes his stede toke he:</L>
<L N="6980">Of &thorn;erl he hadde gret pite,
<PB REF="00000370.tif" N="366"></L>
<L>For his sone he hadde aqueld,</L>
<L>And for he was a man so eld.</L>
<L>Fiftene &yogh;er weren agon</L>
<L>&THORN;at he er in armes come.</L>
<L N="6985">'Sir,' seyd Gij &thorn;er anon,</L>
<L>'Nim &thorn;i stede, &amp; wor&thorn; &thorn;eron.</L>
<L>What wonder dede &thorn;e armes bere?</L>
<L>To &yogh;er more &thorn;ou schust rest &thorn;e here.</L>
<L>Her ich &yogh;iue &thorn;e &thorn;i stede,</L>
<L N="6990">For &thorn;ou &yogh;eue me &thorn;e mete at nede.</L>
<L>In chaumber &thorn;ou schust ligge stille,</L>
<L>O&thorn;er to chirche gon to bid godis wille.</L>
<L>&THORN;i court ichil quite-cleym &thorn;e.</L>
<L>Ded ich wold ra&thorn;er be,</L>
<L N="6995">Ar ich wold wi&thorn; &thorn;e ete</L>
<L>At souper o&thorn;er at o&thorn;er mete.'</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="section">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Gij went for&thorn; fulleliche wi&thorn;alle:</L>
<L>Was him &thorn;er no nedes to duelle.</L>
<L>On ich side he seye come kni&yogh;tes,<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="6689"></L>
<L N="7000">Burieys, and seriaunce redi to fi&yogh;tes</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; alle &thorn;at crie of &thorn;at cuntre:</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; hem nomen no wold ben he.</L>
<L>Him no was &thorn;er nou&yogh;t wor&thorn; to abide:</L>
<L>He priked his hors &amp; gan to ride.</L>
<L N="7005">Into a forest he gan to go.</L>
<L>Oft his stede he wi&thorn;-went &thorn;o:</L>
<L>Mani he wounded, &amp; mani he slou&yogh;</L>
<L>Of kni&yogh;tes &thorn;at wer gode y-nou&yogh;.</L>
<L>Gij ferd for&thorn; swi&thorn;e wi&thorn;-alle</L>
<L N="7010">Opon his stede, &thorn;at bar him snelle.</L>
<L>&THORN;urch &thorn;e forest swi&thorn;e he rode.</L>
<L>&THORN;erl him o&yogh;ein went wi&thorn;outen abode.</L>
<L>Michel sorwe he made, y-pli&yogh;t,</L>
<L>For his sone awreke he no mi&yogh;t.</L>
<L N="7015">His sone anon biri he dede<MILESTONE N="145a:b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>In a chirche bifore &thorn;e auter in &thorn;at stede.
<PB REF="00000372.tif" N="368"></L>
<L>Alle &thorn;at day Gij for&thorn; rod,<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="6707"></L>
<L>Alle what &thorn;e sonne adoun glod:</L>
<L>Of alle ni&yogh;t he no blan rideinge</L>
<L N="7020">Fort amorwe in &thorn;e daweinge,</L>
<L>So &thorn;at<NOTE PLACE="marg">Another <I>&thorn;at</I> erased it seems.</NOTE> he to Loreyin com:</L>
<L>&THORN;e cuntres he knewe anon.<NOTE PLACE="marg">The <I>o</I> indistinct.</NOTE></L>
<L>Wel<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>Wel</I> Turnbull, <I>Wil</I> MS.</NOTE> ri&yogh;t he &yogh;ede to &thorn;at cite:</L>
<L>Ichon<NOTE PLACE="marg">About three letters erased after <I>Ichon</I>.</NOTE> &thorn;er fond he,</L>
<L N="7025">Alle &thorn;e best &thorn;at weren &thorn;are:</L>
<L>For him &thorn;ai had<NOTE PLACE="marg">Not <I>made</I>.</NOTE> michel care.</L>
<L>When &thorn;ai him hole &amp; sounde y-se&thorn;</L>
<L>Of his coming glad hij be&thorn;.</L>
<L>&para; Gij hem told &thorn;e so&thorn;e, y-wis,</L>
<L N="7030">Hou he fram &thorn;erl aschaped is.</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;ai &thorn;onked god &thorn;o,</L>
<L>&THORN;at deliuerd him of his wo.</L>
<L>Se&thorn;&thorn;en wold he nou&yogh;t long duelle,<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="6721"></L>
<L>To his cuntre he wold snelle.</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="section">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="7035">Gij of &thorn;e douke toke his leue,</L>
<L>Ac he it him &yogh;af wele vnne&thorn;e.</L>
<L>Anou&yogh; he him bede of siluer &amp; gold,</L>
<L>Ac he &thorn;erof nou&yogh;t nim nold.</L>
<L>To &thorn;erl Tirri he &yogh;ede &thorn;o,</L>
<L N="7040">&amp; &thorn;is wordes seyd him to:</L>
<L>'Sir erl Tirri,' seyd Gij,</L>
<L>'Now ichil gon, sikerli,</L>
<L>Vnto mi cuntre into Inglond</L>
<L>(&THORN;at way no may y nou&yogh;t wi&thorn;stond),</L>
<L N="7045">Mine fader &amp; min frendes to se:</L>
<L>Y not &yogh;if &thorn;ai oliues be.</L>
<L>Seuen &yogh;er &amp; more agon it is</L>
<L>&THORN;at ich in &thorn;at cuntre was, y-wis.</L>
<L>&YOGH;if it bitide ani-&thorn;ing sone</L>
<L N="7050">&THORN;at &thorn;ou haue wi&thorn; me to don,</L>
<L>Be it in pes o&thorn;er in werre,</L>
<L>Whe&thorn;er it be ner or ferre,
<PB REF="00000374.tif" N="370"></L>
<L>Anon ri&yogh;t sende after me:</L>
<L>Ichil come anon to &thorn;e,<NOTE PLACE="marg">So MS.</NOTE></L>
<L N="7055">&THORN;at ich no fot hot com to &thorn;e</L>
<L>Al sone as ich &thorn;i sond y-se.</L>
<L>&THORN;i wer we haue ouer-com,</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;ou hast spoused &thorn;i loue.</L>
<L>Destrud we haue &yogh;our fon,<MILESTONE N="145b:a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="7060">Erls, barouns mani on.</L>
<L>&THORN;i lond we han brou&yogh;t in pes:</L>
<L>No bestow neuer iuel at esse.</L>
<L>&THORN;ou art a kni&yogh;t of mi&yogh;ti dede:</L>
<L>Of &thorn;ine fon &thorn;arf &thorn;e nou&yogh;t drede.</L>
<L N="7065">Alle min estris of Inglond</L>
<L>Sende ichil to [&thorn;e bi] mi sond,</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;ou schalt to me also:</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;ine wille sende me to;</L>
<L>&amp; ich me self wille com to &thorn;e</L>
<L N="7070">Sone so ich mi time may se.'</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="section">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'Felawe,' qua&thorn; Tirri, 'gramerci.<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="6755"></L>
<L>Iuel biladde now am y.</L>
<L>Oft fram de&thorn; &thorn;ou hast me scheld,</L>
<L>&amp; neuere no haddestow for me &yogh;eld.</L>
<L N="7075">&YOGH;if &thorn;ou wilt fro me go,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou me sext neuer mo.</L>
<L>Al-so<NOTE PLACE="marg">Something erased between <I>al</I> and <I>so</I>.</NOTE> sone so it wite our fon,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ou art fro me gon,</L>
<L>On ich side ous schal arise werre</L>
<L N="7080">Of Almeyns, Lombardes neye &amp; ferre,</L>
<L>&THORN;at ben Otus kinsmen;</L>
<L>For he was come of gret ken.</L>
<L>&THORN;e king of Speyne his em is,</L>
<L>His soster ha&thorn; wedded &thorn;e douke Moralis.</L>
<L N="7085">Doukes, erls of gret pouste</L>
<L>His de&thorn; wille<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>wille</I> added at the end of the line.</NOTE> &thorn;ai wite me.</L>
<L>In wer &amp; wo schal y be</L>
<L>&THORN;er-while &thorn;e liue is in me.
<PB REF="00000376.tif" N="372"></L>
<L>&amp; &yogh;if we were togider baye,</L>
<L N="7090">Of wer no &thorn;urt ous stond no aye.</L>
<L>And &yogh;if &thorn;ou here wi&thorn; me bileue wold,</L>
<L>Anou&yogh; we haue of siluer &amp; of gold,</L>
<L>God cites and castels strong,</L>
<L>&THORN;e feirest and &thorn;e best of &thorn;is lond.</L>
<L N="7095">Wi&thorn; douke Loer ichil be,</L>
<L>&amp; alle Gormoise ichil &yogh;iue &thorn;e</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; alle &thorn;e wor&thorn;schip &thorn;at li&thorn;e &thorn;er-to</L>
<L>&amp; &yogh;ete an o&thorn;<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>ano&thorn;er</I> instead of <I>an o&thorn;</I> MS.</NOTE> ichil &thorn;e do</L>
<L>&THORN;at neuere<NOTE PLACE="marg">&amp; instead of <I>&thorn;at neuere</I> MS.</NOTE> &thorn;e wor&thorn; of a<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>a</I> omitted in MS.</NOTE> pani<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>Paui</I> Turnbull.</NOTE></L>
<L N="7100">Ichil &thorn;er-of chalangij.'</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="section">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'Sir erl,' qua&thorn; Gij, '&thorn;er-of speke nou&yogh;t:<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="6781"></L>
<L>Al idel &thorn;ou hast me &thorn;er-of bisou&yogh;t.</L>
<L>Gret wille ich haue to &thorn;at waye:<MILESTONE N="145b:b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Y no lete it nou&yogh;t, &thorn;er-fore to daye.</L>
<L N="7105">No were it for &thorn;e loue of mi leman,</L>
<L>Nold ich neuer wende &thorn;e fram,</L>
<L>Ac wi&thorn; &thorn;e euer duelle ich wolde,</L>
<L>&THORN;at neuer departi we ne scholde.</L>
<L>Gon ich mot, wille y so nille,</L>
<L N="7110">O-&thorn;ink &thorn;e nou&yogh;t, y may nou&yogh;t duelle.'<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>deulle</I> origin|ally, but the <I>e</I> underdotted, and another added above the line.</NOTE></L>
<L>Togider &thorn;ai kisten hem &thorn;o,</L>
<L>At her departing &thorn;ai wepen bo:</L>
<L>Bo&thorn;e &thorn;ai wepen bitterliche,</L>
<L>&THORN;at folk hadde &thorn;erof pite miche.</L>
<L N="7115">Alle &thorn;e men &thorn;at &thorn;er were</L>
<L>Was for hem sori &thorn;ere</L>
<L>At the departing of to feren:<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>ferren</I> MS.</NOTE></L>
<L>Wel gode kni&yogh;tes bo&thorn;e &thorn;ai weren.</L>
<L>Gij lepe on a mule ambling,<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="6795"></L>
<L N="7120">Bi &thorn;e way he ride&thorn; sorweing.</L>
<L>Tirri bileft sorwe makeing,</L>
<L>&amp; Gij his felawe bimeninge.</L>
<L>So miche sorwe he made day &amp; ni&yogh;t,</L>
<L>No man mi&yogh;t tellen it, y &yogh;ou pli&yogh;t.<NOTE PLACE="marg">This line was omitted, but after|wards added after 1. 7142 with a reference to its place.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000378.tif" N="374"></L>
<L N="7125">Sir Gij no lan neuer rideing,</L>
<L>Til he com to &thorn;e se, wi&thorn;-outen lesing.</L>
<L>Gode winde he ha&thorn;, &amp; passe&thorn; sone,</L>
<L>&amp; come in-to Inglond mididone.</L>
<L>Now for&thorn; to Warwik he is y-go,</L>
<L N="7130">King A&thorn;elston &thorn;er he fond &thorn;o;</L>
<L>&amp; when he was to Warwike com,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; ioie &thorn;ai him vnder-fenge alle &amp; some.</L>
<L>&THORN;e king to&yogh;eines him is y-go</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; kni&yogh;tes &amp; burieys also,</L>
<L N="7135">For he him herd preyse so miche:</L>
<L>&THORN;e king him loued, sikerliche,</L>
<L>And wi&thorn; him<NOTE PLACE="marg">Added above the line.</NOTE> soiournd sir Gij &thorn;e fre.</L>
<L>On a day at &thorn;e ches pleyden he:<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="6813"></L>
<L>Wi&thorn; &thorn;at come &thorn;er &thorn;re men rideinde,</L>
<L N="7140">Of &thorn;e cuntre fre men heldinde:</L>
<L>To &thorn;e king &thorn;ai seyd, 'sir, vnder-stond:</L>
<L>Hard tidinges we bring &thorn;e an hond.</L>
<L>Bot &yogh;e sone take &yogh;eme &thorn;er-to,</L>
<L>Alle &yogh;our lond &yogh;e schul forgo.</L>
<L N="7145">&THORN;er is comen opon &thorn;i lond</L>
<L>A best &thorn;at bringe&thorn; it al to schond.</L>
<L>Out of Irlond it come:<MILESTONE N="146a:a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>To miche harm<NOTE PLACE="marg">A letter erased after <I>harm</I>.</NOTE> it ha&thorn; y-don.</L>
<L>It no leue&thorn; man no wiman non,</L>
<L N="7150">&THORN;at it no sle&thorn; hem<NOTE PLACE="marg">Added above the line.</NOTE> ichon</L>
<L>Bot sum &thorn;at aschaped be&thorn;</L>
<L>&THORN;urch chaunce and to &thorn;e cites.</L>
<L>It frete&thorn; men &amp; bestes also;</L>
<L>Ri&yogh;t for so&thorn;e y telle &thorn;e to,</L>
<L N="7155">Neuer nas best no so kene.</L>
<L>Gret heued it ha&thorn; &amp; gastelich to sene:</L>
<L>His nek is greter &thorn;an a bole,</L>
<L>His bodi is swarter &thorn;an ani cole.</L>
<L>It is michel, &amp; long, &amp; griseliche,</L>
<L N="7160">Fram &thorn;e nouel vpward vnschepliche.
<PB REF="00000380.tif" N="376"></L>
<L>&THORN;e smallest scale &thorn;at on him is</L>
<L>No wepen no may atame, y-wis.</L>
<L>As a somer it is brested bifore in &thorn;e brede</L>
<L>&amp; swifter ernend &thorn;an ani stede.</L>
<L N="7165">He ha&thorn; clawes also a lyoun.</L>
<L>Men sey&thorn; &thorn;at it is a dragoun.</L>
<L>Gret wenges he ha&thorn; wi&thorn; to fle.</L>
<L>His schaft to telle alle ne mow we.</L>
<L>&THORN;e bodi is gret toward &thorn;e teyle.</L>
<L N="7170">Swiche a best nas neuer, saunfeyle.</L>
<L>&THORN;e teyle is gret &amp; wel long:</L>
<L>In &thorn;e warld nis man so strong,</L>
<L>&amp; were y-armed neuer so,</L>
<L>&amp; he wi&thorn; &thorn;e teyle smot him to,</L>
<L N="7175">&THORN;at he no wor&thorn; ded anon:</L>
<L>No schuld he neuer ride no gon.'<NOTE PLACE="marg">The abbreviation for the <I>n</I> not quite distinct.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="section">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>When &thorn;e king ha&thorn; y-herd &thorn;is<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="6841"></L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;e men him teld, y-wis,</L>
<L>An gode while he him bi-&thorn;ou&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="7180">Er &thorn;an &thorn;at he speke mou&yogh;t.</L>
<L>'Sir,' qua&thorn; Gij, 'no care &thorn;ou nou&yogh;t:</L>
<L>&THORN;er-of no haue &thorn;ou no &thorn;ou&yogh;t.</L>
<L>Into Nor&thorn;-humberlond ichil wende,</L>
<L>&amp; &yogh;if ich &thorn;at best may fende,</L>
<L N="7185">Ich him schal ouercome &thorn;urch godes mi&yogh;t;</L>
<L>For wi&thorn; him ichil hold fi&yogh;t.'</L>
<L>&para; 'Gij,' qua&thorn; &thorn;e king, 'schaltow nou&yogh;t so.</L>
<L>No wille ich &thorn;at &thorn;ou al-on go.</L>
<L>An hundred kni&yogh;tes schul wende wi&thorn; &thorn;e,</L>
<L N="7190">&THORN;at &thorn;ou may &thorn;e sikerer be.'</L>
<L>Gij answerd anon ri&yogh;t,<MILESTONE N="146a:b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>'Nold neuer god ful of mi&yogh;t</L>
<L>&THORN;at for a best onlepi</L>
<L>Schuld so miche folk traueli.'</L>
<L N="7195">At &thorn;e king his leue he nam,</L>
<L>And hom to his in he cam.
<PB REF="00000382.tif" N="378"></L>
<L>His felawes he lete &thorn;er ichon:</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; him most go neuer on</L>
<L>Bot Herhaud, &thorn;at was gode at nede,</L>
<L N="7200">&amp; o&thorn;er to kni&yogh;tes y-armed on stede.</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="section">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>So &thorn;ai come &thorn;ider on a day,<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="6867"></L>
<L>&amp; spired where &thorn;at best lay,</L>
<L>Gij armed him wel richeliche,</L>
<L>&amp; seyd to his felawes hastiliche</L>
<L N="7205">&THORN;at so hardi &thorn;er be non</L>
<L>O fot wi&thorn; him for to gon.</L>
<L>Now is Gij to a launde y-go</L>
<L>Wher &thorn;e dragoun duelled &thorn;o.</L>
<L>&THORN;o Gij him seye so griseli,</L>
<L N="7210">Of him no was he nou&yogh;t al trusti.</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; &thorn;e spere he him smot smertliche,</L>
<L>&THORN;at was kerueand scharpeliche,</L>
<L>&THORN;at alto schiueres<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>schiuere&THORN;</I> MS.</NOTE> it to-fleye;<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>fley&THORN;e</I> originally, but the <I>&THORN;</I> struck out.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ac &thorn;e bodi com it nou&yogh;t neye.</L>
<L N="7215">&THORN;o he had smiten &thorn;at best so,<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>&THORN;</I> erased before <I>so</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>Wel heye he bar his heued &thorn;o,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn;-went him, &amp; lepe him to:</L>
<L>Him &amp; his<NOTE PLACE="marg">A letter (<I>d</I>?) erased after <I>his</I>.</NOTE> stede he feld bo.</L>
<L>Gij of &thorn;at strok astounded is:</L>
<L N="7220">Neuer hadde he non swiche, y-wis.</L>
<L>Up he stirt anon ri&yogh;t:</L>
<L>'God,' he seyd, 'fader almi&yogh;t,<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="6888"></L>
<L>&THORN;at made &thorn;e day &amp; ni&yogh;t also,</L>
<L>&amp; for ous sinful &thorn;oldest wo,</L>
<L N="7225">&amp; heldest Daniel fram &thorn;e lyoun,</L>
<L>Saue me fram &thorn;is foule dragoun.'</L>
<L>His swerd he drou&yogh; anon ri&yogh;t:</L>
<L>To him he lepe wi&thorn; gret mi&yogh;t,</L>
<L>&amp; smot him in &thorn;e heued schod</L>
<L N="7230">A wel gret strok wi&thorn;-outen abod;</L>
<L>Ac no-&thorn;ing sen &thorn;an was his dent:</L>
<L>Gij him held &thorn;an al schent,
<PB REF="00000384.tif" N="380"></L>
<L>&THORN;at he no mi&yogh;t him deri nou&yogh;t</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; no wepen of stiel y-wrou&yogh;t.</L>
<L N="7235">Bitvene hem was strong bateyle:<MILESTONE N="146b:a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Ai&thorn;er gan o&thorn;er for to aseyle.</L>
<L>At asaut wi&thorn; Gyes partinge</L>
<L>&THORN;at wers he hadde at &thorn;at wendinge,</L>
<L>&THORN;e best him<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>went</I> struck out after <I>him</I>.</NOTE> neyed, &amp; smot him</L>
<L N="7240">Wi&thorn; his vp-coming so fel &amp; grim,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he a lappe rent out<NOTE PLACE="marg">The <I>t</I> added above the line.</NOTE> anon</L>
<L>Of his brini, &thorn;at alle his trust was on.</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="section">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Now ha&thorn; Gij michel to done:<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="6915"></L>
<L>To a tre he went him sone;</L>
<L N="7245">&THORN;er he wille bateyle abide</L>
<L>Of &thorn;at best, what schaunce so bitide.</L>
<L>&THORN;at best bisides him it went,</L>
<L>&amp; wi&thorn; his<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>stroke</I> struck out after <I>his</I>.</NOTE> teyle a strok him sent:</L>
<L>On &thorn;e scheld he smot him an heye,</L>
<L N="7250">&THORN;at euen ato<NOTE PLACE="marg">The <I>a</I> added above the line.</NOTE> it to-fleye,</L>
<L>Al-so it were wi&thorn; a swerd broun.</L>
<L>Well neye Gij him fel adoun.</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; his taile he bigirt sir Gij,</L>
<L>&amp; him &thorn;rest so strongli,</L>
<L N="7255">&THORN;at &thorn;re ribbes he brac atvo;</L>
<L>&amp; Gij wi&thorn; streng&thorn;e smot him &thorn;o:</L>
<L>Atvo he him karf smartliche,</L>
<L>&amp; deliuerd him seluen manliche.</L>
<L>Bi &thorn;e nauel he carf him ato,</L>
<L N="7260">&amp; wi&thorn; a gret pine deliuerd him fro.</L>
<L>Gij him perceyued in &thorn;at stounde</L>
<L>&THORN;at neuer more &thorn;urch wepen y-grounde</L>
<L>&THORN;at<NOTE PLACE="marg">To be omitted?</NOTE> fram &thorn;e nauel vp-ward so</L>
<L>No slou&yogh; him man neuer mo.</L>
<L N="7265">&THORN;o &thorn;at best hirt him feled,<NOTE PLACE="marg">The second <I>e</I> underdotted.</NOTE></L>
<L>Swi&thorn;e loude he grad &amp; &yogh;eled,</L>
<L>&THORN;at alle &thorn;at cuntre dined &thorn;ere,</L>
<L>&amp; als wide as men herd his bere,
<PB REF="00000386.tif" N="382"></L>
<L>Nis man in &thorn;e werld &thorn;at wer &thorn;er neye</L>
<L N="7270">&THORN;at him no mi&yogh;t agrise &thorn;at it seye.</L>
<L>To a tre &thorn;an drou&yogh;t him sir Gij,</L>
<L>&amp; werd him wele for &thorn;e maistri.<NOTE PLACE="marg">The first <I>i</I> added above the line.</NOTE></L>
<L>His hauberk was to-rent tofore</L>
<L>As a clout &thorn;at were al to-tore.</L>
<L N="7275">Stalwor&thorn;li sir Gij &thorn;er fau&yogh;t,</L>
<L>Ac wele he seye it gained him nau&yogh;t</L>
<L>To smite on the bodi bifore:</L>
<L>He no mi&yogh;t him sle no no man bore.</L>
<L>Also &thorn;at best him went aboute,<MILESTONE N="146b:b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="7280">Gij him bi&thorn;ou&yogh;t he was in doute:</L>
<L>Bine&thorn;en<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>&thorn;</I> erased between <I>bi</I> and <I>ne&thorn;en.</I></NOTE> &thorn;e wenge he him smot:</L>
<L>&THORN;urch &thorn;at bodi &thorn;at swerd bot.</L>
<L>&THORN;urch &thorn;e bodi he him<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>smot</I> struck out after <I>him.</I></NOTE> carf atvo:</L>
<L>Ded he fel to grounde &thorn;o.</L>
<L N="7285">He grad &amp; &yogh;elled swi&thorn;e loude,</L>
<L>&THORN;at it schilled into &thorn;e cloude.</L>
<L>Gij wi&thorn;-drou&yogh; him &thorn;er-fro anon:</L>
<L>For stink &thorn;at of &thorn;e bodi come</L>
<L>Neye &thorn;at bodi he no durste.</L>
<L N="7290">After &thorn;at he &yogh;ede him to reste.<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="6953"></L>
<L>When &thorn;at best &thorn;er ded lay,</L>
<L>For so&thorn;e y &yogh;ou telle may,</L>
<L>&THORN;ritti fote meten it was</L>
<L>&THORN;er it lay in &thorn;at plas.</L>
<L N="7295">&THORN;e folk of &thorn;e cuntre it mette</L>
<L>&THORN;er it lay wonderliche grete.</L>
<L>&THORN;at heued he bar &thorn;e bodi fro,</L>
<L>And wi&thorn; &thorn;at Gij for&thorn; went &thorn;o.</L>
<L>He come to his feren, apli&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="7300">&THORN;at for him bad to god almi&yogh;t.</L>
<L>To Warwike he is y-went,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; &thorn;at heued he made &thorn;e king present.</L>
<L>&THORN;e king was bli&thorn;e &amp; of glad chere</L>
<L>For &thorn;at he seye Gij hole &amp; fere.
<PB REF="00000388.tif" N="384"></L>
<L N="7305">At Warwik &thorn;ai henge &thorn;e heued anon:</L>
<L>Mani<NOTE PLACE="marg">Written twice, but erased the second time.</NOTE> man wondred &thorn;er-apon.</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="section">
<LG N="1" TYPE="stanza">
<L>God graunt hem heuen blis to mede</L>
<L>&THORN;at herken to mi romaunce rede</L>
<L>Al of a gentil kni&yogh;t:</L>
<L>&THORN;e best bodi he was at nede</L>
<L N="5">&THORN;at euer mi&yogh;t bistriden stede,</L>
<L>&amp; freest founde in fi&yogh;t.</L>
<L>&THORN;e word of him ful wide it ran,</L>
<L>Ouer al &thorn;is warld &thorn;e priis he wan</L>
<L>As man most of mi&yogh;t.</L>
<L N="10">Balder bern was non in bi:</L>
<L>His name was hoten sir Gij</L>
<L>Of Warwike, wise &amp; wi&yogh;t.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="2" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Wi&yogh;t he was, for so&thorn;e to say,</L>
<L>&amp; holden for priis in eueri play</L>
<L>As kni&yogh;t of gret bounde.</L>
<L>Out of &thorn;is lond he went his way</L>
<L N="5">&THORN;urch mani diuers cuntray,<MILESTONE N="147a:a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&THORN;at was bi&yogh;ond &thorn;e see.</L>
<L>Se&thorn;&thorn;en he com into Inglond,</L>
<L>&amp; A&thorn;elston &thorn;e king he fond,</L>
<L>&THORN;at was bo&thorn;e hende &amp; fre.</L>
<L N="10">For his loue, ich vnder-stond,</L>
<L>He slou&yogh; a dragoun in Nor&thorn;humberlond,</L>
<L>Ful fer in &thorn;e nor&thorn; cuntre.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="3" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; He &amp; Herhaud, for so&thorn;e to say,<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="6967"></L>
<L>To Wallingfor&thorn; toke &thorn;e way,</L>
<L>&THORN;at was his faders toun.</L>
<L>&THORN;an was his fader, so&thorn;e to say,</L>
<L N="5">Ded &amp; birid in &thorn;e clay:</L>
<L>His air was sir Gioun.</L>
<L>
<PB REF="00000390.tif" N="386">. . . . . </L>
<L>Alle &thorn;at held of him lond or fe</L>
<L>Deden him omage &amp; feute,</L>
<L N="10">&amp; com to his somoun.</L>
<L>He tok alle his faders lond,</L>
<L>&amp; &yogh;af it hende Herhaud in hond</L>
<L>Ri&yogh;t to his warisoun.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="4" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; &amp; alle &thorn;at hadde in his seruise be</L>
<L>He &yogh;af hem gold &amp; riche fe</L>
<L>Ful hendeliche on honde,</L>
<L>And se&thorn;&thorn;en he went wi&thorn; his meyne</L>
<L N="5">To &thorn;erl Rohaud, &thorn;at was so fre:</L>
<L>At Warwike he him fond.</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;an were &thorn;ai glad &amp; bli&thorn;e,</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;onked god a &thorn;ousand si&thorn;e</L>
<L>&THORN;at Gij was comen to lond.</L>
<L N="10">Se&thorn;e on hunting &thorn;ai gun ride</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; kni&yogh;tes fele &amp; miche pride</L>
<L>As &yogh;e may vnderstond.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="5" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; On a day sir Gij gan fond,<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="6991"></L>
<L>&amp; feir Felice he tok bi hond,</L>
<L>&amp; seyd to &thorn;at bird so bli&thorn;e:</L>
<L>'Ichaue,' he seyd, '&thorn;urch godes sond</L>
<L N="5">Won &thorn;e priis in mani lond</L>
<L>Of kni&yogh;tes strong &amp; sti&thorn;e,</L>
<L>&amp; me is boden gret anour,</L>
<L>Kinges douhter &amp; emperour</L>
<L>To haue to mi wiue.</L>
<L N="10">Ac, swete Felice,' he seyd &thorn;an,</L>
<L>'Y no schal neuer spouse wiman</L>
<L>Whiles &thorn;ou art oliue.'</L>
</LG>
<LG N="6" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; &THORN;an answerd &thorn;at swete wi&yogh;t,<MILESTONE N="147a:b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&amp; seyd o&yogh;ain to him ful ri&yogh;t:</L>
<L>'Bi him &thorn;at schope mankinne,
<PB REF="00000392.tif" N="388"></L>
<L>Icham desired day &amp; ni&yogh;t</L>
<L N="5">Of erl, baroun, &amp; mani a kni&yogh;t.</L>
<L>For no&thorn;ing wil &thorn;ai blinne.</L>
<L>Ac Gij,' sche seyd, 'hende &amp; fre,</L>
<L>Al mi loue is layd on &thorn;e:</L>
<L>Our loue schal<NOTE PLACE="marg">The <I>h</I> is incom|plete.</NOTE> neuer tvinne,</L>
<L N="10">&amp; bot ich haue &thorn;e to make</L>
<L>O&thorn;er lord nil y non take,</L>
<L>For al &thorn;is warld to winne.'</L>
</LG>
<LG N="7" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Anon to hir &thorn;an answerd Gij,</L>
<L>To fair Felice, &thorn;at sat him bi,</L>
<L>&THORN;at semly was of si&yogh;t:</L>
<L>'Leman,' he seyd, 'gramerci!'</L>
<L N="5">Wi&thorn; ioie &amp; wi&thorn; melodi</L>
<L>He kist &thorn;at swete wi&yogh;t.</L>
<L>&THORN;an was he bo&thorn;e glad &amp; bli&thorn;e:</L>
<L>His ioie cou&thorn;e he noman ki&thorn;e</L>
<L>For &thorn;at bird so bri&yogh;t.</L>
<L N="10">He no was neuer &thorn;er-biforn</L>
<L>Half so bli&thorn;e se&thorn;e he was born</L>
<L>For nou&yogh;t &thorn;at man him hi&yogh;t.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="8" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; On a day &thorn;erl gan fond,<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="7011"></L>
<L>&amp; fair Felice he tok bi hond,</L>
<L>&amp; hir moder biside:</L>
<L>'Douhter,' he seyd, 'now vnder-stond;</L>
<L N="5">Why wiltow haue non husbond</L>
<L>&THORN;at mi&yogh;t &thorn;e spouse wi&thorn; pride?</L>
<L>&THORN;ou has ben desired of mani man,</L>
<L>&amp; &yogh;ete no wostow neuer nan</L>
<L>For nou&yogh;t &thorn;at mi&yogh;t bitide.</L>
<L N="10">Leue douhter hende and fre,<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>hende and fre</I> on an erasure.</NOTE></L>
<L>Telle me now, par charite,</L>
<L>What man &thorn;ou wilt abide.'
<PB REF="00000394.tif" N="390"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="9" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Felice answerd o&yogh;ain:</L>
<L>'Fader,' qua&thorn; hye, 'ichil &thorn;e sain</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; wordes fre &amp; hende.</L>
<L>Fader,' qua&thorn; sche, 'ichil ful fayn</L>
<L N="5">Tel &thorn;e at wordes tvain,</L>
<L>Bi him &thorn;at schop mankende,</L>
<L>Opon sir Gij, &thorn;at gentil kni&yogh;t,</L>
<L>Y-wis, mi loue is alle ali&yogh;t,</L>
<L>In warld where &thorn;at he wende;</L>
<L N="10">&amp; bot he spouse me, at o word,<MILESTONE N="147b:a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Y no kepe neuer take lo[r]d</L>
<L>Day wi&thorn;outen ende.'</L>
</LG>
<LG N="10" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; &THORN;an seyd &thorn;erl wi&thorn; wordes fre,</L>
<L>'Douhter, y-blisced mot &thorn;ou be</L>
<L>Of godes mou&thorn;e to mede.</L>
<L>Ich hadde wele leuer &thorn;an al mi fe</L>
<L N="5">Wi&thorn; &thorn;an he wald spousy &thorn;e,</L>
<L>&THORN;at douhti man of dede.</L>
<L>He ha&thorn; ben desired of mani woman,</L>
<L>&amp; he ha&thorn; forsaken hem euerilcan,</L>
<L>&THORN;at wor&thorn;ly were in wede.</L>
<L N="10">Ac na&thorn;eles ichil to him fare,</L>
<L>For to witen of his answare,</L>
<L>&THORN;at douhti man of dede.'</L>
</LG>
<LG N="11" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; On a day, wi&thorn;outen lesing,<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="7047"></L>
<L>&THORN;erl him rode on dere hunting,</L>
<L>&amp; sir Gij &thorn;e conquerour.</L>
<L>Als &thorn;ai riden on her talking</L>
<L N="5">&THORN;ai speken togider of mani &thorn;ing,</L>
<L>Of leuedis bri&yogh;t in bour.</L>
<L>&THORN;erl seyd to sir Gij hende &amp; fre,</L>
<L>'Tel me &thorn;e so&thorn;e, par charite,</L>
<L>Y pray &thorn;e par amoure:
<PB REF="00000396.tif" N="392"></L>
<L N="10">Hastow ment euer in &thorn;i liue</L>
<L>Spouse ani wiman to wiue</L>
<L>&THORN;at falle&thorn; to &thorn;ine anour?'</L>
</LG>
<LG N="12" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Sir Gij answerd &amp; seyd &thorn;an,</L>
<L>'Bi him,' he seyd, '&thorn;at &thorn;is warld wan,</L>
<L>To sauen al man-kende,</L>
<L>Bi nou&yogh;t &thorn;at y tel can</L>
<L N="5">Y nil neuer spouse wiman</L>
<L>Saue on is fre &amp; hende.'</L>
<L>'Sir,' qua&thorn; &thorn;erl, 'listen nov to me:</L>
<L>Y haue a douhter bri&yogh;t on ble;</L>
<L>Y pray &thorn;e, leue frende,</L>
<L N="10">To wiue wiltow hir vnderstond?</L>
<L>Y schal &thorn;e sese in al mi lond,</L>
<L>To hold wi&thorn;-outen ende.'</L>
</LG>
<LG N="13" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; 'Gramerci!' seyd Gij anon;</L>
<L>'So help me Crist &amp; seyn Ion,</L>
<L>And y schuld spouse a<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>a</I> is a later insertion in the same hand.</NOTE> wiue</L>
<L>Ich hadde leuer hir bodi alon</L>
<L N="5">Than winnen al &thorn;is warldes won</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; ani woman oliue.'<MILESTONE N="147b:b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&THORN;an seyd &thorn;erl, 'gramerci!'</L>
<L>&amp; in his armes he kist sir Gij,</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;onked him mani a si&thorn;e.</L>
<L N="10">'Sir Gij,' he seyd, '&thorn;ou art mi frende:</L>
<L>Now &thorn;ou wilt spouse mi dohter hende</L>
<L>Was y neuer are so bli&thorn;e.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="14" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Ac certes,' seyd &thorn;erl so fre,</L>
<L>'Sir Gij, &yogh;if &thorn;ou wilt trowe me</L>
<L>No lenger &thorn;ou no schalt abide:</L>
<L>Now for fourteni&yogh;t it schal be</L>
<L N="5">&THORN;e bridal hold wi&thorn; gamen &amp; gle</L>
<L>At Warwike in &thorn;at tyde.'
<PB REF="00000398.tif" N="394"></L>
<L>&THORN;an was sir Gij glad &amp; bli&thorn;e:</L>
<L>His joie cou&thorn;e he no man ki&thorn;e.</L>
<L>To his ostel he gan ride.</L>
<L N="10">&amp; &thorn;o Gij com hom to his frende,</L>
<L>He schuld spouse his douhter hende</L>
<L>He teld Herhaud &thorn;at tide.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="15" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; &THORN;erl Rouhaud as swi&thorn;e dede sende<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="7091"></L>
<L>After lordinges fer &amp; hende</L>
<L>&THORN;at pris wel told in tour.</L>
<L>When &thorn;e time was comen to &thorn;ende</L>
<L N="5">To chirche wel feir gun &thorn;ai wende</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; mir&thorn;e &amp; michel anour.</L>
<L>Miche semly folk was gadred &thorn;are</L>
<L>Of erls, barouns lasse &amp; mare,</L>
<L>&amp; leuedis bri&yogh;t in bour.</L>
<L N="10">&THORN;an spoused sir Gij &thorn;at day</L>
<L>Fair Felice, &thorn;at miri may,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; ioie &amp; gre[t] vigour.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="16" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; When he hadde spoused &thorn;at swete wi&yogh;t</L>
<L>&THORN;e fest lasted a fourtenni&yogh;t,</L>
<L>&THORN;at frely folk in fere</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; erl, baroun, &amp; mani a kni&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="5">And mani a leuedy fair &amp; bri&yogh;t,</L>
<L>&THORN;e best in lond &thorn;at were.</L>
<L>&THORN;er wer &yogh;iftes for &thorn;e nones,</L>
<L>Gold, &amp; siluer, &amp; precious stones,</L>
<L>&amp; druries riche &amp; dere.</L>
<L N="10">&THORN;er was mir&thorn;e &amp; melody,</L>
<L>And al maner menstracie</L>
<L>As &yogh;e may for&thorn;eward here.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="17" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; &THORN;er was trumpes &amp; tabour,</L>
<L>Fi&thorn;el, croude, &amp; harpour,<MILESTONE N="148a:a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Her craftes for to ki&thorn;e,
<PB REF="00000400.tif" N="396"></L>
<L>Organisters &amp; gode stiuours,</L>
<L N="5">Minstrels of mou&thorn;e, &amp; mani dysour,</L>
<L>To glade &thorn;o bernes bli&thorn;e.</L>
<L>&THORN;er nis no tong may telle in tale</L>
<L>&THORN;e ioie &thorn;at was at &thorn;at bridale</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; menske &amp; mir&thorn;e to mi&thorn;e;</L>
<L N="10">For &thorn;er was al maner of gle</L>
<L>&THORN;at hert mi&yogh;t &thorn;inke o&thorn;er ey&yogh;e<NOTE PLACE="marg">A faint dot over the second <I>e</I>, which seems to be casual, but was taken by Turn|bull for the ab|breviation for <I>n.</I></NOTE> se</L>
<L>As &yogh;e may list &amp; li&thorn;e.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="18" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Herls, barouns hende &amp; fre,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;er war gadred of mani cuntre,</L>
<L>&THORN;at wor&thorn;liche were in wede,</L>
<L>&THORN;ai &yogh;ouen glewemen for her gle</L>
<L N="5">Robes riche, gold, &amp; fe:</L>
<L>Her &yogh;iftes were nou&yogh;t gnede.</L>
<L>On &thorn;e fiften day ful &yogh;are<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="7107"></L>
<L>&THORN;ai toke her leue for to fare,</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;onked hem her gode dede.</L>
<L N="10">&THORN;an hadde Gij, &thorn;at gentil kni&yogh;t,</L>
<L>Feliis to his wil day &amp; ni&yogh;t</L>
<L>In gest al-so we rede.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="19" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; When Gij hadde spoused &thorn;at hendy flour,</L>
<L>Fair Feliis, so bri&yogh;t in bour,</L>
<L>&THORN;at was him leue &amp; dere,</L>
<L>Y-wis, in Warwike in &thorn;at tour</L>
<L N="5">Fiften days wi&thorn; honour</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; ioie togider &thorn;ai were.</L>
<L>So it bifel &thorn;at first ni&yogh;t</L>
<L>&THORN;at he ney&yogh;ed &thorn;at swete wi&yogh;t</L>
<L>A child &thorn;ai geten y-fere,</L>
<L N="10">&amp; se&thorn;&thorn;en wi&thorn; sorwe &amp; sikeing sare</L>
<L>Her ioie turned hem into care</L>
<L>As ye may forward here.
<PB REF="00000402.tif" N="398"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="20" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; &THORN;an was sir Gij of gret renoun</L>
<L>&amp; holden lord of mani a toun</L>
<L>As prince proude in pride;</L>
<L>&THORN;at erl Rohaut &amp; sir Gyoun,</L>
<L N="5">In fret&thorn;e to fel &thorn;e dere adoun,</L>
<L>On hunting &thorn;ai gun ride.</L>
<L>It bi-fel opon a somers day<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="7119"></L>
<L>&THORN;at sir Gij at Warwike lay</L>
<L>(In herd is nou&yogh;t to hide);</L>
<L N="10">At ni&yogh;t, in tale as it is told,<MILESTONE N="148a:b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>To bedde went &thorn;e bernes bold</L>
<L>Bi time, to rest &thorn;at tide.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="21" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; To a turet sir Gij is went,</L>
<L>&amp; biheld &thorn;at firmament,</L>
<L>&THORN;at thicke wi&thorn; steres stode.</L>
<L>On Iesu omnipotent,</L>
<L N="5">&THORN;at alle his honour hadde him lent,</L>
<L>He &thorn;ou&yogh;t wi&thorn; dreri mode;</L>
<L>Hou he hadde euer ben strong werrour,</L>
<L>For Iesu loue, our saueour,</L>
<L>Neuer no dede he gode.</L>
<L N="10">Mani man he hadde slayn wi&thorn; wrong.</L>
<L>'Allas, allas!' it was his song:</L>
<L>For sorwe he &yogh;ede ner wode.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="22" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; 'Allas,' he seyd, '&thorn;at y was born:</L>
<L>Bodi &amp; soule icham forlorn.</L>
<L>Of blis icham al bare.</L>
<L>For neuer in al mi liif biforn</L>
<L N="5">For him &thorn;at bar &thorn;e croun of &thorn;orn</L>
<L>Gode dede dede y nare;</L>
<L>Bot wer &amp; wo ichaue wrou&yogh;t,<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>don wrou&yogh;t</I>, MS.</NOTE></L>
<L>&amp; mani a man to grounde y-brou&yogh;t:</L>
<L>&THORN;at rewes me ful sare.
<PB REF="00000404.tif" N="400"></L>
<L N="10">To bote min sinnes ichil wende</L>
<L>Barfot to mi liues ende,</L>
<L>To bid mi mete wi&thorn; care.'</L>
</LG>
<LG N="23" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; As Gij stode &thorn;us in tour alon</L>
<L>In hert him was ful wo bigon:</L>
<L>'Allas!' it was his song.</L>
<L>&THORN;an com Feliis sone anon,<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="7151"></L>
<L N="5">&amp; herd him make rewely mon</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; sorwe &amp; care among.</L>
<L>'Leman,' sche seyd, 'what is &thorn;i &thorn;ou&yogh;t?</L>
<L>Whi artow &thorn;us in sorwe brou&yogh;t?</L>
<L>Me&thorn;enke &thorn;i pain wel strong.<NOTE PLACE="marg">The <I>r</I> added above the line.</NOTE></L>
<L N="10">Hastow ou&yogh;t herd of me bot gode,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ou makes &thorn;us dreri mode?</L>
<L>Y-wis, &thorn;ou hast gret wrong.'</L>
</LG>
<LG N="24" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; 'Leman,' seyd Gij o&yogh;ain,</L>
<L>'Ichil &thorn;e telle &thorn;e so&thorn;e ful fain</L>
<L>Whi icham brou&yogh;t to grounde.</L>
<L>Se&thorn;&thorn;en y &thorn;e sey&yogh;e first wi&thorn; ayn</L>
<L N="5">("Allas &thorn;e while," y may sayn)</L>
<L>&THORN;i loue me ha&thorn; so y-bounde,<MILESTONE N="148b:a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&THORN;at neuer se&thorn;&thorn;en no dede y gode,</L>
<L>Bot in wer schadde mannes blode</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; mani a griseli wounde.</L>
<L N="10">Now may me rewe al mi liue.</L>
<L>That euer was y born o wiue,</L>
<L>Wayle-way &thorn;at stounde!</L>
</LG>
<LG N="25" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Ac &yogh;if ich hadde don half &thorn;e dede</L>
<L>For him &thorn;at on rode gan blede</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; grimly woundes sare,</L>
<L>In heuene he wald haue quit mi mede,</L>
<L N="5">In joie to won wi&thorn; angels wede</L>
<L>Euer-more wi&thorn;-outen care.
<PB REF="00000406.tif" N="402"></L>
<L>Ac for &thorn;i loue ich haue al wrou&yogh;t:</L>
<L>For his loue dede y neuer nou&yogh;t.</L>
<L>Iesu amende mi fare!</L>
<L N="10">&THORN;erfore ich wot &thorn;at icham lorn:</L>
<L>Allas &thorn;e time &thorn;at y was born!</L>
<L>Of blis icham al bare.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="26" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Bot god is curteys &amp; hende,</L>
<L>&amp; so dere he ha&thorn; bou&yogh;t mankende,</L>
<L>For no&thorn;ing wil hem lete.</L>
<L>For his loue ichil now wende</L>
<L N="5">Barfot to mi liues ende,</L>
<L>Mine sinnes for to bete,</L>
<L>&THORN;at whore so y lye ani&yogh;t</L>
<L>Y schal neuer be seyn wi&thorn; si&yogh;t</L>
<L>Bi way no bi strete.</L>
<L N="10">Of alle &thorn;e dedes y may do wel</L>
<L>God graunt &thorn;e, lef, &thorn;at haluendel</L>
<L>And Marie, his moder swete.'</L>
</LG>
<LG N="27" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; &THORN;an stode &thorn;at hende leuedi stille,<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="7185"></L>
<L>&amp; in hir hert hir liked ille,</L>
<L>&amp; gan to wepe anon.</L>
<L>'Leman,' sche seyd, 'what is &thorn;i wille?</L>
<L N="5">Y-wis, &thorn;i speche wil me spille:</L>
<L>Y not what y may don.</L>
<L>Y wot &thorn;ou hast in sum cuntre</L>
<L>Spoused ano&thorn;er woman &thorn;an me,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ou wilt to hir gon.</L>
<L N="10">&amp; now &thorn;ou wilt fro me fare,</L>
<L>Allas, allas, now come&thorn; mi care:</L>
<L>For sorwe ichil me slon.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="28" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; For wer &amp; wo &thorn;atow hast wrou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>God &thorn;at al mankende ha&thorn; bou&yogh;t<MILESTONE N="148b:b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>So curteys he is &amp; hende,
<PB REF="00000408.tif" N="404"></L>
<L>Schriue &thorn;e wele in word &amp; &thorn;ou&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="5">&amp; &thorn;an &thorn;e &thorn;arf dout ri&yogh;t nou&yogh;t</L>
<L>O&yogh;aines &thorn;e foule fende.</L>
<L>Chirches &amp; abbays &thorn;ou mi&yogh;t make</L>
<L>&THORN;at schal pray for &thorn;i sake</L>
<L>To him &thorn;at schope mankende:</L>
<L N="10">Hastow no nede to go me fro,</L>
<L>Saue &thorn;ou mi&yogh;t &thorn;i soule fram wo</L>
<L>In joie wi&thorn;outen ende.'</L>
</LG>
<LG N="29" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; 'Leue leman,' &thorn;an seyd sir Gij,</L>
<L>'Lete ben alle &thorn;is reweful cri:</L>
<L>It is nou&yogh;t wor&thorn; &thorn;i tale.</L>
<L>For mani a bern &amp; kni&yogh;t hardi</L>
<L N="5">Ich haue y-sleyn, sikerly,</L>
<L>&amp; strued cites fale,</L>
<L>&amp; for ich haue destrued mankin</L>
<L>Y schal walk for mi sinne</L>
<L>Barfot bi doun &amp; dale.</L>
<L N="10">&THORN;at ich haue wi&thorn; mi bodi wrou&yogh;t</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; mi bodi it schal be bou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>To bote me of &thorn;at bale.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="30" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Leman,' he seyd, 'par charite,</L>
<L>Astow art bo&thorn;e hende &amp; fre,</L>
<L>O &thorn;ing y &thorn;e pray:</L>
<L>Loke &thorn;ou make no sorwe for me,</L>
<L N="5">Bot hold &thorn;e stille astow may be</L>
<L>Til to-morwe at day.</L>
<L>Gret wele &thorn;i fader, &thorn;at is so hende,</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;i moder, &amp; al &thorn;i frende</L>
<L>Bi sond as y &thorn;e say.</L>
<L N="10">Grete wele Herhaud, y &thorn;e biseche.</L>
<L>Leman, god y &thorn;e biteche:</L>
<L>Y wil fare for&thorn; in mi way.
<PB REF="00000410.tif" N="406"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="31" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Leman, y warn &thorn;e biforn,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; a knaue child &thorn;ou art y-corn,</L>
<L>&THORN;at douhti be&thorn; of dede.</L>
<L>For him &thorn;at bar &thorn;e croun of &thorn;orn</L>
<L N="5">&THORN;erfore as sone as it is born</L>
<L>Pray Herhaud wi&yogh;t in wede</L>
<L>He teche mi sone as he wele can</L>
<L>Al &thorn;e &thorn;ewes of gentil man,</L>
<L>&amp; helpe him at his nede;</L>
<L N="10">For he is bo&thorn;e gode &amp; hende,<MILESTONE N="149a:a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&amp; euer he ha&thorn; ben trewe &amp; kende:</L>
<L>God quite him his mede!</L>
</LG>
<LG N="32" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Leman,' he seyd, 'haue here mi brond,</L>
<L>&amp; take mi sone it in his hond,</L>
<L>Astow art hende &amp; fre!</L>
<L>He may &thorn;er-wi&thorn;, ich vnder-stond,</L>
<L N="5">Winne &thorn;e priis in eueri lond;</L>
<L>For better may non be.</L>
<L>Leman,' he seyd, 'haue now gode day:</L>
<L>Ichil fare for&thorn; in mi way,</L>
<L>&amp; wende in mi jurne.'</L>
<L N="10">&THORN;ai kist hem in armes tvo,</L>
<L>&amp; bo&thorn;e &thorn;ai fel aswon &thorn;o.</L>
<L>Gret diol it was to se.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="33" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Gret sorwe &thorn;ai made at her parting,</L>
<L>&amp; kist hem wi&thorn; ey&yogh;en wepeing:</L>
<L>Bi &thorn;e hond sche gan him reche.</L>
<L>'Leman,' sche seyd, 'haue here &thorn;is ring,</L>
<L N="5">For Iesus loue heuen-king</L>
<L>A word y &thorn;e biseche:</L>
<L>When &thorn;ou ert in fer cuntre</L>
<L>Loke heron, &amp; &thorn;enk on me,</L>
<L>&amp; god y &thorn;e biteche.'
<PB REF="00000412.tif" N="408"></L>
<L N="10">Wi&thorn; &thorn;at word he went hir fro</L>
<L>Wepeand wi&thorn; ey&yogh;en to</L>
<L>Wi&thorn;outen more speche.</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="section">
<LG N="34" TYPE="stanza">
<L>Now is Gij fram Warwike fare,<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="7267"></L>
<L>Vnto &thorn;e se he went ful &yogh;are,</L>
<L>&amp; passed ouer &thorn;e flod.</L>
<L>&THORN;e leuedy bileft at hom in care</L>
<L N="5">Wi&thorn; sorwe, &amp; wo, &amp; sikeing sare:<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>fare</I> MS.</NOTE></L>
<L>Wel drery was hir mode.</L>
<L>'Allas, allas!' it was hir song:</L>
<L>Hir here sche drou&yogh;, hir hond sche wrong,</L>
<L>Hir fingres brast o blode.</L>
<L N="10">Al &thorn;at ni&yogh;t til it was day</L>
<L>Hir song it was 'wayleway':</L>
<L>For sorwe sche &yogh;ede ner wode.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="35" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Hir lordes swerd sche drou&yogh; biforn,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Read <I>bifore: sore?</I></NOTE></L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;ou&yogh;t haue slain hirself for sorn<NOTE PLACE="marg">Read <I>bifore: sore?</I></NOTE></L>
<L>Wi&thorn;outen more delay.</L>
<L>To sle hirseluen, er &thorn;e child wer born,</L>
<L N="5">Sche &thorn;ou&yogh;t hir soule it wer forlorn<NOTE PLACE="marg">The <I>r</I> added above the line.</NOTE></L>
<L>Euermore at domesday,<MILESTONE N="149a:b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;at hir fader, hir frendes ichon</L>
<L>Schuld seyn hir lord it hadde y-don,</L>
<L>And were so fled oway.</L>
<L N="10">&THORN;erfore sche dede his swerd o&yogh;ain,</L>
<L>Elles for sorwe sche hadde hir slain,</L>
<L>In gest as y &yogh;ou say.
<PB REF="00000414.tif" N="410"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="36" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Arliche amorwe when it was day</L>
<L>To chaumber, &thorn;er hir fader lay,</L>
<L>Sche com wringand hir hond.</L>
<L>'Fader,' sche seyd, 'ichil &thorn;e say</L>
<L N="5">Mi lord is went fro me his way,</L>
<L>In pilgrimage to fond.</L>
<L>He will passe ouer &thorn;e se,</L>
<L>Schal he neuer com to me</L>
<L>O&yogh;ain into Inglond.'</L>
<L N="10">For sorwe &thorn;at sche hadde &thorn;at stounde</L>
<L>Aswon sche fel adoun to grounde:</L>
<L>O fot no mi&yogh;t sche stonde.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="37" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; 'Douhter,' seyd hir fader, 'lat be.</L>
<L>Y trowe nou&yogh;t &thorn;at sir Gij &thorn;e fre</L>
<L>Is &thorn;us fram &thorn;e fare.</L>
<L>Y-wis, he nis nou&yogh;t passed &thorn;e se:</L>
<L N="5">He ne do&thorn; nou&yogh;t bot for to fond &thorn;e,</L>
<L>Hou trewe of hert &thorn;ou ware.'</L>
<L>'Nay, sir,' sche seyd, 'so god me spede,</L>
<L>He is walked in pouer wede,</L>
<L>To beggen his mete wi&thorn; care.</L>
<L N="10">&amp; &thorn;er-fore now singen y may,</L>
<L>"Allas &thorn;e time &amp; wayleway</L>
<L>&THORN;at mi moder me bare." '</L>
</LG>
<LG N="38" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; &THORN;erl ros vp with sikeing sare,</L>
<L>For sir Gij was fram him fare:</L>
<L>In hert him was ful wo,</L>
<L>&amp; alle his frendes lesse &amp; mare</L>
<L N="5">For sir Gij &thorn;ai hadde gret care,</L>
<L>For he was went hem fro.
<PB REF="00000416.tif" N="412"></L>
<L>&THORN;ai sou&yogh;t him &thorn;an al about</L>
<L>Wi&thorn;in &thorn;e cite &amp; wi&thorn;out,</L>
<L>&THORN;er he was won to go.</L>
<L N="10">&amp; when &thorn;ai founde him nou&yogh;t &thorn;at day</L>
<L>&THORN;ere was mani a wayleway,</L>
<L>Wrin-gand her hondes tvo.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="39" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; And when Gij was fram hem gon<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="7335"></L>
<L>Herhaud, &amp; his frendes ichon,<MILESTONE N="149b:a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&amp; o&thorn;er barouns him by</L>
<L>To &thorn;erl Rohaut &thorn;ai seyden anon,</L>
<L N="5">'&THORN;e best rede &thorn;at we can don,</L>
<L>Smertliche &amp; hastily</L>
<L>Messangers we schul now sende</L>
<L>Ouer alle &thorn;is lond fer &amp; hende,</L>
<L>To seche mi lord sir Gij.</L>
<L N="10">&amp; &yogh;if he be nou&yogh;t in &thorn;is lond</L>
<L>He is in Loreyn, ich vnderstond,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; his bro&thorn;er Tirry.'</L>
</LG>
<LG N="40" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Menssangers anon &thorn;ai sende</L>
<L>Ouer al &thorn;is lond fer &amp; hende</L>
<L>Fram Londen in-to Lou&thorn;e,</L>
<L>Ouer al bi&yogh;onde Humber &amp; Trent,</L>
<L N="5">&amp; est &amp; west &thorn;urch-out al Kent</L>
<L>To &thorn;e hauen of Portesmouthe.</L>
<L>&THORN;ai sou&yogh;t him ouer al vp &amp; doun,</L>
<L>Ouer alle &thorn;e lond in euerich toun</L>
<L>Bi costes &thorn;at wer cou&thorn;e,</L>
<L N="10">&amp; se&thorn;&thorn;en to Warwike &thorn;ai gan wende,</L>
<L>&amp; seyd &thorn;ai mi&yogh;t him no-whar fende</L>
<L>Bi nor&thorn; no bi sou&thorn;e.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="41" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Herhaud was wele vnder-stond<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="7355"></L>
<L>&THORN;at Gij was fer in vncou&thorn;e lond.</L>
<L>Ful hende he was &amp; fre:
<PB REF="00000418.tif" N="414"></L>
<L>Palmers wede he tok on hond,</L>
<L N="5">To seche his lord he wald fond</L>
<L>Vnto &thorn;e Grekis see.</L>
<L>To &thorn;erl Rohaut he seyd anon</L>
<L>To seche his lord he most gon</L>
<L>&THORN;urch alle Christiante.</L>
<L N="10">When &thorn;erl seye him &thorn;us y-di&yogh;t,</L>
<L>'&THORN;ou art,' he seyd, 'a trewe kni&yogh;t:</L>
<L>Y-blisced mot &thorn;ou be.'</L>
</LG>
<LG N="42" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; &THORN;o went Herhaud so trewe in tale</L>
<L>To seche his lord in londes fale:</L>
<L>For no&thorn;ing he nold abide.</L>
<L>He &yogh;ede ouer alle bi doun &amp; dale</L>
<L N="5">To eueri court &amp; kinges sale</L>
<L>Bi mani a lond side,</L>
<L>&THORN;urch Normondye<NOTE PLACE="marg">The <I>r</I> added above the line.</NOTE> and alle Speyne,</L>
<L>Into Fraunce &amp; &thorn;urch Breteyne:</L>
<L>He &yogh;ede bo&thorn;e fer &amp; wide</L>
<L N="10">&THORN;urch Lorain &amp; &thorn;urch Lombardye,<MILESTONE N="149b:b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&amp; neuer no herd he telle of Gij</L>
<L>For nou&yogh;t &thorn;at mi&yogh;t bitide.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="43" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; When Herhaud had sou&yogh;t him fer and hende,</L>
<L>&amp; he no mi&yogh;t him no-whar fende,</L>
<L>Noi&thorn;er bi se no sond,</L>
<L>Into Inglond he gan wende,</L>
<L N="5">&amp; &thorn;erl Rohaut &amp; al his frende</L>
<L>At Warwike he hem fond,
<PB REF="00000420.tif" N="416"></L>
<L>&amp; teld he hadde his lord sou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;at he no mi&yogh;t finde him nou&yogh;t</L>
<L>In non skinnes lond.</L>
<L N="10">Mani a moder child &thorn;at day</L>
<L>Wepe &amp; gan say, 'waileway,'<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. <I>waileway</I> rather than <I>walleway</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>Wel sore wringand her hond.</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="section">
<LG N="44" TYPE="stanza">
<L>Now herken, &amp; &yogh;e may here<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="7391"></L>
<L>In gest, &yogh;if &yogh;e wil listen &amp; lere,</L>
<L>Hou Gij as pilgrim &yogh;ede.</L>
<L>He welke about wi&thorn; glad chere</L>
<L N="5">&THORN;urch mani londes fer &amp; nere,</L>
<L>&THORN;er god him wald spede.</L>
<L>First he went to Jerusalem,</L>
<L>&amp; se&thorn;&thorn;en he went to Bedlem</L>
<L>&THORN;urch mani an vncou&thorn;e &thorn;ede.</L>
<L N="10">&YOGH;ete he bi&thorn;ou&yogh;t him se&thorn;&thorn;en &thorn;o</L>
<L>For to sechen halwen mo,</L>
<L>To winne him heuen mede.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="45" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; &THORN;o he went his pilgrimage</L>
<L>Toward &thorn;e court of Antiage,</L>
<L>Bi &thorn;is half &thorn;at cite</L>
<L>He mett a man of fair parage:</L>
<L N="5">Y-comen he was of hey&yogh;e linage,</L>
<L>&amp; of kin fair &amp; fre.</L>
<L>Michel he was of bodi y-pi&yogh;t,</L>
<L>A man he semed of michel mi&yogh;t</L>
<L>&amp; of gret bounte,</L>
<L N="10">Wi&thorn; white-hore heued &amp; berd y-blowe,</L>
<L>As white as ani driuen snowe:</L>
<L>Gret sorwe &thorn;an made he.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="46" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; So gret sorwe &thorn;er he made,</L>
<L>Sir Gij of him rew&thorn;e hade.</L>
<L>He gan to wepe so sare,
<PB REF="00000422.tif" N="418"></L>
<L>His clo&thorn; he rent, his here to-tore,<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>to torn</I> MS.</NOTE></L>
<L N="5">&amp; curssed &thorn;e time &thorn;at he was bore:<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>born</I> MS.</NOTE></L>
<L>Wel diolful was his fare.<MILESTONE N="150a:a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>More sorwe made neuer man.</L>
<L>Gij stode &amp; loked on him &thorn;an,</L>
<L>&amp; hadde of him gret care.</L>
<L N="10">He seyd, 'allas &amp; walewo!</L>
<L>Al mi joie it is ago.</L>
<L>Of blis icham al bare.'</L>
</LG>
<LG N="47" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; 'Gode man, what artow,' seyd Gij,</L>
<L>'&THORN;at makest &thorn;us &thorn;is reweful cri</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;us sorweful mone?</L>
<L>Me&thorn;enke, for &thorn;e icham sori,</L>
<L N="5">For &thorn;at &thorn;ine hert is &thorn;us drery,</L>
<L>&THORN;i ioie is fro &thorn;e gon.</L>
<L>Telle me &thorn;e so&thorn;e, y pray &thorn;e</L>
<L>For godes loue in trinite,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;is world ha&thorn; in won;</L>
<L N="10">For Iesu is of so michel mi&yogh;t,</L>
<L>He may make &thorn;ine hert li&yogh;t,</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;ou no[s]t neuer hou son.'</L>
</LG>
<LG N="48" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; 'Gode man,' seyd &thorn;e pilgrim,</L>
<L>'&THORN;ou hast me frained bi god &thorn;in</L>
<L>To telle &thorn;e of mi fare,</L>
<L>And alle &thorn;e so&thorn; wi&thorn;-outen les</L>
<L N="5">Ichil &thorn;e telle, hou it wes,</L>
<L>Of blis hou icham bare.</L>
<L>So michel sorwe is on me steke,</L>
<L>&THORN;at min hert it wil to-breke</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; sorwe &amp; sikeing sare.</L>
<L N="10">Forlorn ich haue al mi blis:</L>
<L>Y no schal neuer haue joie, y-wis.</L>
<L>In er&thorn;e y wald y ware.
<PB REF="00000424.tif" N="420"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="49" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; A man y was of state sum stounde,<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="7429"></L>
<L>&amp; holden a lord of gret mounde,</L>
<L>&amp; erl of al Durras.</L>
<L>Fair sones ich hadde fiftene,</L>
<L N="5">&amp; alle were kni&yogh;tes stout &amp; kene.</L>
<L>Men cleped me &thorn;erl Ionas.</L>
<L>Y trowe in &thorn;is warld is man non,</L>
<L>Y-wis, &thorn;at is so wo-bi-gon,</L>
<L>Se&thorn;&thorn;en &thorn;e world made was;</L>
<L N="10">For alle min sones ich haue forlorn:</L>
<L>Better berns were non born.</L>
<L>&THORN;erfore y sing, "allas!"</L>
</LG>
<LG N="50" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; For bli&thorn;e wor&thorn; y neuer more:</L>
<L>Alle mi sones ich haue forlore<MILESTONE N="150a:b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&THORN;urch a batayl vnride,</L>
<L>&THORN;urch Sarrazins &thorn;at fel wore:</L>
<L N="5">To Ierusalem &thorn;ai com ful &yogh;ore</L>
<L>To rob &amp; reue wi&thorn; pride,</L>
<L>&amp; we toke our ost anon,</L>
<L>O&yogh;aines hem we gun gon,</L>
<L>Bateyl of hem to abide.</L>
<L N="10">&THORN;e acountre of hem was so strong,</L>
<L>&THORN;at mani dyed &thorn;er-among,</L>
<L>Or we wald rest &thorn;at tide.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="51" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; &THORN;urch mi fiftene sone<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>som</I> MS.</NOTE></L>
<L>Were &thorn;e geauntes ouer-come,</L>
<L>&amp; driuen doun to grounde.</L>
<L>Fiftene amirals &thorn;er wer nome:</L>
<L N="5">&THORN;e king gan fle wi&thorn; alle his trome</L>
<L>For drede of ous &thorn;at stounde.</L>
<L>Ich &amp; mi sones, wi&thorn;outen lesing,</L>
<L>Out of &thorn;at lond we driuen &thorn;e king,</L>
<L>And his men &yogh;af dedli wounde.
<PB REF="00000426.tif" N="422"></L>
<L N="10">&THORN;e king him hi&yogh;t Triamour:</L>
<L>A lord he was of gret honour,</L>
<L>&amp; man of michel mounde.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="52" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; &THORN;an dede we wel-gret foly:</L>
<L>We suwed him wi&thorn; maistrie</L>
<L>Into his owhen lond.</L>
<L>Into Alisaundre &thorn;ai fleye owy:</L>
<L N="5">&THORN;e cuntre ros vp wi&thorn; a cri,</L>
<L>To help her king anhond.</L>
<L>In a brom feld &thorn;er wer hidde</L>
<L>&THORN;re hundred Sarrazins wele y-schridde</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; helme &amp; grimly brond.</L>
<L N="10">Out of &thorn;at brom &thorn;ai lepen anon,</L>
<L>&amp; bilapped ous euer-ichon,</L>
<L>&amp; drof ous alle to schond.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="53" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; &THORN;ai hewen at ous wi&thorn; michel hete,</L>
<L>&amp; we leyd on hem dintes grete,</L>
<L>&amp; slouwen of her ferred.</L>
<L>&amp; ar &thorn;at we were alle y-nome</L>
<L N="5">Mani of hem were ouercome,</L>
<L>Ded wounded vnder wede.</L>
<L>&THORN;ai were to mani &amp; we to fewe:</L>
<L>Al our armour &thorn;ai to-hewe,</L>
<L>&amp; stiked vnder ous our stede.</L>
<L N="10">&YOGH;ete we fou&yogh;ten afot long,<MILESTONE N="150b:a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Til swerdes brosten &thorn;at were strong,</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;an &yogh;eld we ous for nede.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="54" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; To &thorn;e king we &yogh;olden ous al &amp; some</L>
<L>&THORN;at we mi&yogh;t to raunsom come,</L>
<L>To saue our liues ichon.</L>
<L>Into Alisaunder he ladde ous &thorn;o,</L>
<L N="5">&amp; into his prisoun dede ous do,</L>
<L>Was maked of lime &amp; ston.
<PB REF="00000428.tif" N="424"></L>
<L>Litel was our drink &amp; lasse our mete,</L>
<L>For hunger we wende our liues lete:</L>
<L>Wel wo was ous bigon.</L>
<L N="10">So were we &thorn;er alle &thorn;at &yogh;er</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; michel sorwe bo&thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="marg">Read <I>alle</I>?</NOTE> y-fere,</L>
<L>&THORN;at socour com ous non.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="55" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; So it bifel &thorn;at riche Soudan<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="7487"></L>
<L>Made a fest of mani a man,</L>
<L>Of &thorn;ritti kinges bi tale.</L>
<L>King Triamour com to court &thorn;o,</L>
<L N="5">&amp; Fabour, his sone, dede also,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; kni&yogh;tes mani &amp; fale.</L>
<L>&THORN;e &thorn;ridde day of &thorn;at fest,</L>
<L>&THORN;at was so riche &amp; so honest,</L>
<L>So derlich di&yogh;t in sale&mdash;</L>
<L N="10">After &thorn;at fest, &thorn;at riche was,</L>
<L>&THORN;er bifel a wonder cas,</L>
<L>Wher-&thorn;urch ros michel bale.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="56" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; &THORN;at riche Soudan hadde a sone</L>
<L>&THORN;at was y-hold a doughti gome:</L>
<L>Sadok was his name.</L>
<L>&THORN;e kinges sone Fabour he cleped him to:</L>
<L N="5">Into his chaumber &thorn;ai gun go,</L>
<L>&THORN;o knightes bo&thorn;e y-same.</L>
<L>Sadok gan to Fabour sayn</L>
<L>&YOGH;if he wald ate ches playn,</L>
<L>&amp; held o&yogh;ain him game;</L>
<L N="10">&amp; he answerd in gode maner</L>
<L>He wald play wi&thorn; him y-fere,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn;-outen ani blame.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="57" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Ate ches &thorn;ai sett hem to playn,</L>
<L>&THORN;o hendy kni&yogh;tes bo&thorn;e tvayn,</L>
<L>&THORN;at egre were of si&yogh;t:<NOTE PLACE="marg">Read <I>fi&yogh;t?</I></NOTE>
<PB REF="00000430.tif" N="426"></L>
<L>Er &thorn;ai hadde don half a game,</L>
<L N="5">Wi&thorn; strong wret&thorn;e &thorn;ai gan to grame,</L>
<L>&THORN;o gomes michel of mi&yogh;t.<MILESTONE N="150b:b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&THORN;urch a chek Fabour seyd, for so&thorn;,</L>
<L>Sadok in hert wex wro&thorn;,</L>
<L>&amp; missayd him anon ri&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="10">&amp; clep[e]d him 'fiz a putayn,'</L>
<L>&amp; smot him wi&thorn; mi&yogh;t and main,</L>
<L>Wher-&thorn;urch ros michel fi&yogh;t.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="58" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Wi&thorn; a roke he brac his heued &thorn;an,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;e blod biforn out span</L>
<L>In &thorn;at ich place.</L>
<L>'Sadok,' seyd &thorn;an Fabour,</L>
<L N="5">'&THORN;ou dost me gret deshonour</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ou me manace.</L>
<L>Nar &thorn;ou mi lordes sone were,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou schuldest dye ri&yogh;t now here:</L>
<L>Schustow neuer hennes passe.'</L>
<L N="10">Sadok stirt vp to Fabour,</L>
<L>&amp; cleped him anon 'vile traitour,'</L>
<L>&amp; smot him in the face.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="59" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Wi&thorn; his fest he smot him &thorn;ore,</L>
<L>&THORN;at Fabour was agreued sore,</L>
<L>&amp; stirt vp in &thorn;at stounde.</L>
<L>&THORN;e cheker he hent vp fot hot,</L>
<L N="5">And Sadok in &thorn;e heued he smot,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he fel ded to grounde.</L>
<L>His fader sone he ha&thorn; y-teld</L>
<L>&THORN;at he ha&thorn; the Soudan sone aqueld,</L>
<L>&amp; &yogh;ouen him de&thorn;es wounde.
<PB REF="00000432.tif" N="428"></L>
<L N="10">On hors &thorn;ai lopen &thorn;an biliue,</L>
<L>Out of &thorn;e lond &thorn;ai gun driue</L>
<L>For ferd &thorn;ai were y-founde.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="60" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; When it was &thorn;e Soudan teld,<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="7551"></L>
<L>&THORN;at his sone was aqueld,</L>
<L>&amp; brou&yogh;t of his liif dawe,</L>
<L>On al maner he him bi&thorn;ou&yogh;t</L>
<L N="5">Hou &thorn;at he him wreke mou&yogh;t</L>
<L>&THORN;urch iugement of lawe.</L>
<L>After &thorn;e king he sent an hey&yogh;e,</L>
<L>To defende him of &thorn;at felonie,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he his sone ha&thorn; y-slawe;</L>
<L N="10">&amp; bot he wald com anon</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; streng&thorn;e he schuld on him gon,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; wilde hors don him drawe.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="61" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; King Triamour com to court &thorn;o,</L>
<L>&amp; Fabour, his sone, dede also,<MILESTONE N="151a:a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>To &thorn;e Soudans parlement.</L>
<L>When &thorn;ai bi-forn him comen be&thorn;</L>
<L N="5">&THORN;ai were adouted of her de&thorn;:</L>
<L>Her liues &thorn;ai wende haue spent;</L>
<L>For &thorn;e Soudan cleped hem fot hot,</L>
<L>&amp; his sones de&thorn; hem atwot,</L>
<L>&amp; seyd &thorn;ai were alle schent.
<PB REF="00000434.tif" N="430"></L>
<L N="10">Bot &thorn;ai hem &thorn;erof were mi&yogh;t</L>
<L>In strong perile he schuld hem di&yogh;t</L>
<L>And to her iugement.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="62" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; &THORN;an dede he com for&thorn; a Sarrazine,</L>
<L>Haue he Cristes curs &amp; mine</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; boke &amp; eke wi&thorn; belle.</L>
<L>Out of Egypt he was y-come,</L>
<L N="5">Michel &amp; griselich was &thorn;at gome</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; ani god man to duelle.</L>
<L>He is so michel &amp; vnrede,</L>
<L>Of his si&yogh;t a man may drede,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; tong as y &thorn;e telle.</L>
<L N="10">As blac he is as brodes brend:</L>
<L>He semes as it were a fende,</L>
<L>&THORN;at comen were out of helle.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="63" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; For he is so michel of bodi y-pi&yogh;t,</L>
<L>O&yogh;ains him tvelue men haue no mi&yogh;t,</L>
<L>Ben &thorn;ai neuer so strong;</L>
<L>For he is four fot, sikerly,</L>
<L N="5">More &thorn;an ani man stont him bi:</L>
<L>So wonderliche he is long.</L>
<L>&YOGH;if king Triamour &thorn;at &thorn;er was</L>
<L>Mi&yogh;t fenden him in playn place</L>
<L>Of &thorn;at michel wrong,</L>
<L N="10">&THORN;an is &thorn;at vile glotoun</L>
<L>Made &thorn;e Soudans champioun,</L>
<L>Batayl of him to fong.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="64" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; King Triamour answerd &thorn;an<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="7593"></L>
<L>To &thorn;at riche Soudan</L>
<L>In &thorn;at ich stounde</L>
<L>&THORN;at he wald defende him wele y-nou&yogh;</L>
<L N="5">&THORN;at he neuer his sone slou&yogh;,</L>
<L>No &yogh;af him dedli wounde.
<PB REF="00000436.tif" N="432"></L>
<L>When he seye Amoraunt so grim</L>
<L>(&THORN;er durst no man fi&yogh;t wi&thorn; him:</L>
<L>So grille he was on grounde),</L>
<L N="10">&THORN;an asked he respite til a day,<MILESTONE N="151a:b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>To finde ano&thorn;er &yogh;if he may</L>
<L>O&yogh;aines him durst founde.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="65" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; &THORN;an hadde he respite al &thorn;at &yogh;ere</L>
<L>&amp; fourti days: so was &thorn;e maner</L>
<L>&THORN;urch lawe was &thorn;an in lond,</L>
<L>&YOGH;if him seluen durst nou&yogh;t fi&yogh;t</L>
<L N="5">Finde ano&thorn;er &yogh;if he mi&yogh;t</L>
<L>O&yogh;aines him durst stond.</L>
<L>&THORN;e king as swi&thorn;e hom is went,</L>
<L>Ouer alle his lond anon he sent</L>
<L>After erl, baroun, and bond,</L>
<L N="10">&amp; asked &yogh;if ani wer so bold:</L>
<L>&THORN;riddendel his lond haue he schold</L>
<L>&THORN;e batayl durst take an hond.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="66" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Ac for nou&yogh;t &thorn;at he hot mi&yogh;t</L>
<L>&THORN;er was non durst take &thorn;e fi&yogh;t</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; &thorn;e geaunt for his sake.</L>
<L>&THORN;an was ich out of prisoun nome,</L>
<L N="5">Biforn him he dede me come,</L>
<L>Conseyl of me to take,</L>
<L>And asked me at worde fewe</L>
<L>&YOGH;if y wist o&thorn;er y-knewe</L>
<L>A man so mi&yogh;ti of strake</L>
<L N="10">&THORN;at for him durst take &thorn;e fi&yogh;t:</L>
<L>Were he buriays o&thorn;er kni&yogh;t,</L>
<L>Riche prince he wald him make.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="67" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; &amp; &yogh;if y mi&yogh;t ani fende</L>
<L>He wald make me riche &amp; al mi kende,</L>
<L>&amp; &yogh;if me gret honour,
<PB REF="00000438.tif" N="434"></L>
<L>&amp; wold sese into min hond</L>
<L N="5">To helden &thorn;riddendel his lond</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; cite, toun, &amp; tour.</L>
<L>Ac ichim answerd &thorn;an</L>
<L>In alle &thorn;is warld was &thorn;er [no] man</L>
<L>To fi&yogh;t wi&thorn; &thorn;at traitour,</L>
<L N="10">Bot &yogh;if it Gij of Warwike were,</L>
<L>Or Herhaud of Ardern, his fere:</L>
<L>'In warld &thorn;ai bere &thorn;e flour.'</L>
</LG>
<LG N="68" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; When &thorn;e king herd &thorn;o<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="7633"></L>
<L>&THORN;at y spac of &thorn;o kni&yogh;tes to,</L>
<L>Ful bli&thorn;e he was of chere.</L>
<L>He kist me, so glad he was.</L>
<L N="5">'Merci,' he seyd, 'erl Ionas!</L>
<L>&THORN;ou art me leue &amp; dere.<MILESTONE N="151b:a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&YOGH;if ich hadde here sir Gij,</L>
<L>Or Herhaud, &thorn;at is so hardi,</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e maistri siker y were.</L>
<L N="10">&amp; &thorn;ou mi&yogh;test bring me her on,</L>
<L>&THORN;e &amp; thine sones y schal lete gon</L>
<L>Fram prisoun quite &amp; skere.'</L>
</LG>
<LG N="69" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Bi mi lay he dede me swere</L>
<L>&THORN;at y schuld trewelich bode bere</L>
<L>To &thorn;o kni&yogh;tes so hende,</L>
<L>&amp; seyd to me as swi&thorn;e anon</L>
<L N="5">Wi&thorn; michel sorwe he schuld me slon</L>
<L>Bot ichem mi&yogh;t fende,
<PB REF="00000440.tif" N="436"></L>
<L>&amp; al mine sones do to-drawe,</L>
<L>&amp; ichim graunt in &thorn;at &thorn;rawe,</L>
<L>To bring hem out of bende.</L>
<L N="10">Out of &thorn;is lond y went &thorn;o</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; michel care &amp; michel wo:</L>
<L>Y nist wider to wende.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="70" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Y sou&yogh;t hem into the lond of Coyne,</L>
<L>Into Calaber, &amp; into Sessoyne,</L>
<L>&amp; fro &thorn;ennes into Almayne,</L>
<L>In Tuskan &amp; in Lombardye,</L>
<L N="5">In Fraunce &amp; in Normondye,</L>
<L>Into &thorn;e lond of Speyne,</L>
<L>In Braban, in Poil, &amp; in Bars</L>
<L>&amp; in-to kinges lond of Tars,</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;urch al Aquitayne,</L>
<L N="10">In Cisil, in Hungri, &amp; in Ragoun,</L>
<L>In Romayne, Borgoine, &amp; Gascoine,</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;urch-out al Breteyne.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="71" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; &amp; into Inglond wenden y gan,</L>
<L>&amp; asked &thorn;er mani a man,</L>
<L>Bo&thorn;e &yogh;ong &amp; old,</L>
<L>&amp; in Warwike &thorn;at cite,</L>
<L N="5">&THORN;er he was lord of &thorn;at cuntre,</L>
<L>For to hauen in wold;</L>
<L>Ac y no fond non lite no miche</L>
<L>&THORN;at cou&thorn;e telle me sikerliche</L>
<L>Of &thorn;o to kni&yogh;tes bold,</L>
<L N="10">Wher y schold Gij no Herhaud fende</L>
<L>In no lond fer no hende:</L>
<L>&THORN;erfore min hert is cold.
<PB REF="00000442.tif" N="438"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="72" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; For ich haue &thorn;e king mi trew&thorn;e y-pli&yogh;t</L>
<L>&THORN;at y schal bring Gij now ri&yogh;t<MILESTONE N="151b:b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&YOGH;if ich oliues be.</L>
<L>&amp; &yogh;iue y bring him nou&yogh;t anon</L>
<L N="5">Wele ich wot he wil me slon:</L>
<L>&THORN;er-fore wel wo is me.</L>
<L>&amp; min sones he schal don hong,</L>
<L>&amp; to-drawe wi&thorn; michel wrong,</L>
<L>&THORN;o kni&yogh;tes hende &amp; fre.</L>
<L N="10">&amp; &yogh;if &thorn;ai dye gret harm it is.</L>
<L>For hem ich haue swiche sorwe,<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>sorwe</I> added at the end of the line.</NOTE> y-wis:</L>
<L>Mine hert wil breken on &thorn;re.'</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="section">
<LG N="73" TYPE="stanza">
<L>'God man,' seyd Gij, 'listen me now.<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="7703"></L>
<L>For &thorn;ine sones gret sorwe hastow,</L>
<L>&amp; no wonder it nis.</L>
<L>When &thorn;ou Gij &amp; Herhaud hast<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>ha&thorn;</I> MS.</NOTE> sou&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="5">&amp; &thorn;ou no may hem finde nou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>&THORN;i care is michel, y-wis.</L>
<L>&THORN;urch hem &thorn;ine hope was to go fre,</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;i sones al for&thorn; wi&thorn; &thorn;e,</L>
<L>&THORN;urch godes help &amp; his.
<PB REF="00000444.tif" N="440"></L>
<L N="10">Sum time bi dayes old</L>
<L>For douhti man y was<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>men &thorn;ai wer</I> MS.</NOTE> told</L>
<L>&amp; holden of gret priis.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="74" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; &THORN;urch godes helpe, our dri&yogh;t</L>
<L>(He be min help, &amp; &yogh;iue me mi&yogh;t,</L>
<L>&amp; leue me wele to spede!),</L>
<L>&amp; for Gyes loue &amp; Herhaud also,</L>
<L N="5">&THORN;at &thorn;ou hast sou&yogh;t wi&thorn; michel wo,</L>
<L>&THORN;at douhti were of dede,</L>
<L>Batayl ichil now for &thorn;e fong</L>
<L>O&yogh;ain &thorn;e geaunt, &thorn;at is so strong,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou seyst is so vnrede.</L>
<L N="10">&amp; &thorn;ei he be &thorn;e fende out-ri&yogh;t,</L>
<L>Y schal for &thorn;e take &thorn;e fi&yogh;t,</L>
<L>&amp; help &thorn;e at &thorn;is nede.'</L>
</LG>
<LG N="75" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; When &thorn;erl herd him speke so,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he wald batayl fong for him &thorn;o,</L>
<L>He biheld fot &amp; heued:</L>
<L>Michel he was of bodi pi&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="5">A man he semed of michel mi&yogh;t,</L>
<L>Ac pouerliche he was biweued;</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; a long berd his neb was growe.</L>
<L>Miche wo him &thorn;ought he hadde y-drowe.</L>
<L>He wende his wit were reued,</L>
<L N="10">For he seyd he wald as &yogh;ern<MILESTONE N="152a:a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Fi&yogh;t wi&thorn; &thorn;at geaunt stern</L>
<L>Bot.<NOTE PLACE="marg">Read <I>As</I>?</NOTE> &yogh;if he hadde him preued.<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>proued</I> MS.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG N="76" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; 'God man,' &thorn;an seyd he,</L>
<L>'God al-mi&yogh;ten for-&yogh;eld it &thorn;e,</L>
<L>&THORN;at is so michel of mi&yogh;t,</L>
<L>&THORN;atow wost batayl for me fong</L>
<L N="5">O&yogh;ain &thorn;e geaunt, &thorn;at is so strong.</L>
<L>&THORN;ou knowest him nou&yogh;t, y pli&yogh;t.
<PB REF="00000446.tif" N="442"></L>
<L>For &yogh;if he loked on &thorn;e wi&thorn; wrake</L>
<L>Sternliche wi&thorn; his ey&yogh;en blake,</L>
<L>So grim he is of si&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="10">Wastow neuer so bold in al &thorn;i teime,<NOTE PLACE="marg">So MS.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;atow durst batayl of him nim,</L>
<L>No hold o&yogh;aines him fi&yogh;t.'</L>
</LG>
<LG N="77" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; 'Gode man,' seyd Gij, 'lat be &thorn;at &thorn;ou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>For swiche wordes help ous nou&yogh;t</L>
<L>O&yogh;ain &thorn;at schrewe qued.</L>
<L>Mani ha&thorn; loked me opon</L>
<L N="5">Wi&thorn; wicked wil, mani on</L>
<L>&THORN;at wald han had min hed;</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;ei no fled y neuer &yogh;ete,</L>
<L>No neuer for ferd batayl lete</L>
<L>For noman &thorn;at brac bred.</L>
<L N="10">&amp; &thorn;ei he be &thorn;e deuels rote,</L>
<L>Y schal nou&yogh;t fle him a fot,</L>
<L>Bi him &thorn;at suffred ded.'</L>
</LG>
<LG N="78" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; 'Leue sir,' &thorn;an seyd he,</L>
<L>'God of heuen for&yogh;eld it te:</L>
<L>&THORN;ine wordes er ful swete.'</L>
<L>For ioie he hadde in hert &thorn;at stounde</L>
<L N="5">On knes he fel adoun to grounde,</L>
<L>&amp; kist sir Gyes fet.</L>
<L>Gij tok him vp in armes to.</L>
<L>Into Alisaunder &thorn;ai gun go,<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="7755"></L>
<L>Wi&thorn; &thorn;e king to mete;</L>
<L N="10">&amp; when &thorn;ai com in-to &thorn;e tour</L>
<L>Bifor &thorn;e king sir Triamour,</L>
<L>Wel fair &thorn;ai gun him grete.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="79" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; And when he seye &thorn;erl Ionas,</L>
<L>Unne&thorn;e he knewe him in &thorn;e fas:</L>
<L>So chaunged was his ble.
<PB REF="00000448.tif" N="444"></L>
<L>'Erl Ionas,' seyd &thorn;e king,</L>
<L N="5">'Telle me now wi&thorn;-outen lesing,<MILESTONE N="152a:b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Gij &amp; Herhaud where ben he?'</L>
<L>&THORN;erl answerd, &amp; siked sore,</L>
<L>'Gij no Herhaud sestow no more;</L>
<L>For so&thorn;e y telle &thorn;e,</L>
<L N="10">For hem ich haue in Inglond ben,</L>
<L>&amp; y no mi&yogh;t hem no-whar sen:</L>
<L>&THORN;er-fore wel wo is me.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="80" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Ac &thorn;e lond folk teld me in speche</L>
<L>&THORN;at Gij was gon halwen to seche</L>
<L>Wel fer in vncou&thorn;e lond,</L>
<L>&amp; Herhaud after him is went</L>
<L N="5">For to seche him, verrament:</L>
<L>Noi&thorn;er of hem y no fond,</L>
<L>Ac &thorn;is man ich haue brou&yogh;t to &thorn;e</L>
<L>&THORN;at ha&thorn; ben man of gret bounte,</L>
<L>&THORN;at wele dar take on hond</L>
<L N="10">O&yogh;ain &thorn;e geaunt &thorn;at is so fel,</L>
<L>Al for to fende &thorn;e ful wel:</L>
<L>For drede wil he nou&yogh;t wond.'</L>
</LG>
<LG N="81" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; 'Erl Ionas,' seyd &thorn;e king,<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="7779"></L>
<L>'Loke wi&thorn; him be no feynting,</L>
<L>&THORN;at y deseyued be.</L>
<L>&amp; &yogh;if &thorn;er be, &thorn;ou schalt anon</L>
<L N="5">Be honged &amp; &thorn;i sones ichon.'</L>
<L>'Y graunt, sir,' &thorn;an seyd he.</L>
<L>&THORN;e king cleped sir Gyoun,</L>
<L>&amp; asked him at schort resoun,</L>
<L>'What is &thorn;y name? tel me.'</L>
<L N="10">Sir Gij answerd to &thorn;e king,</L>
<L>'Youn,' he said, 'wi&thorn;-outen lesing,</L>
<L>Men clepe&thorn; me in mi cuntre.'
<PB REF="00000450.tif" N="446"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="82" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; 'What cuntre artow?' &thorn;e king sede.</L>
<L>'Of Inglond, so god me rede:</L>
<L>&THORN;erin ich was y-bore.'<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>y born</I> MS.</NOTE></L>
<L>'Owe,' seyd &thorn;e king, 'artow Inglis kni&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="5">&THORN;an schuld y &thorn;urch skil and ri&yogh;t</L>
<L>Hate &thorn;e euer more.</L>
<L>Knewe &thorn;ou nou&yogh;t &thorn;e gode<NOTE PLACE="marg">An erasure before <I>gode.</I></NOTE> Gij</L>
<L>Or Herhaud &thorn;at was so hardi?</L>
<L>Tel me &thorn;e so&thorn;e bifore.</L>
<L N="10">Wele ou&yogh;t ich be Gyes foman:</L>
<L>He slou&yogh; mi bro&thorn;er Helmadan;</L>
<L>&THORN;urch him icham forlore.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="83" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Min em<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>Minem</I> MS.</NOTE> he slou&yogh;, &thorn;e riche Soudan,</L>
<L>Ate mete among ous euerilkan.<MILESTONE N="152b:a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Sey&yogh;e y neuer man so bigin:<NOTE PLACE="marg">The first two letters are indis|tinct; Turnbull <I>ingin.</I></NOTE></L>
<L>Y sey&yogh;e hou he his heued of smot,</L>
<L N="5">&amp; bar it oway wi&thorn; him fot hot,</L>
<L>Maugre &thorn;at was &thorn;er-inne.</L>
<L>After him we driuen &thorn;o,</L>
<L>&THORN;e deuel halp him &thorn;ennes to go:</L>
<L>Y trowe he is of his kinne.</L>
<L N="10">Mahoun &yogh;af &thorn;at &thorn;ou wer he!</L>
<L>Ful siker mi&yogh;t y &thorn;an be</L>
<L>&THORN;e maistri for to winne.'</L>
</LG>
<LG N="84" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Sir Gij answerd to &thorn;e king,</L>
<L>'Wel wele y knowe, wi&thorn;outen lesing,</L>
<L>Herhaud, so god me rede.</L>
<L>&amp; &yogh;if &thorn;ou haddest her on here,</L>
<L N="5">Of &thorn;e maistri siker &thorn;ou were,</L>
<L>&THORN;e bateyl for to bede.'
<PB REF="00000452.tif" N="448"></L>
<L>&THORN;e king asked him anon ri&yogh;t,</L>
<L>'Whi artow &thorn;us iuel y-di&yogh;t</L>
<L>And in &thorn;us pouer wede?</L>
<L N="10">A feble lord &thorn;ou seruest, so &thorn;enke&thorn; me,</L>
<L>Or oway he ha&thorn; driuen &thorn;e</L>
<L>For sum iuel dede.'</L>
</LG>
<LG N="85" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; 'Nay, sir, for god,' qua&thorn; Gij,</L>
<L>'A wel gode lord [ar] &thorn;an serue[d] y:</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; him was no blame.</L>
<L>Wel michel honour he me dede,</L>
<L N="5">&amp; gret wor&thorn;schipe in eueri stede,</L>
<L>&amp; sore ich haue him grame[d],<NOTE PLACE="marg">The <I>r</I> added above the line.</NOTE></L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;er-fore icham &thorn;us y-di&yogh;t,</L>
<L>To cri him merci day &amp; ni&yogh;t,</L>
<L>Til we ben frendes same.</L>
<L N="10">&amp; mi lord &amp; y frende be,</L>
<L>Ichil wende hom to mi cuntre,</L>
<L>&amp; liue wi&thorn; ioie &amp; game.'</L>
</LG>
<LG N="86" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; 'Frende Youn,' seyd &thorn;e king,<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="7838"></L>
<L>'Wiltow fi&yogh;t for mi &thorn;ing?</L>
<L>O&thorn;er y schal ano&thorn;er puruay.'</L>
<L>'&THORN;erfor com ich hider,' qua&thorn; Gij,</L>
<L N="5">'&THORN;urch Godes help &amp; our leuedi</L>
<L>As wele as y may.</L>
<L>Bot first &thorn;erl Ionas &amp; his sones</L>
<L>Schal be deliuerd<NOTE PLACE="marg">The <I>i</I> added above the line.</NOTE> out of prisones</L>
<L>&THORN;is ich selue day.'<NOTE PLACE="marg">A line erased after this.</NOTE></L>
<L N="10">&THORN;e king answerd, 'y graunt &thorn;e.<MILESTONE N="152b:b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Mahoun he mot &thorn;ine he[l]p be,</L>
<L>&THORN;at is mi lord verray.'
<PB REF="00000454.tif" N="450"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="87" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; 'Nay,' seyd Gij, 'bot Marie sone:</L>
<L>He mot me<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>me</I>] <I>&thorn;e</I> erased in MS.</NOTE> to help come,</L>
<L>For Mahoun is wor&thorn; nou&yogh;t.'</L>
<L>'Frende Youn,' seyd &thorn;e king,</L>
<L N="5">'Under-stond now mi teling,</L>
<L>Al what ich haue y-&thorn;ou&yogh;t.</L>
<L>&YOGH;if &thorn;at &thorn;ou may ouercom &thorn;e fi&yogh;t,</L>
<L>&amp; defende me wi&thorn; ri&yogh;t</L>
<L>(&THORN;e wrong is on me sou&yogh;t),</L>
<L N="10">So michel y schal for &thorn;e do,</L>
<L>&THORN;at men schal speke &thorn;er-of euer mo</L>
<L>As wide as &thorn;is wald is wrou&yogh;t.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="88" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Alle &thorn;e men &thorn;at in my prisoun be</L>
<L>&THORN;ai schul be deliuerd for loue of &thorn;e</L>
<L>&THORN;at Cristen men be told.</L>
<L>Fram henne to Ynde &thorn;at cite</L>
<L N="5">Quite-claym &thorn;ai schul go fre</L>
<L>Bo&thorn;e &yogh;ong and old.</L>
<L>And so gode pes y schal festen anon,</L>
<L>&THORN;at Cristen men schul comen &amp; gon</L>
<L>To her owhen wille in wold.'</L>
<L N="10">'Gramerci,' &thorn;an seyd sir Gij.</L>
<L>'&THORN;at is a fair &yogh;ift, sikerly.</L>
<L>God leue &thorn;e it wele to hold.'</L>
</LG>
<LG N="89" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; &THORN;e king dede make a ba&thorn;e anon ri&yogh;t,<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="7881"></L>
<L>For to ba&thorn;e Gij &amp; better di&yogh;t:</L>
<L>In silk he wald him schrede.
<PB REF="00000456.tif" N="452"></L>
<L>'Nay, sir,' &thorn;an seyd sir Gij,</L>
<L N="5">'Swiche clo&thorn;es non kepe y,</L>
<L>Also god me rede,</L>
<L>To were clo&thorn;es gold-bi-go</L>
<L>(For y was neuer wont &thorn;erto)</L>
<L>No non so wor&thorn;liche wede.</L>
<L N="10">Mete and drink anou&yogh; &yogh;iue me,</L>
<L>&amp; riche clo&thorn;es lat &thorn;ou be:</L>
<L>Y kepe non swiche prede.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="90" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; <NOTE PLACE="marg">In MS. the first three lines of st. 90 are written as if belonging to st. 89.</NOTE>&amp; when &thorn;e time com to &thorn;ende,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ai schuld to court wende,</L>
<L>&THORN;er sembled a fair ferred.</L>
<L>King Triamour maked him &yogh;are &thorn;o,</L>
<L N="5">And Fabour his sone dede also,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; kni&yogh;tes sti&thorn;e on stede.</L>
<L>To court ward &thorn;an went he,</L>
<L>To Espire, &thorn;at riche cite,<MILESTONE N="153a:a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Wi&thorn; joie &amp; michel prede.</L>
<L N="10">To &thorn;e Soudan &thorn;ai went on heye</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; wel gret cheualrie,</L>
<L>Bateyle<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>of him</I> erased after <I>Bateyle</I>.</NOTE> for to bede.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="91" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Gij was ful wele in armes di&yogh;t<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="7899"></L>
<L>Wi&thorn; helme, &amp; plate, &amp; brini bri&yogh;t,</L>
<L>&THORN;e best &thorn;at euer ware.</L>
<L>&THORN;e hauberk he hadde was renis,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Read <I>eluis</I>?</NOTE></L>
<L N="5">&THORN;at was king Clarels, y-wis,</L>
<L>In Ierusalem when he was &thorn;are.</L>
<L>A &thorn;ef stale it in &thorn;at stede,</L>
<L>&amp; oway &thorn;erwi&thorn; him dede:</L>
<L>To he&thorn;enesse he it bare.</L>
<L N="10">King Triamours elders it bou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>&amp; in her hord house &thorn;ai &thorn;ou&yogh;t<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>&thorn;ai it &thorn;ou&yogh;t</I> MS.</NOTE></L>
<L>To hold it euer mare.
<PB REF="00000458.tif" N="454"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="92" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Sir Gij &thorn;ai toke it in &thorn;at plas.</L>
<L>&THORN;ritti winter afrayd it nas:</L>
<L>Ful clere it was of mayle,</L>
<L>As bri&yogh;t as ani siluer it was:</L>
<L N="5">&THORN;e halle schon &thorn;erof as sonne of glas,</L>
<L>For so&thorn;e wi&thorn;outen fayle.</L>
<L>His helme was of so michel mi&yogh;t,</L>
<L>Was neuer man ouer-comen in fi&yogh;t</L>
<L>&THORN;at hadde it on his ventayle.</L>
<L N="10">It was Alisaunders, &thorn;e gret lording,</L>
<L>When he fau&yogh;t wi&thorn; Poreus &thorn;e king,</L>
<L>&THORN;at hard him gan aseyle.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="93" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; A gode swerd he hadde, wi&thorn;-outen faile,</L>
<L>&THORN;at was Ectors in Troye batayle,</L>
<L>In gest as so men fint.</L>
<L>Ar he &thorn;at swerd dede forgon,</L>
<L N="5">Of Grece he slou&yogh; &thorn;er mani on,</L>
<L>&THORN;at died &thorn;urch &thorn;at dint.</L>
<L>Hose &amp; gambisoun so gode kni&yogh;t schold,</L>
<L>A targe listed wi&thorn; gold</L>
<L>About his swere he hint.</L>
<L N="10">Nas neuer wepen &thorn;at euer was make[d]</L>
<L>&THORN;at o schel mi&yogh;t &thorn;erof take,</L>
<L>Na more &thorn;an of &thorn;e flint.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="94" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Or<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>For</I> MS.</NOTE> king Triamours elders it lau&yogh;t,</L>
<L>King Darri sum time it au&yogh;t:</L>
<L>&THORN;at Gij was vnder pi&yogh;t.</L>
<L>Ich man axe o&thorn;er bigan<MILESTONE N="153a:b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="5">Whennes &amp; who was &thorn;at man</L>
<L>&THORN;at wi&thorn; &thorn;e geaunt durst fi&yogh;t.</L>
<L>King Triamour seyd wi&thorn; wordes fre,<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="7939"></L>
<L>'Sir Soudan, herken now to me,</L>
<L>Astow art hendy kni&yogh;t.
<PB REF="00000460.tif" N="456"></L>
<L N="10">To &thorn;i court icham now come</L>
<L>To defende me of &thorn;at ich gome</L>
<L>&THORN;at is so stern of si&yogh;t.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="95" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; &THORN;is litel kni&yogh;t &thorn;at stont me by</L>
<L>Schal fende me of &thorn;at felonie,</L>
<L>&amp; make me quite &amp; skere.'</L>
<L>'Be stille,' seyd &thorn;e Soudan &thorn;o,</L>
<L N="5">'&THORN;at batail schal wel sone be go,</L>
<L>Also brouke y mi swere.'</L>
<L>He dede clepe Amorant so grim,</L>
<L>&amp; Gij stode &amp; loked on him,</L>
<L>Hou foule he was of chere.</L>
<L N="10">'It is,' seyd Gij, 'no mannes sone:</L>
<L>It is a deuel fram helle is come.</L>
<L>What wonder do&thorn; he here?</L>
</LG>
<LG N="96" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Who mi&yogh;t his dintes dreye,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he no schuld dye an heye?</L>
<L>So strong he is of dede.'</L>
<L>&THORN;an speken &thorn;ai alle of &thorn;e batayle:</L>
<L N="5">Where it schuld be, wi&thorn;-outen fayle,</L>
<L>&THORN;ai token hem to rede.</L>
<L>&THORN;an loked &thorn;ai it schuld be</L>
<L>In a launde vnder &thorn;e cite:</L>
<L>&THORN;ider &thorn;ai gun hem lede.</L>
<L N="10">Wi&thorn; a riuer it ern al about:</L>
<L>&THORN;er-in schuld fi&yogh;t &thorn;o kni&yogh;tes stout.</L>
<L>&THORN;ai mi&yogh;t fle for no nede.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="97" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Ouer &thorn;e water &thorn;ai went in a bot,</L>
<L>On hors &thorn;ai lopen fot hot,</L>
<L>&THORN;o kni&yogh;tes egre of mode.
<PB REF="00000462.tif" N="458"></L>
<L>&THORN;ai priked &thorn;e stedes &thorn;at &thorn;ai on sete,</L>
<L N="5">&amp; smiten togider wi&thorn; dentes grete,</L>
<L>&amp; ferd as &thorn;ai wer wode,</L>
<L>Til her schaftes in &thorn;at tide</L>
<L>Gun to schiuer bi ich a side</L>
<L>About hem &thorn;er &thorn;ai stode.</L>
<L N="10">&THORN;an &thorn;ai drou&yogh; her swerdes grounde,</L>
<L>&amp; hewe togider wi&thorn; grimli wounde,</L>
<L>Til &thorn;ai spradde al ablode.<MILESTONE N="153b:a" UNIT="folio"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="98" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Sir Amoraunt drou&yogh; his gode brond,<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="7975"></L>
<L>&THORN;at wele carf al &thorn;at it fond,</L>
<L>When he hadde lorn his launce:</L>
<L>&THORN;at neuer armour mi&yogh;t wi&thorn;stond</L>
<L N="5">&THORN;at was made of smit&thorn;es hond</L>
<L>In he&thorn;enesse no in Fraunce.</L>
<L>It was sir Ercules &thorn;e strong,</L>
<L>&THORN;at mani he slou&yogh; &thorn;er-wi&thorn; wi&thorn; wrong</L>
<L>In batayle &amp; in destaunce.</L>
<L N="10">&THORN;er was neuer man &thorn;at it bere</L>
<L>Ouer-comen in batayle no in were,</L>
<L>Bot it were &thorn;urch meschaunce.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="99" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; It was ba&thorn;ed in &thorn;e flom of helle:</L>
<L>A goddes<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>A goddes</I>] MS. <I>Agnes</I>.</NOTE> &yogh;af it him to wille,</L>
<L>He schuld &thorn;e better spede.</L>
<L>Who &thorn;at bar &thorn;at swerd of mi&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="5">Was neuer man ouercomen in fi&yogh;t,</L>
<L>Bot it were &thorn;urch vnlede.</L>
<L>&THORN;er wor&thorn; sir Gij to de&thorn; y-brou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>Bot &yogh;if god haue of him &thorn;ou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>His best help at nede.</L>
<L N="10">Togider &thorn;ai wer &yogh;ern heweinde</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; her brondes wele kerueinde,</L>
<L>And maden her sides blede.
<PB REF="00000464.tif" N="460"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="100" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Sir Amoraunt was agreued in hert,</L>
<L>&amp; smot to Gij a dint ful smert</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; alle &thorn;e mi&yogh;t he gan welde,</L>
<L>&amp; hitt him on &thorn;e helme so bri&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="5">&THORN;at alle &thorn;e stones of michel mi&yogh;t</L>
<L>Fley&yogh;e doun in &thorn;e feld.</L>
<L>Al of &thorn;e helme &thorn;e swerd out stint,</L>
<L>&amp; for&thorn; ri&yogh;t wi&thorn; &thorn;at selue dint</L>
<L>O&thorn;er half fot of &thorn;e scheld,</L>
<L N="10">&THORN;at neuer was atamed ar &thorn;an</L>
<L>For kni&yogh;t no for no no&thorn;er man,</L>
<L>No were he neuer so beld.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="101" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; &THORN;e sadel bowe he clef atvo,</L>
<L>&THORN;e stedes nek he dede also,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; his grimli brond.</L>
<L>Wi&thorn;-outen wem<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. <I>when</I>.</NOTE> or ani wounde</L>
<L N="5">Wele half a fot in-to &thorn;e grounde</L>
<L>&THORN;e scharp swerd it wond.</L>
<L>Sir Gij to grounde fallen is,</L>
<L>He stirt vp anon, y-wis,</L>
<L>&amp; loked, &amp; gan wi&thorn;-stond.</L>
<L N="10">Anon ri&yogh;t in &thorn;at ich stede<MILESTONE N="153b:b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>To god almi&yogh;ten he bad his bede,</L>
<L>&amp; held vp bo&thorn;e his hond.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="102" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Sir Gij anon vp stirt</L>
<L>As man &thorn;at was agremed in hert,</L>
<L>Nou&yogh;t wel long he lay.</L>
<L>'Lord,' seyd Gij, 'god al-mi&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="5">&THORN;at made &thorn;e &thorn;erkenes to &thorn;e ni&yogh;t,</L>
<L>So help me to-day.</L>
<L>Scheld me fro &thorn;is geaunt strong,</L>
<L>&THORN;at y no de&thorn; of him afong,</L>
<L>Astow art lord verray.
<PB REF="00000466.tif" N="462"></L>
<L N="10">&THORN;at dint,' he seyd, 'was iuel sett.</L>
<L>Wele schal y com out of &thorn;i dett</L>
<L>&YOGH;if &thorn;at I libbe may.'</L>
</LG>
<LG N="103" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Gij hent his swerd, &thorn;at was ful kene,<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="8007"></L>
<L>&amp; smot Amoraunt wi&thorn; hert tene</L>
<L>A dint &thorn;at sat ful sore,</L>
<L>&THORN;at a quarter of his scheld</L>
<L N="5">He made to fleye in &thorn;e feld</L>
<L>Al wi&thorn; his grimli gore.</L>
<L>&THORN;e stedes nek he smot atvo,</L>
<L>Amoraunt to grounde is fallen &thorn;o:</L>
<L>Wo was him &thorn;erfore.</L>
<L N="10">&THORN;an wer on fot &thorn;o kni&yogh;tes bold:</L>
<L>Fi&yogh;t ofot &yogh;if &thorn;ai wold.</L>
<L>Her stedes &thorn;ai han forlore.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="104" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Amoraunt wi&thorn; hert ful grim</L>
<L>Smot to Gij, &amp; Gij to him,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; strokes stern &amp; stiue.</L>
<L>Hard &thorn;ai hewe wi&thorn; swerdes clere,</L>
<L N="5">&THORN;at helme &amp; swerd, &thorn;at strong were,</L>
<L>&THORN;ai gun hem al to-driue.</L>
<L>Hard fou&yogh;ten &thorn;o champiouns,</L>
<L>&THORN;at bo&thorn;e plates &amp; hauberiouns</L>
<L>&THORN;ai gun to ret &amp; riue,</L>
<L N="10">&amp; laiden on wi&thorn; dintes gret.</L>
<L>Ai&thorn;er of hem so o&thorn;er gan bete,</L>
<L>&THORN;at wo was hem oliue.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="105" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Sir Amoraunt was agreued strong,<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="8025"></L>
<L>&THORN;at o man stode him &thorn;o so long.</L>
<L>To Gij a strok he rau&yogh;t,</L>
<L>&amp; hit him on &thorn;e helme so bri&yogh;t,<MILESTONE N="154a:a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="5">&THORN;at al &thorn;e floures fel doun ri&yogh;t.</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; a ful grimly drau&yogh;t
<PB REF="00000468.tif" N="464"></L>
<L>&THORN;e cercle of gold he carf ato,</L>
<L>&amp; for&thorn; wi&thorn; his dint also</L>
<L>&THORN;er bileued it nou&yogh;t:</L>
<L N="10">On &thorn;e scheld &thorn;e swerd doun fel,</L>
<L>And cleue it in-to haluendel,</L>
<L>Almost to grounde him brou&yogh;t.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="106" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; What wi&thorn; &thorn;e swerdes out draweing,</L>
<L>&amp; wi&thorn; his hetelich out braiding,</L>
<L>&THORN;er fel a wonder cas:</L>
<L>Sir Gij fel on knes to grounde,</L>
<L N="5">&amp; stirt vp in &thorn;at selue stounde,</L>
<L>&amp; seyd, 'lord ful of grace,</L>
<L>Neuer dint of kni&yogh;t non</L>
<L>No mi&yogh;t me are knele don</L>
<L>In no stede &thorn;er y was.'</L>
<L N="10">Sir Gij hent vp his swerd fot hot,</L>
<L>Amoraunt on &thorn;e hod he smot,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he stumbled in &thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>&thorn;e &thorn;e</I> MS.</NOTE> place.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="107" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; He hit him on &thorn;e helme an hey&yogh;e,</L>
<L>&amp; wi&thorn; &thorn;at dint &thorn;e swerd it fley&yogh;e:</L>
<L>Bi &thorn;e nasel it gan doun founde,</L>
<L>&amp; so it dede bi &thorn;e ventayle,</L>
<L N="5">&amp; carf it ato, saunfaile,</L>
<L>&amp; in-to his flesche a wounde.</L>
<L>His targe wi&thorn; gold list</L>
<L>He carf atvo &thorn;urch help of Crist,</L>
<L>He cleue &thorn;at ich stounde.</L>
<L N="10">So heteliche &thorn;e brond out he pli&yogh;t,</L>
<L>&THORN;at Amoraunt anon ri&yogh;t</L>
<L>Fel on knes to grounde.
<PB REF="00000470.tif" N="466"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="108" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; So strong batayle was hem bitvene:<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="8071"></L>
<L>So seyd &thorn;ai &thorn;at mi&yogh;t it sene</L>
<L>&THORN;at seye &thorn;ai neuer non swiche,</L>
<L>&THORN;at neuer was of wiman born</L>
<L N="5">Swiche to kni&yogh;tes as &thorn;ai worn,</L>
<L>&THORN;at fou&yogh;ten togider wi&thorn; wreche.</L>
<L>On a day bifor &thorn;e natiuite</L>
<L>Of seyn Ion, &thorn;e martir fre,</L>
<L>&THORN;at holy man is to seche,</L>
<L N="10">Togider fou&yogh;t &thorn;o barouns bo&thorn;e,</L>
<L>&THORN;at in hert wer so wro&thorn;e.</L>
<L>Of loue was &thorn;er no speche.<MILESTONE N="154a:b" UNIT="folio"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="109" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Sir Amoraunt wi&thorn;-drou&yogh; him</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; loureand chere wro&thorn; &amp; grim,</L>
<L>For &thorn;e blod of him was lete,</L>
<L>&THORN;at drink he most, o&thorn;er his liif forgon:</L>
<L N="5">So strong &thorn;rust &yogh;ede him opon,</L>
<L>So michel was his hete.</L>
<L>'Fourti batayls ichaue ouercome,</L>
<L>Ac fond y neuer er moder sone</L>
<L>&THORN;at me so sore gan bete.</L>
<L N="10">Tel me,' he seyd, 'what artow?</L>
<L>Felt y neuer man ar now</L>
<L>&THORN;at &yogh;af dintes so grete.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="110" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Tel me,' he seyd, 'wennes &thorn;ou be;</L>
<L>For &thorn;ou art strong, so mot y the,</L>
<L>&amp; of michel mi&yogh;t.'
<PB REF="00000472.tif" N="468"></L>
<L>Sir Gij answerd, 'wi&thorn;-outen bost,</L>
<L N="5">Cristen icham, wele &thorn;ou wost,</L>
<L>Of Inglond born, y pli&yogh;t.</L>
<L>King Triamour me hider brou&yogh;t</L>
<L>For to defenden him, &yogh;if y mou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>Of &thorn;at michel vnri&yogh;t</L>
<L N="10">&THORN;at &yogh;e beren on him wi&thorn; wou&yogh;,</L>
<L>&THORN;at Fabour neuer Sadony slou&yogh;</L>
<L>Noi&thorn;er bi day no ni&yogh;t.'</L>
</LG>
<LG N="111" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; 'O, artow Inglis?' seyd Amorant.</L>
<L>'Now wald mi lord Teruagaunt</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ou were Gij &thorn;e strong!</L>
<L>Mahoun &yogh;af &thorn;at &thorn;ou wer he!</L>
<L N="5">Bli&thorn;e wald y &thorn;an be</L>
<L>Batail of him to fong:</L>
<L>For he ha&thorn; destrud al our lawe,</L>
<L>His heued wald ichaue ful fawe,</L>
<L>Or hei&yogh;e on galwes hong;</L>
<L N="10">For keuer schal we neuer<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. <I>neuer er</I></NOTE> more</L>
<L>&THORN;at he ha&thorn; don ous forlore</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; wel michel wrong.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="112" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Wi&thorn; michel wrong &amp; michel wou&yogh;</L>
<L>Fourti &thorn;ousend of ous he slou&yogh;</L>
<L>In Costentin on a day:</L>
<L>He &amp;<NOTE PLACE="marg">&amp; added above the line.</NOTE> Herhaud, his felawe,</L>
<L N="5">Michel han destrud our lawe,</L>
<L>&THORN;at euer-more mon y may.</L>
<L>&YOGH;if he wer slain wi&thorn; brond of stiel</L>
<L>&THORN;an were y wroken on hem<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. him.</NOTE> ful wel<MILESTONE N="154b:a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&THORN;at han destrud our lay.'</L>
<L N="10">Sir Gij answerd, 'whi seistow so?</L>
<L>Ha&thorn; Gij ani &thorn;ing &thorn;e misdo?'</L>
<L>Amoraunt seyd, 'nay,</L>
</LG>
<LG N="113" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Ac it wer gret wor&thorn;schip, y-wis,</L>
<L>To alle &thorn;e folk of he&thorn;enisse,</L>
<L>&THORN;at y hadde so wroken mi kende.
<PB REF="00000474.tif" N="470"></L>
<L>Cristen,' he seyd, 'listen to me.<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="8105"></L>
<L N="5">&THORN;e weder is hot, astow may se;</L>
<L>Y pray &thorn;e, leue frende:</L>
<L>Leue, to drink &thorn;ou lat me gon</L>
<L>For &thorn;e lordes loue &thorn;ou leuest on,</L>
<L>Astow art gode &amp; hende.</L>
<L N="10">For &thorn;rist mi hert wil to-spring,</L>
<L>&amp; for hete, wi&thorn;-outen lesing,</L>
<L>Mi liue wil fro me wende.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="114" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; &amp; &yogh;if y schal be &thorn;us aqueld</L>
<L>&THORN;urch strong hete in &thorn;e feld</L>
<L>It were o&yogh;ain &thorn;e skille:</L>
<L>Unwor&thorn;schipe it war to &thorn;e,</L>
<L N="5">It were &thorn;e gret vilete</L>
<L>In wat lond<NOTE PLACE="marg">Another <I>lond</I> expunged.</NOTE> &thorn;ou com tille.</L>
<L>Ac lete me drink a litel wi&yogh;t</L>
<L>For &thorn;i lordes loue ful of mi&yogh;t</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ou louest wi&thorn; wille,</L>
<L N="10">&amp; y &thorn;e hot bi mi lay,</L>
<L>&YOGH;if &thorn;ou haue ani &thorn;rest to-day,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou shalt drink al &thorn;i fille.'</L>
</LG>
<LG N="115" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Sir Gij answerd, 'y graunt &thorn;e,</L>
<L>&amp; &yogh;ete to-day &thorn;ou &yogh;eld it me</L>
<L>Wi&thorn;-outen ani fayle.'</L>
<L>&amp; when he hadde leue of sir Gij<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="8127"></L>
<L N="5">He was ful glad,<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>ful</I> struck out after <I>glad</I>.</NOTE> sikerli:</L>
<L>No lenger nold he dayle.</L>
<L>To &thorn;e riuer ful swi&thorn;e he ran,</L>
<L>His helme of his heued he nam,</L>
<L>&amp; vnlaced his ventayle.</L>
<L N="10">When he hadde dronken alle his fille</L>
<L>He stirt vp wi&thorn; hert grille,</L>
<L>&amp; sir Gij began to asayle.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="116" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; 'Kni&yogh;t,' he seyd, '&yogh;eld &thorn;e biliue;</L>
<L>For &thorn;ou art giled, so mot y &thorn;riue.</L>
<L>Now ichaue a drink,<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>adrink</I> MS.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000476.tif" N="472"></L>
<L>Icham as fresche as ich was amorwe:<MILESTONE N="155b:b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="5">&THORN;ou schalt dye wi&thorn; michel sorwe,</L>
<L>For-so&thorn;e, wi&thorn;outen lesing.'</L>
<L>&THORN;an &thorn;ai drowen her swerdes long,</L>
<L>&THORN;o kni&yogh;tes &thorn;at wer stern &amp; strong,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn;-outen more dueling,</L>
<L N="10">&amp; ai&thorn;er gan o&thorn;er &thorn;er asayle;</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;er bi-gan a strong bataile</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; wel strong fi&yogh;ting.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="117" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Amoraunt was ful egre of mode,</L>
<L>&amp; smot to Gij as he wer wode</L>
<L>(Ful egre he was to fi&yogh;t),</L>
<L>&THORN;at a quarter of his scheld</L>
<L N="5">He made it fleye into the feld,</L>
<L>And of<NOTE PLACE="marg">Read <I>on?</I></NOTE> his brini bri&yogh;t:</L>
<L>Of his scholder &thorn;e swerd glod doun,</L>
<L>&THORN;at bo&thorn;e plates &amp; hauberioun</L>
<L>He carf atvo, y pli&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="10">Al to &thorn;e naked hide, y-wis,</L>
<L>&amp; nou&yogh;t of flesche atamed is</L>
<L>&THORN;urch grace of god almi&yogh;t.
<PB REF="00000478.tif" N="474"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="118" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; &THORN;e scharp swerd doun gan glide</L>
<L>Fast bi sir Gyes side</L>
<L>(His knew it com ful neye),</L>
<L>&THORN;at gambisoun &amp; iambler</L>
<L N="5">Bo&thorn;e it karf atvo y-fere:</L>
<L>Into &thorn;er&thorn;e &thorn;e swerd it fleye<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. originally <I>fleyee</I></NOTE></L>
<L>Wi&thorn;-outen wem or ani wounde</L>
<L>Half a fot in-to &thorn;e grounde,</L>
<L>&THORN;at mani man it seye.</L>
<L N="10">&amp; when Gij seye &thorn;at fair grace,</L>
<L>&THORN;at no&thorn;ing wounded he was,</L>
<L>Iesu he &thorn;anked on heye.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="119" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; &amp; when Gij feld him so smite</L>
<L>He was wro&thorn;, &yogh;e mow wite:</L>
<L>To Amoraunt he gan reken.</L>
<L>He hent his brond wi&thorn; wel gode wille,</L>
<L N="5">&amp; stroke to him wi&thorn; hert grille:</L>
<L>His scheld he gan to-breken.</L>
<L>So hetelich Gij him smot,</L>
<L>&THORN;at into &thorn;e scholder half a fot</L>
<L>&THORN;e gode swerd gan reken;</L>
<L N="10">&amp; wi&thorn; &thorn;at strok Gij wi&thorn;-drou&yogh;:</L>
<L>Weri he was forfou&yogh;ten y-nou&yogh;;</L>
<L>To Amoraunt he gan speken.<MILESTONE N="155a:a" UNIT="folio"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="120" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; 'Sir Amoraunt,' &thorn;an seyd Gij,<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="8173"></L>
<L>'For godes loue now merci,</L>
<L>&YOGH;if that &thorn;i wille be.</L>
<L>Ichaue swiche &thorn;rist &thorn;er y stond,</L>
<L N="5">Y may vnne&thorn;e drawe min hond;</L>
<L>&THORN;erfore wel wo is me.</L>
<L>&YOGH;eld me now &thorn;at ich dede:</L>
<L>Y &yogh;af &thorn;e leue to drink at nede.</L>
<L>Astow art hende &amp; fre,</L>
<L N="10">Leue, to drink &thorn;ou lat me go,</L>
<L>As it was couenaunt bitven ous tvo:</L>
<L>For loue y pray &thorn;e.'
<PB REF="00000480.tif" N="476"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="121" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; 'Hold &thorn;i pes,' seyd Amoraunt,</L>
<L>'For, bi mi lord sir Teruagaunt,</L>
<L>Leue no hastow non.</L>
<L>Ac now &thorn;at y &thorn;e so&thorn;e se,</L>
<L N="5">&THORN;at &thorn;ou ginnes to feynt &thorn;e,</L>
<L>&THORN;ine heued &thorn;ou schalt forgon.'</L>
<L>'Amoraunt,' seyd Gij,<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>gij</I> added in the margin.</NOTE> 'do ari&yogh;t:</L>
<L>Lete me drink a litel wi&yogh;t</L>
<L>As y dede &thorn;e anon,</L>
<L N="10">&amp; togider fi&yogh;t we:</L>
<L>Who schal be maister we schal se,</L>
<L>Wiche of ous may o&thorn;er slon.'</L>
</LG>
<LG N="122" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; 'Hold &thorn;i pays,' seyd Amoraunt,</L>
<L>'Y nil nou&yogh;t held &thorn;e couenaunt</L>
<L>For ful &thorn;is toun of gold;</L>
<L>For when ichaue &thorn;e sleyn now ri&yogh;t</L>
<L N="5">&THORN;e Soudan, treweli, ha&thorn; me hi&yogh;t</L>
<L>His lond &yogh;if me he schold</L>
<L>Euermore to haue &amp; hold fre,</L>
<L>&amp; &yogh;iue me his dou&yogh;ter bri&yogh;t o ble,</L>
<L>&THORN;e miriest may on mold:</L>
<L N="10">When ichaue &thorn;e sleyn &thorn;is day</L>
<L>He schal &yogh;iue me &thorn;at fair may</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; alle his lond to hold.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="123" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Ac do now wele &amp; vnarme &thorn;e,</L>
<L>&amp; trewelich &yogh;eld &thorn;ou &thorn;e to me:</L>
<L>Oliue y lat &thorn;e gon.</L>
<L>&amp; &yogh;if &thorn;ou wilt nou&yogh;t do bi mi red</L>
<L N="5">&THORN;ou schalt dye on iuel ded:</L>
<L>Ri&yogh;t now y schal &thorn;e slon.'</L>
<L>'Nay,' seyd Gij, '&thorn;at war no lawe:</L>
<L>Ich hadde leuer to ben to-drawe<MILESTONE N="155a:b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&THORN;an swiche a dede to don.
<PB REF="00000482.tif" N="478"></L>
<L N="10">Ar ich wald creaunt &yogh;eld me</L>
<L>Ich hadde leuer an-hanged be,</L>
<L>&amp; brent bo&thorn;e flesche &amp; bon.'</L>
</LG>
<LG N="124" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; &THORN;an seyd Amoraunt, 'at a word,<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="8215"></L>
<L>Bi &thorn;e treu&thorn;e &thorn;ou owe &thorn;i lord,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ou louest so dere,</L>
<L>Tel me what &thorn;i name it be,</L>
<L N="5">&amp; leue to drink &yogh;iue y &thorn;e</L>
<L>&THORN;i fille of &thorn;is riuer.</L>
<L>&THORN;ou seyd &thorn;i name is sir Youn:</L>
<L>It is nou&yogh;t so, bi seyn Mahoun,</L>
<L>It is a lesing, fere.</L>
<L N="10">&YOGH;if &thorn;i name were Youn ri&yogh;t</L>
<L>&THORN;ou nere nou&yogh;t of so miche mi&yogh;t,</L>
<L>No &thorn;us vnbiknowen here.'</L>
</LG>
<LG N="125" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; 'Frende,' seyd Gij, 'y schal telle &thorn;e:</L>
<L>Astow art hendi man &amp; fre,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou wray me to no wi&yogh;t.</L>
<L>Gij of Warwike mi name it is:</L>
<L N="5">In Inglond y was born, y-wis.</L>
<L>Lete me now drink wi&thorn; ri&yogh;t.'</L>
<L>When Amoraunt seye, sikerly,</L>
<L>&THORN;at it was &thorn;e gode Gij</L>
<L>&THORN;at o&yogh;aines him was di&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="10">He loked on him wi&thorn; michel wrake</L>
<L>Sternliche wi&thorn; his ey&yogh;en blake,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; an vnsemli si&yogh;t.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="126" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; 'Sir Gij,' he seyd, 'welcom to me!</L>
<L>Mahoun, mi lord, y thank &thorn;e</L>
<L>&THORN;at ich haue &thorn;e her-inne.</L>
<L>Michel schame &thorn;ou hast me don:</L>
<L N="5">&THORN;i liif &thorn;ou schalt astite forgon,</L>
<L>&THORN;i bodi schal atvinne,
<PB REF="00000484.tif" N="480"></L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;ine heued, bi Teruagaunt,</L>
<L>Mi leman schal haue to presaunt,</L>
<L>&THORN;at comly is of kinne.</L>
<L N="10">Hennes-forward, siker &thorn;ou be,</L>
<L>Leue no tit &thorn;e non of me,</L>
<L>For al &thorn;is warld to winne.'</L>
</LG>
<LG N="127" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; 'Allas,' seyd Gij, 'what schal y don?<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="8247"></L>
<L>Now y no may haue drink non</L>
<L>Mine hert breke&thorn; ato.'</L>
<L>Anon he bi&thorn;ou&yogh;t him &thorn;enne<MILESTONE N="155b:a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="5">Ri&yogh;t to &thorn;e riuer he most renne:</L>
<L>He turned him, &amp; gan to go.</L>
<L>Amoraunt wi&thorn; swerd on hond</L>
<L>He thou&yogh;t haue driuen Gij to schond:</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; sorwe he wald him slo.</L>
<L N="10">Gij ran to &thorn;e water ri&yogh;t:</L>
<L>Bot on him &thorn;enke god almi&yogh;t</L>
<L>Vp come&thorn; he neuer mo.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="128" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; &THORN;o was sir Gij in gret drede.</L>
<L>In &thorn;e water he stode to his girdel stede,</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;at &thorn;ou&yogh;t him ful gode.</L>
<L>In &thorn;e water he dept his heued anon,</L>
<L N="5">Ouer &thorn;e schulders he dede it gon;</L>
<L>&THORN;at keled wele his blod.</L>
<L>&amp; when Gij hadde dronken anou&yogh;</L>
<L>Hetelich his heued vp he drou&yogh;</L>
<L>Out of &thorn;at ich flod;</L>
<L N="10">&amp; Amoraunt stode opon &thorn;e lond</L>
<L>With a drawen swerd in hond,</L>
<L>&amp; smot Gij &thorn;er he stode.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="129" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Hetelich he smot Gyoun:</L>
<L>Into &thorn;at water he fel adoun</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; &thorn;at dint vnride,
<PB REF="00000486.tif" N="482"></L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;e water arn him about.</L>
<L N="5">Sir Gij stirt vp in gret dout:</L>
<L>For no&thorn;ing he nold abide,</L>
<L>&amp; schoke his heued as kni&yogh;t bold.</L>
<L>'In &thorn;is water icham ful cold</L>
<L>Wombe, rigge, &amp; side,</L>
<L N="10">&amp; no leue, sir, ich hadde of &thorn;e,</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;er-fore haue &thorn;o[u] miche maugre,</L>
<L>&amp; iuel &thorn;e mot bi-tide.'</L>
</LG>
<LG N="130" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Sir Gij stirt vp, wi&thorn;outen fayl,<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="8269"></L>
<L>&amp; Amoraunt he gan to asayl:</L>
<L>To fi&yogh;t he was ful boun.</L>
<L>Hard togider &thorn;ai gan to fi&yogh;t:</L>
<L N="5">Of loue was &thorn;er no speche, y pli&yogh;t,</L>
<L>Bot heweing wi&thorn; swerdes broun.</L>
<L>'Amoraunt,' &thorn;an seyd Gij,</L>
<L>'&THORN;ou art ful fals, sikerly,</L>
<L>&amp; ful-filt of tresoun.</L>
<L N="10">No more wil y trust to &thorn;e</L>
<L>For no bihest &thorn;ou hotest me:</L>
<L>&THORN;ou art a fals glotoun.'<MILESTONE N="155b:b" UNIT="folio"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="131" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Hard togider &thorn;ai gun fi&yogh;t:</L>
<L>Fro &thorn;e morwe to &thorn;e ni&yogh;t</L>
<L>&THORN;at long somers day,</L>
<L>So long &thorn;ai fou&yogh;ten bo&thorn;e &thorn;o.</L>
<L N="5">Wiche was &thorn;e better of hem to</L>
<L>Noman chese no may.</L>
<L>Bot at a strok as Amoraunt cast,</L>
<L>Sir Gij mett wi&thorn; him in hast,</L>
<L>&amp; tau&yogh;t him a sori play:</L>
<L N="10">&THORN;e ri&yogh;t arme wi&thorn; &thorn;e swerd for hot</L>
<L>Bi &thorn;e scholder of he it smot,</L>
<L>To grounde it fleye oway.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="132" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; When Amoraunt feld him to smite</L>
<L>In his left hond wi&thorn; michel hete</L>
<L>&THORN;e swerd he hent fot hot:
<PB REF="00000488.tif" N="484"></L>
<L>As a lyoun &thorn;an ferd he,</L>
<L N="5">&THORN;ritti sautes he made &amp; &thorn;re</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; his swerd, &thorn;at wel bot;</L>
<L>Bot for &thorn;e blod &thorn;at of him ran</L>
<L>Amoraunt streng&thorn;e slake bigan.</L>
<L>When Gij &thorn;at so&thorn; wot,</L>
<L N="10">&THORN;at Amoraunt was<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. <I>was gin.</I></NOTE> faynting,</L>
<L>Sir Gij him folwed wi&thorn;outen dueling:</L>
<L>&THORN;at o&thorn;er hond of he smot.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="133" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; When Amoraunt had bo&thorn;e hondes forlore</L>
<L>A wreche he held him-self &thorn;erfore:</L>
<L>His wit was alto-dreued.</L>
<L>On sir Gij he lepe wi&thorn; alle his mi&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="5">&THORN;at almast he had feld him doun ri&yogh;t,</L>
<L>&amp; sir Gij was agreued,</L>
<L>&amp; stirt bisiden fot hot,</L>
<L>&amp; Amoraunt in &thorn;e nek he smot:</L>
<L>His mi&yogh;t he ha&thorn; him bireued.</L>
<L N="10">He fel to grounde, wi&thorn;outen faile,</L>
<L>&amp; sir Gij vnlaced his ventayle,</L>
<L>&amp; he strok of his heued.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="134" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Ouer &thorn;e water he went in a bot,<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="8313"></L>
<L>&amp; present &thorn;er-wi&thorn; fot hot</L>
<L>&THORN;e king, sir Triamour.</L>
<L>&THORN;e king, sir Triamour, &thorn;an</L>
<L N="5">Went to &thorn;at riche Soudan,</L>
<L>&amp; also his sone Fabour.</L>
<L>&THORN;an was<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>was</I> added under the line.</NOTE> &thorn;e Soudan swi&thorn;e wo:</L>
<L>Quite-claim he lete hem go<MILESTONE N="156a:a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Wi&thorn; wel michel honour.
<PB REF="00000490.tif" N="486"></L>
<L N="10">Into Alisaunder &thorn;ai went, &thorn;at cite,</L>
<L>&amp; ladde wi&thorn; hem sir Gij &thorn;e fre,</L>
<L>&THORN;at hadde ben her socour.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="135" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; &THORN;e king tok &thorn;erl Ionas &thorn;o,</L>
<L>&amp; clept him in his armes to,</L>
<L>&amp; kist him swete, ich wene,</L>
<L>An hundred times &amp; &yogh;ete mo,</L>
<L N="5">&amp; quite-claim he lete him go</L>
<L>&amp; his sones fiftene.</L>
<L>'Erl Ionas,' seyd &thorn;e king,</L>
<L>'Herken now to my teling,</L>
<L>&amp; what ichil mene:</L>
<L N="10">For mi liif &thorn;ou sauedest me,</L>
<L>Half mi lond ich graunt &thorn;e</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; &thorn;is kni&yogh;t strong &amp; kene.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="136" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Vnderstond to me, sir kni&yogh;t:</L>
<L>Mahoun &yogh;aue ful of mi&yogh;t</L>
<L>&THORN;ou wost duelle wi&thorn; me!</L>
<L>&THORN;ridde part mi lond y &yogh;iue &thorn;e to:</L>
<L N="5">Michel honour ichil &thorn;e do,</L>
<L>A riche prince make &thorn;e.</L>
<L>Y nil nou&yogh;t &thorn;ou<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>&thorn;ou</I> added over the line.</NOTE> forsake god &thorn;ine:</L>
<L>&THORN;ou art bileueand wele afine</L>
<L>Better may no be.'</L>
<L N="10">Sir Gij answerd him ful stille,</L>
<L>'Sir, of &thorn;i lond nou&yogh;t y nille,</L>
<L>For-so&thorn;e y telle &thorn;e.'</L>
</LG>
<LG N="137" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; &THORN;at erl to Ierusalem went anon,<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="8335"></L>
<L>Gij of Warwike wi&thorn; him gan gon</L>
<L>&amp; alle his sones on rawe.</L>
<L>&THORN;erl wold &yogh;if he mi&yogh;t</L>
<L N="5">Wite &thorn;e name of &thorn;at kni&yogh;t,</L>
<L>&YOGH;if he him euer-more sawe.</L>
<L>In conseyl, 'sir kni&yogh;t,' &thorn;an seyd he,</L>
<L>'&THORN;at &thorn;ou Youn dost clep &thorn;e,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou no hatest nou&yogh;t so, y trowe.
<PB REF="00000492.tif" N="488"></L>
<L N="10">For Iesu loue y pray &thorn;e,</L>
<L>&THORN;at died on &thorn;e rode tre,</L>
<L>&THORN;i ri&yogh;t name be aknawe.'</L>
</LG>
<LG N="138" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Sir Gij seyd, '&thorn;ou schalt now here,</L>
<L>Se&thorn;&thorn;en &thorn;ou frainest me in &thorn;is maner:</L>
<L>Mi name ichil &thorn;e sayn.</L>
<L>Gij of Warwike mi name is ri&yogh;t.<MILESTONE N="156a:b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="5">Astow art hende &amp; gentil kni&yogh;t,</L>
<L>To non &thorn;ou schalt me wrayn.</L>
<L>Batayl for &thorn;i loue y nam,</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;e geaunt ouer-cam;</L>
<L>&THORN;erof icham ful fain.'</L>
<L N="10">When &thorn;erl seye it was sir Gij</L>
<L>He fel doun on knes him bi,</L>
<L>&amp; wepe wi&thorn; bo&thorn; his ayn.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="139" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; 'For godes loue,' he seyd, 'merci!</L>
<L>Whi artow so pouer, sir Gij,</L>
<L>&amp; art of so gret valour?</L>
<L>Here ich &yogh;iue &thorn;e in &thorn;is place</L>
<L N="5">Al &thorn;erldam of Durras,</L>
<L>Cite &amp; castel tour:</L>
<L>&THORN;i man ichil bicomen &amp; be,</L>
<L>&amp; alle mi sones for&thorn; wi&thorn; me</L>
<L>Schal com to &thorn;i socour;</L>
<L N="10">For &thorn;e priis of he&thorn;en lond</L>
<L>&THORN;ou hast &thorn;urch douhtines of hond</L>
<L>Wonne wi&thorn; gret vigour.'
<PB REF="00000494.tif" N="490"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="140" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; 'Erl Ionas,' &thorn;an seyd sir Gij,</L>
<L>'Mi leue frende, gramerci</L>
<L>For &thorn;i gode wille!</L>
<L>&THORN;an schustow hire me al to dere</L>
<L N="5">To &yogh;iue me &thorn;i lond in swiche manere;</L>
<L>&THORN;er-of nou&yogh;t y nille.</L>
<L>To &yogh;our owen cuntre wende&thorn; hom:</L>
<L>God biteche y &yogh;ou euerichon.</L>
<L>Mi way ichil ful-fille.'</L>
<L N="10">&THORN;an went &amp; kist him eueri man:</L>
<L>&THORN;erl so sore wepe bigan,</L>
<L>&THORN;at mi&yogh;t him no man stille.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="141" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; &THORN;erl to Durras went anon</L>
<L>&amp; his sones euerichon,</L>
<L>Were scaped out of care.</L>
<L>Gij &thorn;an in his way is nome:</L>
<L N="5">For &thorn;at &thorn;e geaunt was ouer-come,</L>
<L>Ful bli&thorn;e &thorn;an was he &thorn;are.</L>
<L>Into Grece &thorn;an went he,</L>
<L>&amp; sou&yogh;t halwen of &thorn;at cuntre,</L>
<L>&THORN;e best &thorn;at &thorn;er ware.</L>
<L N="10">Se&thorn;&thorn;e for&thorn; in his way he &yogh;ede</L>
<L>&THORN;urch-out mani vncou&thorn;e &thorn;ede:</L>
<L>To Costentyn he is y-fare.<MILESTONE N="156b:a" UNIT="folio"><NOTE PLACE="inter">[Cf. Reinbroun 1-31]</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000506.tif" N="502"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="142" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; When Gij in Costentin hadde be<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="8747"></L>
<L>Out of &thorn;at lond &thorn;an went he,</L>
<L>Walkand in &thorn;e strete</L>
<L>On pilgrimage in his iurnay,</L>
<L N="5">His bedes bidand ni&yogh;t &amp; day,</L>
<L>His sinnes for to bete.</L>
<L>In Almaine &thorn;an went he, y-wis,</L>
<L>&THORN;er he was sumtime holden of gret pris.</L>
<L>He com to a four way lete</L>
<L N="10">Bi&yogh;onde Espire, &thorn;at riche cite:</L>
<L>Under a croice, was maked of tre,</L>
<L>A pilgrim he gan mete,</L>
</LG>
<LG N="143" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; &THORN;at wrong his honden, &amp; wepe sore,</L>
<L>&amp; curssed &thorn;e time &thorn;at he was bore:</L>
<L>'Allas,' it was his song.</L>
<L>'Wayleway,' he seyd, 'that stounde!</L>
<L N="5">Wickedliche icham brou&yogh;t to grounde</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; wel michel wrong.'</L>
<L>Sir Gij went to him &thorn;o:</L>
<L>'Man,' he seys, 'whi farstow so?</L>
<L>So god &yogh;eue &thorn;e ioie to fong,</L>
<L N="10">Tel me what &thorn;i name it be,</L>
<L>&amp; whi &thorn;ou makest &thorn;us gret pite:</L>
<L>Me&thorn;enke &thorn;i paynes strong.'</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="section">
<LG N="144" TYPE="stanza">
<L>'Godeman,' seyd &thorn;e pilgrim &thorn;o,</L>
<L>'What hastow to frein me so?</L>
<L>Swiche sorwe icham in sou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>&THORN;at, &thorn;ei y told &thorn;e alle mi care,</L>
<L N="5">For &thorn;e mi&yogh;t y neuer &thorn;e better fare:</L>
<L>To grounde icham so brou&yogh;t.'</L>
<L>'&YOGH;is,' seyd Gij, 'bi &thorn;e gode rode,</L>
<L>Conseyl y can &yogh;iue &thorn;e gode,</L>
<L>&amp; tow telle me &thorn;i &thorn;ou&yogh;t;
<PB REF="00000508.tif" N="504"></L>
<L N="10">For oft it falle&thorn; vncou&thorn;e man</L>
<L>&THORN;at gode conseyle &yogh;iue can.</L>
<L>&THORN;erfore hele it nou&yogh;t.'</L>
</LG>
<LG N="145" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; 'For god,' he seyd, '&thorn;ou seyst ful wel.</L>
<L>Sumtime ich was, by seyn Mi&yogh;hel,<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="8783"></L>
<L>An erl of gret pouste.</L>
<L>&THORN;urch al cristendom, y-wis,</L>
<L N="5">Ich was teld a man of gret pris</L>
<L>&amp; of gret bounte,</L>
<L>&amp; now icham a wroche beggare:</L>
<L>No wonder &thorn;ei icham ful of care.<MILESTONE N="156b:b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Allas, wel wo is me!'</L>
<L N="10">For sorwe he mi&yogh;t speke na more:</L>
<L>He gan to wepe swi&thorn;e sare,</L>
<L>&THORN;at Gij hadde of him pite.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="146" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; &THORN;an seyd &thorn;e pilgrim, '&thorn;ou hast gret wrong<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>wrong</I> added above the line.</NOTE></L>
<L>To frain me of mi sorwe strong,</L>
<L>&amp; mi&yogh;t no&yogh;t bete mi nede.</L>
<L>To begge mi brede y mot gon:</L>
<L N="5">Se&thorn;&thorn;en &yogh;istay at none ete y non,</L>
<L>Also god me rede.'
<PB REF="00000510.tif" N="506"></L>
<L>'&YOGH;is, felawe,' qua&thorn; Gij, 'hele it nau&yogh;t.</L>
<L>Telle me whi &thorn;ou art in sorwe brau&yogh;t:</L>
<L>&THORN;e better &thorn;ou schalt spede;</L>
<L N="10">&amp; se&thorn;&thorn;en we schul go seche our mete.</L>
<L>Ichaue a pani of old bi&yogh;ete:</L>
<L>&THORN;ou schalt haue half to mede.'</L>
</LG>
<LG N="147" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; 'Gramerci, sir,' &thorn;an seyd he;</L>
<L>'&amp; alle &thorn;e so&thorn; y schal telle &thorn;e.</L>
<L>Erl Tirri is mi name,<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="8819"></L>
<L>Of Gormoys &thorn;erls sone Aubri.</L>
<L N="5">Ich hadde a felawe &thorn;at hi&yogh;t Gij,</L>
<L>A baroun of gode fame.</L>
<L>For &thorn;e douk of Paui sir Otoun</L>
<L>Hadde don him oft gret tresoun,</L>
<L>He slou&yogh; him wi&thorn; gret grame.</L>
<L N="10">Now is his neue &thorn;emperour steward,</L>
<L>His soster sone, &thorn;at hat Berard:</L>
<L>He has me don alle &thorn;is schame.
<PB REF="00000512.tif" N="508"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="148" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; &THORN;emperour he ha&thorn; serued long.</L>
<L>For he is wonderliche strong</L>
<L>&amp; of michel mi&yogh;t,</L>
<L>He no come&thorn; in non batayle</L>
<L N="5">&THORN;at he no ha&thorn; &thorn;e maistri, saunfayl:</L>
<L>So egre he is to fi&yogh;t.</L>
<L>In &thorn;is warld is man non</L>
<L>&THORN;at o&yogh;aines him durst gon,</L>
<L>Herl, baroun, no kni&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="10">&amp; he loked on him wi&thorn; wrake,</L>
<L>&THORN;at his hert no mi&yogh;t quake:</L>
<L>So stern he is of si&yogh;t.
<PB REF="00000514.tif" N="510"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="149" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; &amp; for his scherewdhed sir Berard</L>
<L>&THORN;emperour ha&thorn; made him his steward,</L>
<L>To wardi his lond about.</L>
<L>&THORN;er nis no douk in al &thorn;is lond<MILESTONE N="157a:a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="5">&THORN;at his hest dar wi&thorn;-stonde:</L>
<L>So michel he is<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>is</I> altered from <I>it.</I></NOTE> dout.</L>
<L>&YOGH;if a man be loued wi&thorn; him,</L>
<L>Be he neuer so pouer of<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>for</I> struck out before <I>of.</I></NOTE> kin,</L>
<L>&amp; he wil to him lout,</L>
<L N="10">He make&thorn; hem riche anon ri&yogh;t,</L>
<L>Douk, erl, baroun, or kni&yogh;t,</L>
<L>To held wi&thorn; him gret rout.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="150" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; &amp; &yogh;if a man wi&thorn; him hated be,</L>
<L>Be he neuer so riche of fe,</L>
<L>He fleme&thorn; him<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>his lond</I> ex|punged after <I>him.</I></NOTE> out of lond:</L>
<L>Anon he schal ben to-drawe,</L>
<L N="5">Als tite he schal ben y-slawe,</L>
<L>&amp; driuen him al to schond.</L>
<L>So it bifel, our emperour<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="8901"></L>
<L>Held a parlement of gret honour:</L>
<L>For his erls he<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>he</I> altered from <I>hen.</I></NOTE> sent his sond.</L>
<L N="10">Y<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>Y</I> altered from <I>&thorn;ai.</I></NOTE> come &thorn;ider wi&thorn; michel prede</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; an hundred kni&yogh;tes bi mi side,</L>
<L>At nede wi&thorn; me to stonde.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="151" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; &amp; when y come vnto &thorn;e court</L>
<L>&THORN;e steward, &thorn;e wicked pourt,</L>
<L>To me he gan to reke:</L>
<L>He bicleped me of his emes ded,</L>
<L N="5">&amp; seyd he was sleyn &thorn;urch mi red:</L>
<L>On me he wald be wreke.</L>
<L>&amp;, when ich herd &thorn;at chesoun</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e doukes de&thorn; Otoun,<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>of toun</I> MS.</NOTE></L>
<L>Mine hert wald to-breke.</L>
<L N="10">To &thorn;emperour y layd mi wedde an hei&yogh;e
<PB REF="00000516.tif" N="512"></L>
<L>To defende me of &thorn;at felonie</L>
<L>&THORN;at he to me gan speke.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="152" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; No wonder &thorn;ei y war fordredde.</L>
<L>&THORN;emperour tok bo&thorn;e our wedde,</L>
<L>As y &thorn;e telle may.</L>
<L>For in alle &thorn;e court was &thorn;er no wi&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="5">Douk, erl, baroun, no kni&yogh;t,</L>
<L>&THORN;at durst me borwe &thorn;at day,</L>
<L>&THORN;emperour comand anon</L>
<L>Into his prisoun y schuld be don</L>
<L>Wi&thorn;-outen more delay.</L>
<L N="10">Berard<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>Bernard</I> originally.</NOTE> went, &amp; sesed mi lond;</L>
<L>Mine wiif he wald haue driuen to schond:</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; sorwe sche fled oway.<MILESTONE N="157a:b" UNIT="folio"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="153" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; &THORN;an was ich wi&thorn; sorwe &amp; care</L>
<L>Among min fomen nomen &thorn;are,</L>
<L>&amp; don in strong prisoun.</L>
<L>Min frendes token hem to rede,</L>
<L N="5">To &thorn;emperour &thorn;ai bisou&yogh;t &amp; bede</L>
<L>To pay for me ransoun.</L>
<L>&THORN;emperour &amp; sir Berard</L>
<L>Deliuerd me bi a forward</L>
<L>&amp; bi &thorn;is enchesoun,</L>
<L N="10">Y schuld seche mi felawe Gij,</L>
<L>To defende ous of &thorn;at felonie</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e doukes de&thorn; Otoun.<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>of toun</I> MS.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000518.tif" N="514"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="154" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Out of &thorn;is lond went y me,</L>
<L>&amp; passed ouer &thorn;e salt se:</L>
<L>In Inglond y gan riue.</L>
<L>At Warwike ichim sou&yogh;t:</L>
<L N="5">When y com &thorn;ider y fond him nou&yogh;t</L>
<L>(Wo was me oliue),</L>
<L>No sir Herhaud fond y nou&yogh;t tare:</L>
<L>To seche Gyes sone he is fare,</L>
<L>&THORN;at was stollen wi&thorn; striue.</L>
<L N="10">&THORN;erfore y wot &thorn;at Gij is ded:</L>
<L>For sorwe can y me no red;</L>
<L>Mine hert wil breke o fiue.'</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="section">
<LG N="155" TYPE="stanza">
<L>Sir Gij biheld Tirri ful ri&yogh;t,<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="8989"></L>
<L>&THORN;at whilom was so noble a kni&yogh;t,</L>
<L>&amp; lord of michel mounde.</L>
<L>His bodi, was sumtim wele y-schredde,</L>
<L N="5">Almost naked it was bihedde,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; sorwe &amp; care ful bounde.
<PB REF="00000520.tif" N="516"></L>
<L>His legges, &thorn;at wer sumtime hosed wel,</L>
<L>To-brosten he sei&yogh;e hem eueridel.</L>
<L>'Allas,' seyd Gij, '&thorn;at stonde.'</L>
<L N="10">For sorwe &thorn;at he hadde &thorn;o</L>
<L>Word mi&yogh;t he speke no mo,</L>
<L>Bot fel aswon to grounde.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="156" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Sir Tirri anon com to him &thorn;an,</L>
<L>&amp; in his armes vp him nam,</L>
<L>&amp; cleped opon him &thorn;are.</L>
<L>'Man,' he said, 'what aile&thorn; &thorn;e?</L>
<L N="5">&THORN;ou art iuel at aise, so &thorn;enke&thorn; me.</L>
<L>Hard it is &thorn;i fare.'</L>
<L>Sir Gij answerd &thorn;er-after long,</L>
<L>'&THORN;is iuel greue&thorn; me so strong,<MILESTONE N="157b:a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>In er&thorn;e y wold y ware;</L>
<L N="10">For, se&thorn;&thorn;en &thorn;at y was first man,</L>
<L>Nas neuer sorwe on me cam</L>
<L>&THORN;at greued me so sare.'</L>
</LG>
<LG N="157" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; &THORN;an seyd Tirri, 'felawe, y-wis,</L>
<L>To-day a &yogh;er gon it is</L>
<L>Out of &thorn;is lond y went</L>
<L>To seche Gij, mi gode frende,</L>
<L N="5">Y no finde nou&yogh;t fer no hende:<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>hende</I> altered from <I>hente</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;erfore icham al schent;</L>
<L>For now it is teld me our emperer</L>
<L>Ha&thorn; taken a parlement of &thorn;is maner</L>
<L>For mi loue, verrament,</L>
<L N="10">&THORN;at douk no erl in his lond be,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he no schal be at &thorn;at semble,</L>
<L>For to here mi iugement.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="158" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; &amp; now no lenge abide y no may,</L>
<L>&THORN;at ne me bi-houe&thorn; hom &thorn;is day,</L>
<L>O&thorn;er for to lese min hed.<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>heued</I> MS.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;emperour ichaue mi treu&thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="marg">The <I>u</I> of <I>treuthe</I> added above the line.</NOTE> y-pli&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="5">Y schal bring sir Gij to-ni&yogh;t</L>
<L>To fi&yogh;t o&yogh;ain &thorn;at qued,
<PB REF="00000522.tif" N="518"></L>
<L>To fende ous of &thorn;at felonie</L>
<L>O&yogh;ain &thorn;e douke Berard of Paui</L>
<L>Al of his emes ded.<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>ded</I> altered from <I>dede.</I></NOTE></L>
<L N="10">Y wot wele, &yogh;if y &thorn;ider fare,</L>
<L>&THORN;ai schal me sle wi&thorn; sorwe &amp; care:</L>
<L>Certes, y can no red.'</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="section">
<LG N="159" TYPE="stanza">
<L>Gij biheld Tirri wi&thorn; wepeand ei&yogh;e,<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="9033"></L>
<L>&amp; sei&yogh;e him al &thorn;at sorwe drei&yogh;e,</L>
<L>&THORN;at was him lef &amp; dere:</L>
<L>'Allas,' &thorn;ou&yogh;t Gij, '&thorn;at ich stounde</L>
<L N="5">&THORN;at Tirri is &thorn;us brou&yogh;t to grounde!</L>
<L>So gode felawes we were.'</L>
<L>He &thorn;ou&yogh;t, 'mi&yogh;t y mete &thorn;at douke,</L>
<L>His heued y schuld smite fro &thorn;e bouke,</L>
<L>Or hong him bi &thorn;e swere.</L>
<L N="10">Y no lete for al &thorn;is warldes won</L>
<L>&THORN;at y no schuld &thorn;e traitour slon,</L>
<L>To wreke Tirri, mi fere.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="160" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Tirri,' seyd Gij, 'lat be &thorn;i &thorn;ou&yogh;t:</L>
<L>Y-wis, it helpe&thorn; &thorn;e ri&yogh;t nou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>For sorwe it wil &thorn;e schende.</L>
<L>To court go we bo&thorn;e y-fere:<MILESTONE N="157b:b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="5">Gode tidinges we schul &thorn;er here;</L>
<L>Swiche grace god may sende.</L>
<L>Haue gode hert, dred &thorn;e no del;</L>
<L>For god schal help &thorn;e ful wel:</L>
<L>So curteys he is &amp; hende.'</L>
<L N="10">Up risen &thorn;o kni&yogh;tes tvo</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; michel care &amp; ful of wo:</L>
<L>To court ward &thorn;ai gan wende.
<PB REF="00000524.tif" N="520"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="161" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; &amp; as &thorn;ai went &thorn;o kni&yogh;tes fre</L>
<L>To court ward in her iurne</L>
<L>Ful bold &thorn;ai were &amp; &yogh;epe.</L>
<L>'Allas,' sir Tirri seyd &thorn;o,</L>
<L N="5">'Ich mot rest er ich hennes go,</L>
<L>Or mi liif wil fro me lepe.'</L>
<L>'For god, felawe,' &thorn;an seyd Gij,</L>
<L>'Ly doun, &amp; y schal sitt &thorn;e bi,</L>
<L>&amp; feir &thorn;ine heued vp kepe.'</L>
<L N="10">&amp; when he hadde &thorn;us y-seyd</L>
<L>On Gyes barm his heued he leyd:</L>
<L>Anon Tirri gan slepe.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="162" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; &amp; when sir Tirri was fallen on slepe</L>
<L>Sir Gij biheld him, &amp; gan to wepe,</L>
<L>&amp; gret morning gan make.</L>
<L>&THORN;an sei&yogh;e he an ermine com of his mou&thorn;e</L>
<L N="5">Als swift als winde, &thorn;at blowe&thorn; on clou&thorn;e,</L>
<L>As white as lilii on lake.</L>
<L>To an hille he ran wi&thorn;outen obade:</L>
<L>At &thorn;e hole of &thorn;e roche in he glade.</L>
<L>Gij wonderd for &thorn;at sake.</L>
<L N="10">&amp; when he out of &thorn;at roche cam</L>
<L>Into Tirries mou&thorn;e he nam:</L>
<L>Anon Tirri gan wake.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="163" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Sir Gij was wonderd of &thorn;at si&yogh;t,<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="9093"></L>
<L>&amp; Tirri sat vp anon ri&yogh;t,</L>
<L>&amp; biheld Gij opon.</L>
<L>&THORN;an seyd Tirri, 'fader of heuen!</L>
<L N="5">Sir pilgrim, swiche a wonder sweuen</L>
<L>Me met now anon,</L>
<L>&THORN;at to &yogh;on hille &thorn;at stont on hei&yogh;e,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ou may se wi&thorn; &thorn;i nei&yogh;e,</L>
<L>Me &thorn;ou&yogh;t &thorn;at y<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>&thorn;ou</I> MS.</NOTE> was gon,
<PB REF="00000526.tif" N="522"></L>
<L N="10">&amp; at an hole in y wond,</L>
<L>&amp; so riche tresour as y fond</L>
<L>Y trow in &thorn;is world is non.<MILESTONE N="158a:a" UNIT="folio"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="164" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Biside &thorn;at tresour lay a dragoun,</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;er-on lay a swerd broun,</L>
<L>&THORN;e sckauberk comly corn:</L>
<L>In &thorn;e hilt was mani precious ston,</L>
<L N="5">As bri&yogh;t as ani sonne it schon,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn;-outen o&thorn; y-sworn.</L>
<L>&amp; me &thorn;ou&yogh;t Gij sat at min heued,</L>
<L>&amp; in his lappe me biweued</L>
<L>Astow dest<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>dost</I> MS.</NOTE> me biforn.</L>
<L N="10">Lord, merci, &amp; it wer so</L>
<L>Wele were me &thorn;an bi-go,</L>
<L>&THORN;at euer &yogh;ete was y born.'</L>
</LG>
<LG N="165" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; 'Now, felawe,' seyd Gij, 'bi mi leute,</L>
<L>&THORN;at s[w]euen wil turn gret ioie to &thorn;e,</L>
<L>&amp; wele y schal it rede:</L>
<L>&THORN;urch Gij &thorn;ou schalt &thorn;i lond keuer.</L>
<L N="5">Trust wele to god, &thorn;ei &thorn;ou be pouer:</L>
<L>&THORN;e better &thorn;ou schalt spede.</L>
<L>To &thorn;e hulle nim we &thorn;e way,</L>
<L>&THORN;er &thorn;e &thorn;ou&yogh;t &thorn;e tresour lay,</L>
<L>&amp; in &thorn;ou schalt me lede.</L>
<L N="10">Now god, &thorn;at schope al mankinde,</L>
<L>Wald we mi&yogh;t &thorn;at tresour finde:</L>
<L>It wald help ous at nede.'</L>
</LG>
<LG N="166" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Vp risen &thorn;o kni&yogh;tes tvay,<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="9123"></L>
<L>&amp; to &thorn;e hille &thorn;ai nom &thorn;e way,</L>
<L>&amp; in &thorn;ai went ful euen,</L>
<L>&amp; founde &thorn;e tresour, &amp; &thorn;e dragoun,</L>
<L N="5">&amp; &thorn;e swerd of stiel broun,</L>
<L>As Tirri met in his sweuen.</L>
<L>Sir Gij<NOTE PLACE="marg">added above the line.</NOTE> drou&yogh; out &thorn;at swerd anon,</L>
<L>&amp; alle &thorn;e pleynes &thorn;er-of it schon,</L>
<L>As it were li&yogh;t of leuen.
<PB REF="00000528.tif" N="524"></L>
<L N="10">'Lord,' seyd Gij, 'y &thorn;anke &thorn;i sond:</L>
<L>Y sei&yogh;e neuer are swiche a brond;</L>
<L>Y wot it com fram heuen.'</L>
</LG>
<LG N="167" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Sir Gij gan &thorn;e hilt bi-hold,</L>
<L>&THORN;at richeliche was grauen wi&thorn; gold,</L>
<L>Of charbukel &thorn;e pomel.</L>
<L>Into &thorn;e sckaweberk o&yogh;ain he it<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>it</I> added above the line.</NOTE> dede,</L>
<L N="5">&amp; seyd to Tirri in &thorn;at stede,</L>
<L>'Bi god &amp; seyn Mi&yogh;hel,</L>
<L>Of alle &thorn;is riche tresore</L>
<L>Y no kepe &thorn;erof no more,<MILESTONE N="158a:b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Bot &thorn;is brond of stiel.'<NOTE PLACE="marg">Three lines are wanting.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG N="168" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; To courtward &thorn;o kni&yogh;tes went:</L>
<L>To aspie after &thorn;e parlement</L>
<L>For drede wald &thorn;ai nou&yogh;t lete.</L>
<L>Ac Tirri was aferd ful sare</L>
<L N="5">Of his fomen be knowen &thorn;are,</L>
<L>In &thorn;e cite &yogh;if he sete;</L>
<L>&THORN;erfore &thorn;ai toke her ostel gode</L>
<L>At an hous wi&thorn;outen &thorn;e toun stode</L>
<L>Al bi a dern strete.</L>
<L N="10">Of al ni&yogh;t Gij slepe nou&yogh;t:</L>
<L>So michel his hert was euer in &thorn;ou&yogh;t</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; douk Berard to mete.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="169" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Erlich amorwe &thorn;an ros Gij,<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="9155"></L>
<L>&amp; bisou&yogh;t god &amp; our leuedi</L>
<L>He schuld scheld him fro blame,</L>
<L>&amp; seyd to sir Tirri &thorn;e hende,</L>
<L N="5">'Kepe me wele &thorn;is swerd, leue frende,</L>
<L>Til y sende &thorn;er-fore, bi name,</L>
<L>&amp; y schal go to court &thorn;is day,</L>
<L>&amp; &yogh;if y &thorn;e douke mete may</L>
<L>Y schal gret him wi&thorn; grame,</L>
<L N="10">&amp; &yogh;if he say ou&yogh;t bot gode
<PB REF="00000530.tif" N="526"></L>
<L>Bi him &thorn;at schadde for ous his blod,</L>
<L>Him tit a warld schame.'</L>
</LG>
<LG N="170" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Gij go&thorn; to toun wi&thorn; michel hete:</L>
<L>&THORN;emperour fram chirche he gan mete,</L>
<L>&amp; gret him wi&thorn; anour.</L>
<L>'Lord,' seyd Gij, '&thorn;at wi&thorn; hond</L>
<L N="5">Made wode, water, &amp; lond,</L>
<L>Saue &thorn;e, sir emperour.</L>
<L>Icham a man of fer cuntre,</L>
<L>&amp; of &thorn;i gode par charite</L>
<L>Ich axse to mi socour.'</L>
<L N="10">&THORN;emperour seyd, 'to court come,</L>
<L>&amp; of mi gode &thorn;ou schalt haue some</L>
<L>For loue of seyn sauour.'</L>
</LG>
<LG N="171" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; To court &thorn;ai went al &amp; some.<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="9173"></L>
<L>&THORN;emperour dede Gij<NOTE PLACE="marg">added above the line.</NOTE> biforn him come:</L>
<L>'Pilgrim,' &thorn;an seyd he,</L>
<L>'&THORN;ou art wel weri me&thorn;enke&thorn; now:</L>
<L N="5">Fram wiche londes comestow?</L>
<L>For &thorn;i fader soule, telle me.'</L>
<L>'Sir,' seyd<NOTE PLACE="marg">added above the line.</NOTE> Gij, 'ich vnderstond,<MILESTONE N="158b:a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Ichaue ben in mani lond</L>
<L>Bi&yogh;ond &thorn;e Grekis se:</L>
<L N="10">In Ierusalem &amp; in Surry,</L>
<L>In Costentin &amp; in Perci</L>
<L>A gode while haue ich be.'</L>
</LG>
<LG N="172" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; 'Sir pilgrim,' seyd &thorn;emperour fre,</L>
<L>'What speke&thorn; man in &thorn;at lond of me</L>
<L>When &thorn;ou com &thorn;ennes ward?'</L>
<L>Sir Gij answerd, 'bi &thorn;e gode rode,</L>
<L N="5">Men speke&thorn; &thorn;e &thorn;er ful litel gode,</L>
<L>Bot tidinges schrewed &amp; hard;</L>
<L>For &thorn;ou hast schent so &thorn;erl Tirri</L>
<L>&amp; o&thorn;er barouns, &thorn;at ben hendy,</L>
<L>For loue of &thorn;i steward.</L>
<L N="10">Gret sinne it is to &thorn;e
<PB REF="00000532.tif" N="528"></L>
<L>To stroye so &thorn;i barouns fre</L>
<L>Al for a fals schreward.'</L>
</LG>
<LG N="173" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; When &thorn;e douk herd him speke so,<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="9197"></L>
<L>As a wilde bore he lepe him to,</L>
<L>His costes for to schawe.</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; his fest he wald haue smiten Gij,</L>
<L N="5">Bot barouns held him owy</L>
<L>Wele tventi on a rawe.</L>
<L>He seyd to Gij, 'vile traitour,</L>
<L>Ner &thorn;ou bifor &thorn;emperour,</L>
<L>&THORN;ei y wende to ben to-hewe,</L>
<L N="10">Bi thi berd y schuld &thorn;e schokke,</L>
<L>&THORN;at al &thorn;i te&thorn;<NOTE PLACE="marg">Part of the <I>&thorn;</I> gone.</NOTE> it schuld rokke;</L>
<L>For &thorn;ou art<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>rt</I> rather in|distinct.</NOTE> a kinde schrewe.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="174" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Bi &thorn;i semblaunt se men may</L>
<L>&THORN;ou hast ben traitour mani a day:</L>
<L>God &yogh;if &thorn;e schame &amp; schond.</L>
<L>&YOGH;if &thorn;at y &thorn;e mai ouergon,</L>
<L N="5">To wicked ded &thorn;ou schalt be don,</L>
<L>As a traitour to ly in bond:</L>
<L>In swiche a stede &thorn;ou schalt be,</L>
<L>&THORN;is seuen winter<NOTE PLACE="marg">An erasure after <I>winter</I>.</NOTE> no schaltow se</L>
<L>Noi&thorn;er<NOTE PLACE="marg">The <I>i</I> added above the line.</NOTE> fet no hond.</L>
<L N="10">So schal men chasti foule glotuns</L>
<L>&THORN;at wil missay gode barouns</L>
<L>&THORN;at lordinges ben in lond.'</L>
</LG>
<LG N="175" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; 'Ow sir,' seyd Gij, 'ertow &thorn;as<NOTE PLACE="marg">Read <I>&THORN;es: wes?</I></NOTE><MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="9217"></L>
<L>Y nist no nar ho<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>hou</I> MS.</NOTE> it was,</L>
<L>Bi &thorn;e gode rode,<MILESTONE N="158b:b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&amp; now y wot &thorn;at &thorn;ou art he:</L>
<L N="5">&THORN;ou art vncurteys, so &thorn;enke&thorn; me.</L>
<L>&THORN;ou farst astow wer wode,</L>
<L>&amp; art a man of fair parage:</L>
<L>Y-com &thorn;ou art of hei&yogh;e linage</L>
<L>&amp; of gentil blod.</L>
<L N="10">It is &thorn;e litel curteysie
<PB REF="00000534.tif" N="530"></L>
<L>To do me swiche vilanie</L>
<L>Bifor &thorn;emperour &thorn;er y stode.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="176" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; &amp; for &thorn;e wil y wond no-&thorn;ing:</L>
<L>Y schal telle &thorn;e &thorn;e so&thorn;e wi&thorn;outen lesing</L>
<L>Bifor his barouns ichon,</L>
<L>&THORN;at wi&thorn; gret wrong &amp; sinne, ywis,</L>
<L N="5">&THORN;erl Tirri deshirrite is</L>
<L>&amp; o&thorn;er gode mani on.</L>
<L>A &thorn;ousend men ichaue herd teld</L>
<L>Bo&thorn;e in toun &amp; in feld,</L>
<L>As wide as ichaue gon,</L>
<L N="10">&THORN;at he is giltles of &thorn;at dede:</L>
<L>&THORN;ou berst on him wi&thorn; falshede</L>
<L>&THORN;i neme he schuld slon.'</L>
</LG>
<LG N="177" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; &THORN;e douk Berra[r]d was wro&thorn;,<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="9235"></L>
<L>Bi Iesu Crist he swore his o&thorn;,</L>
<L>'Y wald &thorn;at &thorn;ou were Gij,</L>
<L>Or &thorn;at &thorn;ou so douhti were</L>
<L N="5">&THORN;ou durst fi&yogh;t for him here:</L>
<L>God &yogh;af it &amp; our leuedi!'</L>
<L>Sir Gij<NOTE PLACE="marg">Added above the line.</NOTE> answerd, 'bi seyn sauour,</L>
<L>Drede &thorn;e no&thorn;ing, vile traitour:</L>
<L>&THORN;erto icham redy.</L>
<L N="10">Bi &thorn;ou wro&thorn;, be &thorn;ou gladde,</L>
<L>To &thorn;emperour y &yogh;if mi wedde</L>
<L>To fi&yogh;t for &thorn;erl Tirri.'
<PB REF="00000536.tif" N="532"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="178" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; &THORN;e douk Berard &thorn;er he stode</L>
<L>Stared on Gij as he wer wode,</L>
<L>&amp; egrelich seyd his &thorn;ou&yogh;t.</L>
<L>'Pilgrim,' he seyd, '&thorn;ou art ful stout:</L>
<L N="5">Y-wis, &thorn;i wordes &thorn;at er so prout</L>
<L>Schal be ful dere abou&yogh;t.</L>
<L>Y warn &thorn;e wele,' he seyd &thorn;o,</L>
<L>'&THORN;at &thorn;ine heued &thorn;ou schalt forgo,</L>
<L>Where so &thorn;ou may be sou&yogh;t.'</L>
<L N="10">Sir Gij seyd, '&thorn;an &thorn;ou it hast,</L>
<L>&THORN;an make &thorn;er-of &thorn;i bast;<MILESTONE N="159b:a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>For &yogh;ete no getes &thorn;ou it nou&yogh;t.'</L>
</LG>
<LG N="179" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Bifor &thorn;emperour &thorn;an come Gij,<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="9261"></L>
<L>&amp; seyd, 'sir Berard of Paui</L>
<L>Is a man of mi&yogh;ti dede,</L>
<L>&amp; fram fer cuntres comen icham,</L>
<L N="5">&amp; am a sely pouer man:</L>
<L>Y no haue here no sibbered,</L>
<L>No y no haue wepen no armour bri&yogh;t.</L>
<L>For &thorn;e loue of god al-mi&yogh;t,</L>
<L>Finde me armour &amp; stede.'</L>
<L N="10">&THORN;emperour answerd, 'bi Iesu,</L>
<L>Pilgrim, &thorn;ou schalt haue anow</L>
<L>Of al &thorn;at &thorn;e is nede.'</L>
</LG>
<LG N="180" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; &THORN;e douk Berra[r]d &thorn;ennes he went:</L>
<L>His hert was in strong turment,</L>
<L>He no wist what he do mi&yogh;t.</L>
<L>&THORN;emperour cleped his douhter, a mayde<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>amayde</I> MS.</NOTE>:</L>
<L N="5">'Leue douhter,' to hir he seyd,</L>
<L>'Kepe &thorn;is pilgrim to-ni&yogh;t.'</L>
<L>Sche him vnderfenge ful mildeliche,</L>
<L>&amp; dede ba&thorn;e him ful softliche:</L>
<L>In silke sche wald him di&yogh;t,
<PB REF="00000538.tif" N="534"></L>
<L N="10">Ac &thorn;erof was no-&thorn;ing his &thorn;ou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>Bot of gode armour he hir bisou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; &thorn;e douke Berard to fi&yogh;t.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="181" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Amorwe aros &thorn;at emperour:<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="9293"></L>
<L>Erls, barouns of gret honour</L>
<L>To chirche wi&thorn; him &thorn;ai &yogh;ede,</L>
<L>&amp; when &thorn;e barouns asembled was</L>
<L N="5">&THORN;an mi&yogh;t men sen in &thorn;at plas</L>
<L>To-gider a fair ferred.</L>
<L>&THORN;ider com &thorn;e douk Berard</L>
<L>Prout &amp; stern as a lipard,<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>alipard</I> MS.</NOTE></L>
<L>Wele y-armed on stede,</L>
<L N="10">&amp; priked ri&yogh;t as he wer wode</L>
<L>Among &thorn;e barouns &thorn;er &thorn;ai stode,</L>
<L>Batayle for to bede.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="182" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; &THORN;e maiden for&yogh;at neuer a del,</L>
<L>&THORN;e pilgrim was armed ful wel</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; a gode glaiue in honde,</L>
<L>&amp; a swift ernand stede</L>
<L N="5">Al wrin sche dede him lede,</L>
<L>&THORN;e best of &thorn;at lond.</L>
<L>&THORN;an sir Gij him bi-&thorn;ou&yogh;t,<MILESTONE N="159a:b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&THORN;e gode swerd for&yogh;at he nou&yogh;t</L>
<L>&THORN;at he in tresour fond.</L>
<L N="10">He sent &thorn;erafter priueliche</L>
<L>(Noman wist litel no miche),</L>
<L>&amp; Tirri sent him &thorn;e brond.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="183" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; When &thorn;at mayden hadde grai&thorn;ed Gij,</L>
<L>Wele y-di&yogh;t &amp; ful richely,</L>
<L>Men gan on him biheld.
<PB REF="00000540.tif" N="536"></L>
<L>Sche ledde him for&thorn; swi&thorn;e stille</L>
<L N="5">To &thorn;emperour wi&thorn; gode wille:</L>
<L>Sche tau&yogh;t him for to weld.</L>
<L>&THORN;an seyd &thorn;emperour hende &amp; fre,<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="9323"></L>
<L>'Lordinges, listen now to me,</L>
<L>Bo&thorn;e &yogh;ong &amp; eld.</L>
<L N="10">&THORN;is kni&yogh;t, &thorn;at &yogh;e se now here,</L>
<L>Ha&thorn; taken batail in strong maner,</L>
<L>Al for to fi&yogh;t in feld.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="184" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; &THORN;is kni&yogh;t,' he seyd, '&thorn;at ston[t] me bi,</L>
<L>Wil fi&yogh;t for &thorn;erl sir Tirri</L>
<L>(For no &thorn;ing wil he wond),</L>
<L>&amp; defende him of &thorn;at felonie</L>
<L N="5">O&yogh;ain &thorn;e douk Berard of Paui</L>
<L>&THORN;at he ber&thorn; him an hond;</L>
<L>For Tirri is out of lond went</L>
<L>To seche Gij, verrament,</L>
<L>&THORN;at for him mi&yogh;t stond</L>
<L N="10">(&THORN;is day is sett bitven hem tvo),</L>
<L>Or be deshirrite for euer-mo,</L>
<L>&amp; flemed out of lond.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="185" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Bot now is comen here &thorn;is kni&yogh;t,</L>
<L>O&yogh;ain Berard ha&thorn; taken &thorn;e fi&yogh;t:</L>
<L>For no &thorn;ing wil he flen.</L>
<L>Ac, lordinges,' he seyd, 'euerichon,</L>
<L N="5">Where the batayl schal be don</L>
<L>Loke, where it may best ben.'</L>
<L>&THORN;an loked &thorn;ai it schuld be</L>
<L>In a launde vnder &thorn;e cite.</L>
<L>&THORN;ider in &thorn;ai went bi-den:
<PB REF="00000542.tif" N="538"></L>
<L N="10">Mani man bad god &thorn;at day</L>
<L>Help &thorn;e pilgrim, as he wele may,</L>
<L>&THORN;e douk Berard to slen.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="186" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; On hors lopen &thorn;o kni&yogh;tes prest,</L>
<L>&amp; lopen to-gider til schaftes brest,</L>
<L>&THORN;at strong weren &amp; trewe,<MILESTONE N="159b:a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&amp; her ger&thorn;es brusten, &thorn;at strong were,</L>
<L N="5">&amp; &thorn;o kni&yogh;tes bo&thorn;e y-fere</L>
<L>Out of her sadels &thorn;rewe.</L>
<L>After &thorn;ai drou&yogh; her swerdes gode,</L>
<L>&amp; leyd on as &thorn;ai were wode,</L>
<L>&THORN;at were gode &amp; newe;</L>
<L N="10">&amp; astow sest &thorn;e fir on flint</L>
<L>&THORN;e stem out of her helmes stint</L>
<L>So hetelich &thorn;ai gun hewe.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="187" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Wele wer armed &thorn;o kni&yogh;tes stout,</L>
<L>Bot he had more yren him about</L>
<L>&THORN;at fals Berardine:</L>
<L>Tvay hauberkes he was in weued,</L>
<L N="5">&amp; tvay helmes opon his heued,</L>
<L>Was wrou&yogh;t in Sarazine.</L>
<L>Opon his schulder henge a duble scheld</L>
<L>(Better<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>Berter</I> MS.</NOTE> mi&yogh;t non be born in feld),</L>
<L>A gode swerd of stiel fine:</L>
<L N="10">Mani man &thorn;erwi&thorn; his liif had lorn.</L>
<L>It was sumtim &thorn;er-biforn</L>
<L>&THORN;e kinges Costentine.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="188" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Strong batayl held &thorn;o kni&yogh;tes bold,</L>
<L>&THORN;at alle &thorn;at euer gan hem bihold</L>
<L>&THORN;ai seyden hem among</L>
<L>&THORN;e pilgrim was non er&thorn;ely man;</L>
<L N="5">It was an angel, from heuen cam</L>
<L>For Tirri batayle to fong:
<PB REF="00000544.tif" N="540"></L>
<L>'For mani gode erle &amp; mani baroun</L>
<L>Berard ha&thorn; y-brou&yogh;t adoun</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; wel michel wrong,</L>
<L N="10">&THORN;er-fore ha&thorn; God sent, y-wis,</L>
<L>An angel out of heuen blis</L>
<L>To sle &thorn;at traitour strong.'</L>
</LG>
<LG N="189" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Al &thorn;e folk in &thorn;at cite was,<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="9375"></L>
<L>Litel &amp; michel, more &amp; las,</L>
<L>To se &thorn;e batayl &thorn;ai &yogh;ede;</L>
<L>Bot Tirri in a chirche liis,</L>
<L N="5">&amp; euer he bisou&yogh;t god, y-wis,</L>
<L>He schuld him help &amp; spede.</L>
<L>When he herd telle [&thorn;at a] pilgrim</L>
<L>Fau&yogh;t o&yogh;ain &thorn;e douke Berardin,</L>
<L>To help him at his nede,</L>
<L N="10">Wel fain he wald &thorn;ider gon,</L>
<L>Bot for knoweing of his fon:<MILESTONE N="160b:b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Wel sore he gan him drede.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="190" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Ac na&thorn;eles he ros vp &thorn;o</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; michel care &amp; michel wo,</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;ider he went wel swi&thorn;e.</L>
<L>When he com to &thorn;e plas</L>
<L N="5">&THORN;er &thorn;e bataile loked was,</L>
<L>Amonges hem he gan li&thorn;e,</L>
<L>&amp;, when he sey&yogh;e the douk so strong</L>
<L>&amp; his armes to-hewe among,</L>
<L>In his hert he was ful bli&thorn;e,
<PB REF="00000546.tif" N="542"></L>
<L N="10">&amp;, &thorn;o he sey&yogh;e his blod spille,</L>
<L>God he &thorn;onked wi&thorn; gode wille.<NOTE PLACE="marg">A line is here omitted in the MS.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG N="191" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; 'Lord, merci!' Tirri gan say:</L>
<L>'&THORN;is is nou&yogh;t &thorn;e pilgrim y met &yogh;isterday<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>&yogh;ist</I> blotted.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at is so richeliche di&yogh;t.</L>
<L>He was a feble pouer body,</L>
<L N="5">Sely, messays, &amp; hungri;</L>
<L>&amp; he is of michel mi&yogh;t.</L>
<L>Y trow non er&thorn;elich man it be.</L>
<L>On Gij y &thorn;enke when ichim se:</L>
<L>So douhti he was in fi&yogh;t.</L>
<L N="10">&YOGH;if Gij, mi felawe, nou&yogh;t<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>now</I> MS.</NOTE> ded nere,</L>
<L>Ich wald sigge &thorn;at he it were:</L>
<L>So liche &thorn;ai ben of si&yogh;t.'</L>
</LG>
<LG N="192" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Into chirche o&yogh;ain he &yogh;ede,</L>
<L>&amp; fel on knes in &thorn;at stede,</L>
<L>&amp; Iesus Crist he bi-sou&yogh;t</L>
<L>He schuld help &thorn;e pilgrim</L>
<L N="5">&THORN;at fau&yogh;t o&yogh;ain douk Berardin,</L>
<L>&THORN;at miche wo ha&thorn; him wrou&yogh;t.</L>
<L>Hard togider gun &thorn;ai fi&yogh;t</L>
<L>Fro the morwe to &thorn;e ni&yogh;t,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ai rest hem nou&yogh;t;</L>
<L N="10">&amp; when hem failed li&yogh;t of day</L>
<L>&THORN;ai cou&thorn;e no rede what &thorn;ai do may:</L>
<L>To &thorn;emperour &thorn;ai hem brou&yogh;t.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="193" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; 'Sir emperour,' &thorn;ai seyd anon,<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="9431"></L>
<L>'What schul we wi&thorn; &thorn;is kni&yogh;tes don?</L>
<L>At &thorn;i wille schal it be.'</L>
<L>&THORN;emperour clept to him &thorn;o</L>
<L N="5">Four barouns &thorn;at his trust was to.</L>
<L>'Lordinges,' &thorn;an seyd he,</L>
<L>'Kepe me wele &thorn;e douk Berard,</L>
<L>&amp; bring him tomorwe bi a forward,<MILESTONE N="160a:a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Opon al &yogh;our fe.
<PB REF="00000548.tif" N="544"></L>
<L N="10">&amp; y schal kepe &thorn;e pilgrim to-ni&yogh;t:</L>
<L>Til tomorwe &thorn;at it is day li&yogh;t</L>
<L>He schal bileue wi&thorn; me.'</L>
</LG>
<LG N="194" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;an departed &thorn;is batayle:</L>
<L>&THORN;o four barouns, wi&thorn;-outen fayl,</L>
<L>Vnder-stode Berard to kepe,</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;emperour toke &thorn;e pilgrim,</L>
<L N="5">In a chaumber to loken him</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; seriaunce wise &amp; &yogh;epe.</L>
<L>&THORN;e douke Berard for-&yogh;at him nou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>Of a foule tresoun he him bi-&thorn;ou&yogh;t:</L>
<L>Four kni&yogh;tes he gan clepe.</L>
<L N="10">'F[or]<NOTE PLACE="marg">blotted.</NOTE> mi loue,' he seyd, 'go&thorn; to-ni&yogh;t</L>
<L>&THORN;[er]<NOTE PLACE="marg">blotted.</NOTE> &thorn;e pilgrim li&thorn; ful ri&yogh;t,</L>
<L>&amp; sle&thorn; him in his slepe.'</L>
</LG>
<LG N="195" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; &THORN;ai armed hem swi&thorn;e wel<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="9455"></L>
<L>Bo&thorn;e in iren &amp; in stiel,</L>
<L>&amp; went hem for&thorn; in hast.</L>
<L>Into &thorn;e chaumber &thorn;ai went anon:</L>
<L N="5">&THORN;e pilgrims kepers euerichon</L>
<L>Lay &amp; slepe full fast.</L>
<L>To &thorn;e pilgrim &thorn;ai went ful ri&yogh;t,</L>
<L>&amp; left vp &thorn;e bedde wi&thorn; her mi&yogh;t,</L>
<L>&THORN;o four traitours vnwrast:</L>
<L N="10">To &thorn;e se &thorn;ai beren him,</L>
<L>&amp; bo&thorn;e bed &amp; &thorn;e pilgrim</L>
<L>Into &thorn;e see &thorn;ai cast.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="196" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; To sir Berard &thorn;ai went anon,</L>
<L>&amp; teld him hou &thorn;ai hadden don;</L>
<L>&THORN;erof he was ful fawe.</L>
<L>'Sir,' &thorn;ai seyd, 'be nou&yogh;t adred:</L>
<L N="5">Bo&thorn;e &thorn;e pilgrim &amp; &thorn;e bed,</L>
<L>Into &thorn;e se we han y-&thorn;rawe.'
<PB REF="00000550.tif" N="546"></L>
<L>&THORN;e pilgrim waked, &amp; loked an hey&yogh;e:</L>
<L>&THORN;e sterres on &thorn;e heuen he sei&yogh;e,</L>
<L>&THORN;e water about him drawe.</L>
<L N="10">&THORN;ei he was ferd no wonder it nis:</L>
<L>Non o&thorn;er &thorn;ing he no sey&yogh;e, y-wis,</L>
<L>Bot winde &amp; wateres wawe.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="197" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; 'Lord,' seyd Gij, 'god almi&yogh;t,<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="9475"></L>
<L>&THORN;at winde, &amp; water, &amp; al &thorn;ing di&yogh;t,</L>
<L>On me haue now pite!</L>
<L>Whi is me fallen &thorn;us strong cumbring?<MILESTONE N="100a:b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="5">&amp; y no fi&yogh;t for to win no &thorn;ing,</L>
<L>Noi&thorn;er gold no fe,</L>
<L>For no cite no no castel,</L>
<L>Bot for mi felawe y loued so wel,</L>
<L>&THORN;at was of gret bounte.</L>
<L N="10">For he was sumtyim so douhti,</L>
<L>&amp; now he is so pouer a bodi,</L>
<L>Certes, it rewe&thorn; me.'
</L>
</LG>

</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="section"><PB REF="00000552.tif" N="548">
<LG N="198" TYPE="stanza">
<L>Now herkene&thorn; a litel striif,</L>
<L>Hou he saued &thorn;e pilgrims liif</L>
<L>Iesu, &thorn;at sitt in trone,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; a fischer &thorn;at was comand,</L>
<L N="5">In &thorn;e se fische takeand</L>
<L>Bi himself al-on.</L>
<L>He se&thorn; &thorn;at bed floter him by:</L>
<L>'On godes half,' he gan to cri,</L>
<L>'What artow? say me son.'</L>
<L N="10">&THORN;e pilgrim his heued vp pli&yogh;t,</L>
<L>&amp; crid to him anon ri&yogh;t,</L>
<L>&amp; made wel reweli mon.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="199" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; 'Gode man,' &thorn;an seyd he,<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="9501"></L>
<L>'Y leue on god in trinite:</L>
<L>&THORN;e so&thorn;e &thorn;ou schalt now sen.</L>
<L>Vnderstode &thorn;ou ou&yogh;t of &thorn;e batayl hard</L>
<L N="5">Bitven &thorn;e pilgrim &amp; sir Berard,</L>
<L>Hou &thorn;ai fou&yogh;ten bitven?'</L>
<L>&THORN;e fischer seyd, 'y sei&yogh;e &thorn;e fi&yogh;t</L>
<L>Fro &thorn;e morwe to &thorn;e ni&yogh;t:</L>
<L>For no&thorn;ing wald &thorn;ai flen.</L>
<L N="10">&THORN;emperour comand &thorn;o</L>
<L>&THORN;ai schuld be kept bo&thorn;e tvo,</L>
<L>Tomorwe bring hem o&yogh;en.'</L>
</LG>
<LG N="200" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; 'Icham,' he seyd, '&thorn;e pilgrim</L>
<L>&THORN;at fau&yogh;t wi&thorn;<NOTE PLACE="marg">The <I>&thorn;</I> of <I>wi&thorn;</I> added above the line.</NOTE> &thorn;e douke Berardin</L>
<L>For Tirri, &thorn;e hendi kni&yogh;t.</L>
<L>&YOGH;istreuen we wer deled ato;</L>
<L N="5">In a chaumber y was do</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; seriaunce wise &amp; wi&yogh;t:</L>
<L>Hou ich com her no wot y nou&yogh;t.</L>
<L>For his loue &thorn;at &thorn;is warld ha&thorn; wrou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>Saue me &yogh;if &thorn;ou mi&yogh;t.'</L>
<L N="10">&THORN;e fischer tok him into his bot anon,</L>
<L>&amp; to his hous he ladde him hom,</L>
<L>&amp; saued his liif &thorn;at ni&yogh;t.<MILESTONE N="160b:a" UNIT="folio">
<PB REF="00000554.tif" N="550"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="201" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; &THORN;emperour ros amorwe, y-wis,<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="9525"></L>
<L>&amp; at<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>at</I> altered from <I>atte.</I></NOTE> &thorn;e chirche he herd his messe</L>
<L>In &thorn;e first tide of &thorn;e day,</L>
<L>&amp; into his halle he gan gon,</L>
<L N="5">&amp; after &thorn;e steward he axed anon</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;e pilgrim wi&thorn;-outen delay.</L>
<L>&THORN;e four barouns for&yogh;at hem nou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>&THORN;e douke Berard &thorn;ai han for&thorn; brou&yogh;t</L>
<L>Redy armed to play;</L>
<L N="10">&amp; &thorn;e pilgrims kepers com euerichon,</L>
<L>&amp; seyd to &thorn;emperour, bi seyn Ion,</L>
<L>&THORN;e pilgrim was oway.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="202" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; &THORN;emperour was wel wro&thorn;:</L>
<L>Bi his fader soule he swore<NOTE PLACE="marg">The <I>s</I> of <I>swore</I> added above the line.</NOTE> his o&thorn;,</L>
<L>&THORN;ai schuld ben hang &amp; drawe.</L>
<L>'For godes loue,' he seyd, 'merci!</L>
<L N="5">&THORN;is douke Berard of Paui</L>
<L>Ha&thorn; him brou&yogh;t o dawe.'</L>
<L>&THORN;emperour seyd, 'bi seyn Martin,</L>
<L>Hastow don &thorn;is fals, Berardin,</L>
<L>&middot; To don &thorn;e pilgrim slawe?</L>
<L N="10">&YOGH;eld him de&thorn;es or liues to me,</L>
<L>Or in mi court demp[t] &thorn;ou schalt be</L>
<L>&THORN;urch iugement of lawe.'</L>
</LG>
<LG N="203" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; &THORN;e douke Berard wex wro&thorn; &amp; wo;<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="9551"></L>
<L>&THORN;emperour he answerd &thorn;o</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; wel michel hete:</L>
<L>'Ichaue serued &thorn;e long, sir emperour,
<PB REF="00000556.tif" N="552"></L>
<L N="5">&amp; kept &thorn;i londes wi&thorn; michel anour,</L>
<L>&amp; now &thorn;ou ginnest me &thorn;rete.</L>
<L>&THORN;erof &yogh;iue y nou&yogh;t a chirston.</L>
<L>Hom to Lombardy ichil gon:</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; alle &thorn;e ost y may gete</L>
<L N="10">Y schal com in-to Almayn; for al &thorn;i tene</L>
<L>Of al &thorn;i lond, siker mot &thorn;ou ben,</L>
<L>O fot y no schal &thorn;e lete.'</L>
</LG>
<LG N="204" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; When &thorn;emperour herd &thorn;at,</L>
<L>&amp; of his &thorn;retening vnder-&yogh;at,</L>
<L>He bad wi&thorn; wordes bold</L>
<L>Out of his court he schuld gon.</L>
<L N="5">&amp; he answerd sone anon</L>
<L>&THORN;at sikerliche he nold.<NOTE PLACE="marg">The <I>e</I> of <I>he</I> and the <I>n</I> of <I>nold</I> blotted.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;er com &thorn;e fischer priueliche,</L>
<L>&amp; puked &thorn;emperour softliche:<MILESTONE N="160b:b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>His tale to him he told.</L>
<L N="10">'Sir emperour,' he seyd, 'listen to me:</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e pilgrim ichil telle &thorn;e,</L>
<L>&YOGH;if &thorn;ou me herken wold.'</L>
</LG>
<LG N="205" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; 'Fischer,' seyd &thorn;emperour fre,<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="9857"></L>
<L>'Of &thorn;e pilgrim telle &thorn;ou me,</L>
<L>&YOGH;if &thorn;ou &thorn;e so&thorn;e can sayn.'</L>
<L>'For-so&thorn;e,' he seyd, 'y can ful wel:</L>
<L N="5">Y schal &thorn;e ley&yogh;en neuer a del;</L>
<L>&THORN;erof icham ful fain.</L>
<L>&YOGH;istreuen, wi&thorn;-outen lesing,</L>
<L>Y went to &thorn;e se of fischeing,</L>
<L>Mine nettes for to layn.</L>
<L N="10">A bedde y fond &thorn;er floterand,
<PB REF="00000558.tif" N="554"></L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;er-on a kni&yogh;t liggeand,</L>
<L>A man of michel mayn.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="206" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; &amp; ich him axed what he were:</L>
<L>He told me &thorn;e so&thorn;e &thorn;ere</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; wordes fre &amp; hende.</L>
<L>'Icham,' he seyd, '&thorn;e pilgrim</L>
<L N="5">&THORN;at fau&yogh;t wi&thorn; &thorn;e douke Berardin</L>
<L>&YOGH;isterday to &thorn;e nende.'</L>
<L>Y tok him into mi bot anon,</L>
<L>&amp; to min hous y lad him hom,</L>
<L>&amp; kept him as mi frende.</L>
<L N="10">&YOGH;if &thorn;ou leuest nou&yogh;t he is &thorn;are,</L>
<L>Do sum seriaunt &thorn;ider fare,</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;er &yogh;e may him fende.'</L>
</LG>
<LG N="207" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; &THORN;emperour sent after him &thorn;o<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="9603"></L>
<L>Wi&thorn; &thorn;e fischer &amp; other mo,</L>
<L>&amp; brou&yogh;t him, saunfayle.</L>
<L>&THORN;ai were don togider bliue</L>
<L N="5">Wi&thorn; hard strokes for to driue:</L>
<L>&THORN;ai gun hem to asayle.</L>
<L>Wel hard togider gun &thorn;ai fi&yogh;t:</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; her brondes, &thorn;at wer bri&yogh;t,</L>
<L>&THORN;ai hewe hauberk of mayle.</L>
<L N="10">&THORN;us togider gun &thorn;ai play,</L>
<L>Til it was &thorn;e hey&yogh;e midday,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; wel strong batayle.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="208" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para;<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; wanting in MS.</NOTE> &THORN;e douk Berard was egre of mode:</L>
<L>He smot to Gij as he wer wode;</L>
<L>His liif he wende to winne.</L>
<L>He hit [him]<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>him</I> here omitted in MS, but the catchword on fol. 160 v. is <I>he hit him on &thorn;e helm</I></NOTE> on &thorn;e helm on hi&yogh;t,<MILESTONE N="161a:a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="5">&THORN;at alle &thorn;e floures feir &amp; bri&yogh;t</L>
<L>He dede hem fley&yogh;e atvinne.</L>
<L>&THORN;e nasel he carf atvo,</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;e venteyle he dede also</L>
<L>Ri&yogh;t to his bare chinne.<NOTE PLACE="inter">[Three lines are here omitted in MS.]</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000560.tif" N="556"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="209" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Sir Gij was wro&thorn; anon fot hot,</L>
<L>&amp; Berard on &thorn;e helme he smot:</L>
<L>To stond hadde he no space;</L>
<L>For bo&thorn;e helmes he carf atvo,</L>
<L N="5">&amp; his heued he dede also</L>
<L>In midward of &thorn;e face.</L>
<L>&THORN;urch al his bodi &thorn;e swerd bot</L>
<L>Into &thorn;e er&thorn;e wele half a fot,</L>
<L>&THORN;at sei&yogh;e men in &thorn;e place.</L>
<L N="10">&THORN;[e s]<NOTE PLACE="marg">The letters in brackets blotted.</NOTE> oule went fro &thorn;e bodi &thorn;ere:</L>
<L>&THORN;[e fol]k<NOTE PLACE="marg">The letters in brackets blotted.</NOTE> of &thorn;e cite wel glad were;</L>
<L>&THORN;[ai]<NOTE PLACE="marg">The letters in brackets blotted.</NOTE> &thorn;onked our lordes grace.
<PB REF="00000562.tif" N="558"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="210" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Bifor &thorn;emperour &thorn;an com sir Gij:<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="9653"></L>
<L>'Ichaue wroken &thorn;erl Tirri</L>
<L>(&THORN;e so&thorn;e &thorn;ou mi&yogh;t now sen),</L>
<L>&amp; defended him of &thorn;at felonie</L>
<L N="5">O&yogh;ain &thorn;e douke Berard of Paui,</L>
<L>&THORN;at was so stout &amp; ken.</L>
<L>&THORN;erfore &thorn;e so&thorn;e ich ax &thorn;e,</L>
<L>&YOGH;if Tirri schal quitecleymed be,</L>
<L>&amp; haue his lond o&yogh;en.</L>
<L N="10">&amp; who so &thorn;er-o&yogh;ain wi&thorn;stond</L>
<L>He schal haue schame of min hond,</L>
<L>Wel siker may he ben.'</L>
</LG>
<LG N="211" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; &THORN;emperour seyd, 'sikerly,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou hast wroken &thorn;erl Tirri;</L>
<L>Gret honour &thorn;ou hast him don.</L>
<L>&THORN;erfore when he is come</L>
<L N="5">His londes &thorn;an al &amp; some</L>
<L>He schal haue euerichon.'</L>
<L>&THORN;an was Gij glad &amp; bli&thorn;e,</L>
<L>&amp; kest of his armes also swi&thorn;e:</L>
<L>After him he thou&yogh;t to gon.</L>
<L N="10">&THORN;emperour wald clo&thorn;e him in gold,</L>
<L>Ac, sikerliche, he seyd he nold:</L>
<L>His sclauain he axed anon.
<PB REF="00000564.tif" N="560"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="212" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; To toun he went in his way<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="9673"></L>
<L>To finde Tirri &yogh;if he may</L>
<L>In sorwe &amp; care ful bounde.<MILESTONE N="161a:b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Into a chirche he him dede,</L>
<L N="5">&amp; fond him in a priue stede</L>
<L>Liand on knes to grounde.</L>
<L>'Arise vp, Tirri,' he seyd &thorn;o;</L>
<L>'To court &thorn;ou schalt wi&thorn; me go,</L>
<L>Now ichaue &thorn;e founde.'</L>
<L N="10">Tirri anon his heued vpbreyd,</L>
<L>&amp; seyd, 'pilgrim, hastow me treyd,</L>
<L>Allas &thorn;at ich stounde!</L>
</LG>
<LG N="213" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Allas, allas,' &thorn;an seyd he,</L>
<L>'To what man may men trust be,</L>
<L>To chese to his make?</L>
<L>&THORN;ou &thorn;at semed so stedefast</L>
<L N="5">To &thorn;emperour me wraied hast:</L>
<L>To sle me &thorn;ou hast take.</L>
<L>In iuel time was it to me</L>
<L>&THORN;at y mi name told to &thorn;e:</L>
<L>Allas &thorn;at ich sake!'</L>
<L N="10">For sorwe &thorn;at he hadde &thorn;o</L>
<L>O word no mi&yogh;t he speke mo,</L>
<L>Bot stode &amp; gan to quake.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="214" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; 'Tirri,' seyd Gij, 'drede &thorn;e no-&thorn;ing:<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="9697"></L>
<L>&THORN;ou schalt to-day here gode tiding</L>
<L>&THORN;urch grace of godes sond.</L>
<L>&THORN;e schrewed douke Berard he is ded;</L>
<L N="5">Under &thorn;e cite he is y-leyde:</L>
<L>Y slou&yogh; him wi&thorn; min hond.'</L>
<L>&THORN;o was Tirri glad &amp; bli&thorn;e:</L>
<L>To court he went also swi&thorn;e;</L>
<L>For no&thorn;ing wald he wond.</L>
<L N="10">'Sir emperour,' seyd Gij anon,</L>
<L>'Now is Tirri comen hom</L>
<L>To resceiue his lond.'
<PB REF="00000566.tif" N="562"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="215" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; &THORN;emperour on him gan bihold,</L>
<L>&amp; seyd to him wi&thorn; wordes bold,</L>
<L>'Artow &thorn;erl Tirri?</L>
<L>Where is now &thorn;i bold chere</L>
<L N="5">&THORN;at whilom so douhti were,</L>
<L>&amp; holden so hardi?'</L>
<L>'&YOGH;a, sir,' he seyd, 'icham he.</L>
<L>Whilom y was of gret bounde,</L>
<L>&amp; helden ful douhti;<NOTE PLACE="marg">The whole line on an erasure.</NOTE></L>
<L N="10">&amp; now ich haue al forlorn</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; miche sorwe on euen &amp; morn<MILESTONE N="161b:a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>To seke mi felawe sir Gij.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="216" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Ich haue him sou&yogh;t in mani lond,</L>
<L>Ac neuer man &yogh;ete ich fond</L>
<L>Can telle of him no sawe:</L>
<L>He is dede, ich wot full wel.</L>
<L N="5">God almi&yogh;ti &amp; seyn Mi&yogh;hel</L>
<L>To blis his soule drawe!</L>
<L>Ac now is it told me &thorn;is pilgrim</L>
<L>As slayn &thorn;e douke Berardin;</L>
<L>&THORN;erof icham ful fawe.</L>
<L N="10">Sir emperour, y bid merci:</L>
<L>For godes loue &amp; our leuedi,</L>
<L>&THORN;o[u] do me londes lawe.'</L>
</LG>
<LG N="217" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; &THORN;ritti erls wel curteys,<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="9725"></L>
<L>&amp; alle &thorn;e lordinges of &thorn;e palais,<NOTE PLACE="marg">altered from <I>paylais</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>&amp; mani baroun afine</L>
<L>Crid merci to &thorn;emperour bold.</L>
<L N="5">&THORN;emperour gan him bihold,<NOTE PLACE="marg">The <I>i</I> of <I>bihold</I> partially gone.</NOTE></L>
<L>&amp; seyd, 'Tirri, frende min,</L>
<L>Here y sese &thorn;e in al &thorn;i lond,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; wor&thorn;schip to held in &thorn;ine hond,</L>
<L>Bi god &amp; seyn Martine.</L>
<L N="10">Bifor mi barouns y graunt &thorn;e,</L>
<L>Steward of mi lond &thorn;ou schalt be</L>
<L>As was &thorn;e douke Berardine.'
<PB REF="00000568.tif" N="564"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="218" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; &THORN;emperour kist him ful swete,</L>
<L>For&yogh;af him his wre&thorn;e &amp; his hete</L>
<L>Bifor hem al &thorn;ere.<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>&THORN;re</I> MS.</NOTE></L>
<L>When &thorn;emperour &amp; &thorn;erl were at on,</L>
<L N="5">&THORN;e lordinges euerichon</L>
<L>Wele bli&thorn;e of hertes were.</L>
<L>'Sir Tirri,' seyd &thorn;emperour fre,</L>
<L>'For &thorn;i fader soule, tel &thorn;ou me,</L>
<L>Astow art me leue &amp; dere,</L>
<L N="10">Whennes is &thorn;is pilgrim?</L>
<L>Is he &thorn;i nem or &thorn;i cosyin</L>
<L>&THORN;at fau&yogh;t for &thorn;e here?'</L>
</LG>
<LG N="219" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; 'Sir emperour,' seyd sir Tirri,</L>
<L>'So god me help &amp; our leuedi,</L>
<L>For-so&thorn;e wi&thorn;outen fayle,</L>
<L>Y no sei&yogh;e neuer ere &thorn;is pilgrim,</L>
<L N="5">Bot &thorn;is o&thorn;er day y met wi&thorn; him,</L>
<L>&amp; told him mi conseyl.<MILESTONE N="161b:b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>He swore astite bi seyn Ion</L>
<L>To &thorn;i court he wald gon</L>
<L>&THORN;e douk Berard to asayle.</L>
<L N="10">Ich wend wel litel &thorn;an, y pli&yogh;t,</L>
<L>He hadde ben of michel mi&yogh;t,</L>
<L>To hold wi&thorn; him batayle.'
<PB REF="00000570.tif" N="566"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="220" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; &THORN;emperour dede as a gode man,<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="9763"></L>
<L>&amp; Tirri into his chaumber he nam,</L>
<L>&amp; richeliche gan him schrede.</L>
<L>He fond him wepen, &amp; armour bri&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="5">&amp; al &thorn;at schuld falle to kni&yogh;t,</L>
<L>&amp; feffed him wi&thorn; prede;</L>
<L>&amp; fond him hors &amp; stedes gode,</L>
<L>Of al his lond &thorn;e best stode,</L>
<L>Hom wi&thorn; him to lede.</L>
<L N="10">&THORN;emperour wald &thorn;e pilgrim at-hold,<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>hold</I> blotted.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ac, sikerliche, he seyd he nold:</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; Tirri hom he &yogh;ede.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="221" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; When Tirri was comen hom,</L>
<L>&THORN;e pilgrim he wald anon</L>
<L>Sesen in al his lond,</L>
<L>&amp; he for-soke it al out-ri&yogh;t;</L>
<L N="5">For riches loued he no-wi&yogh;t</L>
<L>For to hold in hond.</L>
<L>&THORN;erl as swi&thorn;e his sond he sent</L>
<L>Ouer al his lond, verrament,</L>
<L>Til &thorn;at his wiif he fond:</L>
<L N="10">&THORN;o was sche founden in an ile<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>anile</I> MS.</NOTE></L>
<L>In a nunri &thorn;at while</L>
<L>For doute of Berardes bond.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="222" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; &THORN;o was Tirri a noble man,<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="9779"></L>
<L>In al &thorn;at lond better nas nan,</L>
<L>As y &yogh;ou tel may.</L>
<L>Destrud were al his enemis:</L>
<L N="5">He liue&thorn; in michel ioie &amp; blis,</L>
<L>Al-so a prince in play.</L>
<L>Anon sir Gij him bi-&thorn;ou&yogh;t</L>
<L>&THORN;at lenger wald he duelle nou&yogh;t.</L>
<L>To sir Tirri on a day</L>
<L N="10">He seyd to him in &thorn;at tide,</L>
<L>'Here nil y no lenger abide:</L>
<L>Ich mot wende in mi way.
<PB REF="00000572.tif" N="568"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="223" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; O &thorn;ing,' he seyd, 'y pray &thorn;e:<MILESTONE N="162a:a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Out of &thorn;e cite go wi&thorn; me,</L>
<L>Astow art hendi kni&yogh;t.</L>
<L>Alon we shul go bo&thorn;e y-fere,</L>
<L N="5">&amp; swich tidinges &thorn;ou schalt here,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou schalt haue wonder, apli&yogh;t.'</L>
<L>&THORN;erl him graunt wi&thorn; hert fre,</L>
<L>&amp; went wi&thorn; him out of &thorn;at cite</L>
<L>In his way ful ri&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="10">&amp; when &thorn;ai wer &thorn;ennes half a mile<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>amile</I> MS.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;er &thorn;ai duelled a litel while,</L>
<L>&THORN;o gomes of michel mi&yogh;t.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="224" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; 'Tirri,' seyd Gij, 'vnderstond &thorn;ou &thorn;e:<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="9811"></L>
<L>&THORN;ou art vnkinde, so &thorn;enke&thorn; me;</L>
<L>For Gij, &thorn;i gode fere,</L>
<L>Whi<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>hi</I> blotted.</NOTE> wiltow him knowe nou&yogh;t?</L>
<L N="5">Y-wis,<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>wis</I> blotted.</NOTE> &thorn;ou art iuel bi&thorn;ou&yogh;t.</L>
<L>No was he &thorn;e leue &amp; dere?</L>
<L>&THORN;enke he slou&yogh; &thorn;e douk Otoun,</L>
<L>&amp; brou&yogh;t &thorn;e out of his prisoun,</L>
<L>&amp; made &thorn;e quite &amp; skere,</L>
<L N="10">&amp; hou he fond &thorn;e ded almast</L>
<L>As he rode &thorn;urch a forest<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>aforest</I> MS.</NOTE></L>
<L>Wi&thorn; a rewely chere,
<PB REF="00000574.tif" N="570"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="225" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; &amp; hou he socourd &thorn;i leman schene,</L>
<L>&amp; al &thorn;e fiften outlawes ken</L>
<L>He slou&yogh; hem al on rawe,</L>
<L>&amp; slou&yogh; &thorn;e four kni&yogh;tes radde,</L>
<L N="5">&amp; &thorn;i bodi to toun ladde,</L>
<L>To leche &thorn;i woundes ful fawe,</L>
<L>&amp; he socourd &thorn;i fader in wer,</L>
<L>&amp; halp &thorn;e bo&thorn;e nere &amp; fer</L>
<L>&THORN;o &thorn;ou was fallen ful lawe,</L>
<L N="10">&amp; now y slou&yogh; Berard &thorn;e strong.</L>
<L>Icham Gij; &thorn;ou hast wrong:</L>
<L>Why wiltow me nou&yogh;t knawe?'</L>
</LG>
<LG N="226" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; When &thorn;erl herd him speke so,</L>
<L>Wepen he gan wi&thorn; ey&yogh;en to,</L>
<L>&amp; fel aswon to grounde.</L>
<L>'For godes loue,' he seyd, 'merci!</L>
<L N="5">Iuel at ese now am y,</L>
<L>In sorwe &amp; care ful bounde.</L>
<L>Ful wele mi&yogh;t y knowe &thorn;e ar now:</L>
<L>In al &thorn;is warld was non<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>man</I> MS.</NOTE> bot &thorn;ou<MILESTONE N="162a:b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>O&yogh;ain Berard durst founde.</L>
<L N="10">Merci, sir, par charite:</L>
<L>&THORN;at ich haue misknowen &thorn;e,</L>
<L>Allas, allas &thorn;at stounde!'</L>
</LG>
<LG N="227" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Merci he crid on his kne:<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="9851"></L>
<L>Bo&thorn;e for sorwe &amp; for pite</L>
<L>Wepen he bigan.
<PB REF="00000576.tif" N="572"></L>
<L>He sey&yogh;e his legges brosten ich-del,</L>
<L N="5">&THORN;at whilom wer y-hosed ful wel:</L>
<L>More sorwe made neuer man.</L>
<L>Sir Gij went to him &thorn;o:</L>
<L>In his hert him was wo,</L>
<L>&amp; in his armes vp him nam.</L>
<L N="0">Atvix hem was gret diol in &thorn;at stounde:</L>
<L>Bo&thorn;e &thorn;ai fel aswon to grounde:</L>
<L>For sorwe &thorn;ai wex al wan.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="228" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; 'Tirri,' seyd sir Gij &thorn;o,</L>
<L>'&THORN;ou schalt bileue, &amp; y schal go:</L>
<L>Y biteche &thorn;e heuen king.</L>
<L>Bot ich haue a sone, y-wis,</L>
<L N="5">Y not whe&thorn;er he kni&yogh;t is,</L>
<L>For he is bot a &yogh;ongling:</L>
<L>&YOGH;if he haue ani nede to &thorn;e,</L>
<L>Help him for &thorn;e loue of me,</L>
<L>Y pray &thorn;e, in al &thorn;ing.</L>
<L N="10">Ich hope he schal be a gode kni&yogh;t:</L>
<L>Y pray Iesu ful of mi&yogh;t</L>
<L>He graunt him his blisceing.'</L>
</LG>
<LG N="229" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; 'Merci, sir,' &thorn;an seyd he,</L>
<L>'For godes loue, leue her stil wi&thorn; me:</L>
<L>Y pray &thorn;e par amour.</L>
<L>Mi treu&thorn;e y pli&yogh;t in &thorn;ine hond,</L>
<L N="5">Y schal &thorn;e sese in al mi lond,</L>
<L>Bo&thorn;e in toun &amp; tour.</L>
<L>&THORN;i man y wil be &amp; serue &thorn;e ay</L>
<L>&THORN;er while mi liif lest may,</L>
<L>To hold vp &thorn;in honour.</L>
<L N="10">&amp; &yogh;if &thorn;ou no wilt ichil wi&thorn; &thorn;e go:</L>
<L>Y-wis, ichaue wele leuer so</L>
<L>&THORN;an bileue wi&thorn; &thorn;emperour.'
<PB REF="00000578.tif" N="574"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="230" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para;<NOTE PLACE="marg">No &para; in MS.</NOTE> 'Do oway, sir Tirri: &thorn;er-of speke nou&yogh;t;<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="9887"></L>
<L>Al idel speche it is &thorn;i &thorn;ou&yogh;t.</L>
<L>Wende o&yogh;ain hom now ri&yogh;t,<MILESTONE N="162b:a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&amp; be nou&yogh;t to prout, y &thorn;e rede:</L>
<L N="5">To serue &thorn;i lord at al his nede</L>
<L>&THORN;ou proue wi&thorn; &thorn;i mi&yogh;t.</L>
<L>Desirite no man of his lond:</L>
<L>&YOGH;if &thorn;ou dost &thorn;ou gos to schond;</L>
<L>Ful siker be &thorn;ou, apli&yogh;t.</L>
<L N="10">For &yogh;iue &thorn;ou reue a man his fe</L>
<L>Godes face schaltow neuer se,</L>
<L>No com in heuen li&yogh;t.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="231" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Bi&thorn;enke &thorn;e wele of douke Berard,</L>
<L>Hou prout he was, for he was steward,</L>
<L>&amp; flemed &thorn;e out of lond,</L>
<L>&amp; he now desirite is,</L>
<L N="5">Wi&thorn; michel sorwe slayn, y-wis,</L>
<L>&amp; schamelich driuen to schond.</L>
<L>Y schal gon, &amp; &thorn;ou bileue schalt:</L>
<L>Y biteche &thorn;e god, &thorn;at al &thorn;ing walt,</L>
<L>&amp; maked wi&thorn; his hond.'</L>
<L N="10">&THORN;ai kisten hem togider &thorn;o:</L>
<L>Oliue &thorn;ai sey&yogh;en hem neuer eft mo,</L>
<L>As &thorn;e gest do&thorn; ous vnderstond.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="232" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Gret sorwe &thorn;ai made at her parting,</L>
<L>&amp; kist hem wi&thorn; ei&yogh;e wepeing.</L>
<L>&THORN;ai wenten hem bo&thorn;e atvo.</L>
<L>Als swi&thorn;e &thorn;erl Tirri went him hom,</L>
<L N="5">&THORN;re days he no ete mete non:</L>
<L>In hert him was ful wo;</L>
<L>&amp; when &thorn;e countas, sikerly,
<PB REF="00000580.tif" N="576"></L>
<L>Herd seyn it was sir Gij</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;an was went hem fro,</L>
<L N="10">Sche vpbreyd hir lord day &amp; ni&yogh;t</L>
<L>&THORN;at he no had holden him wi&thorn; streng&thorn;e &amp; mi&yogh;t,</L>
<L>&amp; laten him nou&yogh;t &thorn;ennes go.<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>gon</I> MS.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="section">
<LG N="233" TYPE="stanza">
<L>Now went Gij for&thorn; in his way<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="9909"></L>
<L>Toward &thorn;e see so swi&thorn;e he may;</L>
<L>For Tirri he siked sare.</L>
<L>Into schip he went biliue:</L>
<L N="5">Ouer &thorn;e se he gan driue;</L>
<L>Into Inglond he gan fare.</L>
<L>&THORN;e lond folk he axed anon</L>
<L>After king A&thorn;elston,</L>
<L>In what cuntre he ware.</L>
<L N="10">'At Winchester, verrament,</L>
<L>&amp; after his barouns he ha&thorn; sent<MILESTONE N="162b:b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Bo&thorn;e lasse &amp; mare.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="234" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Erls, barouns, &amp; bischopes,</L>
<L>Kni&yogh;tes, priours, &amp; abbotes</L>
<L>At Winchester &thorn;ai ben ichon,</L>
<L>&amp; han puruayd, wi&thorn;-outen lesing,</L>
<L N="5">&THORN;re days to ben in fasting,</L>
<L>To biseke god in tron</L>
<L>He sende hem<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>him</I> MS.</NOTE> &thorn;urch his swet sond</L>
<L>A man &thorn;at were douhti of hond</L>
<L>O&yogh;ain Colbrond to gon.</L>
<L N="10">&THORN;er is &thorn;e king &amp; &thorn;e barnage, y-wis,</L>
<L>For doute of her enemis,</L>
<L>&THORN;at wayt hem for to slon.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="235" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; For sir Anlaf, &thorn;e king of Danmark,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; a nost store &amp; stark</L>
<L>Into Inglond is come,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; fiften &thorn;ousend kni&yogh;tes of pris:</L>
<L N="5">Alle &thorn;is lond &thorn;ai stroyen, y-wis,</L>
<L>&amp; mani a toun<NOTE PLACE="marg">The <I>t</I> of <I>toun</I> altered from <I>d.</I></NOTE> han nome.</L>
<L>A geaunt he ha&thorn; brou&yogh;t wi&thorn; him
<PB REF="00000582.tif" N="578"></L>
<L>Out of Aufrike stout &amp; grim:</L>
<L>Colbrond hat &thorn;at gome.</L>
<L N="10">For him is al Inglond forlore</L>
<L>Bot godes help be bi-fore,</L>
<L>&THORN;at socour sende hem some.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="236" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; To &thorn;e king he ha&thorn; sent his sond</L>
<L>For to &yogh;eld him al Inglond,<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>Inglong</I> MS.</NOTE></L>
<L>&amp; &yogh;if him trowage out-ri&yogh;t;</L>
<L>&YOGH;if he no wil nou&yogh;t, finde a baroun,</L>
<L N="5">A geaunt o&thorn;er a champioun,</L>
<L>O&yogh;ain Colbrond to fi&yogh;t.</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;er-of &thorn;ai han taken a day,</L>
<L>Ac our king non finde may:</L>
<L>Erl, baroun, no kni&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="10">No squier, no seriaunt non</L>
<L>O&yogh;ain &thorn;e geaunt dar gon:</L>
<L>So grim he is of si&yogh;t.'</L>
</LG>
<LG N="237" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; &THORN;an seyd sir Gij, 'whare i[s] Herhaud,</L>
<L>&THORN;at in his time was so bald?</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;ai answerd ful swi&thorn;e,</L>
<L>'To seche Gyes sone he is fare,</L>
<L N="5">&THORN;at marchaunce hadde stollen &thorn;are:</L>
<L>For him he was vnbli&thorn;e.'</L>
<L>'&amp; where is &thorn;erl Rohaut of pris?'<MILESTONE N="163a:a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;ai answerd, 'dede he is,</L>
<L>A gode while is go si&thorn;e;</L>
<L N="10">&amp; Feliis, his douhter, is his air:</L>
<L>So gode a leuedi no so fair,</L>
<L>Y-wis, nis non oliue.'
<PB REF="00000584.tif" N="580"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="238" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Gij went to Winchester a ful gode pas,<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="9995"></L>
<L>&THORN;er &thorn;e king &thorn;at time was,</L>
<L>To held his parlement.</L>
<L>&THORN;e barouns weren in &thorn;e halle:</L>
<L N="5">&THORN;e king seyd, 'lordinges alle,</L>
<L>Mine men &yogh;e ben, verrament.</L>
<L>&THORN;erfore ich ax, wi&thorn;-outen fayl,</L>
<L>Of &thorn;is Danis folk, wil ous aseyl.</L>
<L>Ich biseche &yogh;ou wi&thorn; gode entent,</L>
<L N="10">For godes loue y pray &yogh;ou,</L>
<L>Gode conseyl &yogh;iue me now,</L>
<L>Or elles we ben al schent.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="239" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; For &thorn;e king of Danmark wi&thorn; wrong</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; his geaunt, &thorn;at is so strong,</L>
<L>He wil ous al schende.</L>
<L>&THORN;erfore ich axi &yogh;ou ichon,</L>
<L N="5">What rede is best for to don?</L>
<L>O&yogh;aines hem for to wende?</L>
<L>&YOGH;if he ouercom ous in batayle</L>
<L>He wil slen ous alle, saunfeyle,</L>
<L>&amp; strouen al our kende:</L>
<L N="10">&THORN;an schal Inglond euermo</L>
<L>Liue in &thorn;raldom &amp;<NOTE PLACE="marg">Repeated in MS.</NOTE> in wo</L>
<L>Vnto &thorn;e warldes ende.
<PB REF="00000586.tif" N="582"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="240" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; &THORN;erfore ich axi &yogh;ou now ri&yogh;t</L>
<L>&YOGH;if &yogh;e knowe our ani kni&yogh;t</L>
<L>&THORN;at is so stout &amp; bold</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;e batayle dar take an hond,</L>
<L N="5">To fi&yogh;t o&yogh;ain Col-brond:</L>
<L>Half mi lond haue he schold</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; alle &thorn;e borwes &thorn;at li&thorn; &thorn;er-to</L>
<L>To him &amp; to his aires euer-mo,</L>
<L>To haue &yogh;iue he wold.'</L>
<L N="10">[S]til seten erls &amp; barouns,</L>
<L>As men hadde schauen her crounes:</L>
<L>Nou&yogh;t on answere nold.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="241" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; 'Allas,' seyd &thorn;e king, '&thorn;at y was born:</L>
<L>Al mi ioie it is forlorn;</L>
<L>Wel wo is me oliue.<MILESTONE N="163a:b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Now in al mi lond nis no kni&yogh;t</L>
<L N="5">O&yogh;ains a geant to hold fi&yogh;t:</L>
<L>Mine hert wil breken on fiue.</L>
<L>Allas, of Warwike sir Gij,</L>
<L>Y no hadde &yogh;euen &thorn;e half mi lond frely,</L>
<L>To hold wi&thorn;outen striue!</L>
<L N="10">Wele were me &thorn;an bifalle,</L>
<L>Ac, certes, now &thorn;e Danis men alle</L>
<L>To sorwe &thorn;ai schul me driue.'
<PB REF="00000588.tif" N="584"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="242" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; When it was ni&yogh;t to bedde &thorn;ai &yogh;ede:<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="10065"></L>
<L>&THORN;e king for sorwe &amp; for drede</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; teres wett his lere.</L>
<L>Of al &thorn;at ni&yogh;t he slepe ri&yogh;t nou&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="5">Bot euer Iesu he bisou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>&THORN;at was him leue &amp; dere,</L>
<L>He schuld him sende &thorn;urch his sond</L>
<L>A man to fi&yogh;t wi&thorn; Colbrond,</L>
<L>&YOGH;if it is wille were;</L>
<L N="10">&amp; Iesus Crist ful of mi&yogh;t</L>
<L>He sent him a noble kni&yogh;t,</L>
<L>As &yogh;e may forward here.</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="section">
<LG N="243" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;er cam an angel fram heuen li&yogh;t,</L>
<L>&amp; seyd to &thorn;e king ful ri&yogh;t</L>
<L>&THORN;urch grace of godes sond.</L>
<L>He seyd, 'king A&thorn;el-ston, slepestow?</L>
<L N="5">Hider me sent &thorn;e king Iesu</L>
<L>To comfort &thorn;e to fond.</L>
<L>To-morwe go to &thorn;e nor&thorn; &yogh;ate ful swi&thorn;e:</L>
<L>A pilgrim &thorn;ou schalt se com biliue,</L>
<L>When &thorn;ou hast a while stond.
<PB REF="00000590.tif" N="586"></L>
<L N="10">Bid him for seynt Charite</L>
<L>&THORN;at he take &thorn;e batayl for &thorn;e,</L>
<L>&amp; he it wil nim on hond.'</L>
</LG>
<LG N="244" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; &THORN;an was &thorn;e king glad &amp; bli&thorn;e.<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="10087"></L>
<L>A-morwe he ros vp ful swi&thorn;e,</L>
<L>&amp; went to &thorn;e gate ful ri&yogh;t;</L>
<L>Tvay erls went wi&thorn; him &thorn;o,</L>
<L N="5">&amp; tvay bischopes dede also.</L>
<L>&THORN;e weder was fair &amp; bri&yogh;t.</L>
<L>Opon &thorn;e day about prime</L>
<L>&THORN;e king sei&yogh;e cum &thorn;e pilgrim.</L>
<L>Bi &thorn;e sclauayn he him pli&yogh;t:</L>
<L N="10">'Pilgrim,' he seyd, 'y pray &thorn;e,</L>
<L>To court wende &thorn;ou hom wi&thorn; me,<MILESTONE N="163b:a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&amp; ostel &thorn;er al ni&yogh;t.'</L>
</LG>
<LG N="245" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; 'Be stille, sir,' seyd &thorn;e pilgrim:</L>
<L>'It is nou&yogh;t &yogh;ete time to take min in,</L>
<L>Al-so god me rede.'</L>
<L>&THORN;e king him bisou&yogh;t &thorn;o,</L>
<L N="5">&amp; &thorn;e lordinges dede also:</L>
<L>To court wi&thorn; hem he &yogh;ede.</L>
<L>'Pilgrim,' qua&thorn; &thorn;e king, 'par charite,</L>
<L>&YOGH;if it be &thorn;i wil, vnderstond to me:</L>
<L>Y schal schewe &thorn;e al our nede.</L>
<L N="10">&THORN;e king of Danmark wi&thorn; gret wrong</L>
<L>&THORN;urch a geaunt, &thorn;at is so strong,</L>
<L>Wil strou al our &thorn;ede.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="246" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; &amp; whe han taken of him batayle,</L>
<L>On what maner, saunfayle,</L>
<L>Y schal now tellen &thorn;e.</L>
<L>&THORN;urch &thorn;e bodi of a kni&yogh;t,<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>akni&yogh;t</I> MS.</NOTE></L>
<L N="5">O&yogh;ains<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>O&yogh;ains</I> altered from <I>O&yogh;anss.</I></NOTE> &thorn;at geaunt to hold fi&yogh;t,</L>
<L>Schal &thorn;is lond aquite be.
<PB REF="00000592.tif" N="588"></L>
<L>&amp;, pilgrim, for him &thorn;at dyed on rode,</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;at for ous schadde his blod,</L>
<L>To bigge ous alle fre,</L>
<L N="10">Take &thorn;e batayle now on hond,</L>
<L>&amp; saue ous &thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="marg">Added above the line.</NOTE> ri&yogh;t of Inglond,</L>
<L>For seynt Charite.'</L>
</LG>
<LG N="247" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; 'Do way, leue sir,' seyd Gij.</L>
<L>'Icham an old man, a feble bodi:</L>
<L>Mi streng&thorn;e is fro me fare.'</L>
<L>&THORN;e king fel on knes to grounde,</L>
<L N="5">&amp; crid him merci in &thorn;at stounde,</L>
<L>&YOGH;if it his wille ware,</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;e barouns dede also:</L>
<L>O knes &thorn;ai fellen alle &thorn;o</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; sorwe &amp; sikeing sare.</L>
<L N="10">Sir Gij biheld &thorn;e lordinges allc,</L>
<L>&amp; whiche sorwe hem was bi-falle:</L>
<L>Sir Gij hadde of hem care.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="248" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Sir Gij tok vp &thorn;e king anon,</L>
<L>&amp; bad &thorn;e lordinges euerichon</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ai schuld vp stond,</L>
<L>&amp; seyd, 'for god<NOTE PLACE="marg">Another <I>god</I> erased in MS.</NOTE> in trinite</L>
<L N="5">&amp; for to make Inglond fre,</L>
<L>&THORN;e batayle y nim on hond.'</L>
<L>&THORN;an was &thorn;e king ful glad &amp; bli&thorn;e,<MILESTONE N="163b:b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;onked Gij a &thorn;ousend si&thorn;e<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="10127"></L>
<L>&amp; Iesu Cristes sond.</L>
<L N="10"><NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; here by mistake in MS.</NOTE>To &thorn;e king of Danmark he sent &thorn;an,</L>
<L>&amp; seyd he hadde founden a man</L>
<L>To fi&yogh;t for Inglond.
<PB REF="00000594.tif" N="590"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="249" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; &THORN;e Danismen busked hem &yogh;are</L>
<L>Into batayle for to fare:</L>
<L>To fi&yogh;t &thorn;ai war wel fawe.</L>
<L>&amp; Gij was armed swi&thorn;e wel</L>
<L N="5">In a gode hauberk of stiel</L>
<L>Wrou&yogh;t of &thorn;e best lawe.</L>
<L>An helme he hadde of michel mi&yogh;t</L>
<L>With a ce[r]cle of gold, &thorn;at schon bri&yogh;t,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; precious stones on rawe.</L>
<L N="10">In &thorn;e frunt stode a char-bukel ston:</L>
<L>As bri&yogh;t as ani sonne it schon</L>
<L>&THORN;at glemes vnder schawe.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="250" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; On &thorn;at helme stode a flour:</L>
<L>Wrou&yogh;t it was of diuers colour;</L>
<L>Mirie it was to b[i]hold.</L>
<L>Trust &amp; trewe was his ventayle,</L>
<L N="5">Gloues, &amp; gambisoun, &amp; hosen of mayle</L>
<L>As gode kni&yogh;t haue scholde.</L>
<L>Girt he was wi&thorn; a gode brond</L>
<L>Wele kerueand, bi-forn his hond</L>
<L>A targe listed wi&thorn; gold,</L>
<L N="10">Portreyd wi&thorn; &thorn;re kinges corn,</L>
<L>&THORN;at present god when he was born:</L>
<L>Mirier was non on mold.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="251" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; &amp; a swift ernand stede</L>
<L>Al wrin &thorn;ai dede him lede:</L>
<L>His tire it was ful gay.
<PB REF="00000596.tif" N="592"></L>
<L>Sir Gij opon &thorn;at stede wond</L>
<L N="5">Wi&thorn; a gode glaiue in hond,</L>
<L>&amp; priked him for&thorn; his way,</L>
<L>&amp;, when he com to &thorn;e plas</L>
<L>&THORN;er &thorn;e batayl loked was,</L>
<L>Gij li&yogh;t wi&thorn;-outen delay,</L>
<L N="10">&amp; fel on knes doun in &thorn;at stede,</L>
<L>&amp; to god he bad his bede,</L>
<L>He schuld ben his help &thorn;at day.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="252" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; 'Lord,' seyd Gij, '&thorn;at rered Lazeroun,</L>
<L>&amp; for man &thorn;oled passioun,</L>
<L>&amp; on &thorn;e rode gan blede,<MILESTONE N="164a:a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&THORN;at saued Sussan fram &thorn;e feloun,</L>
<L N="5">&amp; halp Daniel fram &thorn;e lyoun,</L>
<L>To-day wisse me &amp; rede:</L>
<L>Astow art mi&yogh;ti heuen king,</L>
<L>To-day graunt me &thorn;i blisseing,</L>
<L>&amp; help me at &thorn;is nede.</L>
<L N="10">&amp;, leuedi Mari ful of mi&yogh;t,</L>
<L>To-day saue Inglondes ri&yogh;t,</L>
<L>&amp; leue me wele to spede.'</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="section">
<LG N="253" TYPE="stanza">
<L>When &thorn;e folk was samned bi bo&thorn;e side,<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="10199"></L>
<L>&THORN;e to kinges wi&thorn; michel pride</L>
<L>After &thorn;e relikes &thorn;ai sende,</L>
<L>&THORN;e corporas, &amp; &thorn;e messe gere:</L>
<L N="5">On &thorn;e halidom &thorn;ai gun swere</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; wordes fre &amp; hende.</L>
<L>&THORN;e king of Danmarke swore furst, ywis,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Added above the line.</NOTE></L>
<L>&YOGH;if &thorn;at his geant slayn is,</L>
<L>To Danmarke he schal wende,</L>
<L N="10">&amp; neuer more Inglond cum wi&thorn;inne,</L>
<L>No non after him of his kinne</L>
<L>Vnto &thorn;e warldes ende.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="254" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Se&thorn;&thorn;en swore &thorn;e king A&thorn;elston,
<PB REF="00000598.tif" N="594"></L>
<L>&amp; seyd among hem euerichon</L>
<L>Bi god &thorn;at al may weld,</L>
<L>&YOGH;if his man &thorn;er slayn be,</L>
<L N="5">Or ouer-comen, &thorn;at men may se,</L>
<L>Recreaunt in &thorn;e feld,</L>
<L>His man he wil bicom an hond,</L>
<L>&amp; alle &thorn;e reme of Inglond</L>
<L>Of him for to helde,</L>
<L N="10">&amp; hold him for lord &amp; king,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; gold, &amp; siluer, &amp; o&thorn;er &thorn;ing</L>
<L>Gret trowage him for to &yogh;elde.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="255" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; When &thorn;ai had sworn &amp; ostage founde,</L>
<L>Colbrond stirt vp in &thorn;at stounde:</L>
<L>To fi&yogh;t he was ful felle.</L>
<L>He was so michel &amp; so vnrede,</L>
<L N="5">&THORN;at non hors mi&yogh;t him lede,</L>
<L>In gest as y &yogh;ou telle.</L>
<L>So mani he hadde of armes gere,</L>
<L>Vnne&thorn;e a cart mi&yogh;t hem bere,</L>
<L>&THORN;e Inglisse for to quelle.</L>
<L N="10">Swiche armour as he hadde opon,</L>
<L>Y-wis, no herd &yogh;e neuer non,<MILESTONE N="164a:b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Bot as it ware a fende of helle.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="256" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Of mailes was nou&yogh;t his hauberk:</L>
<L>It was al of ano&thorn;er werk,</L>
<L>&THORN;at meruail is to here.</L>
<L>Alle it were &thorn;icke splentes of stiel,</L>
<L N="5">&THORN;icke y-ioined strong &amp; wel,</L>
<L>To kepe &thorn;at fendes fere.</L>
<L>Hossen he hadde also wele y-wrou&yogh;t:</L>
<L>O&thorn;er &thorn;an sp[l]entes was it nou&yogh;t</L>
<L>Fram his fot to his swere.</L>
<L N="10">He was so michel &amp; so strong,</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;er-to so wonderliche long:</L>
<L>In &thorn;e world was non his pere.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="257" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; An helme he hadde on his heued sett,
<PB REF="00000600.tif" N="596"></L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;er-vnder a &thorn;icke bacinet.</L>
<L>Unsemly was his wede.</L>
<L>A targe he had wrou&yogh;t ful wel</L>
<L N="5">(O&thorn;er metel was &thorn;er non on bot stiel),</L>
<L>A michel &amp; vnrede.</L>
<L>Al his armour was blac as piche.</L>
<L>Wel foule he was &amp; lo&thorn;liche,</L>
<L>A grisely gom to fede.</L>
<L N="10">&THORN;e hei&yogh;e king &thorn;at sitte&thorn; on hei&yogh;e,</L>
<L>&THORN;at welt &thorn;is warld fer &amp; nei&yogh;e,</L>
<L>Made<NOTE PLACE="marg">Read <I>Make?</I></NOTE> him wel iuel to spede.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="258" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; A dart he bar in his hond kerueand,</L>
<L>&amp; his wepen about him stondand</L>
<L>Bo&thorn;e bihinde &amp; biforn,</L>
<L>Ax[e]s, &amp; gisarmes scharp y-grounde,</L>
<L N="5">&amp; glaiues for to &yogh;iue wi&thorn; wounde,</L>
<L>To hundred &amp; mo &thorn;er worn.</L>
<L>&THORN;e Inglis biheld him fast:</L>
<L>King A&thorn;elston was sore agast,</L>
<L>Inglond he schuld haue lorn;</L>
<L N="10">For, when Gij sei&yogh;e &thorn;at wicked hert,</L>
<L>He nas neuer so sore aferd<NOTE PLACE="marg">The <I>d</I> in <I>aferd</I> altered from <I>t.</I></NOTE></L>
<L>Se&thorn;&thorn;en &thorn;at he was born.</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="section">
<LG N="259" TYPE="stanza">
<L>Sir Gij lepe on his stede fot hot,<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="10253"></L>
<L>&amp; wi&thorn; a spere, &thorn;at wele bot,</L>
<L>To him he gan to ride.</L>
<L>&amp; he schet to Gij dartes &thorn;re:</L>
<L N="5">Of &thorn;e tvay &thorn;an failed he,</L>
<L>&THORN;e &thorn;ridde he lete to him glide.</L>
<L>&THORN;urch Gyes scheld it glod<MILESTONE N="164b:a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;urch his armour wi&thorn;outen abod</L>
<L>Bitvene his arme &amp; side,</L>
<L N="10">&amp; quitelich into &thorn;e feld it &yogh;ede</L>
<L>&THORN;e mountaunce of an acre brede</L>
<L>Er &thorn;at it wald abide.
<PB REF="00000602.tif" N="598"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="260" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Sir Gij to him gan to driue,</L>
<L>&THORN;at his spere brast afiue</L>
<L>On his scheld &thorn;at was so bounde.</L>
<L>&amp; Colbrond wi&thorn; michel hete</L>
<L N="5">On Gyes helme he wald haue smite,</L>
<L>&amp; failed of him &thorn;at stounde:</L>
<L>Bitvix<NOTE PLACE="marg">The <I>x</I> altered from <I>&yogh;</I>?</NOTE> &thorn;e sadel &amp; &thorn;e arsoun</L>
<L>&THORN;e strok of &thorn;at feloun glod adoun</L>
<L>Wi&thorn;outen wem or wounde,</L>
<L N="10">&THORN;at sadel &amp; hors atvo he smot,</L>
<L>Into &thorn;e er&thorn;e wele half a fot,</L>
<L>&amp; Gij fel doun to grounde.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="261" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Sir Gij astite vp stirt<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="10275"></L>
<L>As man &thorn;at was agremed in hert:</L>
<L>His stede he hadde for-lore.</L>
<L>On his helme he wald hit him &thorn;o,</L>
<L N="5">Ac he no mi&yogh;t nou&yogh;t reche &thorn;erto</L>
<L>Bi to fot &amp; &yogh;ete more,</L>
<L>Bot on his schulder &thorn;e swerd fel doun,</L>
<L>&amp; carf bo&thorn;e plates &amp; hauberioun</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; his grimli gore.</L>
<L N="10">&THORN;urch al his armour stern &amp; strong</L>
<L>He made him a wounde a spanne long,</L>
<L>&THORN;at greued him ful sore.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="262" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Colbrond was sore aschame,</L>
<L>&amp; smot Gij wi&thorn; michel grame:</L>
<L>On his helm he hit him &thorn;o,</L>
<L>&THORN;at his floures euer-ichon</L>
<L N="5">&amp; his gode charbukel ston</L>
<L>Wel euen he carf atvo:
<PB REF="00000604.tif" N="600"></L>
<L>Euen ato he smot his scheld,</L>
<L>&THORN;at it fley&yogh;e into &thorn;e feld.</L>
<L>When Gij sey&yogh;e it was so,</L>
<L N="10">&THORN;at he hadde his scheld forlorn,</L>
<L>Half bihinde &amp; half biforn,</L>
<L>In hert him was wel wo.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="263" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; &amp; Gij hent his swerd an hond,</L>
<L>&amp; heteliche smot to Colbrond:</L>
<L>As a child he stode him vnder.<MILESTONE N="164b:b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Opon &thorn;e scheld he &yogh;aue him swiche a dent,</L>
<L N="5">Bifor &thorn;e stroke &thorn;e fiir out went,</L>
<L>As it were li&yogh;t of &thorn;onder.</L>
<L>&THORN;e bondes of stiel he carf ichon,</L>
<L>&amp; in-to &thorn;e scheld a fot &amp; half on</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; his swerd he smot asunder.</L>
<L N="10">&amp; wi&thorn; &thorn;e out-braiding his swerd brast:</L>
<L>&THORN;ei Gij were &thorn;an sore agast</L>
<L>It was litel wonder.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="264" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; &THORN;o was Gij sore desmayd,</L>
<L>&amp; in his hert wel iuel y-payd,</L>
<L>For &thorn;e chaunce him was bifalle,</L>
<L>&amp; for he hadde lorn his gode brond</L>
<L N="5">&amp; his stede opon &thorn;e sond.</L>
<L>To our leuedi he gan calle.</L>
<L>&THORN;an gun &thorn;e Danis ost</L>
<L>Ich puken o&thorn;er &amp; make bost,</L>
<L>&amp; seyd among hem alle,</L>
<L N="10">'Now schal &thorn;e Inglis be slain in feld.</L>
<L>Gret trouage Inglond schal ous &yogh;eld,</L>
<L>&amp; euermore ben our &thorn;ral.'</L>
</LG>
<LG N="265" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; 'Now, sir kni&yogh;t,' seyd Colbrond,<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="10309"></L>
<L>'&THORN;ou hast lorn &thorn;i swerd in &thorn;ine hond,</L>
<L>&THORN;i scheld, &amp; eke &thorn;i stede.</L>
<L>Do now wele, &yogh;eld &thorn;e to me,</L>
<L N="5">&amp; smertlich vnarme &thorn;e:</L>
<L>Cri merci, y &thorn;e rede;
<PB REF="00000606.tif" N="602"></L>
<L>&amp;, for &thorn;ou art so douhti kni&yogh;t,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou durst o&yogh;ain me held fi&yogh;t,</L>
<L>To mi lord y schal &thorn;e lede,</L>
<L N="10">&amp; wi&thorn; him &thorn;ou schalt acorded be:</L>
<L>In his court he wil hold &thorn;e,</L>
<L>&amp; finde &thorn;at &thorn;e is nede.'</L>
</LG>
<LG N="266" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; 'Do way,' seyd Gij, '&thorn;erof speke nou&yogh;t.</L>
<L>Bi him &thorn;at al &thorn;is world ha&thorn; wrou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>Ich hadde leuer &thorn;ou were an-hong!</L>
<L>Ac &thorn;ou hast armes gret plente:</L>
<L N="5">Y-wis, &thorn;ou most lene me</L>
<L>On of &thorn;ine axes strong.'</L>
<L>Colbrond swore bi Apolin,</L>
<L>'Of al &thorn;e wepen &thorn;at is min</L>
<L>Her schaltow non afong.</L>
<L N="10">Now &thorn;ou wilt nou&yogh;t do bi mi rede,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou schalt dye on iuel dede,<MILESTONE N="165a:a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Er &thorn;at it be ou&yogh;t long.'</L>
</LG>
<LG N="267" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; When Gij herd him speke so,</L>
<L>Al sone he gan him turn &thorn;o,</L>
<L>&amp; to his wepen he ge&thorn;.</L>
<L>&THORN;er his axes stoden bi hem-selue,</L>
<L N="5">He kept on wi&thorn; a wel gode helue,</L>
<L>&THORN;e best him &thorn;ou&yogh;t he se&thorn;.</L>
<L>To Colbron[d] o&yogh;ain he ran,</L>
<L>&amp; seyd, 'traitour,' to him &thorn;an,</L>
<L>'&THORN;ou schalt han iuel de&thorn;.</L>
<L N="10">Now ich haue of &thorn;i wepen plente,</L>
<L>Where-wi&thorn; &thorn;at y may were me</L>
<L>Ri&yogh;t maugre al &thorn;in te&thorn;.'
<PB REF="00000608.tif" N="604"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="268" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Colbrond &thorn;an wi&thorn; michel hete</L>
<L>On Gyes helme he wald haue smite</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; wel gret hert tene,</L>
<L>Ac he failed of his dint,<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>de</I> erased before <I>dint</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L N="5">&amp; &thorn;e swerd into &thorn;e er&thorn;e went</L>
<L>A fot &amp; more, y wene,</L>
<L>&amp; wi&thorn; Colbrondes out-drau&yogh;t</L>
<L>Sir Gij wi&thorn; ax a strok him rau&yogh;t,</L>
<L>A wounde<NOTE PLACE="marg">The <I>o</I> of <I>wounde</I> altered from <I>a</I>.</NOTE> &thorn;at was wele sene.</L>
<L N="10">So smertliche he smot to Colbrond,</L>
<L>&THORN;at his ri&yogh;t arme wi&thorn; alle &thorn;e hond</L>
<L>He strok of quite &amp; clene.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="269" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; When Colbrond feld him so smite,</L>
<L>He was wel wro&thorn;, &yogh;e may wel wite:</L>
<L>He gan his swerd vp fond,</L>
<L>&amp; in his left hond op it haf,</L>
<L N="5">&amp; Gij in &thorn;e nek a strok him &yogh;af</L>
<L>As he [gan] stoupe for &thorn;e brond,</L>
<L>&THORN;at his heued fro &thorn;e bodi he smot,</L>
<L>&amp; into &thorn;e er&thorn;e half a fot:</L>
<L>&THORN;urch grace of godes sond</L>
<L N="10">Ded he feld &thorn;e glotoun &thorn;are.</L>
<L>&THORN;e Denis wi&thorn; sorwe &amp; care</L>
<L>&THORN;ai di&yogh;t hem out of lond.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="270" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Bli&thorn;e were &thorn;e Inglis men ichon:<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="10371"></L>
<L>Erls, barouns, &amp; king A&thorn;elston</L>
<L>&THORN;ai toke sir Gij &thorn;at tide,</L>
<L>&amp; ladde him to Winchester toun
<PB REF="00000610.tif" N="606"></L>
<L N="5">Wi&thorn; wel fair processioun</L>
<L>Ouer al bi ich a side.</L>
<L>For ioie belles &thorn;ai gun ring,<MILESTONE N="165a:b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>'Te deum laudamus' &thorn;ai gun sing,</L>
<L>&amp; play, &amp; michel pride.</L>
<L N="10">Sir Gij vnarmed him, &amp; was ful bli&thorn;e:</L>
<L>His sclauain he axed also swi&thorn;e:</L>
<L>No lenger he nold abide.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="271" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; 'Sir pilgrim,' &thorn;an seyd &thorn;e king,</L>
<L>'Whennes &thorn;ou art, wi&thorn;outen lesing,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou art douhti of dede;</L>
<L>For &thorn;urch douhtines of &thorn;in hond</L>
<L N="5">&THORN;ou hast saued al Inglond:</L>
<L>God quite &thorn;e &thorn;i mede,</L>
<L>&amp; mi treu&thorn;e y schal pli&yogh;t &thorn;e,</L>
<L>So wele y schal feffe &thorn;e</L>
<L>Bo&thorn;e in lond &amp; lede,</L>
<L N="10">&THORN;at of riches in toun &amp; tour</L>
<L>&THORN;ou schalt be man of mest honour</L>
<L>&THORN;at wone&thorn; in al mi &thorn;ede.'</L>
</LG>
<LG N="272" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; 'Sir king,' seyd &thorn;e pilgrim,</L>
<L>'Of alle &thorn;e lond &thorn;at is tin</L>
<L>Y no kepe &thorn;erof na mare;</L>
<L>Bot, now ichaue &thorn;e geant slain</L>
<L N="5">(&THORN;erof, y-wis, icham ful fain),</L>
<L>Mi way ichil for&thorn; fare.'</L>
<L>'Merci, sir,' &thorn;e king seyd &thorn;an,<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="10391"></L>
<L>'Tel me, for him &thorn;at made man</L>
<L>(For no&thorn;ing &thorn;ou ne spare),</L>
<L N="10">Tel me what &thorn;i name it be,</L>
<L>Whennes &thorn;ou art, &amp; of what cuntre,</L>
<L>Or y schal dye for care.'
<PB REF="00000612.tif" N="608"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="273" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; 'Sir king,' he seyd, 'y schal tel it &thorn;e:</L>
<L>What mi ri&yogh;t name it be</L>
<L>&THORN;ou schalt witen anon,</L>
<L>Ac &thorn;ou schalt go wi&thorn; me y-fere,</L>
<L N="5">&THORN;at noman of our conseyl here,</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;ou &amp; y alon.'</L>
<L>&THORN;e king him graunted &amp; was bli&thorn;e:</L>
<L>He comand his folk al so swi&thorn;e</L>
<L>No wi&yogh;t wi&thorn; him to gon.</L>
<L N="10">Out of &thorn;e toun &thorn;an went he</L>
<L>Wele half a mile fram &thorn;at cite,</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;er made Gij his mon.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="274" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; 'Sir king,' seyd Gij, 'vnderstond to me:</L>
<L>O &thorn;ing y schal now pray &thorn;e,</L>
<L>Astow art curteys and hende,<MILESTONE N="165b:a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&YOGH;if y mi name schal &thorn;e sayn,</L>
<L N="5">&THORN;at to noman &thorn;ou no schalt me wrayn,</L>
<L>To &thorn;is &yogh;ere com to &thorn;ende.</L>
<L>Gij of Warwike mi nam is ri&yogh;t:</L>
<L>Whilom y was &thorn;ine owhen kni&yogh;t,</L>
<L>&amp; held me for &thorn;i frende;</L>
<L N="10">&amp; now icham swiche astow may see.</L>
<L>God of heuen biteche y &thorn;e:</L>
<L>Mi way y wil for&thorn; wende.'</L>
</LG>
<LG N="275" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; When &thorn;e king sei&yogh;e, sikerly,</L>
<L>&THORN;at it was &thorn;e gode Gij</L>
<L>&THORN;at fro him wald his way,</L>
<L>On knes he fel adoun to grounde:</L>
<L N="5">'Leue sir Gij,' in &thorn;at stounde,</L>
<L>'Merci,' he gan to say.</L>
<L>'For godes loue, bi-leue wi&thorn; me,</L>
<L>&amp; mi treuthe y schal pli&yogh;t &thorn;e,</L>
<L>&THORN;at y schal &thorn;is day</L>
<L N="10">Sese &amp; &yogh;iue in-to &thorn;ine hond</L>
<L>Half<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>In half</I> MS.</NOTE> &thorn;e reme of Inglond.</L>
<L>For godes loue, say nou&yogh;t nay.'
<PB REF="00000614.tif" N="610"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="276" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; 'Sir king,' seyd Gij,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Added above the line.</NOTE> 'y nil nou&yogh;t so.</L>
<L>Haue &thorn;ou &thorn;i lond for euer-mo,</L>
<L>&amp; god y &thorn;e bi-teche.</L>
<L>Ac, &yogh;if Herhaud to &thorn;is lond com,</L>
<L N="5">&amp; bring wi&thorn; him Reynbroun, mi sone,</L>
<L>Help him, y &thorn;e biseche;</L>
<L>For &thorn;ai er bo&thorn;e hende &amp; fre.</L>
<L>On Herhaud &thorn;ou mi&yogh;t trust &thorn;e</L>
<L>To take of &thorn;ine fon wreche.'</L>
<L N="10">&THORN;ai kisten hem togider &thorn;o:</L>
<L>Al wepeand &thorn;ai wenten ato</L>
<L>Wi&thorn;outen ani more speche.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="277" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; &THORN;e king wel sore wepe for pite,</L>
<L>&amp; went him hom to his meyne</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; a mournand chere.</L>
<L>His folk o&yogh;aines him gan gon,</L>
<L N="5">&amp; asked &thorn;e king sone anon</L>
<L>What man &thorn;e pilgrim were.</L>
<L>&THORN;ai seyd, 'he is a douhti kni&yogh;t:</L>
<L>Wald Iesu ful of mi&yogh;t</L>
<L>He wald leue wi&thorn; ous here.'</L>
<L N="10">&THORN;e king seyd, 'al stille &yogh;e be:</L>
<L>What he is &yogh;our non schal wite for me,<MILESTONE N="165b:b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>I-wis, of al &thorn;is &yogh;ere.'</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="section">
<LG N="278" TYPE="stanza">
<L>Sir Gij went in his way for&thorn; ri&yogh;t,<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="10475"></L>
<L>Oft he &thorn;onked god almi&yogh;t</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;e geaunt was slawe.</L>
<L>To Warwike he went, to &thorn;at cite</L>
<L N="5">&THORN;er he was lord of &thorn;at cuntre</L>
<L>To hold wi&thorn; ri&yogh;t lawe.</L>
<L>He nas knowen &thorn;er of no man,</L>
<L>When he to &thorn;e castel &yogh;ates cam:</L>
<L>&THORN;erof he was ful fawe.</L>
<L N="10">Among &thorn;e pouer men he him dede</L>
<L>&THORN;er &thorn;ai weren vp in a stede,</L>
<L>&amp; sett him on a rawe.
<PB REF="00000615.tif" N="611"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="279" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; &amp; Feliis &thorn;e countas was &thorn;er &thorn;an:</L>
<L>In &thorn;is warld was non better wiman,</L>
<L>In gest as-so we rede;</L>
<L>For &thorn;ritten pouer men &amp; &yogh;ete mo</L>
<L N="5">For hir lordes loue sche loued so</L>
<L>Ich day sche gan fede,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; &thorn;an god &amp; our leuedi</L>
<L>Schuld saue hir lord sir Gij,</L>
<L>&amp; help him at his nede.</L>
<L N="10">Sche no stint noi&thorn;er day no ni&yogh;t,</L>
<L>For him sche bisou&yogh;t god almi&yogh;t</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; bedes &amp; almos dede.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="280" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; On a day &thorn;e leuedi went to mete,</L>
<L>&amp; bad men schuld biforn hir fete</L>
<L>Hir pouer men al biden,</L>
<L>&amp; men brou&yogh;t hem euerichon,</L>
<L N="5">&amp; Gij of Warwike was &thorn;at on</L>
<L>Of &thorn;o ich &thorn;ritten.</L>
<L>In his hert he hadde gret care,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he schuld be knawen &thorn;are</L>
<L>Of hem &thorn;at hadde him sen,</L>
<L N="10">Ac &thorn;er was non so wise of si&yogh;t</L>
<L>&THORN;at him &thorn;er knowe mi&yogh;t:</L>
<L>So misais he was &amp; lene.</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="section">
<LG N="281" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;e leuedi biheld him inliche,</L>
<L>Hou mesays he was, sikerliche.</L>
<L>Curteys sche was &amp; hende:</L>
<L>Of euerich mete, of euerich d[r]ing</L>
<L N="5">&THORN;at sche ete of herself, wi&thorn;outen lesing,</L>
<L>Sche was him ful mende;</L>
<L>Of hir bere &amp; of hir wine<MILESTONE N="166a:a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>In hir gold coupe afine</L>
<L>Oft sche gan him sende,</L>
<L N="10">&amp; bad him ich day com he schold:</L>
<L>Mete &amp; drink sche finde him wold</L>
<L>Vnto his liues ende.
<PB REF="00000616.tif" N="612"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="282" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Sir [Gij] &thorn;onked &thorn;at leuedi oft,</L>
<L>Bot alle ano&thorn;er was his &thorn;ou&yogh;t</L>
<L>&THORN;an he wald to hir say.</L>
<L>When &thorn;e grace were y-seyd,<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="10521"></L>
<L N="5">&amp; &thorn;e bordes adoun layd,</L>
<L>Out of toun he went his way.</L>
<L>Into a forest wenden he gan</L>
<L>To an hermite he knewe er &thorn;an,</L>
<L>To speke him &yogh;if he may.</L>
<L N="10">&amp;, when he &thorn;ider comen was,</L>
<L>&THORN;e gode hermite &thorn;urch godes grace</L>
<L>Was dede &amp; loken in clay.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="283" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; &THORN;an &thorn;ou&yogh;t sir Gij anon</L>
<L>&THORN;at wald he neuer &thorn;ennes gon</L>
<L>&THORN;er whiles he war oliue.</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; a prest he spac of &thorn;at cuntray</L>
<L N="5">&THORN;at dede him seruise ich day,</L>
<L>&amp; of his sinnes gan schriue.</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; him he hadde &thorn;er a page</L>
<L>&THORN;at serued him in &thorn;at hermitage</L>
<L>Wi&thorn;outen chest &amp; striue.</L>
<L N="10">No lenger was he liues &thorn;ere</L>
<L>Bot ni&yogh;en mone&thorn;es of a &yogh;ere,</L>
<L>As &yogh;e may listen &amp; li&thorn;e.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="284" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; In slepe as Gij lay ani&yogh;t,</L>
<L>God sent an angel bri&yogh;t</L>
<L>Fram heuen to him &thorn;are.</L>
<L>'Gij,' seyd &thorn;e angel, 'slepestow?</L>
<L N="5">Hider me sent &thorn;e king Iesu</L>
<L>To bid &thorn;e make &thorn;e &yogh;are;</L>
<L>For bi &thorn;e ei&yogh;tenday at morwe</L>
<L>He schal deliuer &thorn;e out of &thorn;i sorwe,</L>
<L>Out of &thorn;is warld to fare.</L>
<L N="10">To heuen &thorn;ou schalt com him to,</L>
<L>&amp; liue wi&thorn; ous euer-mo</L>
<L>In ioie wi&thorn;outen care.'
<PB REF="00000618.tif" N="614"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="285" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; When Gij was waked of &thorn;at drem,</L>
<L>Of an angel he sei&yogh;e a glem:</L>
<L>'What artow?' &thorn;an seyd he.<MILESTONE N="166a:b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&THORN;e angel answerd, 'fram heuen y cam:</L>
<L N="5">Mi&yogh;hel is mi ri&yogh;t nam.</L>
<L>God sent me to &thorn;e</L>
<L>To bid &thorn;e make &thorn;e redi way:</L>
<L>Bi &thorn;e ei&yogh;tenday &thorn;ou schalt day,</L>
<L>Wel siker mau&yogh;tow be.</L>
<L N="10">&amp; y schal feche &thorn;i soule ful euen,</L>
<L>&amp; bere it to &thorn;e &thorn;lis of heuen</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; grete solempnete.'</L>
</LG>
<LG N="286" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; &THORN;e angel go&thorn; for&thorn;, &amp; Gij bileft stille:</L>
<L>His bedes he bad wi&thorn; gode wille</L>
<L>To Iesu heuen king,</L>
<L>&amp; when his term was nere gon<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="10577"></L>
<L N="5">His knaue he cleped to him anon,</L>
<L>&amp; seyd, wi&thorn;outen lesing,</L>
<L>'Sone,' he seyd, 'y pray now &thorn;e,</L>
<L>Go to Warwike &thorn;at cite</L>
<L>Wi&thorn;-outen more duelling,</L>
<L N="10">&amp; when &thorn;ou comest &thorn;er, y &thorn;e biseche,</L>
<L>Gret wele &thorn;e countas wi&thorn; &thorn;i speche,</L>
<L>&amp; take hir &thorn;is gold ring.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="287" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; &amp; say &thorn;e pilgrim hat hir biforn,</L>
<L>&THORN;at hir mete was to born,</L>
<L>On &thorn;e pouer mannes rawe,</L>
<L>Gret hir wele in al &thorn;ing,</L>
<L N="5">&amp; sende to hir &thorn;is gold ring,</L>
<L>&YOGH;if &thorn;at sche wil it knawe.</L>
<L>Als son as sche ha&thorn; &thorn;er-of a si&yogh;t,</L>
<L>Sche wil it knawe anon ri&yogh;t,</L>
<L>&amp; be &thorn;erof ful fawe.</L>
<L N="10">&THORN;an wil sche ax ware y be:</L>
<L>Leue sone, for loue of me</L>
<L>&THORN;e so&thorn;e to hir &thorn;ou schawe,
<PB REF="00000620.tif" N="616"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="288" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; &amp; say icham for godes loue</L>
<L>In &thorn;e forest hermite bicome,</L>
<L>Mine sinnes for to bete,</L>
<L>&amp; bid hir for &thorn;e loue of me</L>
<L N="5">&THORN;at sche com hider wi&thorn; &thorn;e:</L>
<L>For no &thorn;ing sche no lete.</L>
<L>&amp; when &yogh;e com &yogh;e finde me dede:</L>
<L>Do me neuer hennes lede,</L>
<L>Bot graue me here in grete.</L>
<L N="10">&amp; after sche schal dye, y-wis,</L>
<L>&amp; com to me in-to heuen blis,<MILESTONE N="166b:a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&THORN;er ioies her ful swete.'</L>
</LG>
<LG N="289" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; &THORN;e knaue went for&thorn; anon,</L>
<L>In-to Warwike he gan gon</L>
<L>Bifor &thorn;at leuedi fre,</L>
<L>&amp;, when he hadde &thorn;at leuedi founde,</L>
<L N="5">On knes he fel adoun to grounde,</L>
<L>&amp; seyd, 'listen to me:</L>
<L>&THORN;e pilgrim &thorn;at ete &thorn;e biforn,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;i mete was to born,</L>
<L>An hermite now is he.</L>
<L N="10">He grete&thorn; &thorn;e wele in al &thorn;ing,</L>
<L>&amp; sent &thorn;e &thorn;is gold ring</L>
<L>In sum tokening to be.'</L>
</LG>
<LG N="290" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; &THORN;e leuedi tok &thorn;at ring anhond,</L>
<L>&amp; loked &thorn;eron &amp; gan wi&thorn;stond,</L>
<L>&THORN;e letters for to rede.</L>
<L>'Ow, certes,' qua&thorn; &thorn;e leuedi,</L>
<L N="5">'&THORN;is ring y &yogh;af mi lord sir Gij,</L>
<L>When he fro me &yogh;ede.'
<PB REF="00000622.tif" N="618"></L>
<L>For sorwe sche fel aswon, y-wis,</L>
<L>&amp; when &thorn;at sche arisen is</L>
<L>To &thorn;e knaue sche gan spede.</L>
<L N="10">'Leue sone,' sche<NOTE PLACE="marg">indistinct.</NOTE> seyd, 'y pray &thorn;e,</L>
<L>Wher is &thorn;at pilgrim? telle &thorn;ou me,</L>
<L>&amp; gold schal be &thorn;i mede.'</L>
</LG>
<LG N="291" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; 'Madame,' seyd &thorn;e knaue ful skete,</L>
<L>'In &thorn;e forest ichim lete:</L>
<L>Ri&yogh;t now y com him fro.</L>
<L>He is ner ded in &thorn;e hermitage:</L>
<L N="5">On his halue y make &thorn;e message;</L>
<L>Y-wis, he bad me so,</L>
<L>&amp; bad &thorn;ou schust to him come</L>
<L>For &thorn;at ich trewe loue</L>
<L>&THORN;at was bitvene &yogh;ou tvo.</L>
<L N="10">Do him neuer lede oway,</L>
<L>Bot biri him ri&yogh;t &thorn;er in clay.</L>
<L>Oliue sestow him no mo.'</L>
</LG>
<LG N="292" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; &THORN;e leuedi was glad of &thorn;at tiding,<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="10641"></L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;onked Iesu heuen king,</L>
<L>&amp; was in hert ful bli&thorn;e</L>
<L>&THORN;at<NOTE PLACE="marg">The <I>t</I> indistinct.</NOTE> sche schuld sen hir lord sir Gij;</L>
<L N="5">Ac for o &thorn;ing sche was sori,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he schuld dye so swi&thorn;e.</L>
<L>&THORN;ai made hem redi for to wende<MILESTONE N="166b:b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Wi&thorn; kni&yogh;tes &amp; wi&thorn; leuedis hende:</L>
<L>On a mule &thorn;ai sett hir si&thorn;e,</L>
<L N="10">&amp; wi&thorn; al &thorn;e best of &thorn;at cite</L>
<L>To &thorn;ermitage went sche,<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>s</I> underdotted before <I>sche.</I></NOTE></L>
<L>As &yogh;e may listen &amp; li&thorn;e.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="293" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; To &thorn;ermitage when &thorn;ai com,</L>
<L>&THORN;er &thorn;ai li&yogh;t al &amp; some,</L>
<L>&amp; in sche went wel euen.</L>
<L>When &thorn;at sche sei&yogh;e hir lord sir Gij,</L>
<L N="5">Sche wept &amp; made doleful cri</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; a ful reweful steuen.
<PB REF="00000624.tif" N="620"></L>
<L>Sir Gij loked on hir &thorn;are:</L>
<L>His soule fram &thorn;e bodi gan fare.</L>
<L>A &thorn;ousand angels &amp; seuen</L>
<L N="10">Vnder-fenge &thorn;e soule of Gij,</L>
<L>&amp; bar it wi&thorn; gret molodi</L>
<L>Into &thorn;e blis of heuen.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="294" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; &THORN;an was &thorn;at leuedi ful of care,<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="10675"></L>
<L>For hir lord was fram hir fare:</L>
<L>'Allas' it was hir song.</L>
<L>Sche kist his mou&thorn;e, his chin also,</L>
<L N="5">&amp; wepe wi&thorn; hir ei&yogh;en to,</L>
<L>&amp; hir hondes sche wrong.</L>
<L>Gret honour dede our lord for Gij:</L>
<L>A swete bra&thorn;e com fram his bodi,</L>
<L>&THORN;at last &thorn;at day so long,</L>
<L N="10">&THORN;at in &thorn;is world spices alle</L>
<L>No mi&yogh;t cast a swetter smalle</L>
<L>As &thorn;en was hem among.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="295" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; &THORN;e leudy astite dede send hir sond</L>
<L>After bischopes, abotes of &thorn;e lond,</L>
<L>&THORN;e best &thorn;at mi&yogh;t be founde,</L>
<L>&amp;, when &thorn;ider was com &thorn;at fair ferred,</L>
<L N="5">To Warwike &thorn;ai wald him lede,</L>
<L>As lord of michel mounde.</L>
<L>Bot al &thorn;e folk &thorn;at &thorn;er was
<PB REF="00000626.tif" N="622"></L>
<L>No mi&yogh;t him stir of &thorn;at plas</L>
<L>&THORN;er he lay on &thorn;e grounde.</L>
<L N="10">An hundred men about him were,</L>
<L>No mi&yogh;t him nou&yogh;t &thorn;ennes bere</L>
<L>For heuihed &thorn;at stounde.
<PB REF="00000628.tif" N="624"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="296" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; &THORN;an seyd &thorn;e leuedi, 'lete him be stille,</L>
<L>Neuer more remoun him y nille,</L>
<L>No do him hennes lede.<MILESTONE N="167a:a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>He sent me bode wi&thorn; his page</L>
<L N="5">To biri him in &thorn;is hermitage</L>
<L>Simpliche wi&thorn;outen prede.'</L>
<L>&THORN;ay tok a &thorn;rou&yogh; of marbel ston,</L>
<L>&amp; leyd his bodi &thorn;er-in anon</L>
<L>Atird in kni&yogh;tes wede.</L>
<L N="10">Fair seruise &thorn;an was &thorn;are</L>
<L>Of bischopes, abbotes &thorn;at &thorn;er ware,</L>
<L>&amp; clerkes to sing &amp; rede.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="297" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; When &thorn;ai hadde birid his bodi, anon<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="10713"></L>
<L>&THORN;e gret lordinges euerichon</L>
<L>Hom &thorn;ai gun wende,</L>
<L>Ac &thorn;e leuedi left stille &thorn;are:</L>
<L N="5">Sche nold neuer &thorn;ennes fare;</L>
<L>Sche kidde &thorn;at sche was kende.</L>
<L>Sche liued no lenger, so&thorn;e to say,<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>day</I> MS.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000630.tif" N="626"></L>
<L>Bot ri&yogh;t on &thorn;e fiftenday</L>
<L>Sche dyed &thorn;at leuedi hende,</L>
<L N="10">&amp; was birid hir lord by;</L>
<L>&amp; now &thorn;ai er togider in compeynie</L>
<L>In ioie &thorn;at neuer schal ende.</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="section">
<LG N="298" TYPE="stanza">
<L>When sir Tirri herd telle &thorn;is,<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="10749"></L>
<L>&THORN;at Gij, his fere, ded is,</L>
<L>&amp; birid in &thorn;e clay,</L>
<L>He com to &thorn;is<NOTE PLACE="marg">The <I>s</I> added above the line.</NOTE> lond, wi&thorn;-outen lesing,</L>
<L N="5">&amp; bisou&yogh;t A&thorn;elston &thorn;e king</L>
<L>His bodi to leden oway.</L>
<L>He it graunted him ful &yogh;are,
<PB REF="00000632.tif" N="628"></L>
<L>Into Lorain wi&thorn; him gan fare,</L>
<L>Into his owhen cuntray.</L>
<L N="10">An abbay he lete make &thorn;o</L>
<L>For to sing for hem to</L>
<L>Euermore til domesday.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="299" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Now haue &yogh;e herd, lordinges, of Gij,<MILESTONE UNIT="C line" N="10725"></L>
<L>&THORN;at in his time was so hardi,</L>
<L>&amp; holden hende &amp; fre,</L>
<L>&amp; euer he loued treu&thorn;e &amp; ri&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="5">&amp; serued god wi&thorn; al his mi&yogh;t,</L>
<L>&THORN;at sit in trinite,</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;er-fore at his ending day</L>
<L>He went to &thorn;e ioie &thorn;at laste&thorn; ay,</L>
<L>&amp; euer-more schal be.</L>
<L N="10">Now god leue ous to liue so,</L>
<L>&THORN;at we may &thorn;at<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>&thorn;ai</I> MS.</NOTE> ioie com to.<MILESTONE N="167a:b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Amen, par charite.</L>
</LG>
<TRAILER>Explicit.</TRAILER>


</DIV2>
</DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="version"><PB REF="00000007.tif" N="3">
<HEAD>Guye of Warrewik. [<I>Caius MS.</I>, 107, <I>page</I> 1.]</HEAD>
<DIV2 TYPE="section">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>SYTh THE TYME &thorn;AT CRYST IHESU,</L>
<L>Thorough hys grace &amp; vertu,</L>
<L>Was in &thorn;is world bore</L>
<L>Of a mayd withowt hore,</L>
<L N="5">And &thorn;e world crystendom</L>
<L>Among mankynd first becom,</L>
<L>Many aduentures hath be wrou&yogh;t</L>
<L>&THORN;at all men knoweth nou&yogh;t.</L>
<L>Therfore m&emacr;n shull herken blythe,</L>
<L N="10">And it vndirstonde right swythe,</L>
<L>For they that were borne or wee</L>
<L>Fayre aduenturis hadden they;</L>
<L>For euere they louyd sothfastenesse,</L>
<L>Faith with trewthe and stedfastnesse.</L>
<L N="15">Therfore schulde man with gladde chere</L>
<L>Lerne goodnesse, vndirstonde, and here:</L>
<L>Who myke it hereth and vndirstondeth it</L>
<L>By resoun he shulde bee wyse of witte;</L>
<L>And y it holde a fayre mastrye,</L>
<L N="20">To occupye wisedome and leue folye.</L>
<L>For why as of an Erle j shall yow telle,</L>
<L>How of hym it beefelle;</L>
<L>And of hys stewarde, withoute lesynge,</L>
<L>And of the stewarde sone, a fayre yonge thynge,</L>
<L N="25">That gentil was and fayre bee-seen,</L>
<L>And how he loued a mayden sheen,
<PB REF="00000009.tif" N="5"></L>
<L>The Erles doughter, that was so bryghte,</L>
<L>And how he spoused that swete wyghte,</L>
<L>And how that he reynbroun beegate&mdash;</L>
<L N="30">All y kanne tell yow that&mdash;</L>
<L>And how he wente into wildernesse:<MILESTONE UNIT="Caius MS. 107 page" N="2"></L>
<L>All y canne tell yow as it ys.</L>
<L>A wyseman it vnto vs seyd</L>
<L>That it wrote and in ryme it leyd.</L>
<L N="35">I woll it not any longer concell,</L>
<L>But open the sentence as ye may fele.</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="section">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>IN ENGLONDE an Erle was wonnynge</L>
<L>In Warrewyke Citee, ryght as I fynde:</L>
<L>Ryche he was and grete of myght,</L>
<L N="40">Erle he was, and a full stronge knygnt,</L>
<L>Riche of gold and of syluer bothe,</L>
<L>Of clothes of gold and vessell, withoute othe,</L>
<L>Of stronge castellis and riche Citees:</L>
<L>Thorugh all Englond preised he was.</L>
<L N="45">In all Englond ne was ther none</L>
<L>That durste in wrath ayenste hym goon.</L>
<L>Good knyghtis he loued y-wys,</L>
<L>And freely he gaue them of hys,</L>
<L>Therfore welbelouyd he was,</L>
<L N="50">And grettly doubted in euery place.</L>
<L>Erle he was of grete price:</L>
<L>All that contree tho was hys;</L>
<L>Of oxenford and all that contrey</L>
<L>He was gouernoure at that day;</L>
<L N="55">Of Bokyngham, and of all that shyre,</L>
<L>He was klepyd both lord and syre.</L>
<L>That Erle Rohaude hyght,</L>
<L>Baroun he was of grete myght.</L>
<L>A doughter he had of hys wyue,</L>
<L N="60">Hyr grete beaute y can not dyscryue:</L>
<L>For the fairest men chesen hir y-wys.<MILESTONE UNIT="Caius MS. 107 page" N="3"></L>
<L>That y you telle, sothe it is.
<PB REF="00000011.tif" N="7"></L>
<L>Of hir beaute yet a litell wighte:</L>
<L>With a faire visage louely in sighte,</L>
<L N="65">Hir skynne was white of brighte coloure;</L>
<L>Bodied wele and of grete valour;</L>
<L>Large tresses, and wele bee-comyng,</L>
<L>Browes bente and nose well sittyng;</L>
<L>The mouthe so wele sittyng ywys,</L>
<L N="70">To kisse it ofte it was grete blys;</L>
<L>With grey eyen and nekke white,</L>
<L>Hir to see it was grete delite.</L>
<L>Hir bodye well sette and shaply;</L>
<L>By thoo daies ther was n&omacr;&omacr;n suche truely.</L>
<L N="75">Gentil she was and as demure</L>
<L>As girfauk, or fawkon to lure,</L>
<L>That oute of muwe were drawe;</L>
<L>So faire was noon, in sothe sawe.</L>
<L>She was therto curteys and free ywys,</L>
<L N="80">And in the .vii. artes well lerned, withoute mys.</L>
<L>All the .vii. artis she kouthe well,</L>
<L>Noon better that euere man herde tell.</L>
<L>Hir maisters were thider come</L>
<L>Oute of Tholouse all and some;</L>
<L N="85">White and hoore all they were,</L>
<L>Bisy they were that mayden to lere;</L>
<L>And they hir lerned of astronomye,</L>
<L>Of Ars-meotrik, and of geometrye.</L>
<L>Of Sophestrie she was also witty,</L>
<L N="90">Of Rethoric, and of other clergye;</L>
<L>Lerned she was in musyke;<MILESTONE UNIT="Caius MS. 107 page" N="4"></L>
<L>Of clergie was hir noon like.</L>
<L>She was a woman of grete corage,</L>
<L>Wise and faire and of gaye parage.</L>
<L N="95">To haue hir to wif he did hir sende</L>
<L>Erles, Dukes, fro the worldes ende;</L>
<L>And noon of theim haue she wolde,</L>
<L>For that she was so faire holde.
<PB REF="00000013.tif" N="9"></L>
<L>Felice .la bele hir name is:</L>
<L N="100">Moche she was belouid ywis;</L>
<L>Of all faire she was the floure,</L>
<L>Noon so faire in halle nor boure</L>
<L>As she was; who that soughte</L>
<L>So faire to fynde, for noughte he wroughte:</L>
<L N="105">He that all hir beaute write wolde,</L>
<L>To longe tarying make he sholde.</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="section">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>NOWE WE shull leue of hir here,</L>
<L>And telle you forthe of our matiere.</L>
<L>Speke we schull of the Stywarde:</L>
<L N="110">Well true he was, and highte Sywarde.</L>
<L>This Syward was slighe and wise,</L>
<L>Riche of kynde, and of grete prise:</L>
<L>In his tyme noon better was,</L>
<L>For of grete worship was noon in his caas.</L>
<L N="115">Of armes he had been chief on grounde,</L>
<L>And therof preised in many a londe;</L>
<L>For that he wolde preysed bee,</L>
<L>He did him bee knowen in many a contree.</L>
<L>In Walyngforde he was borne.</L>
<L N="120">All that Contree to him was sworne.</L>
<L>A swiche noble man he was,<MILESTONE UNIT="Caius MS. 107 page" N="5"></L>
<L>On this half the see noon suche was,</L>
<L>That serued his lorde so truely,</L>
<L>And in all thinges so worshipfully.</L>
<L N="125">Ther was noon Erle in all that londe</L>
<L>That his lorde durste withstonde,</L>
<L>Bot he with loue it amended anoone,</L>
<L>Hastely he<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. we.</NOTE> wolde vpon him goone,</L>
<L>And with strengthe hym haue wolde,</L>
<L N="130">Though he therfor in to Scotlonde sholde.</L>
<L>All his lordes londe well and truely</L>
<L>He maynteyned it full worshipfully;</L>
<L>That noon was so hardy a man,</L>
<L>That with wronge durste come than.
<PB REF="00000015.tif" N="11"></L>
<L N="135">Fastenned he had suche a pees,</L>
<L>That neuere sithe noon better was:</L>
<L>Though men did bere an hundred pounde,</L>
<L>Vpon him, of penyes rounde,</L>
<L>There shulde not bee founde in all the londe</L>
<L N="140">A theef that him wolde hurte ne shonde,</L>
<L>Nor take fro him the worthe of a sloo:</L>
<L>So good pees there was thoo.</L>
<L>That same Stywarde had a sone</L>
<L>Wise and curteys at Frome;</L>
<L N="145">All men him did loue sothely,</L>
<L>Ther was noon that him wolde shonye.</L>
<L>To All men yiftes yiue he wolde,</L>
<L>Therfore so curteis he was holde.</L>
<L>The Erle Rohaud he serued thoo,</L>
<L N="150">His kynde Lorde, so mote y goo.</L>
<L>The Erle him loued hertly and dere,<MILESTONE UNIT="Caius MS. 107 page" N="6"></L>
<L>Ouer all other that with him were.</L>
<L>Of his coupe he him serue Didde,</L>
<L>And priuyest with him in euery stede:</L>
<L N="155">The Erle Rohaud mikel him worshipped,</L>
<L>And for his fader loue thoo farther him cleped.</L>
<L>Guye of Warrewik his name was,</L>
<L>In all the courte n&omacr;&omacr;n more honoured nas:</L>
<L>Of knyghtes and of grete lordinges,</L>
<L N="160">Of more and lasse, in all thinges.</L>
<L>Mikell he was, and of grete mighte,</L>
<L>And fairest of all other be sighte:</L>
<L>All him behelde wondirly,</L>
<L>His fairenesse was so grete truly;</L>
<L N="165">So many goodnesses in him were:</L>
<L>All him preised that were there.</L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L>Guye a foster fader hadde,</L>
<L N="170">That him lerned and also redde
<PB REF="00000017.tif" N="13"></L>
<L>Of wode, of Ryuer, of all game:</L>
<L>Heraude of Arderne was his name.</L>
<L>He was curteys, and well taughte,</L>
<L>Guye he lerned and forgate him naughte;</L>
<L N="175">Mikell he kouthe of haukes and houndes,</L>
<L>Of Ostours, of Faukons of grete moundes.</L>
<L>All that wolde of him oughte craue,</L>
<L>With good wille they shulde it haue.</L>
<L>To parsons and to pouer knyghtes</L>
<L N="180">Ofte he wolde yiue riche yiftes;</L>
<L>And to other ofte yiue he wolde</L>
<L>Palfrey or stede, siluer and golde,</L>
<L>Euery man after his good dede<MILESTONE UNIT="Caius MS. 107 page" N="7"></L>
<L>Of Guye vnderfangeth his mede.</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="section">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="185">ON WITSONDAYE called Pentecoste</L>
<L>The Erle helde a grete feste</L>
<L>In Warrewik, that good Citee,</L>
<L>As it euer was wonte to bee.</L>
<L>There were Erles, barons, and knyghtes,</L>
<L N="190">And many a man of grete myghtes;</L>
<L>Ladies and maydens of grete renown,</L>
<L>The grettest desired ther' to bee bown.</L>
<L>Many a mayde there chese hir loue anone</L>
<L>Of knyghtes that thider were come,</L>
<L N="195">And the knyghtes also their' lemans there</L>
<L>Of the maidens that there were.</L>
<L>Whan they fro chirche were come,</L>
<L>In to the halle they yode full sone.</L>
<L>Whan the Erle to the mete sette was,</L>
<L N="200">Guye stode before him in that plaas,</L>
<L>He that was Sywardes sone,</L>
<L>To whom the Erle grete loue had nome.</L>
<L>The Erle cleped to him Guye,</L>
<L>To him gan sey and commaunded on highe,</L>
<L N="205">That he in to the chambre wente</L>
<L>And grete well his doughter that was so gente;
<PB REF="00000019.tif" N="15"></L>
<L>And that he shulde at mete that Daie</L>
<L>Bee willyng to serue that faire may&emacr;.</L>
<L>'Sir,' seide Guy full freely,</L>
<L N="210">'I doo youre heste full blithely.'</L>
<L>With a silken kirtell began him shrede,</L>
<L>And in to the Chambre than he yede.</L>
<L>The kirtell so well sitting it was,<MILESTONE UNIT="Caius MS. 107 page" N="8"></L>
<L>It to amende noo nede it has;</L>
<L N="215">Guy was so well shape and gentille,</L>
<L>The maidens him behelde with good wille.</L>
<L>On knees before Felice he him sette,</L>
<L>And on hir fader behalue he hir grette,</L>
<L>And seide how he was thider sentte</L>
<L N="220">To serue hir to hir talentte.</L>
<L>Felice answerd ayene to Guye,</L>
<L>'Beaux amye, moult gramercye.'</L>
<L>And than she asked him in that place</L>
<L>Where that he borne was.</L>
<L N="225">And Guye seide, 'my fader is called Sywarde,</L>
<L>That is youre faders Stywarde;</L>
<L>Many a daye he hath me with him holde,</L>
<L>And forthe me bredde, god him foryelde!'</L>
<L>'Bee ye,' she seide, 'Sywardes sone,</L>
<L N="230">That all goodnesse hath in wone?'</L>
<L>Guye stode stille and spake noughte.</L>
<L>With that the water was forth broughte:</L>
<L>She did wesshe and wente to mete anone</L>
<L>And so did knyght, squier, and grome.</L>
<L N="235">All his mighte he did that daie</L>
<L>To serue well that faire maye.</L>
<L>Wele to serue he did his myghte</L>
<L>Moo than thirty maidens brighte;</L>
<L>That all they anamoured were</L>
<L N="240">On Guye for his faire chere.</L>
<L>And he therof rekked noughte,</L>
<L>For vpon another' was his thoughte:
<PB REF="00000021.tif" N="17"></L>
<L>On Felice with the nebbe so brighte<MILESTONE UNIT="Caius MS. 107 page" N="9"></L>
<L>He kaste his loue with all his mighte;</L>
<L N="245">That he ne wiste what to doo,</L>
<L>Hir loue werked him suche woo.</L>
<L>He wepte with mayne slilye,</L>
<L>And mourned in hym self softelye,</L>
<L>That he euere shulde see</L>
<L N="250">Hir brighte rodye, hir faire blee.</L>
<L>Moche wonder he hath ywis,</L>
<L>That she so faire a creatur is.</L>
<L>He durste not to hir his loue kithe,</L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L>Bot to his chambre wente right swithe:</L>
<L>Withoute any leue takyng of Felice thoo,</L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L N="260">Oute of his chambre he did goo.</L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L>Than asked of him his meyne,</L>
<L>Why that he so heuy wolde bee.</L>
<L N="265">Guye answerd theim anone,</L>
<L>Seying that sikenesse is come him vpon,</L>
<L>Wherthurgh his lif he weneth to forgoo,</L>
<L>And neuere helth to haue of his woo.</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="section">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>IN THE COURTE mikel bemened is Guy:</L>
<L N="270">For him was many a man sory;</L>
<L>For he was wonned to serue theim wele,</L>
<L>And to theim yiue many a ieowele.</L>
<L>Nowe is Guy in grete tempeste,</L>
<L>Sorowe he maketh with the moste;</L>
<L N="275">For loue that he had to the maye</L>
<L>His sorowe encressed nyghte and daie.</L>
<L>Nowe is Guye so euyll bee stadde,</L>
<L>Hym self he helde for a man madde.
<PB REF="00000023.tif" N="19"></L>
<L>For the sorowe that bim befallen is,<MILESTONE UNIT="Caius MS. 107 page" N="10"></L>
<L N="280">Ofte he bemeneth him self y-wis:</L>
<L>'In wicked peyne sey y may,</L>
<L>That y ne may beholde hir eyen gray,</L>
<L>Hir graye eyen, hir nebbe so shene;</L>
<L>For hir my lif is in a wene.</L>
<L N="285">To hir y shall telle my thoughte,</L>
<L>For whom y am in this sorowe broughte.</L>
<L>What so euere come to me good or ylle,</L>
<L>I woll it noo lenger concele for to spille.</L>
<L>Bot streight to hir woll y goo,</L>
<L N="290">And in hir mercy y shall me doo;</L>
<L>And if she woll, she may me slee,</L>
<L>And hir wille doo with me.</L>
<L>Yf I my sorowe hir doo not telle,</L>
<L>Allas, wrecche, how shall y duelle?</L>
<L N="295">Allas, wrecche, that me is woo!</L>
<L>Ine wote what y may doo:</L>
<L>For my lordys Doughter she is,</L>
<L>And y his norry ywis;</L>
<L>Therfor the more beholding to him y bee,</L>
<L N="300">And neuere noo-wher his harme to see.</L>
<L>If y hir loued and wite might he,</L>
<L>And therwith he may take me,</L>
<L>Brenne he me wolde, or the hede of smyte,</L>
<L>Or highe hange for that dispite,</L>
<L N="305">Or all to-hewe with swerdes kene,</L>
<L>And y him did suche a tene.</L>
<L>Allas, y wrecche! what may y doo?</L>
<L>I loue hir that is my foo.'</L>
<L>Nowe is Guye in so moche sorowe broughte,<MILESTONE UNIT="Caius MS. 107 page" N="11"></L>
<L N="310">That of his lif he rekketh noughte;</L>
<L>Nor he woteth what he may doo,</L>
<L>For the grete sorowe that cometh him to.</L>
<L>He wende, he trende his bodde vpon,</L>
<L>As man that is woo bee goon;
<PB REF="00000025.tif" N="21"></L>
<L N="315">He ne may sitte, nor he may stonde,</L>
<L>Nor vnnethe vnto him drawe his honde,</L>
<L>Ne reste take of any slepinge,</L>
<L>Nor ete mete, nor drinke drinke;</L>
<L>Nor may noo man him comforte,</L>
<L N="320">Bot euere is songe is woo with disporte.</L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L N="325">Thus lyueth Guy in grete turmente</L>
<L>Till the feest was ouer wente;</L>
<L>Afterward he bethoughte is</L>
<L>That he doth as the man wyse,</L>
<L>That he shall loue bot strengthe haue</L>
<L N="330">Him self whan him luste to with-drawe.</L>
<L>Than thinketh he, good it is hir to shewe</L>
<L>The peynes that for hir greueth me newe:</L>
<L>And she of my sorowe knoweth noughte,</L>
<L>To ende y wolde my lif were broughte.</L>
<L N="335">Bee-tide me yuel either goode,</L>
<L>I woll not lyue in this mode;</L>
<L>Bot y shall to hir goo,</L>
<L>And in hir mercy y shall me doo.</L>
<L>Yf that she woll, she may me spille;</L>
<L N="340">Bot for all that y ne leue wille.</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="section">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>GUYE IS to courte come,</L>
<L>As man that is in sorowe nome.</L>
<L>On knees before Felice he hym didde,<MILESTONE UNIT="Caius MS. 107 page" N="12"></L>
<L>And sorowfully seide in that stede,</L>
<L N="345">All with quakyng steuene;</L>
<L>Thus he seide, and spake full euene:</L>
<L>'Felice the faire, for goddis loue, mercy!</L>
<L>On me haue reuthe for our lady,</L>
<L>That y ne fynde the my full foo,</L>
<L N="350">For loue y you praye, herken me to.
<PB REF="00000027.tif" N="23"></L>
<L>Hense forewarde y woll not hele</L>
<L>The grete loue, that me doth fele:</L>
<L>Shewe y muste the peyne and sorowe</L>
<L>That y haue for you euyne and morowe.</L>
<L N="355">Ye bee that thynge for whom y mourne,</L>
<L>Fro you ne may my herte tourne:</L>
<L>Ouere all thinge y muste you loue,</L>
<L>Whether it tourne benethe or aboue,</L>
<L>Bot that y shall loue you aye,</L>
<L N="360">Whiles that y lyue maye.</L>
<L>Vnder heuen noo thinge is,</L>
<L>Were it good or yuel ywis,</L>
<L>That y for the doo it [ne] wolde,</L>
<L>My lif to lese though y shulde.</L>
<L N="365">Ye bee my lif and my deth y-wis:</L>
<L>Withoute you loste is all my blis.</L>
<L>Well more y loue you than me:<MILESTONE UNIT="Caius MS. 107 page" N="12:2"></L>
<L>Deye y shall for loue of you pardee,</L>
<L>Bot thou haue mercy on me,</L>
<L N="370">Myself y shall for sorowe slee.</L>
<L>Yf ye wiste the heuynesse,</L>
<L>The grete peyne, and the sorowfulnesse,</L>
<L>That y haue for you nyghte and daye<MILESTONE UNIT="Caius MS. 107 page" N="13"></L>
<L>(With true loue y it saye)&mdash;</L>
<L N="375">And you it might witterly see,</L>
<L>I trowe ye wolde haue mercy on me.'</L>
<L>Felice to him answerde thoo,</L>
<L>'Telle me, Guye, if ye bee so</L>
<L>The Stywardis sone that highte Sywarde,</L>
<L N="380">I holde you for a fole musarde.</L>
<L>Nowe thou me haste of loue besoughte,</L>
<L>To fole-hardy thou art in thoughte,</L>
<L>Or thou me takest for a fole.</L>
<L>Thou art taughte of wikked scole,</L>
<L N="385">Whiles y am thy lordes Doughter by name;</L>
<L>Me thinketh thou doost him mikel shame,
<PB REF="00000029.tif" N="25"></L>
<L>Whan thou of loue besechest me,</L>
<L>And that y shulde thy lemman bee.</L>
<L>Ne fonde y neuere man that so moche mysseide,</L>
<L N="390">Nor that so folisshe of loue me preide,</L>
<L>Neither knyghte, Erle, ne baron;</L>
<L>Bot thou art bot a garson,</L>
<L>That art my man, and shuldest bee.</L>
<L>Euyll were my beaute besette on the,</L>
<L N="395">Yf y a grome loued and toke,</L>
<L>And so many faire knyghtis forsoke.</L>
<L>Erles, Dukes, of all the beste,</L>
<L>And of all the worlde the richeste</L>
<L>Ouere all men desired me a plighte,</L>
<L N="400">Suche as on me neuere had sighte;</L>
<L>Dispreised to moche y shuld bee</L>
<L>To leue all theim and take the!</L>
<L>All to grete hardiship thou thoughtest,<MILESTONE UNIT="Caius MS. 107 page" N="14"></L>
<L>Whan thou of loue me besoughtest.</L>
<L N="405">By my moder soule y the swere,</L>
<L>And y to my fader this tyding bere,</L>
<L>To slee the or the vtterly fordoo,</L>
<L>(By the shull bee warned other moo)</L>
<L>Or with wilde hors all to-drawe,</L>
<L N="410">For thy folie that were the lawe.</L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L>Goo hense swithe! vp arise,</L>
<L>And come nomore here in this wise!'</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="section">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="415">Full SOROWFULLY thense gooth Guy</L>
<L>Home to his Inne all sory:</L>
<L>In to his Chambre he is goon,</L>
<L>And beshette him therin all aloon.</L>
<L>There he made sorowe and sorowe enough:</L>
<L N="420">His clothes he rende, his heer he drough.
<PB REF="00000031.tif" N="27"></L>
<L>Of loue he bemeneth him strongely,</L>
<L>For whom he hath sorowe gretly:</L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L>'Loue, a-slake me of this wodenesse,</L>
<L N="430">And respite graunte me more or lesse,</L>
<L>That y might reste me a throwe,</L>
<L>Wherthurgh my sorowe may ouere blowe.</L>
<L>To farre y am kaste in vnmyghte,</L>
<L>My herte is heuy, and noo-thing lighte.</L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L>What shall y doo? how shall y fare?</L>
<L>I may not lyue longe in this kare.</L>
<L>Allas, deth! what art thou?</L>
<L>Vnnethe may y stonde now:</L>
<L N="445">Deth! come forth, and take me anoon;</L>
<L>For loste been my wittes euerych oon.</L>
<L>Dede y deserue for to bee,<MILESTONE UNIT="Caius MS. 107 page" N="15"></L>
<L>Whan y muste loue that hateth me.</L>
<L>And herken nowe what seith the wise,</L>
<L N="450">That sheweth ensample of good assise:</L>
<L>For a fole he seith y him holde,</L>
<L>That taketh a more burden than he may welde;</L>
<L>So fare y nowe, weleawaye!</L>
<L>I loue the loue that y ne haue maye.'</L>
<L N="455">To a wyndowe Guy yede thoo,</L>
<L>For to beholde the castell and the toure also:</L>
<L>'O toure, thou art full faire sette!</L>
<L>In the is that maide beshette,
<PB REF="00000033.tif" N="29"></L>
<L>That lyueth in ioye and in blisse:</L>
<L N="460">Hir loue me woundeth withoute mysse.</L>
<L>O toure, why ne were thou ouerethrawe,</L>
<L>And vpon the grounde all to-drawe!</L>
<L>Than might y my lemman see,</L>
<L>That y loue more than me!'</L>
<L N="465">He gynneth him bethinke and sore sighe,</L>
<L>His sorowe enneweth euere gretly;</L>
<L>To grounde he felle, and swowne beganne:</L>
<L>More sorowe had neuere manne.</L>
<L>The tyme he cursed that he was borne;</L>
<L N="470">For loue he hath his witte lorne.</L>
<L>'O loue,' he seide, 'cursed thou bee!</L>
<L>So moche mighte is in the.</L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L>Allas, Felice! that same stounde,</L>
<L>That euere thy loue hath me so stronge bounde!</L>
<L>And that y the serue shulde that daye,</L>
<L N="480">Allas the while! nowe y sey maye.</L>
<L>Shall y not haue noon other mede,<MILESTONE UNIT="Caius MS. 107 page" N="16"></L>
<L>To a-slake my sorowe y had nede.</L>
<L>I loue the and thou noughte me.</L>
<L>Eeuenly deled ne that may<NOTE PLACE="marg">[<I>read</I> ne may that]</NOTE> bee:</L>
<L N="485">Of all my sorowe thou hast noughte.</L>
<L>Allas! to grounde y am broughte!</L>
<L>Thou hast the good and y the quede:</L>
<L>I brenne as doth the sparke on glede.</L>
<L>Thou art to lither a woman,</L>
<L N="490">That for a lokyng the vpon</L>
<L>A man shuld dye for that sighte:</L>
<L>Mercy, Felice, thou swete wighte!</L>
<L>Myn herte is with venym spilde;</L>
<L>With blisse nomore it is like bee filde.'
<PB REF="00000035.tif" N="31"></L>
<L N="495">Suche lif had Guy sikirly</L>
<L>All that weke hoolly.</L>
<L>For him his fader was well sory,</L>
<L>Sabyne his moder bemeneth Guy,</L>
<L>The Erle for him sory was,</L>
<L N="500">That it liked noon in that place:</L>
<L>Litell and moche, all and some,</L>
<L>Guy bemeneth at Frome.</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="section">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>THE ERLE did for leches sende</L>
<L>To wite of Guyes euyl an ende.</L>
<L N="505">The leches to him been goo:</L>
<L>Guy they fonde as blak as sloo;</L>
<L>Than they asked how it with him stode.</L>
<L>'For hete,' he seide, 'y breide nyghe wode:</L>
<L>So mikell hete is in me,</L>
<L N="510">That longe y ne may on lyue bee.</L>
<L>Hotter y am thanne fire brennyng,<MILESTONE UNIT="Caius MS. 107 page" N="17"></L>
<L>Sorowe and woo is my menyng;</L>
<L>All my body it hath vnright:</L>
<L>Suche lif y lede daye and nyght.</L>
<L N="515">After that hete cometh a chele</L>
<L>That sore me greueth withoute hele;</L>
<L>Than wexe y colder than the yys:</L>
<L>Suche maner myn yuel is.</L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L N="520"></L>
<L>This is my lif nyghte and daie:</L>
<L>No more y kan therof you saie.'</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="section">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>THANNE seide that oon, 'a feuer'. it is.'</L>
<L>'Ye,' quoth Guy, 'the leuer me. y-wis.'</L>
<L N="525">The leches goth, and Guy leue allone,</L>
<L>That rewthfully maketh his mone.</L>
<L>'Now god,' quoth Guy, 'what shall y doo?</L>
<L>How longe shall laste me this woo?</L>
<L>Why ne may y dede bee,</L>
<L N="530">Whan y ne may hir mery yen see,
<PB REF="00000037.tif" N="33"></L>
<L>That hath all myn hertis thoughte?</L>
<L>And y neuere amysse did hir noughte,</L>
<L>Bot oonly that y loue hir well,</L>
<L>And euere while y lyue shall.</L>
<L N="535">Yf y hir beseche, she woll it telle</L>
<L>Hir fader, and than he woll me quelle.</L>
<L>And though he it wiste right nowe, a plighte,</L>
<L>Nomore than slee me doo he mighte.</L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L N="541">Bot y shall goo and speke hir too,</L>
<L>And shewe hir my grete woo.</L>
<L>Vnder heuen is not so harde thing</L>
<L>As is loue in wowyng.'</L>
<L N="545">Yet seide he after thanne,<MILESTONE UNIT="Caius MS. 107 page" N="18"></L>
<L>'Though she me blame, noo force y kanne;</L>
<L>Bot to hir y shall sey so,</L>
<L>That loue me did thider goo.'</L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L N="551">Guy with that arisen is,</L>
<L>And to the Courte he wente ywis.</L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="section">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Nowe is Guy to Courte come,</L>
<L>As man that was with woo nome;</L>
<L N="565">In to an herber he is goo,</L>
<L>Felice he fonde therin thoo;
<PB REF="00000039.tif" N="35"></L>
<L>At hir fete he him leyde,</L>
<L>And than all wepyng to hir he seide:</L>
<L>'Y am come mercy to aske of the;</L>
<L N="570">Yf thou woll thou maist slee me;</L>
<L>Thy commaundement y wote well y haue broke,</L>
<L>Now that y am come before thy loke.</L>
<L>And leef me were surely</L>
<L>The sorowe that y haue suffred by and by,</L>
<L N="575">Stronge peyne sorowe and woo</L>
<L>That y for the haue endured eueremoo.</L>
<L>Myn herte shall y leue with the:</L>
<L>Woll thou or not, so shall it bee;</L>
<L>My body farther goo ne may,</L>
<L N="580">And my wille lasteth ay.</L>
<L>While y lyue, the loue y wille,</L>
<L>Whether y saue my self or spille;</L>
<L>Thurgh me demed it shall not bee</L>
<L>Whiles that lif is within me.</L>
<L N="585">The to loue thou may not forbede,</L>
<L>With sorowe and woo thou dost me fede.</L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L>Fro hense foreward it rekketh not me<MILESTONE UNIT="Caius MS. 107 page" N="19"></L>
<L>Of my lif how so it bee,</L>
<L N="595">Ne of my deth neuere the moo</L>
<L>I ne rekke how that it goo,</L>
<L>For of this lif y am chekmate.'</L>
<L>A-downe he felle swounyng with that;</L>
<L>Felice loked vpon him thoo.</L>
<L N="600">And behelde his grete woo;</L>
<L>Ruthe she had in hir herte</L>
<L>Of his sorowe and his smerte.
<PB REF="00000041.tif" N="37"></L>
<L>To a maide she seide thoo:</L>
<L>'Take him vp in thyn armes twoo,</L>
<L N="605">And ley him vp fro the grounde,</L>
<L>Till him bee past that bitter stounde.'</L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L>'By god of heuen,' that maide seide,</L>
<L N="610">'Though y were of the worlde the fairest maide,</L>
<L>And the Richest Kyngis Doughter were</L>
<L>That in this worlde crowne dooth bere,</L>
<L>And he of my loue desirous were,</L>
<L>As he is of thine in stronge manere,</L>
<L N="615">Ne wolde y him my loue werne,</L>
<L>And he me wolde therof lerne.</L>
<L>Felice the faire answerd therto:</L>
<L>'Avoide, damesell, why seist thou so?</L>
<L>So thou shuld not rede me;</L>
<L N="620">Thou art to blame forsothe y telle the.</L>
<L>Thou hast ofte herde this speche,</L>
<L>That we ne shuld noman beseche,</L>
<L>But they shuld beseche women</L>
<L>On the fairest manere that they kan,</L>
<L N="625">And assaye yf they spede may<MILESTONE UNIT="Caius MS. 107 page" N="20"></L>
<L>Either by nyghte or by day.'</L>
<L>Guy of swounyng awaked thoo;</L>
<L>The maide helde him in hir armes twoo.</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="section">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'GUYE,' QUOTH Felice, 'thou doost folie:</L>
<L N="630">Woll thou for my loue dye?</L>
<L>After my fader y woll sende,</L>
<L>And telle him euery worde to the ende,</L>
<L>That thou him doost grete disworship</L>
<L>Whan thou desirest my shenship;</L>
<L N="635">In this Courte he shall dampne the</L>
<L>Highe to hange, to please me.</L>
<L>Guye answerd anone right thoo:</L>
<L>'Now god wolde it might bee so,
<PB REF="00000043.tif" N="39"></L>
<L>That of my deth thou might bee the wite!</L>
<L N="640">Therof y shulde bee wonder lighte!</L>
<L>I am all redy it to fonge,</L>
<L>Bee it with right or with wronge;</L>
<L>For suche a drinke me is yiue,</L>
<L>That y ne kepe noo lenger lyue;</L>
<L N="645">Myn hede y shall fayne for the leye,</L>
<L>I rekke not what any man seye.'</L>
<L>Felice had of him grete ruthe:</L>
<L>'Guye,' she seide, 'thou louest in truthe;</L>
<L>To moche thou art thurgh loue assailled,</L>
<L N="650">That thy wittes been gretly dismaied.</L>
<L>So moche y shall nowe doo for the</L>
<L>That more thou maist not bidde me:</L>
<L>Ther nys Lady nor man noon,<MILESTONE UNIT="Caius MS. 107 page" N="21"></L>
<L>So wide as me might in this Contree goon,</L>
<L N="655">And thou loued hir as thou doost me,</L>
<L>But she wolde graunte to loue the.'</L>
<L>'Felice,' quoth Guy, 'lete that bee,</L>
<L>For thou doost bot scorne me.'</L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L>'Guy,' quoth Felice, 'nowe vnderstonde:</L>
<L>My wille y haue to the in this stounde;</L>
<L N="665">And take it not for noon vnskille</L>
<L>Though y sey to the my wille.</L>
<L>I woll loue noo knaue in wone</L>
<L>Before that he bee knyght bee-come,</L>
<L>Faire and hende and gretly sette by,</L>
<L N="670">Of armes good and hardy;</L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L>Thanne shall thou haue the loue of me,</L>
<L>Yf thou wolbee as y telle the.'
</L>
</LG>

</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="section"><PB REF="00000045.tif" N="41">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="675">THANNE GUY herde that tyding,</L>
<L>For ioye his herte beganne to spryng;</L>
<L>His loue to hir anone he kaste than,</L>
<L>And in-to the Castell forthwith he cam;</L>
<L>As sone as he might it doo,</L>
<L N="680">To the highe palais he gan goo:</L>
<L>Of oon daie hym thoughte ten,</L>
<L>That he ne might see his lemman.</L>
<L>Whan he him felte hole and suer,</L>
<L>To Courte he gooth with gladde cher;</L>
<L N="685">Full gladde chere they him made,</L>
<L>And thanked god, and were right glade</L>
<L>That Guy was to Courte come:<MILESTONE UNIT="Caius MS. 107 page" N="22"></L>
<L>Gladde they were all and some.</L>
<L>Before the Erle tho come Guy,</L>
<L N="690">To him he kneled as to his lorde mighti;</L>
<L>'Sir,' quoth Guy, 'armes y aske the,</L>
<L>Yf y bee worthy accepte to bee;</L>
<L>Yf it bee thy wille that y theim fonge,</L>
<L>And serue the lorde withoute wronge.'</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="section">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="695">THE ERLE Rohaud answerd thoo,</L>
<L>'Blithely, Guy, sithe thou wolt so.'</L>
<L>The Erle dooth than apparaille</L>
<L>Guyes dobbing withoute faille;</L>
<L>He dud him dobbe richely,</L>
<L N="700">And with him of his felawes twenty</L>
<L>That all good barons sones were,</L>
<L>(For Guyes loue he dobbed theim all there)</L>
<L>That with the Erle Rohaud had bee longe</L>
<L>In seruice, armes for to fonge.</L>
<L N="705">It was at the fest of the holy Trinyte,</L>
<L>That the Erle dobbed Guy so free,</L>
<L>And other twenty for his loue,</L>
<L>Good knyghtis [and] barons sones, aboue.</L>
<L>Of riche Clothes and sendall</L>
<L N="710">Was their dobbyng, thurgh-oute all;
<PB REF="00000047.tif" N="43"></L>
<L>Of riche panys of faire grys,</L>
<L>And with mantellis riche of pris;</L>
<L>Of good armes and stoute stedes,</L>
<L>Of all the londe the beste at nedes.</L>
<L N="715">Ouere theim all was Guy best dighte,</L>
<L>Though he an Emperouris sone had bee righte:'</L>
<L>Ther might noon better dighte bee:<MILESTONE UNIT="Caius MS. 107 page" N="23"></L>
<L>With all kynnes armes dobbed was he.</L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L>Ther ne was squier neither knaue</L>
<L>That failled oughte bot he shuld haue.</L>
<L>Now is Guy dobbed knyght,</L>
<L>Curteis and hende, and of grete myght.</L>
<L N="725">Than to Felice he ganne goo,</L>
<L>With grete loue he resouned hir thoo:</L>
<L>'Well thou wotest, lemman, that it is so,</L>
<L>For the that y haue suffred grete woo</L>
<L>In all my body, y the plighte,</L>
<L N="730">Thou hast made me passing lighte.</L>
<L>Armes y haue for the fonge,</L>
<L>The to see me thoughte longe;</L>
<L>Now y am at thy wille come,</L>
<L>As to hir that y loue most in wone.</L>
<L N="735">Than seide Felice, 'ne haste the nought:</L>
<L>Yet hast thou noo thing of armes wroughte.</L>
<L>Noo better thou art neuere a dele</L>
<L>Than thou were before, y preoue it wele,</L>
<L>Bot oonly that thou hast newe dobbyng,</L>
<L N="740">And knyght art cleped withoute lesyng.</L>
<L>Bot whan y may wite and see</L>
<L>That thou hast in tormentis bee,</L>
<L>And that thou hast knyghtes nome,</L>
<L>Castellis and Toures ouerecome,</L>
<L N="745">And thurgh all the londe and Contree</L>
<L>Thy knyghthode full good knowen bee,
<PB REF="00000049.tif" N="45"></L>
<L>And that it bee for thy myghte,</L>
<L>And than thou may aske me loue with righte.</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="section">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>WHANNE GUY herde Felice so speke,<MILESTONE UNIT="Caius MS. 107 page" N="24"></L>
<L N="750">His leue he toke and ganne oute reke;</L>
<L>Of Felice he toke his leue anone,</L>
<L>And to his Fader he gan gone.</L>
<L>'Sir,' he seide, 'vnderstonde me:</L>
<L>I am nowe dobbed as ye may see;</L>
<L N="755">Ouer see y woll fare</L>
<L>To take lawes and pris there.'</L>
<L>Syward his fader answerd his sone,</L>
<L>'God graunte the well ayene to come!</L>
<L>Siluer and golde take enowe,</L>
<L N="760">As moche as nedeth for thy prowe;</L>
<L>At thy wille take with the</L>
<L>Hors and harneys and good mayne.'</L>
<L>Sywarde clepeth heraude to him,</L>
<L>And seide, 'heraude, frende myn,</L>
<L N="765">With my sone thou shalt wende</L>
<L>In good stede with him to lende.</L>
<L>Thou shalt kepe my sone Guy</L>
<L>That is yonge knyght and thy nory,</L>
<L>For he is bot a yongelyng;</L>
<L N="770">I you beteche bothe to heuen King,</L>
<L>And the heraude for to kepe;</L>
<L>And thy felawes all by hepe,</L>
<L>That is Tureld and Vrry,</L>
<L>In you y truste sikirly;</L>
<L N="775">To-gider with heraude they shull goo,</L>
<L>To kepe my sones body fro woo.'</L>
<L>'Sir,' quoth they euerychon,<MILESTONE UNIT="Caius MS. 107 page" N="25"></L>
<L>'Full gladly we woll with him goon.'</L>
<L>Knyghtes they were full good, y plighte,</L>
<L N="780">Of all the contree the best in fighte.</L>
<L>Guy toke of siluer and golde</L>
<L>As moche as he haue wolde.
<PB REF="00000051.tif" N="47"></L>
<L>To the see they been come,</L>
<L>And ouere they saille at Frome;</L>
<L N="785">Come they been in-to Normandye,</L>
<L>Knyghthode shewyng by and by.</L>
<L>At . . . . . <NOTE PLACE="marg">[Blank space in MS.]</NOTE> taketh Guy herborough</L>
<L>With the richest of that borowgh;</L>
<L>Of the best they had enough,</L>
<L N="790">Ne was ther noon that it with-drough;</L>
<L>For they had enough euere<NOTE PLACE="marg">[read <I>ouere</I>?]</NOTE> see,</L>
<L>Golde and siluer grete plentee.</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="section">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>GUYE HIS hoste cleped him to;</L>
<L>Tidinges he asked of him thoo</L>
<L N="795">Where that any torment shuld bee,</L>
<L>So many sheldes ledde sawe he.</L>
<L>'Sir,' quoth his hoste, 'ne wote ye nought</L>
<L>Of a torment that is bethought?'</L>
<L>'Noo,' quoth Guy, 'by Iesu swete,</L>
<L N="800">Therof ne herde y neuere yette.'</L>
<L>'Sir,' quoth his hoste, 'and ye woll duelle,</L>
<L>All that y wote y shall you telle:</L>
<L>A maide brighte and of grete pris,</L>
<L>(Of Almaigne the Emperours Doughter she is)</L>
<L N="805">A turnement she hath doo cryde,</L>
<L>I herde neuere noon suche on this side;</L>
<L>For there nys knyghte in all Spaigne,<MILESTONE UNIT="Caius MS. 107 page" N="26"></L>
<L>Anone to the see of Britaigne,</L>
<L>That of armes aughtis named bee,</L>
<L N="810">Bot there his might men shall see.</L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L>Of euery londe thider come knyghtes,</L>
<L>Proude and bolde, and stronge in fightes,</L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L>And they that been of most mighte,</L>
<L>Grete worship they shall wynne, aplighte.
<PB REF="00000053.tif" N="49"></L>
<L>For that maide y spake of eer,</L>
<L N="820">Is the Emperours doughter Reyner;</L>
<L>To that turnement he woll bringe that daye</L>
<L>(Well may him bee that it wynne maye)</L>
<L>A Girfauk all swanne white</L>
<L>(Of his better y herde neuere yette)</L>
<L N="825">And an hors of grete bountee</L>
<L>(It is worthe all a contree)</L>
<L>And twoo Greyhoundes that good bee<NOTE PLACE="marg">white grey|hounds,</NOTE></L>
<L>(Their better did ye neuere see);</L>
<L>And he that the turnement ouere-cometh all</L>
<L N="830">On euery behalue, the pris he haue shall,</L>
<L>The White Girfauk and the stede</L>
<L>Bothe he shall haue to his mede</L>
<L>And the Greyhoundes that so good beth,</L>
<L>All shall he haue that best doeth;</L>
<L N="835">And that maide that is so free,</L>
<L>Bot he haue a lemman that fairer bee.'</L>
<L>Whan Guy herde this tyding,</L>
<L>Well gladde he was withoute lesyng;</L>
<L>Than seide Guy to his feere,</L>
<L N="840">'In good tyme come we here.</L>
<L>To morowe as sone as it is daye,<MILESTONE UNIT="Caius MS. 107 page" N="27"></L>
<L>We woll doo vs on oure weye.'</L>
<L>Guy to his hoste a palfrey yaf</L>
<L>For the tidingis that he him tolde hath.</L>
<L N="845">On the morowe full tymely</L>
<L>On their wey thei dresse theim sikirly,</L>
<L>Guy and his feres goode</L>
<L>Barons all of kynde blode.</L>
<L>Of riding doth they neuere stent</L>
<L N="850">Till they come to that turnement.</L>
<L>Whan thei thider were come</L>
<L>And<NOTE PLACE="marg">read <I>thei</I></NOTE> sawe there many a semely man.</L>
<L>Bothe by Ryuers and by feldes riding</L>
<L>Many knyghtes they sawe comyng
<PB REF="00000055.tif" N="51"></L>
<L N="855">And whan thei thider all were come,</L>
<L>To ioustes they wente than full sone;</L>
<L>Oute of the thrange they gan theim dighte,</L>
<L>The Barons all of grete mighte.</L>
<L>Than asked sir Guy</L>
<L N="860">Of a lorde that stode him by:</L>
<L>'Who is nowe that same Knyght</L>
<L>That oute of the rowe dooth him dight?'</L>
<L>'I shall telle the: as y wene,</L>
<L>That same with the armes shene</L>
<L N="865">A Knyght he is of grete pris,</L>
<L>And y the swere by seynt Denys,</L>
<L>For to iouste he is dighte,</L>
<L>And he may fynde any knyghte</L>
<L>That ayenst him darre iousty:</L>
<L N="870">Therto he maketh him redy.'</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="section">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>WHANNE GUYE sawe comyng was Gayer,<MILESTONE UNIT="Caius MS. 107 page" N="28"></L>
<L>Redy to iouste he draweth him ner;</L>
<L>Oute of the Rowe he dooth him hye,</L>
<L>Well he sembled as a knyghte hardye.</L>
<L N="875">They smytten than to geders thoo,</L>
<L>Full harde strokes they yiuen bothe two.</L>
<L>Gaer smote Guy before,</L>
<L>Thurghoute the shelde his launce he bore;</L>
<L>The launce to-brake, that was so well wrought:</L>
<L N="880">The hauberkis were good and failled nought.</L>
<L>And Guy to Gaer thoo he smote,</L>
<L>That to grounde he felled him fote hote;</L>
<L>That hors he taketh by the Reyne</L>
<L>And forthe he wendeth with meyne.</L>
<L N="885">Tho beganne that turnement:</L>
<L>Eche Knyght on other smote good dent;</L>
<L>Harde they smyte, y the plighte,</L>
<L>Eche to take other they doo their mighte.</L>
<L>So many knyghtis Guy toke that daye</L>
<L N="890">And thurgh his strength ouerecome that playe,
<PB REF="00000057.tif" N="53"></L>
<L>That euery man wondred therof:</L>
<L>So many helmes he there all to-drof.</L>
<L>That daye satte noman there so faste,</L>
<L>Bot that he felled him at the laste.</L>
<L N="895">And the Duke Otes of Pauye</L>
<L>At Guy he had grete enuye;</L>
<L>For pride he wolde with him iousty,</L>
<L>And therof hym befelle grete vilanye.</L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L>Thurgh the shulder Guy him smote,</L>
<L>To grounde he felle, god it wote.</L>
<L N="905">The Duke Reyner sawe that caas,<MILESTONE UNIT="Caius MS. 107 page" N="29"></L>
<L>And therfore he full angry was.</L>
<L>Toward Guy he ganne dryue,</L>
<L>Him to smyte he hieth bylyue</L>
<L>And seide to Guy: 'in euyl stounde</L>
<L N="910">Thou gaue Duke Otes a greuous wounde.</L>
<L>In euyl tyme thou iousted with him.</L>
<L>He is my nyghe germayne Cousyn:</L>
<L>I am the Duke Reyner that to the speke;</L>
<L>I am come him on the to awreke.'</L>
<L N="915">'I graunte,' quoth Guy, 'so mote y thee.</L>
<L>Withdrawe the anone and iouste with me.'</L>
<L>Guy to him beganne to smyte</L>
<L>And did him not spare bot a lite;</L>
<L>An highe he smote him in the shelde,</L>
<L N="920">That downe he felled him in the feelde.</L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L>The hors by reyne he hath nome,</L>
<L>And to the Duke therwith he is come.</L>
<L N="925">'Nowe here thy hors y take the;</L>
<L>Yf y haue nede, yelde it me.'
<PB REF="00000059.tif" N="55"></L>
<L>And he full well quytte his while,</L>
<L>As a good knyght shuld withoute gile;</L>
<L>Sone ye may here euery dele</L>
<L N="930">How he him it yelde swithe wele.</L>
<L>Whan the Duke Otes herde this,</L>
<L>Ayenst Guy he come, ywis:</L>
<L>'Sir Knyght, telle thou me</L>
<L>Of whennes thou art and what thy name bee.'</L>
<L N="935">And Guy answerd than boldely,</L>
<L>'I telle the nowe full truely:</L>
<L>Guy of Warrewik men clepe me;<MILESTONE UNIT="Caius MS. 107 page" N="30"></L>
<L>I was borne in that Contree.'</L>
<L>The Duke of Louayne cometh with this</L>
<L N="940">And a good spere in his hande, ywis;</L>
<L>To Guy he smote with grete hete,</L>
<L>And he to him and wolde not lete:</L>
<L>With grete dyntes they to-geder dryueth,</L>
<L>That their launces all to-slyuereth.</L>
<L N="945">They smyte to-geder harde and wele</L>
<L>With their swerdes of good steele.</L>
<L>They thirle armes and sheldes also:</L>
<L>Stronge fighte ther is betwene theim two.</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="section">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>THANNE Heraude of Ardern forth gan springe,</L>
<L N="950">And the Duke he mette in his comynge:</L>
<L>Farre of his hors he hath him felled</L>
<L>All longestreight in the felde.</L>
<L>To the Duke Gaudemer than he smote,</L>
<L>And of his hors he felled him fote hote:</L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L>Well he dooth as knyght hardy.</L>
<L>With that cometh to him vrry.</L>
<L>Thanne beganne that fighte with swerde:</L>
<L N="960">Of suche ye ne haue bot seelde herde.</L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L>
<PB REF="00000061.tif" N="57">. . . . . </L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L N="965">Bot the folke sey of that contree</L>
<L>That Guye euer the beste is he.</L>
<L>And on morowe for the same</L>
<L>The pris he had of that game.</L>
<L>Guy is preised on euery side,</L>
<L N="970">And on him is tourned all the pride.</L>
<L>And, tho come the thirde daye,</L>
<L>That euery man shulde wende his weye,</L>
<L>There come the Duke Reyner priking,<MILESTONE UNIT="Caius MS. 107 page" N="31"></L>
<L>That good knyght was and well doyng.</L>
<L N="975">'Lordynges,' he seide, 'vnderstonde me,</L>
<L>Yf y myssey, that it may amended bee.</L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L>This Girfauk and this stede,</L>
<L>Thise Greyhoundes shall haue to mede</L>
<L>He that theim beste hath gete</L>
<L>Is Guy of Warrewik, take ye kepe.</L>
<L N="985">And that therto withseith aught,</L>
<L>Of bataille ne may he faille naught.'</L>
<L>All they seide comenly,</L>
<L>'Thy dome we graunte, sikirly.'</L>
<L>Than they cryde as was the lawe</L>
<L N="990">That Guy the presente&yogh; shuld haue by sothe sawe.</L>
<L>Whan they were all went,</L>
<L>Guy to his Inne is come, verament,</L>
<L>And did him vnarme lightly;</L>
<L>For of the turnement he was wery.</L>
<L N="995">With this cometh a sergeant ridyng</L>
<L>Slie and wise and wele speking;</L>
<L>To Guyes Inne he is come,</L>
<L>And to Guy he wente right sone.
<PB REF="00000063.tif" N="59"></L>
<L>Curteisly Guy he grette:</L>
<L N="1000">'Sir Guy,' he seide, 'god the kepe:</L>
<L>Thou art holde the best in this borough</L>
<L>And in all this londe thurgh and thorough.</L>
<L>Thou hast wonne the turnement,</L>
<L>Therfore y bringe to the this present</L>
<L N="1005">In the Maidens behalue Blanchefloure,</L>
<L>My lordes doughter the Emperoure:</L>
<L>This white Girfauk, the stede also,<MILESTONE UNIT="Caius MS. 107 page" N="32"></L>
<L>Thise white Greyhoundes, that good bee bothe two.</L>
<L>Hir loue the she graunteth with all than,</L>
<L N="1010">Bot if thou haue a fairer lemman,</L>
<L>Than she that is the toure withynne:</L>
<L>This daie thou may hir loue wynne.'</L>
<L>Full curteisly answerd Guy:</L>
<L>'Of thise presente&yogh; moult graunt mercy,</L>
<L N="1015">And thanke hir that theim hider sent:</L>
<L>Full gladly y resceiue hir present,</L>
<L>Hir knyght to bee withoute wronge:</L>
<L>I shall hir duely vnderfonge.</L>
<L>My leue frende, nowe vnderstonde me:</L>
<L N="1020">Thou shall doo as y sey the.</L>
<L>Thise armes y shall the nowe yiue</L>
<L>And make the riche while thou lyue;</L>
<L>And all thy felawes that bee with the</L>
<L>Riche yiftes they shull haue of me,</L>
<L N="1025">And doo you y shall grete honour</L>
<L>For the Maidens loue Blancheflour.'</L>
<L>'Grant mercy, sir Guy,' seide he;</L>
<L>'For armes y come not to the,</L>
<L>And right to the maide y shall wende</L>
<L N="1030">And telle hir worde and ende,</L>
<L>To Blancheflour, that swete thing,</L>
<L>And telle hir of the good tyding.'</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="section">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>THE YONGE man gooth and Guy lefte there,</L>
<L>That is in ioye and not in kare.
<PB REF="00000065.tif" N="61"></L>
<L N="1035">Two sweynes Guy cleped him to,</L>
<L>To theim he seide and bade also,</L>
<L>That they with that present&yogh; shuld fonde<MILESTONE UNIT="Caius MS. 107 page" N="33"></L>
<L>Assone as they might in-to Englonde</L>
<L>And presente therwith in his worde</L>
<L N="1040">The Erle Rouhaude, his kynde lorde.</L>
<L>Whan they herde what Guy theim bade,</L>
<L>Full redy thei made theim with hert glade.</L>
<L>They wente than in-to Englonde:</L>
<L>At Warrewik the Erle there they fonde.</L>
<L N="1045">The White Girfauk and the stede,</L>
<L>The two Greyhoundes that by theim yede,</L>
<L>To the Erle they made their present;</L>
<L>And that Guy it wanne at the turnement</L>
<L>All they haue the Erle telde,</L>
<L N="1050">And that he was the best in the felde,</L>
<L>And that he was moste sette by</L>
<L>Of all the knyghtis in Normandy,</L>
<L>And that the Emperrour doughter with all than</L>
<L>Hadde him chose to hir lemman.</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="section">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1055">WHANNE the Erle herde this,</L>
<L>Full gladde he was therof, ywis,</L>
<L>That Guy so moche preised was.</L>
<L>His fader thanked god of that cas:</L>
<L>Felice the faire did also,</L>
<L N="1060">Whan the tidinges were tolde hir to.</L>
<L>All his frendes olde and yinge</L>
<L>Were full gladde of that tidinge.</L>
<L>Tho wente Guy in-to farrer londe</L>
<L>Turnementis and ioustes for to fonde.</L>
<L N="1065">In Almaigne and in Lombardie,</L>
<L>In Fraunce and in Normandie.</L>
<L>Ther was noo turnement, ywis,<MILESTONE UNIT="Caius MS. 107 page" N="34"></L>
<L>Bot he was therat and had the pris.</L>
<L>He was oute more than a yere:</L>
<L N="1070">Thurgh all londes men preised him there
<PB REF="00000067.tif" N="63"></L>
<L>And helde him the best vnder sonne.</L>
<L>Many a good frende he had there wonne.</L>
<L>To <NOTE PLACE="marg">[Blank space left in MS.]</NOTE>ayene he is come</L>
<L>And with his good hooste his Inne nome.</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="section">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1075">'SIR,' QUOTH heraude to Guy</L>
<L>(His maister he was, a Knyght hardy),</L>
<L>'To Englonde nowe woll we goo:</L>
<L>With worship we may it nowe doo;</L>
<L>For we haue ouere all bee</L>
<L N="1080">And the pris wonne in euery contree.</L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L N="1085">To the kyng thou shall acqueynte the</L>
<L>Of Englond, that is so free,</L>
<L>And to the Barons also</L>
<L>Wel bee-knowen thou shalt the doo.'</L>
<L>'Maister,' he seith, 'y graunte wele,</L>
<L N="1090">After the that it bee euery dele;</L>
<L>And to-morowe whan it is daye,</L>
<L>We woll forthe on oure weye.'</L>
<L>Guy aroosse on morowe thoo,</L>
<L>And to the see they been goo:</L>
<L N="1095">Assone as they might, to shippe they wente,</L>
<L>And in-to Englond they come in the lente.</L>
<L>To kyng Athelston Guy is come,</L>
<L>And with him he is aqueynted full sone,</L>
<L>With the Erles and Barons also,</L>
<L N="1100">And full riche yiftes they gaue him tho.</L>
<L>To Warrewik than he is fare:<MILESTONE UNIT="Caius MS. 107 page" N="35"></L>
<L>The Erle Rohaude he fonde there,</L>
<L>That faire vnderfonge him and his feere;</L>
<L>For he was him bothe leef and dere.</L>
<L N="1105">He kissed him full swetely</L>
<L>And of his present thanked him hertly.
<PB REF="00000069.tif" N="65"></L>
<L>To his lemman he is well-come,</L>
<L>And him to kisse she maketh hir bowne.</L>
<L>The Erle proferd him siluer and golde,</L>
<L N="1110">And noothing therof take he wolde.</L>
<L>Full gladde is his fader of him</L>
<L>And his moder and all his kynne,</L>
<L>And all the folke of that Contree</L>
<L>Were gladde him for to see.</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="section">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1115">ON A DAYE he is to Felice goo,</L>
<L>And full louyngly he seith hir too:</L>
<L>'I am come as thou may see.</L>
<L>My lif y haue, lemman, thurgh thee:</L>
<L>Ne were thou, lemman, dede y were,</L>
<L N="1120">My body destroied and leide on bere.</L>
<L>Armes y toke for loue of the,</L>
<L>Thoo thy wille thou tolde me,</L>
<L>That, whan y had armes take,</L>
<L>Thou woldest not than me for-sake.</L>
<L N="1125">And thou hast herde me preised bee</L>
<L>In many astraunge contree:</L>
<L>Thy loue shuld not me bee werned,</L>
<L>For y haue it, me thinketh, ayerned.</L>
<L>Sweting, nowe y am come to the,</L>
<L N="1130">Thy wille therof thou telle me.'</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="section">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>FELICE answerd swithe on highe,<MILESTONE UNIT="Caius MS. 107 page" N="36"></L>
<L>And iaped not with sir Guye:</L>
<L>'Yet art thou not preised so,</L>
<L>Bot y kanne fynde suche other moo.</L>
<L N="1135">Stronge thou art and of grete mighte,</L>
<L>Good and hardy and kene in fighte:</L>
<L>And if y the had my loue yiue,</L>
<L>And wille it the whiles y liue,</L>
<L>Sleuthe wolde the so ouerecome,</L>
<L N="1140">That thou woldest nomore armes doon,</L>
<L>Ne come in turnement nor in fighte.</L>
<L>So amerous thou wolde bee anone righte.
<PB REF="00000071.tif" N="67"></L>
<L>I shuld misdoo, as thinketh me,</L>
<L>And gretly offende ayenst the.</L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L>Guy,' quoth she, 'concele y nelle,</L>
<L>Bot all the sothe y shall the telle:</L>
<L>Thou art me leeuest of other alle,</L>
<L N="1150">And my lemman y shall the calle;</L>
<L>Bot my loue thou shalt not haue</L>
<L>For noo thing that thou kan craue,</L>
<L>Vnto tyme thou so perilous holde bee</L>
<L>And best doyng in euery Contree,</L>
<L N="1155">That neither by londe nor by water</L>
<L>Bee founde in any wise thy better;</L>
<L>And whan thou art holde best doynge</L>
<L>In armes that man may fynde,</L>
<L>That vnder heuen thy better ne bee,</L>
<L N="1160">My loue than y shall graunte the,</L>
<L>For to doo with me thi wille</L>
<L>Eerly and late, loude and stille.</L>
<L>In other wise, how so it goo,<MILESTONE UNIT="Caius MS. 107 page" N="37"></L>
<L>My loue ne shall thou haue ellis neuere the moo.'</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="section">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1165">WHANNE Guy herde Felice speke so,</L>
<L>Full depe he ganne sighe tho:</L>
<L>'Now wote y well, thou skornest me,</L>
<L>Whan y suche answer haue of the,</L>
<L>That y shuld the best bee in felde</L>
<L N="1170">In fighting with spere and shelde;</L>
<L>And so good might y neuere worthe</L>
<L>To bee the best vpon the erthe;</L>
<L>And in-to straunge londe wende y shall,</L>
<L>For thy loue to werke woo ouere all.</L>
<L N="1175">For doubte of deth y woll not flee:</L>
<L>If y dye, it is for the.'</L>
<L>Guy of hir toke his leeue on hie,</L>
<L>And kissed hir with weping yie.
<PB REF="00000073.tif" N="69"></L>
<L>To his Inne he gooth, as y you telle,</L>
<L N="1180">And there he doth not longe duelle.</L>
<L>To the Erle he gan goon</L>
<L>To take of him his leeue anoon.</L>
<L>Nowe is Guy to Courte come</L>
<L>To take his leeue all and some.</L>
<L N="1185">To the Erle Rohaude he yede thoo,</L>
<L>And tolde him what he wolde doo.</L>
<L>'Sir Erle,' quoth Guy, 'y pray the,</L>
<L>Leeue to wende that thou yiue me.</L>
<L>God to good hauen me sende:</L>
<L N="1190">Ouer the see y shall wende.</L>
<L>Tyme it is that y fonde</L>
<L>To wynne pris in straunge londe;</L>
<L>For all the gladder ye may bee<MILESTONE UNIT="Caius MS. 107 page" N="38"></L>
<L>That men of armes doo preise me;</L>
<L N="1195">For if ye haue folke of grete mighte,</L>
<L>It is to you worship, y you plighte;</L>
<L>For the more men woll the doubte</L>
<L>Within thy londe and withoute.'</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="section">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'SIR GUY,' quoth the Erle tho,</L>
<L N="1200">'Failleth the aught that y may doo,</L>
<L>Golde or siluer or highe stede,</L>
<L>To passe the see yf thou haue nede?</L>
<L>Sir Guy, lete bee all this,</L>
<L>And thou shalt haue all that nedefull is,</L>
<L N="1205">To chase the herte and the hynde,</L>
<L>And to pley vnder the wode lynde:</L>
<L>Of all thinge thou shalt haue plentee,</L>
<L>And abide at home, y bidde the.</L>
<L>We shull wende bothe in feere</L>
<L N="1210">And pleye vs in wode and by Ryueer.</L>
<L>All by tymes thou may ouere wende:</L>
<L>Thou hast not soiourned a moneth to the ende.'</L>
<L>'Mikel thanke,' quoth Guy tho;</L>
<L>'For sothe so may it not goo.'
<PB REF="00000075.tif" N="71"></L>
<L N="1215">His leeue he toke withoute more;</L>
<L>The erle it forthoughte full sore.</L>
<L>He gooth him to his fader thoo,</L>
<L>That for his goyng was full woo:</L>
<L>'Fader,' quoth Guy, 'goo y wille:</L>
<L N="1220">For noo thing y woll lette by skille;</L>
<L>Yiue me leeue, y woll not spare</L>
<L>Ouer the See for to fare,</L>
<L>To wynne pris and losse also,<MILESTONE UNIT="Caius MS. 107 page" N="39"></L>
<L>As a yonge man in his youghte shuld doo.</L>
<L N="1225">To abide longe in this contree</L>
<L>It is not worthe noo thing to me;</L>
<L>For a yonge man that is mighti</L>
<L>In his youthe shuld make bowne and redy,</L>
<L>So that in age he may bee preised,</L>
<L N="1230">And so to honour to bee arreised.</L>
<L>Whiles that y am yonge and lighte,</L>
<L>My name y shall encrese by my mighte.'</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="section">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'LEEF SONE,' he seide, 'lete bee that thoughte:</L>
<L>Yet shall thou wende noughte.</L>
<L N="1235">Thou shalt abide here with me;</L>
<L>All the gladder y may bee.'</L>
<L>'Leef sone,' his moder him seide,</L>
<L>'Doo by thy faders rede:</L>
<L>Abide with vs here to yere mo,</L>
<L N="1240">I rede the, sone, thou so doo.</L>
<L>Another yere thou may ouere fare.</L>
<L>And bot thou doo thus, y dye for care,</L>
<L>For we ne haue sones moo:</L>
<L>And yf we shuld nowe the forgoo,</L>
<L N="1245">Gladde ne shuld we neuere bee,</L>
<L>Bot for sorowe oure self slee.'</L>
<L>Guy answerd with that speche,</L>
<L>'Fader, god y you beteche,</L>
<L>And my moder y doo also;</L>
<L N="1250">For hastely y woll goo.'
<PB REF="00000077.tif" N="73"></L>
<L>Guy gooth forth and theim lefte there,</L>
<L>That for him in grete sorowe were.</L>
<L>To the see he is come,<MILESTONE UNIT="Caius MS. 107 page" N="40"></L>
<L>Good wynde he hath nome.</L>
<L N="1255">Come he is in-to Normandye,</L>
<L>Knyghthode he secheth full hastily.</L>
<L>Fro thense he wente him in-to Ispaigne</L>
<L>And so fro thense in-to Almaigne.</L>
<L>At euery turnement Guy hath bee,</L>
<L N="1260">And moche preised ouere all is he.</L>
<L>Fro thense to lombardie he is wente:</L>
<L>Ther were ioustes and turnemente,</L>
<L>There they did him preise myche,</L>
<L>The lombardes him loued in-liche;</L>
<L N="1265">For he was curteys, large and free,</L>
<L>And of moche might and grete bountee.</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="section">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>NOWE OF a straunge case y shall you telle,</L>
<L>Ye that woll a while duelle,</L>
<L>That Guy befell comyng fro a turnement</L>
<L N="1270">That was withoute Boneuent:</L>
<L>In the body he wounded was:</L>
<L>Sore it him greued, noo wonder nas.</L>
<L>That aspied well the Duke Otoun,</L>
<L>That was vntruste and feloun,</L>
<L N="1275">That he wolde bee a-wreke that daie</L>
<L>On Guy of Warrewik, if he maye;</L>
<L>For he him wounded at a tournement,</L>
<L>As y before tolde verraiment;</L>
<L>Therfor Guy was yet<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>was</I> struck out after <I>yet</I>.</NOTE> him lothe,</L>
<L N="1280">And full depe he swore his othe</L>
<L>That he wolde on him wroken bee</L>
<L>Or he wente oute of that contree.</L>
<L>Whanne Duke Otes wiste that caas,<MILESTONE UNIT="Caius MS. 107 page" N="41"></L>
<L>That Guy so sore wounded was,</L>
<L N="1285">Than the Erle Lambard he clepid him to,</L>
<L>That good knyght was, and bade him goo
<PB REF="00000079.tif" N="75"></L>
<L>With .xv. knyghtes stalworthe,</L>
<L>That euerich was his armes worthe.</L>
<L>In a priue stede he did him hyde,</L>
<L N="1290">Ther Guye of Warrewik shuld come ride.</L>
<L>'Lordinges,' seide the Duke Otoun,</L>
<L>'Vnderstonde, sires, to my Reesoun:</L>
<L>My men ye bee all to me swore,</L>
<L>Holde ye shull with me therfore.</L>
<L N="1295">Myn heste doo ye shall,</L>
<L>That y to you now telle woll.</L>
<L>Me to awreke ye shull goo</L>
<L>On a traytour that is my foo,</L>
<L>That is come in-to my londe</L>
<L N="1300">(Werre he me thinketh to werke with honde),</L>
<L>Guy of Warrewik that wounded is</L>
<L>With a swerde thurgh the body ywis.</L>
<L>On the halidome ye shull swere</L>
<L>That in the forest that is full neere,</L>
<L N="1305">There ye shull you all huyde:</L>
<L>As Guy of Warrewik shall come ride,</L>
<L>His body on lyue ye shall me bringe,</L>
<L>Slee his felawes olde and yinge.</L>
<L>I shall him doo in my prison;</L>
<L N="1310">Ne shall he neuere come to Raumpson.</L>
<L>With sorowe and woo he shall ende:</L>
<L>Ne shall he neuere thense wende.'</L>
<L>'Sir,' quoth they, 'we woll goo,<MILESTONE UNIT="Caius MS. 107 page" N="42"></L>
<L>All thy commaundement for to doo.'</L>
<L N="1315">They doo theim arme swithe wele</L>
<L>Bothe in yren and in stele.</L>
<L>To their place they wende snelle,</L>
<L>And houed there softe and stille,</L>
<L>As Guy of Warrewik shuld come</L>
<L N="1320">Not knowyng of that wicked treason,</L>
<L>Ne of the sorowe neuere the moo,</L>
<L>That him was comyng to;
<PB REF="00000081.tif" N="77"></L>
<L>For all his felawes that good were,</L>
<L>Euerychoon he loste than there,</L>
<L N="1325">And his owne lif had forlore,</L>
<L>Ne were goddis helpe before,</L>
<L>Thurgh the traitours that were his foon,</L>
<L>That kepte him for to slee anoon.</L>
<L>Now cometh Guy softe riding</L>
<L N="1330">Vpon a litell mule ambling.</L>
<L>His wounde greued him full sore,</L>
<L>And euere the lenger smerted the more.</L>
<L>In pees he wened for to wende,</L>
<L>As the traitours were redy him to shende.</L>
<L N="1335">The helmes they sawe brighte shyne,</L>
<L>And anone after befelle theim pyne.</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="section">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'ALLAS,' QUOTH Guy, 'y am nome!</L>
<L>All we been dede thurgh treasoune.'</L>
<L>Guy of that Mule alighte,</L>
<L N="1340">And on his stede lepte, and gan his armes righte,</L>
<L>And seide to his felawes all:</L>
<L>'Full deere oure liffis we selle shall.</L>
<L>Oure deth is here as nowe, y speke,<MILESTONE UNIT="Caius MS. 107 page" N="43"></L>
<L>Bot we manly vs awreke.</L>
<L N="1345">Eche helpe him self, nowe it thus is,</L>
<L>And y shall doo what y may ywis:</L>
<L>As dere as y may, y wolle</L>
<L>To the traitours lombardes my lif selle.'</L>
<L>Than seide heraude thoo:</L>
<L N="1350">'For goddis loue hense thou goo.</L>
<L>For thy loue we woll dye,</L>
<L>Or defende this passage trulye.'</L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L N="1355">Than Guy answerd anone right,</L>
<L>As a good knyght of mikell might:</L>
<L>'Yf ye deye, y shall also;</L>
<L>I woll neuere fro you goo.'
</L>
</LG>

</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="section"><PB REF="00000083.tif" N="79">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>WITH THAT come a Lombard ride,</L>
<L N="1360">As a man of grete pride.</L>
<L>'Guy,' quoth he, 'yelde the anone,</L>
<L>Or ye bee dede euerychone.</L>
<L>To the Duke Otes y haue the plighte,</L>
<L>Thy body to bringe him anone righte.'</L>
<L N="1365">The Lombard was hote withoute lette,</L>
<L>And Guy him hath with harme grette;</L>
<L>He ne spared for noo drede,</L>
<L>That deed he felled him in the mede.</L>
<L>'By the trouth,' quoth Guy, 'that y shall my lemman yelde,</L>
<L N="1370">Thou shalt not thy trouth to the Duke holde.'</L>
<L>To another lombarde he smote anone,</L>
<L>That thurgh the body his swerde gan goone:</L>
<L>'Nor thou, traitour, thou ne shall me lede</L>
<L>To thy Duke that is so full of quede,</L>
<L N="1375">Nor to his prisoun for the bee broughte.'<MILESTONE UNIT="Caius MS. 107 page" N="44"></L>
<L>Heraude smote to another and spared noughte,</L>
<L>That thurgh the swerde glode:</L>
<L>Deed he felled him withoute bode.</L>
<L>Than come Toraude, a good knyghte:</L>
<L N="1380">Swithe good he was in fighte.</L>
<L>With a lombarde he so mette,</L>
<L>And so well he his stroke besette,</L>
<L>That the heed fro the body fleighe:</L>
<L>He smote his shuldres alowe so neighe.</L>
<L N="1385">With that come Vrry priking</L>
<L>(A better knyght might noman fynde),</L>
<L>To a lombarde he smote so,</L>
<L>That thurgh the body his swerde gan goo:</L>
<L>So he smote him, the sothe to sey,</L>
<L N="1390">That deed he felled him in the wey;</L>
<L>And than he seide: 'thou ne Otoun</L>
<L>Ne shall vs bringe in-to your prison.'</L>
<L>There might men see fighte begynne,</L>
<L>Hedes clouen downe to the chynne.
<PB REF="00000085.tif" N="81"></L>
<L N="1395">All that Guy with his swerde toke,</L>
<L>Sone anone his lif forsoke.</L>
<L>Some he smote vpon the hode,</L>
<L>That at the girdelstede the swerde abode;</L>
<L>Some he smote thurgh the side,</L>
<L N="1400">That they ne might neuere more goo nor ryde.</L>
<L>Was there noon that might stonde</L>
<L>The dynte that come oute of his honde.</L>
<L>So mighti strokes ther were yiue,</L>
<L>That the stronge shaftes all to-dryue.</L>
<L N="1405">There was noon in that stede<MILESTONE UNIT="Caius MS. 107 page" N="45"></L>
<L>Bot of his lif he was adredde.</L>
<L>With that come ride the Erle Lambard,</L>
<L>A sterne knyght and a Lombard;</L>
<L>Vrry he hath sleyne there,</L>
<L N="1410">That forthoughte Guy whan he therof was ware:</L>
<L>With the Erle lambard he did iousty,</L>
<L>To awreke the deth of good Vrry.</L>
<L>With suche an hete he smote him to,</L>
<L>That all his armes auailled him not a sloo;</L>
<L N="1415">Thurgh his herte the launce he bare,</L>
<L>And adown he felled him dede there.</L>
<L>With that cometh forth hugon,</L>
<L>He was the Dukes Nieue Otoun:</L>
<L>Knyght he was of grete mighte,</L>
<L N="1420">Swithe hardy and good in fighte.</L>
<L>Toraude there he hath felled,</L>
<L>And to deth stiked him thurgh his sheelde.</L>
<L>And whan heraude saw that cas,</L>
<L>That Toraulde so foule sleyne was,</L>
<L N="1425">For his deth he was sorye:</L>
<L>Him to awreke he doth him hye.</L>
<L>Neuere so sory he was,</L>
<L>Toward hugon he made a chas.</L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L>
<PB REF="00000087.tif" N="83">. . . . . </L>
<L>Thurgh the body he him smote</L>
<L>With so grete strength, god it wote,</L>
<L>That there before the Lombardes all</L>
<L>Of his hors he did him dede fall.</L>
<L N="1435">Whan Danz Gauter that sighe</L>
<L>(A knyght he was of herte highe),</L>
<L>Ouere thwert<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. <I>thewert</I>.</NOTE> he smote to Heraude so<MILESTONE UNIT="Caius MS. 107 page" N="46"></L>
<L>That all his hauberk he rende thoo;</L>
<L>Thurgh heraudes body the swerde yede,</L>
<L N="1440">All they wende he had bee dede.</L>
<L>Whan Guy sawe heraude felde,</L>
<L>To-hewe his hauberk and his shelde</L>
<L>(And of his hors felled he was</L>
<L>As a dede man vpon the gras),</L>
<L N="1445">And sawe the blode that ranne him fro,</L>
<L>Wonder he thoughte, and seide thoo:</L>
<L>'Thou lordyng, to the y seye,</L>
<L>His deth thou shalt full dere abeye!</L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L>And by him that made sone and mone,</L>
<L>Thou shalt wite swithe sone</L>
<L N="1455">That thou shalt it forgete nought</L>
<L>That thou him hast to deth brought.'</L>
<L>Guy with spores smote his stede,</L>
<L>As a man that had grete nede.</L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L>Than with all his mighte he smote him to,</L>
<L>Full euen he karffe his herte in two.</L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L N="1465">And ther in grene he felled him downe,</L>
<L>And bade him Cristes malesoune,
<PB REF="00000089.tif" N="85"></L>
<L>For that he did heraude slee,</L>
<L>And lete him on lyue bee.</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="section">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>NOWE IS Guy full harde befalle,</L>
<L N="1470">Loste he hath his felawes alle;</L>
<L>So sory he is, he ne wote what to doo,</L>
<L>And he<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>ne?</I></NOTE> woteth to whom he may bemene hym to.</L>
<L>Bot three of the Lombardes on lyue ther were,</L>
<L>That vpon Guy thoughte grete deere.</L>
<L N="1475">Tweyn of theim were hoole and sounde,<MILESTONE UNIT="Caius MS. 107 page" N="47"></L>
<L>The thridde thurgh the body had a wounde.</L>
<L>Guy with his swerde that oon raughte,</L>
<L>That his hede fleighe of with a draughte.</L>
<L>With that come priking Dan Guychard,</L>
<L N="1480">He was a full proude Lombarde.</L>
<L>'Guy,' he seide, 'yelde the to me!</L>
<L>Thou seest it woll noon other bee.</L>
<L>All thy men fro the been refte:</L>
<L>Sauf thy self is noon lefte,</L>
<L N="1485">And thyn helme is all to-hewe,</L>
<L>Thyn hauberk to-tore that was newe;</L>
<L>Wounded thou art, well y see,</L>
<L>That longe thou maist not alyue bee.</L>
<L>This daie y shall the bringe to Duke Otoun,</L>
<L N="1490">And he the shall doo in his prisoun.'</L>
<L>Than seide Guy, 'Guychard, y nelle</L>
<L>Yelde me to Otes by my wille,</L>
<L>While y haue my swerde grounde</L>
<L>And my body stiffe to sitte astounde.'</L>
<L N="1495">Guychard smote Guy with grete mighte</L>
<L>Vpon his helme that shone brighte,</L>
<L>That a quarter awey fleighe;</L>
<L>The knyght was stronge, hardy, and sleighe.</L>
<L>Vpon the shoulder the swerde glode,</L>
<L N="1500">Of the hauberk he toke an handbrode;</L>
<L>God saued Guy that he was not dede,</L>
<L>Ne for that stroke had noo quede.
<PB REF="00000091.tif" N="87"></L>
<L>To Guychard he fondeth to smyte,</L>
<L>And his swerde woll aughte byte.</L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L>To him he striketh swithe smerte<MILESTONE UNIT="Caius MS. 107 page" N="48"></L>
<L>Thurgh the body well nyghe the herte:</L>
<L>That good swerde in he thurste,</L>
<L N="1510">Guychard to abide noo lenger had luste,</L>
<L>Bot tourned his hors and gan to flee,</L>
<L>And Guy after him faste rode he.</L>
<L>Good was that hors that Guychard rode on,</L>
<L>Guy wente ayene and lete him goon:</L>
<L N="1515">For that he ne might him ouere-take,</L>
<L>Full grete sorowe Guy gan make.</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="section">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>GUYCHARD fleying toke his wey</L>
<L>Toward Pauy, as swithe as he may.</L>
<L>The Duke Otes fro huntyng come,</L>
<L N="1520">And with him Barons and knyghtis many oone.</L>
<L>A knyght he sawe come priking</L>
<L>With armes rende, his woundes bledyng.</L>
<L>The Duke Otes duelled athrowe,</L>
<L>Tyll Guychard he might knowe:</L>
<L N="1525">Him thoughte he semed a man aferde,</L>
<L>Or that harde tidynges had herde.</L>
<L>With that is Guychard to theim come;</L>
<L>The Duke him asked full sone,</L>
<L>'Sey, Guychard, who hath wrathed the?</L>
<L N="1530">Where hast thou in bataille bee?</L>
<L>Where is Guy? is he nome?</L>
<L>Quykke or dede lete him to me come.'</L>
<L>'I shall you telle sikirly</L>
<L>As moche as y wote of Guy:</L>
<L N="1535">At a Forde we him mette,</L>
<L>And strongly we him besette,</L>
<L>And his body ne toke we nought:<MILESTONE UNIT="Caius MS. 107 page" N="49"></L>
<L>All we been to deth brought;
<PB REF="00000093.tif" N="89"></L>
<L>Bot y am eskaped as ye may see.'</L>
<L N="1540">'My Nieueu hugon, where is he?'</L>
<L>Quoth the Duke Otes, 'telle thou me.'</L>
<L>'In the playne he lieth sleyn pardee.'</L>
<L>'And the Erle Lambard, the good knyght?'</L>
<L>'Deed he lieth in that fighte.'</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="section">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1545">WHANNE the Duke Otes herde that,</L>
<L>Full sory he was for that myshap,</L>
<L>For his folke were so sleyne,</L>
<L>And thurgh Guy broughte fro lif to peyne.</L>
<L>For sorowe he waxe all-moste wode,</L>
<L N="1550">His herte to-berste well nyghe for mode.</L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="section">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>NOWE GUY maketh sorowe pitously,</L>
<L>And for his felawes wepeth gretly.</L>
<L N="1555">'Allas,' quoth Guy, 'felawes dere,</L>
<L>So well doyng knyghtis as ye were.</L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L>For thy loue, Felice, faire may,</L>
<L N="1560">Floure of knyghtis is sleyn this day.</L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L N="1565">Nowe all other may by me,</L>
<L>Yf they woll, warned bee.</L>
<L>Allas, heraude, my dere frende,</L>
<L>That were so curteys and so hende,</L>
<L>Who shall me helpe now in fighte?</L>
<L N="1570">In the worlde nas a better knyghte.</L>
<L>In euery place full well thou holpe me,</L>
<L>Euyl y haue it acquytte the;</L>
<L>For me thou hast thy lif forgoon,</L>
<L>Of the nomore helpe shall y haue noon.
<PB REF="00000095.tif" N="91"></L>
<L>A-cursed bee thise Lombardes echoone,<MILESTONE UNIT="Caius MS. 107 page" N="50"></L>
<L>That slowe the, and lete me goone.'</L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L N="1595">What for his woundes that greuously bledeth,</L>
<L>And what for sorowe that he fredeth,</L>
<L>Thus for sorowe and for woo</L>
<L>Adowne he felle in swounyng thoo.</L>
<L>Whan he of his swounyng was awaked,</L>
<L N="1600">Vp he stode, his sorowe not slaked.</L>
<L>Than he worthe vpon his stede,</L>
<L>And to an hermytage he gan him spede.</L>
<L>'Heremyte,' quoth Guy, 'come with me,</L>
<L>And this hors of pris y yiue to the.</L>
<L N="1605">Twoo bodies thou shalt in erthe graue,</L>
<L>That in this forest their dethes haue.'</L>
<L>'Blithely, sir,' seide than he;</L>
<L>'Wende forthe, y shall folowe the.'</L>
<L>Than the bodies him shewed Guy</L>
<L N="1610">Of Toraulde and<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>and</I> added over the line.</NOTE> of good Vrry.
<PB REF="00000097.tif" N="93"></L>
<L>Sithe he toke another stede,</L>
<L>And Heraude with him he dooth lede,</L>
<L>And rode him forthe all softely:</L>
<L>For him he wepeth full hertly,</L>
<L N="1615">For he wende in sothe there</L>
<L>That heraude to deth wounded were.</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="section">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>NOWE IS Guy forthe fare,</L>
<L>And for his felawes maketh grete kare.</L>
<L>Heraudes body with him he dooth bere</L>
<L N="1620">Forto burye it ellis-where.</L>
<L>He wente him to an Abbey</L>
<L>That was ther beside the highe wey.</L>
<L>The Abbot Guy there he mette,<MILESTONE UNIT="Caius MS. 107 page" N="51"></L>
<L>And full pitously he him grette:</L>
<L N="1625">'Sir Abbot,' he seide, 'god the blisse</L>
<L>That man made for his owne, ywis:</L>
<L>All for loue of the Trynyte</L>
<L>I the beseche, for sainte Charite,</L>
<L>That thou this body here, loo,</L>
<L N="1630">In a faire buriel thou hit doo.</L>
<L>Full well y shall it yelde the,</L>
<L>And yf y any while lyuyng bee.'</L>
<L>'What art thou?' quoth the Abbot, 'telle me.'</L>
<L>'Blithely, sir: y sey the,</L>
<L N="1635">I am a knyght of farre Contree;</L>
<L>At a passage assailled were we</L>
<L>Of stronge theeffis and outelawes,</L>
<L>That my felawes haue broughte to dethis dawes;</L>
<L>And y meself haue many a wounde,</L>
<L N="1640">That y wene y shall lyue noo stounde;</L>
<L>And if y lyue, y shall yelde it the,</L>
<L>The trauaille that thou doost for me.'</L>
<L>To Guy answerd the Abbot tho:</L>
<L>'All thy wille, sir, shalbee doo.'</L>
<L N="1645">Nowe gooth Guy sore dismaide,</L>
<L>His woundes haue him sore affraide.
<PB REF="00000099.tif" N="95"></L>
<L>To an heremyte he is goo,</L>
<L>That he was acqueynted with or thoo;</L>
<L>His woundes hele there he dedde</L>
<L N="1650">Withoute noyse in that stede;</L>
<L>For moche he dredde the Duke Otoun,</L>
<L>Full of hatrede and of treasoun.</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="section">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>NOWE THE Abbot of wom y you telle,<MILESTONE UNIT="Caius MS. 107 page" N="52"></L>
<L>Of heraude hath grete reuthe with-all;</L>
<L N="1655">He lete bere his bodye</L>
<L>In-to a Chambre to vnarme lightly;</L>
<L>And whan they had vnarmed him</L>
<L>A monke behelde euery lymme.</L>
<L>The same monke a phisician was,</L>
<L N="1660">The mighte he knewe of many a gras.</L>
<L>The woundes he behelde stedefastly,</L>
<L>That in the body were so grisely.</L>
<L>By the woundes he sawe ywis</L>
<L>That he to deth ne wounded is,</L>
<L N="1665">And that [he] him hele might;</L>
<L>And so he dooth sothely aplight.</L>
<L>In the meane tyme, ye may me leue,</L>
<L>Guy was heled and toke his leue</L>
<L>Of the good heremyte and wente his wey</L>
<L N="1670">Toward Poyle right as he may.</L>
<L>To the king of Poyle he was welcome,</L>
<L>And that he knewe full sone.</L>
<L>Of siluer he bade him and of golde,</L>
<L>And Guy therof nought take wolde.</L>
<L N="1675">At euery place in turnement</L>
<L>Guy had the pris verament.</L>
<L>Was ther noon in all the londe,</L>
<L>That Guyes dyntes might withstonde.</L>
<L>Therfor men loued him swithe,</L>
<L N="1680">And vnderfange him full blithe;</L>
<L>With all good men he was leef and dere,</L>
<L>And therwith-all their pleyfere.
<PB REF="00000101.tif" N="97"></L>
<L>At the king he toke his leeue thoo;<MILESTONE UNIT="Caius MS. 107 page" N="53"></L>
<L>In-to Cessoigne he is goo.</L>
<L N="1685">He is come to the Duke Reyner,</L>
<L>That him loued and had full deer;</L>
<L>And he him fange full worshipfully,</L>
<L>And did him honour full manly.</L>
<L>So longe in the Contree ther his duelling is,</L>
<L N="1690">That ouere all other he bereth the pris.</L>
<L>Guy him bethoughte thoo</L>
<L>That he had enough ther doo:</L>
<L>To Englonde he thoughte to wende,</L>
<L>For to speke with his frende;</L>
<L N="1695">For it was agoo .v. yere</L>
<L>That he was laste there;</L>
<L>In lasse stounde than that was</L>
<L>Befalleth many a wonder cas.</L>
<L>Thurgh the contrees as he hath wente,</L>
<L N="1700">Quenes and Contasses for him hath sente,</L>
<L>And noon he wolde sikirly</L>
<L>Bot Felice that he loued so hertly.</L>
<L>What for his mikell goodnesse,</L>
<L>And for his might and large prowesse,</L>
<L N="1705">Ther nys knyght that so moche preised bee</L>
<L>Anone to Antioche, that good Citee.</L>
<L>Guy him spedde nyghte and daie,</L>
<L>Toward Englond he toke his weye.</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="section">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>OFF GUY y shall leue nowe,</L>
<L N="1710">And a litell while telle yow</L>
<L>Of heraude another stounde,</L>
<L>How he was heled of his wounde.</L>
<L>Whanne he felte him-self hooll and quarte,<MILESTONE UNIT="Caius MS. 107 page" N="54"></L>
<L>Of the Abbot he toke his leeue and did departe;</L>
<L N="1715">His lorde Guy he gooth seching</L>
<L>Nighte and daye for him bidding,</L>
<L>As Guy toward Englond toke his wey:</L>
<L>Crist him saue that best may!
<PB REF="00000103.tif" N="99"></L>
<L>At a pynacle of the see</L>
<L N="1720">He sawe a man sitte of ruly blee</L>
<L>In a pouere pilgrymes wede,</L>
<L>And that was heraude veraily in-dede.</L>
<L>Anone Guy cleped to him,</L>
<L>And seide, 'of whens art thou, pilgrym?'</L>
<L N="1725">'Sir,' he seide, 'fro Lombardie.'</L>
<L>'What tydingis there?' quoth sir Guye.</L>
<L>'By god,' quoth heraude, 'y kan noone;</L>
<L>For many a daie it is goone</L>
<L>That y loste my kynde lorde</L>
<L N="1730">That good knyght was, at a worde.</L>
<L>Betraye vs did the Duke Otoun:</L>
<L>Haue he cristis malison!</L>
<L>Therfor in this wise y shall goo,</L>
<L>And bidde for my lorde euere moo.'</L>
<L N="1735">'Sey me, pilgrym,' quoth Guy, 'truly,</L>
<L>What height that man that thou loued so hertly?'</L>
<L>'Guy of Warrewik was his name:</L>
<L>A knyght he was withoute blame.'</L>
<L>With that he gan sighe sore:</L>
<L N="1740">He wepte and seide 'allas' euermore;</L>
<L>He might it noo lenger kepe in holde.</L>
<L>Guy full ruly he gan him beholde.</L>
<L>'Good man,' quoth Guy, 'for thy leaute,<MILESTONE UNIT="Caius MS. 107 page" N="55"></L>
<L>What is thy name? telle thou me.'</L>
<L N="1745">'Heraude of Ardern men clepe me</L>
<L>In contrees there as y haue bee.</L>
<L>.V. yere y haue thus goo</L>
<L>Seching my lorde Guy that y loued so.'</L>
<L>Whan Guy herde heraude so speke,</L>
<L N="1750">Of his teres he gan downe reke.</L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L>
<PB REF="00000105.tif" N="101">. . . . . </L>
<L N="1755">'Allas, heraude, maister myn!</L>
<L>Knowest not Guy, a felawe of thyn?'</L>
<L>'Certes,' quoth heraude, 'sir, nay:</L>
<L>Dede he was goon many a day.'</L>
<L>And he answerd, 'y am Guy.'</L>
<L N="1760">'A, sir,' quoth heraude, 'mercy.'</L>
<L>As sone as heraude vnderstode</L>
<L>That he was Guy, the knyght goode,</L>
<L>In swowe he felle adowne anone,</L>
<L>And Guy in his armes him toke full sone.</L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L>Adowne they sette theim bothe there,</L>
<L N="1770">And tolde eche other of their kare.</L>
<L>Sir Guy hath heraude telde</L>
<L>How he him bare oute of the felde,</L>
<L>For to burye him at an Abbey</L>
<L>That was there beside the highe wey.</L>
<L N="1775">And than heraude he him teelde</L>
<L>How his woundes were heled,</L>
<L>And thurgh how many londes he had goo</L>
<L>Seching his lorde Guy with sorowe and woo.</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="section">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>THEIR HORS they toke after this,</L>
<L N="1780">And rode to the next Citee ywis;</L>
<L>There did Guy Heraude in herbes bathy,<MILESTONE UNIT="Caius MS. 107 page" N="56"></L>
<L>And with good metes him comforte hertly.</L>
<L>Fro thens they wente to the Duke Mylone,</L>
<L>To whom they bothe were welcome.</L>
<L N="1785">Of their auentures they tolde there,</L>
<L>And thanked good in many maner.</L>
<L>At the Duke they toke their leeue thoo,</L>
<L>Toward Englond they gan goo.
<PB REF="00000107.tif" N="103"></L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L N="1795">To seynt Omers is Guy come,</L>
<L>And heraude with him all and some.</L>
<L>Towarde the see they take their wey,</L>
<L>As swithe as the hors theim bere may.</L>
<L>Whan they to the Town were come,</L>
<L N="1800">Their Inne they take full sone.</L>
<L>To a wyndowe is Guy goo,</L>
<L>Into the strete he behelde thoo;</L>
<L>A palmer he sawe comyng,</L>
<L>Easely by the wey goyng.</L>
<L N="1805">To him than cleped Guy,</L>
<L>And curteisly he gan him asky,</L>
<L>'Woll thou herburgh? for it is nyghte;</L>
<L>For fa[r]t[h]er thou ne goo myghte.'</L>
<L>The palmer answerd to Guy,</L>
<L N="1810">'Sir,' quoth he, 'grauntmercy.'</L>
<L>To sitte downe Guy gaue him leeue,</L>
<L>Farther he ne might, it was nyghe eeue.</L>
<L>Than he praide him he wolde him sey</L>
<L>Some tidingis, yf he kouthe, of the Contrey,</L>
<L N="1815">Yf he herde nyghe or farre</L>
<L>Speke of bataille or of werre.</L>
<L>'I shall telle,' quoth he, 'fote hote<MILESTONE UNIT="Caius MS. 107 page" N="57"></L>
<L>Of grete werre that y wote:</L>
<L>Of a strenger y haue not herde;</L>
<L N="1820">Therof is many a man ferde.'</L>
<L>Guy him seide, 'telle it me.'</L>
<L>'Forsothe y graunte,' seide he.</L>
<L>'Of Almaigne the Emperour,</L>
<L>Reyner, that is of grete honour,</L>
<L N="1825">The Duke of Louaigne hath bee-sette,</L>
<L>His Castellis destroied withoute lette;
<PB REF="00000109.tif" N="105"></L>
<L>For his Neuyeu that he slowe,</L>
<L>He hath wroughte him moche woo nowe.</L>
<L>All-moste a yere it is goo,</L>
<L N="1830">At a turnement that is doo,</L>
<L>The Duke Segwyn was ther thoo,</L>
<L>That all louaigne belongeth vnto,</L>
<L>With all the knyghtes of his londe</L>
<L>That thider come their might to fonde.</L>
